<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION MECHANICS CLAIM VINDICATION IN AMWEST FINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 and KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the moment America West Airlines fired 500 mechanics three
years ago, some workers in the airline's hangar have sounded dire
warnings about lax maintenance. America West management repeatedly
dismissed the concerns as sour grapes and union rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of the mechanics, the Federal Aviation
Administration validated their worries Tuesday by levying a $5
million fine against the Tempe airline for maintenance lapses,
mechanics say.
</P>
<P>
   Even if half the fine is forgiven as proposed, it will be the
largest fine paid by a U.S. airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mechanics feel a certain vindication here,'' Patrick
Lacefield, a spokesman for the Teamsters, which represents the 350
remaining mechanics, said Wednesday. ``They've been talking about
this outsourcing stuff from day one, ever since 1995. America West
has always pooh-poohed it.''
</P>
<P>
   America West maintains the layoffs and shift to outside
contractors is not the problem. Executives said late Tuesday that
the biggest problem the FAA found, involving inspection lapses on
numerous Airbus A320 aircraft, goes back to changes by the
manufacturer in inspection procedures instituted in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This predates it (the layoffs) by two years,'' Richard
Goodmanson, the carrier's chief executive officer, said late
Tuesday after the fine was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA didn't single out the layoffs and outsourcing in its
announcement, but its settlement agreement with America West calls
for the airline to set up a team to oversee its outside maintenance
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hefty fine, Wall Street and most travelers were
nonplussed. The Tempe airline's stock fell Wednesday just 56 cents,
to $29.69 a share on the New York Stock Exchange. Trading volume
was normal.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts focused on the company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are retaining our buy rating, as the bulk of this
headline-making issue appears to be behind the company, and its
near-term earnings momentum remains among the best in the airline
group,'' analyst James Higgins of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
wrote in a brief report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said the only continuing issue at the airline appears to
be labor negotiations, which prompted the FAA, in a separate move,
to increase its scrutiny of the airline last month. The FAA said it
has received anonymous complaints about safety and maintenance from
flight attendants and mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   One industry analyst went so far as to blast the size of the
fine and the FAA's national media blitz announcing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more of a fine than they laid on the ValuJet incident
where 110 people died,'' said Mike Boyd of the Boyd Group in
Evergreen, Colo., referring to the 1996 crash in the Florida
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said $5 million _ even though it'll be cut in half if
America West complies with the settlement agreement _ is a hefty
penalty for what he calls regulatory, not safety violations. He
added that some of the issues raised were important but were not
``life-threatening failures'' and probably occur at one time or
another at all the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety is an important issue, I don't discount that. And
missing inspections is something that's important,'' he said. ``But
this isn't a case where an airline, like ValuJet, blatantly ignored
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, who has never consulted for America West, said the FAA,
which was criticized after the ValuJet crash, is using America West
to make a statement that it's tough on safety. The carrier is a
good target because it's relatively small and lacks the political
clout of industry biggies such as American and United, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a political photo opportunity,'' he said, noting that FAA
Administrator Jane Garvey was featured in the announcement about
the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA dismissed Boyd's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The action was initiated by career FAA employees and was
carried on in its entirety by career FAA employees,'' spokesman
Mitch Barker said. ``There was nothing political about the
action.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite safety assurances by America West, some passengers
remain skittish and refused to fly the carrier.
</P>
<P>
   One traveler said she was so upset by the FAA fine that she
called America West, demanding a refund on a flight her husband is
taking next week to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went round and round and round,'' said Patty Snyder, who
lives in Waddell, northwest of Phoenix. ``That's just crazy that
when you can't even find a customer service person to complain
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder eventually got through to a manager, who told her that
every other call was from a passenger who wanted a refund.
</P>
<P>
   America West spokeswoman Patty Nowack said there's no such
panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had very, very few people request that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowack said the airline's regular refund policy stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a customer has purchased a non-refundable ticket, they have
a non-refundable ticket,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one travel agency heard from concerned clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had regular, loyal flyers wanting to switch and fly on
another carrier,'' said Ella Caine, owner of Ella Caine Travel in
Scottsdale. ``I had one corporate account that called today and
said, `No, put us on another airline. We won't fly America West.'
''
</P>
<P>
   But other agencies said they hadn't heard from any passengers
booked on America West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gotten one phone call,'' said Dawn Poturalski, an
agent with A World of Travel in Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto at Bon Voyage Travel in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Van Epps, a partner in Moon Valley Travel, said there were
no questions from travelers about the FAA's action on Wednesday,
but they have cropped up since reports of the airline's FAA
troubles surfaced a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of an ongoing thing with them since this whole
thing started,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers aren't so much concerned with whether the airline is
safe as much as persistent flight delays and cancellations, Van
Epps said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been shifting equipment (planes) around,'' he said,
adding that a client's flight from Mexico City to Phoenix scheduled
for next week was canceled because the plane was needed on another
route.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters' Lacefield said he can't believe how America West
is spinning the huge fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe the America West press release, it seems like
they've been given a $5 million fine for good behavior,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call.''  &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson can be reached at 444-8617 or at
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
