<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES CRUSH RANGERS, 14-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Tonight will not be foreign for right-hander
Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-game winner will be asked to terminate yet another losing
streak for the American League West contenders known collectively
as the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling, attempting to join Yankees
right-hander David Cone as the major leagues' only 13-game winner,
suffered his worst performance this season in the Orioles' 14-3
victory last night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lost their fourth consecutive game, and Helling
played a significant role because of his inability to pitch down in
the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitch was up here,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said
as he motioned above the letters on his jersey. ``He's always been
able to make that adjustment. That's the reason he's 12-5. He's
always been able to make that adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night was a rare exception.
</P>
<P>
   Helling could not complete the fifth inning before the
fifth-largest gathering for a regular-season game at The Ballpark.
Helling surrendered eight runs on seven hits and matched a
single-game high with five walks in a 41/3-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was more mechanical than anything else,'' Helling
said. ``I was rushing a bit and getting behind in the count. When
you walk guys in the big leagues, you're going to pay for it more
often than not.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven consecutive batters reached safely, including three via
walks, in the Orioles' five-run second inning. Orioles catcher
Lenny Webster and second baseman Roberto Alomar produced most of
the damage with two-run base hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make any excuses, but I lost my rhythm during
that second inning,'' Helling said. ``I put our team in a hole, and
I'm very disappointed in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, who won their seventh consecutive game, continued
their assault against right-hander Tim Crabtree and left-hander
Scott Bailes. The Orioles collected a single-game, season-high 19
hits and matched their single-game best for runs.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Sele (12-5) in a familiar position.
</P>
<P>
   He does not lack experience.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the third time since June 23 that Sele will step on
the mound with the Rangers amid a losing streak of three or more
games.
</P>
<P>
   Sele met the challenge on both those occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander allowed four runs (three earned) in a
seven-inning appearance in the Rangers' 16-5 victory June 23
against the Arizona Diamondbacks, and pitched six scoreless innings
in a 9-2 victory July 4 against Seattle. That translates into a 2-0
record with a 2.08 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows what kind of pitcher Aaron is,'' Helling said. ``I
wish I could have been the guy tonight to stop this losing
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Sele's turn now, and he should recognize the way.
</P>
<P>
   No map required.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
