<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BANK-KICKBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BANK SUSPENDS 3 EMPLOYEES FOR SUSPECTED KICKBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The World Bank, which lends billions of dollars a
year for development projects in poor countries, is investigating
possible kickbacks and other wrongdoing by at least three bank
employees, bank officials said on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The three employees have been notified that they are under
suspicion and have been suspended, said Klas Bergman, the World
Bank's chief of media relations. Bergman said the three are
midlevel employees at the bank's headquarters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Malloch Brown, the bank's vice president for external
affairs, said on Wednesday night that more bank aides could come
under investigation, but he could not speculate how many.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to confirm the allegations or disprove them,'' Malloch
Brown said, adding that the bank's ``moral authority'' was at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the investigation involves a water utility project
in Algiers. The bank is suing a former bank employee in federal
court to recover thousands of dollars that it believes he took in
kickbacks from a contractor who was a former neighbor and who did
not complete the work properly, the bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of the investigation involves possible misuse of
a trust fund set up by the Japanese government to subsidize bank
administrative expenses, according to The Washington Post, which
first reported on the investigation in Thursday's editions. Bergman
said he could not comment on that part of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bank funnels as much as $25 billion a year into
development projects abroad _ and tries to guard against corruption
in the needy countries that get its loans _ the World Bank's
integrity is all-important, Malloch Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the amount of money involved in the investigation might
be in the tens of thousands of dollars, or what he called ``pretty
small beer'' compared to the bank's moral stature.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman said the bank set up a special unit, the Oversight
Committee on Fraud and Corruption, this spring after top officials
began to get word of possible wrongdoing. The bank has also hired
the global accounting firm Price Waterhouse Coopers and two outside
fraud specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank president, James Wolfensohn, distributed a
message to bank staff members on Wednesday in which he underlined
the seriousness of the accusations, regardless of the amount of
money involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank has a passionate commitment to fight corruption,''
Wolfensohn said, calling it a ``cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While I have no reason to believe there is a widespread
problem in the bank, even one case is one too many,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has about 8,600 employees and has its headquarters a
short distance from the White House, which Bergman said is being
kept abreast of the investigation through the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman said he could not state whether the current accusations,
if proven, would constitute the worst wrongdoing in the bank's
history.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that, despite the bank's generally good record, an
employee was convicted a few years ago of embezzling about
$500,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
