<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, July 16.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-FARM-ATTACKS (Mooinooi, South Africa) _ The farmers
around here, like many elsewhere in the country, are numbering
their farms on color-coded maps and setting up command posts in
their basements where automatic weapons, helmets, gas masks and
bulletproof vests are at the ready. Attacks on white farmers have
been mounting, and some assaults have been particularly brutal. The
farmers may well be feeling the brunt of a crime wave that has
swept across the country, leaving many South Africans living behind
high fences and barred windows. But many farmers believe the
attacks are more calculated _ the work of black militants aiming at
a group that remains among the most right-wing in the country. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GENITAL-MUTILATION (United Nations) _ For the Sabiny people of
eastern Uganda, 1998 is a circumcision year _ as are all even years
_ when girls as well as boys would normally be expected to endure a
painful rite of passage to young adulthood. But not this time, said
G.W. Cheborian, chairman of the Sabiny Elders Association, a
council of clan leaders. While young men of 14 to about 22 will
still take part in elaborate circumcision ceremonies in December to
mark their entry into manhood, for many if not most girls and young
women, there will be no genital cutting. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   USAF-PILOT-TRAINING (Mountain Home, Idaho) _ As it scrambles to
find new or expanded places to train fighter and bomber pilots, the
Air Force is running into intensifying opposition from ranchers,
environmentalists, sportsmen and Native Americans who believe the
roar of fast, low-flying jets is disrupting some of the nation's
last refuges of peace and quiet. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics client.
Photos [NYT17,18) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-THREAPY (Undated) _ Tests on mice show that
Angiostatin, which blocks formation of blood vessels that feed
tumors, is far more effective in combination with radiation
treatment than when used alone. The researchers say this could lead
to a ``clinically feasible'' treatment strategy that could be
particularly useful in brain, head and neck cancers. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-BOOM (Dubuque, Iowa) _ From the porch views of the
Victorian-era houses sitting high on the limestone bluffs over the
Mississippi River, it looked like a sad parade on the streets of
Dubuque in the '80s, an exodus of downhearted Iowans fleeing the
farm-crisis economy. In those days, with unemployment rates over 14
percent, young Iowans with roots five or six generations deep came
to see their future prospects here as hopeless. These days,
Dubuque, a city of some 60,000 people, has a new and enviable
problem: too many good jobs and not enough workers. So Dubuque
civic and business officials have begun an aggressive program to
bring back its sons, daughters and grandchildren. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
