<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS NEED A LEADER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took half a season but the Los Angeles Dodgers
finally have wandered into the pennant race, albeit with all the
nonchalance of the thousands of fans who found their Dodger Stadium
seats well after the opening pitch in Wednesday's twilight game
between the host team and the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, bless their souls, had been like guides in the
wilderness, marking the Dodgers' path by dropping five games in a
row. It took an ex-Dodger, of all people, to remind the Giants this
was the enemy they were helping, which Orel Hershiser did in time
to avoid a series sweep via a 5-3 win in the three-game series
finale in front of a crowd of 34,596.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, only the Dodgers' third in seven games since the
All-Star break, left L.A. 5{ behind the Giants in the wild-card
race with 68 games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Having come this far, the question is where do the Dodgers go
from here, besides to St. Louis for a four-game set against a
Cardinals team that is seven games under .500 and staring vacantly
at the Dodgers' backs?
</P>
<P>
   It says here the Dodgers have plenty of trail left to straighten
out this wayward season, but only if they go out and get someone
fiery to lead them _ by the ear or the scruff of the neck, if
necessary _ the rest of the way. Someone with a wicked fastball and
an even nastier disposition. Someone by the name of Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the Seattle southpaw recently got into a scuffle with
a teammate, David Segui, over something seemingly as silly as the
volume of the clubhouse stereo? The Dodgers need somebody to
brazenly step forward and turn up the passion in the Dodgers' room
until the walls are throbbing with intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Raul Mondesi is the leader in the clubhouse by
da' vault, having signed the richest contract in team history over
the winter. To his credit, the Dominican Republic native has taken
great pains to be more vocal, jumping on the chance to speak
English the way he used to the first offerings of opposing
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, warming to his No.3 spot in the order, batted .560 (14
for 25) in six games against the Giants this month. He was 3 for 4
with two RBI Wednesday to improve his batting average to .385 for
the month and .293 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to think we can win 10 games in a row,'' Mondesi
said before the game, trying to set the proper tone.
</P>
<P>
   But attitudes are instilled by actions and not just words.
Mondesi muddled his message last month when he was pulled over for
drunk driving in Glendale hours after a home game against Colorado
and some eight hours before he was due at the stadium for a matinee
against the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Partying has its place and it's decidedly not in the middle of a
race toward respectability. As soon as the Dodgers, to a man,
realize there's a bigger high out there than the one provided by
alcohol or the mere donning of a major-league uniform, then the
team will have the right mindset to put the fear of Abner Doubleday
into the likes of division-leading San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Dodgers claimed a postseason victory, in 1988,
they kept winning until there were no more games left. The unerring
compass of that year's world championship team was an
obstinate-minded professor of a pitcher named Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   In Hershiser's eyes then and now, the only thing worse than
swearing in the clubhouse is not caring so completely you die a
little with every loss. Hershiser was working with three days' rest
between starts and a strained shoulder, but the man otherwise known
as ``Bulldog'' scratched and clawed and stubbornly hung in for the
win in his first appearance at Dodger Stadium as a Giant.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Hershiser's 81 pitches found Dodger flesh but neither of
the walked wounded, Adrian Beltre in the fourth inning nor Wilton
Guerrero in the fifth, could parlay the free base into the score
that would have broken a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   However, when starter Darren Dreifort hit Darryl Hamilton with a
pitch in the seventh, the Dodgers would end up feeling the hurt as
Hamilton went on to score on a wild pitch to give the Giants their
insurance run.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort has pitched well recently, yielding 22 earned runs over
the past 53 innings. But for all the enthusiasm that can be drummed
up for Dreifort, Ismael Valdes, Chan Ho Park, Dave Mlicki and Brian
Bohanon, there can be no silencing this one simple truth: Bohanon
is the only lefty among them.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Bohanon and Johnson would at least switch up
opposing batters a couple times every five days. And that's just
for starters.
</P>
<P>
   For all the changes the Dodgers have made, something still is
missing. It's a mean streak. A Bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hershiser, ``There's definitely something going on here
where they're trying to change the chemistry between the team and
the city (and) the chemistry within the team (and) the chemistry in
the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   If they're serious about winning, it says here they're not
through yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
