<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM COMES SLOWLY TO BOXING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Last of a three-part series) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dean Bonham, a Denver-based sports marketing
executive, has an image of what boxing in this country should look
like.
</P>
<P>
   It has a central governing body, like the NBA or NFL, that
regulates every aspect of the sport _ from matchmaking to rankings,
business practices to safety. It has long-term promotional
campaigns in place.
</P>
<P>
   And it has integrity.
</P>
<P>
   In this boxing world, with only eight champions in each of the
weight divisions, fighters must face their most compelling
challengers or risk sanctions. Finally, the public will see the
fights it most wants to see.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is fantasy. For the past century, boxing could
be likened to a lawless town in the Wild West, where anarchy rules
and only the most cunning _ or most devious _ survive.
</P>
<P>
   Many agree that those in control had better take a close look at
the idealistic model. Clearly, boxing must make changes if it hopes
to thrive into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to adapt to a changing marketplace on a regular basis
or lose our competitive edge. It's as simple as that,'' said Mark
Taffet, senior vice president of TVKO, HBO's pay-per-view arm. &QL; 
MAKING CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   Forces are at work to clean up boxing. Two of the most
vociferous are U.S. senators John McCain (R-Ariz.) and Richard
Bryan (D-Nev.).
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, they co-authored a law to improve safety
standards for boxers. Now, they've introduced legislation that
would protect boxers from being exploited by promoters and enhance
the integrity of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 11 provisions of ``The Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform
Act'':
</P>
<P>
   _All sanctioning bodies (organizations that rank fighters) that
do business in the United States ``must establish objective and
consistent criteria'' and accept no payoffs when they compile their
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   _All contracts between promoters and boxers will be strictly
regulated with the boxers' interest in mind.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``option'' contracts _ binding a boxer to a
promoter as a condition of getting a particular bout _ would be
limited to one year. The objective is to prevent a promoter from
controlling a weight division by coercing options from all
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   _Sanctioning bodies and promoters must submit to state boxing
commissions all contracts and fees before each event.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bryan admit this legislation, as well as their
safety-oriented law, won't change boxing. However, they and many
inside boxing agree that such steps are vital for the health of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' said The Ring editor Nigel Collins, referring to
the proposed act. ``There's a lot of good stuff in there, it's well
thought out. If it passes, it will be a huge step toward getting
rid of the bandits and parasites in the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Those in the sport also are making changes.
</P>
<P>
   Bonham's vision of a central boxing authority probably won't be
realized anytime soon. However, the newly formed Association of
Boxing Commissions could be the embryo of such an entity.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, boxing is regulated by individual state commissions,
some well organized (like California), some not. The purpose of the
ABC is to provide national standards under which the sport would
operate.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, its authority could be expanded to deal with the
proliferation of sanctioning bodies, which has rendered
``championships'' all but meaningless and contributes to the
inability to make the best fights.
</P>
<P>
   One day, some believe, the ABC, under the eye of federal
regulators, could actually rank fighters and establish one champion
in each weight class, ridding the sport of sanctioning bodies
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, its small inroads provide hope for a better
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a (government-sponsored) federal boxing
commission, per se, would work,'' said Marc Ratner, the director of
the Nevada State Athletic Commission. ``I just think it would be
too political...
</P>
<P>
   ``(The ABC) already has elevated itself. Now, we have one set of
rules for the nation on championship fights. I never thought we
could do that. And we're working on a standard set of medical
requirements....
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a lot of things better but there's a lot to be
done.'' &QL; 
CULTIVATING FANS
</P>
<P>
   Boxing's traditional fans _ largely Latino _ are fiercely loyal.
Consistently solid pay-per-view buy rates for compelling fights are
proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly competitive sports market, boxing must reach
new fans _ in particular, young fans.
</P>
<P>
   HBO has taken steps in that direction. Its Boxing After Dark
series on Saturday nights is geared to a young audience and the
network says its ratings are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball, the NFL, the NBA, they're always
re-evaluating their marketing, their ability to meet the needs of
their audience on a regular basis,'' said Taffet, the HBO
executive. ``They try to create a new market every day, hold on
that one and then create another new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The onus is on boxing to do the same thing, to take a more
sophisticated approach to sustain and grow the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo!, says Bonham, president and CEO of The Bonham Group
marketing firm.
</P>
<P>
   Under the auspices of his fictional central authority, the
sport, with one voice, would devise a marketing strategy that would
counteract the sport's negative image.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, fighters such as Naseem Hamed, whose
self-promotion is positively Ali-like, would be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   And all this must be done in the context of a reformed industry,
one whose back-alley ways _ not just its image _ have changed. The
public, Bonham insisted, isn't as ignorant as it might seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core boxing fans are always going to be there,'' Bonham
said. ``The question I have is this: How much bigger and better can
it be? How many of those who are so turned off by boxing that they
would never buy a pay-per-view fight could be convinced to watch a
fight, to attend a fight or an autograph signing?
</P>
<P>
   ``How much more integrated can boxing _ if it's truly a clean
sport, with clean promoters, clean managers _ be in our society?
These are the questions I have.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears change is happening slowly. The legislation written
by McCain and Bryan will have impact if it becomes law. The
prospect of a central authority _ whether it's the ABC or something
like it _ is encouraging. And those in the sport are beginning to
realize it must update its marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   For the foreseeable future, it's up to the Don Kings and Bob
Arums, the HBOs and Showtimes, to rethink the way they operate.
</P>
<P>
   The promoters and managers must take risks and give the public
the fights it wants to see regardless of the matchups the
sanctioning bodies demand of them.
</P>
<P>
   Television networks, whose exclusive contracts with top fighters
hinder competition, must loosen their reins. And, as obvious as it
might seem, they must learn to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is a sport that will continue to underachieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing has been around for centuries,'' said Jay Larkin, head
of Showtime Sports. ``It's always had a black eye. And just when
you think it can't stoop any lower, it does. But I think things are
changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
