</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER BEATS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Orel Hershiser walked through the late
afternoon shadows of Dodger Stadium, he refused to give in to the
twilight.
</P>
<P>
   There were old teammates in the stands and as many old memories
as there were faces in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But at age 40, Hershiser blocked out the echoes Wednesday and
did what he always has done best _ win a game in a pennant race
when his team needed him most.
</P>
<P>
   He lasted six innings on three days rest, giving his new team,
the San Francisco Giants, an emotional 5-3 victory over the Los
Angeles Dodgers, his first love, in front of 34,596.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to run up the tunnel before I went out there to collect
myself,'' Hershiser said. ``And then I threw three straight balls
to the first hitter. It was all still there, the mound, the past. I
told myself, `this is about the future now.'''
</P>
<P>
   The victory snapped a five-game losing streak for the Giants and
moved them 5{ games ahead of the Dodgers in the National League
wild-card race. It also dropped the Dodgers 13{ games behind N.L.
West-leading San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly it was more than that.
</P>
<P>
   It was about Hershiser (8-7) taking the ball the way he had when
he won the 1988 Cy Young Award and World Series MVP the same year.
He was replacing Shawn Estes, the Giants' best pitcher a year ago,
in the rotation after Estes complained of shoulder stiffness that
could land him on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had won the first two games of the series and were
desperate for a sweep, heading into St. Louis for four games
beginning tonight. Hershiser even fell behind 3-0 after three
innings. But then the bulldog, the nickname given him by his former
manager Tom Lasorda, began to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   He shut down the Dodgers for his final three innings. The Giants
tied the game on home runs by Jeff Kent and Brent Mayne in the
fourth off Darren Dreifort (5-8) and went ahead for good when Mayne
singled home J.T. Snow in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all he had done for us, it was time to get him out of
there,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``He came in on three
days rest and did everything we asked. That is the way the guy has
always been.''
</P>
<P>
   As he walked in after warming up, Hershiser received a mild
ovation from crowd. The game began at 5:05 and many fans were still
on the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been gone 3{ years,'' said Hershiser, who signed with
Cleveland after the 1994 season. ``A lot of things have been going
on here. Plus, I don't know if fans here are feeling very
sympathetic about baseball these days.''
</P>
<P>
   After throwing three consecutive balls to Wilton Guerrero to
open the bottom of the first, Hershiser stepped off the rubber to
collect himself.
</P>
<P>
   He got Guerrero to fly to right then struck out Juan Castro and
Raul Mondesi to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser (8-7), who defeated the Dodgers 6-3 on July 3 in San
Francisco, had been struggling through most of his previous five
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he allowed a run in the second and two in the third
when Mondesi singled home two runs. There was no shame in getting
hit by Mondesi, who went 14 for 25 (.560) in six games against the
Giants this month.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was getting the better of the game until the fourth,
when Kent opened with a homer. After retiring Snow on an infield
out, Dreifort walked Stan Javier and hung a slider to Mayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a problem with the pitch I threw Kent,''
Dreifort said. ``I had a big problem with the pitch I threw Mayne.
And I never should have walked Javier. One bad inning, but that's
one too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, like Hershiser 10 years ago, is a power pitcher with a
sharp sinker. But he said he was not affected by the nostalgia
surrounding Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Others were convinced it was just Hershiser's night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could just see all the adrenaline in him tonight,'' said
Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman, who played with Hershiser in 1987.
``He was pumped. We wanted this win with St. Louis coming up, but
we couldn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, who signed with the Giants during the off-season
after three years in Cleveland, actually has played with very few
of today's Dodgers. Aside from Mondesi, Eric Karros is the only
teammate left.
</P>
<P>
   But probably his biggest emotions were reserved for physical
therapist Pat Screnar, who helped him resume his career in 1990
after Hershiser underwent radical reconstructive shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Former teammates Steve Garvey, Steve Yeager, Ken Landreaux and
even fired manager Bill Russell were on hand. But this one was as
much for Screnar as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very weird seeing Pat in the dugout,'' Hershiser said.
``He's the reason I'm still pitching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
