<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7513 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-SPARKS-MONARCHS-L     07-16 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-MONARCHS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS BEAT MONARCHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Tamecka Dixon scored six of her team-high 22
points in overtime Wednesday night, giving the Sparks their first
victory over the Sacramento Monarchs, 81-76, before an announced
crowd of 5,774 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Toler and Lisa Leslie had 16 points each for the Sparks,
who improved to 5-9 with the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not allowing them to sweep us for the season is definitely a
positive, but we have to be ready for Houston on Friday night,''
said Leslie, who also had seven rebounds and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   The win snapped a three-game losing streak against the Monarchs,
who fell to 4-11. But it didn't come easily for the Sparks, who
played their first overtime game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs' Tangela Smith missed a layup, and Toler got the
rebound and passed it down the court to Lisa Leslie, who shipped it
to Mwadi Mabika, giving the Sparks a 75-71 edge with 2:07 to play
in the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   Smith cut it to two with a layup with 1:42 to play, but she was
later forced to foul Dixon, who made two free throws with 19.3
seconds remaining, giving the Sparks a four-point advantage. Mabika
converted a pair of free throws 10 seconds later to seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   In regulation, Latasha Byears scored with 17.3 seconds to go to
tie the score at 73. The Sparks who have not shown they can wrap up
a close game in the final seconds, stayed true to form.
</P>
<P>
   Ticha Penicheiro stole the ball from Toler, but was called for
traveling, giving the ball back to Sparks. With nine-tenths of a
second to go in regulation, time ran out on Leslie, who missed a
10-foot baseline shot.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Sacramento had used a 12-2 run to erase a 10-point
Sparks lead. With 2:46 to play, a putback by Adia Barnes tied the
score at 63 for the first time since the opening minutes of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Sparks shot 47 percent (14 of 30) to the
Monarchs' 29 percent (11 of 41) to take a 35-24 halftime lead.
Leslie led the charge with 13 points and blocked four shots.
</P>
<P>
   Byears struggled in the first half, missing eight of her 10
attempts, while Barnes was 1 of 6 from the field for Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks led by as many as 14 points three times in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   On one such occasion, the Monarchs trimmed their deficit to
31-21 on back-to-back baskets by Franthea Price. But Eugenia Rycraw
and Dixon both scored to give the Sparks their third 14-point
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   However, Penicheiro was open for a 3-pointer with 33.3 seconds
left, to close the gap for Sacramento, and with time winding down
she stole the ball from Dixon to deny the Sparks the last shot.
</P>
<P>
   Byears finished with 16 points for the Monarchs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7514 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-16 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY BRINGS PERSPECTIVE, IRONS TO OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Amid the trepidations, lamentations and
exclamations that came from those golfers who tramped the
gale-scoured links of Royal Birkdale while holding down their
derbies, there was this from John Daly on the eve of the oldest of
tournaments:
</P>
<P>
   Let the wind blow.
</P>
<P>
   Daly has seen worse things.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the wind blows hard, I've got a chance,'' he said
Wednesday, offering the least apprehension of any of the world's
great golfers about Thursday's commencement of the 127th British
Open on the shores of the Irish Sea. ``If it stops and guys make
putts, I don't have as good a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As one who has already won an Open, in 1995 at St. Andrews, and
as one who has the power to tear a hole in the breeze, Daly is
about as unaffected by Thursday's expected conditions as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   And as one who has been affected by many other conditions, wind
hardly ranks as his most formidable adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day that I wake up is like winning a major,'' Daly said.
``I've been doing real good the last 15 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly is, of course, the most public of recovering alcoholics in
major professional sports. His multiple falls from the wagon have
provided some of the most poignant drama in golf.
</P>
<P>
   So far, his current sobriety has served him well in mind, soul
and golf. He even reunited with his third wife, Paulette, about two
months ago. But his body ... well, he can't have everything.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has attempted to eat everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burgers, pizza, steak, any chocolate I can get my hands on,''
he explained of his nutritional regimen that swelled his 5-foot-11
frame to 247 pounds in March. He's since dropped 20 pounds, but he
remains as round as his game is long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tend to go from one addiction to another,'' Daly said.
``My addiction seems to be food now. My mind is tougher but my body
is changing a lot. I'm overweight and out of shape.''
</P>
<P>
   But to the profound joy of middle-agers everywhere, Daly not
only seems unbothered by the corpulence, he thinks it might have
given him a tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually helped because my right arm hugs this fat belly
right here,'' he said, clutching his side. ``It never gets out of
place now. When I lose weight, (my arm) flies all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way, I guess, I'm made. I'm made to be fat, so
there's no sense in worrying about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, 32, now is possessed of the ballast _ or sand, as
ex-Seahawk coach Chuck Knox used to say admiringly of his
heavy-butted offensive linemen _ that can resist the urgent air
that circles and swoops over the dunes here that once, in 1961,
ripped the press tent from its moorings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the wind blows like this, par is one helluva score,'' he
said of the par-70 links, considerably toughened and improved since
the Open last rotated through here in 1991. Even though the course
is 7,018 yards, Daly said he's likely to keep his legendary driver
in his bag, to the disappointment of his many British fans who want
to see the first man to reach Ireland from England with a golf
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You miss a fairway here, you can't really advance the ball
unless you get a good lie,'' he said. ``You're dead. There is no
let-up. You can't really go to a hole and say, `This is a birdie
hole here.'''
</P>
<P>
   During a practice round Wednesday, Daly went
uncharacteristically conservative, almost completely abandoning his
driver to avoid the gorse, which is plant life that dreams of
growing up to become barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   He did the same last month for the first two rounds of the U.S.
Open in San Francisco, making like Jay Buhner forced to lay down
multiple sacrifice bunts.
</P>
<P>
   Drove him crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My patience lasted two days at the U.S. Open,'' he said,
referring to the unleashing of his driver that inflated his gallery
as well as his score.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it has been and probably always will be for Daly
_ mercurial. He has won only four tournaments in his PGA career,
but two were majors, including the 1991 PGA. Last year his best
tourney finish was seventh, but he remains one of the game's most
charismatic figures, particularly here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I've been over here, it's wonderful,'' he said.
``Everywhere I've been, it's great. That motivates me more than
anything. I can't have anything better, gallery-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   He would love to entertain his followers, but he fears the
consequences of unsheathing his terrible, swift sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem with my life right now _ I don't know how
the hell I'm going to wake up every morning,'' he said. ``I don't
know what mood I'm going to be in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I'm saying I'm going to hit irons. Tomorrow I may wake
up and hit the driver on the first hole. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   That is perhaps the most endearing thing about Daly. In a field
of men who tend to think they are masters of their universes, Daly
suffers no illusions about having all the answers.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing he knows for sure this week is that he wants to
get his cherubic behind among some kindred folk at an Alcoholics
Anonymous meeting somewhere here in the pastoral suburbs of
Lancashire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to find a meeting, or just have one,'' Daly said,
chuckling. ``There's drunks all over this world, man _ we're
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   What wind?
</P>
<P>
   What fat?
</P>
<P>
   What putt?
</P>
<P>
   Some days _ many days _ are made simply by waking up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
