<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7515 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL IN ALL, JUST A BRICK IN THE WALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Drat! The phone lines at Ticketmaster were totally
jammed Wednesday, which meant I could not place the order for my
brick.
</P>
<P>
   What brick, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the people in charge of the Mariners' new $425 million
ballpark are going to let baseball fans have a little piece of
Safeco Field glory, with the operative word here being ``little.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Public Facilities District announced that for $75
plus tax, you can purchase a brick. That price includes having your
brick inscribed and placed in the sidewalk along the Royal Brougham
Fan Walk. (Just call 206-622-4487, if you can get through.)
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a bargain for getting your name on The House That
Griffey Built. Or is it The House That John Ellis Built? I forget.
But it's not a bad deal considering Safeco Insurance will shell out
$40 million (over 20 years) for exclusive naming rights to the new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Forty million or $75, plus tax? It's a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For Safeco, the ballpark will be a major feature in branding its
corporate name. Savvy business practice of the '90s foisted upon us
_ the doltish, voiceless general population.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who lost sleep over the selling of Safeco Field should
not exactly blame the insurance guys. Stadia all over this fair
land have come to be drably named: Bank One Ballpark, Qualcomm
Park, the RCA Dome and KeyArena. Yawners, huh?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing to be sorry about is that a more radically named
company (like Amazon.com, Yahoo! or Bed, Bath &AMP; Beyond) didn't have
the nerve to outbid Safeco. Then we'd be excited about our new
ballyard, all right.
</P>
<P>
   At least with this bricks-for-fans announcement, Mariner fans
and concerned taxpayers who felt betrayed by the corporate sellout
have a chance to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Brick inscription suggestion No. 1:
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Safeco: Brand This!
</P>
<P>
   And think of the entertainment value. Imagine the fun you and
your family will have at the new park, roaming Royal Brougham Fan
Walk in search of your personalized brick. Heck, you might hardly
care if Griffey is going 4-for-5 with two jacks and an
over-the-back Willie Mays catch. You'll have more important
business, like visiting your brick!
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, look, honey. There it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where? I don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there, next to that cluster of Dr. Martens and Nikes.
... Excuse me, sir. Could I ask you to step over a little? You're
standing on our brick. Thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of allowing people to purchase an inscribed brick is
hardly novel. Many of the new parks have done it. And in Atlanta
during the 1996 Summer Olympics, Centennial Park was a sea of
inscripted red bricks, all of which survived the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, Pike Place Market raised $1.6 million for renovation
and a new floor in 1986 when 45,600 tiles were sold to the public
for $35 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   So the Safeco Field brick idea isn't totally awful, especially
since the money raised for selling upwards of 10,000 bricks will be
used not to defray construction costs, but to pay for a baseball
museum _ one that will feature memorabilia from Little League to
the Pacific Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   However, the metaphor involved in the inscripted brick walkway
is just a little too rich to let slip by us.
</P>
<P>
   Brick inscription suggestion No. 2:
</P>
<P>
   Hi, I'm a taxpayer. Step on me.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to the logical question: What are you going to
say on your brick?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A lot of diehard baseball lovers will see this brick thing as a
fun opportunity. This includes my brother, who told me Wednesday he
plans to buy a brick and inscribe it with the name of his
soon-to-be-born child _ which I hope isn't a boy since my brother's
favorite baseball player was Lenny Dykstra and I couldn't tolerate
a nephew named ``Nails.''
</P>
<P>
   We're all for free speech, but it just makes sense that some of
the more cynical among us will be tempted to use this brick thing
as a form of personal protest. After all, a bulk of Seattle and
King County citizens did not actually agree to this stadium, since
the September 1995 public referendum fell a few votes short of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium naysayers could, for the soul-cleansing price of $75
plus tax, undertake a bit of mischief now, laying such zesty bricks
as:
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. Thiss Z. Aripoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Fuhd-Stampz Family
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ineeda Tacks Break
</P>
<P>
   Jack Thisoneout, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   On Grand Opening Night next July, who will join me out on Royal
Brougham Fan Walk, searching for amusing rebel bricks like these?
</P>
<P>
   It's a date, then. We'll head out there immediately after Pink
Floyd sings the national anthem, just as the rock group launches
into its famous song.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear it now ... 45,600 fans crammed into the
natural-grass Safeco Field, Griffey in center and eight minor
leaguers surrounding him. We'll sing in unison: ``All in all you're
just another brick in the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   A fitting tribute to the real builders of Seattle's new
ballyard.
</P>
<P>
   Just another brick in the wall, or walk, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
