<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BO     07-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ MASTERFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ These are the games, so precious and few, that become
even better in the retelling, because they usually happen just once
or so in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   What Roger Clemens did here, 11 years ago, Pedro Martinez
duplicated Wednesday night before a packed house of 33,501 in
Fenway Park that sweated and screamed and sweated some more before
Martinez completed a 1-0, four-hit, nine-strikeout masterpiece over
the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in tropical heat more suited for his native Manoguayabo
than for Yawkey Way, and with the new 1999 All-Star logo adorning
the Green Monster as backdrop behind him, Martinez outdueled fellow
Dominican All-Star Bartolo Colon while shutting down one of
baseball's most dangerous lineups on just four singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A game like this, you take it home and flavor (sic) it,'' said
Martinez, who insisted there was no bitter aftertaste left from
being skipped over last week as the All-Star starter by Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove, who Wednesday night had no choice but to
watch Martinez at the absolute top of his craft.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams had Tom Gordon warming up in the
bullpen, but said there was no question that Martinez would come
out for the ninth, giving him the chance to be the first pitcher
since Clemens to record a 1-0 complete-game win in Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to pick up my teammates a little bit,'' Martinez
said, alluding to a Red Sox offense that has yet to find itself in
the second half. ``They did it for me when I was struggling, and
now it was my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The only run Wednesday night was scored on a fifth-inning home
run by DH Midre Cummings, who has barely been heard from since his
two electrifying home runs in late April against the Tigers, five
days apart. Cummings, the stand-in for newly disabled Reggie
Jefferson, delivered a 408-foot home run into the right-field
grandstand to open the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chibo is in the house,'' said Martinez, who for reasons known
only to himself has decided Cummings's nickname should be the
Spanish word for goat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I saw Midre hit that ball, I said, `I will have to win
with that one. I will win with that one.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cummings had driven in just two runs in just 33 at-bats since
June 1, but launched a first-pitch fastball from Colon into the
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time before, we struck him out with the same pitch,'' said
Indians catcher Sandy Alomar. ``We tried to go in and back him off
the plate a little bit, but the pitch was on the white and not the
black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he'd keep it fair, but he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 12-3 after his second complete-game shutout, has an
ERA of 1.17 in his last six starts, giving up just six earned runs
in 46 innings. He allowed singles by Manny Ramirez and Alomar
(infield hit) in the second, then did not allow another hit until
Brian Giles singled with two out in the seventh. In between the
hits by Alomar and Giles, he set down 15 Indians in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great, great changeup,'' said pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan. ``He threw 41 changeups, 27 for strikes, and got 11 outs
on his changeup. His fastball? He topped out at 97, was still
throwing at 95 in the ninth, and sat at 94-95 all game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome. What a show for national TV (ESPN). A baseball
night, playoff atmosphere. It was good for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez did not walk a batter until the eighth, when Alomar
drew a one-out pass, and one out later, he walked his second and
last batter, pitching carefully to pinch hitter Jim Thome. The
Indians' strongman was still feeling the effects of being hit in
the forearm by the Yankees' Andy Pettitte the night before and
wasn't in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But with two on and two out, Martinez coaxed Kenny Lofton to pop
out to third baseman John Valentin, who opened the next inning by
making a terrific barehanded pickup of Omar Vizquel's bid for a
bunt base hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to keep him from bunting,'' said Valentin, who
stood so close to the plate he could have shaken hands with the
Indians' shortstop, ``and he still almost got a hit, that's how
great a bunt it was.''
</P>
<P>
   David Justice reached out and hit an end-of-the-bat liner into
center for the Indians' fourth hit. But Martinez blew an outside
fastball past Manny Ramirez, the Indians' cleanup hitter, and with
the fans on their feet retired Brian Giles on a game-ending tapper
to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro did a great job, Bartolo did a great job,'' Valentin
said. ``We're fortunate that Midre got a good pitch to hit, or we'd
still be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that long before he came to the ballpark, he
expected it would go this way against Colon, the 23-year-old
righthander who is just three years younger than Martinez but
considers Mr. Pedro his hero. But while Martinez was braced for a
duel with Colon, who still leads the league in ERA with a 2.48
mark, a fraction ahead of Martinez (2.72), the Red Sox ace said he
sensed the crowd had something else in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was very confusing for me,'' he said. ``I saw the
fans getting on Mo (Vaughn), I don't know why. Then they were
standing for me. They weren't as loud early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they love their offense. It was pretty quiet until the
last inning.''
</P>
<P>
   But then there was thunder on the Fens, the kind that will echo
long into memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
