<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-PITCHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINICAN DANDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Maybe it's something in the water they drink in the
Dominican Republic. The tiny country produces so many great young
arms, it's getting to be hard to keep track of them all.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' 1-0 victory over the Cleveland Indians Wednesday
night at Fenway Park was a marvelous showdown between two of the
best Dominican pitchers in the major leagues. Pedro Martinez (12-4)
turned in his 10th career shutout, and loser Bartolo Colon made
just one mistake but wound up losing because of it.
</P>
<P>
   But anybody who saw the 99 mile-per-hour fastball on Colon's
120th and final pitch of the game will tell you the 23-year-old
pitcher is a superstar in the making. In only his second major
league season, Colon made the AL All-Star team this year.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, Colon is probably the best pitcher to come out of the
Dominican Republic since ... Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   One guess as to Colon's hero?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a honor to pitch against him,'' said Colon, who at 185
pounds dwarfs Martinez. ``Pedro was one of my idols and it was a
dream of my father to see me facing him. I felt I did a good job,
too. But I made one mistake. And in baseball, you have to pay for
that mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistake was a home run by Midre Cummings in the fifth
inning. Rather than throw a strike, he tried to back Cummings off
the plate with a fastball inside. He missed, and Cummings's quick
bat did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   That looked very familiar to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told by Felipe Alou at Montreal,'' said Martinez, ``that
once when you find your rhythm, keep going. When you're throwing
strikes and doing things the way you want, keep going. He got ahead
sometimes and then he came back and threw some bad pitches. That
was me three-four years ago. I'd throw strike one or strike two
then mess around and make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's role models were Hall of Famer Juan Marichal and his
brother, Ramon. Not only were both great pitchers, they were
teachers. If Colon listens to his mentors, he might some day be as
good as Martinez. Colon not only throws in the high 90s, but he'd
be doing it the eighth and ninth innings. If he can harness that
raw power, like Martinez has learned to do, he could go a lot
farther than his 9-5 record would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy throws 100 miles an hour,'' said Martinez. ``He's
probably the best arm to come from the Dominican in the last five
years. It's funny he should look up to me. I'm smaller. It's a
great honor. Especially coming from a guy who could be 10 times
better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Colon was on a shuttle between Buffalo (7-1, 2.22
ERA) and Cleveland (4-7, 5.65). With a divisional title at stake,
Colon simply had to wait his turn. But Wednesday night was his 20th
start of the season, and with each outing he gets better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can throw the ball 98 miles an hour after throwing 140
pitches,'' said Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove. ``He's been over
130 pitches three times, but in the last inning of those games I
left him in he was there, he was throwing 98-99 m.p.h. He's a real
strong kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent and velocity have always been there. He's just
starting to get his breaking stuff over for strikes, also his
changeup. I think he's become convinced that he can pitch in the
big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great pitching matchup,'' said Indians catcher Sandy
Alomar. ``He did a good job of getting out of jams. Unfortunately,
we didn't score a lot of runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
