<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-UNITED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FALL TO UNITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It's the same old frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution once again played well against D.C. United, but
once again, they fell by one goal.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Lassiter's 12th goal of the season, scored from directly in
front of the net after passes from Jaime Moreno and Mike Slivinski
in the 81st minute, gave D.C. United a 1-0 win over the Revolution
before 17,202 Wednesday night at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out to block what turned out to be a pass when Moreno
had the ball,'' said Revolution goalkeeper Ian Feuer. ``If you
stayed on, I would be asked why I didn't come out. Basically, you
have to play the one with the ball, and that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes before that, Lassiter headed a crossing pass from
John Harkes toward the goal, but the ball was high by about 3 feet,
causing Lassiter and Harkes to place their hands over their heads
in despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to see him come back,'' D.C. United coach Bruce
Arena said. ``Lassiter did miss a header, but he's the type of
player whose job it is to score goals. Roy knows what he's about;
he's supposed to score goals, so when he misses some goals, he's
the first to get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in four games that D.C. United, Major
League Soccer's best team each of the previous two seasons, has
beaten the Revolution this year, twice in shootouts. Each game has
been decided by a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never pleased when we lose,'' said Revolution coach Thomas
Rongen. ``It was a heartbreaker. We played this team well, but the
difference in the game was that we didn't put in our chances, even
though we played them toe-to-toe and head-to-head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective was to get three points; we didn't come here for
a shootout,'' Arena said. ``We play tough against a lot of teams.
We're the target for other teams on our schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution (5-14) were in a 3-5-2 defensive alignment for
just the second time this season, and it worked well as they
controlled play for most of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of game D.C. United (16-5) expected, especially
when Arena saw Edwin Gorter, the Revolution's top assist man, as
the sweeper, standing in front of Revolution defenders Mike Burns
and Richard Goulooze in the different alignment.
</P>
<P>
   On the offensive end, however, the Revolution didn't fare well.
They once again had difficulty finishing off scoring opportunities.
Joe-Max Moore had his chances, as did Johnny Torres and Raul Diaz
Arce, but they all went for naught.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of chances for the Revolution: A crossing pass
from Imad Baba to Moore with 33:20 left in the first half looked
promising, but Moore was stopped. Moore had another shot along the
right side with 27 minutes left in the first half, but the ball
went wide to the right by a foot and a half. And then Diaz Arce
missed from the right side on a header, with 10:55 remaining. Two
other late first-half shots, by Baba and Torres, also went awry.
</P>
<P>
   And with 16:07 remaining in the second half, Moore tried a shot
from just inside the box from the right side, but D.C. United
netminder Scott Garlick stretched his fingers out and knocked away
the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work on our shooting a lot,'' Rongen said. ``The players
take their shots in practice, but you can't teach a forward how to
finish. Not when he's in his mid-20s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
