<HEADER>
A7535 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-DEVILRAYS-     07-16 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-DEVILRAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT DEVIL RAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The slumping Anaheim Angels met the slumping
Tampa Bay Devil Rays on Wednesday night at Edison Field, so
something had to give.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had lost nine of 11 and have not looked anything like
the first-place team they are. But the expansion Devil Rays snapped
an 11-game losing streak only one night earlier, and have looked
everything like a team that went into the game 33{ games out of
first place in the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   Angels first baseman Cecil Fielder broke a tie score with a solo
homer in the fourth inning, then drove in another run with a
two-out single in the fifth, helping the Angels to a 4-2 win before
a crowd of 19,681.
</P>
<P>
   With Texas losing Wednesday night, the Angels increased their AL
West lead to 1{ games.
</P>
<P>
   Though Fielder's two RBI _ giving him a team-leading 64 _
provided the margin of victory for the Angels, reliever Shigetoshi
Hasegawa (4-1) deserves most of the credit for this one.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa entered the game in the fifth inning after starter
Chuck Finley had to leave with a cut on his right knee. Finley, who
injured the knee covering first base on an infield grounder,
received ``several'' stitches and is listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa pitched 31/3 scoreless innings to get the win over
Devil Rays starter Wilson Alvarez (4-7). Troy Percival pitched 11/3
perfect innings to earn his 27th save.
</P>
<P>
   Finley sailed through the first three innings of the game before
giving up two unearned runs in the fourth. In the fifth, Dwight
Winn led off with a chopper behind the bag at first, which was
fielded cleanly by Fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, however, was late covering first, and he slid on his
knees as he tried to tag Winn going by. Winn was safe, and Finley
had a cut on his right knee that forced him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some kind of cut,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``When I went out there at first I thought it was just a
scrape. The only thing we could think of was that he hit a rock or
something. It was that long (two inches) and that deep (half-inch).
(Trainer) Rick Smith said he was going to need stitches, but they
couldn't close it. There was no skin left.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Angels clinging to a 3-2 lead, Hasegawa replaced Finley
and performed a high-wire act, getting himself into trouble before
getting out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa immediately gave up a hit-and-run single to Miguel
Cairo as Winn took third. After Cairo stole second, Hasegawa struck
out Quinton McCracken on a 3-2 pitch for the first out of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa then walked Bobby Smith on a 3-2 pitch to load the
bases, but struck out Aaron Ledesma on a 3-2 pitch for the second
out of the inning. Hasegawa went 3-2 to Paul Sorrento, who fouled
out to third baseman Dave Hollins despite colliding with catcher
Matt Walbeck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
