A7536 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-16 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ, MOYER TOUGH ON TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In case you are wondering how long this will last _
the current group of Mariners, not their recent surge _ you're not
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez is curious, too.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is not oblivious to the rumor mill that mentions his
name in possible trades. The Mariner designated hitter remains
cool, though. Ken Griffey Jr. was much more blunt before the M's
knocked off the Minnesota Twins, 4-1, last night at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey suggested the Mariners simply blow up their new ballpark
if they trade certain players.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Martinez is on Griffey's list of untouchables.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Martinez said he would love to play at Safeco Field.
He wants to set off the fireworks there like he has all week at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about (the team trading me). It could happen,'' said
Martinez, who went 2-for-3 with a double and a home run that
propelled the Mariners to their third straight win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen. I don't know what I'm
going to do if I get traded.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their 5-2 record since the All-Star break, the Mariners
figure to make a deal before the July 31 trading deadline. The club
is still 11 games behind Anaheim in the American League West. The
M's will be pressed shortly on whether they will have to start
preparing for next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners last month said they are not going to trade
disgruntled pitcher Randy Johnson. There have been rumblings of the
team moving Martinez, an aging yet effective hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``His production is good. His RBI and home run production is
where you expect him to be,'' M's manager Lou Piniella said of
Martinez. ``You're accustomed to seeing Edgar hit .330. He's
hitting .294 or .295. A lot of people would take that very
gladly.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said the Mariners haven't yet talked to him about next
season. The club has an option to pick up the final year of his
contract for more than $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he would be devastated if he were traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played here for a long time. Yes I'd be disappointed. ...
I feel like I can play. Sometimes I think I want to play four or
five more years,'' said Martinez, who later added: ``As long as I
can still hit I'm going to be playing (somewhere).''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of wins, consistent defense and pitching, the
Mariners haven't been short on power this season. Last night, the
long ball gave the Mariners breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Martinez hit two homers in a 10-3 win against the
Texas Rangers. He ignited a three-run sixth inning last night.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez put the Mariners ahead 2-1 with his 18th home run _ a
solo shot to left field. Two batters later, Dan Wilson stepped up
with Jay Buhner at first and smacked a two-run homer to virtually
the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   Both long balls came off Minnesota loser LaTroy Hawkins (5-9).
</P>
<P>
   The power surge gave the Mariners all the runs starter Jamie
Moyer needed. Moyer, who was on cruise control most of the night,
earned his sixth victory. Mike Timlin pitched the ninth for his
fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the start that Moyer would give himself a good
chance at a victory. In his seven losses, Moyer posted a 6.86 ERA.
Conversely, his ERA is 0.65 in the five previous wins.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer also benefitted from solid defense behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have not committed an error in 242/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference,'' Moyer said of the team's improved
defense. ``We don't have to throw as many pitches. It's a plus. You
can't play the game missing one or two things. You have to do
everything to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota rattled Moyer only in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Lawton led off with a base hit and took second when Paul
Molitor drew a walk. The Twins then loaded the bases after Marty
Cordova walked. Lawton eventually tagged and scored off Ron
Coomer's sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer then got David Ortiz to ground into a double play that
ended the threat. The Twins managed only a 1-0 lead after that
frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the key to the game,'' Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners tied the game in their half of the fourth behind
Buhner's RBI double. Martinez scored from first on the play after
he walked with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who is often teased for being slow, turned on the
afterburners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very fast,'' Martinez joked when asked about his
speed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
