<HEADLINE>
NO SHOCK: MER CURY VICTORIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Continuing its push into uncharted success, the
Mercury increased its winning streak to a franchise record four
games and rose to eight games over .500 for the first time with a
methodical 73-60 win Wednesday over the Detroit Shock.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but Michele Timms guarantees a fifth straight win
Saturday over the New York Liberty, which embarrassed Phoenix at
America West Arena last season in the WNBA playoff semifinals and
won, 71-68, when the teams played June 29 at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said to each other in New York after the game, when they
come to our house, it's going to be a different story,'' Timms
said. ``We promised ourselves that. If anyone's in town, they want
to come down and watch the game because that's going to be
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Timms wore her lucky World Championships shoes _ ``I needed a
boost'' _ at the risk of being fined for the Australian green color
scheme. League officials might not even bother with the point
guard's footwear once they read Coach Cheryl Miller's comments
about the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the season-best performance by Andrea Kuklova off
the bench, Miller launched into a controlled critique of the
officials for calling tic-tac fouls away from the basket (like one
against Kuklova) but not protecting the posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reward for aggressive play by the offensive post
player or penetrator,'' said Miller, who received her second
technical foul of the season early in the second half. ``I've tried
reasoning with the officials, asking questions, and I cannot get a
consistent answer as to why so many touch officials are being
called away from the basket and nothing (underneath).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer Gillom cannot get to the free-throw line, and that's
ludicrous, that's ridiculous, it's upsetting. I'm just glad she
doesn't get frustrated, but I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to be more attune in making sure I don't dance up and
down the sidelines is ridiculous. They're more focused on my _ if
you want to call it _ antics than officiating the game. That's what
frustrating. It will probably cost me $500 or more, but I've got a
rich brother.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine is almost a certainty. Houston guard Cynthia Cooper was
tapped for $300 for criticizing officials after the defending
champion Comets' only loss of the season to the Mercury on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   Good or bad, the officiating wasn't much of a factor as Phoenix
(11-3) took the lead three minutes into the first half and never
gave it back. The game was nothing like that in Detroit a week
earlier when the expansion Shock led, 44-32, at halftime and only
succumbed, 78-76, on a buzzer-beating three-pointer by Gillom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the type of team you don't want it to go down to the
wire,'' Miller said. ``We didn't want it to get close then have
someone win it at the buzzer like we were able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The best Mercury lineup was all reserves, considering Michelle
Griffiths is starting in place of injured Toni Foster. She and
Marlies Askamp in the post with Kristi Harrower, Kuklova and Brandy
Reed on the perimeter were the group that took the lead to a
game-high 16 points (72-56) and sent the Shock (7-9) to its fifth
loss in the last six games.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, a third-round draft pick and easily the Mercury's most
athletic player, had five points, four rebounds and four assists in
a season-high 19 minutes. Kuklova scored nine points, one off her
high, and added three assists in 17 minutes. Askamp had nine points
and Griffiths 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing what the coaches want from me,'' Reed said. ``Every
time I touch it, I don't have to score. Our ballclub is very
structured, and I'm beginning to learn that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
