<HEADER>
A7542 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-DRY-TRAIN     07-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-DRY-TRAINING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRON MEN  
 NHL PLAYERS BOARD OFF-SEASON TRAINING EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ZUCKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mental image is at first odd, maybe even a little ludicrous.
Rick Tocchet, a 13-year NHL veteran and a key member of the
Coyotes, spending his summer working out at Gold's Gym in Venice
Beach, Calif., with a 37-year-old ex-college hockey player at his
side.
</P>
<P>
   This is the famous ``Muscle Beach'' we're talking about, home to
hundreds of beefed-up wannabes who have nothing better to do than
flaunt their pecs and abs to scores of passers-by. It's the last
place you would expect to find a professional athlete diligently
working on his off-season training.
</P>
<P>
   Then you hear some of the other names involved _ Chris Chelios,
Rob Blake, Jeremy Roenick, Bob Probert, Oleg Tverdosky, Petr
Svoboda and Chris Simon. Now this starts to sound intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in the off-season anymore,'' said Tocchet, who
participates in Pro Camp, a unique training program designed
specifically for professional athletes. ``Nowadays, it's an
11-month-a-year job, maybe even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to move to LA for two months to train. It's hard to
get guys out here, but when people see the results . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The program, which Tocchet said has him feeling _ and playing _
like he is three or four years younger, is the brainchild of T.R.
Goodman, a self-professed ``frustrated athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman never realized his dream to play professionally after
lettering in college hockey and lacrosse in in the East in the
early 1980s. He went on to become an athletic trainer in
California, met several NHL players who were dissatisfied with
their own teams' training programs and decided he could do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I learned about what was available to the
professional athlete,'' Goodman said, ``the more I realized it was
a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Bold words for a relative unknown in the sports world, but words
that more professional athletes are starting to take seriously.
When Tocchet came to Goodman four years ago, looking to improve his
ailing back, Pro Camp consisted of only a handful of NHL players,
most notably Chicago Blackhawks defender Chelios.
</P>
<P>
   Word got around, though, and Goodman's program now boasts 35 to
40 NHL players, most of them veterans trying to regain their past
form or young prospects trying to gain an edge, plus a couple of
NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still ever-evolving,'' Goodman said. ``It's taken a
certain number of years for guys to come here and surrender
themselves to me and to be willing to do whatever I tell them to
unconditionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman has been able to get these athletes to ``surrender to
him'' because he caters his unique training program to each
individual. The result of his three-month program, each athlete
said, is phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees us play during the season and sees what we need to
work on,'' said Jason Doig, the Coyotes' impressive 21-year-old
defenseman who has played in only 19 NHL games in his short career.
``And he also listens to what we tell him. He combines that and
comes up with a program that's catered toward you. You're working
on stuff that you know is designed just for you. That's what makes
him special.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things Goodman does when he begins to work with
an athlete is ``try to find what the makeup of the person is.''
This includes determining such physical traits as rotated
shoulders, tilted pelvises or misaligned hips.
</P>
<P>
   For example, after Philadelphia Flyers defenseman Svoboda
underwent neck surgery last year after taking a hard hit to the
side of his head, Goodman discovered that Svoboda's shoulders are
rotated significantly forward. This caused him to pull his
trapezius muscles, placing added stress on his spine. Where other
trainers would have tried to work on Svoboda's strained muscles,
Goodman helped him bring his shoulders back to a more natural
position.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman's Pro Camp features three phases. The first,
rehabilitation of the body, includes regular visits with a massage
therapist, a structural massage therapist (who aligns your body)
and a nutritionist. The second consists of two or three weeks of
lifting heavier weights and simulated skating.
</P>
<P>
   The last, which Tocchet affectionately calls ``the dreaded
circuit,'' is headlined by one hour of constant exercise each day
for three weeks without any rest.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Players say they have an easier time surviving the
arduous NHL season without succumbing to injury or fatigue. Players
like Tocchet, Chelios and Blake, who have battled through injuries
during their careers, said they now feel they are in great shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Kings' Blake, for example, had been plagued by
injuries for six years before joining Pro Camp, playing in only six
games in 1995-96. Last year, he played 81 games and won the NHL's
Norris Trophy, which honors the league's top defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a coincidence,'' Tocchet said. ``There's nothing
worse than a team going into March or April and to have four or
five guys get hurt on you. I wish I knew about this when I was 20,
21 years old. I probably could have stayed injury-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro Camp also attracts younger hockey players, such as Doig, who
are on the cusp of becoming impact players in the NHL but are still
trying to gain an edge by working out in the off-season. Though it
requires quite a bit of sacrifice from the players, Doig said the
results are well worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe that at this point of my career, I have a
lot to prove,'' Doig said. ``I'm going to sacrifice my time, and
I'm willing to do it because of how much it helps me.''
</P>
<P>
   As more players go out on their own during the off-season and
discover what their efforts produce, more and more teams may
consider instituting these kinds of programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to win Stanley Cups, yeah, they will,'' Tocchet
said. ``The teams that are quicker getting to these programs are
going to win Stanley Cups.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
