<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH OPEN IS TOUGHEST TEST IN GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southport, England - Mark O'Meara claims a golf ball doesn't
know how old you are. ``It just sits there,'' stupidly, the
41-year-old Masters champion implies, ``waiting to be struck.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for any other object designed to be hit,
pitched, punted, dribbled, served.
</P>
<P>
   But a golf ball is perceptive, and intelligent for its size.
Studies that measure brain waves show that a golf ball is smarter
than a football or a tennis ball and far brighter than a badminton
birdie. Besides a high IQ, a golf ball is born with an adventurous
spirit and the willfulness of a headstrong child.
</P>
<P>
   A dimpled ball has a mind of its own. It oftentimes will do
whatever it wishes, on a whim, especially at the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's over there?'' a Titleist will wonder, curious as a
tourist.
</P>
<P>
   And off it will go, climbing toward the oyster-gray clouds,
riding a 40-mph crosswind. The player to whom the ball belongs can
quit and walk off the course _ in frustration, some do _ or grimly
follow after it, raindrops dripping off his tweed cap as he
marches, head down, collar upturned, across the moonscape that is
Royal Birkdale, the links course on the northwest coast of England,
home of this year's championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost six balls in nine holes,'' Tom Lehman, the 1996 British
Open champion, said after a practice round. U.S. Open champion Lee
Janzen commiserated. ``I think I lost five.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Open is the toughest test in golf, and more fun to
watch than any other tournament. This is the one time each year
when everything bad that can happen in golf happens to the game's
best shotmakers, instead of to you and me. &QL; 
Take my irons, please &QL; 
The last time the Open was played here, Mark Calcavecchia shot
9-over par on the front nine. After his round of 79, he presented
his irons to a stranger in the gallery. Gave them away.
</P>
<P>
   Why, Mark?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cause I hate 'em,'' Calcavecchia fumed.
</P>
<P>
   At the British Open more than golf balls disappear. During a
weekend round years ago, television's Jim McKay told American
viewers: ``Let's go out to the 12th hole and Ed Sneed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sneed, a golfer who had missed the 36-hole cut, was working for
the network as a roving reporter, which required he speak in a
whisper and wear an antenna on his head.
</P>
<P>
   But when McKay gave Sneed his cue, Ed didn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   McKay tried again to contact his colleague. Again, no luck.
Later Jack Whitaker gave it a shot. ``Ed Sneed, are you out there?
. . . Ed? . . . Hello, Ed?''
</P>
<P>
   Watching at home, I remember thinking the glitch had to be some
minor problem. Crossed wires. A pulled plug. But after this went on
awhile _ McKay kept calling Sneed in the persistent tone of a tower
operator, trying to radio a pilot whose plane had disappeared from
the radar screen, ``Come in. Come in. Do you read me?'' _ the
growing silence became unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``was'' Sneed? Like other pros, Ed knew his way around the
PGA Tour. But this wasn't Hilton Head, or the Phoenix Open. It was
Turnberry. Or Troon.
</P>
<P>
   Had Ed tumbled into a pot bunker? Maybe a gust swept him over
the edge of a rocky cliff and into the Firth of Fourth, or the
Fourth of Firth.
</P>
<P>
   Sneed eventually turned up at the clubhouse, safe and sound, but
his lengthy absence provided a subplot of mystery to the telecast
and underscored the curious nature of this tournament. &QL; 
Europeans are due &QL; 
The British Open is as unpredictable as the weather. At this
moment, the sun is out. No, wait, it's raining, again. The
temperature is in the low 50s, the wind off the Irish Sea blowing
long cold notes across the forbidding terrain.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara is a good choice. So is David Duval. But the Europeans
are due. I'll take Colin Montgomerie. He is loved here, and he's
playing well. His ball was unavailable for comment. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
