<SLUG> BC-FBO-RATTLERS-CITYHAWKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATTLERS STRUGGLE FOR BIG FINISH  
 WHITE WANTS TO SEE MORE HEART ON FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The injured-reserve list has become nearly the size of the
roster. Hunkie Cooper is the 12th player to go on it.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the guys who are healthy, who aren't giving their all
on every play, that concern Rattlers Coach Danny White as arena
league playoffs loom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough has been said about the injuries,'' he said. ``It's
time to stop pretending to be champions and start playing like
champions.''
</P>
<P>
   The defending-champion Rattlers (8-3) looked more like an
expansion team Monday in losing to the host Albany Firebirds,
58-34.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers had 11 days to prepare. They came to Albany a day
early to get ready. But they fell flat to a team that had lost
three in a row. They didn't win a quarter, lost three more players
to injuries and didn't put up much of a fight in the end.
</P>
<P>
   White will see how resilient his Rattlers are tonight at America
West Arena, where they play the New York CityHawks (2-9) with only
two days to prepare. The CityHawks, led by quarterback Mike Perez
and offensive specialist Khevin Pratt, have lost seven in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game of leadership,'' White said. ``Either positive
leadership takes over or negative leadership takes over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Albany, our negative leadership took over. We had a
couple of guys not playing very hard, and by the end of the game,
everybody was not playing very hard. You have to have enough out
there setting a positive pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Just having enough bodies to form a team has been difficult
enough.
</P>
<P>
   White has had to turn linemen Tony Henderson and Flint Fleming
into fullbacks because four players have been injured in that
position.
</P>
<P>
   Jet lag after the quick turnaround won't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we're physically tired,'' White said. ``We're not
prepared to play this game. We have to get a lot of rest. We have
to get treatment, do the best we can with the bodies we've got.
This is a test of mental toughness, of will. What's going to
dominate, our minds or our bodies? If we give into what our bodies
are telling us, we won't play a very good game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers still control their destiny. They need to win their
last three games to guarantee the second seed. Tampa Bay (10-1),
which lost to the Rattlers in last year's semifinals, appears to be
uncatchable as the top seed.
</P>
<P>
   Other than quarterback Sherdrick Bonner and offensive specialist
Calvin Schexnayder, the Rattlers' offense is hurting. Cooper, a
receiver/linebacker/return specialist, suffered a sprained
medial-collateral ligament in his left knee Monday and will be out
possibly four weeks. Lineman Joe Burch suffered a shoulder injury,
and reserve receiver Cedric Tillman suffered a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunkie is the spiritual leader of the team, and that's a huge
loss for us,'' Bonner said. ``But we have very capable players. We
have to look to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Cooper and receiver Randy Gatewood (shoulder), and only
Brian Easter at fullback, the Rattlers are left with few options
other than trying to find more creative ways for Bonner to get the
ball to Schexnayder.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four of Bonner's 55 touchdown passes have gone to
Schexnayder. The CityHawks likely will double-team Schexnayder and
hope Shawn Parnell, Marvin Bagley and Herb Duncan don't beat them.
</P>
<P>
   White brought in lineman Oscar Sturgis, a 6-foot-5, 280-pound
import from the Canadian Football League, last week, and he will
make his debut tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in and started throwing people around in practice,''
White said. ``He'll dress as our seventh lineman.''
</P>
<P>
   White still has faith in his depleted team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we're one of the best teams,'' he said. ``We
just have to prove it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
