<HEADLINE>
CARSON, COLISEUM REPS EXCHANGE HEAD SLAPS OVER NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles' desperate attempt to secure an NFL franchise and
build a football stadium is now being waged between two combatants
that view each other with total disdain.
</P>
<P>
   On the one side, you have L.A. politician Mark Ridley-Thomas,
Los Angeles Kings and Staples Center co-owner Ed Roski and Roski
business associate John Semcken making passionate pitches for a new
stadium to be erected within the ancient walls of the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   On the other, you have legendary movie talent agency mogul
Michael Ovitz putting his considerable influence behind a plan to
build a state-of-the-art stadium in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties will tell you with persuasive charm that the other
is destined to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Who to believe?
</P>
<P>
   In an interview I had a week ago with John Semcken, he insisted
an NFL franchise one day would wind up playing at the Coliseum and
that there was no chance that a football stadium ever would be
constructed in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just pure fantasy that Michael Ovtiz ever will be able
to stick a stadium on landfill in Carson that is nothing more than
a toxic waste dump,'' said Semcken, Roski's point man in rebuilding
the Coliseum and getting an NFL franchise for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview I had last Monday with Michael Ovitz, he
snickered at Semcken's claim and pulled out large color prototypes
designed by David Rockwell that showed what the future stadium of
Carson and its accompanying shopping mall would look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that things in Carson are going along just as
planned,'' said a man who has represented some of the biggest names
in the entertainment field. ``By the year 2002, Southern California
is going to have a modern new stadium and an expansion team ready
to play in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who to believe?
</P>
<P>
   Both John Semcken and Michael Ovitz are quite convincing in
extolling the virtues of their own projects while ridiculing the
prospects of each other's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next NFL team in L.A. will play at the Coliseum,''
maintains Semcken, an engaging Naval Academy graduate and former
F-14 fighter pilot who served as a technical adviser on ``Top
Gun.'' ``There's just no other place to play. Hollywood Park is a
dead issue. And so is Carson, despite what Michael Ovitz says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the pictures they're showing of the Carson stadium
are quite impressive. But that's just sizzle. I just can't envision
them ever getting a favorable environmental report on that toxic
waste dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're close to signing a 50-year lease that would give our
company, New Coliseum Venture, total control over the Coliseum,
without interference from the Coliseum Commission. We're going to
completely tear down the Coliseum, but leave the outer walls and
peristyle end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coliseum will be a completely new stadium, but will still
retain the old-style appearance. We've got the necessary investors.
USC has agreed to give us an extra 10,000 parking spaces. The
entire stadium project figures to run in the $300 million range.
The Coliseum is the only place that makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't to Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL will never give its OK to play at the Coliseum
again,'' asserts Ovitz. ``I've been told that by more than one
owner, and there is just no way the Coliseum people would be able
to get the necessary 24 votes from the owners that are needed. They
just don't want to put a team in the area that has poor parking and
not very good freeway access.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planning to have 12 off and on ramps around the Carson
stadium with a new overpass set to be built. The projected price of
the stadium will be $350 million, and we have people like Gary
Wilson, chairman of Northwest Airlines, Ron Burkle, who owns
hundreds of supermarkets, Tom Cruise, Kevin Costner and Magic
Johnson and others set to invest in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to build this stadium, mark my word. We've been
planning to build a mall on the property for a long time, and all
the environmental reports on the property are intact. And I'm sure
there will be no problem getting the environmental agency's OK once
we get the go-ahead from the NFL, which we expect to get sometime
this fall when the owners meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, John Semcken takes issue with Ovitz about the NFL's
reported coolness toward the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of that negative talk you hear about the Coliseum from
NFL owners is gamemanship calculated to drive up the price of the
expansion fees,'' says Semcken. ``When the league's expansion
committee realizes what we're planning to do, I'm confident that
there'll be a more positive attitude among NFL owners about the
Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   No way, contends Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL never will stick a team again at the Coliseum,''
reiterates Ovitz. ``Look, I'm not going to get into a war of words
with the Coliseum people. I'm just convinced that the best way for
the NFL to come back to L.A. is through Carson. I'm sure when Mark
Ridley-Thomas and his friends realize this is the only way to go
that they'll start supporting us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the city of Carson is 100 percent behind us. It's going
to be a wonderful stadium that will seat 67,000 and will have the
facade of a California mission. It's going to be a spectacular
sight that will be visible for people driving on the San Diego and
Harbor Freeways. It's going to be the best football stadium ever
built, and there will be parking for 30,000 cars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Carson will never happen,'' insists John Semcken, loyal
Coliseum backer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Carson stadium will be a jewel every one of us in Southern
California will be proud of,'' says Michael Ovitz, loyal Carson
backer.
</P>
<P>
   Who to believe?
</P>
<P>
   Only time will expose what side is headed in the right
direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
