<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' TRAIN ING METHODS BLASTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ZUCKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Coyotes lost 473 player-games to injuries last season, among
the highest in the NHL. According to the founder of Pro Camp, an
off-season training program several Coyotes players participate in,
that number could be reduced if the team were to revise its own
training procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a joke what the Coyotes have over there,'' said T.R.
Goodman, who works with Coyotes Rick Tocchet, Jeremy Roenick, Oleg
Tverdovsky and Jim Cummins, among others, at Pro Camp. ``I know the
stuff we're doing here is definitely going to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's main problem, Goodman said, is a lack of
communication between different parties, such as the team training
staff, strength coaches, doctors and surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at what's going on, you never have the right
hand talking with the left hand,'' he said. ``The communication
ceases to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet, who began seeing Goodman four years ago when he was
suffering from back problems and says he now feels ``three or four
years younger,'' says the problem is not necessarily with the
Coyotes, but is leaguewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think NHL teams are four or five years behind on
this stuff,'' Tocchet said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes do offer both in-season and off-season training for
their players, including a four-week summer session in Minnesota
with a personal trainer, and rookie training camps before the
preseason begins. Last February, the team opened a $29 million
training facility in Scottsdale to help players get ice time and
off-ice training year-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, they would simply get dressed and leave,'' said Mike
O'Hearn, president of BG Ice, which operates the new facility.
``(With the new facility) the encouragement doesn't have to be such
an issue for them because the equipment is right there for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, you're finding players realize that the game
has become a 12-month-a-year deal. It's far too competitive, the
money on the table is too much and the competition is too great to
ignore anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some players say programs such as Pro Camp, which is
designed to cater toward the individual, has more impact than
team-sponsored programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Pro Camp) is definitely more personal,'' said Coyotes
defenseman Jason Doig. ``In the team sessions, you'll have 20 guys
out there all doing the same thing.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
