<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRISH-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SOILS REPUTATION OF SCHOOL, BACKERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The son of legendary Notre Dame Coach Frank Leahy says
legions of Fighting Irish haters are enjoying seeing the school go
public with its ``dirty laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Notre Dame Coach Dan Devine thinks the football program's
soiled reputation is something it is going to have to live with.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals linebacker Lyron Cobbins, who played for the Fighting
Irish from 1994-97, just wishes former Notre Dame Coach Lou Holtz
wouldn't have had his character and mental stability questioned in
the trial that was completed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The school was found guilty of age discrimination for firing
former offensive line coach Joe Moore, who was 64 at the time.
Moore filed a lawsuit seeking $1 million but was awarded only
$84,000.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie, Holtz's successor
and former defensive coordinator, questioned whether Holtz was
having mental problems.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was accused of punching players, parking his car on the
practice field, smoking during workouts and taking three-hour
lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the testimony was bizarre. Former Notre Dame offensive
lineman Chris Clevenger told of players watching school
cheerleaders have oral sex at the team hotel in Ireland. Clevenger
also acknowledged that the school's recruiting coordinator drank
alcohol at a party in which some underaged Irish players also were
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole affair is an embarrassment to the school and
everyone who is associated with Notre Dame football,'' said Jim
Leahy, the son of Frank Leahy and father of former Cardinals
offensive lineman Ryan Leahy, who played for the Fighting Irish
from 1993-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our dirty laundry is out of the closet, and we're hanging it
in public. There are a lot of Notre Dame haters who are going to
love this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leahy, who played offensive line for Notre Dame from
1966-68, questioned whether the team, 7-6 last year, can have a
good 1998 season with ``all of the family squabbling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dysfunctional family, too,'' said Leahy of the Fighting
Irish, which plays at Arizona State on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Devine, the former Arizona State coach who directed the Fighting
Irish from 1975-80, thinks Davie needs to have a successful season
for the program to overcome its highly publicized problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning fixes anything,'' Devine said.
</P>
<P>
   Cobbins, like Holtz, said he is ``mystified'' by Davie's
comments questioning the former coach's mental stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davie would come into our meeting and say, `That little guy
(Holtz) is phenomenal, the things he knows.' '' Cobbins said from
his home in Kansas City, Kan. ``(Davie) would compliment Coach
Holtz every day. So, it's like this is coming out of nowhere. I
guess that's what a position of power will do to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is because they brought in Bob Davie. Everything
was peaches and cream until they brought him in. I think they'll
get Bob Davie (fired) out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said Moore was hard-nosed but doesn't know of him
physically abusing players.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Leahy was on his way to Green Bay Packers camp and
unavailable for comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
