<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-LEES-FERRY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE TROUT AT LEES FERRY  
 BUT FISH ARE SMALLER, WEIGH LESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEES FERRY, Ariz. - It's an eerie trip up the Colorado River
toward Glen Canyon Dam.
</P>
<P>
   The deck boat was launched about 15 miles below the dam in
darkness. The river moves swiftly. The U.S. Bureau of Reclamation
releases a large quantity of water as it tries to rid Lake Powell
of excesses from runoff of a huge snowpack in the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Janisch, head of fisheries for the Arizona Game and Fish
Department, runs the boat. He has experience, which is needed here.
The river takes a serpentine route through Marble Canyon. It takes
knowledge to miss the rocks and riffles between the massive cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   This 15-mile stretch of water is known as Lees Ferry, named for
a historic Mormon river crossing. It also is among the best
tailwater (below a dam) trout fisheries anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Around four miles upstream, the scene is even more bizarre.
Bright lights can be seen on the water, creating a surreal
atmosphere. The source of the lights is a generator on a shocking
boat. The boat sends electrical current into the water, stunning
trout, which are netted, measured, weighed and injected with
computer chips that allowed them to be identified when they're
netted again.
</P>
<P>
   Results are unbelievable. Each shock brings up more trout. That
night, the crew will cover four stretches of the Ferry. The crew
won't return to Marble Canyon Lodge until about 4 a.m. This litany
will be repeated three straight nights as Game and Fish continues
its intensive research on the trout at Lees Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Any fishery potentially this good is bound to be controversial.
Everyone wants it. Lees Ferry has been a roller coaster of a
fishery since the gates at Glen Canyon Dam closed in 1963 and Game
and Fish stocked it with trout.
</P>
<P>
   At first, according to Janisch, the trout grew huge because of
food available from the lake and from fish already in the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lake had a huge population of shad then,'' Janisch said.
``They came through the (power generating) turbines into the river.
There also was a large population of fish in the river itself. The
trout just gorged themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Trout of 14 pounds or larger were taken from the lake for a
period of time. But the original source of food began to run dry,
and Game and Fish introduced a tiny freshwater shrimp, the
gammarus, in 1968. Within three years, the shrimp were found in the
stomach of trout. Since then, a small insect also has taken up
residence in the frigid water released from the bowels of Lake
Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Irregular releases of water caused the fishery to rise and fall.
Because of drastically fluctuating flows, the fishery crashed
completely from 1991 through 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, flows were established that considered more than power
generation and delivery of water to downstream users. The new
management created by the Glen Canyon Protection Act of 1992 also
considered the health of the Colorado River below the dam,
especially on its run through the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish stocked as many as 150,000 trout a year over the
years but dropped that figure to 20,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that natural reproduction increased from about 25
percent of the trout population in 1986 to about 90 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the growth rate also has slowed,'' Janisch said. ``In
1989, a 4-year-old fish was about 18 inches long. Now the same fish
is about 14 inches.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, is because there are too many trout at Lees
Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many more fish and not enough more food,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons is the management of the Ferry. It's a
blue-ribbon fishery now, with a bag limit of two trout. Fish
between 16 and 22 inches are protected. Flies and lures, with
barbless hooks only, are the only legal method of fishing for
trout.
</P>
<P>
   Lees Ferry also has become dominated by purists. Janisch said
that creel surveys indicate that only about 5,000 trout a year are
being killed. The population continues to grow. The user-days have
decreased greatly since the Ferry was open to all kinds of fishing,
according to studies.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, small shrimp and insects require more work to eat
than forage fish and the like. Fish grow old and die before they
can attain the huge size they once did.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who would like the Ferry to be a completely
catch-and-release fishery, such as the San Juan in New Mexico.
Janisch said that isn't possible. The San Juan has little natural
reproduction, allowing biologists to control populations with
stocking. That's no longer possible at Lees Ferry, Janisch said.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been enough angler requests for a new management
plan that the Arizona Game and Fish Commission will consider
changing it at the October fisheries meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Four alternatives are listed in a new study. The department's
recommendation is that there be no change until more studies can be
done. Other recommendations include dividing the river into no-kill
and harvest areas, increasing the harvest of smaller fish, and
making the whole stretch no-kill only.
</P>
<P>
   Janisch said a number of anglers also have asked that some
stretch of the river also be opened to bait fishing again. That is
not a listed option but could be considered by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Walsh, a member of Trout Unlimited's state council, said
the state already has enough bait waters. A trout almost always is
killed when it eats bait.
</P>
<P>
   Five public meetings for input on the four proposals are
scheduled next week. All begin at 7 p.m. The first is Tuesday in
Flagstaff at Game and Fish's regional office, 3500 S. Lake Mary
Road.
</P>
<P>
   There are two on Wednesday, one in Page at the National Park
Service office on U.S. 89, the other in Phoenix at Game and Fish's
home office, 2221 W. Greenway Road.
</P>
<P>
   On Thurday, meetings will be held at Marble Canyon Lodge near
Lees Ferry, and in Tucson at the University of Arizona cooperative
county office, 4210 N. Campbell Ave. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
