<HEADLINE>
GARY HALL TESTED POSITIVE AT ATLANTA GAMES, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Phoenix Swim Club sprinter Gary Hall Jr., currently
under provisional suspension from competition, was told by U.S.
Swimming in 1996 that he could not march in closing ceremonies of
the Atlanta Olympics because of a positive test for marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sanctioned Gary there by not allowing him to participate
in the closing ceremonies,'' his father, Dr. Gary Hall, said
Wednesday. ``They sent him home, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall still was in Hawaii on Wednesday as he awaited results of a
second test of a twin sample taken on May 15, when swimming's
international governing body, FINA, reported that the Olympic
gold-and-silver medalist tested positive for marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The test of the so-called B sample was scheduled for Wednesday
at an International Olympic Committee lab in Montreal. It was not
known how or when FINA would announce the result from its
headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   If the second test is positive, there is controversy over
whether Hall would be subject to a suspension of three months to
two years. That would be determined at a hearing before FINA's
doping panel. Hall has withdrawn from the Goodwill Games, scheduled
to begin Sunday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gunnar Werner, an honorary secretary for FINA, was quoted last
week as saying Hall would be considered a two-time offender because
of the 1996 test.
</P>
<P>
   Werner said Hall was sent a letter of warning. Hall's father
confirmed Wednesday that he has a copy of that letter.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not clear whether marijuana was a banned substance at
the 1996 Olympics. Werner said the substance was added to the
banned list on July 17, just before the start of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hall Sr., FINA Vice President Ross Wales has said
the 1996 test could not be viewed as an offense because marijuana
was not subject to sanctions until mid-September, or about six
weeks after the closing ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   A marijuana test in Atlanta also did not call for any of the
standard procedures such as testing for a B sample, according to
Wales.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, nobody I knew with U.S. Swimming or at the IOC
level had made any indication that it had been added to the list,''
said the senior Hall, a three-time Olympian who carried the
American flag at the 1976 Olympics in Montreal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
