<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-SKILES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT CAN'T SEE BULLS OFFERING JOB TO SKILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Chicago Bulls conducted a formal interview with
Suns assistant coach Scott Skiles six days ago, but Skiles' agent
said he would be surprised if his client was hired to succeed Phil
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal feeling from the first day has been that we're not
getting this job,'' Keith Glass said Wednesday. ``We didn't ask for
the job. We haven't applied for the job. As of right now, we
haven't applied. Scott has a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, 34, met Saturday for three hours with Bulls owner Jerry
Reinsdorf and General Manager Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, neither Reinsdorf nor Krause gave any indication
as to when a decision would be made, according to Glass. There had
been media speculation that an announcement would be made today.
Skiles was on vacation in the Midwest and was unavailable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf said Wednesday on ESPN's ``Up Close'' that the Bulls
new head coach would be announced ``within the next week or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf confirmed that he had talked to Michael Jordan about
the coaching vacancy before July 1, start of the NBA's ongoing
lockout. He said he mentioned names of possible candidates to
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be foolish to hire somebody without feeling confident
this is somebody that Michael could play for,'' Reinsdorf said.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles has been reported to be one of at least five candidates.
Iowa State Coach Tim Floyd, a friend of Krause's, is considered the
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The other three are NBA assistants Rick Carlisle of Indiana, Ron
Rothstein of Cleveland and Charlotte's Paul Silas, a former Suns
assistant and player. There have been conflicting reports about
whether former Dallas Mavericks guard Brad Davis is a sixth
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Skiles also is being mentioned as a possibility for
the NBA's two other head-coaching jobs: the Denver Nuggets and Los
Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flattering, very flattering for a guy his age,'' Glass
said of Skiles, who was hired to assist Suns Coach Danny Ainge last
summer after coaching for a season in Greece. ``Obviously, somebody
knows Scott can coach other than me, him and Danny Ainge. That's
all nice stuff. I just hope people there (Phoenix) understand that
Scott is not out beating the bushes for a job. He's happy in
Phoenix.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0321EDT &QL; 
