<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS COME BACK  
 KLASSEN'S 2-OUT HIT IN 11TH SAVES DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In a season chock-full of firsts _ many of them
painful _ the Diamondbacks finally registered two huge ones in a
9-8, 11-inning victory over the Central Division-leading Houston
Astros Wednesday night that left them relieved.
</P>
<P>
   After going 0 for 54 in games when they trailed after eight
innings, they finally kicked the monkey off their back, thanks to
rookie Danny Klassen's two-out, two-strike shot into the
right-center field gap off Astros reliever Mike Magnante that
scored Kelly Stinnett from second.
</P>
<P>
   More important, for the first time in their brief 94-game
history, they finally not only won a three-game series against a
team playing above .500, but they also beat the National League
Central Division leader.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't easy, and more so for Houston's ace reliever Billy
Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, after allowing a leadoff single to Matt Williams while
protecting an 8-7 lead in the ninth inning, was struck in the head
by a vicious line drive off the bat of Diamondbacks catcher
Stinnett and left the game on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   His vital signs were good and he never lost consciousness, but
he was taken a neurological center for more tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks managed to send the game into extra innings
when pinch-hitter Karim Garcia greeted reliever Jay Powell with a
double off the glove of second baseman Craig Biggio and scored
Williams. Powell escaped further damage by whiffing pinch-hitter
Jorge Fabregas with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks starter Andy Benes, winless in his last four
outings, cruised through the first five innings protecting a
six-run lead and seemed to be out of the sixth when Williams booted
Carl Everett's two-out grounder to third with runners at the
corners.
</P>
<P>
   Williams can be blamed for prolonging the inning, but what
followed was the product of Benes, who allowed all five unearned
runs. When the inning finally ended, Benes was showering and the
Astros closed the gap to 7-6 behind three more singles and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Houston tied the game at 7 in seventh on Moises Alou's towering
homer to left off reliever Clint Sodowsky, then scored in the
eighth behind a leadoff double by Brad Asmus, who went to third on
Sean Berry's deep fly to right center and scored on Craig Biggio
slow roller to short.
</P>
<P>
   All looked rosy when rookie superstar Travis Lee clubbed his
19th homer of the season in the fourth. It marked the 100th of the
season for the Diamondbacks, Lee's 100th hit and 50th RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks gave Benes the kind of lead he has only dreamed
about with this expansion team, sending 11 men to the plate against
Astros starter Mike Hampton in a five-run second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yamil Benitez stroked a one-out single to left, then scored on
David Dellucci's double into the gap in left-center. Dellucci's
two-bagger was significant in that it kept alive the Diamondback's
major league-leading streak of 81 consecutive games with an
extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   But shortstop Jay Bell soon rendered the double moot by stroking
a 384-foot three-run homer into the left-field seats after Devon
White drove in a run with a bases-loaded fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Benes helped keep the rally alive and loaded the bases for White
by beating out a perfect two-strike bunt after whiffing on two
previous attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was lit up for six runs and 10 hits in a 7-4 loss to the
Diamondbacks in Houston on July 4, but it was his first start since
coming of the 15-day disabled list because of a groin pull.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason on Wednesday, Astros Manager Larry Dierker
offered him up as so much snake fodder. Not only did Hampton remain
in the game, but after a scoreless third he was thoroughly hammered
as the Diamondbacks took a 7-1 lead with back-to-back homers by Lee
and catcher Kelly Stinnett.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the seventh time this year the Diamondbacks have had
consecutive homers.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who entered the game with an 8-4 record and a solid
3.04 ERA, was mercifully removed for a pinch-hitter to lead off the
fifth, but not before allowing seven earned runs, seven hits, three
homers, a double and a hit batsman in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different story for Benes, who allowed only one run
through the first five innings after wriggling out of possible
trouble spots in the first two innings.
</P>
<P>
   He escaped the first inning by inducing Astros cleanup hitter
Jeff Bagwell to ground into an inning-ending double play with
runners at the corners, and he stranded Ricky Gutierrez at second
in the second. The Astros finally dented him in the fourth, when
Alou scored on an infield out after tripling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
