<HEADER>
A7559 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-PITCHING-ROTATION     07-16 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PITCHING-ROTATIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANDED ROTATION HAS EXTENDED CAREERS OF MANY STARTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every so often, a fan of baseball's glorious past will rise and
ask, ``Why doesn't anyone use a four-man rotation anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair question, especially considering how well minds
preserve the memories of the now-deceased four-man rotation. Just
about everyone who was a fan in the 1950s and '60s can recall the
names of the great pitchers of that era.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers such as Bob Gibson, Sandy Koufax and Don Drysdale, Juan
Marichal, Whitey Ford, Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain, Dave McNally
and Jim Kaat routinely started 40 games a year and generally
provided many more 20-game winners for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the game has always evolved, the four-man rotation
stopped being used in the early 1970s when the Baltimore Orioles
and Los Angeles Dodgers finally succumbed and went to the
now-popular five-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest reasons cited for the decline of the four-man
rotation was the weakening of quality arms available. It's a theory
that several pitchers who threw in a four-man rotation believe to
be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lost art,'' said Cincinnati pitching coach Don Gullett,
who started his career in a four-man rotation. ``A four-man staff
is more symmetrical: You pitch, you're off, you have your throw
day, you're off and then you pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I threw in a four-man, I didn't feel the extra zip on my
fastball, but I did have more movement on my pitches because I
wasn't as strong. Pitching is all about movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullett's thoughts are shared by many pitchers who played the
game before 1970, considered the general cutoff of the four-man
staff. Probably the primary reason the four-man staff died was the
inability of the human arm to rebound quickly enough to pitch in
four days' time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is you can't find four guys who can hold
up,'' said St. Louis pitching coach Dave Duncan, considered one of
the best at his profession. ``Back in the 1950s there were only
eight teams in each league and there were all those minor leagues
stocked with more pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a starter went down, you simply pulled another one out of
the pool. The quality was much greater because there were fewer
big-league clubs. The Mike Garcias, Bob Lemons, Bob Gibsons and Don
Drysdales _ physically, those guys were freaks because they
survived.''
</P>
<P>
   A current major league manager, who requested anonymity because
he did not want to offend anyone, said, ``It's true. For every one
of the pitchers we remember, there were three or four who would get
injured and never surface again. Anyone who says that was the
golden age of pitching doesn't have a good memory. Guys were
getting hurt all the time back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Earl Weaver's Orioles of the early 1970s were one of the
last to hold out on the four-man staff. Of course, those Orioles
had four quality arms in Jim Palmer, Dave McNally, Mike Cuellar and
Pat Dobson.
</P>
<P>
   The 1971 Orioles will probably forever be the answer to a trivia
question: What was the last club to have four 20-game winners on
the same staff?
</P>
<P>
   It's a feat that is unlikely to ever happen again because
starters now receive about 32 starts per season instead of the 40
those pitchers routinely got each year.
</P>
<P>
   Durability was the biggest problem with the majority of the
starters back then. Even when they took the ball every four days,
the damage several pitchers were causing their arms tended to be
irreparable.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Denny McLain, who in 1968 was the game's last 30-game
winner, received at least eight cortisone injections in his right
shoulder during the Tigers' pennant-winning season that year.
</P>
<P>
   An ailing pitcher will usually receive a maximum of two
cortisone injections over a full year nowadays. But McLain,
possibly unaware of the long-term damage and partly with an eye on
winning 30 games, passed on the notion of skipping a turn in the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Within four years, at age 28, McLain was out of baseball. He
followed his 31-win season with 24 more victories in 1969 at age
25, but wound up with a combined 17-34 record in his final three
seasons in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys bit the dust that we never heard of,'' Duncan
said. ``In order to pitch in a four-game rotation, all the starters
would have to be able to pitch on three days' rest and stay
healthy. The extra day certainly helps, especially over the course
of a 162-game season.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's pitchers simply could not hold up over the
course of a long season in a four-man rotation, a fact several
readily admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out there seven innings every time out there over
the course of a season, it takes a toll,'' Diamondbacks pitcher
Willie Blair said. ``I think it would be tough to go out and throw
100 pitches every four days. Some might be able to do it. Me,
personally, I don't think I could. Over the course of a full
season, I think you'd see pitchers fall by the side.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the biggest motivation toward evolving into a five-man
staff. Of course, several of today's pitchers could hold up in a
four-man rotation. Roger Clemens, Greg Maddux and Curt Schilling
jump to the top of the list when such pitchers are mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   The list, however, is so short that no club could afford to
switch to a four-man rotation for an extended period, especially
considering none of today's starters are groomed for such a taxing
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the five-man was a blessing because I developed some
arm problems and couldn't make it on three days rest,'' said
Houston Manager Larry Dierker, a former 20-game winner during his
playing days. ``Now, my first three years, when my arm was strong,
I loved it. But I had to be realistic after my arm trouble. You
have to have good stuff and a very strong arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Several smart baseball people believe a four-man rotation can
still be employed. It would, they say, take strong dedication from
an organizational standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it can be done, but it's got to start no later than at
the Double-A level,'' said San Diego pitching coach Dave Stewart,
who had the type of physical ability to probably hold up in a
four-man staff. ``Then you run into trouble if you sign a free
agent who wouldn't want to do it. Overall, I'd say it's gone
forever.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0325EDT &QL; 
