<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FANTASY-CADE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADES MAKE FOR INTERESTING TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF CADE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the supposed trade rumors flying around, it comes down
to this: When you throw enough mud on the wall, some of it is bound
to stick.
</P>
<P>
   The number of free agents _ and the agendas that teams have on
whether to make a run for a playoff spot or sell off and rebuild _
makes predicting trades a crap shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Robin Ventura would look good in a Cubs uniform, or Kenny
Rogers back in a Rangers outfit. And imagine Dante Bichette with
the Red Sox. But you can drive yourself batty trying to anticipate
moves that'll only turn out wrong anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Each summer the biggest deals are the ones that come out of the
blue involving names no one is figuring on.
</P>
<P>
   It's bound to work that way again this summer. Just watch. &QL; 
Getting what they want &QL; 
In years past, actual baseball owners have been slow to realize
that free agency can work in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Next year could be their year. With the large number of free
agents available, the law of supply and demand should take effect.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, Mike Piazza, Mo Vaughn, Bichette, Ellis Burks,
Roberto Alomar, Kevin Brown, Todd Stottlemyer and Rafael Palmeiro
are simply the ones off the top of my head.
</P>
<P>
   Each player will want long-term, big-money contracts, but with
fewer teams willing to spend the big money on players, that means
the supply of top talent will exceed the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Their prices will fall, or should. In short, Vaughn should sign
now. &QL; 
Box score-itis &QL; 
A magnifying glass truly helps when poring over the box scores for
the slightest movement in your favor.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in contention in your league, then the weeks before
the trade deadline are times that will try your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: The Blue Jays score 15 runs in a win. You tear
apart the box scores, happily salivating as you look up the
rejuvenated Jose Canseco. And what do you find?
</P>
<P>
   He didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   Nooooo! (You'll probably utter something worse if this happens
to you.)
</P>
<P>
   Or, say your starting pitchers had a great day, only to discover
the Cleveland Indians decided not to overlook pitcher Jose Mesa,
and he gives up five runs in a third of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   And if your boat is leaking so quickly that you resort to
keeping Shawn Boskie or Doug Drabek aboard, then you know you are
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   What the gracious fantasy team owner is looking for is poise.
You know there will be good times. You also know there will be bad
times and dry times and injuries _ you just want them to happen to
somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners, when their teams are doing badly, refuse to look at
the box scores, at least not in the morning. It only ruins their
day and disrupts the household.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking the cat, beating the dog and spilling the coffee: These
incidents are vastly on the rise this time of year. Of course,
knowing it's 95 degrees at 8 in the morning doesn't help, either.
</P>
<P>
   For the luckless contender, the imminent feeling of injury or
having a player traded out of the league may not haunt you, but
rather it's the slow, agonizing unraveling of what had been an
utterly perfect first half.
</P>
<P>
   Drifting into fifth place, and there's nothing you can do about
it. Let's hope this doesn't happen to you. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 0327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
