<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS KNOW POSTSEASON IS KEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Yankees' runaway locomotive is hitting on all
cylinders. As each passing week demonstrates, there appears to be
absolutely no end in sight to what this Yankees juggernaut can
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing the first half with a 61-20 record, the Yankees
started the second half on a tear, winning five of their first six
games since the break. More importantly, the Yankees are the class
of Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta and San Diego may think they're close, but the Yankees'
bench separates them from everyone else. When Manager Joe Torre can
call on Chad Curtis, Tim Raines and Luis Sojo to fill in for his
starters, then it's almost not fair.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees have even done something the famed 1927 Yankees,
generally considered the greatest club ever, never did. They won 57
of their first 81 games. The true test, of course, will be how the
1998 Yankees do in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Losing in the playoffs will erase everything these Yankees have
accomplished. But before New York meets Anaheim or Texas (which
would be the Yankees' first-round opponent right now) in the first
round of the playoffs, the Yankees have another 2{ months left to
chase 120 victories, which would be a 20th century record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be proud,'' said David Cone, who is one of three
Yankees' pitchers with at least 10 victories. ``It's a great start.
It's a great accomplishment to be named with the best teams of all
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees no longer are built around free agents. While
several of their stars are from other organizations, they were
acquired through trades. That includes Paul O'Neill, Chuck
Knoblauch and Scott Brosius. The other stars on the team _ Bernie
Williams, Derek Jeter, Andy Pettitte and Mariano Rivera _ are
home-grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a team that is as focused as this one,''
Yankees boss George Steinbrenner said. &QL; 
What to do? &QL; 
Seattle's front office set an artificial deadline of July 14 for
making some kind of move in the American League West. In the week
since the All-Star break, the Mariners have managed to win four of
six games and sliced two games off their deficit in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are still uncertain of whether they're in the race.
In the meantime, Seattle's front office will continue to wrestle
with the notion of trading former Cy Young Award winner Randy
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles and Cleveland remain the most likely clubs to trade
for Johnson. The question now is whether the Mariners will pull the
trigger on a deal before the July 31 trading deadline. It is highly
unlikely that Johnson will clear waivers and be available to be
traded before Aug. 31, the final deadline to make deals and have
players eligible for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners Manager Lou Piniella said that if it were up to him,
he'd ``explore possibilities of a trade'' for Johnson. &QL; 
Rocky Road &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, which along with Baltimore is one of the two biggest
disappointments, is slipping farther behind National League
West-leading San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable has started to creep up in the Rocky Mountain
region: How long can the Rockies continue to founder? While that's
the question coming from Rockies fans, ownership seems intent on
keeping the management team of General Manager Bob Gebhart and
Manager Don Baylor together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the fans and media are frustrated,'' Colorado owner
Jerry McMorris said. ``I'm frustrated, too. But it is easier to
tear something down than to build it up. We have two good baseball
men who have been loyal to our ownership group. This is a time that
they have to have every opportunity to correct the performance of
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's difficult not to take note of the Rockies' poor home
record (20-29 as of Wednesday). Colorado had the best home record
each of the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't lay awake worrying about losing my job,'' Baylor said.
``If that's going to come it is going to come. I worry about how to
play better that particular day. I try to be positive going into
each day that we're going to put a (winning) streak together.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is talking about the Blake Street Bombers right now.
Pitchers don't seem to come in here intimidated. What I'd like to
see is us get that feeling back that we're not out of any game
until it's over.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
