<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBM-DBACKS-MINORS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUCSON'S RYAN EARNS RAVES WITH PLAY, ATTI TUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone associated with the Diamondbacks is enamored of their
short, sturdy outfielder who hustles and dives for balls and plays
with energy and passion. But this isn't about David Dellucci. Not
entirely, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson's Rob Ryan was named organizational Player of the Month
in June after batting .368 with seven home runs and 23 RBIs. Going
into Wednesday night's game, he was hitting .332 with 12 homers, 47
RBIs and an on-base percentage of .437.
</P>
<P>
   But what seems to draw the most raves about Ryan are his
attitude and work ethic. Manager Buck Showalter loves Ryan. So does
Mel Didier, director of player development.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous worker,'' Didier said. ``He's built himself
up, he's strong. He reminds me a great deal of Dellucci. He plays
like him. He's hard-nosed. He's Buck's kind of guy. He's our kind
of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A 26th-round pick out of Washington State in 1996, Ryan hit .303
for Lethbridge in 1996 and .314 for South Bend last year, when he
was named team Most Valuable Player. He set club records for
batting average, on-base percentage, doubles and walks.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has continued along the same path with the Sidewinders.
When Danny Klassen, Tucson's only Triple-A All-Star, was called up,
Ryan went to the game in his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have more power potential than Dellucci,'' Didier
said. ``He runs a shade better and throws a shade better. As far as
the overall game, Dellucci right now is probably playing it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the comparison Didier favors with both Dellucci and
Ryan is the Texas Rangers' Rusty Greer, who quietly has become one
of the game's better outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   But because they are ``corner outfielders'' with somewhat
limited power, Didier said it might be difficult to play both at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very difficult,'' he said. ``You've got to have big corner
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, the center fielder can generate a lot of pop.
Devon White, who currently occupies center field, has 13 homers but
is not considered a power hitter. Plus, he's 35. But you never
know. Let's say White is traded, hypothetically speaking. Then the
Diamondbacks could sign a free-agent center fielder with power.
Someone like Bernie Williams, hypothetically speaking. &QL; 
Brief stints
</P>
<P>
   Another young pitcher has moved up to Tucson. Right-hander
Stephen Randolph joined the Sidewinders this week after going 4-4
with a 3.59 ERA and 104 strikeouts in 85 innings. In his last start
for High Desert, Randolph pitched seven scoreless innings against
Bakersfield and combined with Tim Grieve for the first one-hitter
in team history. Not to be outdone, the next day Brad Penny pitched
seven scoreless innings and struck out 13 in another High Desert
shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson outfielder Brent Cookson's season might be over. He broke
his wrist while swinging the bat against Salt Lake on Monday.
Cookson, who singled on the play, apparently hurt himself on the
follow-through. It's been a tough year for Cookson, who missed 36
games because of a knee injury. He was batting .360 in 100
at-bats. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
