<SLUG> BC-GALAXIES-CLUES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR-FLUNG GALAXIES GIVE CLUES TO EARLY STAGES OF UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ Teams of astronomers in Hawaii and Japan have
detected hidden galaxies deep in space, a discovery that scientists
say will force major changes in prevailing theories about the early
chapters of the universe.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists who found the previously unknown ``starburst''
galaxies _ star-forming systems at least 11 billion light-years
from Earth _ said earlier conclusions about when galaxies were born
may have to be thrown out. Galaxy formation was thought to have
peaked when the universe _ believed to be 13 billion to 15 billion
years old _ was 8 billion to 10 billion years old. But this newly
observed burst of galaxy formation may have occurred much earlier _
perhaps when the universe was less than 2 billion years old.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the development appears in Thursday's issue of the
journal Nature. Similar conclusions were reported in the same
journal by researchers in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawaii-Tokyo astronomers surveyed two seemingly blank
regions of sky with a special camera attached to the 15-meter James
Clerk Maxwell Telescope on the dormant Mauna Kea volcano.
</P>
<P>
   The new camera _ called SCUBA, for ``Submillimeter Common User
Bolometer Array'' _ measures energy emissions from cosmic dust
particles, smaller than a millimeter in size, which fall outside
the visual and infrared portions of the light spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the great distances involved, it takes billions of
light-years for the energy emitted by the newfound galaxies to
reach Earth. So when scientists view them with the new devices,
they are looking at a piece of the universe far back in time.
</P>
<P>
   Such feats in extending the so-called ``lookback'' times &UR;  &LR; were
not possible before the advent of the powerful new tools _ the use
of which could help unravel some of the primordial mysteries of how
and when the cosmos was created.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes our view of how the universe evolved,'' said Amy
Barger, a member of the Hawaii team. ``In order to come up with a
comprehensive view of the universe, you have to know something
about all the major components that make it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Enveloped in cosmic dust, the newfound ``starburst'' galaxies
appear to be radiating the same amount of stellar energy as the
entire visible universe, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the possibility that regions of sky that appear to
be utter voids, even when viewed through the Hubble Space Telescope
or the most powerful earthbound instruments, in fact may be
swarming with billions of hot young stars and cosmic debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The existence of such dust-enshrouded galaxies has been
proposed by various groups, and there has been some evidence for
them already,'' said Drew Phillips, a researcher at the Lick
Observatory at the University of California at Santa Cruz. ``It
sounds like these folks have established that a large number of
these galaxies actually do exist _ certainly a significant, albeit
not totally unexpected, discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ellis, director of the Institute of Astronomy at
Cambridge University in England, said the astronomical observations
``have opened an exciting new era in cosmological exploration
comparable to that which happened with the restoration of image
quality with the Hubble Space Telescope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding this new population (of galaxies) is essential
in order to obtain a comprehensive picture of cosmic galaxy
formation,'' he said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   It took a record 51-hour exposure with the SCUBA cameras at
Mauna Kea to get the results reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It will take further study, however, to put the findings into
perspective _ and possibly unlock some fundamental questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until quite recently,'' Phillips noted, ``we have been limited
in our study of the early universe by how small and faint distant
galaxies appear.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this story.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
