r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISSBANK-BOYCOTT-SFC     07-16 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANK-BOYCOTT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SWISS BANK BOYCOTT, CALIFORNIA TREASURER JOINS NEW ACTIVISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT COLLIER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When California Treasurer Matt Fong announced a
state boycott of Swiss banks because of a legal fight over funds
stolen from Jews by the Nazis, it seemed like a politically adroit
overture to a powerful lobby. But it also gave him some unexpected
bedfellows _ and an unwanted controversy over economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Fong and officials from New York state and New York
City on July 1 renews a decision of a year ago to stop investing
billions of dollars of government funds in Swiss banks, in order to
help Holocaust victims' heirs recover family assets held by the
banks since World War II. The boycott had been suspended during
negotiations with the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Fong's decision to champion the issue could enable him to gain
backing from Jewish groups, which generally support his opponent in
the U.S. Senate race, incumbent Barbara Boxer, who herself is
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   But Fong's move also put him smack in the midst of an ungainly
mix of activists from the left and right. In recent years, state
and local governments, from the Bay Area to the South to the East
Coast, have enacted boycotts of corporations over a wide range of
issues: selling tobacco; tolerating exploitative working
conditions; making violent, sex-filled movies; and doing business
with pariah nations like Burma and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The human-rights activists, tobacco opponents and religious
conservatives to whom the politicians were responding agree on
little except that government boycotts can be a powerful tool _ and
they don't cost the taxpayers anything.
</P>
<P>
   Fong insists that he doesn't care for the types he finds himself
in company with, saying the Holocaust has nothing in common with
``social activist'' issues. However, lawmakers elsewhere gladly
claim him as a new ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``California's stand on Swiss banks shows how people and local
governments across the country are realizing they have a lot of
power and can use it to advance human rights,'' said Massachusetts
state Rep. Byron Rushing, a Democrat who wrote the legislation for
his state's 1996 boycott on Burma and its sanctions against South
Africa during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The new breed of economic activism uses two types of boycotts:
divestment, in which the state treasury or state pension funds sell
their investments (or simply refuse to buy more) in companies
involved in the undesired activity; and selective purchasing, in
which the state government refuses to purchase products made by the
target companies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1996, San Francisco barred investments in
companies that do business with Burma; this April, the Board of
Supervisors voted to divest tobacco company stocks owned by the
city's $9 billion pension fund; currently, the city attorney's
office is analyzing how to implement a resolution passed last year
by the supervisors urging the city to stop buying products made by
low-wage, ``sweatshop'' foreign labor.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the boycotts enjoy bipartisan backing, while in
others they are controversial. And in some, they may be treading on
thin legal ground.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the Swiss bank boycott stretches far beyond the
estimated 10,000 Holocaust survivors in California. But it was
influential Jewish groups in Southern California, such as the Simon
Wiesenthal Center, that pushed the issue, prompting Fong to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   Any payoff in votes or campaign donations would be welcome for
Fong, who faces an uphill battle against Boxer in November's
election.
</P>
<P>
   Fong says _ and many experts agree _ that California's $32
billion short-term investment fund has so much economic clout that
it may force the Swiss to settle rapidly. The fund bought a total
of $2.2billion in Swiss bank financial notes in the 16 months prior
to Fong's initial ban last July. Now, it holds none.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every morning, my office makes $600 million in new
investments, but now none of them are Swiss, so that's a pretty big
incentive for the banks,'' said Fong.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a similar standoff ended when the German
auto giant Volkswagen agreed to set up a fund to compensate workers
who were forced into slave labor during World War II. The firm's
move was an abrupt about-face from a decision announced only a
month earlier, and was interpreted by analysts as a sign that the
corporation's bosses feared a California-style boycott.
</P>
<P>
   However, other hot-button social issues get no sympathy from
Fong. He and the Wilson administration have strongly opposed
attempts in the Legislature to extend the boycott strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Fong has refused a request by Elected Officials for Responsible
Public Investment, a coalition of officials from 11 California
cities, to set social standards _ including a ban on tobacco
investments _ on the state's $12 billion Local Agency Investment
Fund, which acts as a short-term savings account for cities,
counties and special districts.
</P>
<P>
   Fong also fought legislative proposals to force the state's two
public pension funds, California Public Employee Retirement System
and the State Teachers Retirement System, to divest from tobacco
stocks and Hollywood film companies, and he opposed a bill to bar
the state from doing business with firms that operate in Burma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fong certainly seems to have a double standard,'' said Mark
Friedman, an El Cerrito councilman and co-chairman of Elected
Officials for Responsible Public Investment. ``He takes one stand
on Swiss banks, but he claims he can't act on tobacco or Burma. . .
. This is more about politics than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fong denies any link between the Swiss banks issue and the
coalition's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holocaust was the greatest crime against humanity ever
committed, and there's no way to compare it with rap music or
cigarette smoking or other social issues that some people want us
to use'' as investment criteria, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over boycotts began in the 1980s, when 185 such
laws were enacted by state and local governments nationwide _
including California and most cities in the Bay Area _ to punish
white-ruled South Africa. The sanctions were widely credited in
helping undermine the apartheid system and bring democratic
elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   After a lull of several years in the early 1990s, sanctions
again became the rage by mid-decade. Florida, Pennsylvania and New
York City moved to divest from tobacco companies; Maryland
boycotted firms that do business in Nigeria; Texas announced Friday
that it will divest from Walt Disney Co. because of violence and
sex in its movies.
</P>
<P>
   But a backlash against the boycotts has started.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has criticized Fong's move, saying it runs
contrary to American foreign-policy goals of encouraging open
markets and free trade. Complaining of ``flagrant propaganda,'' the
Swiss government said the sanctions violate World Trade
Organization rules and threatened to file a complaint with the WTO
to force them to be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Big business is not pleased, either. USAEngage,(CQ) a coalition
of 600 major corporations that opposes all trade sanctions, said
the California and New York boycotts are unconstitutional and
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   The boycott strategy's overall fate may be decided in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union and Japan have threatened to file a complaint
against the state in the WTO, saying that its boycott of firms that
do business with Burma violates the WTO's rules on government
procurement.
</P>
<P>
   And the National Foreign Trade Council, an arm of USAEngage, is
suing in federal court, saying the state boycott violates the U.S.
Constitution's stipulation that foreign policy is in the federal
government's purview, not the states'.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts officials say the lawsuit has major implications
for states and cities nationwide, including California.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a definitive ruling on the federal
constitutionality of state sanctions,'' said Massachusetts
Assistant Attorney General Thomas Barnico, who directs his state's
defense at the WTO and in federal court. ``This case may set a
historical precedent in the 200-year-old debate over federalism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
