<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY No 2463- JULY 16, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. Coming up Monday July 20 : Another story from the NATURE News
Service confirming that Dolly was indeed cloned from adult cells
and that other animals such as mice have now been cloned from adult
cells as well. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------2. RAISA GORBACHEV INTERVIEW By Carolee
Morrison Not so long ago, in the mid-1980s, Raisa Gorbachev, in her
crisp pastel business suits, became an internationally known figure
as the Kremlin's first visible first lady. Now, at age
sixtysomething, she is still a voice to be heard, particularly in
support of women and children, struggling to advance, or merely to
survive, in the morass of post-communist Russia. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------3. AND LUXURY FOR ALL By Holly Brubach from
the New York Times Magazine Luxury used to be the province of the
old rich. Bernard Arnault, the French fashion magnate whose empire
includes Christian Dior, Givenchy,Veuve Clicquot, Louis Vuitton and
Guerlain, is often accused of being too American - he has made
luxury available to anyone with the money to buy it. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------4. STEVEN SPIELBERG
GOES TO WAR - A rare interview by Cindy Pearlman - 1.400 words
Steven Spielberg is the world's richest movie director, its most
popular and its most powerful. He has a couple of Oscars for
``Schindler's List'', his own movie studio and no fewer than four
of his films graced the American Film Institute's recent list of
the 100 best American films. But the director continues to
challenge himself. His latest film, the ambitious World War II epic
``Saving Private Ryan'' will soon be released. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------5. EUROPE'S PAST MUST
NOT BE ASIA'S FUTURE By Fareed Zakaria - A New York Times Op-Ed -
2.000 words Fareed Zakaria, managing editor of Foreign Affairs
Magazine, says that since all the other assumptions of the Asian
crisis have proven wrong, it is naive to think it will not
profoundly affect the United States. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------6. THE PEACE THAT
FAILED AT 4:30 a.m. SUNDAY by Sebastian Barry - A New York TImes
Op-Ed - 800 words Sebastian Barry, a playwright and the author of
``Prayers of Sherkin'' and ``The Steward of Christendom'', finds
himself in the same situation as the father of the three Irish
children who were burned alive on Sunday: he is Catholic, his wife
is Protestant and they have three young children. He writes that
the upheavals of the Orangemen in the Drumcree area of Portadown
may have provided the necessary cloak of passion and righteousness
for the attack. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------7. IT WILL TAKE FORCE
TO END FIGHTING IN KOSOVO By Flora Lewis - 800 words The fighting
has stopped in Bosnia, 300.000 troops have been demobilized, and
people are starting although rather slowly and cautiously to
rebuild their homes. But the region is still a long way from safe
sailing away from its storms of violence. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------8. WHAT'S DOING IN
WASHINGTON By David E. Sanger from the New York Times Way to Go -
2.000 words Washington has always been a city of multiple
personalities. There is monumental Washington, the mecca for
tourists who line up for the White House tour, wander the
statue-lined halls of Congress and cram the National Air and Space
Museum. There is green Washington, the leafy parks and residential
neighborhoods of Northwest, and the jogging routes through Rock
Creek Park. And there is dysfunctional Washington, the world's most
famously mismanaged capital, parts of which are plagued by crime,
troubled schools and deeply impoverished neighborhoods where few
tour buses stray. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------9. SAVE YOUR OWN SKIN By Gale Hayman - 1.000
words How, once and for all, do you really protect yourself against
the sun? Gale Hayman, author of ``How Do I Look?'' and co-founder
of the Giorgio boutique in Beverly Hills, shows how to protect and
beautify skin at this, the riskiest time of the year. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------10. ROBOTIC SURGERY By
Kathy A. Svitil from Discover Magazine - 700 words Surgeons make
big incisions because of the need to get their hands in the body.
But with laparoscopic surgery, tiny robotic hands, their incisions
can be made smaller. Patients are less traumatized, require shorter
hospital stay and heal faster than with conventional procedure. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------11. YOUR NEXT CAR WILL
BE GREENER INSIDE by Paul Eisenstein From Diversion - 1.800 words
Marvin Rush spends his life living in the future. As
cinematographer for the television series ``Star Trek: Voyager'',
he works in the 24th century. But even when the set shuts down for
the night and Rush heads home, he's still a few light-years ahead
of the other folks commuting on L.A.'s crowded freeways : He is
driving one of the first electric vehicles sold in the United
States, a lightweighttwo seater that some see as the automotive
answer for tomorrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
