<HEADER>
A7758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX     07-16 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Beware congressmen bearing Teddies
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans who are worried their lousy
environmental voting records may hurt them at the polls have
created a fake environmental organization and have started giving
each other trophies that declare them environmental champions _
something to show the home folks. It is a scam of breathtaking
brazenness.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, please, that not all Republicans have it in for
Mother Nature, though those who do not are a dwindling number.
Thirty-eight Republicans in the House and six in the Senate score
50 percent or better with the League of Conservation Voters. The
senators were crucial recently in blocking legislation to grease a
legal fast track for property-rights claims against zoning,
land-use planning and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP invented environmentalism with President Theodore
Roosevelt's national parks, wildlife refuges and innovative forest
management. President Richard Nixon set up the Environmental
Protection Agency and signed the Clear Air, Clean Water and
Endangered Species Acts. No major environmental law was enacted
without substantial Republican support.
</P>
<P>
   Until, that is, Ronald Reagan hit the White House, denouncing
trees as the great polluters. GOP environmental stewardship has
been on the skids ever since and reached its low point, so far,
with the election of a horde of hot-to-trot conservatives in the
1994 congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty much those folks who have created the new Coalition
of Republican Environmental Advocates. CREA says it's for
free-market, non-bureaucratic, property rights-oriented solutions
to environmental problems. Translated into real-world English, that
means anything goes if you can make a buck doing it and if the
biosphere collapses, what the hell, we had fun while it lasted,
didn't we?
</P>
<P>
   The group's steering committee is loaded with, and its kickoff
banquet was bankrolled by, lobbyists for the oil, coal, paper,
mining and chemical industries. The conservation league figures
Senate members of the group averaged only 8 out of 100 on its key
votes, House members 23 _ miles below the over-all Senate average
of 46 and House average of 47.
</P>
<P>
   CREA fingers are on the triggers in the current fusillade of
legislative sniping that is using amendments to essential
legislation to pick off environmental targets _ amendments to
increase national-forest logging, run roads through wildlife
refuges, bar salmon restoration on habitat rivers, import dangerous
chemicals banned years ago and cut funding for environmental
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Shamelessly, though, the perps are now giving themselves
``Theodore Roosevelt Conservation Awards'' _ Teddies. One went to
Sen. Jeff Sessions of Alabama, with a zero rating by the League of
Conservation Voters. Theodore Roosevelt IV, the president's
great-grandson, said, ``T.R. would be outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Appalled at the radicalized GOP's outright animus to nature,
environment-minded Republicans have formed REP America in hopes of
returning conservation to the high place it once held in Republican
esteem. So far, the group is a voice in the wilderness, but that
could change soon. Congress may do away with the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
