A7775 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN17-COX     07-16 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We need to sell patience, understanding at the store
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was standing in the line at the grocery store and, boy, was I
hot.
</P>
<P>
   It had nothing to do with the near-triple digit temperatures
outside. No, I was hot as in angry. Angry at the world, at the
store management, at the cashier, and most especially of all at the
woman who had dumped half a million products on the check-out line
in front of me.
</P>
<P>
   And I was beyond angry because this, after all, was the express
line.
</P>
<P>
   It was marked express and I was standing still, but not in time.
The second hand on my watch was sweeping along at a frightening
pace. I am an Important Person with oodles of Important Things to
do. I couldn't be waiting at the check out line.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't be waiting, but there I was. People pulled in with
carts behind me, stopped for a few minutes, then fled to shorter,
faster lines. As there was always someone behind me, I could not
move. The conveyor belt on the check-out counter was making more
progress.
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking it couldn't get worse when it did. Thinking
things cannot get worse is a sure-fire way to make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's bill rang up to $123.41. The lady in front of me
pulled out a wad of cash and handed it, crumpled up, to the
cashier. She carefully counted it out.
</P>
<P>
   It was $80. The woman had miscalculated her purchasing power by
about one-third.
</P>
<P>
   The cashier, who had (it seemed to me) gone about the checking
process rather slowly, gave the woman a sweet smile and told her
that she did not have enough money.
</P>
<P>
   The woman looked confused for a moment and then said, ``Can I
put some of it back?''
</P>
<P>
   I stomped my foot.
</P>
<P>
   The cashier ignored me and flashed the woman another warm smile.
Sure. It was fine. Just pick out what needs to be returned.
</P>
<P>
   My anger turned up another notch and I turned my head. The
people behind me were beginning to grumble, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Why couldn't this cashier speed things up? Why was she letting
this woman hold up the progress of an entire line of Important
People?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cashier paid no attention. She was focused on the
customer at hand, who seemed to me to be intent on taking the
longest time possible in deciding what to return. Small things,
worth only a dollar or two were being taken off the total.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to suggest that the lady put back that curling iron.
Heck, that was almost $20 by itself. I wanted to raise my voice.
More, still, I wanted the cashier to raise her voice. Get this
thing moving, let progress march forward.
</P>
<P>
   It was about that time that my wife pointed out to me something
I had missed. This was no ordinary transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The woman in front of me in line that day, though she must have
been in her 20s, had perhaps the intelligence level of a 9- or
10-year-old. Someone had given her the money to go shopping,
perhaps to buy whatever she wanted, perhaps to buy food for the
week. I hope the latter isn't true, because
</P>
<P>
   there was very little food in the basket.
</P>
<P>
   It was taking all the mental ability that the woman could muster
to look at the items, think about how much they cost, make a
decision and ask that they be returned.
</P>
<P>
   The cashier was being an angel in the truest sense of the word.
I wouldn't be surprised to learn she had spotted this mentally
challenged woman and urged her to come into her line, express lane
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe such a thing could get a cashier in trouble with the store
management, but she certainly scored high that day on the test of
being a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Though the pressure was on from me and others, the cashier never
once treated that customer with anything less than the utmost
respect. When she found that she had purchased something
unnecessary, she called over another store official to help her get
her money back. When we made our quick purchases she apologized,
``for all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   If life were like a grocery store, we might all be a little
different. I might buy a little patience, much more humility and a
waistline that would fit into some of my trousers. The
mentally-challenged woman could find herself a brain that would
allow her to live life in the mainstream where people like me
wouldn't treat her with either impatience or indifference.
</P>
<P>
   What the cashier could buy to improve herself, I just don't
know, but she could sure sell a little understanding to all of us
who pass through her line.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
