<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7776 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-LIFE17-COX     07-16 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George Chalhub has a quiet spot in a very busy place
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ He gets up before 6 because when you're
84, that's just what you do. But, also, the trees and the vines and
the shrubs await him. Mangoes. Watermelons. Lemons. Pineapples. The
yard is a veritable collection of lollipop flavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be plenty of tangerines,'' says George Chalhub.
``You can come over any time to pick them.''
</P>
<P>
   Chalhub started growing things 52 years ago on this patch of
land not far from what today is Palm Beach International Airport.
Back then, a few little planes took off now and then from the
airstrip nearby, and Chalhub and the missus and the three kids
would wander over there to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing here,'' he says. ``This was all
wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's all changed. There's development all around his
little town of Glen Ridge now. Heck, there's even a porn store
right around the corner. The missus is gone; she died on a Sunday
morning four years ago this October. Just fell off the couch from a
massive heart attack as he was getting himself ready for church.
And the three kids, well, they're grown with jobs and mortgages and
kids' college tuitions of their own.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves George Chalhub, a man who leads a quiet life in a
busy place.
</P>
<P>
   Chalhub figures he has about 100 assorted trees on his 2 1/2
acres. Years ago, whenever he'd visit somewhere, he'd come back
with a little something: a lemon tree, a plum tree, even an olive
branch. All these years later, he can grind coffee from his own
beans. (``Although it's a lot of work,'' he warns.) He can stand
there in the heat of the morning, his hands wet from the juice of a
ripe Haden mango.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest pleasure I have in the world is to go outside,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   And a mighty big pleasure it is, when you've got cataracts and a
heart valve that's leaking and a counter full of medicine that
needs swallowing every morning. Thursday was Chalhub's birthday,
his 84th, and don't ya know, he got the calls you'd hope to get on
your 84th. He heard from his brothers, 85 and 81, and he heard from
the folks at his church. They all called bright and early, of
course, but George had already been outside, picking.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he does each morning, makes the tour of his land.
Thank goodness it all doesn't bloom or bear fruit at once, because
Chalhub might be doing just fine for his age, thank you very much,
but he is, after all, an old man with only two hands.
</P>
<P>
   What a smorgasbord awaits him each day! The Indian nut tree
right outside his back door, next to the gardenia, and the
pistachio that doesn't bear fruit. (Too hot here.) The apple tree _
they're delicious, literally _ the 12 varieties of avocado and the
pomegranate. The kids used to love those! Every morning when it's
bearing fruit, Chalhub picks a bunch of boysenberries off the bush
and takes them inside to eat with his cereal. Now, that's some good
eating. And bananas, the little, lady finger kind, are ``as sweet
as sugar.'' He swears.
</P>
<P>
   Then, step right over here, please, to the lemon tree and, oh
yeah, the papaya, although ol' George _ who will eat just about
anything _ isn't too crazy about papayas. He much prefers a good,
juicy sapodilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I square 'em in four pieces and eat 'em like that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Grapes. Figs. Cucumbers. Tomatoes. And watermelons. Lots of
them. ``Of course,'' says Chalhub nonchalantly, ``everyone has
watermelons.'' Which is true. It's just that most of us buy ours at
the market.
</P>
<P>
   This land, these memories, this constant cycle of life, have
given George Chalhub his greatest pleasures. But today, with his
wife Evelyn gone, so much is different.
</P>
<P>
   There is no one to take the apples he brings in and make them
into a pie. No one to make the mango bread. And the kids have been
bugging him to sell lately. He supposes he will, someday soon.
</P>
<P>
   But not yet.
</P>
<P>
   So, the next time you are dashing off to somewhere in an
airplane, cramped between two fighting children, already tense and
nervous about going wherever it is you are going to go, stop and
think of a man named George Chalhub.
</P>
<P>
   He could be right down there below you on his little patch of
paradise, the juice from a ripe sapodilla dripping off his wobbly
chin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
