<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPRUDER-COMMENTARY17     07-16 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER-COMMENTARY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Yes! It's the American Way!
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's all for sale in America. That's the way it is. That's the
way it oughta be. Otherwise, it wouldn't be America.
</P>
<P>
   We bought Jackie O's stuff at auction, Princess Di's dresses,
the car Jayne Mansfield died in. We bought the gun that Jack Ruby
used to shoot Lee Harvey Oswald. We buy it all. We sell it all.
This is the Golden Age of shopping.
</P>
<P>
   If the Zapruder movie of JFK's assassination were not for sale,
we'd have cause for worry.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because somebody would have to decide it wasn't for sale.
Somebody in a position of power. I don't want anyone telling me
what to buy, what to see and, most important, what to think.
</P>
<P>
   But the Zapruder film is for sale, thank goodness _ 26 seconds
of pure historical document. It's not opinion, not conjecture. This
film is pure primary source, the stuff of archives. My archives, if
I so elect.
</P>
<P>
   It's for sale, and the fact that it is verifies our freedom.
I'll sleep a little better tonight knowing that the forces of
mercantilism once again bested the forces of moral outrage.
</P>
<P>
   We're more than the land of the free; we're the land of the
deeply discounted, the clearance, the going-out-of-business sale.
We sell conspiracy theories, advice, solace, drama, karma and
dreams. More important, we buy it all. And we love to buy history,
real or imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The Titanic a grave site to be revered? Baloney. You can buy the
Titanic's coal through your Sunday newspaper. We crave so much to
know what it was like on that cold April night that we've spent
more than a billion dollars sating our voyeurism at a movie that
cost more to make than the original ship. We buy anything.
</P>
<P>
   But then we sift through it all, discard the junk, laugh at the
outrageous, maybe learn something along the way. Free expression
derives from free thought, which derives from unfettered access to
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Some things are not and should not be for sale: the
Constitution, politicians, truth, rights, air and Guinness Stout.
Alas, the Guinness family has property rights to Guinness Stout, so
per our Constitution, the Guinness folks get to sell their product
to those, like me, who choose to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Same with the Zapruder family. It owns the movie and, by golly,
it can sell that movie. Willing seller, willing buyer. That's what
makes the world go round.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the basic argument against selling the Zapruder film:
It's volatile, disturbing, bound to confuse those who don't know
history (the masses) and is best kept safe to be studied by
professional scholars and archivists.
</P>
<P>
   Well, in 16th-century England, the politicians and priests used
the same argument against publishing in English a book they knew,
in their wisdom, would only inflame the masses and lead to
wholesale anarchy and radical goings on.
</P>
<P>
   The book in question was the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Another argument against marketing the movie: Selling it is
crass and opportunistic.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody should have a copy of this historical document, free
of charge, like the Constitution. But then, we own the
Constitution, while the Zapruder family owns the copyrights to the
movie. There's that pesky concept of private property again.
</P>
<P>
   Look, we've been dipping shirts in the blood of martyrs since
there were shirts and martyrs. Enough pieces of the True Cross were
sold to naive pilgrims during the Middle Ages to build a forest of
oak trees. We've always bought, always sold, always flim-flammed
and fleeced each other. It's only human.
</P>
<P>
   But the Zapruder film is the real thing. This is no ``JFK,'' the
movie. This is no Titanic reproduction. It's the real thing, and I
don't want a techno-priest to interpret it for me.
</P>
<P>
   I certainly didn't like it when the editors of Life withheld
portions of the film they said would disturb me. Speaking of Life,
before JFK was in his grave, Life had bought the rights to the film
for $150,000. Exclusive rights.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'm as suspicious of exclusive
rights as I am of exclusive clubs. Always seems like I'm excluded.
</P>
<P>
   When history becomes the exclusive domain of those with
exclusive rights, then history gets rewritten. Usually with bad
results.
</P>
<P>
   So, you don't want to look at the film? Don't buy it. Just tell
me where to go. To buy the tape, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
