<HEADER>
A7781 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPRUDER-FILM17-COX     07-16 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPRUDER-FILM17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Zapruder film distorts history
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is pretty much all you need to know about the new,
digitally enhanced version of the Zapruder film: 53 minutes, 39
seconds. That's how long you have to wait for the clearest,
closest, slow-motion view of President Kennedy's head exploding.
</P>
<P>
   That's all anyone wants to see, isn't it? Really, that's all
there is.
</P>
<P>
   If you were hoping the wonders of computer manipulation would
reveal a shadowy figure on the grassy knoll, too bad. All you'll
see if you buy the tape that goes on sale for $19.95 this week is a
much sharper, much more colorful replay of the clip you already
watched a dozen times. Or a hundred.
</P>
<P>
   So shocking, so sad when the first frames were published in Life
magazine a week after President Kennedy's death, the Zapruder film
has been rerun so many times on news shows, talk shows and
documentaries that it is as familiar and unreal as an old episode
of ``Gunsmoke'' or ``Bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so grainy, blurred and jerky that it seems like something
from a more distant time, like the crash of the Hindenburg or the
sinking of the Maine. The new version is so much more vivid that it
restores the shock of human tragedy. That may be its only virtue.
</P>
<P>
   There's certainly nothing of value in the first three-quarters
of the tape, unless you always wanted to see and hear more about
the late Abraham Zapruder, lionized as a prescient historical
preservationist.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas dress manufacturer turned his home-movie camera on
the presidential motorcade before the first shot was fired and held
his focus for 26 seconds. It's the only known moving image of the
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Zapruder, the tape reveals, had the presence of mind to put the
film in his company safe before sitting down in his office for a
good cry. He recovered sufficient composure by the next day to
begin negotiations with Life, which paid him $150,000 for all
rights. Life sold the rights back to Zapruder's family for $1 after
his death.
</P>
<P>
   While he resisted Secret Service pressure to surrender the
original, Zapruder did turn over a copy and later allowed the
Warren Commission, which investigated the president's death, to
examine the original. The digital version is billed as a new and
valuable research tool, as well as ``a collector's item for all
Americans!''
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything at all admirable in this? Not that I can see.
</P>
<P>
   If Zapruder or his heirs had any real interest in history or
public service, the original film would have been turned over to a
university research center. Of course, there would have been no
profit in that. And there would be no digital version to profit
from today.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: This is no historical document. Digitally
enhanced images make great entertainment, but they are distortions.
Computers don't really ``restore'' lost information; they're merely
a high-tech method of coloring in the missing bits. The great value
of computers over crayons for this sort of work is that computer
enhancement is seamless: You can't tell what's been added or
altered.
</P>
<P>
   So, even if you did see a shadow on the grassy knoll, you'd have
to wonder if it was really there in the original. But I don't
suppose anyone will really worry about that when the first Zapruder
video parties are held this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And I don't suppose it really says much about our times or our
society that people really will do that, or that some will include
the kids, and a few will serve nachos.
</P>
<P>
   If the technology existed, there surely would have been an
audience for Caesar's assassination, and Lincoln's.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Secretary of War Edwin McMasters Stanton, who took
control of the government the night Lincoln was shot, tried to
thwart the power of morbid curiosity by ordering that no pictures
be taken of the dead president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market boomed with drawings of the death scene, some
realistic and some ``enhanced'' with the inclusion of characters
who weren't really there, such as Lincoln's son Tad.
</P>
<P>
   One boarder at the rooming house where Lincoln died managed to
sneak into the room to take a picture after the body was removed.
The photograph, hidden for many years, showed the blood-soaked
pillow that held Lincoln's head and the short, wooden chair where
Mary Lincoln sat sobbing at his side.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in some ways, as powerful and affecting as any image on
the Zapruder film and every bit as instructive. You might cry
watching the Zapruder tape, you might feel nauseated or even a bit
ashamed, but you won't learn anything.
</P>
<P>
   You might as well just fast-forward to 53:39 and be done with
it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
