<SLUG> BC-MECHANIC17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Be kind to your car: Buy good gasoline
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Gasoline is a hot topic these days. Three readers
have fuel-related questions, two about fuel quality and one about
gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   Let's tackle the confusion about fuel first.
</P>
<P>
   David Harris writes: ``I take excellent care of our three cars
(change the oil every 2,500 miles, etc.), but I buy the cheapest
gasoline I can find. How do I determine which fuel is a
good-quality fuel?''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially all gasoline, no matter where it comes from, must go
through the same process to get it from crude oil to a combustible
fuel. Further refinement of this fuel produces what is commonly
referred to as either ``regular'' or ``premium'' gasoline, which is
only a rating of the fuel's ability to resist knock.
</P>
<P>
   Either the refiner or the retailer determines the differences
between the fuel quality, which depends on the special chemicals
added to the base fuel. Additives include detergents for the
control of deposits, corrosion inhibitors and antioxidants, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say Fish Oil Co. is a large refiner and retailer of
gasoline. The gasoline in its storage tanks is the basically the
same as that of Olive Oil Co., another refiner.
</P>
<P>
   When the tanker truck fills up with Fish Oil fuel for delivery
to its own stations, a special additive package that ``won't clog
fuel injectors and keeps the inside of your engine sparkling
clean'' is mixed with the fuel in the truck before it is delivered
to Fish Oil retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The Olive Oil distributors use a similar ``clean and healthy
engine'' additive package for their Olive Oil service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom Co. has a large chain of quickie marts/gas stations. It
buys its fuel from the lowest bidder and adds it own ``we guarantee
our gas'' package to the gasoline it sells.
</P>
<P>
   Snake Oil Co., a small independent chain of stations
specializing in cheap gasoline, also buys the least expensive fuel.
</P>
<P>
   However, to keep prices low, this company doesn't use an
additive package. Snake Oil gas is 10 cents a gallon cheaper than
Fish or Olive Oil gas and 5 cents less than Zoom, but that savings
will be short-lived by the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Without the benefit of the fuel additives, a car -- especially
if it is fuel injected -- is more likely to develop the
driveability problems all of those chemicals were designed to
eliminate. Combustion chamber deposits, varnish buildup on fuel
injectors, fuel system component corrosion and PCV valve gook are
the most common.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when a person is experiencing poor engine performance,
the first question I ask is: ``Where are you buying your gas?''
</P>
<P>
   The pat reply I hear is: ``With the money I save in gas, I can
buy those bottles of gas cleaner stuff they sell at auto parts
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong answer. Excessive use of these products can damage fuel
systems. Not enough and you have the same cheap-gas problems as
before. If you are a chemical engineer, you may be able to arrive
at the right formula, but personally, I don't want to think that
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Good-quality gasoline contains an additive package and is sold
at reputable, high-volume retailers. Some will even supply you with
information on the additives and their benefits, if you ask. Don't
take chances with your car's fuel system. Buy good gas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7783 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-RYAN17-COX     07-16 1922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-RYAN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spielberg and Hanks talk about new film
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ In his new World War II film ``Saving Private Ryan,''
Steven Spielberg _ who grumbles that he's known chiefly for pumping
our emotions with a plastic shark and a plastic alien _ strove for
a battleground realism hitherto unseen at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   If that meant showing bullets reducing human heads to red
confetti, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   If that meant depicting a young soldier writhing in a mound of
his own guts, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   And if that meant Spielberg would again, following the gruelling
historical epics ``Schindler's List'' and ``Amistad,'' subvert his
hardened reputation as kiddie-friendly confectionery, then so be
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is why I have decided for the first time in 17 years to
travel around the country with my movie _ to warn parents and kids
that this is a very, very honest and graphic look at war and to be
prepared for that,'' says Spielberg, reclining in a Dallas hotel
suite. ``If you're 14 or under, you shouldn't see the movie at all.
This is not one of my kinder, gentler movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Many films have wrenchingly portrayed war as hell. ``Saving
Private Ryan'' portrays war as slaughter. The lengthy film's first
30 minutes reenact the storming of Omaha Beach on D-Day, June 6,
1944. Under cloud-choked skies, Allied forces alight from steel
Higgins boats and press onto the sloshy sands, only to meet head-on
a symphonic barrage of bullets and shrapnel. Sea and sand are
promptly mottled by the blood and viscera of a thousand young men,
a Francis Bacon painting writ large, and real.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's blinkless verisimilitude spurs historian Stephen E.
Ambrose to declare ``Saving Private Ryan'' ``the best war movie
ever made and by far the most honest portrayal we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers consulted three of Ambrose's bestselling books _
``D-Day: The Climactic Battle of World II,'' ``Citizen Soldiers''
and ``Band of Brothers'' _ for source and reference material.
Though Ambrose was never directly contacted during production, he
is credited as the film's historical consultant. He is touring with
Spielberg to promote the film.
</P>
<P>
   Opening nationwide Friday, ``Ryan'' stars Tom Hanks as the
captain of an eight-man Army squad, which includes Edward Burns
(``The Brothers McMullen'') and Tom Sizemore (``Heat''), on a
special mission to retrieve a single soldier, Pvt. James Ryan,
played by Matt Damon.
</P>
<P>
   Six other Hollywood films about World War II are reportedly in
the works, including ``The Thin Red Line,'' the highly anticipated
work-in-progress by Austin's Terrence Malick based on the James
Jones novel. The film, slated for a fall release, stars Sean Penn,
George Clooney and John Travolta. It's all part of a resurgence in
public interest in the war, which Ambrose ascribes to our
collective ``yearning for heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   In Spielberg's film, Pvt. Ryan's three brothers have been killed
in combat within days of one another. After delivering all three
telegrams to the Ryans' mother on the same day, the Army, in a
display of feel-good public relations, decides to pluck Ryan out of
the war and send him home. Robert Rodat's screenplay was inspired
by the true story told in Ambrose's ``Band of Brothers,'' in which
Fritz Niland, of the 101st Airborne, loses three brothers in a week
during the war and is delivered to the arms of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with Ambrose, Spielberg, Hanks and Damon,
however, the story recedes into low-relief, quickly eclipsed by the
subject of Spielberg's frank and grisly treatment of combat
carnage. With them, the words ``realism'' and ``graphic'' assume
incantatory power.
</P>
<P>
   After a slew of explicit Vietnam movies in the 1980s, Spielberg
says it's about time people saw World War II in a similarly
unvarnished manner, stripped of romantic hyperbole, fraudulent
glory and John Ford-style mythologizing.
</P>
<P>
   To place their picture in perspective, Spielberg and Hanks
screened 25 war films, from ``The Longest Day'' to Sam Fuller's
``The Steel Helmet,'' before shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It occurred to me that all the films made during the war were
propaganda films to bolster the courage of the home front and to
sell war bonds,'' Spielberg says. ``The films unashamedly put
everyone on a pedestal and made everyone a hero. When we got out of
the war years and Hollywood was no longer part of the war
information department, films became a little more honest, like
William Wellman's `Battleground.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Vietnam changed everything. It was the first time a war
was fought in our living rooms, and that was when people started to
see the difference between our boys suffering and John Wayne
screaming `Lock and Load! Saddle up!' in `The Sands of Iwo Jima.'
Vietnam certainly informed me in how to make a picture about
combat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a post-Vietnam-era film,'' says Damon. ``There was a
shift in consciousness because of the violence in `Platoon' and
`Full Metal Jacket.' We're willing to look at it now. A war movie
doesn't have to be blindingly patriotic. This movie doesn't say
that we shouldn't have been there. It just says that this is what
they saw. I think this generation demands that of war films now.
The bar was raised in showing combat, and I think Steven has raised
it again.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be tempting to regard the film's staggering volume of
mutilated flesh as typical Spielbergian manipulation _ hitting
strategic emotional targets with the Enola Gay instead of a
bayonet. The director of ``Jaws,'' ``E.T.'' and ``Raiders of the
Lost Ark'' demurs, saying technical decisions, from using handheld
cameras and desaturated color film stock to studying the famous war
photos of Robert Capa, abetted the sense of verity as much as the
staged carnage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be manipulative and devilish when it comes to big
entertainment movies. I've done that all of my career,'' Spielberg
says. ``But something like this, where there's so much chaos and
confusion on a beach and you're being fired upon from three
different directions and people are dying and you're trying to find
some refuge from all that murderous cross-fire, everything's a
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   To create that level of pitched anarchy, Spielberg chose not to
storyboard scenes. ``Not one. That was because I didn't know what
it was like to fight a war until I started fighting it. I had to
fight the war in my own small way. My production had to take the
beach an inch at a time the same way those rangers did 54 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't use any special effects or technology to instill any
kind of unease in the audience. I simply took a camera the way a
signal corps combat cameraman would shoot an actual event unfolding
before his eyes. I made the whole movie basically as a member of
the signal corps.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Damon, who appears late and relatively briefly in the
movie, the principal actors were required to undergo six days of
military boot camp under the hectoring command of retired Marine
Capt. Dale Dye, who served as the film's senior military advisor.
His other many advisory credits include ``Platoon,'' ``Forrest
Gump,'' ``Starship Troopers'' and ``Small Soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   WWII has riveted Spielberg since he was a child growing up in
Scottsdale, Ariz., listening to the battle stories of his father,
who fought in Burma during the war. A brainy, wide-eyed kid, he
compulsively watched war movies on television and at age 14 made
one of his first films, an 8 mm WWII flick ``Escape to Nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about a bunch of soldiers, a bunch of 13-year-old kids
wearing helmet liners and dyed T-shirts, who went into battle
against the Germans. I shot it on an old Indian pueblo,'' Spielberg
says.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, many of his movies have been about or set around the
time of WWII _ two of the Indiana Jones movies, ``1941,''
``Schindler's List,'' ``Empire of the Sun,'' and now ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Frumpy in a beige cardigan and dark jeans, the director is
surprisingly diminutive in person. With his pointy features and
short beard, the word ``impish'' clings to him as tenaciously as
``devilish'' does to Jack Nicholson. Damon is the picture of pin-up
youth, all chain-smoking suavity, which threatens to defile his
smile of sugar cubes. Hanks, natty in black jeans and black blazer,
is as effervescent as he is tall. Between them, these Hollywood
golden boys possess five Academy Awards and an Irving Thalberg
Award. Talk about heavy artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, author Ambrose sits restlessly in his suite, a
grizzled veteran of a thousand battles by way of as many interviews
with as many war vets. His face a thick, tawny map, his voice a
mealy grumble, the bluff Mississippian explains why World War II
has suddenly reached critical mass in public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have his two recent books, ``Citizen Soldiers'' and
``D-Day,'' together sold nearly a million copies, Hollywood is in
the midst of a WWII film frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling interest, says Ambrose, is the war's recent 50th
anniversary, as well as the ongoing commemorations of the Berlin
airlift, Pearl Harbor and the war-ending bombings of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most importantly it's because we live in an age in which
we have no heroes,'' he says. ``All I need to say is Franklin
Roosevelt and Winston Churchill, and then say Bill Clinton and Tony
Blair and I've made the point. Of course we're far more cynical
than we were 50 years ago, so figures like Douglas MacArthur and
George Patton look a little ridiculous to us. But there were
genuine heroes in World War II, and they were regular guys you can
identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flight out to Dallas, from Los Angeles, Ambrose and Hanks
chewed the cud on this same subject. ``He told me,'' Hanks says. ``
`Look, we're not living in historic times. The most important
things going on right now are Monica Lewinsky and the Internet.
This is not real compelling stuff. This is not life and death. We
have so many distractions in our lives and there's not one single
energizing and binding moment. I think people would really, really
like something like that to bind us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg submits a different theory about the sudden flux of
WWII movies. ``I think what sparked the interest is me. I'm not
being egocentric, but I find when I announce a project all these
other projects of the same era suddenly come up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there is a resurgence in World War II at the end of
the century. People are finally realizing that it was the defining
event of the entire 20th century, and that's one of the reasons I
wanted to tell the story before the end of the century. But I know
once I declare my major there's a lot of people who come out and
declare theirs, and they somehow seem to be the same major.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spielberg is taking the first shot, so to speak, setting the
benchmark of realism for the rest to match, and redressing what was
never shown before.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been lost in other movies is the absolute personal cost
of what (war) is,'' Hanks says. ``The opening half-hour of `Ryan'
makes it a very, very personal experience for everybody who sees
the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the completed film was really eye-opening,'' adds
Damon. ``It's as close as we can get to war without going.''
Advance for July 19 Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-15-98 1208E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
