<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SOLDIERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nostalgic toys bring out the boy in grown-up collectors
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Joan of Arc rides high upon her steed,
battling enemy troops with her lance. A mustachioed Ghengis Khan,
just inches away, stares blankly ahead, a portrait of menacing
calm. Ivan the Terrible is slumped in his wooden throne. And G.I
Joe, dressed as a P.T. boat commander, appears ready for duty at
all times.
</P>
<P>
   Walk into a place like Grande Armee, the Palm Beach store that
sells military antiques and toy soldiers, and it's easy to imagine
all sorts of possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   Maybe when Joan gets done with her hapless enemies she could
just gallop over and gut Ghengis! Rrrrrripppp! Maybe she could flip
the round table over on King Arthur and crush him in front of his
wimpy court members. Splataroo! Then she could vanquish a stiff
line of World War II infantrymen _ rata-tata-rata-tata _ before
being captured and burned at the stake . . . or at least burned at
the Popsicle stick. I'm melting!!!
</P>
<P>
   What is it about toy soldiers and action figures that brings out
the amateur warrior within?
</P>
<P>
   It's an intoxicating fantasy world that the makers of the movie
``Small Soldiers'' hope to tap into. In theaters'the film is a sort
of ``Toy Story'' on Parris Island. The plot revolves around a clash
between a faction of steroid-choked, jar-headed G.I. Joe types and
a bunch of more mild-mannered action figures.
</P>
<P>
   Toy makers are predicting the movie, which features the voices
of Tommy Lee Jones, Denis Leary and Sarah Michelle Gellar (she
plays Buffy the Vampire Slayer on TV), will stoke interest in
military miniatures and action figures among the Sega and Nintendo
generation.
</P>
<P>
   And while it might be obvious why kids love to play with toy
soldiers, it's valid to ask: What's the allure for the grown-ups?
And why do they spend thousands of dollars on elaborate collections
of toys?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a strong desire to play with cheap Japanese plastic,''
jokes Jim Muir.
</P>
<P>
   As manager of Grande Armee's store on Worth Avenue, Muir, 37,
gets to live his hobby. A collector of vintage G.I. Joe action
figures, he's an expert at what makes one toy soldier or G.I. Joe
doll more valuable than another.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this example: After Hasbro started manufacturing
12-inch tall versions of the military mightyman in 1964, they
decided to go after the Barbie crowd. If they could get boys to
play with dolls _ euphemistically called ``action figures'' _ why
couldn't they get girls to cradle a military nurse?
</P>
<P>
   The nurse doll, dressed in a white uniform and accompanied by
medical accessories, was a horrendous flop. ``Hasbro found out the
hard way that girls didn't want to play dolls with their
brothers,'' Muir said. But today, the doll is the Holy Grail for
G.I. Joe collectors and fetches hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   There are generational differences among G.I. Joe fans, too.
Older collectors tend to go for 12-inch tall figures, while younger
ones focus on acquiring the 3 3/4-inch models Hasbro started
issuing in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who collect toy soldiers, there are factions as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Some only fancy certain time periods _ World War I doughboys or
U.S. Civil war figures. Others stick to specific toy makers such as
W. Britain, a British company from the 1800s. Some current
manufacturers, such as The Petersburg Collection, make military
miniatures of historical figures such as Joan of Arc and Napoleon,
not toy soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Burns of Boynton Beach collects toy soldiers made by W.
Britain. Burns, 59, the president of the South Florida Toy Soldier
Club, began his collection 21 years ago and estimates he has as
many as 6,000 figures arranged in dioramas on the shelves of his
30- by 10-foot Florida room.
</P>
<P>
   His club sponsors a show every year in February in West Palm
Beach that attracts hundreds of enthusiasts. Some collect for the
investment _ figures that sold for 50 cents in the '40s, '50s and
'60s are worth hundreds today. Some collectors are grandparents who
want to introduce the hobby to their grandchildren. Some are
interested because they never had toy soldiers as kids.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Burns remembers going to the five-and-dime, where you
could buy tiny, colorful lead soldiers individually from glass
decanters on the counter. Back in the '30s and '40s, they were
collected mostly by kids from blue- collar families who could only
afford to buy one figure at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, as parents became aware of the dangers of
lead exposure to children, the figures gave way to plastic versions
of ``army men'' that could be mass- produced. Today, hand-painted
toy soldiers produced in Russia by The Petersburg collection are
the standard for quality in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I collect because of the nostalgia,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Muir said he recognizes the monetary allure that draws many
into the hobby, but he says he's interested in collecting only
pieces he knew and loved as a kid, more pristine versions of what
he and his friends might have thrown into a makeshift backyard
sand-box foxhole and blown up with a firecracker. If you can't
enjoy them as toys, he says, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still 12 no matter how old I am,'' Muir said. ``When I
open a new box that I've sent away for . . . it's like Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
