<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    German autobahns can teach us lessons
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It was like a brief trip into automotive heaven. As a
driving enthusiast, the mere mention of the German autobahns has
been like a vision of sugarplums dancing in my head.
</P>
<P>
   It truly was Christmas in July during a trip to Germany. I
jumped at the opportunity when my German-born traveling companion
offered the opportunity to take a turn behind the steering wheel on
her vehicle, a 1999 four-cylinder Saab 9-5 with a light turbo.
</P>
<P>
   Almost coyishly, I asked, ``How fast can I go?''
</P>
<P>
   Her reply: ``As fast as you want; there is no speed limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Her answer was pure symphony music to my ears.
</P>
<P>
   Our trip to Hamburg was roughly 225 miles. Under good
circumstances, we should have made the journey in a little over two
hours. The entire trip was not smooth going.
</P>
<P>
   True, there is no speed limit on the remote stretches of the
autobahns, but the Germans wisely impose speed limits in congested
or populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   The system works with marvelous efficiency. Drivers do not ride
along in the left lane except to pass. Everyone knows the rules: If
you see a car approaching behind you, it is your responsibility to
give way and move to the right lane.
</P>
<P>
   The approaching vehicles don't tailgate. There is no need. If
they close on a vehicle in front of them, they slow some 10 car
lengths or better behind the other vehicle to allow it to move
safely out of the way. On our trip, I saw only one incident in
which the approaching driver blinked his lights as a friendly
reminder to the vehicle ahead to give way.
</P>
<P>
   My companion's comment: ``It must be a tourist. They obviously
don't know the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Our trip was delayed by a seven-mile traffic jam in Bremen. The
autobahn had expanded from two to four lanes. Changeable
illuminated overhead signs posted a speed limit of 60 kmh (about 37
mph) and indicated, via international symbols, congestion ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great time to ``window shop'' in the Germany automotive
``toy store.'' You see many brands of vehicle that are not imported
into the United States -- Fiats, Alfa Romeos, Opels, Vauxhalls,
Citroens and a multitude of models produced by familiar makers that
we also never see. Among them were Mercedes E320s pulling horse
trailers, Ford Modeos (Contours here) cruising down the byway with
a travel trailer in tow and a host of vehicles laden with bicycles.
An American conversion van and a Toyota Land Cruiser seemed out of
place.
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing sight was that in spite of an almost hour delay
in the traffic jam, nobody seemed to get excited. The pace was very
calm and laid back. Perhaps because they knew when they finally
cleared the construction delay, they could make up the time. That
is part of the reason the autobahn system works.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that the Germans take driving very seriously and
require extensive training before granting a driver a license. They
make sure everyone plays by the same rules. Another is that where
there is a speed limit posted, they are serious -- very serious --
about enforcing it. My German friend warned that the fines were
``very, very steep, no slap on the hands, no warnings, no second
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   For me, it was the ultimate treat. Traveling at speeds in excess
of 110 mph, our little 170-horsepower Saab sprinted happily along,
once even legally passing a police car. What a rush!
</P>
<P>
   The system seems so sensible, and it's difficult to argue its
logic. Not once in more than 600 miles of driving did I see a
single accident or a tinge of animosity between drivers. If only we
could make it work on our far superior interstate highway system.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
