<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donnie &AMP; Marie: a little bit corny, a little bit Springer
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The hair. The voice. The teeth. Oh, those
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, even at 40, Donny Osmond still resembles that oh-so-cute
pop music star that made young girls swoon in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a time when Osmond, a father of five boys,
desperately wanted to ditch that Tiger Beat persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a period where I really tried to change my
image,'' Osmond told a gathering of TV critics previewing the new
fall shows. ``I said, `I'm Donny Osmond, the grown-up guy.' But
then I realized I'm not. So you laugh at yourself and say, `Yes, I
wore purple socks. Yes, I sang ``Puppy Love'',' and it was a great
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmond hopes to relieve those great times with sister Marie when
``Donny &AMP; Marie,'' the duo's daytime talk/variety show debuts in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Donny and Marie are no strangers to variety shows.
The toothy brother-and-sister team hosted a music and comedy series
on ABC for four years in the mid-'70s.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot has changed in 20 years. The talk-show arena is more
competitive than ever and boasts a laundry list of failed Rosie
O'Donnell clones.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Donny and Marie's painfully forced and seemingly
scripted presentation during which they needled each other about
age, maturity and nail biting, O'Donnell doesn't have much to worry
about.
</P>
<P>
   Does America really want to hear Marie calling Donny immature
and Donny firing corny one-liners about Marie being born late?
``We're a different Donny and Marie,'' Marie promises. ``We're
going to be like Jerry Springer with music.''
</P>
<P>
   Quotes and stuff:
</P>
<P>
   _ Who could forget ``Hollywood Squares?'' Apparently some TV
writers, who kept asking Whoopi Goldberg, executive producer of a
new version, to explain the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the celebrities or the contestants be in the boxes?''
asked one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, it's `Hollywood Squares','' she cracked. ``One would
assume that the Hollywood people would be in the boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Goldberg, who will sit in the center square, ``Even the
most dense of stars can come and play.'' That might not apply to
some TV writers.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I'm just a mellow, down-to-earth kind of girl.'' _ Pamela
Anderson Lee, star of the new syndicated show, ``VIP.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
