<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author lists books he'd love to write but won't
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christopher Moore, author of ``Practical Demonkeeping'' and
``Island of the Sequined Love Nun,'' has turned his skewed brain to
the topic of Bestsellers I Never Wrote and come up with several
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: ``Return of a Man Called Newt,'' in which
disgruntled voters capture the Speaker of the House and torture him
mercilessly for 200 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Dave Barry Turns State's Evidence,'' in which the
columnist testifies against a Cuban cocaine dealer and is forced
into the witness protection program, thereby giving other, fresher
writers a shot at the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's most commercial idea, though, is ``Men are Homeless,
Women Got Mars in the Settlement,'' the true story of how the only
honest communication between the sexes comes through depositions.
</P>
<P>
   BOO! . . . Pineapple Press has published Joyce Moore's ``Haunt
Hunters Guide to Florida,'' a comprehensive tour of the state's
haunted houses. Included are the St. Augustine Lighthouse, the
Biltmore Hotel in Coral Gables, the Daytona Playhouse in Daytona
Beach, and the Herlong Mansion in festive downtown Micanopy.
</P>
<P>
   I've spent a good deal of time at the Herlong Mansion and have
never seen anything beyond the realm of objective reality, but
maybe I'm just insensitive to ectoplasm.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL AUTHOR CONTINUES TO MAKE GOOD . . . Ruth Turk of Lake
Worth, Fla., continues her series of biographical works for young
people with ``The Play's the Thing,'' the story of William
Shakespeare published by Carolrhoda Books. The book offers all the
facts and most of the drama, and the illustrations by Lisa Harvey
give a good sense of Elizabethan life.
</P>
<P>
   GLORIA IN EXCELSIS . . . One thing for which we have to thank
James Cameron _ possibly the only thing _ is returning Gloria
Stuart to the limelight she left more than 50 years ago. Little,
Brown has bought Stuart's autobiography which will be
rush-published this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hook is her co-starring turn in ``Titanic,'' Stuart
has had a fascinating life: acting for James Whale and John Ford,
helping to found the Screen Actor's Guild, and a happy marriage to
Arthur Sheekman, one of the Marx Brothers' early writers.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart's book will be co-authored by cookbook writer Sylvia
Thompson, who happens to be her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``The dollar as a god is even more
enervating than the Holy Trinity.'' _ Noel Coward
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
