<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-LANGUAGE17-COX     07-16 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-LANGUAGE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teaching children other languages gains popularity
 &HT;    By Julie Bonnin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Twice recently in a two-week period, parents planning
to relocate to the Austin area called the Round Rock Independent
School District to find out if Spanish is part of the elementary
level curriculum there.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Round Rock, where the idea was studied a couple of years
ago, but school officials decided against paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the Eanes Independent School District, which used to
offer Spanish to primary school students before dropping the
classes to save money.
</P>
<P>
   And not in the Austin Independent School District (with the
exception of four campuses, where parents or federal grants pay for
programs). After considering last month an ambitious plan that
would have put Spanish in all its elementary schools, AISD decided
that the costs were too high.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some local students _ those whose parents can afford it and
have made the effort to find or initiate programs _ are learning
foreign languages from Spanish to Chinese to Hebrew to Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Parents have as many reasons for wanting to get children
involved in a second language as there are dialects.
</P>
<P>
   They want to expose them to a variety of cultures _ to learn
more about their own family heritage, or to expand a world view. Or
they want to be sure their children have the advantage of
multilanguage fluency in an increasingly global world. Learning a
second language is even being used as a tactic for slowing down
hyperactive children.
</P>
<P>
   Kids are also (gasp) taking foreign languages just for fun of
it, or for the stunningly obvious reason of being better able to
communicate with a growing number of Spanish-speaking Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Priscilla Lozano helped initiate an after-school Spanish program
at Matthews Elementary School in Austin. Lozano's daughter, Caitlin
O'Hanlon, 7, had taken Spanish in preschool and Lozano wanted her
to continue learning. ``I'm Hispanic,'' Lozano says. ``At home when
I was growing up, my parents were concerned if we learned Spanish
first, our English wouldn't be as strong. So I don't speak Spanish
very well. I think it's part of the culture that's lost. In Texas,
it's crazy if you don't try everything you can to learn Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Research that's found children learn foreign languages easier
when lessons start early is also helping to drive a trend toward
younger foreign language instruction. Children in other countries
for years have been routinely schooled in more than one language,
but in the United States the idea is only now beginning to catch
on.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 31 percent of all public and private schools offered
a foreign language to elementary-school-age children, a 22 percent
increase over 10 years ago, according to the Center for Applied
Linguistics in Washington, D.C. (Twenty-four percent of public
schools offered a foreign language in 1997, compared withto 17
percent a decade ago).
</P>
<P>
   ``There aresome very pragmatic reasons why one should start
foreign languages early in life,'' says Ed Scebold, director of the
American Council of Teachers of Foreign Languages.
</P>
<P>
   Children, Scebold says, have the ability to acquire
pronunciation skills they often lose as they grow older. And, as is
true with English, ``One doesn't learn a language in a couple of
years, he saysadds. ``If you're talking about competence, you need
a lengthy sequence of learning. There needs to be a continuous
stream of learning the language.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine K. Horwitz is director of the University of Texas Foreign
Language Program, which prepares foreign language teachers and
teacher trainers. She thinks it's great for children to learn
another language, but that the idea that they have to start early a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want parents to think that if (their children) have
missed these early years, it's impossible for them to learn a
foreign language,'' Horwitz says. ``That if they haven't done it by
5 or 6, they've blown it. We're even seeing a rebirth in senior
citizens learning foreign language.''
</P>
<P>
   But many parents want their children to learn early and are
taking advantage of programs. Preschools bring in teachers who
focus on Spanish-language songs, rhymes and simple words, or
integrate Spanish in classrooms with Spanish-speaking teachers and
children.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to interested parents like Lozano, extracurricular
Spanish is offered after school at several elementary campuses in
the Eanes, Austin and Round Rock school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Many private schools offer a second language as a part of the
curriculum for primary grade students. There are private tutors and
foreign language schools who will work with children one-on-one or
in groups. Costs vary widely, from college student tutors at the
low end of the scale to private schools that charge more than $300
for a five-week session. Somewhere mid-range is onrisas Spanish
School, which charges $50 a month for twice weekly preschool
classes and a little more for the after-school classes it leads on
elementary campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Will occasional, or even a year's worth of lessons, really
benefit children later in life?
</P>
<P>
   ``What it might do is pique an interest, foster positive
attitudes toward language and culture,'' Horwitz says. ``If you're
talking about two half-hour sessions for 12 weeks, they might pick
up some songs and phrases, but they're not going to speak a lot of
the language.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether a parent speaks the language at home can make a huge
difference. And there are all kinds of ways to support a child's
interest in another language, especially if it's Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Besides books, audiotapes and videos that can enhance Spanish
language skills, there are Spanish-language shows on television.
Churches, schools and parks that attract lots of Spanish-speaking
children can be great resources, Horwitz says.
</P>
<P>
   Older children who can write can get involved with pen pals or
correspond with native speakers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As for classes, Horwitz suggests staying away from those that
stress vocabulary words and grammar analysis. ``What you want is
immersion,'' she says. That means the teacher and children speak in
the target language as kids take part in lots of age-appropriate
activities: art, outdoor play, cooking, etc. Jerry Straubel of
Spanish Language Instruction prefers teaching parents and children
simultaneously, so that parents can reinforce what the kids learn
in class by speaking Spanish at home.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching groups of children years ago, he says, ``was a total
disaster. Because the parents would then say in pristine English
when they got home, 'How was your Spanish class today?' If they
(children) don't see language as a communication tool, they're
going to put it aside with the rest of the toys.''
</P>
<P>
   Straubel will be teaching Lisa Kaufman and her 2-year-old son,
Ned, in a few months, after her son's English-speaking skills
improve some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the demographics change, I think it (knowing Spanish) will
be important for him,'' Kaufman says. ``I think it makes you more
well rounded; it makes you a better sort of partner in the world.
And I think it's probably a lot easier to learn as a child than as
an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Bonnin is a staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
