</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7791 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARRIAGE-COUNSELING17     07-16 2120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-COUNSELING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I thee wed
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ They talked about sex. They talked about
money.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about children, work, recreation and
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about talking _ to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Bethany and Mike Bishop of Palm Beach Gardens were getting
married. They had work to do.
</P>
<P>
   So, they signed up for eight two-hour counseling sessions with
their pastor before the wedding in April last year.
</P>
<P>
   They prayed together, discovered things about each other they
didn't know and found their love language. That's the particular
way each one expresses affection _ and wants it expressed.
</P>
<P>
   They learned that Christian marriage is a threesome. God must be
a part of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the world gives you a good idea of what marriage
is,'' said Bethany Bishop, 27, a member of Palm Beach Gardens
Christ Fellowship. ``You kind of go into this saying, `This is like
a movie. This is like my parents. What is this like?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Most clergy say couples will not know what marriage is really
like until they have been married for a year or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Many recommend that newlyweds have marital checkups with a
counselor after six months of marriage and again near their first
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   But they insist that serious preparation is critical for the
success of many marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Premarital instruction often seems a waste of time to couples
who are convinced that love conquers all, but more than half of all
marriages end in divorce. And many couples remain in painful, even
abusive, relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The hard work of getting to know one another before you say ``I
do'' is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the state of Florida has discovered what clergy have long
known. In June, Gov. Lawton Chiles signed the Marriage Preparation
and Preservation Act.
</P>
<P>
   The law _ which will take effect next Jan. 1 _ encourages
premarital counseling and requires counseling before parents can be
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great step by the state to put more emphasis on
marriage preparation,'' said the Rev. Timothy Lynch, pastor of Mary
Immaculate Roman Catholic Church in West Palm Beach. ``There is a
direct bearing on marriage stability predicated on preparation at
the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   The law urges couples to have four hours of marriage instruction
with a minister or competent counselor. If they do that, they save
$32.50 of the $88.50 cost of a license. Otherwise, they pay full
price and must wait three days to get the license.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who file for divorce must take a four-hour divorce
education course.
</P>
<P>
   That might make parents more sensitive to the likely suffering
that divorce brings to kids. And it might encourage them to work on
saving the marriage, according to Henry Virkler. He is a professor
of psychology who teaches counseling at Palm Beach Atlantic College
in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The law is one of the first of its kind in the country, Virkler
said. And it requires that Florida high schools include courses on
marriage and relationships as part of their life management
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach kids all sorts of things, but we don't educate them
for marriage,'' Virkler said. ``Consequently, half of all marriages
end in divorce with untold pain for the adults and incredible
problems for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Wisk, 43, knows some of that pain. Her first marriage
ended in divorce. She was from the Philippines. Her husband was
not. There were cultural differences. They had different ideas
about marriage, but they had no marriage counseling and no way to
anticipate and resolve problems.
</P>
<P>
   She prepared carefully for her second marriage in April. She and
her fiance, George, had eight two-hour sessions with the associate
pastor, the Rev. Brian Benjamin, at Christ Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   They took a psychological inventory that can pinpoint
personality traits, measure hopes and fears and provide fodder for
discussion. They talked about money, making decisions and trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn to communicate,'' said Wisk, who is from Jupiter.
``The sessions become an open communication where you actually talk
without fear of hearing, `Why do you ask that kind of question?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Most Christian denominations do not officially require
premarital counseling, but most ministers do.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin advises couples to allow four months. He convenes
groups of six or seven couples for eight weekly two-hour sessions.
He also meets privately as many as four times with each couple.
</P>
<P>
   He blends marital counseling with spiritual teaching. Couples
have books to read, tapes to hear, homework to do and
questionnaires to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of hard work,'' said Mike Bishop, 28. ``It's a
chance to get things out in the open and get your eyes focused on
the fact that God brought you together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church requires four to six months of
preparation, Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Each parish has its own program. But most include taking a
psychological inventory _ of more than 150 questions _ that
measures various areas of compatibility, Lynch said. The results
are used for discussion. Couples are also expected to attend a
group program called ``engaged encounter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a one-day workshop in which they benefit from the
insight of married couples as well as professionals in marriage and
family life,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish synagogues are not required to offer premarital
counseling, but most rabbis encourage some degree of marriage
preparation. Many have demanding programs, according to Rabbi
Stephen Pinsky at Temple Beth Torah in Wellington.
</P>
<P>
   The Koran has extensive guidelines that govern Muslim courtship,
engagement and marriage, according to Ibrahim Hooper of the Council
on American Islamic Relations in Washington. But many Muslim
leaders offer marriage preparation as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most clergy believe counseling after the wedding is also
critically important.
</P>
<P>
   It's harder to solve problems when the couple are married,
according to the Rev. Horace Ward, who is pastor of Maranatha
Church in Palm Beach Gardens and has a doctorate in counseling from
Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   After the wedding, couples discover things about each other they
didn't know and don't like. Egos are hurt. Resentment and fear
replace trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very dangerous time, when they fall off their
pedestal and before we discover we have fallen off ours,'' Ward
said.
</P>
<P>
   He requires that couples complete a six-week group course and
have several individual meetings with him before the wedding. But
he wants them to know help is always available.
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of the premarital process, Ward gives each
couple his business card. Keep it in a safe place, he tells them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am asking you to make a lifetime commitment to each other,''
he says. ``I am making a lifetime commitment to you.''
</P>
<P>
   DO HOMEWORK BEFORE SAYING `I DO'
</P>
<P>
   Most denominations urge but do not require marital preparation.
But most clergy insist on some preparation.
</P>
<P>
   That may amount to as little as two informal meetings or as many
as a dozen highly structured sessions over several months.
</P>
<P>
   One example of a solid premarital education format would include
six sessions and about 50 hours of homework.
</P>
<P>
   The couple would take as many as three psychological
inventories:
</P>
<P>
   One identifies what each brings to the marriage from his or her
family of origin.
</P>
<P>
   The second measures how they see themselves and each other.
</P>
<P>
   The third measures 11 areas in the marriage relationship,
including expectations, communications skills, financial
management, sexuality and spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   The couple would read as many as five books on the mystery and
management of married life and listen to two series of audio tapes
on sex and money.
</P>
<P>
   Topics discussed in sessions include: why the couple wants to be
married, their personalities and how they mesh with one another,
finance and budgets, sexual relations, children, family planning
and spiritual life.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Norm Wright, author of The Premarital Counseling
Handbook, Moody Press, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   IN FLORIDA, A COURSE TO GET A DIVORCE
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Marriage Preparation and Preservation Act was signed
into law in June. The law includes:
</P>
<P>
   1. A recommendation that all couples take a four-hour premarital
education course from a clergyman, therapist or qualified
instructor. They save $32.50 of the $88.50 cost of a marriage
license. Otherwise, they must wait three days for the license and
pay the full cost.
</P>
<P>
   2. Florida high schools must offer a course in marriage and
relationship skills as part of life management classes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Couples with children who file for divorce must take a
four-hour divorce education course to help sensitize parents to the
pain of divorce for them and their children. The court fee for
divorce papers was raised $32.50 to $200.
</P>
<P>
   4. The state is directed to develop a handbook of the rights and
responsibilities of marriage to be given to all couples who apply
for a marriage license.
</P>
<P>
   5. Florida State University is directed take the relationship
very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   RED FLAGS
</P>
<P>
   Proceed with caution if your relationship includes:
</P>
<P>
   Personality differences.
</P>
<P>
   They may attract when you date, but, in marriage, differences
often lead to divorce. An introvert may be attracted to an
extrovert, or a messy person may be attracted to a clean person -
but over time, it may require more and more energy to put up with
those differences.
</P>
<P>
   A partner who seems overly eager to be married.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors suspect that an over-eager person may be running from
something, or he or she may be aware of problems and may want to
hook the other person into marriage before the problems become
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   A partner who has unrealistic expectations of the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   We all go into marriage with some unrealistic expectation. The
danger is when one partner expects the other to meet all physical
and emotional needs.
</P>
<P>
   A partner who must control the relationship and have his or her
way in all things. This is a sign of unrealistic expectations - or
a serious behavioral problem.
</P>
<P>
   A partner who has a behavioral or psychological problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people, especially young women, believe their love
will heal a mate's bad behavior. Love does not conquer all. The
better choice is to make sure the future spouse works through the
problem before marriage.
</P>
<P>
   A partner who is reluctant to talk about his or her feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Again, self-awareness and honesty are key to happy marriage. If
we're not aware of our feelings, we're likely to act them out
rather than talking them through. Acted-out feelings often drive
wedges between people.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Dr. Henry Virkler, professor of psychology, Palm Beach
Atlantic College in West Palm Beach, and the Rev. Horace Ward,
pastor of Maranatha Church in Palm Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   HOW'S YOUR MARRIAGE?
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself these questions
</P>
<P>
   Mark each question either SA (Strongly Agree), A (Agree), N
(Neutral), D (Disagree), SD (Strongly Disagree).
</P>
<P>
   1. For the most part, I like my partner's personality.
</P>
<P>
   2. I can share my feelings comfortably and openly with my
partner.
</P>
<P>
   3. I am satisfied with how openly my partner shares his or her
feelings with me.
</P>
<P>
   4. When we have a difference of opinion, I believe we have ways
of finding solutions that leave both of us feeling satisfied and
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   5. I am satisfied with the way we express caring and non-sexual
affection in our relationship.
</P>
<P>
   6. I am satisfied with our sexual life.
</P>
<P>
   7. I feel comfortable with the way we spend our money and make
financial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   8. I am satisfied with the leisure activities that we do
together.
</P>
<P>
   Compare your answers with your partner's answers. Use the
results to talk about your relationship.
</P>
<P>
   DISCUSSION TIP:
</P>
<P>
   Use ``I'' and ``It'' statements when talking about your
marriage. Avoid using ``You'' statements. For example: ``I feel
that we do not spend enough time together'' is better than ``You
never spend any time with me.'' ``I am angry that you did not clean
the house'' is better than ``You're a slob, you never clean up
after yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ADVICE:
</P>
<P>
   Couples should focus on events and issues instead of
personalities,'' says the Rev. Horace Ward, pastor of Maranatha
Church in Palm Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   If talking about these issues becomes difficult, check with your
pastor, rabbi or a marriage and family therapist sooner rather than
later.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Dr. Henry Virkler, professor of psychology at Palm Beach
Atlantic College in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
