<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETSVILLE-SIDE17-COX     07-16 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETSVILLE-SIDE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sidebar to VETSVILLE
 &HT;    By Palm Beach Post staffwriters
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOUNDED in 1993 by Vietnam-era radio host, actress and model
Chris Noel. A private, nonprofit organization, Vetsville is one of
only two programs in Palm Beach County that caters specifically to
homeless veterans, according to the county housing department. (The
other is the VA Medical Center.)
</P>
<P>
   SHELTERS: Two homes in Riviera Beach, one in Boynton Beach and
an apartment complex in West Palm Beach. Another is expected to be
added in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ANNUAL BUDGET: Most recently, $95,000.
</P>
<P>
   PAYS FOR upkeep of the homes, mortgages, food and clothing. No
salaries. Staff, including Noel, works for free.
</P>
<P>
   SERVICES: Besides food, clothes and shelter, Vetsville helps
residents seek medical care, apply for benefits and find work if
they are able. If they are unable to work, residents are assigned
low-pressure jobs at the shelter, such as sorting clothes for the
thrift shop, caring for pets and watering the tropical garden.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY COMES FROM private donations from groups such as the
American Legion, thrift shop sales and fund-raisers. Last year, the
county Department of Housing and Community Development awarded
Vetsville a $25,000 federal grant.
</P>
<P>
   STAFF: Except for Chris Noel, the homes are managed and cared
for by the otherwise-homeless veterans they serve.
</P>
<P>
   ADMISSIONS: Vetsville accepts honorably discharged veterans and
their families who have recovered or are recovering from drug and
alcohol addiction.
</P>
<P>
   WISH LIST: Noel hates to ask, but . . . They need air
conditioning, plywood and insulation, instruments for music
therapy, dog and cat food for pet therapy. They could use the
services of a painter, carpenter and plumber.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION, call Vetsville House at (561) 533-5797.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
