<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETSVILLE17-COX     07-16 2253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETSVILLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When the boys are ready to come home again, Vetsville is waiting
 &HT;    By Dale Fuchs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ ``Mad Dog,'' recently released from the VA
hospital, baked the Smithfield Virginia ham. A Vietnam vet who just
kicked a drug habit made the sweet potato pie.
</P>
<P>
   Here, try some, the guys insist. One of the men will run inside
and get you a fork and a soda to wash it all down.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to the butterfly garden, a husky man frowns at a
wine bottle filled with clear, yellow liquid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only olive oil!'' says another man, who appears to be in
charge. Phew. At Vetsville Cease Fire House for homeless veterans,
``no alcohol'' is one of the 33 rules one must follow _ or be
kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   The radio is playing oldies from the '60s. Watches are set to
military time. American flags wave above the blue-trimmed house on
McIntosh Street where, inside the garden, behind a white picket
fence, a couple dozen otherwise-homeless veterans are celebrating
the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1800 hours, and the Vetsville gang is smoking and eating
and _ with some command-and-control from shelter founder (and
former magazine cover girl) Chris Noel _ managing to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   Here you'll meet the newcomers, such as Vietnam veteran Chuck
Shaylor, 52, who showed up at the West Palm Beach shelter two weeks
ago with his life's possessions in a shopping cart. Firm handshake.
Shaylor didn't eat much this evening; he still has trouble holding
down all this good food after going so many days without.
</P>
<P>
   And here are some longtime residents, such as Jim A. Wilson,
37-year-old ex-Marine. He used to sleep beneath bridges before he
finally dried out and became a manager at this shelter five months
ago. Now he's very busy. He took a break from designing the
Vetsville Web Page to join the festivities. The guys say he's great
on the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   There is Richard Patrick Bennett. He's 47. Used to be a gunner
in the Army, got a Purple Heart in 'Nam. He's a bit withdrawn _ the
metal plate in his head might have something to do with it _ but
when you get him talking, he can tell you all about what happened
to him in the summer of 1970. And before he lights the cigarette,
he'll ask in a gentle voice, ``Do you mind?''
</P>
<P>
   James ``Bob'' Laycock, 52, has been living in a Vetsville
apartment for three years. He worked in Naval Security, but don't
ask him what he did. Apologetic smile. It's classified information,
he says. Can't divulge it, not even three decades later. He gave
his oath. Laycock's a solitary man, a Hemingway fan, and he'd
rather be watching the Texas Rangers on TV. But he'll tear himself
away to meet a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   These are Chris Noel's men.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who don't have dogtags, Noel was the blond
bombshell behind the Armed Forces Radio show ``A Date with Chris''
that heartened U.S. soldiers in Vietnam. Her green, almond-shaped
eyes and toothpaste-ad smile used to appear in magazines and motion
pictures in the '60s and '70s. Since then, she's written a book,
appeared on a dozen sitcoms and hit the talk show circuit: ``Merv
Griffin,'' ``Joe Franklin,'' ``The Tonight Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the glitz was sorrow. Her first husband, a Green
Beret in Vietnam, shot himself in the head on Christmas of '69. He
was 27. She blames his death on post-traumatic stress disorder. His
death fueled her desire to help other veterans: She couldn't bear
to see them in so much pain, she says.
</P>
<P>
   So she traveled around the world telling people about things
such as ``survival guilt'' and ``panic attacks.'' And then she
returned to the place where she grew up, Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 22, 1993, she opened the first Vetsville Cease Fire
House, a pair of three-bedroom cottages in Riviera Beach. Five
years later, Vetsville has expanded to four homes, all managed by
the veterans themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 months alone, 306 honorably discharged servicemen
(Vetsville checks their papers) have sought refuge at Noel's
shelter doors. Many struggle with illness or injury. Most suffer
from post-traumatic stress disorder and have recovered from an
addiction, Noel says.
</P>
<P>
   Noel, now 57, sometimes mothers them, but most often she
``tough-loves'' them: If they break curfew at 2200 hours, that's
one strike. If their rooms fail inspection, that's another strike.
Three strikes and they must leave.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, you get only one strike before you're out. If a
resident wants to take up drugs or drink again, for instance,
there's no negotiation: ``I say, `If you want to be out with crack,
then go,' '' Noel says. ``If you want help, stay here. Kicking this
thing is harder than anything you ever did in Vietnam. Bite that
bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few months at Vetsville, some residents find jobs and
rent apartments on their own, but Noel doesn't keep track of how
many. She feeds, clothes and houses them, and gives them something
to do: To her, that is success enough.
</P>
<P>
   There are 3,090 homeless people in Palm Beach County _ about one
third of them veterans, according the most recent government
survey. Vetsville, with shelters in Riviera Beach, Boynton Beach
and West Palm Beach, can house altogether only 45 people at one
time.
</P>
<P>
   But Noel says she doesn't like to think in terms of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me angry,'' she says, ``like the body counts in
Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   The point of Vetsville, she says, ``is to stop the statistics,
to take care of the individual, to make them the best they can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you want to understand this organization, she says, forget
numbers and talk to the men.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the stories that they told:
</P>
<P>
   Another night of partying _ just liquor, no drugs _ and Jim
Wilson wakes up beneath the Blue Heron Bridge. This time, though,
he takes stock of his 36-year-long life:
</P>
<P>
   Lost the wife. Lost the girlfriend. Left them both for a
``20-year love affair with the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just give me a few days to straighten myself out,'' he had
begged the women. ``I'll be back.'' But he never came back, and he
knows they weren't crazy enough to stick around even if he did.
</P>
<P>
   No sir, Jim Wilson didn't stick around any one place too long.
He joined the Marines, left the Marines, joined again, left for
good with the rank of sergeant. Managed to keep making love to that
bottle of vodka, even in uniform. Knows if you're smart enough, you
can get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   And Jim Wilson sure is smart, so for a long time, he got away
with it: when he worked as a paramedic, when he drifted around the
country, when he landed a technician's job at a manufacturing plant
in Riviera Beach.
</P>
<P>
   That's when events really started getting blurry: He ``screwed
up'' at the plant, so he quit. Stopped paying bills at his friend's
house, so he left.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, he would say he was ``having trouble assimilating''
into civilian society.
</P>
<P>
   So he started sleeping in the parks, John D. MacArthur, John
Prince. He could make it ``in the wild.'' In fact, he felt more
comfortable in the wild, didn't he? He was trained as a Marine,
after all, a damn-tough, backbone-of-our-fighting-force'' Marine.
</P>
<P>
   And so on this particular day, he wakes up beneath the bridge
with the rest of the regulars down there, stumbles over to a nearby
gas station and looks in the mirror. The man looking back is
``pushing that ZZ-top look.'' His beard is gnarly and long, his
camouflage pants, ratty. He's got ``dead man's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's when it hits him: This man is going to die. He breaks
off the affair with the bottle ``cold turkey.'' Four days later, he
slings his red bag over his back and walks about 7 miles to
Vetsville Cease Fire House in West Palm Beach. It's been five
months now since he arrived. He shares a neat two-bedroom apartment
with this plaque at the door: ``When you think you're going to go
over the edge, God in his infinite wisdom made the world round.''
</P>
<P>
   He's the shelter's general manager. Works all day, no salary.
Does everything from bookkeeping to writing grants. Laughs about
his old, errant ways. Now that he's straight, he says they offered
him his old job back at the Riviera Beach plant. But he won't take
it. He needs the structure here, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Ever think about drinking?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too busy helping these guys, training on the computer,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my turn to say, `I'm Jim, and I'm going to help you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe it,'' the middle-aged man says as his son
drops him off at the Salvation Army shelter in West Palm Beach,
handing him a $20.
</P>
<P>
   James Robert Laycock, age ``54 going on a hundred,'' had seen
hard times before. He worked in Naval Security from '63 to '67, and
that had not been easy. Make a mistake, and it could cost you ``big
time,'' as in ``an international incident.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when his panic disorder started _ a terror that would
send him bolting from a room of people and could seize him at any
time. It cost him his job as a sales manager, he says, and after,
his job as a church custodian. It certainly didn't help his failing
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   He had had surgery on his back and neck, too, and that made him
unfit for manual labor.
</P>
<P>
   But he never thought would come to this: A $5-per-night cot at
the Salvation Army, a room shared with 20 other men, wake-up at
4:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, he falls into the routine. He wakes at 3:30 a.m.
to bathe and shave before the early morning rush. He leaves his ID
at the door and walks to the mall. Or wherever. He just keeps
walking. He knows the score: ``Stop and they'll get you.'' ``They''
are the police.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other men try to teach him to panhandle. So he
approaches a man at the nearby McDonald's, pretending he needs
money for a phone call. The man won't give him any.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did I get into this mess?'' he asks himself. ``It's no way
to live.''
</P>
<P>
   On his 10th day at the Salvation Army, he meets a church deacon
who calls Chris Noel. A week before Thanksgiving 1995, Noel
welcomes him to Vetsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was in the Hyatt Regency,'' he recalls three years
later, comfy in the apartment he shares with his pet beagle Daisy.
Here, he has a garden to water, steps to sweep and other jobs Noel
assigns him.
</P>
<P>
   He is wearing sunglasses _ indoors _ but behind them, he says,
tears are coming to his eyes. They well up every time he remembers
that first time he met Noel. ``I started crying,'' he says. ``If I
could have, I would have married her.''
</P>
<P>
   The jungle is quiet. Richard Bennett can hear the chatter of
monkeys and the crack of the occasional machete as it chops through
bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, when a damn B-52 flies over the dense canopy
and drops one _ or many. Then the hot, moist air fills with sound
of bombs exploding, and Bennett feels his muscles tighten. Then,
the bomber passes, and the jungle is quiet again.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1970, and Bennett, then 18, is a foot soldier, an
``M-79 gunner,'' in the northern reaches of the South Vietnamese
jungle, near the Ho Chi Minh Trail.
</P>
<P>
   He cuts an impressive figure: 6-feet tall and 180 pounds _ ``240
pounds with my pack.'' His blue eyes are not yet dulled by
depression or medication; they are alive.
</P>
<P>
   How did he wind up here? His father had been a Marine. So had
his older brothers. But what was Bennett doing right after high
school graduation? Working at a gas station. No plans for college.
On the 6 o'clock news, though, he watched battle scenes from
Vietnam. Interviews with proud American soldiers. The Americans, it
had seemed, were winning.
</P>
<P>
   So Bennett had made a decision: He would serve his country, earn
his college tuition and go through basic training with his best
friend. He had joined the Army's 101st Airborne Division. At 18,
how was he to know about the stench of 30 corpses he would have to
stuff into body bags? About the nightmares that would haunt him
decades later? About six different anxiety-calming drugs?
</P>
<P>
   Could he have guessed that one day, he would cringe, as though
expecting pain, when the woman he adored, his ex-wife, crept up
behind him to give him a hug? What could he have done differently
if he had known that, at age 45, he would be too broke to rent a
room, too medicated to drive or work a machine?
</P>
<P>
   No, on this day in the South Vietnamese jungle, Bennett can not
guess the future. He takes off his helmet and rests a second beside
a tree. He is sweating, as always. His mouth is dry, as always. His
pack is heavy, as always. In the distance, he sees the treetops
dead from Agent Orange. . .
</P>
<P>
   Then drops the bomb that will bury shrapnel in the back of his
head and send Bennett home with four medals and a Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   And then, a decade later, comes the depression, the anxiety and
the nightmares _ what is now known as ``post-traumatic stress
disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bennett quits Job 1, as a truck driver: ``Couldn't drive
with all that medication. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Then he quits Job 2 as a security guard: ``Can't be around too
many people. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1996 his mother sells the family home in Port St. Lucie,
and Bennett has no place else to stay, so while waiting for his
first $700-a-month disability checks from the U.S. government to
come, he knocks on the door of Vetsville Cease Fire House. And
Chris Noel opens it, and gives Bennett something to eat and a
bedroom to sleep in and a small job to do around the house. And
when he wants to talk, she listens to his stories.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
