<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test Drive: Malibu stacks up to imports
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chevrolet likes to bill its Malibu sedan, a midsize
model larger than the Cavalier and smaller than the Lumina, as
``the car you knew America could build.'' The question that phrase
begs, naturally, is, ``Well, why did it take so long?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is equally obvious. After seeing so many midsize
buyers opt for Toyota Camrys, Honda Accords and other imports and
domestics, General Motors realized that generational loyalty and
the what-we-build-is-what-you-buy philosophy wasn't selling cars.
Voila -- here came the '97 Malibu sedan, a sensibly priced,
well-equipped, rather handsome car.
</P>
<P>
   Offered in base and LS trim and with two fairly disparate
engines, the Malibu wowed the critics and won buyers. Motor Trend
proclaimed it car of the year, Kiplinger's named it best in class
and best new car, and the cost-conscious American Automobile
Association tagged it best of class. The Malibu is basically
unchanged for '98, but it is Chevy's best-selling car with a
January-July 7 total of 80,075 vehicles sold.
</P>
<P>
   The base model, with a 150-horsepower four-cylinder engine and
automatic transmission, lists for $16,195. The slightly upscale
Malibu LS, with a 150-hp V-6 engine and automatic transmission, is
priced at $18,615. The ``sandrift metallic'' test Malibu totaled
$20,265, which included a sunroof ($595), power leather bucket
seats ($475), an upgraded stereo with CD and cassette players
($200), and the standard delivery charge ($525).
</P>
<P>
   Although its V-6 has the same 150 hp as the base Malibu's
four-cylinder engine, the tester clearly benefited from the V-6's
extra torque (180 pounds-feet at 3,200 rpm, compared with 155
pounds-feet at 4,400 rpm for the four-banger).
</P>
<P>
   The V-6 Malibu gets to 60 mph in about nine seconds, but,
perhaps more significant to the target market, its power anti-lock
disc brakes help it go from 60 mph to a stop in a very respectable
135 feet. The independent suspension certainly doesn't have a
sporty feel, but it handles nicely enough for a four-door weighing
3,100 pounds. The four-speed automatic shifted smoothly and -- if
the engine's goosed -- the shift points came high enough to provide
satisfactory acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that what's appealing about the Malibu is a
contemporary exterior and an interior that -- believe it or not --
shows the General is thinking about what buyers need and want: good
front seats, a satisfactory rear seat that folds down, air
conditioning, a tilt wheel, cruise control, power windows and
locks, rear vents, and lots of drink holders and storage spaces.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be left-handed to really appreciate the dash-mounted
drink holder to the left of the steering wheel, but some other nice
touches will appeal to right-handers as well. The trunk, plenty
large at 16 cubic feet, has a cargo net. The dash controls are easy
to reach and simple to operate, and there's no shortage of
visibility, headroom and legroom. Judged as the family car it's
supposed to be, the Malibu gives little reason for complaints,
although adults will find the integrated rear headrests are too
short to be of real use, the rear seat bottom is a bit short, and
both road and engine noise penetrate the cabin. Too bad traction
control is not available.
</P>
<P>
   It may have taken some time, but the Malibu, first introduced in
'64 as a Chevelle model and a rear-drive until '84, is a serious
import-fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Chart:
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1998 Chevrolet Malibu LS front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $20,265 (base price: $18,615)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, power anti-lock brakes
with front discs and rear drums, height-adjustable front shoulder
belts, side-door beams, daytime running lights
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 3.1-liter V-6 engine (150 horsepower), four-speed
automatic overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: sunroof, $595; leather bucket seats,
$475; AM/FM stereo radio with CD and cassette players, $200
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 20 mpg regular unleaded city; 29 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-15-98 2034E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
