<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-FALLS-ART-NY     07-16 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-FALLS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE THE NORMAL SNOWMELT TURNS YOSEMITE INTO WATER WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(gm) 
 By CHRIS COURSEY   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE, Calif. _ Visitors gush at the awesome beauty of
Yosemite National Park, and now, Yosemite gushes back.
</P>
<P>
   An El Nino winter that lasted right through spring now is
crashing head-on into summer in the Sierra Nevada. A snowpack that
was measured at 200 percent of normal in May is quickly melting as
temperatures climb to the 70s and 80s.
</P>
<P>
   In Yosemite, that means roaring waterfalls and raging rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The falls are going berserk,'' says Keith Walklet, a park
spokesman. ``We've got two years' worth of water coming through
here in one season, and it's special. I'm excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Water and granite are the park's most basic elements. From the
beginning of time the slow drip and hard freeze have been the
hammer and chisel that have sculpted Yosemite's breathtaking
grandeur. Ancient glaciers carved the canyons, leaving behind
sharp, steep edges from which water now plunges in world-famous
falls: Bridalveil, Vernal, Nevada, Illilouette and the
awe-inspiring Yosemite Falls, which drops more than 2,400 feet from
canyon rim to valley floor.
</P>
<P>
   Water leaps off every precipice; water leaks off every slope.
The trail to Half Dome is a rushing stream in many spots. The
granite staircase alongside Vernal Fall is practically a waterfall
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Mist Trail, so named for the cooling mists that rise as the
Merced River jumps over Vernal Fall, is more monsoon than mist.
Drenching spray gusts from the gusher as untold tons of whitewater
drop 317 feet over the fall. It soaks with icy efficiency,
buffeting hikers with a winter rainstorm on the warmest of summer
afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being blasted by a fire hose,'' says Walklet. ``But
if you can stand the blast in the face, turn around and look at the
fall in the afternoon. If you're lucky, there's a full, round
rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special season.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the season this year should run ``right on through
autumn,'' unlike most years when most of the park's waterfalls dry
up by September.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the late and heavy snowpack makes this early summer
``special'' in other ways as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Merced River, swollen by snowmelt to flood stage, caused
park officials to make some special arrangements for campers and
travelers last week. A few dozen riverside camp sites were
evacuated as the river rose to threatening levels. And the main
road out of the Yosemite Valley's east end was closed for several
days when the river undercut the road bed, forcing motorists to use
the southern route, Highway 41, to get in and out of the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers will encounter snow at much lower levels. Last week, snow
obscured parts of the trail to Half Dome above the 6,500-foot
level.
</P>
<P>
   But with summer finally coming on strong, the snow is quickly
melting. It leaks out from under the drifts, starting as a trickle,
then gurgling through the forest toward the river through Little
Yosemite Valley. From there it tumbles into churning rapids and
thunders over the falls, its power reverberating through the entire
valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like nothing I've seen in 14 years here,'' Walklet says.
``We're going to be enjoying this all summer long.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Coursey writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
