<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: GETTING ON THE BANDWIDTH BANDWAGON
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, July 19.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I'm listening to a radio station in Strasbourg,
France, that pumps classical music down the Internet with CD-like
fidelity as I type away on my personal computer keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of access isn't yet available to most Internet users.
The current generation of modems are too slow to allow you to join
me, a confirmed early adopter, in drawing your music and movies
from an Internet well.
</P>
<P>
   But if the feds change the rules of the game, as they are likely
to do, in a few years' time we could see a radical speed-up in home
access to cyberspace. That would open up some startling new
programming possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if, for less than $1,000 a year, you could run your own
TV station without seeking a broadcast license from the Federal
Communications Commission. While the network anchors would survive,
the evening stars might shine less brightly as more and more folks
got _ and sent _ their ``news'' via the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The digital revolution runs at warp speed. Consider that when
Bill Clinton arrived in the White House, hardly anyone had even
heard of the Internet. By the time Clinton's moving van drives off,
presumably in January 2001, 60 per cent of U.S. families are
expected to be full netizens.
</P>
<P>
   But the real issue is what kind of access we'll have, and at
what cost. And on that score, the signs look promising.
</P>
<P>
   In early August, the FCC is expected to issue new rules on how
the regional Bell companies can market their long-distance data
networks. Until now, the agency has tightly regulated the pricing
structure for home phone services because the Bells hold a virtual
monopoly on the local dial tone.
</P>
<P>
   But it's likely that the FCC will let the Bells sell high-speed
interactive
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
