 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FRIDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Friday, July 17, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TV
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL BLACK ARTS FESTIVAL
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-CARTER _ National Black Arts Festival story looks at the
career of violinist Regina Carter, who has played country, old and
new jazz and more as she's created a national buzz for herself and
her music. She performs at an Atlanta venue Saturday. (SoMurray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 10 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-BLACKROCK _ Story on the Black Rock Coalition and the Last
Poets at Variety Playhouse this night. (SoMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 10 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NBAF-STICKNEY _ Preview of Phyllis Stickney's comedy act, which
debuted last weekend and continues this weekend. (SoMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 10 p.m. ET.NBAF-DANCE _ Dianne McIntyre,
a distinguished dancer Newsweek magazine called one of the great
African-American choreographers, brings her company to the National
Black Arts Festival Thursday and Friday. She's the mentor of Urban
Bush Women artistic director Jawole Willa Jo Zollar. (Brock,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 10 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ PASADENA, Calif. _ More ABC plans for fall
from the TV critics meeting previewing the new season in
Califormia. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Will be filed by 9 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   NYPD-SCHROEDER _ Interview with actor Rick Schroder, who this
fall joins ``NYPD Blue'' and will be teamed with Emmy winner Dennis
Franz as Jimmy Smits exits the ABC cop drama. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DONNIE-DEBUTS _ PASADENA, Calif. _ Even at 40, Donny Osmond
still resembles that oh-so-cute pop music star that made young
girls swoon in the '70s. Osmond hopes to relieve those great times
with sister Marie when ``Donny &AMP; Marie,'' the duo's daytime
talk/variety show debuts in September. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE _ Movie review:Smoke Signals. (Macor, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ZORRO _ Movie review: The Mask of Zorro. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ZORRO-REVIEW _ Review of the movie. (Schwann, Palm Beach Post)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MINIREVIEW-MARY _ Mini review of ``Something About Mary,'' which
stars Matt Dillon, Ben Stiller and Cameron Diaz and opened midweek.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN _ Limited runs and the buzz. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-RYAN _ AUSTIN _ In his new World War II film ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' Steven Spielberg _ who grumbles that he's known
chiefly for pumping our emotions with a plastic shark and a plastic
alien _ strove for a battleground realism hitherto unseen at the
movies. And if that meant Spielberg would again, following the
gruelling historical epics ``Schindler's List'' and ``Amistad,''
subvert his hardened reputation as kiddie-friendly confectionery,
then so be it. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-SOLDIERS _ What is it about toy soldiers and action
figures that brings out the amateur warrior within? It's an
intoxicating fantasy world that the makers of the movie ``Small
Soldiers'' hope to tap into. In theaters'the film is a sort of
``Toy Story'' on Parris Island. The plot revolves around a clash
between a faction of steroid-choked, jar-headed G.I. Joe types and
a bunch of more mild-mannered action figures. (Houck, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ZAPRUDER-FILM _ Here is pretty much all you need to know about
the new, digitally enhanced version of the Zapruder film: 53
minutes, 39 seconds. That's how long you have to wait for the
clearest, closest, slow-motion view of President Kennedy's head
exploding. That's all anyone wants to see, isn't it? Really, that's
all there is. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   HEATWEAR _ It's mid-summer, and you've had it with sweat-soiled
silk. Here's a top 10 list of hints and stay-cool clothes that
won't make you look like a slob. (And you can wash 'em at home!)
(Grantham, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-LANGUAGES _ AUSTIN _ Twice recently in a two-week period,
parents planning to relocate to the Austin area called the Round
Rock Independent School District to find out if Spanish is part of
the elementary level curriculum there. Not in Round Rock. Yet some
local students _ those whose parents can afford it and have made
the effort to find or initiate programs _ are learning foreign
languages from Spanish to Chinese to Hebrew to Italian. (Bonnin,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Christopher Moore, author of ``Practical
Demonkeeping'' and ``Island of the Sequined Love Nun,'' has turned
his skewed brain to the topic of Bestsellers I Never Wrote and come
up with several possibilities. Moore's most commercial idea, is
``Men are Homeless, Women Got Mars in the Settlement,'' the true
story of how the only honest communication between the sexes comes
through depositions. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VETSVILLE _ These are Chris Noel's men. For those of you who
don't have dogtags, Noel was the blond bombshell behind the Armed
Forces Radio show ``A Date with Chris'' that heartened U.S.
soldiers in Vietnam. But beneath the glitz was sorrow. Her first
husband, a Green Beret in Vietnam, shot himself in the head on
Christmas of '69. She blames his death on post-traumatic stress
disorder. On Feb. 22, 1993, she opened the first Vetsville Cease
Fire House, a pair of three-bedroom cottages in Riviera Beach. Five
years later, Vetsville has expanded to four homes, all managed by
the veterans themselves. In the past 10 months alone, 306 honorably
discharged servicemen (Vetsville checks their papers) have sought
refuge at Noel's shelter doors. (Fuchs, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VETSVILLE-SIDE_ Sidebar to VETSVILLE. (Staff, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-COUNSELING _ Most clergy say couples will not know what
marriage is really like until they have been married for a year or
longer. Many recommend that newlyweds have marital checkups with a
counselor after six months of marriage and again near their first
anniversary. But they insist that serious preparation is critical
for the success of many marriages. Now, the state of Florida has
discovered what clergy have long known. In June, Gov. Lawton Chiles
signed the Marriage Preparation and Preservation Act. The law _
which will take effect next Jan. 1 _ encourages premarital
counseling and requires counseling before parents can be divorced.
(Gushee, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA -- It was like a brief trip into
automotive heaven. As a driving enthusiast, the mere mention of the
German autobahns has been like a vision of sugarplums dancing in my
head. It truly was Christmas in July during a trip to Germany. For
me, it was the ultimate treat. Traveling at speeds in excess of 110
mph, our little 170-horsepower Saab sprinted happily along, once
even legally passing a police car. What a rush! The system seems so
sensible, and it's difficult to argue its logic. Not once in more
than 600 miles of driving did I see a single accident or a tinge of
animosity between drivers. If only we could make it work on our far
superior interstate highway system. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MECHANIC _ ATLANTA -- Gasoline is a hot topic these days. Three
readers have fuel-related questions, two about fuel quality and one
about gas stations. Let's tackle the confusion about fuel first.
David Harris writes: ``I take excellent care of our three cars
(change the oil every 2,500 miles, etc.), but I buy the cheapest
gasoline I can find. How do I determine which fuel is a
good-quality fuel?'' (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE _ ATLANTA _ Chevrolet likes to bill its Malibu sedan,
a midsize model larger than the Cavalier and smaller than the
Lumina, as ``the car you knew America could build.'' The question
that phrase begs, naturally, is, ``Well, why did it take so long?''
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
