A7915 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     07-16 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, July 16, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEEPING-CAMERAS (Guilderland, N.Y.) _ Peeping toms have a new
weapon. Home video cameras. No longer confined to window ledges and
tree limbs, voyeurs now stalk their prey at crowded shopping malls,
bus stops and airports with a simple camera stowed in a shopping
bag. Edging up to their victims, they film up skirts and down
blouses, largely without their victims' knowledge. By KIMBERLY
MARTINEAU.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FERRARO-CAMPAIGN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Geraldine Ferraro's campaign
for the Democratic nomination for U.S. Senate garnered $702,000 in
funds in the past quarter, well short of the fund raising by her
well-healed competitors. It's uncertain whether Ferraro will have
enough money for TV ads in the two weeks prior to the Sept. 15
primary. By JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NETSCAPE (San Francisco) _ Netscape Communicator 4.5, available
free on the Net starting Thursday (www.home.netscape.com) contains
features that will only work with Netscape's Netcenter portal site.
Portal sites have been the hottest Internet stocks on Wall Street
this summer. Netscape wants to cash in on that popularity. By MATT
BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DAN-FOGELBERG (Undated) _ It's been 19 years since a 28-year-old
Dan Fogleberg earned immortality with his No. 2 hit single
``Longer'' which has been used at more weddings than a polka band.
Despite the lack of mega-hits through most of the 80s and 90s,
Fogelberg has maintained a loyal following of fans, some of whom
travel in caravans for up to 10 hours or more to catch his
concerts. By JIM ROGALSKI.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Don't worry, New York Yankees fans.
Be happy. Here is a team in the throes of living a dream too vivid
and sublime not to be real. If the government operated as
engagingly and efficiently as the Yankees, there would be no
Internal Revenue Service. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BOOK (Malta, N.Y.) _ In college, Andrew Shanley gave up golf
along with all the other establishment things people of his
generation shunned. Golf definitely wasn't cool for him. Worst of
all, his dad did it. Now he believes that the game is a place to
gently connect with his sons. He's written a book, ``Fathers, Sons
&AMP; Golf: Lessons in Honor and Integrity.'' By JANE GOTTLIEB.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Thanks to a few highly
publicized scandals of late, the American public is getting comfy
with the idea that most journalists are either habitual fabricators
or complete professional slobs. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   JULY-16 (Danville, Calif.) _ July in America turns out to be a
significant month. July 16 is the anniversary of a historic event
that is never celebrated, seldom acknowledged. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY (Pacifica, Calif.) _ Every execution brings up the
question whether civilized people should officially put other
people to death. In my opinion, the death penalty doesn't belong in
a civilized society. The question, therefore, is whether our
society is civilized. By CARLOS TAHMAZIAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
