<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT READY FOR PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently dismissed Microsoft Corp.'s Windows 98 operating
system as barely worthy of notice. Then I saw the sales figures.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know the economy's in great shape. Why else would so many
consumers pay $90 for software that's not worth half that? Compared
to Windows 95, which was a dramatic improvement from earlier
versions of Windows, Windows 98 is just a lot of tweaks and bug
fixes. Yet according to the research firm PC Data, Windows 98 is
selling as fast as Windows 95 did _ 500,000 copies in its first
four days. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   But another aspect of the upgrade saga came as no surprise.
Customers gripe that Windows 98 is buggy and difficult to install
on many computers. Already, Microsoft says it will release a
``service pack'' in September with fixes for Windows 98 bugs. It's
a new chapter in an old story _ Microsoft's notorious habit of
selling software before it ripens.
</P>
<P>
   There are also many reports of conflicts between Windows 98 and
older computer hardware. For example, some of the new Windows
features, such as better battery power management on laptops, will
only work if your computer has an updated set of instructions
called a BIOS. These BIOS instructions are permanently stored on a
chip inside the machine, which can be updated as necessary. In
addition, when you run Windows 98, some add-on hardware devices
like sound cards need updated drivers _ the little programs that
let the devices talk to the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   A number of major computer companies, including Compaq Computer
Corp. and Dell Computer Corp., have posted discussions of these
problems on their Web sites. In some cases, the companies urge
consumers not to install Windows 98 until they've also obtained the
necessary BIOS or driver updates. So check with your machine's
maker before you do something rash.
</P>
<P>
   None of this was a problem for me when I installed a reviewer's
copy of Windows 98 on my home machine a couple of months ago. For
one thing, it's got a new BIOS on the motherboard. Besides, I
wasn't brave enough to install the new software on top of Windows
95. I did that once with a beta version of Microsoft's Internet
Explorer 4.0 browser, and it took me two weeks to get the machine
working properly again. So I took the coward's way out, and did a
``clean install'' of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   I used an excellent utility called System Commander Deluxe that
lets you chop a drive into multiple segments, or partitions, and
treat each one as if it were a separate drive. System Commander
lets you put a different operating system on each partition, and
boot up whichever you like _ DOS, Windows, OS/2, Linux, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   So it was easy to stick Windows 98 on a newly-created partition
where it wouldn't do any harm. Of course, I had to reinstall my
Windows software onto the new partition, but with CD-ROMs, that
doesn't take too long. And if anything had gone wrong, my old
Windows 95 setup and all my data files were safe.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got some extra room on the hard drive, you might want
to use this method. System Commander Deluxe runs about $70, but
there's a $30 ``lite'' version especially for Windows 98 installs.
</P>
<P>
   But after hearing many upgrade complaints, I decided to install
Windows 98 on my Windows 95 partition. I don't believe in suicide
missions, so I took precautions to make the process as smooth as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   I made copies of my important data files, just in case. Next, I
cleaned out a folder called C:/Windows/Start Menu/Programs/StartUp.
This is a folder for programs that start automatically whenever you
boot up. Reboots happen a lot during Windows 98 installation, and
purging this folder can prevent conflicts and speed up the process.
Just copy the contents of the folder to another location, and put
them back once you've finished the installation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I ran Norton Disk Doctor to repair any damaged files on
my hard drive, as well as Speed Disk, which sorts the files on your
disk for maximum efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't have the Norton Utilities, Windows 95 has two
similar products &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; Scandisk and Disk Defragmenter.
</P>
<P>
   And it all worked. Windows 98 installed smoothly and hasn't
given me a hint of trouble so far. My only problem is figuring out
why so many people are actually buying this thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
