<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAINT-BOOK-BOS &LR;      07-16 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINT-BOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINT CONSULTANT'S `RECIPES' YIELD THE RIGHT HUE AND DYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Ever gone to the paint store and stared
glassy-eyed at those little paint chips? With such subtle
differences from one chip to the next, how do you pick the hue that
best adheres to your color scheme? Maybe you don't even have a
scheme? Not knowing where to begin, you make a selection out of
pure frustration. The results: ghastly, and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   To the rescue comes ``The Perfect Palette: Fifty Inspired Color
Plans for Painting Every Room in Your Home,'' by local writer
Bonnie Rosser Krims. Just published by Warner Books, it was the
editor's selection last month for Country Homes &AMP; Gardens Book
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 50 recipes in my book, and each recipe is part of a
chapter representing the seven colors of the spectrum,'' says
Krims, 43, a painter, flutist, color consultant, wife, and mother
of Elise, 4, and Maxwell, 1. ``So there are seven or eight recipes
in each section, starting with red, orange, yellow, and green and
ending with blue, indigo, and violet. What makes it easy is that
every recipe has the same elements _ a title and theme, three main
colors, an accent color, and a trim color.''
</P>
<P>
   To wit: The red section contains a recipe called Pompeii. The
three main colors are red, blue-green, and yellow. These are the
colors to be used on the walls, furniture, and accessories. Black
and white, the accent colors, are to be used on pillows, flowers,
and lamps. White and yellow, the final color, is for trim.
</P>
<P>
   While the book's precept may sound ambitious, its format,
instructions, illustrations, and photographs will be a valuable aid
to even the most inept decorator.
</P>
<P>
   Under the three main colors, which stretch across the top of
each right-hand page, are the paint reference numbers from Benjamin
Moore. At the back of the book is a cross-reference chart listing
the Moore colors and corresponding color numbers from two other
manufacturers _ Pratt &AMP; Lambert and Pittsburgh Paints.
</P>
<P>
   With Krims explaining everything in her introduction, your cat
could follow her instructions. She personalizes every recipe,
bringing a homey spirit to what could otherwise have been a dry
book. Her thoughts on each color scheme are in line with her belief
that colors influence our emotions and attitudes. Under the recipe
for Pompeii, for example, she lists the adjectives that she feels
most represent these colors _ ``rich, lush, muted.'' In the
accompanying block of type, she draws on memories of studying in
Italy and Greece and falling in love with ancient frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``The people in Pompeii lived in rooms with elaborately
decorated walls, ceilings, floors, and furnishings. The frescoes
were primarily decorative rather than symbolic'' and ``were
initially painted in restrained black, white, and reds and
eventually changed to greens, blues, yellows, and sometimes
purples.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Krims then suggests where this color scheme is most appropriate
in the home and what furniture and accessories to use _ `a red
living room, dining room, or library ``with the most formal of
furnishings in sleek, refined, and delicate designs. Heavy
upholstery fabrics and elaborate window treatments are suitable.''
</P>
<P>
   For a recipe she calls Provence in the section on yellow, Krims
advises using rustic distressed or painted furniture with printed
florals, plaids in red and white, and checkered fabrics _
essentially ``piling texture on texture, pattern on pattern.'' For
a simpler approach, she suggests solid-colored fabrics and such
accessories as painted trays, biscuit tins, and wire baskets.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, each recipe includes not only the color scheme
but decorating ideas as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this book is a fail-proof formula that gives answers
but also allows a certain amount of creativity and choice,'' says
Krims, who began the book after moving to Concord with her husband
six years ago. To plan the look of her new home, she jotted down
the color scheme for the first floor of her house. ``In my own home
I wanted to achieve the most continuity possible throughout the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   She chose three main colors, yellow, green, and red _
represented in the recipe called Glastonbury. The accent color is
blue and the trim off-white. She chose yellow for the family room,
red for the hallway, and pale green for the living/dining room. She
painted the kitchen off-white and used the accent color, a deep
indigo, for the porch off the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   She says another plus in this flow of complementary colors is
that furniture and accessories can be moved from room to room
because they come from the same palette.
</P>
<P>
   What Krims emphasizes most is that people ``tune in to colors.''
When she consults with clients, she asks them what colors come to
mind when they are thinking of a favorite season, vacation, smell,
or clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, I love the colors of Greece in the summer _ blue,
white, and lilac _ and the smell of lilac,'' says Krims, whose
Lilac recipe suggests violet, beige, and brown as the main colors
with green and coral accents and light or dark natural wood or
brown paint. With it, to add just one more element to her recipes,
Krims includes favorite quotations; in this case she takes a quote
from Humbert Wolfe's appropriately named ``The Lilac.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Who thought of the lilac? ``I,'' dew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up the lilac, out of my head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She made up the lilac? Pooh?'' thrilled a linnet,
</P>
<P>
   And each dewy note had a lilac on it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, while running a small business painting and
selling used furniture, Krims fell into color consulting.
</P>
<P>
   As she delivered the finished products to her customers, they
would often ask her help on a color scheme to go with the piece of
furniture. Krims obliged _ for free. Eventually, she realized she
could charge for her expertise.
</P>
<P>
   When she stopped painting furniture during her first pregnancy
because of the fumes from stripping compounds, Krims augmented her
consulting money by doing small oil paintings. At the time, a
gallery in Acton sold her work for between $900 and $1,200. She no
longer has the time for these small jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Krims says she is planning to write a second book, one that will
have the same format but concentrate solely on interior decorating.
She notes that she gives 5 percent of her book profits and
consulting fees to Habitat for Humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I have arrived, and that it is time to give back.
I never thought I would own a home, be married, and have
children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1256EDT &QL; 
