<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERRARO-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO TRAILS HER OPPONENTS IN CAMPAIGN FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Geraldine Ferraro's campaign garnered $702,000 in
funds in the past quarter, well short of filling the vast gap
between her and the well-healed competitors seeking the same U.S.
Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations for her are very high,'' said Henry
Sheinkopf, a political strategist. ``Certainly people will be
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheinkopf said it's uncertain whether Ferraro, with just $1.1
million on hand after spending roughly half of the $2 million she
has raised, will have enough money for crucial television ads in
the two weeks prior to the Sept. 15 primary.
</P>
<P>
   In the hotly contested race, incumbent Republican Alfonse
D'Amato, as expected, flexed his fund-raising muscle and eclipsed
$20 million in total collections while spending some $8 million,
according to campaign documents which became available on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, of the Democratic candidates, it appears only Rep.
Charles Schumer, who has raised $12 million, has the financial
strength to box with D'Amato, although polls continue to show that
Ferraro leads Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who has raised almost $12 million, listed $7.2 million
on hand after spending about $2 million during the reporting period
(April 1 to June 30), compared with $1.6 million in the first three
months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Public Advocate Mark Green has raised $2.55
million to date, records show, including $567,678 during the latest
quarter. Green reported $1,054,429 cash on hand after spending
$351,122 during the period.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato is on track to spend more than four times the average of
$4.7 million on a victorious Senate campaign for a seat usually won
by the person with the most money.
</P>
<P>
   Although political strategists rate Ferraro's fund-raising
efforts as disappointing, the former congressswoman from New York
City put a different spin on the money-gathering program.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponents and I have together this quarter raised nearly
the same amount as Al D'Amato has alone, which means that Democrats
are just as competitive as Republicans this election cycle,''
Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center For Responsive Politics, a non-partisan,
non-profit research group in Washington, D.C., candidates don't
have to outspend their opponents to win. But it helps.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the top-spending candidates won 92 percent of House of
Representatives races and 88 percent of of Senate contests, the
group said.
</P>
<P>
   Well-funded incumbents easily beat under-funded challengers, the
center said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in open seat races, the top spenders were the most likely
to win. A total of 43 of the 53 races lacking incumbent congressmen
were won by the top-spending candidate, as were 12 of 14 open
Senate contests.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 elections, the average House winner spent $673,000.
Senate winners' campaigns averaged $4.7 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
