<HEADER>
A8017 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PACK-BOS &LR;      07-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGS AS WOMAN'S BEST FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
PACK OF TWO 
The Intricate Bond Between People and Dogs 
By Caroline Knapp 
Dial, 249 pp., $21.95 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We dog lovers take particular delight not only in telling our
own stories, but in listening to those of others. To hear someone
rhapsodize about the beauty of a pet, or explain in minute detail
the particular quirks and needs of his or her little companion, is
enchanting. That's why dog books have such potential as big
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pack of Two: The Intricate Bond Between People and Dogs,''
Caroline Knapp writes the story of her relationship with her own
dog, and weaves in the experiences of others _ mostly other single,
urban women.
</P>
<P>
   She shows us the beauty, intelligence, and personality of her
dear Lucille, a mixed-breed rescued from a shelter, who may look
unremarkable to others but means everything to the woman who knows
her.
</P>
<P>
   Knapp becomes a poet when she describes this serious little dog:
``When you study a dog you love, you find beauty in every small
detail, and so it is with Lucille: I have become enchanted by the
small asymmetrical whorls of white fur on either side of her chest,
and by her tail, which she carries in a high, confident curve, and
by her eyes, which are watchful and intelligent, the color of
chestnuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Knapp is a talented writer, an astute observer, and a dog lover
of the highest rank. So she is at her best describing Lucille and
the happiness of being in her company. There is a thrill to the
cozy little scene in which Knapp has settled in for the night,
wrapped in a bathrobe, curled up with a crossword puzzle: ``I pass
a lot of evenings this way, hunkered down in that chair, and
sometimes I'll look up from whatever I'm doing, and I'll watch
Lucille for a moment or two. She always knows when I've turned my
attention to her _ she'll open her eyes and gaze back _ and I often
revel in the sense of comfort this gives me, the two of us together
in our quiet affinity.''
</P>
<P>
   Every owner can identify with that feeling, or with the tale of
the blue ball, Lucille's most treasured toy, which Knapp has gone
to heroic measures to rescue. The author will climb fences and ford
streams to retrieve that ball for her dog (non-dog people probably
think this should be the other way around).
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone will identify with Knapp's approach when she
leaves the anecdotal behind. In fact, the problem with ``Pack of
Two'' is that too much of it is told from the perspective of the
analyst's couch instead of the dog bed.
</P>
<P>
   There is a high level of intellectual, urban angst about the
meaning of life. Lucille is often some kind of canine Rorschach
test for Knapp's self-analysis. Most of us have experienced the
frustration of calling a dog who won't come; for Knapp, it's an
event fraught with emotional ramifications. ``When she ignores me
like this, I feel some well of fear rise up about being inadequate,
unworthy of attention, out of control. I hear a small voice inside:
... She doesn't come because she doesn't love you.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this perspective that will be jarring to many dog owners
who count on the love of their dogs. Rather than a source of
anxiety, most people report, dogs are a refuge from stress; they
bring us comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Lucille does this for Knapp at times, yet so much of
the book concentrates on fear and anxiety. Am I doing the right
thing? Does she love me? Do other people think I'm crazy for loving
a dog this much?
</P>
<P>
   Not feeding Lucille from the dinner table inspires pages of
anguish: ``In my mind, food is loaded with meaning, and the giving
and withholding of food are profoundly emotional acts.'' Tail
wagging, dreaming, sitting, running _ all these doggie behaviors
prompt soul-searching for Knapp, who didn't go out to dinner for
six months after finding Lucille because she couldn't bear the
separation.
</P>
<P>
   Knapp, the author of ``Drinking: A Love Story,'' says if there
were a 12-step program for codependent dog owners, she would be in
it. And she seems to associate with others who would be, too _
Milton, the psychiatrist who can't stand to see his boxer play
because it makes him remember feeling vulnerable as an unathletic
child in gym class; and Jonathan, who couldn't ever let his dog out
of his sight, not even for business meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dog as symbol, dog as mirror, dog as barometer of human
affairs,'' one section begins. But Knapp is at her best _ and I
wish there were a lot more of it _ when writing about dog as dog.
In those moments, even in the silly interactions, Knapp touches
upon this little miracle of loving a dog, and the utter joy it
brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armed with the blue ball,'' Knapp writes, ``Lucille gets to
run, and I get to act like a kid. I shout _ `Good save! Yes!' _ and
I run after her, and I tear off my jacket and scale fences, and I
laugh out loud.''
</P>
<P>
   When Knapp simply loses herself in Lucille there is magic. Too
bad the reader has to negotiate such vast, sometimes overwhelmingly
dense psychological terrain to get to those warm and verdant spots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
