<HEADLINE>
_HIGH JULY MOLD COUNT THANKS TO EL NINO   
 _ASTHMA DRUG STUDIES SHOW RELIEF IS FLEETING   
 _ARTICLE EXAMINES LEGALIZING SUICIDE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 High July mold count thanks to El Nino
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   July often is a lousy month for people who are allergic to mold,
but this year is setting records for misery.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of the year there normally would be up to 2,000
mold spores per cubic meter of air. Last week counts exceeded 3,000
spores, on Monday they rose to 4,700, and Wednesday they were above
6,000, which is ``the highest of any mold season we've seen,'' says
Dr. Thomas F. Johnson, medical director of New England Allergy,
Asthma and Immunology, a North Andover, Mass. firm that has tracked
mold counts since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Why so high? ``It's our last gasp of the El Nino effect,''
explains Johnson. ``It's a result of all the water we had this
springtime. With the dampness and heat, mold grows on the barks of
trees in the forests and wetlands. When the days are clear like
they've been the last 10 days, spores blow into the air just like
pollen blows from grass and trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all breathe it in, but if you have a mold allergy you react
exactly like you do to pollen grain if you have hay fever.''
</P>
<P>
   That reaction can range from asthma to sinusitis, hives,
swelling around the eyes, and nasal stuffiness. It already has sent
many people to the hospital and in extreme cases it can be
life-threatening. ``People should stay in air conditioning if
they're mold allergic,'' Johnson says, ``and they can take blocking
medication to prevent a reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news, the allergist adds, is that rain will wash out
the mold spores and, regardless of weather, mold counts
``inevitably will fall by the end of July. They always do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Asthma drug studies show relief is fleeting
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relief can come even sooner for millions of people who suffer
from exercise-induced asthma, although it may not last as long as
they hope.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the current New England Journal of Medicine, from
Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland, found that the drug
salmeterol is effective in treating the common form of asthma
triggered by vigorous exercise in cold, dry air. But there were
caveats: The relief doesn't last 12 hours, as reported, although at
the beginning it can last 9 hours. That relief also wanes after
continued use to the point where, after 30 days at twice-a-day
doses, patients showed no positive effects at 9 hours although they
still got relief 30 minutes after taking the drug.
</P>
<P>
   A second study in the journal looks at montelukast, a second
potential therapy for exercise-related asthma that recently was
approved for chronic asthma. Taking the drug once a day, the
authors from several medical centers said, provides ``significant
protection'' for up to 24 hours during a 12-week period. But it
doesn't work for everyone; 23 percent of subjects experienced
complete relief, while another 25 percent had little or no
response.
</P>
<P>
   The two drugs tested are among a new generation of asthma
medicines that ``prevent attacks from even occurring because they
block the mediator that causes an asthmatic reaction,'' says
Johnson. Older drugs like albuterol treat spasms after they occur.
</P>
<P>
   But two University of Pennsylvania doctors who wrote an
accompanying editorial caution that more studies will be needed to
see how the new drugs stack up against others on the market, and to
see if they work in patients with more severe forms of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Article examines legalizing suicide
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another article in the current New England Journal offers a new
take on the hot-button issue of physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been an assumption that laws to ease such deaths
would, among other things, save the US health care system lots of
money. Researchers from Boston and Salt Lake City explored that
presumption and found it sorely lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The potential savings from legalizing assisted suicide, they
wrote, ``can be predicted to be very small _ less than 0.1 percent
of both total health care spending in the United States and an
individual managed-care plan's budget.''
</P>
<P>
   They reached that conclusion after considering the experience in
the Netherlands, where euthanasia is legal, and looking at cost
data from America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real message of our article is, look, 99.97 percent of
Americans will get their same usual health care,'' Dr. Ezekiel J.
Emanuel, an oncologist at Harvard Medical School and one of the
authors of the current article, said in an interview. ``You just
can't save that much on less than .03 percent of the American
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
