<SLUG> BC-SPIRITUALIST-CAMP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE SPIRIT STILL MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONSET, Mass. _ At first, the Sunday service at the old New
England camp chapel seems conventional enough. There's the
invocation, a hymn, a sermon, prayers for the sick, and some
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the On-I-Set Wigwam Spiritualist Camp, a decidedly
different kind of religious summer colony.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the ``great spirit'' is invoked, the sermon is delivered
by a medium rather than a minister, and the focus is on
spiritualism, not the Bible. The announcements are mostly messages,
believers say, sent to them from those ``in spirit'' _ that is,
from the dead.
</P>
<P>
   At almost any other regional resort, spiritualism _ the belief
that the dead can communicate with the living through psychically
attuned individuals called mediums _ might be dismissed as yet
another New Age fad. But in Onset, a beachside village in Wareham
on the way to Cape Cod, trying to communicate with the dead keeps
alive both an unusual summer colony and a local tradition rooted in
mid-19th-century America.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know that Onset started out as a
spiritualist campground, and we're still here,'' says Mary Lou
Baumhoff of Salem, N.H., president of the Wigwam Camp. The village
was founded as a planned resort and meeting place for spiritualists
in 1877, Baumhoff says, at a time when millions of Americans were
still mourning the dead of the Civil War and when interest in
spiritualism became widespread.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, outdoor meetings in Onset drew crowds
approaching 10,000. These days, almost 200 people visit the camp on
a few special occasions, but midsummer services as a rule attract
no more than 40 or 50 people, believers and the curious alike,
usually including some tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a spiritualist all my life, and I've been coming to
the Wigwam ever since I was 4 years old,'' says 84-year-old Ruth
Dyer of New Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the 104-year-old Wigwam Camp no longer has cottages
or tent sites but does offer twice-weekly services, along with
classes, seminars, and workshops on spiritualism. There is also a
year-round church in the village, the First Spiritualist Church of
Onset, founded in 1903. ``We belong to different spiritualist
denominations,'' says Baumhoff, ``but we're all friends.''
</P>
<P>
   All activities at the camp take place in the original chapel,
the Wigwam. Dedicated in 1894, the red-painted building is an
octagonal, shingled, single-story structure topped by a 26-foot
conical roof that intentionally resembles an Indian tepee.
``There's no other building in the world like it,'' says Baumhoff.
``During the 1938 hurricane, the Wigwam was spun completely around
and settled back on its foundations with the front door where the
back door used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The camp was founded by Mary Weston, a Boston medium and artist
who, says Baumhoff, wanted to honor the American Indian ``guides''
who so many mediums claimed had helped them contact spirits on
``the other side.'' (The camp and village are named for the same
colonial-era local Indian chief.) In particular, Weston wished to
recognize her own guide, whom she called ``Big Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the Wigwam is like going back a century. Varnished
wooden walls are adorned with photos of turn-of-the-century
spiritualist gatherings, old banners and mementos, and many
portraits of noted mediums who long ago ``went into spirit.'' Also
displayed are a number of Weston's oil paintings of Indians,
including several of a surprisingly animated Big Mountain. &UR;  &LR; A
cabinet contains a collection of slates with chalked ``spirit''
messages and drawings done by mediums who said they were relaying
communications during trances.
</P>
<P>
   The focal point of the Wigwam is ``the healing pole,'' a wooden
pillar _ decorated with beads, bunting, and a plaster statue of a
war-bonneted Indian _ around which the sick gather at services to
seek help from the great spirit. ``The pole was sensitized by
Micmac Indians when the Wigwam opened,'' says Baumhoff, ``and
rededicated by a Micmac holy man at our centennial four years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   A Wigwam service is rather matter-of-fact in tone, but offbeat
in content. After a sermon, medium Dorothy Thurlow of West Newbury
points to camp members and delivers to believers such humdrum
messages from the beyond: ``A tall white-haired man named David
sends greetings,'' and ``A man who knew you says be careful when
carrying paper money.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, a message means nothing to the person receiving it or is
so general it could apply to almost anyone. But getting a message
that hits home has been known to convert a sceptic.
</P>
<P>
   Over coffee after the service, Alice O'Brien of
Springfield, &UR;  &LR; Mass., who summers in Wareham, recounts how she
became a spiritualist eight years ago. She says she consulted a
medium who conveyed a message from a man described as having only
one finger on his right hand. ``That was my father,'' says O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't use the term `seance' much anymore,'' says Baumhoff.
``But a nonspiritualist might consider the message circle at our
services, when we contact the so-called dead, as a seance.''
</P>
<P>
   Baumhoff says the services are generally attended by more women
than men, but she insists that the spiritualist movement is not
almost exclusively female, as critics sometimes claim.
``Spiritualism isn't New Age, but many New Age people are attracted
to it now, including men,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Many Wigwam regulars, such as Baumhoff, O'Brien, and Dyer, also
belong to spiritualist churches that they attend in the offseason.
The Wigwam Camp is affiliated with the National Spiritualist
Association of Churches, largest of the 16 American spiritualist
denominations, which has 150 member churches and summer camps
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Like most spiritualists, Baumhoff says, she doesn't conceal her
beliefs but doesn't advertise them or proselytize. ``Spiritualism
is a religion of conviction, not conversion,'' she says. ``We let
people come to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wigwam Camp operates from early June through August. Classes
on spiritualism are held every Wednesday at 6 p.m., followed by a
service at 7:30 p.m. Sunday services are at 2 p.m. ``Medium Days,''
during which practitioners are available for private consulations,
are held from 1 to 3 p.m. on the second and fourth Saturday each
month of the season. The Wigwam building is open to visitors from
10 a.m. to 4 p.m. on weekends, and by appointment during the week
(508 291-0073).
</P>
<P>
   In the decades since the community's founding, the tents of the
first Onset campers gave way to trim summer cottages, handsome
housesand turreted hotels, and guest houses, most of which remain
and make Onset one of the best preserved Victorian seaside
communities in the country. Although only 96 feet in circumference,
the endearingly eccentric Wigwam has become the symbol of the
village's Victorian heyday.
</P>
<P>
   The Wigwam and its grounds and outbuildings were completely
restored by local volunteers for the camp's centennial celebration
in 1994, and the building is the only one in Onset nominated to the
National Register of Historic Places. ``We're not the least bit
embarrassed by our spiritualist beginnings,'' says Geraldine Pearle
of the Onset Protective League.
</P>
<P>
   The Wigwam Camp is credited with initiating what is now a
beloved annual Onset observance, the Harvest Moon Festival held the
first weekend in September to mark the end of the summer season.
The first festivals were organized by Weston and her followers, who
sold food and handicrafts to finance construction of the Wigwam.
``We still have the festival in the park on Onset Bluffs,
overlooking the harbor,'' says Pearle. ``In the old days, that's
also where the spiritualists had all their big events.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
