<HEADLINE>
KEEP THE PROUST, GIVE ME SUPERMARKET TABLOIDS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   I'm tempted to tell you that I'll be spending the summer reading
Proust, but you wouldn't believe it, would you? I didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers and magazines are full of other people's summer
reading lists. Some of the choices seem almost too literary to be
true. Boston broadcaster Christopher Lydon, for example, tells the
Globe's Names &AMP; Faces column that he plans to spend the summer
rereading, emphasis on re-, Emerson. Well, I suppose he would. So
maybe I shouldn't be so cynical and just learn to accept these
things at face value.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, by the time I've gotten through the daily papers it's
all I can do to keep up with the supermarket tabloids, especially
now, with Bruce and Demi splitting and Barbra and what'shisname
getting hitched. The Streisand wedding was either a ``cozy
ceremony'' (Star), or Barbra was ``the bride from hell'' (National
Enquirer). Take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   The unmistakable aroma of sour grapes hovers over both tabloid
accounts of the merger, doubtless because the bride sold People
magazine exclusive rights to cover the wedding for a reported $1
million. After wedding expenses, the Enquirer calculated Barbra
made a profit of $500,000 on the day. Not bad, if true. People's
reverent million-dollar coverage must be seen (and read) to be
believed, and even then ... but there I go again. When will I ever
learn?
</P>
<P>
   One of the very best things about supermarket tabloids is that,
unlike books, you can toss them out when you're done with them.
Unless you feel compelled to keep back copies piled up is little
heaps all over the floor of your office. Which brings me once again
to the crucial matter of whether Nancy Sinatra was at her father's
side when he died, as the obituary in this paper had it, or
watching the ``Seinfeld'' finale, as I claimed in a column.
</P>
<P>
   A reader asked Boston Globe ombudsman Jack Thomas to sort out
the contradiction. Thomas seemed dubious when I scrounged around
under my desk and produced month-old copies of the Star and The
National Enquirer, both of which reported Nancy's absence from her
father's side. Now here's USA Today for July 14th, with Nancy
Sinatra saying that she'd planned to visit her father the night he
died but, ```Seinfeld' reruns started prior to the `Seinfeld'
finale _ isn't this tacky? _ I got so involved watching that damn
show that I never got over to my dad's.'' So there.
</P>
<P>
   The first book on my own summer list is Diane Irons's ``The
World's Best-Kept Diet Secrets.'' I was up until midnight devouring
it, so to speak, only to conclude that some of these secrets should
have remained well-kept, this one, for example: ``If you love a
certain food, save the wrapper even after you've eaten it. You'll
trick yourself into believing you ate it. Smell it when you're
hungry. Models buy candy bars, throw away the candy and carry the
wrappers in their model's bag.'' (No wonder so many young women are
clamoring to get into modeling.)
</P>
<P>
   My second, and so far last, summer book, is Kate Summerscale's
``The Queen of Whale Cay: The Eccentric Story of `Joe' Carstairs,
Fastest Woman on Water.'' Eccentric barely begins to describe
Carstairs, heir to the Standard Oil fortune, speedboat racer,
big-game hunter, ``queen'' of her own Carribbean island. She liked
to think of her life starting where this biography begins, with
Marion Barbara Carstairs, age 5, being thrown off a bolting camel
at the London Zoo and knocked unconscious, and waking up as
``Joe.'' As a teenage ambulance driver in France in World War I,
she was seduced by Dolly Wilde, Oscar Wilde's niece. Eventually she
counted Greta Garbo and Marlene Dietrich among her 120 lovers. The
true love of her life, though, was a little doll, Lord Tod Wadley,
who went everywhere with her, with whom she's pictured on the
book's dustjacket. So it's not Proust. But it's a wonderful
biography.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
