<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTOMOLOGISTS ZAP BEETLES WITH WASPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Within an ever-widening ring around Boston, gardeners have
discovered lacquer-red beetles eating summer lilies down to their
stalks. The new arrival from Europe, which probably dodged customs
by hitching a ride on some infected lily bulbs, is a good flier and
has been found as far as 100 miles from Boston since first being
identified in Cambridge in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But while gardeners have been disgruntled, Richard Casagrande of
the University of Rhode Island was almost jaunty when he heard
about the beetles at an Entomology Society meeting. ``I bet a beer
on the spot with a colleague that we'd solve this one.''
</P>
<P>
   And the way Casagrande's research has gone, he'll be collecting
that beer soon, and we'll be able to grow lilies easily again in
three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Casagrande hopes to be able to release parasitic wasps from
France that eat lily leaf beetles _ and nothing else _ next year.
He and his graduate students have been growing and testing two
kinds of wasps in a quarantine lab in Kingston, R.I. If the federal
paperwork is completed in time, one species of tiny European wasp
may be released into a stand of lilies growing at the Massachusetts
Horticultural Society's Elm Bank in Dover next spring.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Casagrande expects the new parasites to spread
throughout the infected area in about three years, allowing
gardeners to enjoy lilies once again. ``If the wasps need some help
getting around,'' said the entomologist, ``we'll ask Mass Hort to
host `parasite giveaways.'''
</P>
<P>
   Casagrande knows he has a hot commodity, despite the fact that
his is a shoestring operation funded only by lily growers. And he
knew what he was looking for on his research trips to France.
That's because he earned his doctorate at Michigan State University
by finding a parasite to control the cereal beetle, a kissing
cousin of the lily leaf beetle. This one had also arrived from
Europe and was ripping through grain fields. ``But once we got a
parasite, it only took three years to spread through the area. We
went from devastation to no problem in five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the wonder of successful biological control, as the
technique of using a pest's natural enemies is called. It's proving
especially effective against the growing number of invasive plants
and insects that slip through customs now that international travel
and trade is commonplace. Often these new pests cause much more
trouble here than in their native lands because no native predators
have co-evolved locally to feed on them.
</P>
<P>
   So entomologists are going to the pest's native turf to find
some of its natural enemies to keep it under control here. That's
what Mark McClure at the Connecticut Agricultural Experimental
Station is trying to do with ladybugs he imported from Japan that
feed on woolly adelgid, a Japanese aphid that is killing hemlocks
here. And that's what Bernd Blossey of Cornell University did
recently when he imported European insects that are now showing
incredible success in reducing the purple loosestrife that's taken
over our wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation of entomologists less keen on insecticides than
their predecessors, biological control is an exciting alternative.
Sayles Livingston of Little Compton, R.I., who did her master's
dissertation on the lily leaf beetle under Casagrande, was
exhilarated by the project. ``Biological control is such an
up-and-coming way of dealing with insect problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But what should gardeners do to safeguard their lilies while
waiting for the parasitic wasps to arrive on the scene?
</P>
<P>
   If you're growing a small number of lilies, handpicking is best,
though you must keep it up from May through August. The bright red
beetles drop easily into a jar of bleach or alcohol held underneath
the leaf they're on. Snip off and dunk leaves that have
coral-colored lines underneath. Ditto for leaves containing the
ugly, slug-like larvae (immature beetles), which wear their own
excrement as a defense mechanism. Be sure to use gloves. The most
important thing to look for is the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was part of a crew that handpicked the insects at
Habitat, a Belmont, Mass. nature preserve with a policy against
pesticide use. ``When we started five years ago, it was loaded with
lily leaf beetles. Now it's hard to find any there.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to spray, Livingston recommends Neem, a newly
registered insecticide that is relatively nontoxic, based upon
extracts from the neem tree. Neem can be purchased at garden
centers under the trade names Turplex, Azatin EC, Margosan-O,
Align, and BioNeem. But it must be applied every two weeks, June
through July.
</P>
<P>
   Merit (imidacloprid) is effective as a once-a-year spring soil
drench but is not yet readily available for homeowners as it is
sold only in bulk, and few of us would need $100 worth of the
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Lily leaf beetles (liltingly known in Latin as Lilioceris lilii)
travel only about 10 miles a year under their own power and so far
are mostly confined inside the Interstate 495 ring. But some have
hitched rides to as far away as Cape Cod, Worcester, Gardner,
eastern Connecticut, southern New Hampshire, and Maine. To slow the
spread, it's important not to transport potted lily plants outside
Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   If you live farther than 50 miles outside Boston and have lily
leaf beetles in your garden, report it to the URI Biological
Control Laboratory at 401-874-2750.
</P>
<P>
   How to recognize the beetles?
</P>
<P>
   _They look like ladybugs without spots.
</P>
<P>
   _They're half-an-inch long with an oblong, bright scarlet body
and black legs, head antennae, and undersurface.
</P>
<P>
   _They're eating your lilies. They'll also eat your fritillaria,
but not your day lilies.
</P>
<P>
   One more tip-off: If you squeeze them gently, they squeak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
