<HEADLINE>
THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I knew this past spring was going to be tough. In addition to
writing this column every week, I'd be actively promoting my new
book, ``Family Puzzles.'' The newly formed Marblehead (Mass.)
Cancer Prevention Project was planning a major environmental forum
for the town and I had taken on responsibility for being the
moderator.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a tightly scheduled period that I barely squeezed in
time with my grandchildren. I stopped cooking, dropped all forms of
exercise, canceled our social life, and had to make an appointment
with myself to wash my hair. I was as fully occupied as I've ever
been, pushing the limits of my physical and emotional energy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, without warning, my husband developed an aneurysm, had
brain surgery, and came home to recuperate. I struggled to recover
my footing. Two days after Jack's operation (my colleagues in the
MCPP having taken care of every detail), I stood on stage in front
of 600 people, cool as a cucumber. I also managed to make every one
of my scheduled book signings, interviews, and lectures. I was
proud of how efficiently I was making use of every minute, but I
was looking forward to a time when everything would finally slow
down. I imagined long weekends at our shelter in Vermont and lazy
afternoons at the beach with my grandchildren. I longed to get back
to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Then without warning, my son-in-law's father developed
disturbing physical symptoms and in the course of an intensely
emotional week, we found out that Terry had pancreatic cancer,
which had metastasized to his liver and lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Now Laura and Brian were away in Maine every weekend and Jack
and I were trying to help lighten their burden by pitching in when
they needed someone to look after the kids. We spent a weekend
saying goodbye to Terry and another attending the extraordinary
memorial service that his family, friends, and colleagues conducted
at the University of Maine in Augusta, where he'd been a professor
of English for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   That Saturday night, however, after my husband had fallen
asleep, I lay awake in an Augusta motel, trying to plan the coming
week. My assistant was on maternity leave. The unfinished, yet
urgent, business on my desk was beginning to resemble an
archeological dig; I wasn't sure what was there but I knew by now
it stretched back into antiquity. We were heading back first thing
in the morning because my friend Lanie and I were throwing a baby
shower for Jimmi, the young Brandeis graduate whose second child is
due in July. And on Monday, when I'd counted on getting back to
work at last, I was scheduled for jury duty.
</P>
<P>
   I had to figure out how to build some flexibility into this
crushing schedule. After several brief, excruciating headaches, my
sister Susan had just been diagnosed with three aneurysms,
unbelievable as that seems, and was in the process of scheduling
brain surgery. I had this thought: (itals)If my life is so busy
that I can't find time for my sister, this life is not worth
living.(unitals) That realization jolted me into a state of anxiety
so intense I had to wake Jack up to help me calm down.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen? My kids are grown. I'm self-employed. If
anyone has control over her life, I'm that person. Yet, here I was
face-to-face with an unavoidable fact. The machinelike efficiency
that my pace demanded was destroying my spontaneity, my
responsiveness, and my aliveness. Having built too many things into
my life, thinking how enjoyable each one would be, I had severely
diminished my ability to take pleasure from any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Curled up on the bed, my throat so constricted with dread that
Jack had to lean over to hear me, I realized what I'd done wrong.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't left time to be available.
</P>
<P>
   Once again (Will I never learn?), I'd forgotten that there were
important activities not written in my day planner. An illness, a
death, a need, a desire; these were as crucial, if not more so,
than the items on my list. Having blithely ignored them, already
milking my time for every ``nanosecond of productivity,'' as
Richard Swenson puts it in his book, ``Margin: Restoring Emotional,
Physical, Financial, and Time Reserve to Overloaded Lives,'' I felt
overwhelmed when they were called to my attention by some power not
under my control. I'm presently revising my schedule, canceling
dates, saying no, rereading Swenson's book, and visiting Susan, who
has made a remarkable recovery. I have a new mantra I whisper to
myself.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Linda, don't just do something, be there!(unitals)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
