<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-ENCOUNTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHS DRAWN TO CHURCH ORGANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Raymond Nagem is a miniature man. He wears his white
polo shirt neatly tucked into his slacks and his brown hair cleanly
combed to the side. He pauses in reflection before he speaks,
displaying a maturity that belies his 12 years and 5-foot frame.
</P>
<P>
   But behind his compact size, neat appearance, and soft voice is
a boy who likes his music loud. His sound system towers over any
high-end, multispeaker stereo. The boom of its bass can jolt your
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Nagem, you see, plays the mammoth ``king of instruments,'' the
church organ, and has spent this week attacking the biggest, most
majestic pipe organs in Boston. The Pipe Organ Encounter, an annual
five-day overnight camp, concludes today after introducing 52
youths to the musical behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to turn up the volume all the way and feel the bench
shake,'' says Nagem, who lives in Medford. ``I want to make anyone
who's down there turn their heads up and listen. It's an awesome
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the late '80s, Pipe Organ Encounters have been exposing
young people, especially budding pianists, to the might and
splendor of one of the oldest instruments. The Youth Organists
Initiative, which is hosting the Boston encounter, sprang from
concern over the marginal interest in organ playing among young
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things are out there, screaming for our attention _
soccer, ballet, whatever,'' said Glenn Goda, co-director of Pipe
Organ Encounter in Boston. ``We in the organ world have to say this
is a viable alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year an encounter has been held in Boston,
whose prominence in organ playing, composing, and building can be
traced to the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Pipe Organ Encounter camps are being held this
summer, in Seattle; Waco, Texas; and Sioux Trails, S.D. A total of
200 students, most of them ages 12 to 18,enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   At this summer camp, kids don't gather around a fire singing
``Blackbird'' to the strains of a guitar. Here, they circle around
organists tackling Bach's Toccata in D Minor.
</P>
<P>
   As 11-year-old Randy Santini sends his fingers gamboling along
the Flentrop organ at Harvard University's Adolphus Busch Hall, his
shoes seem barely to touch the pedals. Other students can't
reconcile what they see _ a 4-foot-11-inch boy _ and what they hear
_ the complicated, familiar toccata that reaches the depths of
one's heart. ``No, that's not him playing, is it?'' one girl asks.
</P>
<P>
   Santini, of North Weymouth, gets paid to perform local concerts
and has been called a prodigy, according to his father, Paul, a
bandleader. ``But I don't see it,'' says dad. ``To me, he's just a
kid who gets grounded a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pipe Organ Encounter, students take private lessons from
Boston-area organists, visit organ shops, attend concerts, and
indulge in ``organ crawls,'' from one outstanding local church
organ to another. Sometimes the students are permitted to try a few
bars on the instrument. Think of it as bar hopping for the
underaged and musically talented.
</P>
<P>
   During her lesson at First Church in Cambridge, Caty Sumner, 15,
first delivers a frolicky tune that requires a dancelike shuffle of
her feet. Her old Birkenstocks have been tossed onto the floor in
favor of the traditional organ shoes with smooth leather soles,
which easily slide along the giant pedals. She pulls the stops _
sets of knobs that flank the keyboards _ to open additional pipes
behind her. She maneuvers her hands from one keyboard to another.
Her long and loose limbs seem suited for operating the huge battery
of pedals, buttons, keys, and switches.
</P>
<P>
   When she practices Bach's ``Ich ruf zu dir Herr Jesu Christ,''
her teacher, Carl Klein, dances behind her. He switches from her
left to right side, pulling and pushing the stops, searching for
the sound he wants. He lightly touches the small of her back, and
Sumner, as if on reflex, straightens it to an arrow. He walks down
to the pews and bows his head, listening to the acoustics in the
dimly lit church.
</P>
<P>
   After the lesson, Sumner takes multiple snapshots of the stately
organ at rest. She says she does this at every organ she plays.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Sumner's heard all the jokes. Organists ``play with their
feet'' (referring to the keyboard pedals on the floor), jam to
church hymns, and sport those cutesy black pointy shoes _ but with
pride. ``It's countercultural,'' says Klein, an organist at
University Lutheran Church in Cambridge. ``We live in a secular
society. Organ music is usually associated with church music, so
you get that stigma attached to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sumner is a member of the ``Organ Geeks,'' a close-knit group of
young organists around the country. The name was bestowed at a Pipe
Organ Encounter in 1995 by University of Pennsylvania students who,
spotting the group around campus, would yell, ``There go the organ
geeks!''
</P>
<P>
   Some Organ Geeks have now been to three or four encounters, even
though the camps were originally intended for beginning players.
``The Organ Geeks only get five days a year when we can be
together,'' Sumner says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun catching up with each other on what we've been doing
over the past year, the concerts we've been to, etc.,'' says Matt
Emkay, 17, of Wyomissing, Pa. ``It's great to hear people your age
making music. At home, we don't have friends who are organists.
This is the interest that makes us special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Geeks try rebelling against the lights-out rule in their
Boston University dorm, staying up in each other's rooms to sing
Bach fugues. They publish the year-round Organ Geek Newsletter and
send copies to 25 dues-paying members. They trade organ music, brag
about getting their pictures taken with famous organist Diane Bish,
speak breathlessly about the ``wicked loud'' pipes of certain
organs they've played.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Encounter co-director Mary Sue Willie says drawing young
organists together from around the country for five days is the
ultimate reward. ``It's a terrific high,'' she says. ``Most of them
are pretty lonely. ... No one understands them.''
</P>
<P>
   Except here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
