<HEADER>
A8037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-16 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CAMP COMPLAINTS TO COMPROMISING ON PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What do you do if your child gets stuck with a hellion for a
bunkmate at overnight camp?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Consider the timing of the complaint. If you're hearing about
it during the first week, most directors consider it part of the
settling-in process. Be empathetic nonetheless, but take it more
seriously if it persists beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question I'd ask is, `How much is this bothering
you?''' says psychologist Bruce Muchnick of Glenside, Pa., who
consults to camps. ``The second question is, `How much is it
bothering other kids?' There may be a coping skill she can copy.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how she answers those questions, your best strategy is
to empower her _ ``What do you think you can do?'' ``Have you
talked to the counselor?'' _ at the same time you support her:
``How can we help?'' As with many issues at camp, some kids feel
better as soon as they hang up from talking to you (although you
may feel worse). Even if you think your child is overreacting, a
lack of sympathy will make him feel unsupported. ``Whether he's
overreacting or not, it's real for him,'' says Muchnick.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely call the director, says Barnes Boffey, a family
counselor and director of Camp Lanakilia, a boys camp in Vermont.
Expect a director to offer to brainstorm an action plan with your
child. ``You don't want kids to think they call Mom and Dad and
problems get fixed by magic,'' he says. ``They need to see the
process work.'' For him, helping kids learn how to work out
interpersonal differences is what camp is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Once your child is getting help, Boffey says it's OK to ask her
to tough it out for a few days to see if things get better. But
only for a few days. Expecting her to tough it out for any longer
is asking for trouble, he says. If she's miserable, bring her home.
</P>
<P>
   And what if the director reports back that, yes, your child
described the situation accurately, but he, the director, doesn't
think it's a big deal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's a value judgment,'' says Boffey. You may be willing
to go along with a director who brushes off bad language or poor
hygiene, but what about racial epithets, bullying, or hitting?
``The moment you feel uncomfortable leaving your child there
because you don't trust the director's values or think your child
is not safe, you need to go get him,'' says Boffey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's a good response when your child says, ``Don't tell
Dad/Mom''?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. When kids under 5 make this request, it's a way for them to
feel in control, says child psychologist Louise Guerney, a
specialist in parent-child relationships and professor emeritus at
Penn State University. It's OK to go along in an exaggerated,
game-like way, as long as somewhere along the line you say, ``You
know, if it's something serious, I can't keep it a secret from
Daddy.'' With this age, though, the secret is usually innocuous.
</P>
<P>
   By school age, it may not be, and your child's motive for not
wanting you to tell probably isn't either. He may be afraid of
punishment or of facing a parent's disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying message to convey to children of all ages is that
parents don't have secrets from each other about their children.
``It undermines the parenting process,'' says Guerney. She
recommends saying, ``I can't make that promise in advance. If it's
really important, I have to tell Daddy.'' Young children will most
acquiesce but a child 8 or older may feel betrayed and clam up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may feel like you are cutting off communication, and it
may feel to your child like you are leaving him high and dry,''
says Guerney. ``Stress that you will use your judgment _ `Can you
trust me to decide after I hear?' _ and offer alternatives: `If you
don't want to tell me, is there some other adult you can talk
to?''' If you have a spouse who typically overreacts and your child
has reason to be fearful, acknowledge it: ``I know Dad sometimes
comes down too hard, but I can't make that promise until I know
what it's about. Can we evaluate the situation together after I
have the information?''
</P>
<P>
   When an older child's request not to tell is frequent, it can be
a red flag that there's an underlying problem in a relationship.
Sometimes just making your spouse aware is all it takes to reopen
communication. Other times, professional intervention may help.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I read your column last week (on competition) with interest.
Do you have advice concerning my 9-year-old son? He cannot
participate in any game or activity without winning. If he loses,
he is immediately in a bad mood for the next hour. This applies to
playing a family board game or shooting baskets in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A child this age who's a poor sport is at risk for losing
friends and becoming more and more unhappy as time goes on. Marty
Block, an associate professor of education at the University of
Virginia, offers these suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _Make sure you model good sportsmanship yourself and point out
examples of it when you see it. Make it clear you don't admire bad
sports, not even in professionals. Talk about how other kids don't
like poor sports, either.
</P>
<P>
   _Talk about what it feels like to win and to lose. Acknowledge
that it feels better to win but stress the positives that can come
from losing gracefully, like gaining respect in a playmate's eyes,
identifying a weakness so you can work on it, or giving another
person a chance to feel good about himself.
</P>
<P>
   _Make sure he's in situations where teamwork and cooperation are
rewarded. Praise him when he exhibits those qualities, even if all
you can see is that he's trying harder.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the ways to help a poor loser, Block likes natural
consequences the best. ``If his sulking gets him lots of attention,
it's getting rewarded, even though it's negative attention,'' he
says. Avoid this by establishing consequences before you play: ``We
want to play with you, but it spoils our fun if you can't be a good
sport. If you lose and sulk, you need to go to your room.'' Or:
``If you can't be a good sport this time, next time we won't
include you.'' Follow through with the consequences firmly and
without fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   While he's sulking in his room, if you happen to do something he
would have enjoyed, tell him afterward: ``It's too bad you were
sulking. You missed out on ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of natural consequences that get fast
results,'' quips Block.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The mothers of my 6-year-old's new friends would prefer to
drive 10 miles to a park than have the kids play on the swings and
treehouse in our back yard, or go to an indoor arcade instead of
playing in our attic, which is filled with toys. On beautiful days,
``How about a nature hike?'' is met with, ``The boys should rest
before soccer'' which is before baseball ... My husband and I don't
believe in all this for 6-year-olds. Am I heading my son toward
nerdville? Should I cave?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Not cave, but compromise, says Diane Levin, a professor of
early childhood education at Wheelock College who is nationally
recognized for her work on children's play. There's no question the
opportunities you're providing are better for any child's
development. ``These mothers aren't giving them the chance to
direct their own play, which is what kids need at this age,'' says
Levin. ``The more they're programmed, the more they need to be
programmed and expect excitement to be created for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But while it's important for children to have what Levin calls
old-fashioned play where they use their imagination, make their own
rules, and stretch themselves creatively, you're right to sense
that sticking to your guns totally could isolate your son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick out the least offensive activities these mothers do with
their boys and involve your son a little with them,'' she says.
``In the meantime, find other playmates whose parents' values mesh
with yours.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ If you want to help a 7- to 14-year-old improve
baseball skills, try ``The Hitting Recipe,'' a video by Tom Clark,
a scout for the Oakland Athletics. Send $34.95 to Box 60536,
Worcester, MA 01606.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
