<HEADLINE>
HUGE PERSONAL DEBT MAY COST CELLUCCI AT POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN C. MOONEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For a politician known to vacillate on some issues,
Acting Governor Paul Cellucci is remarkably resolute on one matter:
He won't be interviewed about his personal finances this year.
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly has rejected requests for interviews about the
$700,000-plus monkey on his back, most recently last week when he
turned down the Globe's second formal request in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci describes this as ``an old story.'' But it's one that
bears updating since the Globe reported in 1996 that he owed
$750,000, nearly $70,000 on credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   It's significant because Cellucci, over the past 25 years, has
systematically mortgaged his assets to sustain a lifestyle he
apparently could not afford. Today, everything he owns is mortgaged
to or near the hilt. Habitual borrowing unleashes mathematical
forces, which become almost irreversible and now require Cellucci
each month to pay several thousand dollars in interest alone.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it must be embarrassing for Cellucci to explain how
he's become so deeply in debt despite a comfortable family income
which averaged almost $130,000 annually over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   But his explanations in the past have never added up. Two years
ago, he detailed perhaps half of the total loan burden he's
amassed. He says he pays all his bills on time and insists his
assets are worth more than his liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   That's his story, and he's sticking to it. Maybe it will
suffice.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that a relatively small fraction of voters will
consider his financial fiasco a disqualifier-type issue when they
go to the polls. The risk for Cellucci, however, is that his
apparent incompetence in managing his own finances creates one of
those gnawing ``What's going on here?'' issues that other voters,
maybe many, will weigh among other factors.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe's request for an interview last week will not be the
last time he will be asked about his debts between now and the
election. The issue could arise in a debate or news story.
</P>
<P>
   Few will argue that Cellucci is a threat to mismanage state
finances. He isn't. The state is running a $1 billion surplus. Even
if the economy goes south, taking state revenues with it,
administration and finance Secretary Charles D. Baker runs that
part of the show. His ability is unquestioned.
</P>
<P>
   But it's legitimate for voters to consider the degree to which
Cellucci's chronic personal overspending reflects on his judgment
in the most basic of responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci has claimed he fell into a hole because of $130,000 in
home renovations, $100,000 in private school tuitions over a
decade, and a temporary drop in income after he became lieutenant
governor and gave up his part-time law practice.
</P>
<P>
   But he is clearly a man who has lived beyond his means, and not
merely in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   The long slow slide into a financial morass began 24 years ago
when his parents gave Cellucci and his wife an acre lot on Lincoln
Street in Hudson. They borrowed $22,500, and four years later
refinanced for $31,000. A year after that, they began taking
additional equity out in a series of second mortgages, each
progressively larger, starting at $10,000, then $18,000 in 1980,
$45,000 three years after that, and, finally, $60,000 shortly
before they sold the house for $115,000 in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a pattern of Cellucci borrowing against assets, which
precipitated the $70,000 runup on credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   These are not isolated emergencies. When he consolidated three
mortgages on his current Brigham Street home in 1992 for $314,000,
more than a third of the principal was equity taken out of the
property. It had not been used to ``to buy, build or improve'' his
home, according to his most recent tax returns, which he releases
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a vacant lot in Hudson was a gift from his parents
and brother. He borrowed $100,000 against it. When he sold it in
1994 for $150,000, he netted only a few thousand dollars after
paying off the loan, taxes, and fees.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates the fair market value of his 22 percent share of
Cellucci Hudson Corp., the family's commercial real estate
business, at $300,000 to $350,000. Most, if not all, of that is
mortgaged to secure one bank loan worth well over $200,000, plus
another used to pay off the $70,000 in credit card debt.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all that, Cellucci still owes more than $100,000 for a
bank loan unsecured by any collateral at all, according to his most
recent financial disclosure report.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be nice if we could all get one of those?
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Cellucci is breaking up the furniture to keep the
fire going. In the past three years, the family business has sold
two properties, representing a third of its holdings. That
generated some onetime income for our acting chief executive, but
had little impact on his debt total.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever deep pockets Cellucci once had are now about empty. He
owns no other stock with a value of more than $1,000, according to
his state financial disclosure forms. Based on his tax returns last
year, he had an average daily balance of several thousand dollars
in an interest-bearing bank account. He has a pot of retirement
funds set aside for the future (he's 50), but his tax returns show
he also redeemed a life insurance policy, with a cash value of
$7,666, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci blames the sacrifice of giving up his law practice as
one of the fundamental causes of his financial predicament.
</P>
<P>
   But the vast majority of his constituents would consider
themselves well off indeed if they had his income of the last
decade, even in the supposedly low-earnings years.
</P>
<P>
   In the three years before he became lieutenant governor,
Cellucci averaged about $115,000 per year. For the past four years,
Cellucci and his wife declared average adjustable gross income of
$184,175. In between were his first three years in office when he
took the short-term income hit. Even during that time, 1991-93, the
Celluccis averaged $96,719 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters making much less will be forgiven if they look at
Cellucci's debt and wonder: What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Brian C. Mooney is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
