<HEADLINE>
CNN LOSES BATTLE, BUT KEEPS SPOILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the smoke cleared on CNN's ``Operation Tailwind,'' story,
almost all the casualties were from friendly fire. The network's
now-retracted report alleging that US forces used deadly nerve gas
on a 1970 mission in Laos cost three producers their jobs; damaged
the reputation of star correspondent Peter Arnett; raised questions
about the stewardship of CNN/US president Rick Kaplan; and wounded
a network that had been known for straight, solid journalism.
</P>
<P>
   But what about collateral damage done to CNN and its vital
relationship to the Pentagon? The Department of Defense is
certainly angry about charges that it unleashed the same weapon
that the United States has demonized Saddam Hussein for using. And
retired Major General Bill Nash, a visiting lecturer at Harvard's
Shorenstein Center, said that after years of Pentagon/press
detente, the Tailwind report ``caused a flashback to the days of
old'' when those relations were poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems logical that CNN should expect a Pentagon backlash.
Yet, military and media experts said that no matter how angry the
department may be, CNN won't pay a major price for Tailwind. In a
case of pragmatism trumping ideology, the Pentagon knows it still
needs CNN and is smart enough to recognize a public relations
windfall when it sees one.
</P>
<P>
   CNN ``has heard from the highest levels of the Pentagon that
there will be no impact,'' said a network spokesman, Steve Haworth.
``If our relationship survived Peter Arnett ... in Baghdad, it will
certainly survive this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you the Department of Defense has a tremendous
respect for CNN,'' said a Pentagon spokesman, Lieutenant Colonel
Bill Darley. ``And the respect is ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath those official pleasantries is more than a grain of
truth. For one thing, CNN's respected Pentagon correspondent Jamie
McIntyre _ who had no role in developing the Tailwind story _ won
friends in the military by writing a memo questioning the piece
before it aired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Covering the Pentagon is sort of personality dependent, not
institution dependent,'' said CBS Pentagon correspondent David
Martin. Because McIntyre distanced himself from Tailwind, Martin
added, ``I think if anything, it's probably improved their ability
to cover the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the reality that the Pentagon can't afford to
alienate a resource like CNN, which functions not only as a 24-hour
news outlet, but as an intelligence service. ``I think there will
be a certain atmospheric attitude toward CNN over'' at the
Pentagon, said retired general and NBC military consultant Bernard
Trainor. But the network won't incur serious penalties, he said,
because ``CNN's too important to the whole equation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the military, CNN is very important, maybe more than CNN
knows'' said Jack Galvin, dean of Tufts's Fletcher School of Law
and Diplomacy and former supreme allied commander in Europe. In his
military headquarters, Galvin says, ``CNN was on in there all the
time . ... That might be the first indicator that something might
be wrong somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, CNN did not escape unscathed. Even if Tailwind did no
permanent damage to the network's standing at the Pentagon, many
veterans seem less forgiving. ``The place where it has lasting
impact is among vets,'' said CBS's Martin. ``There is a body of
people who see the Jane Fonda-Ted Turner-Peter Arnett conspiracy.''
Sure enough, a posting on the Web site of the Special Operations
Association vigorously attacks the troika of ``Tailwind Ted, Hanoi
Jane, and their pal Baghdad Pete.''
</P>
<P>
   But observers said the Pentagon itself is likely to respond to
Tailwind by choosing an option it rejected in Vietnam: declaring
victory and calling a truce. After CNN hired attorney Floyd Abrams
and his investigation revealed serious flaws in the nerve gas
story, the network humbled itself, handing the department a big
public relations victory in the battle for hearts and minds. That
vindication will be heightened when the Pentagon's own
investigation of the Tailwind charges, to be released soon,
concludes that the nerve gas story is unsupportable.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Major General Neal Creighton, president of the McCormick
Tribune Foundation, which promotes understanding between the
military and media, said this was another credibility-sapping
fiasco for journalists. ``The one who suffers from (Tailwind),'' he
said, ``is the press side of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash predicted that Pentagon spokesman ``Ken Bacon is going to
take the high road.'' CNN ``certainly called it like Abrams saw
it.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC Pentagon correspondent Jim Miklaszewski suggested that
Tailwind finally lets the defense department get payback from the
media decades after the press was credited with turning public
opinion against the war in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's almost a feeling of vindication in this building,'' he
said. ``A feeling that maybe we didn't get Vietnam entirely
correct, but neither did you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
