<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-METALLICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLISHING METALLICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Change is not always a metalhead's best friend. Despite the
ostensibly rebellious, boundary-breaking nature of the genre, many
fans like what they know and want to keep liking that throughout a
group's life span. The more vigilant among the metal hordes are
always sniffing the winds for the whiff of a band's sellout, a
taming of the beast.
</P>
<P>
   With a shrug of ``so what?'' America's top heavy-metal band,
Metallica, took those notions by the shoulders and gave them a good
shake four years ago with their so-called ``black'' album,
``Metallica.'' They continued to do so with ``Load'' and
``Re-Load.'' They're slated to release a new album late in the
year. Singer-guitarist James Hetfield, guitarist Kirk Hammett,
drummer Lars Ulrich, and bassist Jason Newsted committed heresy in
1996 when they cut their manes short and headlined the alternative
rock-oriented Lollapalooza tour.
</P>
<P>
   So Metallica, formed in San Francisco in the early 1980s, is not
the all-thrash, all-speed, all-anger, all-bark-and-bite band it
once was _ not that its members don't cherish their history and
kick much of it up when they get on stage -- usually to sold-out
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica has grown more melodic and it has explored musical
subtleties and other styles _ country, blues, power ballads. The
most moving song on ``Re-Load'' is the bittersweet tower-of-power
ballad ``The Unforgiven II,'' with Marianne Faithfull contributing
haunting backing vocals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another dynamic,'' says Hammett. ``It's just another
way to write a song, something different. A lot of the appeal, for
us, is to create songs like that because everyone says we can't:
`We are a metal band. We have to have 182-beats-per-second.' People
are so rigid in their thinking, that you know (itals)of
course(unitals) we're gonna think otherwise. And that in itself was
appealing to us. It also gives James an opportunity to actually
(itals)sing(unitals) and why not showcase that? ... We might have
changed our sound and, to certain people, we may have lost our
sound. But I think it's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that when Metallica formed, its intense, cathartic
speed-metal ran counter to the prevailing pop-metal of the day. It
was an underground sound, rough and uncompromising, hard as nails,
bitter as bark. ``Master of Puppets'' and ``Ride the Lightning''
were classic against-the-grain albums. A contrary nature courses
through the band's blood.
</P>
<P>
   The early Metallica was an intense, but, internally, a somewhat
rickety, machine, prone to excess. It was derailed in 1986 when
bassist-songwriter Cliff Burton died in a band bus accident in
Sweden. Just two months later, Hammett told the Globe, ``We all
felt there was no reason to stop. What Metallica has been all about
is struggling. The odds have always been against us, but it worked
out and we're back in action.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years down the road, Hammett says, ``I wish I knew what I
know now back then. Way back then, you were kind of figuring it out
as you went along. And now, we are, you know, the `wizened,
experienced' band. We know what to do and what not to do as far as
the show is concerned, because the show is the A-No.1 concern.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Metallica do differently now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, one thing is like, you need sleep,'' he says. ``You need
rest. That much is obvious. And another one is drinking too much.
If you drink too much it affects the show the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: Metallica's self-imposed nickname was Alcoholica.
</P>
<P>
   The guys in Metallica are rock stars, yes, but rather
self-effacing ones. Hammett volunteers that he recently fell on
stage while performing. ``So what?'' he says. ``Everyone falls
down. I just kind of kicked back, had a good laugh at my own
expense.''
</P>
<P>
   As if the band is composed of four human beings, not four rock
robots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' says Hammett. ``More human. We see ourselves as
normal people who interact in the same way everyone else interacts.
That's been no big secret. That really hasn't changed much. ... We
nudge each other a lot. It's fun for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Metallica's concerts are affairs that last more than two hours.
This tour is somewhat stripped down, not the ultimate big-bang
Metallica experience. ``Not anything grandiose,'' Hammett says,
adding that pyrotechnics are involved but not overdone. ``They're
just for augmented dynamics.''
</P>
<P>
   Musically, he says, ``What we try and do is pace it so we create
a scenario where at the top of the set we play the songs that draw
the listener in, just totally attack, and then we slow it down
toward the middle, so it isn't so drastic a change from the heavy
fast stuff to the more ballad-y stuff. Then, two-thirds of the way,
we pick up the energy level and just keep increasing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it ever become a paint-by-numbers situation?
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends,'' says Hammett, ``on the environment. If the
audience is great, the sound is great, the PA's happening, the
monitors are good, we're all well-rested, it's magic. We are as
one. When things are less than ideal, you just have to rise above
it. (Although) it's always more noticeable to the band. I've walked
away from shows thinking `God, that was horrible' and then our
managers come running back saying it's the best show we've played
in a long time. Then, you start thinking: `Why the disparity? What
made it so appealing to everyone else?' It's nothing you can put a
finger on, just a combination of things that make or break a
show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
