<HEADLINE>
IS IT FINALLY MONTGOMERIE'S YEAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ For Colin Montgomerie, who has finished
second three times in the US Open, the 127th British Open should be
his oyster. He has been Europe's dominant player the past five
years and is a native son, but his only top-10 finish has been a
joint eighth in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The record also shows he has failed to make the cut four of the
last six years when he has been in his prime. His approach to this
year's championship has been almost casual. Nine holes Tuesday
night. Nine holes Wednesday morning. Some corporate appearances.
The practice tee, where he will simply try to find a rhythm. If the
wind blows too hard, he'll pack it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried not to put too much pressure on myself,''
Montgomerie said. ``I'm coming in here playing OK. I just thought I
would play nine holes (Wednesday) morning. That's been my
preparation; I'll go practice (Wednesday) afternoon just very
briefly, and go back to my hotel room and rest. I feel whenever I
have relaxed in the past I've done well in any tournament. I'm
trying to treat this as near to any tournament as I possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie said he's at the peak of his game. ``I think I'm
better all around,'' he said. ``I think my course management is
better. I think it's important here to know when to hit a driver
and when to hit a 2-iron and when to go to the middle of the green
and when not to. That's what I tend to pride myself on. Generally,
at these tournaments, par down the last few holes is always quite
good. You have to know where to place your ball to make par.''
</P>
</TEXT>
