<HEADLINE>
DEFENDER LEONARD TAKES A LONG LOOK AT ROYAL BIRKDALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SOUTHPORT, England _ The walk to the 18th green in the final
round of the British Open with victory in hand is one of the finest
trips in all of golf. Justin Leonard had such a walk a year ago at
Royal Troon on the Ayrshire coast of Scotland by the Firth of
Clyde. He earned it by carving out a masterful 65 and stormed from
five shots back on an afternoon when none of the other contenders
could break 70.
</P>
<P>
   That's how you win major championships, and that's what Leonard
did at Royal Troon. It was his first victory in a major and, at 25,
it has taken the pressure off, leaving him completely at ease as he
participates in the 127th British Open Championship at Royal
Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Leonard is an intense competitor out of the mold of
Texas predecessors Ben Hogan, Byron Nelson, Ben Crenshaw, and Tom
Kite, he no longer has to live up to the monicker of ``the best
player never to have won a major.''
</P>
<P>
   That's on the table for Colin Montgomerie, Phil Mickelson, and
David Duval to cope with at the start of the game's oldest
championship. ``They have to live up to their own goals and
expectations,'' said Leonard Wednesday. ``I'm sure those goals and
expectations are probably higher than what people think of them.''
That's a monkey Leonard removed from his back well before he made
it to 30, which was where Kite and Davis Love resided when they won
that elusive first major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a bit more at ease,'' Leonard said. ``I'm sure part of
that is because I expect a lot but I feel more comfortable being
here. It's the same way I felt at the PGA last year and the Masters
and US Open this year. I've felt a little more relaxed because I
had accomplished something at this level and it feels like part of
the pressure from playing before this tournament last year is gone
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, whose final tuneup was in the Greater Hartford Open two
weeks ago in Cromwell, Conn., followed pretty much the same routine
he did a year ago when he arrived at Royal Troon, a course he'd
never seen. He played 80 holes in a practice regimen.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas native had never seen Royal Birkdale until he arrived
here last Saturday. He's played 77 holes on the course in the
company of dependable caddie Bob Riefke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two courses are different,'' said Leonard. ``The greens
here have a lot more undulation. They're a little bigger. And at
Troon you went out and then back except for the eighth hole. Here
you have holes going every which way. It's different, but this is a
wonderful course. You don't need a lot of drivers if you don't want
to. I hit a lot of irons off the tees. The wind died down a bit
today, but if it stays windy I think par is going to be a
reasonable score.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard essentially won at Royal Troon on the incoming nine of
the first round when he put together a 35 in high winds that
buffeted the course. That kept him in the hunt. On Sunday, he
started out the round five shots astern of Sweden's Jesper Parnevik
and beat him by three. He didn't hit a single green in regulation
on the back nine Thursday and finished with a marvelous par on the
18th. On that hole he found the rough off the tee, played out with
an 8-iron, hit a 4-iron into the wind, and made an 8-foot putt to
save par.
</P>
<P>
   The back nine on Sunday was an example of Leonard's true grit.
He saved par on the 10th, birdied the 16th from 15 feet, and made
the putt that iced it on the 17th from 30 feet. ``I definitely knew
that I wanted to win a major,'' said Leonard. ``I hadn't really
contended, but I had played well in some majors. I just feel more
comfortable now because I'm not saying, `Well maybe this could be
the week.''' It wasn't his week at The Olympic Club in the US Open,
but Leonard handled it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty confident going in,'' he said. ``I'd been
playing OK, had a good week before. When I got out there, I didn't
play all that great. I hit the ball fairly well, but it was not a
very good week putting. It was disappointing, but as I said those
weeks don't bother me as much as they did maybe last year or two
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard was runner-up to Love in the PGA Championship at Winged
Foot, came from five shots back to win The Players Championship at
Sawgrass two weeks before the Masters, and is at peace with himself
as he prepares for Royal Birkdale. ``I don't put too much into the
week before or even into the two or three days prior to it,'' he
said. ``I'm out there trying to learn the golf course, trying to
pick out the right shots to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He picked out the right shots at Royal Troon and hopes for a
repeat here on the coast of the Irish Sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
