<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-SUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE ON RIGHT TO SUE HMOS SWELLS IN CAPITOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ When Diane Andrews-Clark sued her insurance
company for denying medical care to her husband, it came as little
surprise that a judge dismissed the case. Under federal law, most
workers have only a narrow right to sue their health insurers.
</P>
<P>
   But what caused a buzz in legal circles was the emotional lament
by US District Judge William Young in Boston about the the law that
had forced him to throw the case out. While the insurer's alleged
conduct ``is extraordinarily troubling,'' Young wrote last October,
``even more disturbing to this court is the failure of Congress to
amend'' the law.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many lawmakers want to do just that. Their effort has
sparked one of the biggest debates in Congress this session and
become the major point of contention as lawmakers and President
Clinton negotiate for broad new rights for the 75 percent of
Americans who rely on health maintenance organizations and other
managed care companies for health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding the right to sue an HMO is a top goal for consumer
groups and doctors, who argue that the threat of legal action will
make HMOs more accountable for their decisions. Right-to-sue
provisions are the key difference between the leading Democratic
``patients rights'' bill, which would allow patients to sue, and
the two main Republican proposals, which would continue the
prohibitions on most HMO lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The issue took on even more prominence Wednesday as Senate
Republicans unveiled a new bill that requires HMOs to give patients
certain benefits but does not expand the right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the current limits on lawsuits also arose as
President Clinton met Wednesday at the American Medical Association
with a small group of doctors, nurses and families with complaints
about HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The current law, passed in 1974, allows patients to sue an
insurer only for the cost of a denied benefit. For example, a
person denied a cancer treatment can sue to force an HMO to provide
the service or to repay a patient who paid for the service out of
pocket. But the patient may not sue for suffering, lost wages or
any other damages, even if the lack of treatment allowed the cancer
to spread.
</P>
<P>
   These limitations apply only to people who obtain health
insurance from their employers, or about 125 million Americans, and
they mostly affect people in HMOs or other plans that require
preapproval for specialized care. Congress approved the limitations
at a time when fewer than 6 million people were in HMOs, compared
to a significant majority of Americans today.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the right to sue say it will make sure HMOs put
patients before profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the HMO industry is the only industry that doesn't
have to compensate people for the harm it causes, HMOs will
continue to have every financial incentive to deny essential
care,'' said Ronald Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a
health care consumers group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians have been held accountable for time immemorial,''
said James Stacey, a spokesman for the American Medical
Association. ``Now, some health plans are making medical decisions.
We feel the right to sue acts as a safety valve for patients, which
will result in better decision-making by medical plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies, however, say that new lawsuits would raise
the cost of health premiums, making policies unaffordable and
forcing employers to cut benefits they offer to workers.
</P>
<P>
   One study commissioned by the American Association of Health
Plans found that changing the liability laws alone would raise
premiums by between 2.7 percent and 8.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A separate study by Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, which examined health
plans serving employees who already have the right to sue,
concluded that the cost of litigation was between three and 13
cents a month per beneficiary, or no more than 0.11 percent of
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have said that a better appeals process would help
patients while avoiding expensing litigation costs.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm, Republican of Texas, said Americans would
rather appeal than sue over HMO decisions. The Democratic solution
``is to bring a government bureaucrat and a lawyer into the
examining room,'' he said. ``But that hardly solves the problem
that most Americans have, because when they're examined by their
doctor, they want to be alone with their doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, some patients have already felt the effects of
the limitiations on lawsuits contained in the 1974 law, called the
Employee Retirement Income Security Act, or ERISA.
</P>
<P>
   Young was not the first judge to complain about the law, but the
strong tone of his comments has caused a stir among lawyers who
follow employee benefit issues, said Robert Macaulay Jr. of the
Boston firm Ropes &AMP; Gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an extraordinary piece,'' Macaulay said. ``It's not
common to see an opinion that strong. I've never seen another case
quite like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's decision concerned the 1994 death of Richard J. Clarke
of Haverhill, Mass., a 41-year-old father of four with a drinking
problem. Through his wife's job at AT&AMP;T Corp., Clarke obtained
health insurance from The Travelers Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in 1994, Clarke was admitted or referred by a court
to an alcohol detoxification program. Each time his insurer refused
to authorize a 30-day stay, even though his policy entitled him to
one 30-day inpatient rehabilitation program each year, Young's
decision said.
</P>
<P>
   One time the insurer authorized a five-day stay, and another
time allowed no more than eight days, the decision said. The third
time, following a commitment hearing, a court ordered Clarke into a
30-day detoxfication program, but the insurer ``incredibly
refused'' to cover the stay, Young's decision said. As a result,
the state court sent Clarke to the Southeast Correctional Center at
Bridgewater, Mass. for the treatment. There, Clarke was forcibly
sodomized by another inmate and received little treatment, Young
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke's life ``spiralled inexorably down and out of control''
after his time in Bridgewater, Young wrote, and in November 1994 he
was found dead in a parked car, with a garden hose extending from
the tailpipe to the passenger compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Young dismissed the suit filed by Clarke's wife, but added that
this resolution was ``of course, ridiculous. The tragic events set
forth in Diane Andrews-Clarke's complaint cry out for relief.'' He
said it was wrong for the insurer to deny treatment that ``doctors
at several hospitals, and even the courts of the Commonwealth'' had
said was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The federal law, Young wrote, has ``evolved into a shield of
immunity that protects health insurers, utilization review
providers, and other managed care entities from potential liability
for the consequences of their wrongful denial of health benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   But the health insurance industry says that more lawsuits will
not improve the country's health care system. Health plans point to
studies showing that the current malpractice law leads to higher
medical costs and a breakdown of trust between doctors and
patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
