<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE FANS, DON'T WORRY, BE HAPPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Don't worry, New York Yankees fans. Be happy.
</P>
<P>
   Why that doesn't go without saying is one of the mysteries of
the universe, like Kim Basinger winning an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are churning out an epic tale that makes the book
that manager Joe Torre spun off the 1996 season, ``Chasing the
Dream,'' read as if it had been ghost-written by Kafka. Here is a
team in the throes of living a dream too vivid and sublime not to
be real.
</P>
<P>
   If the government operated as engagingly and efficiently as the
Yankees, there would be no Internal Revenue Service. People would
pay their taxes willingly, with a smile, without waiting for April
15 to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Barely halfway into the season, the Yankees are so far ahead of
their competition that the only thing left for print and electronic
journalists to do is to poke, to prod, to pontificate of perils
that await.
</P>
<P>
   There are just enough cautionary tales out there to convince
just about anybody that even if the sky doesn't fall today, the
bogeyman will come out from under the bed tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees entered Tuesday night's game against Cleveland on a
pace to go 122-40. Two teams this century have won more than 110
games in a season. The 1906 Chicago Cubs went 116-36 and lost the
World Series to the cross-town rival White Sox in six games. The
1954 Cleveland Indians went 111-43 and got swept by the New York
Giants in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Those were simple, uncomplicated days when the winners of the
American and National League pennant races proceeded directly to
the World Series. Now even the best-pedigreed teams must navigate
though two rounds of playoff minefields before they get to the
World Series. It's enough to drive sweaty-palmed fans to make
frantic speed-dial calls to talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen to the Yankees' legacy if they don't win the
last game they play in October? What if the Yankees run into the
Cleveland Indians again in the playoffs? What if the Indians manage
to swing a deal that adds Randy Johnson to a pitching staff that
already includes Bartolo Colon and Yankee-killer Jaret Wright? What
if an asteroid crashes into the Bronx, wiping out the Yankees
starting rotation?
</P>
<P>
   Step back a moment. Take a deep breath. There will be plenty of
time for the Yankees and their fans to worry about October.
</P>
<P>
   What we have for the rest of July, through August, September and
October, is the best of all baseball worlds. Yankees fans can
follow their team's relentless, one-day-at-a-time pursuit of
excellence. Yankees haters can cling to the hope that pinstripes
will turn into straitjackets when the postseason arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to experience a baseball season is to treat it as a
journey, not a destination. Seasons are too long and take teams on
too many detours for the final stop to be the end-all.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Red Sox fans who wallow in the supposed ``Curse of the
Bambino'' have lost their bearings. Even without having won a World
Series since 1918, the Red Sox have one of the richest traditions
in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams hitting .406 in 1941. The pennant races of 1949 and
1950. The seven-game World Series with the St. Louis Cardinals in
1946. The ``Impossible Dream'' season of 1967, culminating in
another seven-game Word Series. Another seven-game World Series in
1975. Another seven-game World Series in 1986. Wade Boggs in his
line-driving prime. Roger Clemens in his power-pitching prime.
Would Red Sox fans really give up all that to trade places with the
Florida Marlins?
</P>
<P>
   October will come when it is good and ready. What the Yankees
have now is special, no matter what happens later. All things
considered, the Yankees are the best team _ in every sense of the
word _ you're likely to have the privilege of seeing in your
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the chill that would have run through Yankees fans if
they had known before the season that center fielder Bernie
Williams already would have missed 28 games to injury.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if they'd have known that two other Yankees
cornerstones, shortstop Derek Jeter and closer Mariano Rivera,
would have done time on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if they'd have known Chuck Knoblauch would struggle to
hit .260 while conjuring scatter-armed images of Steve Sax at
second base. Imagine the horror of Andy Pettitte, David Cone and
David Wells having higher earned run averages than Hidecki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine first baseman Tino Martinez needing a month to come out
of a funk after a beaning by Armando Benitez. Imagine injuries
limiting designated hitter Chili Davis to four at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the lefty-righty setup tandem of Mike Stanton and Jeff
Nelson combining for a 4.94 ERA in its first 74 fr 2/3 innings of
work.
</P>
<P>
   With all that, and without a single player who is likely to
crack the top five in the most valuable player voting, the Yankees
have been more efficient than the Murderer's Row team of 1927 and
the Mickey Mantle/Roger Maris powerhouse of 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's too good to last through a divisional series,
through a league championship series, through a World Series, is
anybody's guess. A baseball team proves its merit over a marathon
schedule. The playoffs are a series of sprints.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about any of that now. Be happy for the chance to
see if the Yankees are too good not to be true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
