A8075 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI &LR;      07-16 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, July 17, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CRITICS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Six months ago at this
semiannual gathering of TV critics and TV programmers, ABC said it
would introduce a new, original series this summer, a tactic the
Fox network has had some success with. The keystone of ABC's effort
is ``Maximum Bob,'' a one-hour drama about a flamboyant Florida
judge, adapted from the Elmore Leonard novel. It premieres Aug. 4
in the ``NYPD Blue'' spot.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ZORRO (Undated) _ ``The Mask of Zorro'' is a vigorous crowd
pleaser that gradually betrays its own noble ambitions, but it's
also got enough gusto and agility to qualify as a satisfying
swashbuckler in the grand old style.
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Shannon. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BUFFALO (Undated) ``Buffalo 66'' is an odd film full of
surprises, some good, some not so believeable.It's sadly funny as
well as whimsical in spite of its backdrop of potentially abrasive
_ and highly abusive _ situations. It's a strange mix of gritty
realism and fantasy stirred together into an unusual love story
that thankfully only flirts, and then flees, from violence. It's
about missed opportunity, shattered dreams and trying to make a
mark in a world that barely knows you're alive.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LAWN (Undated) _ Australia's John Duigan continually shows
himself to be a director capable of great highs and great lows.
Unfortunately, his latest effort, ``Lawn Dogs,'' is very much at
the low end of his career chart _ indeed, is likely to be regarded
as its all-time nadir. The film is the movies' umpteenth attack on
the shallowness of suburbia, as seen through the eyes of a
10-year-old girl who has what may be the most cardboardishly venal
and hypocritical parents ever be portrayed in a major motion
picture.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
