<SLUG> BC-GLF-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR USES GOLF TO TEACH SONS LESSONS ON LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GOTTLIEB  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALTA, N.Y. _ In college, Andrew Shanley gave up golf along with
all the other establishment things people of his generation
shunned. Golf definitely wasn't cool for him. It was elitist,
frivolous and worst of all, his dad did it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he believes that the game delivers harmony to busy lives,
a broad canvas for the art of play and, most importantly, a place
to gently connect with his sons.
</P>
<P>
   At 46, Shanley lives in Malta with the two teenage sons he
writes about in ``Fathers, Sons &AMP; Golf: Lessons in Honor and
Integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had reconfigured the love between a dad and his little
boys, an intoxicating but fleeting affair, into the love between
fathers and sons, which can be so powerful and long-lasting,'' he
writes in the concluding pages.
</P>
<P>
   The first-time author writes about how he used the links to both
strengthen his relationship with Colin, then 13 and McLean, then
10, and marvels at how completely his own dad's simple wisdom has
sunk in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to become close to my sons. I was coming to
understand my father a lot more and share with him, when all those
years he and I didn't see eye to eye on a lot of things,'' said
Shanley, who also has a two-year-old daughter, Caitlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fathers, Sons and Golf,'' (Hyperion, 222 pages) which came out
at Christmas, follows the progress of Shanley three summers ago,
when he offered his sons tips on golf and life that unfolded
largely at the Saratoga Spa State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Once a week or more the three trudged along the course,
ostensibly so father could teach his sons chips and drives. But
Shanley not only had an agenda but also made up an outline of
life's lessons he wanted to discuss: ideas about hard work, fair
play and all the other things he had thrown out as bunk when he was
young.
</P>
<P>
   Shanley, who had failed thus far in two attempts to be
published, also wanted to see if there was a book in it. ``They
didn't know I was doing it but eventually, they started to joke
about dad's lectures,'' he said of his teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkling his prose with historic references to golf and wisdom
from its most renowned players, Shanley described how he tries to
bring McLean and Colin carefully through the course. He doesn't
want them to enjoy themselves so much that they fail to take the
game seriously, yet fears if it becomes too onerous they will quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as I worried about forfeiting my children's love, I was
especially reluctant to impose discipline on them,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the book his love is mixed with sadness about the things he
won't be able to spare his children, about the lessons they will
insist on learning on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Shanley himself shunned the game when in college during the
1960s, a time he contends that the younger generation was yelling
about community and love and really meaning they wanted to do
whatever they felt like.
</P>
<P>
   All these years later he has quit newspaper work to join the
world of advertising, an occupation he once believed was made up of
bad guys trying to sell people things they don't need. He is
propreitor of Rueckert Shanley, an advertising agency in Colonie,
just outside Albany. Shanley, who represents many medical concerns,
finds the work rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   And he plays the links, fastidiously, lovingly. His own father,
Joseph, was an ad executive who quit newspaper work to rear his
family. His lessons about simple goodness stream back year by year.
``My father and I get together to golf at least once or twice a
summer,'' said Shanley, ``and I think it means more each year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
