<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YOUNG IRANIAN COUPLES FEELING A LITTLE MORE FREEDOM IN COURTSHIP
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, July 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Cupid might not have to sneak around Iran
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   This country's restless youth say they have noticed a relaxation
of the strict rules prohibiting unmarried women and men from being
together in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I watch my limits, it is my right,'' said 15-year-old
Pooneh, who did not want to use her last name.
</P>
<P>
   In February, she and a male friend were detained by the
``Beseej,'' the non-uniformed auxiliary police who cruise the city
streets in vans looking for trangressors of Islam's modesty code.
</P>
<P>
   Pooneh was lucky to be released after signing a statement that,
``I undertake not to be out with a boy -- whether a relative,
friend or boyfriend -- alone, or else my parents will be
informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she reads in newspapers that walking in public will be
allowed as long as there is no hand-holding. Most believe the new
moderate president, Mohammed Khatami, has ushered in the change.
</P>
<P>
   Pooneh believes there has been a lighter touch since a girl
hanged herself while being detained. She was reportedly afraid her
parents were being told she was with a boy.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic Republic's strict, morality-based laws have made
public courtship a risky endeavor over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Married couples have had to be ready to prove they are married.
Youth were fined or detained in police stations. Parents were
called. Boys even complained of being beaten when detained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always walking under a threat of being stopped,'' said
Vahid, 22, who was sitting recently in one of Tehran's many lush,
crowded parks with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Her sister was detained for a night and fined after being caught
driving outside Tehran with a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can go outside Tehran with a girlfriend,'' Vahid said.
</P>
<P>
   Banned from leaving town together, groups of girls and boys
drive in separate cars to rendezvous at parks, swimming spots and
ski lodges outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Dark movie theaters provide cover for couples. They can slip
into each other's homes when parents are away.
</P>
<P>
   Fully more than half of Iran's 60 million people are under 20
years of age, and they expect more freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's promises of a ``civil society'' helped him win an
election landslide with heavy backing from these same young
Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives may still control the police and courts, but
Khatami appeared recently to be admonishing the Beseej-type
intimidation -- or at least trying to keep young Iranians on his
side.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the rhetoric in this country, it was all couched in
the name of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``For attracting the youth to Islam, they should be approached
with forgiveness and kindness,'' he said. ``Society cannot be
advanced with narrow-mindedness and creation of terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Iranians are keenly sensitive to the vagaries of Iranian
politics, where a cleric's speech can alter what couples face on
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easier now,'' said Alex Petrosian, 28. ``But, if (a
religious leader) says something about it at Friday prayers, it's
terrible for the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   More parks and malls are free of the Beseej. Usually recruited
from Iran's poor neighborhoods, they can be spotted by their loose,
untucked shirts -- a nod to modesty standards against showing a
waistline.
</P>
<P>
   Iran remains a genuinely conservative society. Many parents
expect their children to come to them first when they seek to pair
up with someone.
</P>
<P>
   Razad Sadegi, a 25-year-old telecommunications engineer, said he
does not accept casual words like ``boyfriend and girlfriend.'' He
met his wife only a few times before they decided to get engaged.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``It's not good to try to put pressure and limits
on young people . . . Even if we put obstacles in front of them,
they will find their own way.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
