<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8087 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANDS&AMP;-STYLES17-COX     07-16 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANDS&AMP;-STYLES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National swing sensations
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the groups making waves across the country with swing
music, helping it wash up everywhere from the Billboard charts to
MTV. Besides three- and four-word names, they all have hectic tour
schedules in common.
</P>
<P>
   SQUIRREL NUT ZIPPERS _ The surprise hit of last year and the
ones who landed swing music in MTV's Buzz Bin with their hit
``Hell,'' these seven North Carolinians play a quirky, Tin Pan
Alley sort of swing that echoes Cab Calloway more than Glenn
Miller. They return to Austin to play the Backyard on Aug. 13, a
week after their new album, ``Perennial Favorites,'' hits stores.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL CROWN REVUE _ This lively seven-piece is the hottest of
the L.A. swing scene. Based on a classic, bluesy jump sound and
Louis Armstrong-like gruffness, RCR has a new album coming out Aug.
24 to follow up their hit Warner Bros. debut, ``Mugzy's Move.''
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY POPPIN' DADDIES _ The band most responsible for bridging
the gap between swing and ska music, this large Oregonian swing
band relies heavily on horns, sped-up rhythms and pure machismo
(hence the name). Young fans love them, which is why their
independently-release ``Zoot Suit Riot'' album has passed the
500,000 sales mark.
</P>
<P>
   BIG BAD VOODOO DADDY _ ``As seen in the movie `Swingers.'''
That's all that was needed to earn this L.A. outfit a major-label
deal and large following. Its song ``You and Me and the Bottle
Makes Three Tonight'' is right up there with Squirrel Nut Zippers'
``Hell'' as a '90s swing classic, and it exemplifies BBVD's boozy,
loose, hepcat style.
</P>
<P>
   THE STYLE
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Jennifer Barker-Benfield is an ace at putting
together a good swing-set look. She assembled these ensembles from
the racks at Blue Velvet, the vintage-clothing she owns with her
mother, Susan Barker-Benfield. Remember, most of this is
one-of-a-kind vintage stuff. If you snooze, you lose. The store's
at 3203 Red River, 474-5147. For more ideas, Blue Velvet's page on
www.citysearch.com has a category devoted to ``Hip Cat 1940s-50s
Styles.'')
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE GUYS
</P>
<P>
   Fedora - $24
</P>
<P>
   1940s rayon two-pocket shirt - $18
</P>
<P>
   1940s gabardine pleated slacks - $28
</P>
<P>
   Two-tone Doc Marten's shoes - $75
</P>
<P>
   1940s wide tie - $10
</P>
<P>
   Tie bar - $3.50
</P>
<P>
   Button-on suspenders - $8
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DOLLS
</P>
<P>
   Black velvet veiled hat - $12.50
</P>
<P>
   1950s clip-on earrings - $5
</P>
<P>
   1940s cotton wrap blouse - $8.50
</P>
<P>
   1940s rayon printed skirt - $14
</P>
<P>
   1940s leather handbag - $9
</P>
<P>
   Polka-dot silk scarf - $3
</P>
<P>
   1940s mesh shoes - $10
</P>
<P>
   MORE IDEAS
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Barker-Benfield also offers these swing suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   Double-breasted suits, Hawaiian or other ``loud' print shirts,
1960s sharkskin suits, ``golf'' knit shirts, slacks from the '50s
and '60s, wingtip shoes, bowling shirts, sleeveless ribbed
undershirts and DaVinci re-issue retro shirts (in
</P>
<P>
   modern large and extra-large sizes). Or for women, 1940s cotton
or rayon dresses, cocktail dresses from the '50s and '60s, 1950s
full-skirt dresses, shorts from the '40s-'60s, capri pants, strappy
sandals, ladies' suits, men's gabardine pants and shirts, bowling
shirts andfishnet/seamed stockings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
