</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8091 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWING-GUY17-COX     07-16 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWING-GUY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dancing in the dark
 &HT;    By James Hibberd
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm strictly freestyle, you know? I go to a club, step up to the
floor and get my groove on. I'm a free spirit, a nonconformist to
prescribed steps.
</P>
<P>
   In other words I ... don't know how to dance.
</P>
<P>
   There, I said it. I can successfully move to music, but I can't
dance with any consistent form or watchable style.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only time I ever learned a bona fide dance step was
when I first saw Bruce Springsteen get down with Courteney Cox in
the video for ``Dancing in the Dark.'' Remember that one? The Boss
pulled thrilled young Courteney up from the front row and they
busted into that halting, jogging-in-place boogie.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1984, when ``Dancing in the Dark'' made rock music
dancing safe for people without rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, the indie hit ``Swingers'' made swing dance
lessons safe for young men like myself _ guys who normally wouldn't
be caught dead in a boxstep but are now changing their clothes,
their hair, their face to be as smooth as Frank and Dino. Or at
least as cool as Vince Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Before jumping on the trend bandwagon (which is now admittedly
halfway to Lubbock), I wanted to observe a swing dance class in
progress so I'd know what I was getting into.
</P>
<P>
   On a Monday night, I went over to the Caucus Club, where upwards
of 50 students are packed elbow to elbow on the dance floor.
Several of the guys are actually quite good and I wonder why
they're in the novice class, switching partners with girl after
girl, taking their hands and offering suggestions ... oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flirty, it's fun and it's been growing tremendously,''
says instructor Darby O'Shieles. ``I love doing it. I get to hang
out in a bar and dance as my job.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Shieles estimates about 70 percent of students arrive without
a partner. They switch off every few minutes in what seems like the
world's quickest dates: ``Hi, I'm Joe. First time here? Now we hold
hands and dance. Whoops, sorry about your toe. Next!''
</P>
<P>
   After watching the class, I decide to take my first-ever lesson
at the lounge uberclub Speakeasy. I figure a dim, windowless club
will provide more cover.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, I sign up for class and by 8 p.m. there are
about 90 post-Greek twentysomethings milling around Speakeasy,
preparing for their lesson by nervously slamming Shiner Bocks and
vodka tonics.
</P>
<P>
   Dianna Sanford, our capable instructor, smiles like a chorus
line dancer and begins class by separating boys from girls onto
opposite sides of the dance floor. It's tough not to think of your
junior high dances, and I guess that's appropriate since we're all
beginners again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we're going to teach you what to do with your feet,''
Sanford says, then shows us: slow, slow, quick-quick, slow ...
slow, slow, quick-quick, slow ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm lost already. I want to explain to Sanford that my feet are
wild and undisciplined and only a swing dancing dominatrix could
ever tame them. I apologize to Lisa, my partner. We've only been
``dancing'' for a couple of minutes, and I've stomped several toes.
Not just my her toes, other people's toes. When Sanford orders us
to switch partners, I grab onto Lisa's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey doll,'' I say, panicked yet savoring the opportunity to
use sexist swinger lingo in-context. ``Don't go away, you're the
only baby I ever want to dance with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, can it,'' she says. ``You just don't want everybody to
know how bad you are.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right, of course. But looking around, I notice other guys
sweating and awkwardly straining to pick up the moves. I look down
at my feet, wondering what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold on,'' interrupts Sanford, and the instructor points in my
general direction.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. She must have spotted me trying to pass off slam dancing
as swing dancing. She's going to chastise me for sloppy technique,
blame me for throwing off the whole group.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she's pointing at a nearby young man who's standing
alone and blushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the only person that doesn't have a partner?'' Sanford
asks.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety people turn to look at the poor sap without a girl to
dance with; the loser of this grown-up version of musical chairs.
He blushes harder. Sanford somehow finds a match for him, and we're
off again: slow, slow, quick-quick, slow ...
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later _ a long hour later _ something happens. The
bouncy swing music is playing (... slow, slow, quick-quick, slow
... ) and my mental chant quickens (... slow-slow-quickquick-slow
... ) and then, like a huge, clunky DC-10 hurling down a runway, I
lift off ... I'm swing dancing. I feel like Steve Martin in ``The
Jerk'' when he discovers beat and rhythm. I can't believe it. I'm
dancing in the dark at Speakeasy, a successful wannabe of other
hipster wannabes. Suddenly, none of the trendiness of swinger
culture matters.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, bandwagon ... wait up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
