<HEADER>
A8092 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWING-INTRO17-COX     07-16 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWING-INTRO17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It don't mean a thing...
 &HT;    By Michael Corcoran
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Alternative radio stations and MTV are playing swing
music in the form of ``Zoot Suit Riot'' by the Cherry Poppin'
Daddies and ``Hell'' by Squirrel Nut Zippers. The TV shows a Gap
commercial where khaki-clad couples do amazing dance stunts while
Louis Prima sings ``Jump Jive an' Wail.'' At the movies, there's
``Swingers,'' the 1996 film that romanticized the martini life and
had Big Bad Voodoo Daddy as the house band. Meanwhile, such Austin
clubs as the Caucus, the Ritz, Speakeasy, Sullivan's Ringside and
Top of the Marc have increased their bookings of swing bands and
are doing good early business by hosting jam-packed swing dance
lessons. Swing is in the air, and this is one retro movement that
has captured the full attention of the modern marketing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's mid-'30s to late-'40s heyday, swing has been revived
more times than ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' or at least as often
as Martin Landau's career. The appeal of swing is in the dancing,
the clothing and the pure elegance of those moonlight serenades
created by the likes of Benny Goodman, Glenn Miller and Duke
Ellington. Romantic and slinky, swing is the opposite of grunge,
and a well-oiled jitterbugging couple is about as far away from the
mosh pit as you can get. Swing is suave. It's real music by real
people who have been dead a real long time. But the music lives on
in every couple that first kissed on the dance floor. After a night
of dancing, sweat glistens like temptation's jewelry. That's why
swing keeps coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
