<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWING-PRIMER17-COX     07-16 1646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWING-PRIMER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GET IN THE SWING: The No-Risk List
 &HT;    By Michael Corcoran
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids raised on Bush (the band, not the president) may think all
those Cherry Zippin' Squirrel Daddy bands are musical trailblazers,
but the danceable, Big-Band style of music goes all the way back to
the early 1980s when such former punk rockers as Joe Jackson
(``Jumpin' Jive'') and David Johanson (a k a Buster Poindexter)
brought snappy suits, slicked-back hair and wild couples-dancing to
the national consciousness (as it were).
</P>
<P>
   Some may call this bit of musical history ridiculous, claiming
that swing actually started with the second Lyle Lovett album or
the unlikely MTV hit ``Stray Cat Strut'' in 1982. Also, let's not
forget hometown heroes Asleep at the Wheel or their cosmic cousin
Commander Cody, whose brand of swing must've seemed like a
hallucination to so many stoned-out '60s hippies.
</P>
<P>
   Enough kidding, here's the real history: In terms of musical
innovation, swing began in 1924 when Louis Armstrong, a brilliantly
soulful and expressive trumpet player from New Orleans, joined the
Fletcher Henderson band. Holding court at Roseland Ballroom,
Henderson and his orchestra specialized in music that was easy to
dance to, with a lot of stiff riffs the white crowd could hold on
to. What Armstrong brought to the sound was a confident soloing
style that flew all around the beat. He got the band to play looser
by stretching out the sound possibilities. Armstrong lasted only 14
months in Henderson's band before moving on to his own thing, but
along with Duke Ellington, who gave the musical style its name with
``It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing),'' he
pioneered a new style of danceable jazz.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1935, however, when a clarinet player from
Chicago named Benny Goodman broke onto the scene, that swing became
a national craze. Fronting a racially mixed band that included
Count Basie, Teddy Wilson, Lester Young, Gene Krupa and, later,
young Texas-born Charlie Christian (the progenitor of electric jazz
guitar), Goodman sacrificed none of his virtuosity yet still made
music simple enough to dance to by cherishing the melody. Swing is
what happened when the best jazz musicians in the world were hired
to play dance music for the masses. Like gold medal skaters doing a
figure 8, the idea was to find a way to flourish within the
routine. In a way, swing was a precursor to rock 'n' roll because
it showed that simplicity and repetition are the ways to physically
move the crowd. In their ability to do so, Goodman and Glenn
Miller, a couple of bespectacled Midwesterners, became major pop
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Sophistication ruled the bandstand, leading to an overall
quality of performance that makes choosing the best recorded music
from the era such a hard task. But if you're new to the scene and
want to do some catching up, you could do a lot worse than this
starter kit:
</P>
<P>
   THE ESSENTIALS
</P>
<P>
   ``Laughin' Louis,'' Louis Armstrong and His Orchestra
(RCA/Bluebird, 1992 reissue). Containing material from 1932-33 and
featuring such players as saxman Louis Jordan, drummer Chick Webb
and pianist Teddy Wilson, this collection gives a blueprint for the
swing craze that would follow in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Live At Carnegie Hall,'' Benny Goodman (Recorded in 1938,
first released by Columbia in 1950). This is the vortex of swing,
with Goodman's serpentine clarinet notes winding soulfully around a
band that included drummer Gene Krupa, vibe player Lionel Hampton,
the great Count Basie on piano and such other legends as Harry
James, Lester Young, Teddy Wilson and Ziggy Elman. If you can
afford only one album from this era, go for this double disc.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Essential Glenn Miller'' (RCA). Less a virtuoso than
Goodman and an unimaginative band leader compared to Duke
Ellington, Miller attracted bigger crowds than both of those
geniuses by tapping into the romance of swing and creating music
that kept audiences giddy and dancing for hours. ``String of
Pearls,'' ``Moonlight Serenade'' and ``In the Mood'' are the
magical standards of the time. The term ``a class act'' has been
rendered almost without value by overuse, but Miller and his
Orchestra fit the bill like none other.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``16 Most Requested Songs,'' Duke Ellington (Columbia). This
1994 release cuts right to the charts, ignoring the ambitious
suites that are such a part of Sir Duke's legacy. But all the
Harlem classics are here, from ``Don't Get Around Much Anymore''
and ``Caravan'' to ``Mood Indigo'' and ``Sophisticated Lady.'' This
is kind of a cheapo repackaging deal, but in terms of music
included, you can't get more for $12.99.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Best of Louis Jordan'' (MCA). Newer ``swing'' bands
such as Cherry Poppin' Daddies and Royal Crown Revue are
practically tribute groups to this hepcat from Arkansas, who paid
his dues playing with Louis Armstrong and Ella Fitzgerald, then
broke out on the mid-'40s with a host of jumpin' sides such as
``Five Guys Named Moe,'' ``Caldonia,'' ``What's the Use of Getting
Sober'' and ``Ain't Nobody Here But Us Chickens.'' Purists may say
Jordan and his predecessors Cab Calloway and Jimmy Lunceford were
closer in style to jump and boogie music than to swing, but nobody
really swang quite like this.
</P>
<P>
   MORE RECOMMENDED DISCS
</P>
<P>
   ``Vol. 3'' (1938), Django Reinhardt (JSP). Austin's 8 1/2
Souvenirs are unashamedly modeled after some of the swing music
this gypsy jazz guitarist made with The Quintet of the Hot Club of
France and violinist Stephane Grappelli, and this collection by a
tiny British label contains some of the best of those tracks,
including ``Swing From Paris'' and ``Swing '39.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ella and Her Fellas'' (1938), Ella Fitzgerald (Decca).
Containing four tracks with Louis Armstrong, plus such other guests
as the Mills Brothers, Chick Webb and Louis Jordan, this LP boasts
swaggering versions of ``A-Tisket A-Tasket,'' ``Paper Moon'' and
``Sentimental Journey.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Drop Me Off -- n Harlem'' (1942), Charlie Barnet and His
Orchestra (Decca). Featuring the marvelous Kay Starr on vocals and
some fine trumpet from Roy Eldridge and guitar playing by Barney
Kessel, this recording didn't break any new ground, but it's one of
the most danceable slices of hard swing around. If Goodman were the
Rolling Stones, Barnet would be AC/DC.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Yes, Indeed,'' Tommy Dorsey (Bluebird). This compilation of
sides from 1939-42 showcases not only Dorsey's rich trombone tone
but also the spectacular drumming of Buddy Rich and the writing and
arranging talents of Sy Oliver. Plus, Duke Ellington guests on the
last track, ``Minor Goes Muggin'.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Come Dance With Me,'' Frank Sinatra (Capitol). You gotta
have some Frank, and several titles would do the trick, including
``It Might As Well Be Swing,'' which he recorded with the Count
Basie Orchestra, or ``Sinatra's Swingin' Session,'' but this one is
chosen for its lack of ballads and full-on commitment to dance.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Capitol Collector's Series,'' Ella Mae Morse (Capitol 1994
reissue). Besides bringing Nat King Cole to Capitol, this sassy
Texan also had the first hit for the fledgling label with ``Cow Cow
Boogie.'' A relatively unsung hero of swing, perhaps because she
was a white woman who sounded black, Morse recorded many wonderful
tracks, including the original version of ``House of Blue Lights''
and an unsurpassed take of ``Come On Board, Little Chillun.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Jumpin' With Joe: The Complete Aladdin and Imperial
Recordings,'' Big Joe Turner (EMI). Hey, you novice jitterbuggers:
If you can keep up to these hot nuggets of Kansas City swing,
you'll earn your dancing shoes.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Best of the Big Bands,'' Hal Kemp (Columbia). Two reasons
you haven't heard of him: 1) He came from North Carolina, and 2) He
died in 1940. But this collection, great for practicing at home,
proves the reedman had one of the smoothest yet most danceable
bands around.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Free For All'' (1937), Artie Shaw. His distaste for the
music business was almost as legendary as his music, but this 1988
reissue shows him to be a sophisticated and adventurous soul, who
dissipated ``the suits'' with his elegant clarinet. Buddy Rich and
Roy Eldridge are the key sidemen here.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Capitol Collector's Series,'' Louis Prima (Capitol). A
dancer's fave who kept the music hot, hot, hot.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``1934-1937,'' Fletcher Henderson (Classics). The pupil
taught the teacher, when Louis Armstrong joined Henderson's band in
1924 and showed them how to swing it, but credit Henderson for
letting the music show him the way. Here, the pianist/arranger's
got another great band, including Ben Webster, Benny Carter and Chu
Berry, who do that swing thing while on the cusp of bebop.
</P>
<P>
   MORE SWING FOR YOUR BUCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Bands in Hi-Fi'' (Capitol). This double disc starts off
with ``Let's Dance'' from Goodman and ``Satin Doll'' by Ellington,
but doesn't let up as it gives the best of such greats as Count
Basie, Harry James, Artie Shaw, Stan Kenton and Kay Kyser. Glenn
Miller is one of the few greats missing, but he's represented by
covers of his greatest material by Glen Gray.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Kings of Swing: Best of the Big Bands'' (Laserlight), A
budget-priced collection that hits on all the key points _ Glenn
Miller, Count Basie, Benny Goodman, Woody Herman, Harry James, Duke
Ellington and Tommy Dorsey _ in just over an hour.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Swingin' Singles'' (Rhino). Exploring the cheesier side of
the retro sound, this compilation leads off with Della Reese doing
``The Lady Is a Tramp'' and ends 17 tracks later with Eartha Kitt;
in between are some hot numbers by the likes of Bobby Darin,
Rosemary Clooney, Sarah Vaughan, and duets with Louis Prima and
Keely Smith and Count Basie and Tony Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
