<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-16 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISTIC OBSESSION: GETTING IT RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thanks to a few highly publicized scandals of
late, the American public is getting comfy with the idea that most
journalists are either habitual fabricators or complete
professional slobs.
</P>
<P>
   Because a couple of writers have been caught making people and
information out of whole cloth (the Boston Globe's Patricia Smith,
the New Republic's Stephen Glass) or because a CNN producer ignored
major contradictory facts in a now-discredited story about U.S.
defectors and nerve gas during the Vietnam war, journalists in
general are supposed to be lazy and untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   It's sort of like using a handful of malpractice cases to
condemn the American medical profession.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I see plenty that is wrong with the news
media. Usually, I am among the first (and regular) persons to
holler about many of our practices and habits. But, after 27 years
in this business, I think I know when it's fair to holler and when
it ain't.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't nearly as titillating an image as that of a conniving
reporter, gleefully making up facts and inventing people, but I'll
bet my paycheck that some variation on the following is much more
common in journalism than the aforementioned scenario: It's a
little before midnight, and a veteran reporter is pulled by fear
from deep sleep into crypt-cold consciousness. As if it were a
sharp rock in her sheets, a paragraph, two-thirds of the way down
in a story she has written, suddenly dominates her senses.
</P>
<P>
   Just one paragraph. In a story of 50 paragraphs. The part where
she mentions the research findings of (say) a Vanderbilt professor.
</P>
<P>
   She got his name right, yes? It was Robert, not Raymond? Then
again ... oh, God. What if it wasn't the Vanderbilt guy at all who
did that research? Maybe it was the guy from Rutgers.
Raymond-something. She interviewed both of them so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Robert? Raymond?
</P>
<P>
   The reporter is wide awake.
</P>
<P>
   She's worked this story for weeks. She's interviewed dozens of
people, read scores of magazine and newspaper articles, a couple of
inch-thick studies and a half-dozen academic analyses _ all of
which she highlighted with yellow marking pen.
</P>
<P>
   She filled three shorthand notebooks and produced four drafts of
the story as it made its way through several editors and two
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the reporter went over and over her
material _ despite the fact that she has been doing this same kind
of work for a generation _ she knows only one thing will allow her
to calm down and go back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   If she's lucky, she has all of her notebooks and highlighted
reading at home. If she's unlucky (or forgot about this
phenomenon), she gets dressed and drives to her office. When she
finds the right notebook, she scans the pages.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. Vanderbilt. Robert. She had it right all the time.
</P>
<P>
   While I do not personally know a single journalist who makes up
people and quotes, I know plenty who have experienced a little
drama like the one I just described. And they've experienced it
more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Despite our individual faults and weaknesses _ and those of our
very diverse industry _ the preponderance of news women and men
that I have known over three decades retain a remarkable commitment
to ``getting it right.'' Information that satisfies most people
prompts the majority of journalists to ask more questions and head
for the library.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the limits of a daily deadline, every fact cannot be
double-checked nor every quote verified. And, yes, the pressure of
today's competition has worsened those limits, allowing little room
for quality control.
</P>
<P>
   Most days though, most of us still get most of it right.
</P>
<P>
   When we don't, no matter how long we have been in the business,
nobody hates the mistake more than we do.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
