<HEADER>
A8111 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS &LR;      07-16 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `CIVILIZED SOCIETY' REQUIRES THE GUILLOTINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARLOS TAHMAZIAN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFICA, Calif. _ After a scrumptious meal of crab legs with
melted butter, Mandarin-style pork spare ribs, spinach salad, pork
fried rice, a chocolate sundae and a Diet Coke, Thomas M. Thompson
was executed by injection early Tuesday at San Quentin Prison.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, when the U.S. Supreme Court restored the death
penalty, there have been more than 200 executions nationwide.
That's approximately 10 per year, a handful in proportion to the
number of murders.
</P>
<P>
   Every execution brings up the question whether civilized people
should officially put other people to death. In my opinion, the
death penalty doesn't belong in a civilized society. The question,
therefore, is whether our society is civilized.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, you can find child murderers, serial
killers, mass murderers, drive-by shooters, professional assassins,
snipers, gang wars and drug-related deaths. In a nation that
embodies a ``free-for-all society,'' rather than a free society for
all, we can enumerate animal sacrifices in the name of freedom of
religion, cannibalism, incest, torching of people, putting female
immigrants into sexual slavery, child molesters, thousands of
street gangs, youngsters killing other youngsters for basketball
shoes, cruelty to animals for sport, kidnaping girls for sex,
schoolyard shootings, a multinational contingent of organized crime
and too many politicians who indulge in every possible form of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   As proud Americans we can also brag that any European who wants
to commit suicide can buy a ticket to Florida, stop a rental car in
the middle of Miami and ask for directions.
</P>
<P>
   Taking everything into consideration, especially the sad fact
that America provides the opportunity for individuals to amass
billions of dollars, but makes no provisions for the mentally ill
who are left on their own, the answer of course is, no.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, executions are in good standing.
</P>
<P>
   It is understood that the death penalty serves two purposes.
</P>
<P>
   One, it's retribution for taking a life or lives under ``special
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Two, it should make people who have crime in their minds think
twice and forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   After the hanging of child killer Westley Allan Dodd, the
autopsy revealed that his neck was not broken and that he probably
died from a combination of neck damage and strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   Electrocution sends high voltage of electricity through the body
as many times as needed, and sometimes becomes a fireworks show.
</P>
<P>
   In the gas chamber, the guest is advised to breathe as fast as
possible and in the meantime jerks around in agony.
</P>
<P>
   In lethal injection, sometimes the person to be executed helps
in the search for a good vein.
</P>
<P>
   And in Utah, the condemned person is offered the option of
theatrical death by firing squad.
</P>
<P>
   What has to be done in the national interest is to come up with
a fast, painless, foolproof method to put people to death.
Something that would well represent America's idiosyncrasy, showing
the ``deathstyles of the rotten and infamous'' with the same
panache as the ``lifestyles of the rich and famous.''
</P>
<P>
   So why not go to Paris and bring back the guillotine?
</P>
<P>
   There is no faster, cleaner, less painful and more efficient way
to execute somebody. No flames and smoke coming out of the electric
helmet. No desperate gasping for air. No ``let's find the vein''
games. No more guessing how long the rope has to be. Zap, plop and
it's over.
</P>
<P>
   And how about the grandiose, truly American spectacle of the
guillotine itself: Looming high on a raised platform, with a tall,
bare-chested, black-hooded executioner with arms folded.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty would be carried out at 10 p.m. and televised
to coincide with the news hour. Expert camera work would show the
heavy, angled blade race down toward the condemned person's neck.
Millions of people would see the severed head fall into the wicker
basket and watch the executioner and raise it high, showing that
justice was done.
</P>
<P>
   These would be mind-sobering, soul-chilling images for everyone
to see, not much different than your everyday run-of-the-mill cable
TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Examiner contributor Carlos Tahmazian, who works with the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency, is a free-lance writer in Pacifica.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
