   SOLAR _ WASHINGTON _ With the sale of solar cells leaping by
more than 40 percent last year, the world's second fastest growing
energy source may become the wave of the future, according to a new
report from the Worldwatch Institute. The cost of solar energy _
which has dipped by 80 percent since 1980_ is now affordable for
the 2 billion people worldwide not connected to power lines. And
other sources of renewable energy, including wind and biomass, can
be accessed for pennies a day, according to a new Winrock
International report. As technology matures and prices fall,
renewable energy may find its way into U.S. homes, where a few
communites are beginning to try solar energy. (Abulhassan, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDBOARD _The Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board meets
today to consider Texas A&AMP;M's request for a law school (which is
expected to be defeated), proposals to boost financial aid awards
to college students (Texas has a reputation for being stingy with
need-based scholarships), recommendations to change how the board
operates and other matters. Expecting a story to emerge on at least
one of these topics. (Roser, Austin American Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS _ Syphilis, the sexually-transmitted disease that has
crippled and killed people for more than 500 years, may be headed
for eradication by vaccine, thanks to breakthrough Texas research.
Scientists at the University of Texas Houston Health Science Center
have for the first time mapped the complete genetics of the
bacterium that causes the disease. The work, in today's (Friday17)
issue of the journal Science, will lead to better diagnostic tests,
new therapies and, within five years, a vaccine. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
