<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
ZORRO-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ ``The Mask of Zorro'' heartthrob
Antonio Banderas talks about the south-of-the-border swashbuckling
film's difficult shoot, the ups and downs of his movie career and
his directorial debut with ``Crazy in Alabama,'' a satiric comedy
about the 1960s civil rights movement that stars his real-life wife
Melanie Griffith. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
ZORRO-LEGEND (Los Angeles) _ Zorro sprung from the pages of pulp
fiction to silver-screen fame in the 1920s, and this masked avenger
has been universally admired ever since. Every generation has had
its own Zorro, dating back to Douglas Fairbanks Sr. who donned the
masked and cape in the silent film that launched his own legendary
career. By Yvette Cabrera. 
. 
ZORRO-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``The Mask of Zorro'' boasts all the
classic movie virtues. Its story is, by turns, funny, exciting and
heart-touching. Every shot is lovingly composed. The players
operate at a pleasing pitch, with just enough good acting and movie
stardom to be irresistibly infectious. 3{ Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
BUGS-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Bugs, Daffy, Taz and company will split
sides _ and each other's cartoon noggins _ in the ``Bugs Bunny Film
Festival'' coming Thursday through Sunday to Glendale's Alex
Theatre. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
POLISH-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Polish Wedding'' is one of those
eccentric, episodic movies that tries so hard to win your love that
it ends up grating on your nerves. By the time first-time director
Theresa Connelly finally does pique your interest, you're too far
gone to really care. 2 Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
WHATEVER (Los Angeles) _ If you hated high school and couldn't wait
for your teen years to end, if you thought your parents (if you had
parents at all) didn't understand or if you just wanted Mom and Dad
to leave you alone, you might appreciate ``Whatever,'' a sad,
touching look at a young girl facing the daunting task of becoming
an adult. 3 Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ If you caught Lucinda Williams on
late-night TV recently, that was country singer-songwriter Jim
Lauderdale on acoustic guitar and harmony vocals. ``I just love
singing harmonies with her,'' said Lauderdale, whose own album
titled ``Whisper'' was released earlier this year. ``We have a real
natural blend. And I'm a huge fan of her writing.'' By Fred
Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC _ In an effort to put the kibosh on the flood of
unauthorized concert recordings, Counting Crows issued ``Across a
Wire: Live in New York,'' a specially priced double-disc ``bootleg
buster,'' consisting of an unplugged VH1 side and an electric MTV
side. By Fred Shuster and Glenn Whipp. 
. 

