<SLUG> BC-ZORRO-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SMILE BEHIND `THE MASK'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The desert temperatures were brutal. The altitude
was nosebleed territory. The swords were real ... and sharp.
</P>
<P>
   There was really only one way for Antonio Banderas to get
through filming ``The Mask of Zorro.'' The way he's gotten through
most of his life: laugh a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider a sense of humor, being ironic, synonymous with
being intelligent,'' says the 37-year-old Spanish actor, who's made
an international career out of slyly joshing the good looks and
radiant charm that could have typecast him as a latter-day Latin
lover. ``That's my position in life, in general terms. I like the
irony of life _ or, at least, I use that approach when confronted
with things I don't like or understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why I work best with directors who include that wink
in their work, who know that it is always OK to laugh. And of
course, I feel that if you are going to laugh about other stuff,
the first thing you have to be able to laugh about is yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of joshing amidst the swashbuckling in ``Mask of
Zorro,'' which was directed by Martin Campbell (``GoldenEye'') and
executive produced by Steven Spielberg, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Banderas plays Alejandro Murrieta, a less-than-successful bandit
in old Mexican California. He is recruited by the original Zorro
(Anthony Hopkins) to take up the famous black mask and cape against
evil Spanish aristocrat Don Rafael Montero (Stuart Wilson).
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film's comedy springs from Hopkins' noble Don Diego
De La Vega's efforts to teach hotheaded Murrieta both the finer
points of fencing and how to behave like a true Spanish gentleman.
With an out-of-control guy like Murrieta, an extended
trial-and-error period ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ``Mask of Zorro'' is a comedy on the order of George
Hamilton's ``Zorro the Gay Blade.'' But like the Hollywood feature
films it most resembles, the silent 1920 and sound 1940 ``The Mark
of Zorro,'' ``Mask'' is an adventure romp that knows precisely when
to kid itself and when to get down to action-packed business.
</P>
<P>
   Which with this movie, more often than not, meant working to
within inches of one's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very physically tough project,'' Banderas explains.
``Six-and-a-half months in Mexico _ and I love Mexico _ but it was
so hot. We were working in the Sonora Desert in 118 degrees, and I
was wearing suede pants, two shirts and a felt jacket! And they
were catching three or four rattlesnakes a day around the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when we moved to Mexico City, we were working at 2,600
meters altitude, so we were out of breath all the time and had to
get oxygen out of bottles. You can control all of that after all
those months if you're doing a movie in which you don't have to
take any kind of risks. But after working 14 hours a day, when you
have start a swordfight with somebody else _ and have to be funny
about it! _ well, we are actually very lucky that everybody came
away with all of their eyes and ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Or other precious parts. One of ``Zorro's'' signature scenes is
a fencing match between the masked avenger and Elena (Catherine
Zeta-Jones), the daughter of De La Vega who's been raised since
infancy by Montero. Stealing kisses between thrusts and parries,
the new Zorro ends the encounter with a flourish, leaving the
lovely Elena unscratched but, via a few deft strokes, practically
undressed.
</P>
<P>
   Zeta-Jones not only survived the performance, she appreciated
her partner's, um, skillful execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio is so charming,'' the Welsh actress says. ``The guy
deserves everything that's come his way, I think. Not only is he
really professional, he's a very nice man, very generous, and there
was never one moment when I felt the least bit intimidated by
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Banderas' charm and good humor is obviously a big part of what
makes him movie star material. But it's also gotten him over
several rough spots in his personal and professional life.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the city of Malaga on Spain's southern Andalusian
coast, Banderas initially dreamed of becoming a professional soccer
player, but that hope was crushed by a severe foot injury. Banderas
then turned his attention to acting, which soon placed him in the
right place at the right time with the right sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   On the verge of becoming the directing superstar of
freedom-flushed, post-Franco Spain, Pedro Almodovar caught on early
to Banderas' charismatic combination of smoldering sensuality and
self-deprecating silliness. The actor became an integral part of
Almodovar's internationally acclaimed, taboo-busting features ``Law
of Desire,'' ``Matador'' and ``Tie me Up! Tie Me Down!,'' among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Americans in the art film know took notice, too (Madonna, who
later would co-star with him in ``Evita,'' famously lusted after
Banderas in her documentary ``Truth or Dare''). Though unable to
speak English, he made his Hollywood debut in ``The Mambo Kings''
in 1992, and soon was landing significant parts in such major
productions as ``Philadelphia'' and ``Interview With the Vampire.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. But then things got rough. Banderas' 1995 debut
as a Hollywood lead, in Robert Rodriguez's ultra-violent
``Desperado,'' was a tour de force, but not a hit. The films that
immediately followed _ ``Assassins,'' `Four Rooms,'' ``Miami
Rhapsody,'' ``Never Talk to Strangers'' _ had much less to
recommend them.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this career skid, Banderas fell in love with
his ``Two Much'' co-star Melanie Griffith. Since both were married
at the time, he to Spanish actress Ana Leza and she to actor Don
Johnson, the tabloids had a field day. Dire as things might have
appeared from the outside, though, Banderas and Griffith saw each
other through with love and laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have relationships with people who have no sense of
humor,'' he asserts _ and indeed the couple, who married soon after
divorcing their previous spouses, would tack the more ridiculous
tabloid reports on the wall and make fun of them. ``Before I loved
her, even before I met her, I really admired Melanie as an actress,
when I was watching `Working Girl' or `Something Wild,' movies like
that. Being with Melanie has been a gorgeous experience.''
</P>
<P>
   And a fruitful one. Banderas and Griffith have a daughter,
Stella, almost 2, who is clearly her father's proudest achievement.
And Griffith recently headlined Banderas' directing debut, ``Crazy
in Alabama,'' a satiric comedy built around, of all subjects, the
'60s civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people may say, `This is an American story, what do you
have to do with that?' '' Banderas notes. ``But look, from the
middle of this century, young people all around the world have been
raised, to some degree, by the cultural life that comes from
America. Whether it was Hollywood movies or the man on the moon or
the assassination of JFK, it was part of our culture, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its humor, Banderas feels ``Crazy in Alabama'' addresses
the thing he likes most about his adopted country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, with all the civil rights problems in this country
and prejudice against blacks, Asians, Hispanics and whatever, you
guys generally live in peace between so many communities,'' he
says. ``Sure, there's poverty and lots of other problems, but
mainly, you survive with each other. That's a symbol to the whole
world, and it's so attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to ``Mask of Zorro.'' Banderas is
understandably proud to be the first Spaniard to play the
79-year-old pop hero. But even though the new movie employs many
Latinos in small parts, all of its major roles are played by
Europeans _ which has been a less-than-noble Hollywood. (On another
front, Mexican-American Rodriguez, who originated the project with
Banderas, was replaced by British director Campbell, reportedly at
Rodriguez's request over budget concerns).
</P>
<P>
   Banderas sees nothing wrong with ``Mask's'' casting, as long as
the film performs well enough to lead to wider opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be an economic reason'' for the Anglo-centric
casting, Banderas reckons. ``But `Zorro' is a great opportunity for
the studios to discover the Latino audience. It almost happened
with `La Bamba' (the 1987 hit about rock singer Ritchie Valens);
that was a sudden explosion, and a bunch of different Latino movies
came out after that. But they were very bad, and they destroyed the
goose that laid the golden egg.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Zorro' is a second opportunity to attract people back to
that. And, after all, `Zorro' is as American as Elvis Presley,
while at the same time it is Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Banderas, at least, has a bright professional future. He plays
an Arab warrior fighting alongside his Viking captors in the
upcoming Michael Crichton adventure ``The 13th Warrior.'' And if
all goes according to plan, he'll be singing his way through
another Andrew Lloyd Webber musical film next year, this time as
the lead in ``The Phantom of the Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   But, even though he smiles while saying it, Banderas obviously
has learned that survival in Hollywood is no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked what it means for a Spanish guy to continue
working here,'' he notes. `` `Continue,' that's the most important
word. You can probably come here and make it for a while, but
keeping it going is the most difficult thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm trying to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
