<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR LAUDERDALE...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; If you caught Lucinda Williams on late-night TV
recently, that was country singer-songwriter Jim Lauderdale on
acoustic guitar and harmony vocals.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina-born Lauderdale has known Williams for 10
years and appeared on her last two albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love singing harmonies with her,'' Lauderdale said.
``We have a real natural blend. And I'm a huge fan of her
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauderdale's current album, ``Whisper'' (BNA), was released
earlier this year. The disc features a cameo from bluegrass legend
Ralph Stanley of the Clinch Mountain Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Lauderdale's songs have been covered by George Strait, Patty
Loveless, Vince Gill and Mark Chesnutt, among others. He appears
Tuesday at the Mint (6010 W. Pico Blvd., Los Angeles; (323)
954-9630).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, but I have a dual career,'' he said. ``I'm a
songwriter for mainstream acts that have hits, and I'm a recording
artist on my own. But I haven't been picked up by country radio. It
just doesn't seem to be in the cards.''
</P>
<P>
   AND FURTHER-MORE...: Rusted Root drummer Jim Donovan reports
that all is well at the Further Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been fantastic,'' he said. ``All the audiences have been
extremely warm, mellow and really into the music. Everyone's
dancing. Hot Tuna and the others are playing fantastic music.''
</P>
<P>
   The Further Festival comes to Irvine Meadows Amphitheatre on
Wednesday. Along with Pittsburgh, Pa.-based Rusted Root and former
Jefferson Airplane side project Hot Tuna, the bill features
Grateful Dead remnants the Other Ones.
</P>
<P>
   Rusted Root, whose last album was ``Remember'' (Mercury), is
finishing up a new record produced by Susan Rogers (David Byrne,
Prince). The band has a loyal regional following even though
commercial pop radio has been resistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even from the beginning, we set ourselves up so we could have
a career regardless of radio,'' said Donovan, who recently released
a meditative solo effort, ``Indigo'' (Triloka).
</P>
<P>
   MORE MARLEY: Due next month is the second volume of ``The
Complete Bob Marley &AMP; the Wailers'' multi-disc series. The new
three-CD package features all the Wailers singles produced by Lee
``Scratch'' Perry in 1970-71.
</P>
</TEXT>
