<SLUG> BC-BUGS-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S A LONG WAY FROM ALL, FOLKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bugs, Daffy, Taz and company will split sides _
and each other's cartoon noggins _ in the ``Bugs Bunny Film
Festival'' coming Thursday through Sunday to Glendale's Alex
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The two shows, ``Fest of the Best'' and ``Taz Gone Looney,''
will alternate and screen at 11 a.m., 2:15, 3:30, 7 and 9:30 p.m.
There is no late show on Thursday. Tickets cost $10 adults, $5
children and $8 for Alex Film Society members.
</P>
<P>
   The festival makes its L.A. premiere Thursday night with a VIP
kickoff and tribute to Chuck Jones, the creator and director of the
most hilarious Warner Bros. cartoon characters. The studio will
bestow the Golden Carrot Award on Jones, who's credited with
creating Roadrunner and Coyote, Pepe le Pew, Bugs Bunny, Porky Pig
and Daffy Duck.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is a salute to Marvin the Martian's 50th anniversary.
Tickets for the Thursday and Friday night events are $75 for VIP
reception and reserved seating, $30 adults and $15 child for
orchestra seating, and $20 and $10 for balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Matinees will feature Looney Tunes characters and WB merchandise
giveaways. The theater is at 216 N. Brand Blvd. For tickets or
information, call (818) 754-8250.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: ``The Cinematheque's Greatest Hits: 1993-1998''
is a second chance to see the most offbeat and popular films shown
during the past five years, as American Cinematheque's sojourn at
Hollywood's Raleigh Studios draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   The final, five-week exhibition begins at 7:15 tonight with
Peter Sellers in ``The Party'' and at 9:15 with ``Golden Balls''
from Spanish filmmaker Bigas Luna. Saturday brings Bud Boetticher
in person for a showing of his powerful western ``Ride Lonesome,''
followed at 9:15 by a double feature ``Cleo From 5 to 7'' by Agnes
Varda and Oliver Assayas' ``Cold Water.''
</P>
<P>
   General admission is $7, $4 for members. Raleigh Studios is at
5300 Melrose Ave. For series information, call (213) 466-3456, Ext.
2 or visit the Web site at www.americancinematheque.com
</P>
<P>
   American Cinematheque is restoring Hollywood's shuttered
Egyptian Theatre and plans a Dec. 4 grand reopening with a
screening of Cecil B. De Mille's ``The Ten Commandments.''
</P>
<P>
   HIGH NOON: Paseo Camarillo Cinemas revives a grand tradition of
westerns starting at noon today with John Wayne in ``The
Searchers,'' the first in a 10-week salute to 75 years of Warner
Bros. westerns. A different film will be shown each week.
</P>
<P>
   Other westerns in the series include ``Rio Bravo,'' ``The
Left-Handed Gun,'' ``Blazing Saddles,'' ``Unforgiven'' and ``The
Wild Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Shows are Friday through Sunday at noon. Admission is $5. Paseo
Cinemas is at 390 Lantana St., Camarillo. Call (805) 383-2267 for
information.
</P>
<P>
   END OF THE WORLD: Slimy mutants, giant rats, cannibals,
vampires, survivalists and television junkies populate the
apocalyptic nightmare ``Laughing Dead,'' screening tonight and
Saturday at Laemmle Sunset 5.
</P>
<P>
   Two vampires embark on a journey of ``lust, power, addiction,
consumption and ultimately redemption'' in a dismal future world in
this 85-minute independent feature, showing at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Sunset 5 is at 8000 Sunset Blvd., West Hollywood. Call (213)
848-3500 for program and parking information.
</P>
<P>
   UNCENSORED ANIMATION: You know an animation event is really out
there when this crosses your desk:
</P>
<P>
   ``If your idea of animation is a bland feature designed to sell
hamburgers as well as tickets, then go to the freezer and make sure
Uncle Walt hasn't prematurely defrosted.''
</P>
<P>
   That's cold, but definitely apropos for ``General Chaos:
Uncensored Animation,'' showing midnight July 24 and 25 at the
University Village 3, near the USC campus. It promises animation
with a sense of ``visual electricity, moral ambiguity and a wicked
sense of the mature'' that ranges from claymation to puppetry,
cutouts to computer-generated stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty shorts in all will be screened, including works by Bill
Plymptom, the Bolex Brothers, Kathryn Travers, Stefan Eling and
Frances Lea. The Village is at 3323 S. Hoover St., Los Angeles. For
show times, call (213) 748-6321.
</P>
<P>
   WHOOPING IT UP: The upcoming slacker comedy ``BASEketball'' is
shooting to be a major player this summer, and what better way to
build buzz about America's newest sport than over beers with the
fellas.
</P>
<P>
   So, Universal Pictures is throwing the first BASEketball Pub
Crawl in Old Town Pasadena on Wednesday, where players won't get
whistled for traveling. The action starts at 7 p.m. at Moose
McGillycuddy's, moves to Barney's Pub, then Jake's Billiards, and
onto 35er for the final buzzer. Expect drink specials and contests
at every stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Bud and Miller Girls will pose for photos, movie promotional
stuff will be given away, and a King of the Slackers will be
crowned. His or her royal slackness wins VIP passes to the L.A.
premiere of the film, directed by David Zucker (``Naked Gun'') and
starring ``South Park'' co-creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``BASEketball'' tells the story of three guys who morph baseball
and basketball into a driveway sport that snowballs into an
American sports craze. The film opens July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
