<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTN: Managing editors, weekend editors, automotive editors,
business editors
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following automotive and features.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-NYT (Undated) _ A lot of convertibles shake, rattle
and roll. They leak and squeak, and, without the integral bracing
of solid tops, they flex like sponges when you wring them out on
bouncy roads. Outside the Sun Belt, they require 6 to 10 months of
compromise for 2 to 6 months of wind-blown freedom. This accepted
wisdom is fast becoming out of date. By James G. Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-BMW-NYT (Undated) _ A feisty terrier in a dog-eat-dog
business, BMW knows something about survival of the fittest. Its
ever-mutating 3-Series, which accounts for 44 percent of overall
sales, has become a genus with 31 species sold around the world. By
James G. Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-HNS (Undated) - The two stretch-cab Toyota Tacoma
pickup trucks looked pretty much identical: jacked up, huge tires
on modular wheels and the initials TRD written large on the sides
of their pickup boxes. TRD stands for Toyota Racing Development.
Upon closer inspection, the difference between the two trucks is
glaring. One has a rugged four-wheel-drive system for serious
off-road work, complete with low-range gearing, that gives it the
capabilities of a mountain goat. The other truck doesn't. Called
the PreRunner, it's just a two-wheel-drive, despite its rugged
off-road styling and attitude. But before you write it off as a
mere poser, the two-wheel-drive model does have distinct
attributes. By Bob Golfen.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING-COX (Atlanta) _ It was like a brief trip into
automotive heaven. As a driving enthusiast, the mere mention of the
German autobahns has been like a vision of sugarplums dancing in my
head. It truly was Christmas in July during a trip to Germany. For
me, it was the ultimate treat. Traveling at speeds in excess of 110
mph, our little 170-horsepower Saab sprinted happily along, once
even legally passing a police car. What a rush! The system seems so
sensible, and it's difficult to argue its logic. Not once in more
than 600 miles of driving did I see a single accident or a tinge of
animosity between drivers. If only we could make it work on our far
superior interstate highway system. By Linda Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   MECHANIC-COX (Atlanta) _ Gasoline is a hot topic these days.
Three readers have fuel-related questions, two about fuel quality
and one about gas stations. Let's tackle the confusion about fuel
first. David Harris writes: ``I take excellent care of our three
cars (change the oil every 2,500 miles, etc.), but I buy the
cheapest gasoline I can find. How do I determine which fuel is a
good-quality fuel?'' By Nora Carter.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-COX (Atlanta) _ Chevrolet likes to bill its Malibu
sedan, a midsize model larger than the Cavalier and smaller than
the Lumina, as ``the car you knew America could build.'' The
question that phrase begs, naturally, is, ``Well, why did it take
so long?'' By Russ DeVault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
