<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories in sight at this hour from The New York
Times News Service for Friday, July 17.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other entertainment stories from
our partners: Bloomberg News The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic,
Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News,
San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUMMER-ART-RDP (Undated) _ Summer, as always, offers a mix of
shows in the region around New York City, which for someone with a
car, a map, an appreciation for bad roadside food and an esthetic
purview big enough to encompass Caravaggio and Johnny Weissmuller
is a fair alternative to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, this overview is accompanied by four separate reivews:
SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY, SUMMER-HUDSON, SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND,
SUMMER-CONNECTICUT.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS-CITY (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Once this was the edge of
American civilization, a portal to the unknown. The Santa Fe,
Oregon and California Trails all started in Independence and
Westport, two small frontier towns long since melded into greater
Kansas City, and in the 1840s brave souls gathered there each
spring for the arduous journey by Conestoga wagon to the golden
West. Today Kansas City is the metropolis in the middle: 1,435
miles from Boston on the Atlantic, 1,577 from Los Angeles on the
Pacific, 829 from New Orleans to the south, 768 from the Canadian
border to the north. The precise geographic and population centers
of the country are both nearby. But more than geography makes this
the capital of Middle America. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TWELFTH-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews English
director Nicholas Hytner's new production of ``Twelfth Night.''
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-ART (New York) _ In the New York Video Festival, which
opens Friday at the Walter Reade Theater, video art, that unruly
stepchild of television and experimental cinema, has flowered into
a vast, immensely creative alternative culture. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ZORRO-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Mask of Zorro'': Martin
Campbell, dir; with Antonio Banderas, Anthony Hopkins, Catherine
Zeta Jones. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   TWAIN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Mark Twain's America'': Stephen
Low, director; 3D IMAX. Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gerlder.
</P>
<P>
   BOYS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Boys in Love 2'': shorts,
``Twilight of the Gods,'' Stewart Main; ``Achilles,'' Barry Purves
(voice of Derek Jacobi); ``Boot Camp,'' Patrick McGuinn; ``Karen
Black Like,'' David Briggs. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Polish Wedding'': Theresa
Connelly, writer/director; with Claire Danes, Gabriel Byrne, Lena
Olin. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   LAVENDER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Silver Screen/Color Me
Lavender'': Michael Rappaport, director; documentary _ Dan Butler
narrates. Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   SLAMNATION-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Slamnation'': Paul Devlin,
director; a documentary about the spoken-word phenomenon. Reviewed
by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   THIEF-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Thief'': Pavel Chukhrai,
director; in Russian, with English subtitles. Reviewed by Janet
Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Hollywood) _ News of the silver screen. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Capsule reviews by New York Times
critics.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEVIDEO (Undated) _ Short items on what's news in home video
and short reviews of what's new in home video. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
