<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following articles on jobs and the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ More and more companies are
bringing in counselors when a worker dies so that co-workers can
grieve. Why? Some employees feel a lot of guilt over the way they
react to an employee's death. Employees need a ritual to mark the
passing, said Terrence Deal, professor of education at Vanderbilt
University in Nashville, Tenn. By L.M. Sixel.
</P>
<P>
   ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ The recent Supreme Court decision
might sound like a prescription for change, but some specialists
warn working women will still be wary of reporting sexual
harassment. By Diane E. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
