<SLUG> BC-FAMILIES-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Managing editors, lifestyle editors) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following families features.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are from The New York Times (NYT), The Boston Globe
(BOS), Cox News Service (COX), and Hearst Newspapers (HNS).
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, where indicated, have been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CHILD-CARE-NYT (Undated) _ A growing number of companies
pay for child care when their employees must travel as part of
their jobs. But some question whether a benefit like this helps
employees have a more satisfying personal life, or simply keeps
them on the job and away from home longer. By Julia Lawlor.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SPOCK-HNS (Undated) _ ``Dr. Spock: An American Life'' is
more than a well-researched biography of America's favorite baby
doctor; it is fascinating social history that reads like a great
adventure. By Carolyn Poirot.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR (Undated) _ Roy Blount Jr. says much of ``Be
Sweet'' is about his difficult relationship with his mother and how
his self-loathing is at the heart of his comedy efforts. By Anne
Stephenson.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-LANGUAGES-COX (Austin) _ Twice recently in a two-week
period, parents planning to relocate to the Austin, Texas, area
called the Round Rock Independent School District to find out if
Spanish is part of the elementary level curriculum there. Not in
Round Rock. Yet some local students _ those whose parents can
afford it and have made the effort to find or initiate programs _
are learning foreign languages from Spanish to Chinese to Hebrew to
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-COUNSELING-COX _ Most clergy say couples will not know
what marriage is really like until they have been married for a
year or longer. Many recommend that newlyweds have marital checkups
with a counselor after six months of marriage and again near their
first anniversary. But they insist that serious preparation is
critical for the success of many marriages. Now, the state of
Florida has discovered what clergy have long known. In June, Gov.
Lawton Chiles signed the Marriage Preparation and Preservation Act.
The law _ which will take effect next Jan. 1 _ encourages
premarital counseling and requires counseling before parents can be
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ What do you do if your child
gets stuck with a hellion for a bunkmate at overnight camp? A Q&AMP;A
column. By Barbara Meltz.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ The importance of being there. By
Linda Weltner.
</P>
