<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ The Court of Appeals stays Starr's
subpoena on President Clinton's Secret Service detail before the
grand jury. Linda Tripp testifies; other developments.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE (Washington) _ Clinton and other Democrats rally for
their approach to managed care legislation. House GOP proposes its
bill. Other developments. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-INSURE (Washington) _ Tens of thousands of homes across
the nation have been flooded again and again while their owners
repeatedly collected federal flood insurance payments, often in
amounts exceeding the total value of the houses, an environmental
group reported today. By John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Developments in Congress on
various spending bills, riders. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-SAFETY-RAND (Washington) _ National Transportation Safety
Board has hired the RAND Corp. to analyze whether its structure
works in investigating air crashes, following criticism from
victims' families to members of Congress. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-THALIDOMIDE (Washington) _ Thalidomide, the notorious drug
that was removed from pharmacy shelves around the globe in the
1960s after it produced thousands of babies with gross deformities,
was approved today by the Food and Drug Administration for use in
the United States. The decision overturns a 38-year-old ruling,
which rejected thalidomide in 1960. Now, four decades later,
thalidomide shows promise for a wide range of ailments, from AIDS
to cancer. The agency has created a distribution system that will
make thalidomide the most highly regulated drug in the history of
the nation. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SYPHILIS (Undated) _ Scientists have succeeded in sequencing
the genome of the Syphilis bacterium. It's a bacterium that has a
played a rich role in medical history. Scientists' efforts to
understand it and develop a vaccine have been frustrated by their
inability to culture it in the lab. They hope that by studying the
genome they will find a way to grow it. This is the golden age of
deciphering bacteria genomes. In the last three years, seven or
eight have been decoded and they are all famous diseases, and they
have all been done by Craig Venter. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-STRIKE (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ Developments in the
Puerto Rico strike. By Mireya Navarro
</P>
