the IMF moved to bail out Russia. A special report. By Michael
Gordon with David E. Sanger. (3000 words)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CZAR (St. Petersburg) _ As Romonovs from around the word
gather in preparation for the burial of the Czar and his family on
Friday, President Yeltsin, in an unexpected reversal, announces
that he will attend the ceremony. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS-DRUGS (The Hague) _ The head of the U.S. war on
drugs arrives in the Netherlands to a furor over remarks that a
high crime rate there is due to lax drug policies. By Marlise
Simons.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-TIMES (Washington) _ The Cuban American National Foundation
announces that it is filing a lawsuit against The New York Times
over a report about the financing of violent acts against the Cuban
government.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SMUGGLE (Beijing) _ After years of tolerating the steady
growth of lawlessness on their borders, China's leaders announce a
war on smuggling. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-TEACHING-LICENSES (Albany, N.Y.) _ The N.Y. State Board of
Regents is voting to eliminate permanent state licenses for new
teachers. Instead they would be required to qualify for a renewal
every five years by attending courses, which the teacher's union
offers.
</P>
