<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REVERSING HIMSELF, YELTSIN CHOOSES TO ATTEND CZAR'S BURIAL
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ President Boris Yeltsin reversed his
earlier decision and pledged to attend Friday's burial of Russia's
last czar, a final erratic twist in the nation's jumbled plans to
entomb Nicholas II and his family on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise announcement from the Kremlin, Yeltsin said
Thursday he would attend the service in the former imperial capital
of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth (about the executions) was concealed for 80 years,''
Yeltsin said. ``Tomorrow, the truth should be told, and I should
take part.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia will bury the fragmented skeletal remains of Nicholas,
his wife Alexandra, three of their five children and four family
servants. The family and their attendants were killed by a
Bolshevik firing squad in 1918, ending the 300-year reign of the
Romanovs of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's decision last month not to attend the ceremony
followed the refusal of the Russian Orthodox Church to acknowledge
the identification of the bones as that of the czar and his family,
despite exhaustive genetic testing and confirmation by an
international team of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   His decision started an avalanche of official backsliding over
what had been intended as a full-scale royal funeral designed to
celebrate Russian history and heal old wounds following the Russian
revolution and seven brutal decades of Soviet rule.
</P>
<P>
   After the church hierarchy and Yeltsin declined, a host of world
leaders, prominent royalty and Russia's top politicians decided not
to attend. The Russian government scaled back the ceremony,
spending less than $1 million on the three-day observance, which
began Wednesday in Yekaterinburg, the city where Nicholas and his
family were killed.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's pioneering reformer in 1991, Yeltsin prompted the
unearthing of the Romanov's remains from a sha
</P>
</TEXT>
