<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POLISH WEDDING': A CELLAR FULL OF PICKLES AND SOUP MADE OF BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
 (JT)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Lena Olin, looking stunningly slim and sensual as Jadzia
Pzoniak, a Polish-American cleaning woman, tells her lover Roman
(Rade Serbedzija) that her body has been so ravaged by having
children her husband doesn't look at her anymore, you wonder what
body she could possibly be talking about. The discrepancy between
what comes out of her mouth and what is visible on the screen isn't
the worst problem with Theresa Connelly's muddled film ``Polish
Wedding,'' but it is glaring enough to make you question everything
else about this aggressively sentimental, nearly laugh-free comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Jadzia, her husband, Bolek (Gabriel Byrne), and their brood of
four sons and one daughter, along with a daughter-in-law and a
grandchild, live in a crowded house on the outskirts of Detroit.
The movie aspires to be one of those zany ethnic comedies
celebrating the vitality and earthiness of American working-class
life that Hollywood has been trying unsuccessfully to re-make ever
since ``Moonstruck.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jadzia, who favors revealingly low-cut, bright red dresses,
announces that ``making life and love'' are her ``religion,'' you
are supposed to think how much more rooted and healthily in touch
with their basic instincts these people are than everybody else.
For Jadzia, being in touch with her basic instincts means that when
her boyfriend steals into the men's room she is cleaning, she
promptly tackles him and throws him down on the tile floor awash
with soapy water. It means that when Roman offers her a trip to
Paris, she says no, insisting no other city in the world could be
more wonderful than beautiful Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   All that spontaneous self-expression and robust sensuality must
owe partly to the hearty fare Jadzia likes to serve her family. She
has a whole cellar full of pickles. One of the delicacies she
ladles out over the dinner table is a homemade soup made of duck's
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Jadzia is not ashamed to admit that many years ago she and Bolek
had to get married because she was pregnant. Now her only daughter,
Hala (Claire Danes), is running wild the same way she did. When
Hala sneaks out of a basement window night after night to roll
around on the grass with Russell (Adam Trese), a handsome young
policeman who lives in the neighborhood, her basic instincts take
over just as her mom's did. The situation becomes dicey when Hala
agrees to represent virginity in an annual church procession.
</P>
<P>
   With its duck's blood soup and pickles, ``Polish Wedding''
offers ample opportunities for rough-and-tumble family farce. But
none of its humor is allowed to run free. That's because the movie
would like more than anything to be a nostalgically heartwarming
slice of working-class Polish Americana. At the same time, it is so
intent on not striking any downbeat notes of kitchen-sink realism
that the very real problems its characters face _ adultery,
unmarried pregnancy and ethnic discrimination _ have no dramatic
weight. Lost in a stylistic limbo, the most ``Polish Wedding'' can
muster is an attitude that could be described as wanly cute.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   POLISH WEDDING
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Polish Wedding'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It has sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Theresa Connelly; director of
photography, Guy Dufaux; edited by Curtiss Clayton and Suzanne
Fenn; music by Luis Bacalov; production designer, Kara Lindstrom;
produced by Tom Rosenberg, Julia Chasman and Geoff Stier; released
by Fox Searchlight Pictures. Running time: 101 minutes. This film
is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Claire Danes (Hala), Lena Olin (Jadzia), Gabriel Byrne
(Bolek), Daniel LaPaine (Ziggy), Mili Avital (Sofie), Rade
Serbedzija (Roman) and Adam Trese (Russell).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
