<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND-2T     07-16 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: LANDSCAPES, ARCHITECTURE AND MIRO ON LONG ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY, SUMMER-HUDSON, SUMMER-CONNECTICUT,
AND SUMMER-RDP)  
(lh) 
 By KEN JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Appropriately for the season, tranquillity prevails at the art
museums of Long Island, N.Y. From the Nassau County Museum of Art,
the Heckscher Museum of Art and the Museums at Stony Brook along
the North Shore to the Parrish Art Museum, Guild Hall and
Pollock-Krasner House in the Hamptons, the offerings are
interesting, sometimes delightful and, on the whole, comfortably
familiar. There's little to disturb anyone's summertime bliss.
</P>
<P>
   NASSAU COUNTY MUSEUM: If you can visit only one, make it the
Nassau County Museum of Art in Roslyn Harbor. Set in a bucolic
145-acre park, the Georgian mansion that Henry Clay Frick gave his
son Childs as a wedding present is the site of two thoroughly
appealing exhibitions: an extended comparison of the works of
Alexander Calder and Joan Miro, and a selection of prints by Henri
de Toulouse-Lautrec from the Baldwin M. Baldwin Collection.
</P>
<P>
   To associate Miro and Calder is not an original idea. The
artists admired and influenced each other, and, as Constance
Schwartz, who is the co-curator of the show with Franklin Perrell,
notes in her catalog essay, as early as 1936 Calder's mobiles had
been described as ``Miro abstractions come to life.'' Nevertheless,
to see such kindred spirits play off each other like jazz musicians
in this well-selected show is exhilarating and revelatory.
</P>
<P>
   The satisfaction is partly formal. Miro and Calder both liked to
set eccentrically curvey lines and flat, biomorphic shapes floating
freely in space. It's nice to see how that happens in the fictive
space of Miro's painting versus the real space of Calder's
sculpture. On the other hand, in contrast to Miro's tendency to
enrich pictorial space, creating allover fields of quirky
symbolism, Calder tends to pare down his works to elemental
structures, moving away from Miro's Surrealism toward
Constructivism.
</P>
<P>
   Miro and Calder also share certain imaginative and spiritual
predilections. They both work out of childlike states of mind,
producing images of toylike people and friendly animals in magical
spaces where the laws of adult gravity have been rescinded. For
both artists, the child is the doorway to the unconscious, and the
unconscious becomes a source of cosmic transcendentalism, a dreamy
theater of archetypes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both artists tie this playful, mystical primitivism to a
rigorous formal pragmatism, often to comical effect, as in Calder's
``Cow With Yellow Face'' (1971), a construction of flat sheets of
steel with teats attached by steel loops, or Miro's ``Pastorale''
(1923-24), a farmscape populated by a fish, a cow and other life
forms schematically abstracted with a kind of scientific precision.
</P>
<P>
   To climb the museum stairs to the Toulouse-Lautrec exhibition is
to move to another century but not to another universe because he
is, like Calder and Miro, a modern artist and an endlessly witty
and inventive draftsman. There is also in his work a childlike
desire to play and to be entertained, coupled with a hard-working
concentration on form and material.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of this exhibition is an 1896 series of
lithographs called ``Elles,'' representing scenes in Parisian
brothels. The series calls to mind Degas' bathers, but it has more
narrative tenderness. Toulouse-Lautrec does not objectify his
subjects formally or sexually; rather he empathizes, as in ``Femme
sur le Dos: Lassitude,'' in which a young woman lies on her back on
a luxuriantly rumpled bed gazing in private reverie at the ceiling.
Printed in sanguine ink on a dark olive-green field, the print has
a misty subtlety to match the image's drifting mood.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else in the show is so psychologically evocative, but in
dozens of posters, theater programs and portraits of actors,
Toulouse-Lautrec's graphic ingenuity, talent for caricature and
alertness to contemporary fashion are well displayed.
</P>
<P>
   HECKSCHER MUSEUM OF ART: The two remaining North Shore museums
are focusing on artists associated with Long Island. At the
Heckscher, a blocky concrete temple set next to a duck pond in the
middle of Huntington, is an exhibition devoted to William de
Leftwich Dodge (1867-1935), a once famous muralist who created
public works for the Library of Congress, the State House in
Albany, N.Y., and various international exhibitions. In 1906, Dodge
built a Greek Revival mansion in Setauket, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A facile academician trained in Europe (he studied with
Jean-Leon Gerome), Dodge shifted styles easily, moving between
old-fashioned history painting, trendy illustration and plein-air
Impressionism. At best, in modest, impressionistic paintings, he
shows a convincing sensitivity to light and paint, as in a small
dark view of boats on San Francisco Bay or Sargent-like gouaches
representing views in and around Villa Francesca, as he called his
estate. But no coherent artistic identity emerges from this show,
and one leaves with the feeling that Dodge's obscurity is not
undeserved.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge show is supplemented by two exhibitions drawn mostly
from the Heckscher's permanent collections. ``Americans in Paris:
Studies and Sojourns Abroad'' is a selection of works by Americans
who studied in Europe around the same time as Dodge. It includes
some very fine pieces, like a small study for ``The Cello Player,''
by Thomas Eakins, and a male nude drawn in charcoal by Thomas
Anshutz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Country Pleasures: Views of Long Island'' presents an
assortment of restful landscapes and seascapes by several dozen
Long Islanders, including Arthur Dove, Paul Georges and Casimir
Rutkowski, whose painterly view of a leafy residential neighborhood
typifies the show's pastoral mood.
</P>
<P>
   Dove and his wife, Helen Torr, who lived in nearby Centerport,
are also given a tiny exhibition of small, lively works on paper in
the museum lobby, along with a display of tools, materials and
memorabilia from his studio.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUMS OF STONY BROOK: The Museums of Stony Brook, a collection
of low-lying, wooden buildings, are featuring an exhibition about
the Long Island projects of Stanford White (1853-1906), the Gilded
Age architect and libertine who designed the original Pennsylvania
Station in Manhattan, the Boston Public Library and other major
metropolitan buildings. White designed many Long Island residences,
from the house and studio of American academic painter William
Merritt Chase in the Shinnecock Hills of Southampton to the
Versailles-like Harbor Hill in Roslyn (destroyed in 1947). White's
own Long Island home in St. James is a palatially refurbished
farmhouse called Box Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Architecture exhibitions are often frustrating, dependent as
they are on drawings, photographs and text to represent unavailable
buildings, and this one suffers more than most from the genre's
deficits. Its principal merit is to make you want to go see the
buildings. The book accompanying the show, ``The Houses of McKim,
Mead &AMP; White'' by Samuel G. White, Stanford White's great-grandson,
could be a valuable guide for a drive-by tour of the actual
estates.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting part of the exhibition is an hourlong video,
which has been on television, that breathlessly recalls the
scandalous history of White's affair with the beautiful teen-age
starlet Evelyn Nesbit and his murder by the man she married, the
psychotically jealous Harry Thaw.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Stony Brook is a retrospective of the illustrative
realist paintings of Joseph Reboli, a contemporary Long Islander.
If you go, however, don't miss the carriage museum, which houses a
lavish display of more than 100 antique horse-drawn carriages, many
of which are extraordinary works of Old World craft.
</P>
<P>
   POLLOCK-KRASNER HOUSE: In Southampton and East Hampton, things
are quiet this weekend but promise to become more exciting in the
next few weeks as two museum shows open. For now, the best place to
go in the Hamptons is the Pollock-Krasner House and Study Center,
in the Springs section of East Hampton. There's a small temporary
exhibition of works by Douglass Morse Howell (1906-1994), a
papermaker who supplied fine, handmade sheets to, among others,
Jackson Pollock, Lee Krasner, Anne Ryan and Alfonso Ossorio, each
of whom has a piece on Howell paper in the show. Howell's modest
works, made by casting dyed paper, string and other materials into
expressionistic as well as gridded compositions, have an intimate,
delicate sensuality.
</P>
<P>
   But the main attractions at the Pollock-Krasner House are the
small shingled house where Pollock and Krasner lived from 1945
until Pollock's death in 1956 and the studio in one of the
outbuildings, where Pollock created his revolutionary drip
paintings. (Krasner lived here intermittently until she died in
1984.)
</P>
<P>
   If you've never been there before, you're in for a treat. Take
off your shoes, put on a pair of silly, foam-rubber slippers
supplied by the museum and walk around on the splattered floor
where you can still see the ghosts and colors of ``Lavender Mist,''
``Blue Poles'' and other well-known paintings. Around the walls, a
sequence of text panels and photographs by Hans Namuth and Arnold
Newman tells the history of a singular artist and a troubled but
productive marriage. It's amazing to think how the history of art
turned here in this serene place, so far from the tempestuous
cacophony of the Manhattan art world.
</P>
<P>
   GUILD HALL: At Guild Hall in the Village of East Hampton a solo
show of paintings by Julian Schnabel, another denizen of the
Hamptons, will open on Aug. 8. For better or worse, the grandiose
Neo-Expressionist rarely fails to give people something to talk
about. Meanwhile, a crowded exhibition of works by artists who have
lived or vacationed locally remains up through July 26.
</P>
<P>
   Mined from the museum's permanent collection, the show is deep
in inconsequential prints, but it is also studded with gems,
including lush landscapes by the 19th-century painters Thomas Moran
and George Inness; a small, glowing all-over abstraction by
Krasner; a rich green, nearly abstract painting of a sun-dappled
tree by Fairfield Porter, and Henri Cartier-Bresson's 1968
photograph of a car rushing past an old East Hampton graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   PARRISH MUSEUM OF ART: Celebrating its centennial, the Parrish,
in the Village of Southampton, will present ``Dreams for the Next
Century,'' selections from its collection of artists who have lived
in the area. With Klaus Kertess as curator, the show opens on
Sunday and concentrates on the recently deceased painters Willem de
Kooning and Roy Lichtenstein. It will also include works by Joan
Mitchell, John Chamberlain, Chuck Close, Robert Gober and others.
</P>
<P>
   Concurrently with that show, the Parrish will present a major
outdoor installation by Barbara Kruger, a seasonal Hamptons
resident, whose canny showmanship and aggressive ideological
approach will surely stir up the town's tony ambiance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
