<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC LANDMARK PRESERVATION COULD BE HILLARY CLINTON'S LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 19)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So much of what has been reported about Hillary
Rodham Clinton has dealt with her involvement in the Whitewater
affair and her defense of her embattled husband that it was a
pleasure to witness her efforts last week to preserve America's
historic landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, life as first lady has not been what she must have
envisioned when she left the governor's mansion in Little Rock for
the White House in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 1992 presidential campaign, she told a
national television audience that she was not the type to stay home
and bake cookies or follow the ``stand-by-your-man'' credo voiced
by Tammy Wynette.
</P>
<P>
   But, ironically, standing by her man in the face of charges that
he has had extramarital affairs and solicited illegal campaign
contributions has become a big part of her life as first lady.
Although many Republicans, for purely partisan reasons, would like
the president to be impeached or forced to resign, many also have
sound reasons for questioning his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Those reasons transcend Hillary Clinton's assertion that her
husband is simply the victim of a ``right-wing conspiracy.'' Such
hyperbole has tended to diminish the influence of a talented first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   A highly intelligent woman who sought to pattern herself after
Eleanor Roosevelt, she has been unable to play a major public role
in promoting such causes as health care and child welfare.
</P>
<P>
   When, with the president's blessing, she oversaw creation of a
massive but flawed health care plan, her concoction was destroyed
by congressional Republicans and a multi-million dollar drive
headed by insurance and medical interests. When the battle was
over, Hillary Clinton had lost her cause and many supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign against health care was similar to _ and just as
venomous and disingenuous as _ the one launched this year by the
tobacco industry to kill legislation designed to curb smoking among
teen-agers by sharply increasing the tax on cigarettes. It was
equally successful.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton also has had to answer many questions about her
work in the Whitewater matter as a partner in Little Rock's
prestigious Rose Law Firm. She has been summoned to testify before
a federal grand jury and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the first lady has traveled the world at her
husband's side and on her own. Wherever she had gone, she appears
to have made an excellent impression.
</P>
<P>
   But her legacy has not been a strong one.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that will change as she continues her journeys to save
America's treasures for future generations. Like her husband,
Hillary Clinton has her eye on the millennium and her determination
to honor the past while celebrating the future.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that goal, she has drawn attention to the need to
preserve the Star Spangled Banner that inspired Francis Scott Key
during the British shelling of Baltimore's Fort McHenry in 1814 to
write the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Baltimore and Washington's Smithsonian Institution,
where the tattered flag is being restored, she has visited Thomas
A. Edison's historic invention factory in West Orange, N.J., and
the homes of James and Dolley Madison in Virginia, famed American
novelist Edith Wharton in Massachusetts and civil rights pioneer
Harriet Tubman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Seneca Falls, N.Y., last Thursday she challenged the nation
to ``finish the work begun here'' on behalf of women's rights 150
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, she stressed the need to protect America's
illustrious past. She plans to extend her focus across the United
States, spotlighting the need for historic preservation in various
sectors of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Before Eleanor Roosevelt strode onto the national stage in the
1930s, presidents' wives were bound by rather strict rules of
decorum. Unless they were involved with such organizations as the
Girl Scouts or the Daughters of the American Revolution, they
played no role in public life and did not travel about on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   But things began to change. Bess Truman and Mamie Eisenhower
were the last of the traditional first ladies.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s Jacqueline Kennedy redecorated the White House with
many original furnishings. Lady Bird Johnson sought to beautify the
nation by keeping junk yards and billboards off many major highways
and by enlivening the landscape with an abundance of wildflowers.
She also promoted Operation Head Start and other Great Society
programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Johnson's basic view was that the president's wife
should create in the White House an ``island of peace'' for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Nixon was a more retiring first lady, but she made many
friends traveling abroad with her husband and promoting
volunteerism at home.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the White House in 1977, Betty Ford overcame her
dependence on alcohol and then established the clinic that bears
her name and that has helped thousands of individuals overcome
chemical dependency.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalynn Carter's most important mission was to get federal
funds for mental health. She also was a strong advocate of the
Equal Rights Amendment, which ultimately failed.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reagan exerted powerful influence behind the scenes in the
White House, but her most memorable, and most criticized, public
project was urging young people to ``just say no'' to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush, an extremely popular first lady, concentrated on
literacy, Head Start and programs for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The president's wife, no matter who she is, can be a valuable
asset to the nation as a persuader and achiever. That is what
Hillary Clinton now is seeking to do. Preservation of historic
landmarks could be her most important legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
