<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOYS IN LOVE 2': A MEDIOCRE MIX OF SHORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at the end of review.)  
 (js)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Easily the most intriguing film in a mostly mediocre collection
of gay-oriented shorts collected under the title ``Boys in Love 2''
is Barry Purves' ``Achilles.'' The 11-minute animated film
re-imagines the history of the Trojan War as revolving around the
star-crossed love of Achilles and his younger soldier and lover,
Patroclus. Although the movie, narrated by Derek Jacobi, is too
abbreviated and jumpy to carry much dramatic weight, the film's
puppet soldiers, who do battle and make love, are elegant
imitations of classical sculpture brought to life.
</P>
<P>
   The other selections in the anthology are mostly one-joke
affairs. Several borrow their gaudy style from the John Waters
school of brash candy-colored camp. In the longest, Joel Moffett's
``My Body,'' a man wakes up after his first homosexual experience
to discover himself in bed with a dead body that looks just like
him. Discovering that he has contracted a rare new disease called
sexually repressed shedding disorder, he desperately searches for a
cure and winds up in a hospital under the care of a doctor who
preaches the advantages of leading a repressed double life. This
belabored fable about sexual shame and the difficulty of
self-acceptance is directed and performed in an incongruously cute
comic style that quickly runs out of charm.
</P>
<P>
   In Stewart Main's doomed love story, ``Twilight of the Gods,'' a
Maori warrior and a European soldier meet in the jungle, fight,
then become lovers. Although the film strives for a mythical
resonance, it succeeds only as pretentious soft-core fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   David Briggs' leering horror spoof, ``Karen Black Like Me,''
finds a young man chased around his apartment by an extremely
determined sex toy. In Todd Downing's ``Dirty Baby Does Fire
Island,'' a wide-eyed baby doll washed up on the shore becomes a
Peeping Tom. Patrick McGuinn's ``SPF 2000,'' a science fiction
comedy in which a group of lecherous sunbathers encounter a space
alien, is an inept spoof of Italian sexploitation films of the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The wittiest selection, John Scott Matthews' six-minute film
``Boot Camp,'' is also the shortest. As two men cruise each other
in a leather bar, their flirtation turns into a peppy musical
comedy number that bares the ingenuous romanticism seething behind
the characters' studied macho poses.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS IN LOVE 2'
</P>
<P>
   A compilation of short films released by First Run Features. At
the Cinema Village, 22 East 12th St. Running time: 97 minutes. This
film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY-2TA     07-16 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: EXOTICA IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND, SUMMER-HUDSON, SUMMER-CONNECTICUT,
AND SUMMER-RDP)  
(lh) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Manhattanites, and particularly those with underdeveloped
driving skills, an art excursion to New Jersey is a breeze. Many of
the state's museums and galleries are a quick trip by train or bus
from Manhattan. And most of them hop with activity through the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   NEWARK MUSEUM: The Newark Museum, ever adventurous in its
programming, is always a premier attraction. And this year it
greets the travel season in appropriate fashion with a smartly
fashioned think piece of an exhibition devoted entirely to the
despised esthetic category known as ``tourist art.''
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the Heard Museum in Phoenix, Ariz., ``Exotic
Illusions: Art, Romance and the Marketplace'' evolved under
interesting circumstances. A few years ago, the Heard did some
housecleaning and decided to unload a range of items, mostly
African, Oceanic and work from the Americas, that were deemed to be
either knockoffs of traditional objects or entirely modern
inventions. But the curator put in charge of de-accessing, Peter H.
Welsh, had plans of his own. He held onto the unwanted material and
turned it into an extended visual essay, with eye-opening results.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh began with a fundamental premise of post-modern theory,
that ``art'' is a fluid category, changing its meaning depending on
its context and that art objects often have as much to say about
the people who acquire them as about those who make them. The 40
entries he selected, most of them from Africa, illustrate his
point.
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions, they were made for a foreign market and
shaped by its demands. Some objects adapt existing African forms to
reinforce cultural stereotypes. A reproduction of a classic Kifwebe
mask from Congo, for example, adheres to a traditional tribal model
but distorts its features to create a cartoon emblem of brutish
primitivism. Other facsimiles are scuffed up to suggest antique
origin or ceremonial use, factors much valued by collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Certain images are inventive fictions. Sinuous wooden figures
called shetani are among thousands of stylistically similar
sculptures carved by Makonde artists in Tanzania since the late
1950s. Although credited with supernatural origins, the type was
actually conceived with Western esthetic requirements in mind: each
image is unique, if only in minor details, and each is signed with
the name of an individual carver.
</P>
<P>
   By museum standards, such mass-produced objects are historically
inauthentic and artistically suspect. But Welsh argues for a
different set of criteria for judging their validity. For many of
their buyers, including increasing numbers of Africans, they
provide a tenuous psychological link to a lost way of life, a
nostalgia for an imagined Eden. And sometimes they carry clear and
political messages of life in the present.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case with a charming toy-size beaded helicopter made
for the tourist trade in 1991 by a woman named Gabigabi Nzama in
South Africa. On the one hand, the little sculpture exemplifies a
century-old tradition of Zulu beadwork. On the other, it is a
knowing symbol of the apartheid era, when surveillance helicopters
were known among blacks as ``eyes of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Exotic Illusions'' also includes a selection of travel
brochures, grade-B jungle movie posters, and a mockup of a suburban
living room furnished with ersatz tribal art, all obvious
illustrations of neo-colonialist appropriation. But in the end
Welsh keeps his argument in more complex terrain, considering
artists and patrons neither simply as victims nor opportunists, but
as interactive partners in sustaining the cultural illusions that
all art, masterpiece or otherwise, traffics in.
</P>
<P>
   ALJIRA: Tucked in an office building just a block away from the
Newark Museum is Aljira, a contemporary art center, with a
one-person show by sculptor Martha Posner, who lives in rural
Pennsylvania. The six striking pieces in the shape of garments are
made of wire and organic materials: a towering kimono-like robe is
covered with raw fleece; a stiff and unwearable cloak is woven from
wild rose cane threaded with brightly colored cloth scraps.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade in which images of clothing have been enlisted as
stand-ins for the human body, Ms. Posner's work has a lot of
competition, but by drawing nature into the equation, she gives the
metaphor an evocative spin.
</P>
<P>
   ROBESON CENTER ART GALLERY: Nature also infuses a series of 18
recent paintings by Gregory Amenoff at the Robeson Center Art
Gallery on the Newark campus of Rutgers University. Although their
titles are drawn from the poetry of William Blake, they partake
stylistically of a time-honored strain of American visionary art,
particularly the palpitating animism of Albert Pinkham Ryder and
Charles Burchfield. Amenoff's abstraction has always hovered just
this side of landscapes painting; here he passes, at Romantic
full-throttle, across the line.
</P>
<P>
   MASON GROSS GALLERY: In New Brunswick, a half-hour train ride
from Newark, a very different solo show can be found at the Mason
Gross School of the Arts Gallery near the main campus of Rutgers
University. Sponsored by the University's Center for Latino Arts
and Culture, it includes 30 large-scale paintings by Noe Hernandez,
32, a self-taught, Mexican-born artist.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's mix of Roman Catholic, pre-Columbian and populist
references harkens back to the muralists of an earlier day, though
his predominant subject is immigration rather than revolution. In
one composite image, the Virgin of Guadalupe appears as the Statue
of Liberty floating against a barbed-wire fence at the U.S.-Mexican
border; in another Jesus' face appears on a resident-alien card.
Hernandez's didacticism can be heavy-handed, but he has a firm
command of scale _ one can easily see this work as public art _ and
his collage-style splicing of images is often provocative.
</P>
<P>
   The same gallery is host to ``Puerto Rican Graphic Arts From the
Island to El Barrio/Spanish Harlem: 1950 to 1985.'' The 65 works
document the output of artists in the Caribbean and the United
States, with an emphasis on those who settled in the largely Latino
neighborhood on Manhattan's Upper East Side. Many of those artists
_ Marcos Dimas, Antonio Martorell and Fernando Salicrup among them
_ are still vital members of that community, and their work has
real graphic verve. Photographs of the Barrio two decades ago by
Hiram Maristany are an added delight.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   VOORHEES ZIMMERLI MUSEUM: At the Jane Voorhees Zimmerli Art
Museum, also on the Rutgers campus in New Brunswick, ``Paul
Robeson: Artist and Citizen'' is worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   This examination of the life of the protean American actor and
singer, who was a Rutgers graduate, consists primarily of archival
papers and artifacts. But there is a selection of portraits by
Winold Reiss, Charles White, Jacob Epstein and Edward Steichen, a
not-unimpressive lot, whose work distills the feeling of American
life at mid-century when Robeson's career was at its peak. The
exhibition will travel to the Museum of the City of New York next
year.
</P>
<P>
   MONTCLAIR ART MUSEUM: Redolent of a still earlier era is the
work of Boston-born Impressionist Maurice Prendergast (1858-1924)
at the Montclair Art Museum in a traveling exhibition, ``Maurice
Prendergast, the State of the Estate: Selections From the Williams
College Museum of Art.'' The 50 or so small paintings and
watercolors were found in the artist's studio at his death and were
eventually given to the college.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the show is that this material represents the
``private'' Prendergast: works to which he was personally attached
or never finished or was unable to sell. Among them are journeyman
academic portraits, allegorical tableaus and an oversupply of beach
scenes. With his incremental, picture-puzzle technique, Prendergast
could be an attractive artist: his unfinished watercolors, in which
half-formed images and detached swatches of paint float out on a
white ground, look good. But overall he doesn't generate much
excitement here.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting is ``Collecting Culture: Grace Nicholson,'' a
selection from the museum's celebrated American Indian holdings
organized by Twig Johnson that constitutes another exploration of
the dynamics of art-making and patronage. Grace Nicholson
(1877-1948) was a dealer who, indirectly through the collector she
served, supplied a wealth of material to Montclair, and superb
examples of her choice finds are on view.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's standards for ``museum-quality'' art were stiff. She
considered age, indigenous use and formal beauty as essential
ingredients, and as early as 1912 she reported that: ``All Pueblo
and Hopi material is scarce. They offered to make up a lot of
material for me but I did not care for any of that sort of stuff.''
By 1927 she gave up dealing in American Indian work altogether,
stating that all the ``good'' and ``genuine'' art was gone and
``there is no danger of a revival.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's perspective itself qualifies, of course, as an
exotic illusion, but fortunately it was one she wasn't locked into
it. For years she supported the careers of living artists like the
great Karok basket makers Elizabeth and Louise Hickox of
California, who produced work for Western travelers during the
craze for American Indian basketry that swept the country early in
the century.
</P>
<P>
   One of Elizabeth's baskets, incorporating maidenhair fern stems
in its weave, is in the show. A more exquisite example of
``tourist'' art, past or present, is impossible to imagine. And
it's nice to know that a century from now, work by artists of our
own day _ differently but equally inspired _ will be appearing in
exhibitions just like this summer offering at Montclair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
