<P>
   OUSTED-COLUMNIST-HNS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Patricia Smith has always
played with fire. Known as a dynamic performance poet and an
incendiary newspaper columnist, Smith was consumed last month in a
conflagration of her own making _ she was forced to resign from the
Boston Globe after she admitted making up characters and quotes in
work that purported to be fact. By Paul Grondahl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MOVIE-ACTORS-NYT (Los Angeles) _ A tide of movie and theater
actors, as well as established film writers, directors and
producers, are surging into a medium that they once scorned. And
just as important, the gates of movie studios have been flung open
to television actors and writers after decades of not-so benign
neglect. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ZORRO-PROFILE-HNS (Los Angeles) _ Who is that masked man?
Actor Antonio Banderas takes pride in being the first Spaniard to
play Zorro, the fictional Spanish hero. But in the first couple of
scenes of the new movie, ``The Mask of Zorro,'' it's Academy
Award-winning actor Anthony Hopkins behind the mask. What gives?
The stars talk about the scenes, their careers and the movie, which
opens Friday. By Bruce Westbrook.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-WEIL-BOS (Undated) _ It hasn't been that long since Liza
Weil was a high school student, not unlike Anna Stockard, the
character she plays in the new film ``Whatever.'' By Renee Graham.
</P>
<P>
   KEEVE-FILMS (Undated) _ In his half-dozen years as a filmmaker,
Douglas Keeve, a former fashion photographer, has turned his
penchant for voyeurism into a flair for comedic truth telling. By
Ruth La Ferla.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEASTIE-BOYS-NYT (Undated) _ There is a term in hip-hop, flavor.
It is a good thing. Rappers want to have flavor: panache, style,
something extra that enables them to stand out from the pack. In
their 17 years together, however, the Beastie Boys have developed
something much better than flavor: taste. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   MONICA-COX _ Interview with Monica, who's new album comes out
July 14.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-YOAKAM-BOS (Undated) _ A Hollywood sophisticate by day, a
hillbilly by night. That's the duality of Dwight Yoakam's life. By
Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   DAN-FOGELBERG-HNS (Undated) _ It's been 19 years since a
28-year-old Dan Fogleberg earned immortality with his No. 2 hit
single ``Longer'' which has been used at more weddings than a polka
band. Despite the lack of mega-hits through most of the 80s and
90s, Fogelberg has maintained a loyal following of fans, some of
whom travel in caravans for up to 10 hours or more to catch his
concerts. By Jim Rogalski.
</P>
<P>
   DONNIE-DEBUTS-COX (Pasadena) _ Even at 40, Donny Osmond still
resembles that oh-so-cute pop music star that made young girls
swoon in the '70s. Osmond hopes to relieve those great times with
sister Marie when ``Donny &AMP; Marie,'' the duo's daytime talk/variety
show debuts in September.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-METALLICA-BOS (Undated) _ Change is not always a
metalhead's best friend. But Metallica, which has grown more
melodic and has explored musical subtleties and other genres in
recent years, still has sells out its shows. By Jim Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   HANSON-MUSIC-LADN (Los Angeles) _ Those ``MMMBoppers'' are
finally taking it to the streets. A year after Hanson's
breakthrough hit, Ike, Zac and Tay have embarked on a major world
tour. And gals, the towheaded cuties insist they don't have
girlfriends. By Fred Shuster.
</P>
