<HEADLINE>
`ZORRO' IS A GRAND OLD SWASHBUCKLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFF SHANNON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The creators of ``The Mask of Zorro'' wanted to reintroduce the
fabled hero to young '90s audiences with an operatic flair, so
they've beefed up the masked avenger's legacy with enough tragedy,
treachery and hard-earned redemption to make it as ripe as anything
Verdi ever staged.
</P>
<P>
   It's a vigorous crowd pleaser that gradually betrays its own
noble ambitions, but it's also got enough gusto and agility to
qualify as a satisfying swashbuckler in the grand old style.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Fairbanks was a better swordsman than either Anthony
Hopkins or Antonio Banderas, who play Zorro here as a
master-student combo, with Don Diego de la Vega (Hopkins) passing
the torch after serving served 20 years of an unjust prison
sentence. But Fairbanks would surely approve of this dual effort of
charismatic stars, and the sly combination of Hopkins' gravity and
Banderas's seductive insouciance.
</P>
<P>
   Top it off with parallel subplots of vengeance and you've got
familial honor of ``Godfather'' proportions, albeit with old-world
etiquette and more witty joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   Don Diego was jailed by Don Rafael (Stuart Wilson), the Spanish
governor of Alta California, in a confrontation that cost the life
of Diego's beloved wife (Julietta Rosen) and possession of his
infant daughter Elena, who was raised by Rafael with no knowledge
of her real father's fate. Two decades later, Mexican bandit
Alejandro Murieta (Banderas) suffers a similar loss to Rafael's
ironically-named military henchman Capt. Love (Matt Letscher), who
yearns for the now stunningly beautiful Elena (Catherine
Zeta-Jones).
</P>
<P>
   Having passed his time in the heroic spotlight, Diego grooms
Murieta to be the new Zorro, joining forces to combat Rafael's plot
to exploit Mexicans in his quest to purchase California from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   You can easily figure out the rest of the scenario, which
escalates into a zesty display of swordplay, clever maneuvering and
an explosive free-the-slaves climax. ``The Mask of Zorro'' is more
effective in set-up than payoff, and after piling on its subplots
it gradually gives way to the kind of mayhem that director Martin
Campbell handles so well in his 007 blockbuster ``GoldenEye.''
</P>
<P>
   No telling what young maverick Robert Rodriguez would have done
with the movie; he bailed over contract disputes two months before
cameras rolled. But Cambell seems more in line with the lavish,
glossy vision of Steven Spielberg, who fostered the project and was
once intending to direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mask of Zorro'' has just enough sophistication to satisfy
adults (and a script good enough to attract this stellar cast), but
like ``Braveheart' and ``Rob Roy,'' it's an action-drama with youth
appeal and some indulgent concessions to a mainstream audience.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 136 minutes, the story takes some conspicuous shortcuts
(as when Banderas goes from crude rogue to diplomatic ``gentleman''
virtually overnight) and, after all its dashing fancy, it falls
back on a rousing but routine action finale.
</P>
<P>
   And Zeta-Jones, despite the intelligence and grit of her
character, is basically the target of Banderas's sexy (and
occasionally sexist) humor. It's all delightfully good-natured, but
the now-familiar gag (in which Zorro precisely slices Elena's
night-dress off with his sword) tells you where the movie's (and
Zorro's) priorities lie.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part it's good. It could have been better.
</P>
<P>
   The Mask of Zorro. Directed by Martin Campbell. Screenplay by
John Eskow and Ted Elliott &AMP; Terry Rossio. Cast: Anthony Hopkins,
Antonio Banderas, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Stuart Wilson, Matt
Letscher. Tri-Star Pictures. 136 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence,
mature humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1633EDT &QL; 
