<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BUFFALO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODD `BUFFALO 66 MIXES FANTASY AND REALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66'' is named after the Buffalo Bills football team
and the year in which the story's hero was born.
</P>
<P>
   Written by actor Vincent Gallo, who also directs and stars, the
film is about Billy Brown (Gallo), a poor schlub who harbors a
grudge against former Bills' place kicker Scott Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Billy believes Woods wrecked his life by throwing a big game,
causing him to lose a fortune to the local hoods. The only way he
can repay the debt is to take the fall for one of the gang's thugs,
and he goes to prison for a crime he never committed. After Billy
is let out of jail, he returns home to Buffalo to even the score
against those who wrecked his life and his big chance at being the
best bowler in town.
</P>
<P>
   The film features a tender supporting performance by Christina
Ricci as Layla, the young tap dance student Billy clumsily kidnaps
to act as his wife on his homecoming visit to his negligent
parents, played with a scary ferocity and humor by Ben Gazzara and
Anjelica Huston.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's folks embrace Layla as the daughter they never had,
pouring her a glass of wine, stuffing her full of tripe stew, and
telling her they love her. But they ignore Billy, looking at their
son as if he were a stranger, and indeed, he's lied to them for
five years, telling them he's been on a covert mission for the CIA
instead of wasting away in a prison cell.
</P>
<P>
   This odd film _ which won raves at Sundance and played the
recent Seattle International Film Festival _ is full of surprises,
some good, some not so believeable.
</P>
<P>
   It's sadly funny as well as whimsical in spite of its backdrop
of potentially abrasive _ and highly abusive _ situations. It's a
strange mix of gritty realism and fantasy stirred together into an
unusual love story that thankfully only flirts, and then flees,
from violence. It's about missed opportunity, shattered dreams and
trying to make a mark in a world that barely knows you're alive.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, who has played the loser role before in a number of indie
movies like ``Palookaville,'' is surprisingly endearing as Billy,
especially since the character is so critical and judgmental of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Writer/director Gallo's intentions are clearly noble in this
offbeat romance about loving in spite of past scars, but he can't
fully pull his ambitious subtext from beneath the quirkiness. In
the end, ``Buffalo 66'' parallels Billy's story by not fulfilling
its potential.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo 66. Directed and written by Vincent Gallo. Cast: Gallo,
Christina Ricci, Anjelica Huston, Ben Gazzara. Lions Gate Films.
110 minutes. Rated R for nudity, language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
