   &UR; CONSUMER NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PENSIONS-NYT (Undated) _ Nearly 1,400 Americans are
collecting pension benefits because they found their names on an
Internet site created by the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., the
federal agency that insures pensions. The agency posted the names
of about 8,600 people who have not applied for benefits due to them
from plans the agency now administers. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-BONDS-PERSONAL-WEALTH-BLOOM (Undated) _ Ross Shawaker, 72,
was thinking of his 66-year-old wife when he bought $30,000 of
Tennessee Valley Authority bonds. That's because, when he dies, the
bonds can be sold back to the company for what he paid, even if
they have fallen. By Wes Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLOW-OF-FUNDS-BLOOM (New York) _ Some mutual fund managers are
selling shares of Internet-related companies because the investors
worry that the stocks can't go higher after a major surge in price.
By Jon Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-GARP-BLOOM (New York) _ The World According to Garp
in money management relates to an investment strategy popularized
by Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. By Jon Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INTERNET-NYT (Undated) _ It was a wild week on Wall
Street for Internet stocks. But because many of these fledgling
companies may be years away from actually making money, the sight
of their stocks skyrocketing one day and plummeting the next is
enough to make investors wonder if the Internet is paved with gold
or just a high-technology version of the tulip craze. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INFLATION-BOND-NYT (Undated) _ More about the new
inflationed-protection savings bonds the Treasury unveiled this
week. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-AURORA-FOOD-NYT (Undated) _ Aurora is a high profile
example but it hasn't done well. Tropicana, a rumored food IPO, may
not go that route because parent Seagram thinks there's a better
way (private sale). A look at what drove Aurora to the IPO trough
and what's keeping Seagram away. By Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-BADNEWS-NYT (Undated) _ It has become increasingly
unusual for Wall Street securities analysts to deliver bad news on
a stock. Even more unusual is when they not only quit recommending
a stock but call their past advice to buy it a blunder. Such is the
case with the share price of Agco Corp., a leading farm equipment
maker. By Rick Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-AGING-ADVICE-NYT (Undated) _ Investment advice for
Generation A, the 80-somethings, fastest growing segment of the
