<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEL FREE TO SPEAK OUT ON PUBLIC ISSUES _ THAT IS, IF YOUR BOSS
APPROVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suppose you are involved in the anti-abortion movement and you
spend your weekends picketing abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, suppose your boss at the XYZ Co. is pro-choice and doesn't
much like your brand of political activism. So he tells you to cut
out your picketing and any other show of support or you'll lose
your job.
</P>
<P>
   What? What about the First Amendment? Can your boss quash your
free speech rights?
</P>
<P>
   In a word, yes. Private employees don't have any free speech
protections, the courts have ruled over and over.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment refers to protections against government
tyranny of free speech, said Tony Rosenstein, an employment lawyer
for Baker &AMP; Botts in Houston. Employers were not feared tyrants
when the Constitution was written.
</P>
<P>
   The issue recently surfaced in the case involving Edward Blum,
who spent 17 years as a stockbroker for PaineWebber in Houston. He
had been campaigning to abolish affirmative action in Houston _ a
referendum he sponsored on the city ballot was defeated in November
_ and was forced by the brokerage firm to cease all outside
political activity as a condition of employment.
</P>
<P>
   Blum received a reprimand in March telling him that the firm
will not clear any press contacts either on or off the record or
any article in which he espouses an anti-affirmative postition and
that any further violation would result in immediate termination.
The firm requires its employees to clear all interviews and
articles in advance, according to the reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   In his written response, Blum wrote that in the last six to
seven years he's had letters to the editor published in newspapers,
but none of them addressed financial issues relating to the
securities industy, capital markets or investments. Instead, they
dealt with issues such as genetic cloning, racial preferences and
U.S. policy toward Israel, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PaineWebber code of conduct I'm required to sign every
year specifically requires me to clear any investment-related
articles prior to publication,'' he wrote. ``The code does not
address pre-clearance of letters to newspapers, articles, etc.,
that are outside of investment-related topics.``
</P>
<P>
   Blum resigned recently, contending the firm's stipulation to
stop his outside political activities came after a ``very senior
elected offical of the city of Houston'' called the chairman of
PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, PaineWebber said Blum's articles were reflecting
negatively on the firm's reputation and had led to client
complaints and loss of business. After underwriting city bond
offerings for several years, PaineWebber has been passed over
lately for city bond work.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber was within its rights to tell Blum to stop his
political activity, said Andrew S. Golub, an employment lawyer who
represents individuals. Blum probably doesn't have a case against
the brokerage firm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He may, however, have a case against the city of Houston for
interfering with his free speech rights by complaining to his
employer, Golub said. That government muzzling of free speech is
what the First Amendment protects.
</P>
<P>
   Free speech is a trickier situation if an employee works for a
government agency.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, public employees have more freedom to
express themselves. A public school teacher, for example, would
have the right to participate in the pro-choice movement on his own
time, Rosenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation changes if the government employee complains about
his employer. Then issues of public concern and government interest
determine whether the speech is protected or whether it's just like
a private employer-employee relationship.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a city firefighter complains to the media about
not getting a raise and says the fire chief is a bad guy, it's a
personal issue and wouldn't be protected speech, said Bill Helfand,
a defense lawyer in Houston who concentrates on employment law and
civil rights claims.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a matter of public concern _ and thereby protected _ if
an employee in the police department complains the department is
not keeping track of confiscated drugs and they're lying all around
the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Cases are never clear, Helfand said. They have to be judged
individually.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a delicate balance of weighing government interest
with freedom of speech for public employees. That pops up in
sports, said John Zavitsanos, a Houston lawyer who recently opposed
Helfand on a free speech case.
</P>
<P>
   If a coach works for a state-supported college and complains
about a bad referee at a game, courts have ruled that the school's
interest in muzzling its coach is greater than letting a coach
mouth off, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To voice comments, telephone (713) 220-2000 and dial in code
1002. Send e-mail to lm.sixelchron.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
