<HEADER>
A8553 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HELPLINE-HNS &LR;      07-16 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVING SOFTWARE'S OLD VERSION LEAVES PROBLEMS FOR THE NEW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I was using McAfee VirusScan 3.14 when I downloaded version
3.16. I noticed in the Add/Remove program of Windows 95 that both
versions were listed. I decided to remove the old version, but when
I did, it removed the shortcut for both versions. Can you not
remove old versions of software or programs in ``Add/-Remove''
without affecting the new version?
</P>
<P>
   A. In theory, that's how it should work. But as is the case with
Windows 95/98, theory and practice are often two different things.
</P>
<P>
   The Add/Remove module in the Control Panel is the simplest _
though not always the best _ way to remove a program from Windows
95/98. Usually, the entries you see in the list point to a removal
program in each software package's folder.
</P>
<P>
   If you install new versions of a program on your system, the
installation process should handle the listing in Add/Remove. But
sometimes, as apparently is the case with VirusScan, it dropped a
duplicate entry into the list.
</P>
<P>
   The uninstall routine for the older version of McAfee searched
your program groups for shortcuts with a specific name. If both
shortcuts have the same name, the uninstall program will remove
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, even if you have removed a program, Add/Remove will
still show a listing for it. You can remove these phantom listings
using TweakUI, the Windows 95 PowerToy that lets you configure the
Windows desktop. You can get the Windows 95 version at 
www.microsoft.com/windows/downloads/contents/PowerToys/W95TweakUI/de
fault.asp. A version of TweakUI for Windows 98 is on the operating
system's upgrade CD, in the Tools/Reskit/Powertoy folder.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the standard disclaimer about removing Windows
programs: You should never just delete a folder to nuke a program.
Always use either Add/Remove or a third-party uninstall program,
such as CleanSweep or Uninstaller.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last year I bought a computer with an AMD K6 chip, and I
really like it. I'd heard it doesn't play games like Quake very
well, but that's not been my experience. Quake rocks on this thing!
Anyway, now I'm seeing something called the K6-2, and supposedly
it's better for games. What's the difference between the K6 and
K6-2?
</P>
<P>
   A. The K6 is Advanced Micro Devices' answer to the Pentium
family of chips from Intel Corp., though it's significantly less
expensive. This has made PCs that use this chip the favorites of
those who want lots of speed but also want to keep from spending
lots of cash.
</P>
<P>
   However, the K6 doesn't match Intel's Pentium family in one
respect, an area called floating-point calculations. This is a
certain kind of math that's handled by a specific part of the chip.
Games like Quake use floating-point calculations to handle some
aspects of their graphics.
</P>
<P>
   With the K6-2, AMD has added a set of instructions in the chip
called 3DNow!, which can handle a lot of the work done by the
floating-point unit in Pentium chips. And because they are specific
to 3-D graphics, they can in some cases handle it better.
</P>
<P>
   To prove its point, AMD has released a set of drivers and a new
executable for Quake II that works with the 3DNow! instruction set.
I've tried these on a K6-2-based machine running at 300 megahertz,
and the results are indeed spectacular. Quake II is incredibly
fluid.
</P>
<P>
   There's one problem, though. Programs must be tweaked to take
advantage of the K6-2's abilities. Running any old 3-D game on a
K6-2 machine won't yield the kind of results you get with the
specially tuned version of Quake II. As a result, AMD is promoting
the K6-2, hoping to convince software developers to take advantage
of 3DNow!
</P>
<P>
   If you have a machine with a K6-2 chip in it, you can download
the Quake II files at www.amd.com/products/cpg/k623d/drivers.html. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silvermanchron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter access
code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
