<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-HUDSON-2TAKES-     07-16 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-HUDSON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: IN THE HUDSON VALLEY, A FEAST WITH A PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND, SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY,
SUMMER-CONNECTICUT, AND SUMMER-RDP)  
(lh) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People venturing into New York's Hudson Valley in pursuit of
interesting art have their work cut out for them. The summer shows
are diverse, substantial and spread out, forming a feast that
requires no small amount of mobility but is generally worth the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON RIVER MUSEUM: Moving north from the city, the first stop
is the Hudson River Museum in Yonkers, which is living up to its
name with ``Where Land Meets River,'' a selection of works from its
collection by artists of the Hudson River School, their
contemporaries, followers and fellow travelers. It's a small,
thrown-together affair with only two dozen artworks, and it isn't
helped by its setting, a gallery dominated by a large, ugly
stairwell. Still, the show is close to enchanting, its piecemeal
nature underscoring the pervasive influence of the river on
artistic imaginations of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Start with several images from John Hill's ``Hudson River
Portfolio'' of the early 1820s, whose big, capable aquatints are
based on the watercolors of William Guy Wall. Each image shares its
sheet with descriptive text, like that which identifies ``View Near
Fort Montgomery'' as ``one of those happy groupings of mountain and
water scenery, which, among the windings of the highlands, are so
abundant as to render selection difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   This abundance is reiterated by John Douglas' large,
fastidiously detailed late-19th-century canvas, ``View of the
Hudson (Highlands) With Woman Painting.'' The artist has set up her
easel overlooking a panorama that could yield a lifetime of motifs.
</P>
<P>
   The show is peppered with idiosyncratic works. These include a
large panoramic wash from 1831 looking north from West Point by one
A. Van Zandt that is notable for its delicate textures and muted,
almost Chinese atmosphere; a dramatic folk art painting of a stormy
night on the Hudson, in which waves, clouds and sails all tilt
starchily to the right, fighting the wind, and four decorative
panels made from 1830 to 1840 in which riverside scenes, crisply
stenciled in light paint on dark, have the hallucinatory
ghostliness of afterimages.
</P>
<P>
   Certain vistas clearly attracted artists by the the score. The
Hudson's majestic Palisades loom in several images in tones ranging
from lavender to brown, including another Hill/Wall collaboration
whose accompanying text, citing their ``savage grandeur,'' is
nearly redundant.
</P>
<P>
   A second exhibition, ``Go Figure,'' contains a handful of works
from the museum's collection by George Segal, Rigoberto Torres,
Joseph Cornell, Red Grooms and Paul Manship.
</P>
<P>
   NEUBERGER MUSEUM OF ART: Conveniently, the next stop is the
Neuberger Museum of Art, where a survey of Robert Berlind's
landscapes confirms that the tradition is alive and well, and that
water continues to cast its spell. Berlind, who turns 60 this year
(and who has a show of recent work at the Tibor de Nagy Gallery on
Fifth Avenue through July 24), prefers to view water close up, in
puddles and ponds that capture, animate and distort reflections of
trees, sky and river banks. It is a vantage point that brings out
the abstract side of nature while creating a contemplative,
slightly melancholy air.
</P>
<P>
   Representing 14 years of work with roughly 30 paintings and oil
sketches, this exhibition traces a growing artistic command and
emotional complexity. Some early paintings settle tensions that are
largely narrative. ``Field'' a dark lawn illuminated by light from
a barely visible house might almost be a crime scene. Occasionally,
there's a rather coarse decorative buzz, as in ``Winter Vineyard,''
where twisted grape trees dance against the stark whiteness of
snow; a conventional realism, generic and dull, characterizes
industrial images like ``Saw Kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlind began to hit his stride in the early 1990s with a series
of desolate, tree-strewn images in black and white titled ``Damaged
Woods'' that experiment with a more painterly approach. In
subsequent works he turns to trees reflected in water or seen
against empty skies. The drama of his art emanates increasingly
from the paint itself, from the play between depicted and real
light and from the fluidity of both paint and water. The sense of
the artist's hand, mind and eye increases, evoking, oddly, both
Willem de Kooning and John Singer Sargent. But Berlind anchors his
increasingly bravura style in reality, where it is leavened by a
palpable sense of nature's power and inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   Other shows at the Neuberger include a small survey of recent
paintings, most notably ``Glass Houses,'' in which Maura Sheehan,
Ming Hu and Thermon Statom have used various kind of glass to
create handsome installations. An installation work by Nancy
Davidson is also on view.
</P>
<P>
   KATONAH MUSEUM OF ART: ``Pavel Tchelitchew: Landscape of the
Body,''at the Katonah Museum of Art, is the first retrospective in
more than 30 years devoted to the eccentric Russian-born Surrealist
whose star burned brightly in New York, London and Paris in the
late 1930s and '40s. He designed sets for George Balanchine; did
portraits of Dame Edith Sitwell, Lincoln Kirstein and Gertrude
Stein, all of whom admired his work profoundly; drew covers for
View magazine, whose founder, Charles Henri Ford, was his
companion, and was often seen as the rival and equal of Jackson
Pollock.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time he died in Rome in 1957, Tchelitchew's
achievement had faded in the light of Abstract Expressionism's
blazing rise. He became known for exactly one painting:
``Hide-and-Seek,'' the phantasmagoric fusion of child's play,
tree-of-life and truncated body that is among the Museum of Modern
Art's most popular paintings. The exhibition includes this work and
an even more extravagant tour de force, ``Phenomenon,'' an
apocalyptic freak show painting from the late 1930s on loan from
the State Tretyakov Gallery in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative, mystical, preternaturally gifted as a draftsman,
Tchelitchew was born in Russia in 1898 to a wealthy privileged
existence that ended with the Russian revolution, which scattered
his family in exile. His life closely parallels that of Vladimir
Nabokov, who was one year his junior, and an extravagant refinement
inhabits the one's line and the other's language. But beneath
Tchelitchew's crystalline refinement, an element of indulgence and
delusion tinges most of his work.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition traces a trajectory of considerable momentum, by
turn fascinating, beautiful and pandering, and frequently overly
indebted to Picasso and Dali. The artist's ink drawings and
notebooks, which alternate between spontaneous sketches and
meticulous preparations for larger works, show his talent at its
freshest and most immediate. And his late abstractions _ their
luminous circuitries distilling the veins and nerves that
electrified his transparent skulls and bodies, turn calculated
refinement into the genuinely visionary. Dating from the last four
years of Tchelitchew's life, these networks may have been spurred
by Pollock's example, but their fibrillating intensity is all their
own.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   STORM KING ART CENTER: ``The Fields of David Smith,'' at the
Storm King Art Center in Mountainville, just west of the Hudson, is
the second of three surveys of the American sculptor's career being
held during successive summers. It displays nearly two dozen
examples of Smith's often implicitly figurative work outdoors,
where they are forced to compete with gentle mountain views. An
additional 30 sculptures and reliefs, as well as drawings and
photographs, are being shown in the large renovated stone house
that contains the center's galleries. Basically this is another
David Smith show that, despite its pleasures, is rudimentary and
does little more than underscore the need for a large, definitive
examination of the artist's work.
</P>
<P>
   Variously planar or linear, touchingly humorous or offensive in
reference (consider the reclining forms of ``The Lady Painter''),
physically audacious or simply clumsy, Smith's art is complex and
uneven. Unlike the Abstract Expressionist painters, who tended to
distill their visions into a single style or motif, his forms and
styles continued to multiply and divide until his death in 1965.
And while the painters tended to pass through Cubist or Surrealist
phases, Smith's work retained signs of these influences throughout,
remixing and reconsidering their possibilities, so that his work
has a peculiar suspefsion.
</P>
<P>
   It can be seen as bringing to conclusion many of the most
important sculptural ideas of the first half of the 20th century
and also as inaugurating a more abstract and experiential phase of
sculpture. Smith translated the improvisational freshness of
``action painting,'' as Abstract Ex`ressionism was sometimes
called, into three dimensions; he demonstrated how sculpture, like
painting, can be made up as it goes along. His best works make us
aware of the physical decisions and compositional elements involved
in their unity, of the artist's hand, impetuosity and eye for
detail and accident.
</P>
<P>
   But his work doesn't decisively point sculpture in the direction
of environmental art, which was the achievement of various Pop,
Minimal and Post-Minimal artists, prominently Claes Oldenburg,
Donald Judd and Richard Serra.
</P>
<P>
   The show makes much of this clear, but the information is
virtually unorganized, with the presentation of works outdoors in
jumbled disarray being especially unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of Smith's penchant for displaying his work
in the fields around his studio at Bolton's Landing, N.Y. a few
miles up the river, but here, at least, the idea seems overrated.
With works from the Voltri series; stainless steel pieces like ``XI
Books, III Apples'' ``Sentinel V'' and ``Untitled (Candida)'' and
sundry other works, including the powerful, white forms of ``Primo
Piano III,'' one's time outdoors is hardly wasted. Still, the works
are seen to much better advantage in the galleries, where their
often delicate structures, psychological currents and historical
references can be more fully savored and neither their strengths
nor their weaknesses are muffled by the natural setting.
</P>
<P>
   VASSAR COLLEGE: The tour rounds out with two very different but
rewarding group shows. ``Acquisitions on Paper: 1988-1998,'' at the
Frances Lehman Loeb Art Center at Vassar College sounds modest: it
is a selection of drawings, prints and photographs acquired by the
college during the last decade that have not yet been exhibited.
But the 50 works on view include some marvelous things: prints by
Schongauer, Cezanne, Munch and Alexander Calder; drawings by
Gauguin, Tchelitchew and Abraham Jansz van Diepenbeeck, the
17th-century Flemish painter whose ``Mass of St. Gregory'' is a
vision of miniaturized grandiosity. Also included are numerous
photographs, among them images by Walker Evans, Edward Steichen,
Dorothea Lang and Gjon Mili, this last being a view from on high of
the 1947 Madison Square Garden fight between Joe Louis and Jersey
Joe Walcott, so precisely composed it might have been staged.
</P>
<P>
   BARD COLLEGE: The tour finishes squarely in the present at the
Center for Curatorial Studies at Bard College, where Yvo Mesquito,
a visiting fellow from Brazil, has organized ``Stills: A Selection
from the Marieluise Hessel Collection.'' Its subject is vast _ the
influence of film upon recent art _ and was recently tackled in
``Hall of Mirrors: Art and Film Since 1945,'' an ambitious sprawl
of artworks, avant-garde film and feature movie excerpts organized
at the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The only movies in Mesquita's far more modest effort are those
conjured up by the artworks themselves. This eliminates a certain
intermedia competition that hampered ``Hall of Mirrors.'' The
suspects are often usual: Cindy Sherman, John Baldessari, Ed
Paschke, Nan Goldin and Robert Longo, and the borders sometimes so
elastic that nearly any artist would seem to qualify. Mesquita
manages to show how different aspects of film _ the prop, the movie
poster, narrative, sequential frames, stereotype, romance, violence
and visual drama _ have infiltrated contemporary art. The show has
more than its share of dead spots, but it also casts many things in
a new light, providing a reasonable demonstration of the art
exhibition as a form of visual thought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      07-16 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: FROM MAGAZINES TO MOVIES; IMAX GOES 3-D; MIXING
SPORTS AND MTV  
</HEADLINE>
   (js)  
 By James Sterngold   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It's easy! Start a magazine with an eye toward
Hollywood and then sell the articles to producers who will turn
them into movies, money and fame. At least thav's the image some
might have gotten last week when Tina Brown announced she was
quitting as editor of The New Yorker to start a magazine with
Miramax Films that would funnel the articles to the studio.
</P>
<P>
   Well, any ethical issues aside, it might not be so easy after
all, say a number of journalists who have been swallowed up in what
they describe as the miasma of Hollywood filmmaking. Movies like
``Saturday Night Fever,'' ``Urban Cowboy'' and ``\op Gun'' grew out
of magazine stories, but many journalists said those are the rare
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Hollandsworth should know. Hollandsworth is a staff writer
for Texas Monthly, a respected magazine based in Austin that has
taken an aggressive, but sober-minded, approach to the$studios.
Hollandsworth said he has had nine articles optioned by various
studios, but only two have been turned into movies, both for
television. One, about a high-school girl seduced by the football
coach, was so changed by the time it was broadcast that it bore
little resemblance to what he had written about in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering how much gets changed, why do they need to get
these stories from magazines in the first place?'' Hollandsworth
asked. ``I don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   His most recent success was ``The Killer Cadets,'' made for NBC.
Overall, he said, Hollywokd has been a source of frustration and
confusion, which has only made him ever more eager to focus on
journalism and let the chips fall where they may in the film world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your chances of success are so infinitesimally small that you
don't think about it,'' Hollandsworth said. ``If you write an
article with that in mind, I guarantee you're going to fail. The
fact is that journalists are on the bottom rung of the movie-making
ladder, and they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Levy, the founder and publisher of Texas Monthly, said he
recognized that the long narratives the magazine publishes were
potentially good material for films so he hired an agent more than
15 years ago to try to make deals. The magazine is represented by
the William Morris Agency, which has sold options to dozens of
articles. Levy said that among the lessons learned from the
experience are that journalists should write articles and not
``treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no and no,'' he said in response to the idea that the
magazine might focus on pieces with an eye toward Hollywood.
``That's critical. Our editors are too smart for th`t. The point is
if we luck out and get a good movie deal, it's icing on the cake.
It's not the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Better Than Disney?
</P>
<P>
   It seems that hardly a day passes without the announcement of a
new animation project from Hollywood. A number of new animated
shows are coming to television, many for adults, and most of the
major movie studios are feverishly working on animated films.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the filmmakers are chasing the Walt Disney
Company, which all but owns this lucrative franchise, and they are
following Disney's time-tested techniques. But there is a notable
exception. The Imax Corporation is working on several 3-D animated
film projects, using an unusual new technology it has developed,
which bring an entirely new element to this genre.
</P>
<P>
   To get a sense of what Imax is up to one need only watch a
two-and-a-half-minute animated short that the company is showing
along with one of its popular 3-D movies, ``Into the Deep.'' The
short, called ``Paint Misbehavin','' was produced to show off the
new technique, which has been dubbed Sandee, and Rich Gelfand, a
chief executive of Imax, says the film has met with an enormously
favorable reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with animation is that to compete with Disney, you
have to do it better than Disney,'' Gelfand said. ``What we're
thinking is we can do it different than Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning at an Imax theater in Los Angeles, the
short, which involves a character, Roman, twisting back and forth
on a ladder that appears to be tumbling on the heads of the
audience, set off squeals of laughter and had children flailing
their arms and reaching out for the character.
</P>
<P>
   Animation artists using the Sandee technology put on a pair of
3-D glasses and, as Gelfand described it, draw in the air with a
stylus attached to a computer. That produces images on the
computer, which are then transformed into a film that must be
viewed with the glasses to produce the effect.
</P>
<P>
   Gelfand and Brad Wechsler, Imax's other chief executive, said
the company had a range of 3-D projects in development. The first,
called ``T-Rex,'' will be released in October. It involves
life-like dinosaurs _ eight stories tall _ produced on a computer
and placed in a live-action setting.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Imax is working with the noted cartoonist Gahan
Wilson on an original film, and is developing movies based on
``Gulliver's Travels'' and ``Pinocchio.'' It is also considering
transforming existing animated films into 3-D, which can be done
relatively easily if the original movie was computer-generated,
like ``Toy Story,'' Wechsler said. The company is hoping to get the
first of these projects in its Imax theaters next year.
</P>
<P>
   True Grit on the Grid
</P>
<P>
   Can the MTV generation learn to take sports seriously as a moral
guide?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question being addressed by Brian Robbins and Mike
Tollin, the directing and producing team currently finalizing an
unusual sports movie, ``Varsity Blues,'' for MTV Films and
Paramount, which is due in theaters this fall. The movie is billed
as a comedy, but Robbins , who directed the movie and is a
producer, and Tollin, a producer, said the film also carried some
strong messages about character and responsibility, rather than the
simple raucous good times frequently shown in movies aimed at the
MTV crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a drama with a lot of comedy, in my view,'' said Robbins,
who starred for five years in the television show ``Head of the
Class.'' ``I mean, it's high school and there's a lot of comedy in
that, but it's kind of a coming-of-age story and these kids learn
some lessons. `Hoosiers' is really the model for this.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports films made a generation ago, the stories of Jim
Thorpe, Lou Gehrig and Knute Rockne, were thinly disguised lectures
on morals. The gritty sporting arena was a place where character
was tested, and values like loyalty and honesty generally won out.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the entertainment focused on young people today
takes a more flippant and irreverent attitude; just consider
``Beavis and Butt-head Do America,'' another movie MTV co-produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Varsity Blues,'' which stars Jon Voight as an overbearing
football coach and James Van Der Beek, of ``Dawson's Creek,'' as a
second-string quarterback suddenly thrust into the limelight, is
intended to be amusing, but in some ways it is a throwback to the
earlier type of sports movie. That is not surprising, coming as it
does from two filmmakers who are admitted sports freaks and have
long done films that take sports very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins and Tollin first worked together on a documentary,
``Hardwood Dreams,'' which charted the rise and fall of a high
school basketball team in a rough neighborhood of Los Angeles. They
also made the documentary ``Hank Aaron: Chasing the Dream,'' and
have produced ``Nickelodeon's Sports Theater With Shaquille
O'Neal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This film is really about the confrontation between the coach
and his quarterback and the team, and what they take away from
it,'' Tollin said. ``It's not just for laughs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tollin and Robbins also are the executive producers of
``Arliss,'' a show on HBO with a decidedly X-rated side that charts
the path of a fictional sports superagent struggling to maintain
his precarious perch at the top. The two have also created two
other Nickelodeon shows, ``All That'' and ``Kenan and Kel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-CONNECTICUT-2T     07-16 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-CONNECTICUT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: WHERE CARAVAGGIO FIRST CAME TO AMERICA, IN 1943 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND, SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY, SUMMER-HUDSON,
AND NY-SUMMER-RDP)  
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Modern and contemporary art are on view in several Connecticut
museums, with a particularly ambitious and up-to-the-minute survey
in Ridgefield, but the most glamorous show is devoted to an Old
Master, Caravaggio, in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   WADSWORTH ATHENEUM: A year ago the Wadsworth Atheneum in
Hartford ended an old dispute with the Italian authorities by
agreeing to return a painting that was stolen from the Italian
Embassy in Berlin at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908, the Galleria Nazionale d'Arte Antica in Rome lent a
picture by Jacopo Zucchi, a 16th-century Florentine Mannerist and a
follower of Vasari, to the embassy. In 1947 Russian military
officers in Germany offered it for sale. Later it was on the market
in Paris, which is where the Atheneum bought it from a private
dealer in 1965 without knowing its provenance. Italian officials
pressed Hartford for the picture, but decades of fitful
negotiations passed until Peter C. Sutton, who had recently taken
over as director of the museum, cleared the way for it to go back
to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   To say thank you, the Italian government is now lending more
than two dozen paintings by Caravaggio, Carlo Saraceni, Simon
Vouet, Guercino and others to the museum for its exhibition,
``Caravaggio and His Italian Followers.'' It's a remarkable
exchange, and you should go out of your way if necessary to see
this excellent show before it closes on July 26.
</P>
<P>
   The Atheneum was the first American museum to buy a Caravaggio,
his ``Ecstasy of St. Francis,'' in 1943, so the show ostensibly
revolves around that picture, with additional loans from other
American institutions: Caravaggio's ``St. John the Baptist in the
Wilderness,'' from the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas City,
Mo., and his ``Cardsharps,'' from the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort
Worth, Texas, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The result is handsome but it is also clever for mixing, for
example, Neapolitan pictures lent from Rome with ones that Hartford
owns, to the benefit of both, and uniting different versions of the
same subject, like the three Caravaggios of St. John. Moreover,
along with works by better-known artists, there are curios like a
painting of a fishmonger cleaning a skate _ the artist isn't known
_ and another of a laughing woman, her face hard-edged, the surface
like fresco, by Angelo Caroselli, a self-taught artist and skilled
forger of the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   The Caravaggios are the obvious attraction. Caravaggio, better
than anyone, knew how to capture the posture of adolescent angst.
The picture from Kansas City shows St. John as a brooding boy,
slumped, eyes hooded; he is then transfigured by the cold,
impartial light that picks him out of the darkness and makes him
bigger than life, an isolated and hypnotic presence: Olivier
playing Hamlet on an empty stage.
</P>
<P>
   I was struck no less by some of the other artists in the show.
Bernardo Cavallino's ``St. Peter and the Centurion Cornelius'' is a
delicate, elegant image, the figures attenuated like Tiepolo's.
Saraceni's paintings bring to mind what people admire in Vermeer:
soft-edged figures in a clear and even light, jewel-like, as if
suspended in time. Saraceni was a less dynamic painter than
Caravaggio, but he could be more poetic; his picture of St. Cecilia
with an angel is a kind of silent music.
</P>
<P>
   Orazio Gentileschi was a Caravaggesque painter of poetic style
too but darker in mood. ``Judith and Her Maidservant with the Head
of Holofernes,'' from the Atheneum's collection, is a calibrated
mix of refinement and violence. It shows the two women looking in
opposite directions, listening into the darkness behind them.
Gentileschi paints a soft raking light across Judith's dress that
picks out some gold brocade, a counterpoint to the Cevered head of
Holofernes that rests on her lap.
</P>
<P>
   The Zucchi is here, too, by the way: meaty women bathing in
various odd Mannerist poses. It leaves for Rome when the show ends.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ALDRICH MUSEUM: ``Pop Surrealism'' is a big, boisterous show at
the Aldrich Museum in Ridgefield put together by Harry Philbrick,
the museum's director, with a team of curators. It surveys current
art that mixes Pop and Surrealism, which is to say most of what's
new these days.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the art gives a weird or malevolent spin to Pop subjects
(Jim Shaw, Paul McCarthy, Cameron Jamie, John Currin, Manuel
Ocampo, Robert Williams, Miles Coolidge, Pieter Schoolwerth, Peter
Saul). Some of it remakes Surreal objects (Bellmer redux) in
materials like colored latex, or as tchotchkes, giving the works a
Pop twist (Nancy Davidson, Rachael Neubauer).
</P>
<P>
   A whole section of the show is dedicated to underground comics
(Charles Burns and Gary Panter, Kaz, Art Spiegelman). And much of
what's on view involves grotesque bodies or bodies bizarrely
reconfigured (Cindy Sherman, Nicola Tyson, Carroll Dunham, Ashley
Bickerton, Tony Oursler, James Esber).
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bellmer, the unrepresented ancestors include Guston, R.
Crumb, George Herriman, Leger, Paul Cadmus, de Chirico, Beckmann _
the point being that what's new here isn't a completely new
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   But it is distinguished in a few ways. One is the emphasis on
minute detail and an almost obsessive process of construction. You
can see in this exhibition just how much young artists today seem
fixated on technique, causing a kind of unanticipated revival of
the traditional crafts of painting and drawing. Shazia Sikander's
riffs on Persian miniature paintings are an obvious example. Sue
Williams' latest paintings are another, mixing of Pollock and Matta
with the comics.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the assumption (it used to be a radical assertion)
among many younger artists that high and low culture now simply
blend together seamlessly. Dunham, a senior member among the
painters here, makes a remark along these lines in the show's
catalog: ``It used to give me fits every time I would read
something about my paintings because it was cartoon this, cartoon
that, blah, blah, blah, cartoons. It bothered me _ Walt Disney
wasn't the first guy to use black lines around things. Matisse and
Picasso used a lot of black lines. Then I realized I was being
defensive because my attitude about drawing really is influenced by
cartoons. It's silly to pretend it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, I think, has been gradually, almost surreptitiously,
to shift our sense of what's beautiful and well made and serious _
which is what good art should do. With 73 artists and a big
subject, the exhibition is a mixed bag, with some questionable
choices and omissions. But the best work in it is strangely catchy,
funny and fluent. Whitney in Stamford
</P>
<P>
   As proof that there are different ways to slice the same pie,
Gregory Crewdson's photographs, which are in ``Pop Surrealism,''
are also in a show here called ``Where: Allegories of Site in
Contemporary Art'' at the Whitney Museum's Stamford branch. (Ashley
Bickerton is in both shows, too.) ``Where'' is a small,
helter-skelter overview of untraditional landscapes and other
singular views of the built environment _ malls, spaghetti highway
entanglements, abandoned lots, suburban sprawl _ made during the
last 30 years or so. Robert Smithson, Lawrence Weiner and Gordon
Matta-Clark are the Old Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptually speaking, the show is thin, but it has art worth
seeing, including Matta-Clark's familiar photographs of houses he
cut holes out of during the '70s. One of Michael Ashkin's miniature
landscapes is here, along with a few of Martha Rosler's sinister
photographs of airports and Catherine Opie's small, dreamy platinum
prints of Los Angeles freeways. This was the first time I focused
on Gabriel Orozco's photographs, which always struck me as sterile.
The ones here, of unnoticed, hangdog places in the city, seemed to
me to have a delicate, ad hoc poetry.
</P>
<P>
   YALE ART GALLERY: The Yale Art Gallery, ostensibly celebrating
art at Yale since 1945, has put up modern and contemporary art this
summer, much of it from the collection, some of it by artists who
went to Yale, some of it belonging to Yale alumni, but some other
loans. Probably it's best not to worry about the details too much
and just regard what's here as a kind of extravagant summer filler
until the new director of the museum, Jock Reynolds, takes over in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   You might check out the room of works by younger alumni: a small
Matthew Barney sculpture, photographs by Lois Conner and Abelardo
Morell and (who else?) Gregory Crewdson. (Art is dominated by a
pack mentality.) Then see the galleries of more or less
contemporary works: several fine small Gerhard Richters from the
mid-1960s, a Martin Kippenberger collage, a Kiki Smith sculpture of
a flayed arm and an early Wayne Thiebaud of drink syrups. The rooms
of Katherine Dreier's collection have lately been reinstalled and
deserve a look.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the collection of European genre and landscape
paintings from the collection of Herbert and Monika Schaefer, which
is to be given to the museum. A painting of a jester, by a
16th-century Tyrolean artist known as the Angrer Master, is
especially unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   And don't miss the group of American 19th- and 20th-century
drawings belonging to Yale that includes a Dorothy Dehner, a Lesley
Dill, an early gray-on-gray Brice Marden and a funny Thomas Cole
ink drawing of the devil throwing a monk off a cliff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
