<SLUG> BC-NY-SUMMER-ART-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING CARAVAGGIO AND TARZAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND, SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY, SUMMER-HUDSON,
AND SUMMER-CONNECTICUT)  
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer, as always, offers a mix of shows in the region around
New York City, which for someone with a car, a map, an appreciation
for bad roadside food and an esthetic purview big enough to
encompass Caravaggio and Johnny Weissmuller is a fair alternative
to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, for instance, the Newark (N.J.) Museum has a
collection of souvenir masks from Congo, posters of Weissmuller's
Tarzan movies and a foot-long model helicopter covered with bright
Zulu beadwork (it's based on the surveillance helicopters of the
apartheid era), part of an exhibition of odds and ends from the
tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   Sound frivolous? It's not, but the traditional-minded might try
instead the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Conn. A decision by the
museum to return to Italy an Italian painting stolen during World
War II and bought by the museum, unwittingly, years ago has led to
an exhibition of Caravaggios from Italy: a stunning thank you.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hudson Valley, meanwhile, are two shows of mid-century
Americans. For a while Russian-born Pavel Tchelitchew (1898-1957)
had a reputation in New York almost equal to Jackson Pollock's. Now
he's known, if at all, for a single surreal and nightmarish picture
of children at play, which is in the Museum of Modern Art. The
Katonah (N.Y.) Museum of Art has organized the first Tchelitchew
retrospective in 30 years, revealing, among other things, his
wizardry as a draftsman and arguing for his renewed relevance. You
can decide.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith's relevance has never really been in doubt. The
Storm King Art Center in Mountainville, N.Y., is continuing, from
last year, a celebration of him: 57 works plus drawings and
photographs, mostly from the 1940s and '50s. The biggest steel
sculptures are clustered beside the center's meandering lawns
against the picturesque backdrop of the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   And for pure pleasure, you might also make your way to Long
Island for works by Calder and Miro, linked in history by their
combination of whimsy and hands-on practicality; they are the
eternal optimists of modernism, brought together in an exhibition
at the Nassau County Museum of Art in Rosyln Harbor, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
