A8629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLAR17-COX     07-16 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLAR17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOLAR POWER USE GROWING AS COST DROPS, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    460&AMP;add
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fueled by falling costs of photovoltaic cells,
world solar markets are growing 10 times faster than the oil
industry, the Worldwatch Institute reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of solar cells, closely related to silicon
semiconductor chips found in computers, has fallen by 80 percent
since 1980, the environmental group reported. This is making
electricity affordable to more than 2 billion people worldwide not
connected to power lines, as evidenced by a 40 percent rise in
sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the largest increase in a decade,'' said Christopher
Flavin, Worldwatch senior researcher, who co-wrote the report with
researcher Molly O'Meara. While solar power still makes up a tiny
fraction of all power generated, it ``has the potential to move
from the margins of the global energy marketplace right into the
mainstream,'' Flavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Solar power is not yet economically competitive in the United
States, where it still costs two to five times more than
electricity generated by nuclear or fossil fuels. But as technology
matures in the next decade with the use of technology such as
``thin film'' photovoltaic material, scientists believe costs will
dip perhaps another 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In much of the Sunbelt, where air conditioning drives up power
demand, this price would make solar power competitive with
electricity from fossil fuels, Worldwatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, integrating solar cells into roofing tiles and even
window glass _ which allows homes and buildings to generate some of
their own power and even sell electricity back to the utility _ are
beginning to be used in a few pioneering communities such as
Sacramento, where the local utility company partially subsidized
rooftop solar systems for 420 homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwatch found that much of the recent growth in solar sales
was spurred by rooftop solar programs, championed in President
Clinton's goal of installing solar energy systems on the rooftops
of 1 million U.S. buildings by 2010. Japan is the world leader so
far, with 9,400 solar home systems installed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sklar, executive director of Solar Energy Industries
Association, said it's uncertain whether Congress will provide
sufficient funds to achieve the ``million roofs'' goal.
</P>
<P>
   But solar power can't become competitive in the United States
until people can choose the kind of electricity they want, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we deregulate our electricity market, one of 10 homes
will use solar power,'' Sklar said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is currently the No. 1 producer of solar
cells, primarily for the export market.
</P>
<P>
   But without market reforms to encourage solar power at home,
Flavin said, ``the current strong U.S. leadership could be lost
because the industry is likely to migrate where markets are
developing unless we develop a small domestic market.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A separate report released last week by Winrock International
suggests that renewable electricity, including sun, wind and water
sources, can be brought to nearly half the world's population that
lives without power for just pennies a day.
</P>
<P>
   The report makes a direct connection between electricity and
economic growth. For example, it says, a family of onion farmers in
Indonesia could devote 16 hours a day carrying water by hand to
irrigate their fields. But with a small wind power system that
operates water pumps, labor would be slashed to 100 hours per
season.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-page report is ``the first time the market has been
described as comprehensively,'' said John Kadyszewski, director of
Winrock's renewable energy team. Winrock assists governments,
private enterprises and institutions such as the World Bank in
bringing electricity to the rural poor.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyszewski, who has traveled to more than 30 countries, said
that field experience taught him that rural people in developing
countries want electricity and are willing to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt there was a big opportunity to make an impact,'' he
said. ``A small amount of energy changes a person's life.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
