<SLUG> BC-SCHOLDER-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHAPEL' RESONATES WITH UN CERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV. Photo has been send to NYT photo clients)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - The centerpiece of Fritz Scholder's
``Chapel'' for the End of the Century'' is a large bronze angel
standing on a globe.
</P>
<P>
   It is a resonant and ambiguous figure: one you know you've seen
before but can't place and you don't know exactly what it means.
</P>
<P>
   The figure is disquieting. It is neither male nor female. And
although most angels have both arms and wings, this figure has only
a pair of wings and they are too small for flight.
</P>
<P>
   Scholder calls the figure ``Future Clone,'' which is an
ambiguous title. Is it a clone &UR; from the future or is it a clone  &UR; of
the future _ a second future like the original but different by
being unnatural?
</P>
<P>
   We tend to be made uncomfortable by uncertainty, and the whole
chapel rings with it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are clues.
</P>
<P>
   The figure relies on our cultural memory of the original: The
many figures of Christ standing on or holding on to the globe that
symbolizes earthly power. It is an image that has its own familiar
variations. For it is also Christ on Golgotha _ the figure on the
dome of the skull.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of the figure is hinted at in the many collages with
which Scholder has lined the walls: his version of the
stained-glass windows found in Christian chapels.
</P>
<P>
   In those collages, you will find the bronze figure rhymed by
other images.
</P>
<P>
   In one, it is the archangel standing on the vanquished head of
Satan.
</P>
<P>
   In another, it is three astronauts standing behind a large model
of the moon, rising above it like three figures on an orb.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another, it is Charlie Chaplin in ``The Great Dictator,''
where Chaplin of the Hitler parody strides over the globe the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   It is an archetype, an image radiant with meaning, although the
meaning changes with context.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the Caspar David Friedrich that gives us the final
key: a small reproduction of the German painter's ``Wanderer Above
the Sea of Fog.'' It is the same image although the scale has
changed radically: The orb is immense, and the figure, a rather
middle-class German ``burgher,'' is small in relation, standing on
the pinnacle of rocks above the world.
</P>
<P>
   We are all that angel Scholder has cast in bronze. We all stand
every day atop the orb, like the ``burgher,'' although we only
rarely sense the spinning planet beneath us. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1726EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8665 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHEAT-PAKISTAN-SPI &LR;      07-16 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-PAKISTAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SANCTIONS LIFTED, PAKISTAN MAKES MAJOR U.S. WHEAT PURCHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pakistan Thursday agreed to buy about $30 million
worth of wheat from the United States, increasing its planned
purchase to reward Congress and U.S. farmers for acting so quickly
to remove sanctions imposed against the country for testing nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the U.S. wheat Pakistan bought is expected to come from
Washington state, which is the source of half the soft white wheat
exported by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had been barred from selling wheat to Pakistan
_ the largest importer of U.S. white wheat _ under the terms of
sanctions imposed after Pakistan and India tested nuclear weapons
in May.
</P>
<P>
   Congress this week passed a bill to exempt agricultural sales
from the sanctions, and President Clinton signed the measure into
law just 17 hours before Pakistan accepted bids for this week's
major purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan had planned to purchase 300,000 metric tons of soft
white wheat this week, and Australia offered to fill that order at
a lower price than did the United States. But Pakistan decided to
increase its purchase, to 500,000 metric tons, in order to steer a
sizable order to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan will now purchase 300,000 metric tons from the United
States and 200,000 metric tons from Australia. The value of the
U.S. purchase was estimated at $32 million by the Pakistani Embassy
and at $29 million by U.S. Wheat Associates, an export market
development organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting good rates, and we thought that when the U.S.
farmers and their representatives had put in so much effort, we
should buy more wheat from the United States,'' said Farrakh
Qayyum, the trade minister at the Pakistani Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Australians had offered us a very competitive price, but
we wanted the Americans to participate so we held the tender back a
few days to allow Congress to go ahead, and we decided to provide
some satisfaction ... that their efforts hadn't gone to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheat farmers, who are facing historic low prices because of the
Asian economic crisis and strong harvests worldwide, were delighted
to have a rare positive development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful news,'' said Christopher Shaffer, a
fifth-generation wheat farmer in Walla Walla and the chairman of
the Washington Wheat Commission. ``There was a lot of concern they
(Pakistan) would hold a grudge against us for the original embargo,
but it looks like we've been able to work through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan last year accounted for 40 percent of overall U.S.
white wheat exports and 37 percent of Northwest exports, according
to U.S. Wheat Associates. Pakistan purchased 2.2 million tons of
wheat from the U.S. last year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. wheat will actually be purchased from a variety of
exporters, who buy wheat from farmers and sell it to foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much needed dose of export demand at a time when we are
facing a shortage of storage space and a shortage of market,'' said
Jonathan Schlueter, executive vice president of the Pacific
Northwest Grain and Feed Association, which represents commercial
grain handlers. ``There will be fewer ground piles (of wheat) in
the Pacific Northwest as a result. This will move grain through the
system, and we need to get it moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlueter said the industry had expected that Australia would
win a sizable portion of the Pakistani purchase because Australia
had refused to impose agricultural sanctions against Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest lawmakers, including Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash.,
Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., and Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., pushed
hard to have the sanctions removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan has been a good trading partner and is seeking a good
relationship with the U.S.'' said Nethercutt, who was one of
several lawmakers called by Pakistan's ambassador to the United
States about the sale yesterday. ``The purchase is an indication
that they're grateful, rather than resentful, and now we have sold
300,000 tons we wouldn't have otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton was also pleased with the purchase, but said the plight
of wheat farmers demands greater action by the Clinton
administration. He sent a letter to Clinton urging him to
re-evaluate a broad array of sanctions, to implement more
agricultural export programs, to support agricultural research
projects, and to push harder to get U.S. wheat into China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commodity prices are hitting record lows and the fear of
bankruptcy looms for many in the agriculture community,'' Gorton
wrote. ``What we do today ... to help our farmers will determine
their economic viability for years to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOLDER-AZR &LR;      07-16 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOLDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRITZ SCHOLDER AT LAST HAS DISCOVERED SELF IN NEW WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV. Photos have been send to NYT photo clients)  
 (WITH SCHOLDER-SIDE)
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Fritz Scholder has always been a perplexity.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale painter and sculptor is clearly the most
historically important artist in the Phoenix area. . His work
regularly appears in art history texts; if you live outside Arizona
and know an Arizona artist, it is almost certainly Scholder.
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s and '70s, his brash, brilliant Pop icons of American
Indians redefined a sleepy genre. Frothy with color and acidic with
irony, they were among the first paintings to look at modern Indian
life without the distorting gloss of sentimentality. Scholder's
Indians were not noble savages, but guys in Stetsons swigging Coors
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the succeeding years, Scholder's paintings lost
something of their energy. The painter, wandering from subject to
subject, never seemed to regain his vision. The paintings lost the
sure-footedness of their color, and the iconic nature of their
composition _ a single figure on a flat, colored background _
seemed more and more to become mere formula.
</P>
<P>
   Scholder seemed to be going through the motions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there was still something churning inside him, frustrated
to get out.
</P>
<P>
   There were those who complained that Scholder had been seduced
by success and money, that he was just production-lining paintings
to pay the rent. Yet, if that had been so, he would certainly have
continued painting Indians, like so many lesser lights, repeating
themselves endlessly for a comfortable living.
</P>
<P>
   But Scholder didn't do that: He followed his demons, taking up
first one subject and then another. There were mystery women, demon
lovers, martyrs, Liliths and conjurers. Occasionally, there was a
landscape. He left behind his bread and butter and took up Egyptian
subjects, fetish items, skulls. He tried sculpture, lithographs,
even, briefly, jewelry. In recent years he has been attracted to
bookmaking.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear he was doing what he felt compelled to do,
following his muse rather than his bankbook. Yet the results were
not always completely satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is simply that Scholder has never been a
good editor of his own work. He doesn't seem to know the difference
between what is worth saving and what is worth trashing. As a
result, his shows have seemed unfocused and overloaded with weak
work. But that is a minor issue, in the long run. The &UR; real problem
is only now coming clear.
</P>
<P>
   The two new shows at the Scottsdale Center for the Arts are
breakthrough shows for Scholder. As if a foundering man has begun
to find himself at last.
</P>
<P>
   And the show makes clear both Scholder and his public have
misunderstood his essential nature.
</P>
<P>
   His landmark work from the '70s was Pop in sensibility. The time
was right and his bright canvases had the necessary pizazz. But
Scholder's sensibility was a poor fit for Pop, which is all style
and little substance.
</P>
<P>
   Scholder never really fit in as a Pop artist, even though his
mentor was Wayne Thiebaud, the master of the thickly painted pie
slice and ice-cream sundae.
</P>
<P>
   And for the past decade or so, thrashing his way through a host
of familiar demonry, he has seen himself as a latter-day symbolist.
His paintings were filled with serpents and skulls, crucifixions
and dream imagery. Yet, although Scholder was attached to the
symbols, he seldom seemed to break through to what looms behind the
symbols, playing with the alphabet rather than writing words and
sentences. The symbolism was no more his true nature than the Pop.
He was still on the surface. He was driving himself, but in the
wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   The new shows both seem as if a light has been turned on.
Scholder's better angels are awakened; his demons cast off.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have discovered that his allegiance as an artist
isn't to art, but to life. That his experience is more meaningful
than the products of his talent. There is a directness to the new
work that has eluded him for decades.
</P>
<P>
   And a connectedness.
</P>
<P>
   The two shows are quite different. ``The Chapel for the End of
the Century'' is an installation in the form of a church. The
gallery has been reshaped into the form of a Christian cross, with
nave, apse, crossing and transept.
</P>
<P>
   The central axis of the chapel is occupied by three pieces of
sculpture. In the nave is a Minimalist block of metal, brilliantly
lit so it glows. At the crossing is what Scholder calls ``The Last
Book,'' an obscure volume on a lectern, whose words are difficult
to make out. And finally, in the apse is a large bronze, titled
``Future Clone,'' which is a pathetic kind of angel, teetering on a
globe of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the transept are covered with collages, built out
of the detritus of 20th-century culture. They function as the
stained glass in this chapel. Each collage has a theme _ celebrity,
nature, money, war, artists, space exploration _ and together they
define our times.
</P>
<P>
   At the far ends of the transept are opposing discards. On the
south, a vitrine filled with fast-food packaging; on the north, a
Native American shield and buffalo skin. Is culture as disposable
as a paper drinking cup? And what have we lost?
</P>
<P>
   According to the imagery in the chapel, we have lost ourselves
in a tempest of effluvia, wasting our energies on trivia, all the
while missing somehow the central truths of our lives. The lesson
of Scholder's chapel is not an optimistic one.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings upstairs are different, but they also show the
artist going in a new direction. Instead of Pop, instead of
symbolism, he seems to have somehow been jerked back into reality.
He has reacted emotionally to the actuality of the world. And in
doing so, it is as if he has found himself for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The worse for us all, he has found the world at just the time
the world seems to be dwindling, gasping and dying. It is a
pessimistic vision Scholder presents, but it no longer seems merely
arty. It seems genuine, profound.
</P>
<P>
   The painting that greets the visitor first is a depressing
variation on Edward Hick's ``Peaceable Kingdom.'' In that famous
image, the lion and the lamb lie down together as, in the distance,
William Penn makes a treaty with the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   In Scholder's ``Heading Toward Extinction,'' the animals wander
off the edge of the unstretched canvas into an undefined fiery glow
that we must understand as their doom. In the corner, replacing
Penn, is a table full of drunks. One seems to fill the glass of an
Indian with firewater. They are drinking from hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Another painting, ``Sick Rhinoceros,'' owes its existence to
Steven Spielberg's ``Jurassic Park.'' Instead of Laura Dern and a
sick triceratops, it is a distraught woman and a dying rhino. Same
poses, but not some distant fictional dinosaur, but a real,
suffering, endangered animal.
</P>
<P>
   Scholder has found the right level: It is symbolic, but more
importantly, it is real.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is Scholder's reliance on Grand Guignol, and in its place,
genuine suffering. The garish faces of his Ensor-like ``Future
Faces'' might all be his own face in different masks. Yet, it is
not all depression and gloom. Scholder holds out the possibility of
grace. It is not much, but it is real.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is beauty, which is not mere prettiness to distract
us from the gloom, but the very real sense of awe at the splendor
of the universe. It can be found in the only three framed canvases
in the show: a trilogy that are the finest bits of painting
Scholder has done in years.
</P>
<P>
   They are three landscapes collectively titled ``End Time Land.''
The first is a seascape with a distant fire _ like those we have
seen from the burning oil wells of Kuwait, streams of smoke wafting
off into the sky and reflected in the water.
</P>
<P>
   The third is a twilight woods, with the similar glow in the
corner. The dark woods are equally menacing and comforting.
</P>
<P>
   But the second clinches it. It is simply a rock in a field. Like
an Indian medicine rock, it occupies its ground and demands our
attention as if it were the center of the galaxy. Oddly, a
similarly shaped shadow glowers on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the brooding mood, there is in these three
paintings a simple issue: They are basically hopeless, yet they
ring with the love we all have for the world.
</P>
<P>
   Transcendent beauty is one out Scholder offers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another, in two small paintings around the corner.
They are both titled ``Icon of Life,'' and they are pairs of
figures in the act of love. This is not some heavenly, disembodied
love, but the interlaced limbs and friction of lovers. The figures
are embedded in the gold leaf of an Orthodox icon, and like those,
make the figures seem holy.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, they are models of what has changed in Scholder.
Gone is the reliance on surface and unattached symbol. The artist
has given up on trying to be clever, even on trying to be a good
painter. All that counts is the experience of being alive, fully
felt, and fully expressed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
