<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-AIMEE-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WILLARD'S MOM PUSHES FOR AIMEE'S LAW
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 16 -- Gail Willard went from victim to lobbyist
Thursday, walking the halls of Congress in a bid to ensure states
don't release convicted murderers and rapists early.
</P>
<P>
   At a tear-filled press briefing, Willard recounted the horror of
learning that her daughter Aimee had been raped and murdered in
June 1996, only to grow more mortified when she learned that the
alleged killer had already been convicted of murder in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   A little less than two months before the murder trial of Arthur
Bomar begins, Mrs. Willard pushed Congress to pass a ``No Second
Chances'' bill, which its sponsors are calling ``Aimee's law.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bomar had not been given a second chance by Nevada in 1990,
Willard said, her daughter would have gone on to graduate from
George Mason University, where she starred on the lacrosse and
soccer teams. ``Aimee Willard would be alive, teaching, coaching,''
she said, adding, ``Those dreams will never be fulfilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., was already working on a bill
addressing prison releases when prosecutors charged Bomar with the
murder in 1997, and reports soon showed that Bomar had served just
11 years for murder and was paroled in 1990. The Willard case
``galvanized'' Salmon's staff to write ``Aimee's Law,'' an aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   The law would penalize states that release convicted murderers,
rapists or child molesters if they go on to commit another violent
crime. That state would forfeit up to $100,000 in federal funding
for crime fighting, payable to the victim or the family of the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in the Willard case, Pennsylvania would be able to tally
up the costs of investigating, prosecuting and jailing Bomar -- if
he is convicted -- and send the bill to the Department of Justice.
The attorney general would then dock that amount of federal funds
from Nevada, and send the money to Pennsylvania, reimbursing the
state and local police.
</P>
<P>
   The real incentive in ``Aimee's Law,'' Salmon said, was to prod
states into drafting policies that would not allow violent sex
offenders and murderers to go free. ``This provides both a carrot
and stick approach,'' he said, citing Department of Justice
statistics that the average time served for convicted rapists is
four years, nine months. Convicted child molesters serve an average
of two years, nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years, nine months?'' asked Luis Gonzalez, whose brother,
New Jersey police officer Ippolito ``Lee'' Gonzalez, was gunned
down in 1995 by freed murderer Robert ``Mudman'' Simon, an Upper
Darby native convicted of murdering his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are serving a life sentence of grief and lost loved one,''
Luis Gonzalez said. He mocked Pennsylvania's parole system for
calling Simon a ``model'' prisoner upon his release after serving
12 years for his girlfriend's murder. Within 11 weeks of his
parole, Simon, who is now on ``Death Row'' after pleading guilty,
had killed Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Civil liberties groups say the law goes too far because, they
believe, some criminals can be rehabilitated. But Salmon admitted
that he feels most violent criminals don't deserve a chance to be
rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Willard, Luis Gonzalez and other victims met with key House
Republican leaders to press for ``Aimee's Law.'' The bill, which
has been endorsed by Reps. Curt Weldon, R-Aston, and Jon Fox,
R-Abington, does not have any Democratic co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   In her lobbying efforts, Gail Willard said it is difficult to
retell Aimee's story, now to a national audience. ``(But) it needs
to be told over and over again,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
