<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTUNE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FORTUNE IS A RIVER': LEONARDO, MACHIAVELLI AND THEIR BIG DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fascinating, indeed the historically electrifying idea of
Roger Masters' ``Fortune Is a River'' is that Leonardo da Vinci and
Niccolo Machiavelli collaborated on a ``magnificent failure'' that
would have reshaped history, had their project been a success. The
audacious idea, to alter the course of the Arno River in order to
make Florence victorious in war and supreme in global commerce,
brought together the elements of genius for which each of Masters'
protagonists are known: Machiavelli's hard-headed, realistic
political vision and Leonardo's startling prescience as an
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niccolo and Leonardo tried to control both the flow of history
and the flow of the river by combining science, technology and
political power,'' Masters writes. ``To understand the
implications,'' he continues, ``imagine that the atomic bombs
dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki both failed to explode, leading
to a costly and prolonged invasion of Japan by American troops and
the abandonment of nuclear technology.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a marvelously provocative thesis that ought to generate
some discussion. Masters, the Nelson Rockefeller Professor of
Government at Dartmouth College and the author of several previous
historical volumes, makes some important conjectures along the way:
for example, that Leonardo may have been a Florentine spy at the
court of Florence's enemy Cesare Borgia, and that he and
Machiavelli probably met at the Borgia court at Imola in 1502 to
begin formulating their project.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the materials on the personal relationship between
Machiavelli and Leonardo, as Masters acknowledges, are scant. Only
one document specifically links them, and it had nothing to do with
the diversion of the Arno. It was a contract signed by Machiavelli
_ who was second chancellor of the Signoria, Florence's governing
council _ that specified the terms of Leonardo's commission to
paint a mural of the battle of Anghiari in the Great Council Hall
of the Palazzo Vecchio. (The work was never completed.)
</P>
<P>
   The elements of conjecture rob Masters of some authority. To
explain matters, moreover, he plunges fairly deeply into the
convoluted world of Florentine and Roman politics, which can be
slow going for those not absorbed by that subject. Still, whether
Leonardo was a spy or not, and whether he and Machiavelli were
friends or not, there is no doubt that the Arno project existed. It
came in the context of a long war between Florence and Pisa that
occupied the Florentine leadership and drained its treasury between
1494 and 1509.
</P>
<P>
   In 1503 and 1504, a long military campaign against Pisa having
failed, Florence embarked on a plan devised by Leonardo and
supported by Machiavelli to change the Arno's course. The military
objective was to deprive Pisa of water and thereby force the city
into submission. But Masters finds strong circumstantial evidence
that the idea, at least as it existed in the minds of Leonardo and
Machiavelli, was bolder than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diversion of the Arno was not an isolated military action
to defeat Pisa, but merely the first step in Leonardo's grandiose
plan to create a seaport for Florence,'' Masters writes. Indeed, he
finds that the Arno diversion plan links several other important
elements of the epoch, most notably the voyages of Amerigo Vespucci
to South America and Leonardo's conception of the Mona Lisa. The
South America journey, and the realization that the lands
discovered by Columbus were not part of Asia but a vast and
separate continent, stimulated Machiavelli's dream of making
Florence a major seaport.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mona Lisa, Masters speculates that its famous
iconography grew out of Leonardo's immersion in the Arno project.
``The background of `La Gioconda' has been described as a
surrealistic landscape, in part because it is seen from a point in
the sky, high above the ground,'' Masters notes. In fact, he
argues, the background resembles the bird's-eye views of the Tuscan
hills and mountains that Leonardo drew in preparation for the Arno
project.
</P>
<P>
   The actual Arno project takes up a relatively minor portion of
Masters' book, the rest of which is devoted to biographies of its
two main characters, an interpretation of their roles in history,
and descriptions of Renaissance politics in which both men were
enmeshed. Masters' description of the failed effort to divert the
Arno's flow is so succinct as to be a bit confusing on the
technical details. A modern-day chart would have been helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the concept behind the project is clear, and so are
Masters' interpretations of the project's influence on the
subsequent careers of both of his protagonists. Leonardo, he
argues, saw its failure as a lesson in the twin necessities of
money and influence, neither of which had been in sufficient supply
for the Arno diversion. His subsequent successes were built,
Masters maintains, on his skill in courting men of royal power.
</P>
<P>
   Machiavelli's response was, as Masters describes it, more
complex. For one thing, he turned to another of his favored ideas,
opposed by the Florentine nobility, that of a citizen army to wage
the war against Pisa, rather than relying on mercenaries and
implausibly gigantic projects. More generally, as he put it in his
subsequent masterpiece, ``The Prince,'' the successful state needed
to rely on ``good arms'' and ``good laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, there is a bit of conjecture in this interpretation, with
Masters perhaps overdrawing the importance of the Arno project on
Machiavelli's subsequent, remarkably up-and-down career.
Nonetheless, his description of that career, and his portrait of
Machiavelli as both genius and libertine, triumphant statesman and
humiliated intriguer, are among the most interesting passages of a
very interesting book.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FORTUNE IS A RIVER'
</P>
<P>
   By Roger D. Masters
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 278 pages. Free Press. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
