<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 17, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The high temperature in Phoenix, Ariz., soared to a
record-breaking 117 degrees Wednesday, eclipsing the old record of
114. Blistering heat will affect the Western states once again
Friday as high pressure from the surface up to 20,000 feet provides
subsiding air and ample sunshine. Temperatures will rise into the
100s in many areas. The exceptions will be near the Pacific
coastline, where sea breezes and low clouds will keep temperatures
in the 70s, and over the peaks of the southern Rockies where rising
air currents prompt scattered cooling thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Summery heat and mixed sun and clouds will continue in the
southern Plains. A few thunderstorms will develop in western parts
of Texas, Oklahoma, and Kansas during the afternoon. Late morning
sea breezes will lift sultry air into towering thunderheads near
the Texas coast.
</P>
<P>
   Warm air overrunning a stationary front from the central Dakotas
to Iowa will spawn several clusters of thunderstorms. Scattered
thunderstorms will also develop ahead of a series of cold fronts in
the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states. Some of the storms over
interior New York and New England may be severe, with damaging wind
gusts and hail. An upper-level disturbance will trigger tropical
downpours in the stagnant air from the Carolinas to the peninsula
of Florida while isolated showers develop in the seasonal heat over
the remainder of the Deep South. Meanwhile, bright sunshine and
comfortable humidity will accompany high pressure in the upper
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tsunami &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, an undersea earthquake in the central Pacific was
judged to be insufficiently strong to produce a tsunami. A tsunami,
a wave caused by a sudden shift in the ocean floor, is similar to
the storm surge of a hurricane. When a hurricane develops over the
open sea, there is little, if any, storm surge. As a hurricane
nears land, powerful winds push water toward shore which piles up
as the bottom becomes shallow. Tsunamis often possess great energy,
much of which moves swiftly below the surface. As it encounters a
shallow bottom the energy can be converted into monstrously high
waves.
</P>
</TEXT>
