 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, July 19, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACK&AMP;JILL-CLUBS (Undated) _ Jack and Jill is the venerable
social club for children of the black middle class. Founded 60
years ago in an era of inflexible segregation, it once organized
outings like children's swimming parties when public pools were
closed to blacks. During the 1960s and '70s, some blacks viewed
Jack and Jill as a relic as society became less segregated. But now
a new generation of parents who have settled in the suburbs worry
that their children are cut off from African-American roots. They
are making Jack and Jill fashionable again. By Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONE-OBSESSION (Undated) _ The pocket-sized accessories
have been a status symbol for years, of course, in the Hamptons and
other places, but this summer the usage and fascination with things
cellular has blossomed into an obsession. By
</P>
<P>
   GENDER-SCHISM (Undated) _ In 1998, an avalanche of books _ with
titles like ``What Men Don't Want Women to Know: The Secrets, The
Lies, The Unspoken Truths''; ``How to Heal the Hurt by Hating'' and
``How to Dump a Guy: A Coward's Manual'' _ have, beneath their
light-hearted, humorous veneers signalled a growing antipathy
between the sexes. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   COLLARD-OUT-PROFILE (New York) _ ``We need to stop worrying
about what's in and what's out, and start thinking about what we
like,` said James Collard, the new editor-in-chief of Out Magazine.
Interview. By David Colman.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-TRENDS (Undated) _ People complain that fashion moves too
quickly, but really it moves too slowly. This summer, a host of
style trends that should have come and gone as quickly as Madonna's
gold tooth are refusing to exit politely and make room for
whatever's next. It's a problem. Take the French blue dress shirt,
for instance. Gentlemen, it's time for a new look. By Frank DeCaro.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ There's something about the
perpendicular that does not love a lawn mower. No matter how
well-designed the machine, no mower can reach that last inch of
grass next to the garage, or the ring of turf immediately around
the trunk of the front-yard maple. Weed whackers, those noisy
contraptions that slash at the vegetation with a nylon string, were
invented for this reason. A more permanent and quieter solution is
an edging of plants. By Cass Peterson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
