<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     07-16 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: PRESENTS FOR CHILDREN, GOOD AND BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long before there was a Disney, there were
Staffordshire productions. Ceramics factories in Staffordshire,
England, began producing china just for children about 1790. The
ones showing idyllic scenes of perfect children at play _ riding,
fishing, rolling hoops or skipping rope _ were probably directed
toward adoring parents, but most of the production was directed
toward the children themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As Noel Riley explains in her 1991 book, ``Gifts for Good
Children,'' in the early 19th century, ``for the first time
children came into their own as a marketing target.'' She examined
nearly 1,700 examples of this china, made between 1790 and 1890,
mostly from the collection of the dealer Richard Dennis of
Somerset, England, ``to study a popular but relatively uncharted
area of ceramic history.'' In the book, published by Dennis, she
concludes that more than 60 English factories made children's china
in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, cups inscribed with children's names have been
christening presents for centuries, and the antique ones are still
popular gifts. But such mugs were often made of precious materials,
like silver or porcelain, so they were expensive. Most children's
china is made of glazed earthenware.
</P>
<P>
   There was china for every kind of child. Some items were for
goody-goodies: rewards for good behavior. They say things like
``Present for William,'' ``For a Good Girl'' and ``Present for
Being Good in Church.'' The James II Galleries at 11 E. 57th St.,
Manhattan, have a large selection of children's ware, including a
mug with the inscription ``A Present for My Dear Girl'' for $600.
</P>
<P>
   Other plates were for baddies. ``I have plates that portray
quarrelsome children and cruel children,'' said Mo Wajselfish, the
owner of Leatherwood Antiques in Sandwich, Mass., a private dealer
who has what may be the largest stock of antique British children's
wares in America, including the ``Present for William'' mug, circa
1840, for $650. ``One shows a boy torturing a cat. Sometimes you
see bizarre situations on the plates.''
</P>
<P>
   Other dishes capture entertainments that appealed to children:
accordion players, the circus, dog races, and Punch and Judy puppet
shows. Sheila Chefetz, owner of the Country Dining Room Antiques in
Great Barrington, Mass., has an early-19th-century plate ($245)
called ``The Young Charioteer'' that shows a little boy driving a
go-cart pulled by miniature horses. Behind him sits a little girl
carrying a parasol.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items made fun of adults, probably making them
popular with children. One plate in Ms. Riley's book shows an
outrageously dressed dandy trying to impress a lady; its caption
reads, ``Who binds himself till almost dead/And with a wig adorns
his head/And looks like a complete Blockhead/The Dandy.'' There
were also riddles, nursery rhymes and caricatures, all meant for
the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Other plates were intended to edify. Using transfer prints, the
factories represented the flora and fauna, even exotic animals,
designers thought children should know. Clock faces teach time.
Alphabet wares teach the ABC's. In the Riley book, a young man
standing next to the letter Y is shown on one mug, which reads, ``Y
is a youth, who has many kind friends.'' Another mug says, ``Q _
The Queen: God Bless Her.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite copyright laws, engravers at the potteries would
brazenly steal designs from books, magazines and popular prints.
Benjamin Franklin's maxims from ``Poor Richard's Almanack''
(1732-1758) were extremely popular. ``Diligence is the mother of
good luck'' graces a plate with a fat farmer next to his cow and
sheep. ``Experience keeps a dear school, but fools will learn in no
other'' shows a man in front of the village stocks. Leatherwood
Antiques is selling a plate ($385) with a Franklin maxim, ``Employ
thy time well if thou meanest to gain leisure,'' and two foppishly
dressed boys flying kites.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether children's plates were meant to be used
or merely displayed. As Letitia Roberts, Sotheby's porcelain
expert, said, ``In the 18th century, children were dressed as
little adults, so why wouldn't they eat like them?'' The plates,
she said, ``were employed to teach children good manners.''
</P>
<P>
   Wajselfish says the wares were expensive decorations, and they
WERE expensive until the pieces were mass produced at the end of
the 19th century. The early dishes depict the well-to-do at
leisure, and the humor reflects more a Jane Austen than a Charles
Dickens sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Wajselfish has been selling children's creamware, bright yellow
canary ware and lustrous pearlware from England for 15 years at
antiques shows. (The next one is the Nantucket Historical
Association show, Aug. 6-9.) ``I grew up in England, and the humor
and charm of this china always got to me,'' he recalled. ``When I
first started selling it, no one paid attention. Only in the past
five years have prices gone up, because the pottery is getting
rare. You can spend between $400 and $800 for a single cup now.''
</P>
<P>
   Who collects? Julie Seymour of James II said, ``Our customers
are children, young adults and adults who think young.''
</P>
<P>
   Many potteries did not stamp their names on children's china.
``Some of the well-known makers, like Davenport and Minton,
produced and marked their children's china,'' Wajselfish said.
``But small local manufacturers made most of it, and their
anonymous workshops usually lasted only 10 to 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wajselfish, ``what's important is the subject, not the
mark,'' he said. ``You have to buy what you relate to.'' He said he
was moved by intimate scenes of family life. When he bought a plate
reading, ``From an affectionate father,'' he said, he almost cried,
thinking about his own father. He is now selling an octagonal plate
for $350 that depicts a young girl holding a ladder that her
brother has just climbed. It reads: ``When up the ladder I would
go, how wrong it was I now well know. Who cried but held it fast
below: My sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Edith Wolf, the owner of the Bardith Ltd. antique-china shop,
901 Madison Ave. at 72nd Street, pointed out that French and German
factories also produced children's wares. In addition to her large
stock of English children's china, she has, from France, four
late-19th-century plates made by the Digoin &AMP; Sarregulmines factory
in Lorraine ($900 for the set), and a set of hand-colored plates
from Creil, north of Paris (four for $2,500).
</P>
<P>
   She also has an unusual Sowerby &AMP; Co. white pressed-glass beaker
made in England, circa 1850, that has a humorous bas relief, hand
painted in bright colors, that follows the activities of a young
redhead as he hopelessly attempts to do his lessons. It is $750.
</P>
<P>
   Second Childhood, a store at 283 Bleecker St., near Seventh
Avenue, in Greenwich Village, occasionally carries a few pieces and
currently has two German plates, made by Blenheim in 1910, for $22
each.
</P>
<P>
   Long before ``Ozzie and Harriet,'' British factories produced
plates with didactic themes and perfectly scrubbed children. Or at
least these are the plates that have come down to us. As Ms. Riley
writes, the survival of so many ``goody-goody plates may be because
they were simply less popular with children, and therefore less
used and broken, than rhymes and nursery stories that were fun
rather than moralistic.'' Either that, or goody-goodies don't drop
plates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
