<HEADLINE>
`SOMETHING ABOUT MARY' HAS HIGH HIGHS, TOO MANY LOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Of course there's something about Mary. She's played
by Cameron Diaz, who is such a knockout she could fog your glasses
even if you're not wearing any.
</P>
<P>
   There's also something crazy about ``There's Something About
Mary'': It's like the Three Stooges doing a sex comedy. Only in
this case, the Stooges aren't the performers but the directors, the
Farrelly brothers, Peter and Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   They've created six scenes of the most outrageous comedy since
their last movies: ``Dumb and Dumber'' and ``Kingpin.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, those wild moments are embedded in a huge waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the Farrellys thought up these six great scenes, then
ran out of comic material and said, ``That's enough. Let's just use
hamburger filler for the rest of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary, played with lovely fireworks by Cameron Diaz, is the girl
all the guys can't help falling in love with.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with Ted (Ben Stiller), who falls for Mary in high
school when he's a desperate loser.
</P>
<P>
   Then 13 years later, Ted wakes up, still a desperate loser,
realizes he's never gotten over Mary and hires a sleazy private eye
(Matt Dillon) to find her again.
</P>
<P>
   The detective also falls for Mary and uses everything he's
learned from spying on her to romance her.
</P>
<P>
   When Ted plunges back into the chase, we learn that there's
plenty of competition in the fixated-on-Mary race.
</P>
<P>
   You really can't blame them: Mary's the all-American guy's girl:
she wants nothing more than a man who loves sports, hot dogs, beer
and a woman with a tendency to get dressed in front of open
windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' has a strange comic rhythm. If
it were a roller coaster, you'd fly over this huge cliff screaming
your head off, then creep along a flat stretch for about 15 minutes
of snooze time before the next thrill.
</P>
<P>
   But those big scenes, they're wild. If you love those
I-can't-believe-they-did-that comic moments, the ones that offend
most civilized people, this movie has them.
</P>
<P>
   The Farrellys explore the realm of humiliating dates and come up
with some all-time embarrassments. They're enough to make you
change your entire wardrobe from zippers to Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   When the Farrellys get onto a gag, they don't know when to stop.
They just keep heaping on the gross, embarrassing nuttiness until
you're either howling or ready to walk out, more offended than you
thought a comedy could make you feel.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, as the object of adoration, is a delight. When she walks
across the screen, you wonder why they don't devote an entire movie
to that subject.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stiller nor Dillon add much to the fun. The big scenes
are funny because of their outrageous content, not because they're
played funny by the stars.
</P>
<P>
   You don't realize how bland Stiller and Dillon are until a
non-actor sports star drops in for a cameo with all the impact of
flat beer, and you realize that he's doing exactly what the pros
are doing: nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller (''Flirting With Disaster)'' has a comic range that
shifts slightly from embarrassment to humiliation, which fits some
scenes. But his comic bits prove useless in livening up the film
when the Farrellys run short of material.
</P>
<P>
   You begin to be diverted by such thoughts as: is Stiller wearing
prosthetic ears? And why is he trying to impersonate a 10-year-old
boy?
</P>
<P>
   Dillon has a few good scenes as a sleazy jerk, but he's not
nearly as funny as he was in ``The Flamingo Kid'' or ``In &AMP; Out.''
</P>
<P>
   If the kind of offensive comedy the Farrelly's created in ``Dumb
</P>
<P>
   and Dumber'' cracks you up, then you'll love the big scenes in
``There's Something About Mary'' and forgive the rest. But you
could go out of the theater in between those big scenes, make a
couple phone calls and not miss anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' is rated R for profanity,
nudity and sex. 3 stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
