<HEADLINE>
ABC FOLLOWS FOX'S LEAD WITH `MAXIMUM BOB' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Six months ago at this semiannual gathering
of TV critics and TV programmers, ABC said it would introduce a
new, original series this summer, a tactic the Fox network has had
some success with. The keystone of ABC's effort is ``Maximum Bob,''
a one-hour drama about a flamboyant Florida judge, adapted from the
Elmore Leonard novel. It premieres Aug. 4 in the ``NYPD Blue''
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Beau Bridges is Maximum Bob Gibbs, who meets his match in a
feisty public defender played by Liz Vassey. Early consensus at the
fall-season press tour in Pasadena is that the bizarre and funny
``Maximum Bob'' is as good as anything ABC has on its fall
schedule, yet ``Bob'' right now is just a seven-episode series that
will end with the network's fall rollout.
</P>
<P>
   ABC says ``Bob'' will return as a midseason substitute if
audiences like it, but Bridges is philosophical about the show's
short season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago not to have any expectations as far
as longevity goes in a television series,'' he said, ``because
after the actors have done their best, there's really nothing we
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridges said being in the ``NYPD Blue'' time slot for seven
weeks in a row is an enviable launch position in any season, given
the realities of the TV business.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what time of the year you go on,'' he said, ``you've
only got four or five shows to catch people's attention. If you
don't do it by then, you're going to be off anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the less stultifying schedules unveiled so far in
Pasadena belongs to VH1, the older-skewing spinoff of MTV. Starting
with ``Rock &AMP; Roll Jeopardy!'' (premiering Aug. 8), VH1 will unveil
six new fall-season series that follow on the success of quirky
hits like ``Pop-Up Video.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock &AMP; Roll Jeopardy!'' is fairly straightforward: The format
is the same as ``Jeopardy!'' but all the categories relate to rock
music in some way, and Alex Trebek stays home. Jeff Probst, a
correspondent for ``Access Hollywood,'' is the host.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vinyl Justice,'' meanwhile, is highly goofy, with two actors
(Barry Sobel and Wayne Brady) posing as ``music police.'' For
example, they write up one person for playing hip hop in a Volvo.
Another regular segment features ``investigations'' of celebrities'
CD collections.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Rock of Ages,'' which shows diverse groups of
people watching videos and offering opinions on musical styles and
on even weightier matters, such as whether the members of Hanson
are male or female.
</P>
<P>
   The other three new shows are ``Video Timeline,'' looking at the
careers of music's big names chronologically through their videos;
``Viva Le Rock,'' a satirical newsmagazine exploring the outrageous
side of the music business, and ``Where Are They Now?'' an hourlong
show that perpetuates the cachet of four ``Where Are They Now?''
specials that have already aired. Upcoming topics: girl bands, bad
boys of rock, and winners of the Grammy for best new artist.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise! ABC executives Stu Bloomberg and Jamie Tarses are
bullish on this fall's lineup, which includes five new comedies and
three new dramas.
</P>
<P>
   But Bloomberg, chairman of ABC Entertainment, deserves a little
credit for facing facts, the scariest being ABC's dismal showing
last season among viewers in the 18-to-49 age group, the most
highly prized by advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research has armed me with so much ammunition that I could
probably convince you that last season was a brilliant season,''
Bloomberg said. ``We still won four out of seven nights, we had
seven out of the top 20 series, we won 32 percent of all
half-hours, and our demographics were broader than the other
networks and were spread across the entire week and not just one
night.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all true, which demonstrates how good the networks are at
massaging numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you guys know the other truths,'' Bloomberg said. ``We
played `Home Improvement' to death and weakened Tuesday night, we
had critically acclaimed but viewer-challenged dramas, `TGIF'
(Friday programming) relied too heavily on gimmick-oriented
concepts, and our movies failed to reach the right audience and,
some might say, any audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg and Tarses, president of ABC Entertainment, said ABC's
goal this season is to deliver ``smart, urban, fresh, funny and
inclusive'' shows. Perhaps mindful of criticism that ABC mistreated
quality shows like ``Nothing Sacred'' and ``Cracker'' last season,
Tarses said the network will make it easier to find shows, and that
it will program with greater ``consistency and clarity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
