<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NET': BASED ON THE MOVIE, BUT WANTING TO BE `THE X-FILES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angela Bennett, a young, beautiful and reclusive (``I keep to
myself'') free-lance programmer, gets a weird e-mail message about
something called Copper Canyon. She shrugs it off and goes for her
daily run, but when she stops at an ATM, the screen tells her that
her account is closed. A carful of FBI agents promptly arrest her,
believing that she is a criminal named Elizabeth Marx.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as we see, while Angela (Brooke Langton, formerly of
``Melrose Place'') was innocently jogging past the Seattle skyline,
someone was changing all computerized records of her past so that
Angela no longer exists and Angela herself appears to be Liz.
</P>
<P>
   A National Security Agency operative (Joseph Bottoms), oozing
charm, offers to help but turns out to be a fraud. He's soon
standing in her living room, pointing a gun and shouting: ``NSA,
FBI, CIA! They all have too many boundaries, Angela. What we do is
more important, more practical. Give me my e-mail!''
</P>
<P>
   All of this happens in the first half-hour of the premiere of
``The Net'' (Sunday night at 9), USA's new hourlong drama series
based on the 1995 Sandra Bullock film of the same name. But once
the computerized identity changing is done (before the first
commercial), ``The Net'' wants to be something else entirely: ``The
X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to everything, you see, is a mysterious 1984 confab at
Copper Canyon attended by ``the military, philosophers,
theologians, chaos theorists'' and, wouldn't you know it, Angela's
long-lost father. She finds his file in a huge room lined with
cardboard boxes. Meanwhile, her new traveling companion, a
scientist who attended the 1984 meeting, finds evidence that proves
the space shuttle Challenger explosion and other disasters were
planned and carried out by an evil secret agency. When Angela needs
confirmation or just emotional support, she talks to an anonymous
character named Sorceror (the voice of Tim Curry) via her laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Langton seems to be a good enough actress, but she doesn't
have the lovable vulnerability that Ms. Bullock, at her
post-``Speed'' peak, brought to the movie role. And Ms. Langton
doesn't exude the sexy spookiness of David Duchovny as Fox Mulder,
the character who is clearly Angela's male counterpart. The show
itself is inoffensive if a little obvious and could go either way.
</P>
<P>
   The oddest thing is that just when you're expecting a guest
appearance by the Cigarette-Smoking Man, Sorceror's disembodied
voice says ``Stay out of it, Angel'' and Farrah Fawcett, Kate
Jackson and Jaclyn Smith in their '70s prime come to mind. It's
probably just a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE NET'
</P>
<P>
   9 and 11 p.m. Sunday on USA Network
</P>
<P>
   A Columbia Tristar Television production, Irwin Winkler, Rob
Cowan, Patrick Hasburgh and Deborah Pratt, executive producers.
Based on the film ``The Net,'' directed by Winkler and produced by
Cowan and Winkler.
</P>
<P>
   With: Brooke Langton (Angela Bennett), Joseph Bottoms
(Trelawney), Mackenzie Gray (Hearney), Kelli Taylor (Anna Kelly)
and Tim Curry (Sorcerer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8728 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BUFFALO-SPI &LR;      07-16 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BUFFALO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODD `BUFFALO 66 MIXES FANTASY AND REALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66'' is named after the Buffalo Bills football team
and the year in which the story's hero was born.
</P>
<P>
   Written by actor Vincent Gallo, who also directs and stars, the
film is about Billy Brown (Gallo), a poor schlub who harbors a
grudge against former Bills' place kicker Scott Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Billy believes Woods wrecked his life by throwing a big game,
causing him to lose a fortune to the local hoods. The only way he
can repay the debt is to take the fall for one of the gang's thugs,
and he goes to prison for a crime he never committed. After Billy
is let out of jail, he returns home to Buffalo to even the score
against those who wrecked his life and his big chance at being the
best bowler in town.
</P>
<P>
   The film features a tender supporting performance by Christina
Ricci as Layla, the young tap dance student Billy clumsily kidnaps
to act as his wife on his homecoming visit to his negligent
parents, played with a scary ferocity and humor by Ben Gazzara and
Anjelica Huston.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's folks embrace Layla as the daughter they never had,
pouring her a glass of wine, stuffing her full of tripe stew, and
telling her they love her. But they ignore Billy, looking at their
son as if he were a stranger, and indeed, he's lied to them for
five years, telling them he's been on a covert mission for the CIA
instead of wasting away in a prison cell.
</P>
<P>
   This odd film _ which won raves at Sundance and played the
recent Seattle International Film Festival _ is full of surprises,
some good, some not so believeable.
</P>
<P>
   It's sadly funny as well as whimsical in spite of its backdrop
of potentially abrasive _ and highly abusive _ situations. It's a
strange mix of gritty realism and fantasy stirred together into an
unusual love story that thankfully only flirts, and then flees,
from violence. It's about missed opportunity, shattered dreams and
trying to make a mark in a world that barely knows you're alive.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, who has played the loser role before in a number of indie
movies like ``Palookaville,'' is surprisingly endearing as Billy,
especially since the character is so critical and judgmental of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Writer/director Gallo's intentions are clearly noble in this
offbeat romance about loving in spite of past scars, but he can't
fully pull his ambitious subtext from beneath the quirkiness. In
the end, ``Buffalo 66'' parallels Billy's story by not fulfilling
its potential.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo 66. Directed and written by Vincent Gallo. Cast: Gallo,
Christina Ricci, Anjelica Huston, Ben Gazzara. Lions Gate Films.
110 minutes. Rated R for nudity, language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
