<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8733 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV23-     07-16 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMOST EVERYTHING WAS THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday July 23)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every summer I can remember, I've spent the Fourth of July at my
grandmother's farmhouse in West Virginia, eating homemade banana
ice cream, watching the parade, picking blackberries and counting
fireflies from the porch.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, my children and I flew to West Virginia to carry on
the tradition. But it's no longer my grandmother's farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   It's ours.
</P>
<P>
   Before my grandmother died in September, she deeded the
homestead to my mother, who promptly transferred it to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to keep it in the family for the children
anyway,'' says my ever-practical mother, who was born and raised on
the farm and has always been amused by my romantic attachment to
the place.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother and I had exactly one conversation about this
before it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big responsibility,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as we pull up the gravel driveway, I look at the rutted
ditches holding water, the peeling paint, the fence that needs
mending and the overgrown garden.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I are in the midst of a move ourselves. With jobs
in transition and our children's college funds in their embryonic
form, we're not in any financial position to take on another home _
however sentimental its value.
</P>
<P>
   But the farm has long been my bedrock, especially during times
of chaos, and just the sight of it reassures me. The red porch
swing, the old crib stacked with firewood, and the stone walkway to
the elm tree are my indicators that all is right with the world.
</P>
<P>
   After four hours spent in airports and on planes, I was ready
for some serenity. Adam and Sarah tumble out of the car, eager to
explore, and I sink onto the familiar couch in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, where we had so many meals of fresh garden corn,
chicken and dumplings, and apple butter on toast. In the pink,
flowered bedroom upstairs, where her necklaces, scarves and old
purses wait for Sarah to play dress-up. And in the cabinet beside
the living room fireplace, where grandma's 1926 high school
yearbook shows that she was its editor. We spend the week much as I
spent my childhood vacations _ watching the holiday fireworks from
rag rugs on a hill side, sitting on hay bales at an auction, buying
a take-home quart at the church ice-cream social.
</P>
<P>
   And we visit grandmother's grave, bringing her Black-eyed Susans
and Queen Anne's lace.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial bouquets already fill the concrete vases, so Adam
places the flowers on top of the headstone. I read aloud the names
and dates engraved in the marble _ Hobart D. Crum, 1897-1979, and
Freda Sayre Crum, 1904-1997.
</P>
<P>
   During last year's visit, grandma had been disappointed that I
hadn't brought my daughter, who was home with the flu. Grandma had
held Sarah the year before, a smiling baby just starting to hold
her head up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the fading light, Sarah plays with her brother in the
pasture behind the cemetery. As we leave, she turns to wave not at
the graves, but at the empty, rolling field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bye-bye, Grandma Freda,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not prone to fanciful thoughts about spirits roaming the
earth, playing guardian angel to loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   But, at that moment, I am almost certain that grandmother is
there, waving back.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer for The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
