A8744 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRIME17-COX     07-16 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL PROPOSES LIFE SENTENCE FOR RAPISTS; DEATH FOR MURDERERS
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mika Moulton displayed a picture of her 10-year-old
son, Christopher Meyer. Blond hair, a radiant smile, and youthful
innocence caught in a photograph taken just three weeks before he
was abducted.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days after his disappearance from a neighborhood park in
Illinois on Aug. 7, 1995, her murdered son's body _ stabbed 53
times _ was found.
</P>
<P>
   She showed a second snapshot: his grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Bundy, John Wayne Gacy and Jeffrey Dahmer are all safe
because they're dead,'' Moulton said, referring to some of the most
notorious murderers of recent history. ``When you have your first
chance, and you mess up, you shouldn't get a second one.''
</P>
<P>
   Moulton joined others whose lives have been touched by vicious
crimes at a news conference Thursday to support a bill calling for
mandatory life sentence without parole for rapists and child
molesters and the death penalty for first-degree murderers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pass this bill, we will literally save lives,'' said
Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., the bill's sponsor. ``We owe it to every
American to do nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which Salmon said will be formally introduced next
week, has attracted 22 co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Among those participating in the news conference were Marc
Klaas, father of Polly Klaas, who was abducted from her California
home during a slumber party, and Fred Goldman, father of Ron
Goldman, who stabbed to death along with Nicole Simpson, the wife
of O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Klaas, whose 12-year-old daughter was killed by a Richard Allen
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a career criminal now on death row, said it was ``time to
put our foot down.'' He also said states should be responsible for
paying restitution to victims of paroled criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would make states financially responsible for
restitution if previously released or escaped murderers, rapists,
and child molesters commit similar crimes again. It would provide
$100,000 to the victims of the subsequent attack.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where a rapist or murderer from one state commits a
similar crime in another state, the first state would reimburse the
other state's cost of apprehension, prosecution and incarceration
of the criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon released statistics from the Bureau of Justice Statistics
indicating that the average time served in prison for rapists was 4
years, 9 months and the average time served by murderers was 5
years, 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
