<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBAL-WARMING-KAN &LR;      07-16 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-WARMING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER STATISTICS POINT TO GLOBAL WARMING, SOME EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: At least 25 Texans died in record heat this month.
Flash floods swamped 123 Tennessee homes. And forest fires obscured
the July 4 skies over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Is global warming for real, after all?
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore says so, basing his conclusion this week
on the latest federal weather data that showed that this June was
the warmest June on record.
</P>
<P>
   Data from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
revealed that each of the first six months of this year set new
monthly records for global temperatures, measured at the surface.
</P>
<P>
   This follows last year's data that showed the entire year of
1997 was the warmest on record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latest data showing this June was the warmest month on
record provide more evidence that global warming is real,'' Gore
said at a news conference in Washington. ``And disasters around the
country, like the devastating fires in Florida, show just how
vulnerable we are to extreme weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and other Democrats called Wednesday for more
``common-sense'' strategies to protect future Americans from the
impacts of global climate change.
</P>
<P>
   But others scoff at assertions that the recent weather extremes
are connected to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The World Climate Report, edited by Patrick Michaels, a
University of Virginia climate expert who has expressed skepticism
of global warming, noted in this month's edition that early
explorers marveled at the Florida wildfires _ and that was during
an especially cool period on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the first time that Gore has invoked bathos in
support of his agenda even though his science was completely
wrong,'' the editorial stated. ``Last year, he conflated the North
Dakota flood with global warming, which was actually caused by
excessive snowfall that would be reduced as it warms there.''
</P>
<P>
   As a basis for his position as a global warming-skeptic,
Michaels relies, in part, on satellite temperatures, rather than
surface temperatures. He said those satellite readings show no
dramatic rise in temperature.
</P>
<P>
   But such rhetoric frustrates Daniel Lashof, senior scientist at
the Natural Resources Defense Council, a national environmental
group that supports curbs on the nation's greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Lashof discounted looking at satellite temperatures when there
are only about 20 years of data, pointing out that scientists have
more than 100 years of surface temperature data.
</P>
<P>
   That larger set of data is also more reliable because satellite
technology has changed over the years, while the technique of
reading a temperature at the ground has remained pretty much the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more frustrating, Lashof said, is that the data just
continue to mount _ month after month, year after year, but people
still doubt that global warming is occurring.
</P>
<P>
   To Lashof, it's clear that the planet is getting warmer.
</P>
<P>
   The information from this year``strongly reinforces the
conclusion that global warming is under way,'' Lashof said in an
interview Wednesday. ``What's surprising about the data is that
each individual month sets a record for that month.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it sets it by a considerable margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Among many scientists, it's generally accepted that the globe's
climate is being changed by man's release of millions of tons of
carbon and other greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   A November 1997 report by climate expert Jerry Mahlman in the
journal Science stated that it's now ``virtually certain'' that man
has induced a warming of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   What's not certain is the impact of that warming. How much will
the temperatures rise and what regions will be affected the most?
And how will variables that scientists can't yet calculate _ such
as increased cloudiness _ alter the impact?
</P>
<P>
   Currently, it's likely that a warming of 2 to 8 degrees
Fahrenheit will occur, Mahlman predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's not exactly sound science to point to recent weather
extremes as evidence of global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas heat wave, Lashof said, ``is an example of the kind of
problem that is predicted from global warming and the kind of event
we might expect to occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't point to a specific event and say that is proof
of global warming.''
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that there have been quite a few of those
extremes of late.
</P>
<P>
   The current drought in the southern and southeastern United
States, which began in March, is the driest April-June period for
Florida, Louisiana, New Mexico and Texas since record keeping began
in these states more than 100 years ago, said David Easterling of
the National Climatic Data Center in Asheville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   And although it's supposed to be hot in Texas and Florida in
June, it's not normally this hot. In Amarillo, the temperature
topped 100 for 13 days. In Melbourne, Fla., it was above 95 for 24
days.
</P>
<P>
   Such long, hot spells normally have little probability of
occurring. The Amarillo heat wave, for example, would normally
recur only once every 1,000 years, according to the national
climate data center.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the national center's new models of the impacts of
global warming on the United States show that it might soon occur
once every six years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, while some are broiling others are benefiting.
</P>
<P>
   New England enjoyed one of the wettest Junes on record. In the
Midwest, this June was the second wettest. The wettest was in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Across the globe, land and ocean temperatures also reached an
all-time high in June, the climate data center reported.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures averaged more than 1 degree Fahrenheit above the
average recorded temperature since 1880. The highs were more
evident over land, nearly 2 degrees above average.
</P>
<P>
   This June record also came despite the recent demise of El Nino.
As it has subsided, temperatures in the Central Pacific dropped.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect July to bring much relief _ it is expected to
become the seventh month in a row to become the hottest on record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite possible,'' Lashof said. ``And normally July is the
hottest month of the year, which means it could be the hottest
month of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's quite possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1757EDT &QL; 
