A8748 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-16 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS STUCK IN THE SLICES OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Do you feel like a slice of bologna?
</P>
<P>
   Many workers are learning what it feels like to be in the
sandwich generation. They are sandwiched between caring for aging
parents and not-yet-out-of-the-home children.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, then, that a new study by the nonpartisan business
research organization, The Conference Board, finds that sandwichers
are suffering financially and emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it surprising that their employers are incurring
productivity losses because of sandwich-related work intrusions,
particularly absences. Deborah Parkinson, a Conference Board
research associate, put such losses at $11.4 billion a year. That's
a big but fairly meaningless number, unless you're in the sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   There's no simple way to cope simultaneously with 16-year-olds
and 86-year-olds, college tuition and nursing home fees. But the
study identifies one thing as ``the most valuable corporate program
to help employees deal with their dependent-care needs'' _
flextime.
</P>
<P>
   Flexible hours let employees juggle their work time. With
flextime, sandwichers can respond to family needs without
sacrificing time on the job or income. Surveys repeatedly list
flextime among top ways to retain good workers and among benefits
that employees most desire.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, boomers have entered the ranks of parenthood
and clamored for child-care help from employers. Most didn't get
much help, except for referrals to metropolitan child-care
resources. Now the same employers are being asked to provide
elder-care assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, referrals to outside resources are a beginning, but
probably not enough. Sandwichers say they also need dependent-care
accounts, access to elder-care seminars and counseling, and
long-term insurance that will help pay for the health and
residential needs of ill and aging parents.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons why many employers never provided child-care
assistance was that it was an expensive benefit that a relatively
small percentage of workers needed at any one time. So far, that
may be true of elder-care help, but demographics portend growing
demand.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans over age 65 will jump from 34 million in
1995 to 62 million by 2025, the report says. Fortunately, Americans
are living longer in better health, so it's not a given that
workers with aging parents are going to be making daily calls to
the nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're not already a sandwicher, it's a good bet you work
near someone who is. Whether you live it or observe it, it's clear
that caring for the needs of aging parents is a different kind of
stress from caring for your children. For one thing, you're never
as prepared. And, quite often, the learning curve is crammed into a
crisis time frame.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the reason why the new child- and elder-care
initiatives under way at several Kansas City area workplaces are
worth noting. These employers know they'll get better workers when
those employees have information and resources to help them deal
with family needs.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' investments mean that thousands of Kansas City
area workers are going to be in a more comfortable sandwich. It may
mean the difference between feeling like a slice of bologna and a
cut of Kansas City steak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8749 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-ITHINK-REVIEW-K     07-16 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ITHINK-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROMANTIC COMEDY IS AMUSING BUT ULTIMATELY SUPERFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I Think I Do,'' a comedy, is unrated. It contains some mild
language and sexual themes. Running time is 1 hour 40 minutes. Two
and a half out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   A retooled ``Big Chill'' with gay overtones, ``I Think I Do'' is
an often-amusing romantic comedy that never rises above the level
of pleasant trifle.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Sloan's film begins in the early '90s at George Washington
University, where a group of men and women has been partying
heartily. In scenes encompassing several holiday gatherings during
their senior year, we meet the characters.
</P>
<P>
   Principle among them is Bob (Alexis Arquette), who knows he's
gay but hasn't really done much about it. Problem is, he's in love
with his roommate, Brendan (Christian Maelen), who very well may be
gay but certainly hasn't faced the issue. When the desperate Bob
finally makes his move, he's shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile there's a regular round robin of sexual high jinks
going on. There's a womanizing party boy (Guillermo Diaz), a couple
of gal pals who are romantic rivals for the available men (Marianne
Hagen, Maddie Corman), and monogamous longtime steadies Carol and
Matt (Lauren Velez and Jamie Harrold).
</P>
<P>
   Flash to the present. Carol and Matt finally are tying the knot,
and the old gang reunites for the nuptials. Bob, now a successful
TV writer, shows up with his significant other, Sterling (Tuc
Waters), a soap opera star whose hunkish TV persona conceals an
aspiring Martha Stewart. Bob and Sterling are such a tight duo that
they're even thinking of cementing their relationship with a
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Bob's perplexity, then, when Brendan pops up
acknowledging that, yes, he is gay after all. And would Bob like to
make up for lost time?
</P>
<P>
   Writer//director Sloan dishes superficial characters in
superficial situations, but he has a good sense of humor and in
Arquette he has a sort of nebbishy homosexual Woody Allen hero.
Some of the performances, particularly Waters' affected TV actor,
are very funny. And though the film is clearly aimed at gay
audiences, Sloan gives even the straight characters some juicy if
not quite believable dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, nobody in this film is that believable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1800EDT &QL; 
