<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BEYOND-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NOTHING BEYOND `THE BEYOND' BUT BAD FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Beyond,'' a supernatural thriller, is unrated. It contains
graphic violence and gore. Running time is 1 hour 28 minutes. One
out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of his huge success with ``Pulp Fiction,'' Quentin
Tarantino decided to pay homage to those filmmakers who influenced
him by setting up Rolling Thunder Films, a distribution label
devoted to bringing to audiences quirky titles that received few or
no U.S. bookings on their initial release.
</P>
<P>
   The effort paid off when Rolling Thunder brought back Hong Kong
filmmaker Wong Kar-Wai's ``Chung King Express.'' Alas, Tarantino
now subjects us to ``The Beyond,'' a 1981 horror entry from Italian
goremeister Lucio Fulci.
</P>
<P>
   The late Fulci, a colleague of the better known Dario Argento,
has a cult following, presumably among audiences captivated by
bloody makeup, sadism and really awful acting. ``The Beyond,''
playing as the late show this week at the Tivoli Westport Theatre,
is regarded by some as Fulci's best film. That's a depressing
thought.
</P>
<P>
   The movie starts out in the 1920s when the residents of
Louisiana bayou country rise up to torture to death a warlock
living in a picturesque hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, half a century later, the old hotel has been inherited by a
young woman (Catriona MacColl) who hopes to restore it. But it
turns out that the building conceals one of the seven entrances of
hell, and the spirit of the late warlock is still up to mischief,
killing workmen and then animating their corpses.
</P>
<P>
   The film has a mysterious blind girl (Sarah Keller) who
interacts with our heroine but actually doesn't exist, and a
physician (David Warbeck) who doesn't believe in hocus-pocus but is
too dim to figure out that to kill a zombie, you have to shoot it
in the head.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing even vaguely approaching real characterizations
here. (Despite their Anglicized names, most of the cast members are
Italian, and their lines are dubbed in English.) The story is
preposterous, and the scary effects wouldn't alarm a 10-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   At best ``The Beyond'' provides an opportunity for audience
participation in the style of ``Mystery Science Theater 3000.''
Come on down and make up your own dialogue. It's got to be better
than what's on the soundtrack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
