<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SMOKE-REVIEW-KA     07-16 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SMOKE-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-INDIAN FILM SEEMS LOW ON SPIRIT UNTIL POWERFUL END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals,'' a comedy//drama, is rated PG-13 for some
intense images. Running time is 1 hour 29 minutes. Two and a half
out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   As the first feature film written, directed, produced and almost
exclusively acted by American Indians, ``Smoke Signals'' most
certainly will have a lock on the P.C. crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Question is: Just how good is it as a movie?
</P>
<P>
   For most of its running time, ``Smoke Signals'' impresses as a
thoroughly competent, often amusing but vaguely underwhelming
effort. And yet in the final minutes it achieves a rare power and
resonance quite out of proportion to its otherwise workmanlike
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Just how it achieves this is hard to say _ perhaps through the
accumulation of details and emotional moments that individually
don't mean much but that add up to something affecting.
</P>
<P>
   This easygoing film _ written by novelist Sherman Alexie and
directed by Chris Eyre _ begins on the Coeur d'Alene reservation in
Idaho, where the DJ on the local low-powered radio station greets
listeners with ``It's a good day to be indigenous!'' and a guy
posted out by the highway gives an unusual weather report (``One of
the clouds up there looks like a horse!'').
</P>
<P>
   Our protagonists are cousins who, save for their shared
bloodline, might have come from different planets.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Joseph (Adam Beach) is a charismatic former high-school
athlete with a chip on his shoulder and a future already running
low on possibilities. Handsome but sullen and unmotivated, Victor
seems destined to fall into a familiar cycle of poverty and
despair.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Builds-the-Fire (Evan Adams), on the other hand, is a
grinning geek with a taste for nerdy three-piece black suits, heavy
eyeglasses and carefully braided hair. Thomas is a born storyteller
who yaps nonstop about tribal and personal history, recycling
age-old legends and dishing new ones of his own invention. If
Victor is a sullen pessimist, Thomas is willingly naive, with a
mischievous sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Victor finds his cousin an irritating pest, but their shared
history binds them together. When both were infants, Thomas'
parents died in a house fire after a night of heavy boozing.
Victor's father, Arnold (Gary Farmer), saved baby Thomas from the
flames. The boys grew up together as neighbors and classmates.
</P>
<P>
   A good chunk of Victor's bad attitude can be traced to his dad
abandoning the family a decade ago and moving off the reservation.
Now word arrives that Arnold has died in Arizona. Victor and Thomas
are dispatched to bring back his ashes.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a road movie about two innocents set loose in a
foreign land _ namely, the U.S.A. The whites they encounter view
the Indian lads with everything from condescension and contempt to
superficial pleasantries; it doesn't help that the suspicious
Victor bites every friendly hand.
</P>
<P>
   He even mistrusts Suzy (Irene Bedard), a fellow Indian and
social worker who befriended Arnold in his last years and now
relates that Victor's alcoholic dad finally kicked the bottle,
straightened up and in his final days achieved a kind of grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke Signals'' is amiable enough, with a good dose of
American Indian humor and an unhurried, drifting style that is easy
to take even as it fritters away much of the drama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8754 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-ZORRO-REVIEW-KA     07-16 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ZORRO-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHT TOUCHE CARRIES THE DAY IN `ZORRO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Mask of Zorro,'' a swashbuckler, is rated PG-13 for
intense action and violence. Running time is 2 hours 11 minutes.
Three out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   You can try to resist ``The Mask of Zorro,'' but it won't work.
This good-natured if slightly overcooked swashbuckler revives
old-fashioned derring-do and melds it with a post-Indiana Jones
wryness.
</P>
<P>
   Add actor Antonio Banderas in a performance that will most
certainly make him an A-list star, and you've got fine summer fun _
completely lightweight but highly enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   Director Martin Campbell and the screenwriters (Ted Elliott,
Terry Rossio, Randall Jahnson and John Eskow) have come up with an
interesting twist on the legendary caped swordsman of old
California by delivering not one, but two Zorros.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy prologue set in 1821, we see Zorro (played by
Anthony Hopkins and, rather obviously, a stunt man) defeating the
corrupt provincial governor, Don Rafael (Stuart Wilson), and
leading the oppressed peons in a revolt against Spain that marks
the birth of the Mexican nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the wily Don Rafael isn't easily vanquished. Before he
leaves for Spain he orchestrates the capture of Zorro _ whose real
identity is Don Diego de la Vega _ and the death of Zorro's beloved
wife. And he seizes the couple's infant daughter, Elena, to raise
as his own.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 years later, Don Rafael returns to California with plans
to create his own little dictatorship. He brings with him Elena
(Catherine Zeta-Jones), now a spirited and beautiful young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with these events is Don Diego's escape from prison
(finally!) and his recruitment of an impetuous young bandit,
Alejandro Murrieta (Banderas). Worn down by 20 years of chains and
whips, Don Diego knows he's no match for Rafael's army. His idea is
to train Alejandro as the new Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mask of Zorro'' has plenty going on. Too much, in fact.
It's part ``Rocky'' movie (lots of ``training'' sequences), part
``My Fair Lady'' (the proletarian Alejandro must learn how to pass
himself off as a foppish aristocrat), part coy love story
(Alejandro//Zorro and Elena repeatedly cross swords and lips in a
clever dance of seduction and defiance), part ``Lethal Weapon''
flick (huge explosions), part family melodrama (Elena doesn't
realize that the servant ``Bernardo'' is actually her real father).
</P>
<P>
   Nitpickers will find plenty of incongruities. How can Don Diego
come away from two decades of near-starvation with a substantial
middle-aged spread? How do they light those torches placed 20 feet
up a wall? How come some characters speak Spanish-accented English,
others British-accented English, and still others Spanish? What's a
loaded cannon doing inside a soldiers' barracks?
</P>
<P>
   Holding it all together is Banderas, whose impish sense of fun
and bad-boy cockiness provide just the right counterpoint to the
film's heavy-handed handling of political and social events. One of
the film's strengths is that it doesn't take its new Zorro too
seriously _ Alejandro is so eager to get into costume that he dons
the black mask before he's sufficiently skilled, leading to some
very amusing foul-ups involving his horse.
</P>
<P>
   And the stunt guys have done a terrific job, staging stirring
acrobatic sword fights and chases that will no doubt send off an
entirely new generation of kids to turn pillow cases into capes.
</P>
<P>
   If director Campbell, best-known for the James Bond flick
``GoldenEye,'' hasn't quite yet developed the polished
sensibilities of Michael Curtiz (``The Adventures of Robin Hood'')
or even Steven Spielberg (``Raiders of the Lost Ark''), he has come
closer to delivering an old-fashioned Errol Flynn swashbuckler than
anyone else in the past decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
