<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CZAR-YELTSIN _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ President Boris Yeltsin
silenced all the rumors Thursday when he announced that he would
attend the royal burial ceremony for the bones of Nicholas II,
Russia's last czar, and his family. Yeltsin, like many other
high-level dignitaries, had earlier said that he would not attend
the Friday ceremony largely because the powerful Russian Orthodox
Church cast doubt on whether the bones were authentic. (Holmes, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move in both the (i) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories by 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ Unbending in the face of pressure from
business groups and his own Republican leadership, Rep. Lamar
Smith, R-Texas, continues to insist that any new visas for foreign
workers be tied to more protections for U.S. workers. At a news
conference Thursday, Smith presents a tech worker from Williamson
County and two other Texans who he says are jobless or
underemployed because of foreign workers. (Harlan, Cox News Service
500).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH _ WASHINGTON _ Partisan battle lines hardened Thursday
over reform of managed health care as President Clinton appeared at
a news conference with the Democratic leaders of the House and
Senate to push for their version of a ``patients' bill of rights.''
(Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ELDERLY _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Special Aging
Committee holds a hearing on older Americans' increasing use of the
Internet, including possibilities of social interaction, cultural
enrichment, professional development, and information about health
care choices. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-LIST _ WASHINGTON _ Here are some World Wide Web sites
of special interest to seniors. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Armed Services Committee
holds a confirmation hearing on the nomination of Daryl Jones to be
secretary of the Air Force. (Joyce, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI _ ATLANTA _ White Water has done it's own investigation of
the E. coli outbreak, and the investigator, a former esteemed CDC
official, will be discussing his findings Thursday. Also will
update state's investigation, kids conditions. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WHITEWATER-PROFILE _ A profile of the company that owns White
Water park, linked to E. coli infections of at least two dozen
children. Silver Dollar City is one of the most respected names in
the amusement industry. One of the owners of the Branson, Mo.
company says he was so upset when he heard news of the outbreak
that he cried, but stops short of promising to pay medical bills
incurred by parents of the victims. Silver Dollar City, operated by
the Herschend family, has grown one of the nation's largest
amusement companies from a hole in the ground. From its beginning
of setting up some craft stands at the mouth of a Missouri cave and
charging admission, the company grown into an operator of river
boats, water parks in several cities and even Dollywood.
(Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NAACP NATIONAL CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-WRAP_ ATLANTA _ On the last day of the NAACP convention,
Vice President Al Gore speaks, and we ask the delegates if they see
his speech and announcement as sincere or just vote courting and if
it'll make a difference in their selection. (Oglesby, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15-20.
</P>
<P>
