<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE19-COX     07-16 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unwelcome solitude: Alone and adrift in cyberspace trance
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 19: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtual Valhalla, a man named Bran Ferren says, is no more than
25 years off. My timing is never good. I can see I'm going to miss
this one, too. In 25 years I'll be retired _ if I'm lucky. Or maybe
even dead, the worst timing of all.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, on second thought, it's just as well.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about something that Bran Ferren calls an
Internet-connection implant. I don't know what exactly this would
be, only that Ferren, who is an executive with Walt Disney
Imagineering, says it would let you hook up to cyberspace without
even turning on your computer. Ferren has anticipated the doubters
and skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why risk it?'' he asked in The New York Times Magazine a few
months ago. ``Well, imagine that you could understand any language,
remember every joke, solve any equation, get the latest news,
balance your checkbook, communicate with others and have
near-instant access to any book ever published without ever having
to leave the privacy of yourself. Not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   There it is, in that third-to-last word: Yourself. Myself. The
Self, sovereign and solipsistic.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else exists.
</P>
<P>
   An amoeba-like world
</P>
<P>
   As a view of the world, it conforms perfectly to the amoeba-like
inconstancy that Ellen Ullman writes about in ``Close to the
Machine: Technophilia and Its Discontents'' (City Lights Books,
$21.95 hardback, $12.95 paperback). Ullman is as close to a poet as
cyberculture will ever produce. Her prose has a pith and precision
that turns things inside out, exposing the unseen. In Ullman's
hands, virtual reality becomes a trance, its protocols and language
dreamlike, disembodied, disconnected from life. Here, in her
opening paragraph, she locates us in the mind of a programmer
working around the clock:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what time it is. There are no windows in this
office and no clock, only the blinking red LED display of a
microwave, which flashes 12:00, 12:00, 12:00, 12:00. Joel and I
have been programming for days. We have a bug, a stubborn demon of
a bug. So the red pulse no-time feels right, like a read-out of our
brains, which somehow synchronized themselves at the same blink
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Close to the Machine'' is one of those books that get by on no
publicity, but somehow find their audience. It deserves a larger
one. As cultural commentary, it is far more telling than Tracy
Kidder's ``The Soul of a New Machine,'' published in the early
1980s. Where Kidder was writing from the outside, the observer
reporting what he saw but not always what he understood, Ullman
writes from the inside. The effects are dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Ullman has been a software engineer for 20 years, a onetime
English major who got sidetracked into an industry ravenous for
smart people who can learn a new language, a new way of thinking
about what is and is not. And then those people find themselves
drifting in an electronic universe. If it's disturbing to read,
it's because Ullman renders that universe so seamlessly. She takes
you into it, and you want out.
</P>
<P>
   Timeless and unmoored
</P>
<P>
   The features of that universe are by now familiar _ the monitor
and the mouse, the cubicle, the sound of clicks. It is a world
without hard ground:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting in my sun-filled, 1,600 square feet of architectural
cool, I felt light-shocked, stunned. The sudden huge quiet unnerved
me. Now I spent my days in the company of machine hum. Now I worked
whenever, got dressed when I had to. Time on the face of the clock
meant less and less as the weeks went by. I was all unmoored again.
My company and my life had devolved to their inevitable essence: me
and my machines.''
</P>
<P>
   The satisfactions of solitude are restorative, a being with
oneself. It is spiritual, yet tethered still to the physical. This
is not what Ullman means. In the electronic cosmology, being itself
loses meaning because it is denied substantiality. Face-to-face
relationships have no more value than e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Ullman, it happens, also wrote an op-ed piece in the Times
recently, less poetic but no less pertinent. What is the point of a
computer science degree, she asked, if the technology is
continually changing? The original programmers, in the years
following World War II, were mathematicians and physicists. Today,
with the demand for programmers far outpacing any normal supply of
mathematicians and physicists, they have been succeeded by tekkies,
uneducated drones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Programmers,'' she wrote, ``seem to be changing the world. It
would be relief, for them and for all of us, if they knew something
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
