<HEADLINE>
BONDS, DOLLAR FALL DESPITE SIGNS ECONOMY IS COOLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities fell Thursday despite government
reports pointing toward lower economic growth and diminished
inflationary pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Traders attributed the bond market's retreat to a further
decline in the dollar's value and a belief that the effects of the
General Motors Corp. strike had made the latest economic data look
deceptively weak.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar fell to the lowest level against the yen in more than
three weeks on speculation that Japan's next elected prime minister
will support radical bank reform and help rescue the country from
recession. The dollar also fell for the fifth day against the mark
after Russia's Parliament passed austerity measures to secure new
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds have tended to track movements in the dollar's value
lately. A higher dollar attracts foreign investors to assets
denominated in the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 30-year bond slipped 12/32, to a price of 105
21/32. The yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to
5.72 percent, from 5.70 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The price weakness came despite government reports showing a
decline of six-tenths of a percent in June industrial production
and a decline of eight-tenths of a percent in factory use to the
lowest level in more than four years. The data suggested the
economy is cooling, which would tend to help bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But economists said the data reflected the mass shutdown of GM
factories caused by a strike at two plants in Flint, Mich., that
began more than a month ago. The reports would have been stronger
without the effects of the labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GM strike has started to wreak havoc with the economic
data base and market observers are beginning to weave through the
statistical minefield,'' said Donald Fine, the chief market analyst
at Chase Asset Management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-PRICE-COX     07-16 2456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PRICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Reynolds Price, stories `want' to be told
 &HT;    By Teresa K. Weaver
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a society, a region, ``a country of leavers,'' author
Reynolds Price shows a definite propensity toward staying. At age
65, he lives only an hour away from where he was born, in Macon,
N.C., and only 10 minutes away from Duke University, where he's
been teaching since 1958. And 14 years after doctors found a
10-inch-long, pencil-thick tumor on his spinal column, the
silver-haired Price thrives, clearly relishing his role as a master
of contemporary literature.
</P>
<P>
   Price's work is so profoundly grounded in his home territory
that he has spent much of his writing life fending off labels of
``Faulknerian'' or even strictly ``Southern.'' Indeed, his themes
of love vs. independence, a family vs. a life alone, could be set
anywhere. They're usually not, but they could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've tried to do is communicate everything I saw and felt
and thought I knew as clearly as possible _ as close to the truth
as possible,'' Price says in a slow, measured baritone befitting a
natural-born storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work is about the huge struggle that any thoughtful person
has between love, duty and freedom. How much do you have to
surrender to have a companioned life?'' asks Price, who himself has
never married. ``How much are you prepared to surrender? And what
are you going to do when you find out that you've got a husband and
four kids and it's taken away too much of your freedom?''
</P>
<P>
   Such questions come honestly to Price, whose parental families _
the Prices and the Rodwells _ grappled with the vagaries of human
relationships and the fallout of choices poorly made. Two of his
father's three sisters had disastrous marriages and returned to
live in the family home, each of them bringing a child, never
remarrying, and having to find work in a small Southern town at a
time when women _ at least middle-class white women _ didn't work.
His family also had its share of experience with drink and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, part of my fascination with that reality, that
theme of love vs. freedom, comes from my being an only child until
I was 8 years old, and not having a lot of other children to play
with. I was fascinated by, and deeply seduced by, my parents'
social circle, which consisted largely of extended family. And
these people tended to be marvelous talkers and storytellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't leave the adults alone. Even when there were other
children around, I preferred to stay and listen to the adults talk.
Until they ran me off so they could tell a dirty joke. Then I
lurked around a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps predictably, a solitary boy with a penchant for truth
grows up to be a solitary writer with an unerring ear for detail
and an unwavering delight in the complexities of human character.
The themes, the expressions (``a neck as long as any wet week,'' a
man ``quiet as warm dust under your feet,'' ``alone as a crow on a
dead tree''), the gift of storytelling that is still ``a Southern
thing, if you're in the right part of the South, meaning off an
interstate'' _ all those things were laid down early in life as
major sources, major resources.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist of Price's critically acclaimed novel ``Kate
Vaiden'' (1986) was based loosely on his mother, Elizabeth Rodwell
Price, a loyal and loving woman in whom he always detected an
``outlaw spirit.'' His only other first-person female voice is
found in his latest novel, ``Roxanna Slade.'' Roxanna is based,
again loosely, on his mother and her older sister, Price's Aunt Ida
Drake.
</P>
<P>
   Both Roxanna and Kate are products of the small-town South, and
both are strong women.
</P>
<P>
   But Kate, the orphaned survivor of her parents' murder-suicide,
spends her life running, first from her infant son, and eventually
from one place to another, from one man to many others. Roxanna
never leaves, straying from traditional female roles _ sister,
wife, daughter-in-law and mother _ only figuratively, with a
terrifying breakdown and her own brand of emotional detachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The miracle is, you can last through time.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Kate Vaiden'' (1986)
</P>
<P>
   Price is a great conversationalist, as comfortable with words as
his characters are with dialogue. He is cursed, he swears, with
``this fatal Southern liking to talk to people.'' In Atlanta
recently near the end of a 16-city tour promoting ``Roxanna
Slade,'' he speaks easily and elegantly in the rhythm of a natural
poet, in the mesmerizing cadence of a lifelong North Carolinian.
Conversation is peppered with thoughtful pauses and passing
references to a circle of beloved friends ranging from Eudora Welty
to Polly ``Kiss My Grits'' Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so revered,'' says Thom Bales, community relations
coordinator for Borders Books &AMP; Music in Atlanta, where Price read
to about 75 spellbound readers. ``The tone of the audience was so
quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   In a comfortable pace his readers know well, Price will talk
about almost anything _ about the South as a setting and a cultural
phenomenon, about teachers as ``awesome beings'' and about his
life's work.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, he refers to characters from his novels as if
they are lifelong friends or perhaps ne'er-do-well relatives. He
admits he ``fell in love'' with two of his creations: the
unattached and unattainable Polly Drewry in ``The Surface of
Earth'' (1975) and ``The Source of Light'' (1981), and Blue
Calhoun, the title character in his 1992 novel about a middle-aged
man's adulterous affair with a 16-year-old child-molestation
victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Blue and Polly are outlaws. For complicated reasons, they
simply don't buy the standards and moral and ethical and domestic
imperatives of their culture, which is small-town Southern
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Outlaws are universal, Price insists. Both stories could have
been set anywhere, conceivably far outside the South. They could
have been, but they're not.
</P>
<P>
   In his travels, Price continually encounters readers who know
nothing of the South, who may never even have set foot in the
South, yet they understand his work. ``They really get it,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   There does still exist, in Price's view, a tangible, definable
South, despite urbanization and the transient nature of
20th-century society. His definition of that South, though, is far
from romantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that has ever been truly unique about the South
is still under way,'' he says. ``Even those of us who are
Southerners immediately start thinking of the weather, cooking,
Christianity, the King James Bible, music, front porches, etc.,
when we try to describe the South. And a lot of that does seem
imperiled, especially if you live in Atlanta or Charlotte or
Raleigh-Durham or any other metropolitan area. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the only thing that the South has that some other
region doesn't have ... is three centuries plus, ongoing, of
incredible intimacy between two very different races. That is still
very much with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``And with all the horrors like the recent episode in Texas (in
which three white men allegedly tortured and killed a black man
because of his race), and all the huge inequities that continue to
exist, I'm very proud to say we know a hell of a lot more about
segregation and integration than any other part of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember what you see and save it up for me.''
</P>
<P>
   _Polly Drewry in ``The Surface of Earth'' (1975)
</P>
<P>
   Thanks partly to the computer age (no more drafting chapters by
hand) and partly to confinement in a wheelchair (a renewed sense of
discipline), Price's creative output since 1984 is twice what it
was in the two decades before that _ not that he was exactly
slothful before. Since his first novel, ``A Long and Happy Life,''
was published in 1962, he has written 11 novels, two volumes of
memoirs, two collections of short stories, a study of the Gospels
and four collections of poems, along with assorted plays,
screenplays, essays and even song lyrics. His work has appeared in
16 languages.
</P>
<P>
   He spends eight hours a day, six days a week in his office at
the house in the pines outside Durham, where he has lived since
1965. Before his paralysis, Price lived alone. Since, he has
learned to rely on a live-in companion _ usually a former Duke
student, who commits to a yearlong arrangement _ to help with the
rituals of everyday life that a paraplegic cannot take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Price is not given to self-pity, nor to sharing intimate details
of his life. But after his ``cancer crisis'' 14 years ago, he wrote
``A Whole New Life,'' a slender, selfless account that continues to
resonate with readers everywhere he goes. Four years of surgeries,
radiation treatments and drugs left him cancer-free but in a
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every book signing now, without fail, somebody will turn up
with an interesting story that goes with their having read the
book,'' he says. ``A man came up to me in Washington, D.C., last
night and said his wife had just recently died. And even when she
was so sick she couldn't get out of bed, she wanted him to keep
reading her passages from that book.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses. ``Three weeks ago in L.A., a woman who looked like a
trustworthy person _ she seemed to be telling the truth _ described
herself as being a tormented clinical depressive and said that book
saved her life. She said it saved her life.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses again. ``I'll take that,'' he says. Some rewards of a
life spent writing are more poignant than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pretty much have to be driven to be a writer. You've got
to want to have kind of a weird life. ... People always ask me what
I tell young writers. And truthfully, the first thing I tell them
is: Quit if you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Tyler and Josephine Humphreys are two of Price's former
students who couldn't quit. Both went on to become as famous as
their teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best,'' Humphreys says simply. ``He was the
handsomest man any of us had ever seen. He really was extraordinary
looking, with his dark hair and dark eyes. And he was the funniest
man, which always helps in teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best teachers have a kind of magic. They're not like
normal people. ... I think there were two things in particular that
all of us students latched on to. First, he's a genius with the
language. He can put words together in ways that no other living
person can. And he's had a huge influence on the Southern style of
fiction with his wordsmithing. He makes real poetry out of it, and
we all wanted to learn the secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, he has a great deal of insight into the human heart,''
Humphreys adds. ``He taught us that writing is not just about
words. Writing is always an effort to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stories are something I'm better at than life.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Blue Calhoun'' (1992)
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing is simply some hard-wired part of my nature,'' Price
insists. ``It's the only thing I was ever any good at. And I knew
it since I was 16 years old. I just keep doing it, and it keeps
wanting to be done. It really is as mysterious and unexamined as
that. I don't look at it too hard for fear it might go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Chappell, a fellow North Carolina poet and novelist who was
a freshman at Duke when Price was a senior, remembers the
upperclassman ``looking very much like a young Orson Welles'' and
ultimately ``worrying about looking like an old Orson Welles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was someone roughly my age who was the most urbane, the
most polished, knowledgeable person I knew,'' Chappell says. ``And
despite the physical problems, he remains more or less that same
person. Even as a young man, he always had a confidence that he
would be the Reynolds Price that we know today.''
</P>
<P>
   Price still teaches at Duke one semester a year: a
near-legendary course on John Milton and either ``Advanced
Narrative Writing'' for seniors and graduate students or a course
on the Gospels of Mark and John.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to fight really hard not to do the old graybeard thing
_ `you know, back in my day' _ because I really try to remember
with bald realism,'' Price says. ``That was by no means a golden
age of literacy and classical education, but we certainly had some
complicated opportunities that are fairly unavailable today. For
instance, it was very standard for a child to take two or three
years of Latin, and virtually everybody I knew studied foreign
languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's most different today in students' lives is not
so much the level of educational preparation as it is that most
boring of all villains: television. That, I'm convinced, is the
major difference between students now and even students when I
began teaching in 1958. They spend such a phenomenal amount of time
in front of television, from infancy on, that their imaginations
may as well have been surgically removed.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he ultimately wants to be remembered _ as a
successful writer or a good teacher _ Price is slow to answer,
obviously reluctant to choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the beginning, writing and teaching have always been
paired in my life. ... I've taught about 2,000 people. Some of them
will remember me as long as they live, and some of them will tell
their children about me. After that, the teaching part of my life
will vanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The books, I hope, will be around for another few millennia.''
</P>
<P>
   THE REYNOLDS PRICE FILE
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 65
</P>
<P>
   -- Residence: Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   -- Birthplace: Macon, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   -- Education: bachelor of arts, Duke University, 1954; bachelor
of letters (Rhodes scholar), Merton College, Oxford University,
England, 1957.
</P>
<P>
   -- Latest work: 11th novel, ``Roxanna Slade'' (Scribners, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   -- Awards: National Book Critics Circle Award (1986) for ``Kate
Vaiden''; finalist for the Pulitzer Prize in fiction (1994) for
``The Collected Stories of Reynolds Price''; Sir Walter Raleigh
Award and William Faulkner Award (most notable first novel
published by an American in 1962) for ``A Long and Happy Life.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Works in progress: ``Learning a Trade: A Craftsman's
Notebooks'' (Duke University Press, December): Largely unedited _ a
few family names have been changed to nonrepresentative initials
``to protect the guilty'' _ these are Price's working notes from
1955 to 1997. He's also planning to write a book for preteenagers.
(``The subject is a boy and an elephant in North Carolina in the
1940s. ... That's as much as I know so far.'')
</P>
<P>
   -- Pleasures: Drawing, painting, relearning the piano on a new
Steinway, and keeping up with family (brother William Price Jr. is
director of the North Carolina Division of History and Archives in
Raleigh) and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
