<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWII-MOVIES-COX     07-16 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-MOVIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Private Ryan' first to hit the beach as WWII rages again
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 19: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The no-nonsense Army captain still looks a tad Forrest Gumpish,
the Iowa farm boy he's helping to rescue is actually Hollywood's
latest ``It'' boy, and the only shots that really count here are
being captured on 70 mm film.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when ``Saving Private Ryan'' marches into theaters
nationwide Friday _ complete with its harrowingly realistic battle
scenes, inspiringly patriotic themes and a platoon full of highly
decorated performers _ moviegoers may have to blink hard to
convince themselves World War II's not happening all over again.
</P>
<P>
   In a way it is. The war that saved humanity, preserved democracy
and, not coincidentally, spawned more movies than any other
conflict in history is at it again. Indeed, Steven Spielberg's
hugely hyped ``Saving Private Ryan'' is just the opening salvo in a
fusillade of upcoming films set in or around World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Besides getting to relive D-Day in ``Private Ryan'' _ directed
by Spielberg and starring Oscar winners Tom Hanks and Matt Damon _
moviegoers soon can revisit the battlefields of Guadalcanal,
courtesy of John Travolta, George Clooney and Nick Nolte in ``The
Thin Red Line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more coincidental than anything else,'' said ``Thin Red
Line'' producer John Roberdeau. ``People are simultaneously drawn
to the same thing and you get these cycles going.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, some one dozen World War II-themed movies are either
``in the can or in active development,'' according to the industry
bible, The Hollywood Reporter. They range from a French romantic
adventure (``Spoils of War'') to a Philippine fighting epic (``The
Emperor's General'').
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget ``Hogan's Heroes.'' Paramount Pictures last
month optioned the rights to the hit '60s sitcom set in a German
prisoner-of-war camp (now in syndication on cable's TV Land).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``the last great war'' (as historians and ``Private
Ryan's'' publicity materials frequently dub World War II) is the
next big thing well beyond movie screens. HBO recently broadcast
``When Trumpets Fade,'' about an American soldier who is his
company's lone survivor of 1944's Battle of Hurtgen Forest. Next
month, A&AMP;E will premiere ``More Great Escapes of World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   On the publishing front, Hyperion Books in May paid an
undisclosed six-figure sum for the rights to Jefferson native Damon
J. Gause's dramatic account of his escape from a Japanese prison
camp in the Philippines during World War II. Historian Stephen E.
Ambrose's ``Citizen Soldiers,'' spent several months on the
best-seller lists earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose traces the current explosion of interest in World War II
to several factors, including nostalgia for a time when
``individuals made a difference'' and the realization that the
war's aging veterans won't be around much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But bigger than either of those is that we as a nation are
yearning for heroes,'' said Ambrose, a historical consultant on
``Private Ryan.'' ``We don't have any. And we don't live in heroic
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do we live at a time when the issues seem as clearly
delineated as they were during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the forces of good and they were the forces of evil,''
said Western Michigan University professor Lewis H. Carlson about a
plot line with eternal appeal. ``We still like morality plays
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks suggested that's why World War II movies have once again
supplanted other wars,
</P>
<P>
   such as Vietnam, as popular
</P>
<P>
   subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is, Vietnam was a place of questionable morals
and motives,'' Hanks said while in Atlanta last week with Spielberg
promoting the movie. ``And in World War II, the Nazis were evil.
They had to be conquered.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, few World War II veterans tended to open up
about their experiences, said Carlson, who published an oral
history of former POWs last year. Even those who did approached the
subject much like movies at the time: The stories were heavy on
honor, even humor, and light on horror.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 51-year-old Spielberg says he grew up a ``war movie
fanatic.'' As a teenager, he used an 8 mm camera to try and capture
the spirit of the tales of his father, a veteran, about Americans'
combat heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If World War II is undergoing a revival, it may be that people
would rather see films about a war that has a point than films
about a war that many Americans have or had great doubts about,''
said Geoffrey Cocks, an Albion College professor who teaches a
course on Film Images of World War II. ``At least World War II was
for a good cause.''
</P>
<P>
   During Vietnam, the public saw the battlefield presented
unvarnished on daily TV newscasts. The war movies being churned out
in Hollywood became less patriotic than cynical or tragic in tone
(``Platoon,'' ``Apocalypse Now''). Yet by the Gulf War, Cocks says,
the U.S. government had ``learned the Vietnam lesson. There was
very carefully controlled (media) access and the picture presented
back home was very sanitized.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more the reason, perhaps, for our revived interest in
the last great war. And at least now, Spielberg said last week, the
focus is where it should be _ on the men who served at the front,
not behind Hollywood cameras or Washington desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I chose to tell it from the level of the sand as
opposed to the level of the camera crane up 45 feet and showing all
the spectacle of thousands of GI's hitting the beach,'' Spielberg
said quietly, sounding quite unlike that teen with an 8 mm camera
and romantic notions of war. ``I didn't want to tell that story,
because that was a Hollywood version of World War II. I wanted to
tell the veterans' version of World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
