</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On a picnic, it's the atmosphere that matters, not the food
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My New York editor friend, Larry Ashmead, clearly thinks I am a
nut about picnics. And, of course, he is right.
</P>
<P>
   I come from a long line of women, even old ladies in their 80s,
who often said, ``Let's take dinner and go to the woods.'' Our
theory is that whatever you have to eat tastes better under the
open sky, and ants in the cake and sand in the salad never bothered
one of us a whit.
</P>
<P>
   Larry probably remembers to his distress the time I walked him
and two other visitors from New York, Walter Mathews and Mary
Hedges, a couple of weary miles to our beloved Johnson's rock over
by Little River. (Try to find the rock now. Subdivisions have
obliterated the old wagon trail to it.) We spread our dinner on the
rock, which juts out of the hill overlooking the river, with blue
peaks of the mountains edging woods and sky beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The food wasn't notable. I don't remember what the four of us
toted to the rock, but it was probably fried chicken, potato salad,
pimento cheese sandwiches and iced tea. I didn't know there was
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know better. Larry has sent me from a British publication,
Country Life, a piece about the kind of picnics the stylish boating
crowd put on over there. His little note says, ``For your next
picnic _ choux puffs with trout pate, stuffed boned duck and
raspberry hazelnut meringue. Or maybe cherry clafoutis.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I think a really good picnic warrants the best food you
can come up with _ but what's wrong with fried chicken and pimento
cheese sandwiches? Of course, I haven't tried choux puffs with
trout pate or stuffed boned duck, but I'm willing to give them a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that I have a very elegant picnic basket, which
Larry and Walter gave me after the weary walk to Johnson's rock. It
came from Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, and it has plates and cups and
saucers, and knives and forks, and even a couple of small thermos
jugs. It's a lovely thing, and I have used it often, on less
distinguished picnics.
</P>
<P>
   My grandchildren charitably remember walks to Johnson's rock
when the cupboard was bare, and we made do with honey and butter
sandwiches and apples.
</P>
<P>
   One of the boys, now grown and about to get married, said
wistfully the other night, ``Do you ever make honey and butter
sandwiches and walk to the river any more?''
</P>
<P>
   To my shame, I haven't, since I tried to find the road to the
rock and found it blocked by a truckload of garbage, old mattresses
and springs and decaying baby furniture. It's enough to discourage
the most indefatigable picnicker.
</P>
<P>
   However, my neighbor Betsy Hastings, who rides to the rock on
her horse, has promised to show me the new way.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I'll get to work on something boned and
stuffed, and maybe a basket of quail eggs dipped in celery salt and
nestling in chicory leaves with mangos and smoked chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be like that picnic I planned for some guests at the
beach. I was packing the picnic basket, and had planned to haul the
group a couple of miles down the Gulf beach, when a delegation
called on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you mind,'' they began hesitantly, ``if we didn't go
down the beach and just ate here on the porch?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
