<SLUG> BC-MINIREVIEW-MARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everything's fair game in no-holds barred `Mary'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rude, crude and hilarious, this comedy by the ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber''
team of Peter and Bobby Farrelly definitely isn't a family film.
Ben Stiller plays Ted, a nerdy high school senior who suffers a
very particular bathroom mishap that keeps him from attending his
prom with the class golden girl (Cameron Diaz). Thirteen years
later, the still-obsessed Ted hires a lower-rung gumshoe (Matt
Dillon) to track her down.
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned: ``Something About Mary'' hits as many sacred cows
as possible: the physically challenged, the mentally challenged,
little yappy dogs, and people with skin conditions. But at least,
in the movie's sickest, funniest scene, the hair gel that one
character uses is cruelty-free.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is liberating in its scatological, slapstick way. But
the easy-to-offend should find something more polite to watch.
Which would be just about anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cameron Diaz, Ben Stiller and Matt Dillon. Directed by
Peter and Bobby Farrelly. Rated R for strong comic sexual content
(including glimpses of fake mangled genitalia and rubber breasts)
and language. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 58 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: In your face and very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
