<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mary' revels in cruelty jokes, perverse humor
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Preston Sturges' classic ``Sullivan's Travels,'' the
wandering movie director played by Joel McCrea tries to switch from
comedies to serious ``issue'' films, but winds up learning to value
his own gift for making audiences laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber'' team of Peter and Bobby Farrelly aren't
exactly Sturges. After all, he didn't traffic in jokes about
everything good, bad or disgusting that can go in or out of a human
body. But in their exuberant, democratically offensive fashion, the
brothers (also responsible for ``Kingpin'') have a knack for making
you laugh helplessly. And that's a gift.
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned: ``There's Something About Mary'' isn't a family
film. The politically correct, beware. The movie hits as many
sacred cows as possible: the physically challenged, the mentally
challenged, little yappy dogs and people with skin conditions. But
at least in the movie's sickest, funniest scene, the hair gel one
character uses is cruelty-free.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the film's cheery tone makes its comic assaults seem
like a twisted salute to American diversity. As a people, we come
in all shapes, sizes and degrees of skin burn, and the Farrellys
seem committed to give every one the comic once-over.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but what's the movie about? Ben Stiller plays Ted, whom we
meet as a high school senior, infatuated with Mary (Cameron Diaz).
She's the untouchable class golden girl. So imagine his surprise
when she invites him to the prom. And his mortification when a very
particular bathroom mishap keeps him from ever reaching the dance
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years later, Ted is still obsessed with Mary. So he
hires a lower-rung gumshoe named Healy (Matt Dillon) to track her
down. She turns out to be living in Miami, still gorgeous, still
single and a surgeon. Which is why Healy decides to woo Mary
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The ``something'' Mary has _ and Diaz makes us believe it _ is
the ability to make just about every man fall for her. Especially
the worst men, like Healy, or a pizza boy who, like the private
eye, will stop at no lie or crass stunt to have her.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fun in the movie is its riffs and comic bits. So the
less said, the better. The Farrellys know how to set up a joke,
build on it a few scenes later and then make it pay off in one
loud, rude funny way one last time.
</P>
<P>
   And they give the movie its own romance-comedy aura, trotting
out singer Jonathan Richman and drummer Tommy Larkins to give the
audience musical updates of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller does his patented schlemiel bit; after ``Flirting With
Disaster'' and ``Zero Effect,'' it's become his pigeonhole, but he
does it well. Dillon revels in the hidden rot beneath his
character's mock-suave exterior. And while she's a glowing
presence, it's a shame that Diaz, a gifted comedien, has to play a
character so perfect that she never gets a chance to go screwball,
like all the male cast members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' isn't the cookie-cutter
Hollywood romance you're used to. That's a recommendation, and a
warning. It's liberating in its scatological, slapstick way. But
the easy-to-offend should find something more polite to watch.
Which would be just about anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cameron Diaz, Ben Stiller, Matt Dillon. Directed by
Peter and Bobby Farrelly. Rated R for strong comic sexual content
(including glimpses of fake mangled genitalia and rubber breasts)
and language. 1 hour, 58 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Rude, crude and hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
