<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-BLACKROCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black Rock up to the challenge
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The times Greg Tate is recalling could be right now.
There was resistance from audiences to certain kinds of black
instrumental music, especially experimental guitar-oriented music.
And there was resistance from black and white divisions of record
labels to signing this kind of music.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1985. And one of the few major differences between
now and then is the Black Rock Coalition, which Tate co-founded
that year. ``We just banded together to correct that situation in a
proactive way,'' says Tate, 40, a Village Voice columnist and the
author of ``Fly Boy in the Buttermilk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of complaining about what the labels weren't doing, we
decided to be our own kind of industry within the industry. Put out
our own records. Put on our shows. And just create situations where
we challenged the audience to want and expect more.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a gradual process, Tate concedes. A lot of what the
BRC has done is within the popular music vein, taking on Sly and
the Family Stone, Prince, Curtis Mayfield and even Stevie Wonder at
the last National Black Arts Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't get it wrong; we've never been a cover band,'' adds
Vernon Reid, a co-founder of the BRC and the now-defunct Living
Colour. ``We make the individuality of the band members very
pronounced and just use a particular artist's music as a starting
point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's just time for this kind of challenge,'' continues
Tate. ``I feel that what Max Roach was doing as a drummer presaged
drum and bass. And his collaborations with Abbey Lincoln were very
much about addressing the political and social situations of
African people in the world. They were fearless about having a
political agenda inside of jazz. Something like `We Insist' is as
bold as anything in hip-hop when you think about the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And when you think about this time, he adds, such boldness is
still necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Max &AMP; Abbey Conversion in a Jungle Style''
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight. Presented by the Black Rock Coalition. Variety
Playhouse, Atlanta $18. 1-888-836-6223.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
