<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yes, Stickney's funny _ just think about it
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Walking out of comedian-actress Phyllis Yvonne
Stickney's one-woman show, you may think that what you just heard
wasn't funny.
</P>
<P>
   Black people who have ``lost their funk chasing that dollar.''
The near-prostitute-like image of prominent rap stars such as Lil'
Kim. The way black people discriminate against one another because
of their skin color and hair texture.
</P>
<P>
   What had you doubled over with laughter about any of that?
</P>
<P>
   Well, you might realize that what you were laughing at is the
reflection of yourself in Stickney's fun house mirror. Or you might
not have been one of those people Stickney talks about who creates
his own words (``lookeded'' ``'fose to''), but you've heard it
enough to recognize it. So you applaud in affirmation.
</P>
<P>
   With the sharp insight of a more personal Chris Rock, the
curator of the National Black Arts Festival's performance arts
program offers up an affecting form of ``edu-tainment,'' as she
calls it. It's part comedy, part poetry, part audience
participation, with a whole lot of her inspiring personal story.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're watching a masterpiece in the making,'' claims
Stickney, who has appeared in ``The Women of Brewster Place,''
``New Jack City,'' ``Malcolm X'' and the upcoming movie adaptation
of Terry McMillan's ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And being onstage is my therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Yvonne Stickney
</P>
<P>
   Midnight Saturday. 25th floor, Renaissance Atlanta Hotel, 590 W.
Peachtree St. N.W. $15.
</P>
<P>
   1-888-TEN-NBAF (1-888-836-6223).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
