<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEILBERGQandA-COX     07-16 2215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEILBERGQandA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spielberg: `I thought I knew what war was'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 19: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the unexplored realms of extraterrestrial existence to the
unspeakable horrors of the Holocaust, Academy Award-winning
director Steven Spielberg has been known for tackling immense
topics throughout his 26-year career. Yet his latest film may be
his most personally oriented ``big'' film. In ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' Spielberg turns his vision on World War II. In an interview
last week, Spielberg shared his thoughts on war, war movies,
personal courage and a career spent directing everything from
mechanical sharks to the geisha girls who will be the focus of his
next project.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Q:There have been all sorts of theories about your supposed
inspiration for doing this movie. So what was it, really?
</P>
<P>
   A:I wish I did have the idea for the movie, but I read a
completed screenplay by Robert Rodat. It had been given to me by my
agency, who knew I was looking to tell a story about World War II
and had been for years.
</P>
<P>
   I was compelled very much by the morality play at the center of
``Private Ryan.'' But I certainly think that Rodat drew his
inspiration from the stories of brothers who have died in combat,
from the Civil War to the Sullivan brothers (five brothers who died
on the U.S. cruiser Juneau in 1942) _ which was probably the
biggest blow the home front ever took during the war ... and later
on there was the Niland family, who lost two out of four sons and a
minister was sent out into the field to search for the (remaining)
brothers for 10 days before finding them.
</P>
<P>
   Q:One of the things you're being credited for in ``Saving
Private Ryan'' is making one of the first ``realistic'' movies
about World War II. How would you characterize your earlier
efforts?
</P>
<P>
   A:Well, if that's what I'm credited for in this film, then (in)
my first films, I would have been credited for romanticizing war.
You know, making war a paradise for war lovers!
</P>
<P>
   And that's sort of what propaganda films did in the 1940s _ to
help with recruitment, to sell war bonds and to make people back
home feel that their sons were dying for a good cause.
</P>
<P>
   So I was only a creature of habit. I was a kid growing up in
Arizona, and on TV when I was growing up, there were two choices:
Westerns and war movies. And I hated horses, so I watched the war
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So what's next, your western?
</P>
<P>
   A:(Laughing) You're not going to see my western for a long time,
no!
</P>
<P>
   Q:So did a time finally come in your life when you wanted to set
the record straight on WWII?
</P>
<P>
   A:Oh yes, it happened to me _ it happened to all of us. I'm 51,
so I guess I'm the Vietnam generation. I was (classified) 1A before
the lottery. I had a high lottery number, which is the only reason
I didn't go to Vietnam. I took the Army physical in the induction
center and was one month away from getting the ``greetings'' letter
when the lottery was inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
   But I think what changed my mind from the glory movies of the
1940s and '50s was seeing the casualties from the Vietnam War on TV
seven nights a week, over and over and over again. You know, Dan
Rather and Mike Wallace literally out there in the field with their
microphones, on their hands and knees, showing triage of these guys
screaming their lungs out. And I'm in college at the time. A lot of
us were talking about going to Vietnam and suddenly I'm of draft
age, and it's all we thought about.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Since you were so close to being drafted, would you have gone
to Vietnam?
</P>
<P>
   A:Yes. Yes, definitely I would have gone. I would've been too
scared not to. Because then, I did not have the courage of my
convictions _ to have protested the war by leaving the country. I
would have served my country, although I would have been unhappy,
because I didn't agree with that war. But I would have gone anyway.
A lot of guys went into that war who didn't want to fight that war.
They fought and they died. It was something they had to do.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Still, was there ever a point while you were making ``Saving
Private Ryan'' when you said to yourself, ``I only thought I
understood what war was all about?''
</P>
<P>
   A:Yes. I was knocked off my perch every day. I thought I knew
what war was, because who's been teaching me war all my life but
the movies? But when I began to make this picture, I realized, ``My
God, I've been learning from the wrong people.'' The people who
really should have been teaching me (about) war over all those
years were the veterans of those wars _ of Vietnam, Korea and World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You put your actors through a mini-boot camp before filming
began. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A:I was trying to teach them to respect soldiering. You can't
put any individual through five to six days of basic training and
expect them to be soldiers. It takes three to four months to make a
soldier. But I thought six days was better than no time spent
learning how to respect the people they were about to portray. To
me, it was about teaching them respect more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Stephen Ambrose (the renowned World War II historian who
served as an adviser on the film) says D-Day's soldiers got to
confront the question every man wonders about himself _ ``Am I a
coward?'' What situation in your own life similarly tested your
personal bravery?
</P>
<P>
   A:I think that the biggest test of courage in my life was
deciding to direct ``Schindler's List.'' Because I was terrified. I
was terrified that I wasn't enough of a filmmaker, enough of a
human being. Or I was afraid I didn't possess the qualifications
necessary to acquit that event in history and to give honor, not
shame, to the survivors of the Shoah.
</P>
<P>
   I felt that had I told the story wrong _ had it been too
melodramatic, too sentimentalized, which I have an inclination
toward anyway _ that I would have brought shame to a subject that
is already, you know, regarded by many debunkers and deniers as
never having happened. And if I had made a mistake with that story
I would have unwittingly contributed to the side that says, ``See,
it's not real after all. It never really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And so that was probably the scariest decision I ever made. And
it wasn't to do with my career _ (with) making another choice to
direct just another movie. This was an event that could only go in
two directions.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Are your kids going to see ``Saving Private Ryan''?
</P>
<P>
   A:My kids are not going to see it, no. Because it's too graphic.
It's too realistic, and I just don't want my kids being exposed to
this right now.
</P>
<P>
   I think 15 years old is even a gray area. But I think once you
get your learner's permit _ once you can drive a car and see those
``Death on the Highway'' videos they show you, and then once you
can actually serve in the Army _ that's my cutoff age.
</P>
<P>
   But I think people should just be warned that it is not a movie
that glorifies or glamorizes war. It's a movie that tells to the
best of my ability _ with all the actual consultants I had on this
picture, with all the people who were veterans of the war _ it's
just the best job I could do of telling their story. And therefore,
this might not be a film for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Who do you hope goes to see this movie?
</P>
<P>
   A:Well, I hope that people who don't know very much about World
War II will go to see it and understand what it was like, you know,
for the kids who created the baby boomers. I hope people will see
the movie and understand, were it not for that generation _ my
dad's generation, or some of our grandparents' generation _ there
wouldn't be a baby boomer generation and therefore there wouldn't
be a Generation X. That that's how critical in terms of a seminal
moment of the last 100 years that war was for the world.
</P>
<P>
   And I hope veterans will see it. But I don't expect veterans
will see it anymore than the Holocaust survivors saw ``Schindler's
List.'' Most of the Holocaust survivors would not go to see
``Schindler's List'' because the memory of their existence in those
camps was still too current. And I expect that, even though I
really feel I made this movie for the veterans _ as a memorial to
the veterans who didn't come back and, as I say, as a kind of grand
overture of gratitude to those who fought that war and won it. I
expect very few of those veterans will allow themselves that
experience, especially when they read that it's realistic. But
that's who I hope will see the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Has your father seen the movie yet?
</P>
<P>
   A:No, he's seeing it next week.
</P>
<P>
   Q:As one of those vets, did he have to be convinced to see it?
</P>
<P>
   A:No, not at all. He gave me a lot of help on this movie. A
couple of scenes that are in the movie came from my father. ... My
dad will see it because my dad wasn't in combat on the ground. He
was in B-25s in Burma. So he had a different experience. So I think
the ground experience (depicted in the film) will be OK for him.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Since you brought up ``Schindler's List'' earlier, a lot of
people are wondering if ``Saving Private Ryan'' is a companion
piece to that. Do the two films have anything to do with each other
in your mind?
</P>
<P>
   A:No, nothing. I don't even consider the Holocaust part of World
War II. I think the Holocaust was a ... you know, was just a
monstrous evil that would have happened with or without America's
intervention in the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Maybe that's a case of people now looking at your movies in
terms of them being ``the next Steven Spielberg film.'' Do you ever
think back to those days when you could just make a movie like
``E.T.'' because you wanted to, or, maybe in the case of ``Jaws,''
because someone hired you to. ...
</P>
<P>
   A:That was basically it, too! ``Jaws'' was a good job!
</P>
<P>
   Q:Do you ever miss those days?
</P>
<P>
   A:Not at all, and I'm not influenced by it either. I'm not
influenced to try to tell the kind of stories that people either
are hoping I'll tell or expecting me to tell. Because if I did
that, I would simply be dishonest to my own needs.
</P>
<P>
   You know, I'm making a movie in January that I couldn't have
conceived of making until I read this book _ ``Memoirs of a
Geisha.'' I couldn't have conceived of going to Kyoto and making a
geisha movie, are you crazy? When (studio executive) Lucy Fisher
called me and sent me the book, I didn't even read it for a month.
But when I read that book, I said, ``Oh, my God!''
</P>
<P>
   So I need to be open to that kind of influence _ not the
influence of trying to second-guess what the pundits want me to
make next, what might be right for me to make next.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What attracted you to ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' (a first-person
narrative of a Japanese girl sold into the slavery of a geisha
house)?
</P>
<P>
   A:I am so attracted to that wonderful competitive attitude
between the two geisha houses and (the characters) Sayuri and
Pumpkin. And I love Hatsumomo _ she's the greatest villainess since
Cruella De Vil! I just can't wait to get my chops around this
thing!
</P>
<P>
   Q:So you'll be working with a lot of women on this film?
</P>
<P>
   A:All women and all Asians. There are no Americans, no
Westerners in this film.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Won't that be quite a switch from ``Private Ryan,'' which
except for a few opening scenes, has virtually no female
characters?
</P>
<P>
   A:I think women are involved in this movie to a great degree. I
think there is the ghost of motherhood that sort of haunts every
frame of this picture. Because that's why they're saving Private
Ryan, or attempting to, and that's where they want to send him if
they do manage to save him. So I think that American motherhood is
completely a very strong component that runs all through this
picture. But in a sense right now what I'm drawn most to is a men's
movie, because I've just come out of what became a kind of male
bonding experience. I mean, I really bonded with those guys. We've
already had a couple of reunions. The whole cast, Tom, myself _
we've already gotten together and had some cigars, some drinks and
a nice steak dinner. And literally told our war stories, reminisced
about the experience of making ``Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:Speaking of that, were you ever envious of the men in that
``Private Ryan'' platoon?
</P>
<P>
   A:I envied them to the point that I wore a Ranger jacket to work
every day. And I wore fatigues and I wound up picking up a terrible
habit, which is that I began smoking these dumb things. (Spielberg
pulled a short, stubby cigar from his shirt pocket.) Actually I
haven't smoked one in a long time. But on the movie ... gosh, some
of the guys smoked cigars and we were on the field of battle, and I
was smoking cigars with the guys.
</P>
<P>
   So yeah, I envied them. I still wear my dog tags (Spielberg
reached inside his shirt and pulled out a set of authentic military
dog tags hanging around his neck.) These are actual dog tags that
were minted in 1942. Every single soldier in ``Saving Private
Ryan'' wears a dog tag that was minted in the 1940s and was given
to us as a gift from the government. And it has the name, not the
name of the character _ some of them did, but (some) wanted their
real names on them.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's on yours?
</P>
<P>
   A:My name. I am my own character anyway!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
