<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS IN TIE FOR FIRST IN BRITISH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ As the winds subsided and the sun broke
through clouds over the Lancashire coast by the Irish Sea, Tiger
Woods stepped to the front of the opening round of Thursday's 127th
British Open at Royal Birkdale. The American phenom gave an early
hint that he might be ready to assert his considerable presence at
golf's oldest championship. Make no mistake about it, Woods was
hitting on all cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   He had arrived in Ireland last week to fish and play a few
relaxing rounds on the great links courses of Ballybunion and
Waterville, and the pressures he felt a year ago at Royal Troon in
Scotland as the reigning _ and runaway _ Masters champion seemed to
be ancient history. ``It's just learning to play golf,'' said
Woods. ``It's an evolution process I think every player goes
through. I'm no exception.''
</P>
<P>
   At Royal Troon, Woods had a quadruple bogey and two triple
bogeys cluttering his opening-round scorecard. He was wild.
Thursday, he was controlled, hitting a 2-iron tee shot on the
457-yard par-4 eighth and a sand wedge to within 40 feet of the pin
and two-putted. ``I think by coming over a week early has always
helped me in the past in the Scottish Open twice as an amateur,''
said Woods. ``We fished all the time over in Ireland. Unfortunately
the golf got in the way of the fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods's chance for sole possession of the lead evaporated on the
18th hole when his 8-iron second shot went over the green and he
lipped out a par putt from 8 feet. This brought him home at
5-under, (30-35_65) and in a tie with John Huston (34-31_65). They
were one in front of Nick Price, Fred Couples, and defending
Pleasant Valley champion Loren Roberts and two ahead of Rhode
Island's Brad Faxon, PGA Championship winner Davis Love, Vijay
Singh, Sweden's Fredrik Jacobson, and Australia's Robert Allenby.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard, who closed with a majestic 65 to triumph last
year at Royal Troon, painted himself in an early corner with a 73
that was marred by a double bogey on the par-4 13th. ``I'm
disappointed to shoot 3-over on a day when you know there's very
good scores out there,'' Leonard said. ``It's disappointing. I hit
the ball OK in spots, but the bad far overshadows the good today. I
just hit it in some bad places.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who stunned the golf world when he won the Masters by 12
shots at the age of 21, has struggled in subsequent major
championships and his best finish was joint eighth at Augusta
National this year. He was not struggling Thursday. On the 411-yard
ninth he pulled out his driver and split the fairway, then hit a
sand wedge to within 6 feet to set up a birdie. ``To me it makes no
sense to lay up,'' Woods said, ``when I can carry the bunker and
put it right on the green. There's no rough down there. The whole
key to it was to get it up and ride the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Huston in the opening-round hunt isn't
surprising, and he showed in Hawaii this year he can shoot low
numbers, firing a PGA Tour record 28-under 260. Huston closed with
an eagle on 17, sinking a 40-foot putt, and then dropped a 4-foot
birdie putt on 18. After an even-par 34 going out, Huston birdied
the 10th (8-iron, 6 feet), 11th (6-iron, 12 feet), and 12th
(6-iron, 8 feet). ``That sort of jump started my round,'' said
Huston.
</P>
<P>
   Huston, who holed out from the 18th fairway to lead the first
round of the Masters two years ago, has been bothered by tendinitis
and bursitis. At the start of the year he began sleeping on a
magnetic mattress. ``I've been sleeping on it. I travel with it,
and it seems to really help. It's a mattress cover, and it has
little magnets all throughout it. It feels like a bumpy mattress.''
</P>
<P>
   Price won the PGA Championship twice (1992, 1994) during a hot
streak when he was one of the game's dominant players; he won this
tournament four years ago at Turnberry. Thursday, he played what he
felt was a perfect round except for two shots that set up bogeys on
the first and 10th holes. ``They were the only two greens I missed
today,'' said Price. ``The biggest problem over the last six months
is I haven't putted solidly. I felt today I was starting the ball
on line.''
</P>
<P>
   The round for Couples could have been better, but it could have
been worse. He salvaged it with eagle putt the par-5 15th, but then
yanked his drive into heavy trouble on the par-55 17th and wound up
with a par instead of looking at a birdie on a reachable hole. ``I
feel like I'm very close to playing like I did,'' said Couples,
``when every time I went out I felt I was going to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
