<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-WORLD-COX     07-16 1937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WORLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take a more global view with these works from other lands
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 19: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no frigate like a book to take us lands away,'' poet
Emily Dickinson wrote. Maybe so, but even as the U.S. economy
becomes more global, our literature becomes less so.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times reporter Martin Arnold recently explored the
migrations of books across oceans and found that fewer foreign
translations are published in this country now than three or four
decades ago. ``Americans have become isolated from a literary point
of view compared to the '50s and '60s when there were lots of
translations here, of Sartre and Beckett and so forth,'' Richard
Seaver, co-publisher of Arcade Publishing, told Arnold. Today a
translated book usually sells only 3,000 to 6,000 copies, and few
publishing houses are interested. Industry people also cite
American discomfort with foreign languages and the lack of review
attention as reasons for the dearth.
</P>
<P>
   The United States tends to export more fiction than it imports,
even when imports are originally written in English. For example,
10 U.S. authors were listed among the 40 top fiction and nonfiction
best sellers in a recent London Sunday Times. The same sample from
the New York Times Book Review included only four titles by
English-writing non-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, few U.S.-born novelists, traditionally urged to
write about what they know, venture to set novels in other
countries; memoirs and biographies are more often the source of
foreign settings. Still, for readers who hunger to be taken to
other lands, there are some fine recent novels:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Once Upon the River Love.'' By Andrei Makine. Translated
from French by Geoffrey Strachan. Arcade. $24.95. 209 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Makine's ``Dreams of My Russian Summers'' (1997), winner
of two French prizes, was a masterful Proustian view of
contemporary Russia. In this earlier novel, Makine returns to 1970s
Russia in a coming-of-age tale about three boys caught in ``the
pendulum'' of Russian history. Their identities are forged by the
River Amur (Love): Utkin is crippled when he is caught in its ice
floes; Samurai barely escapes a gang rape on its shores; and the
narrator discovers his sexuality when he emerges from a swim. But
when they travel 20 miles over the frozen steppes to see a
Jean-Paul Belmondo movie in Nerlug, they are so altered that they
return 17 times. In the Red October Theatre, located ``between the
squat building of the local militia and KGB and the Communard
factory, where they manufactured the barbed wire that went to all
the camps in that region of Siberia,'' the boys glimpse a vision of
the West. The narrator imagines a mysterious, train-traveling
Western Woman, who is less an erotic fantasy than the embodiment of
the right to imagine and create. Ultimately, the three young men
travel to ironic futures. The narrator turns to filmmaking; Samurai
becomes a merchant marine; and Utkin, a would-be poet, moves to the
United States, where he discovers that empty prose is ``the deathly
ivy closing in on the West. The ivy of words that has killed
life.'' The only bad thing about this novel is that it ends.
Readers can look forward to Makine's next translated work in 1999.
His words are far from deathly ivy; rather, they are the river of
life, and, of course, love.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Way I Found Her.'' By Rose Tremain. Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux. $25. 359 pages.
</P>
<P>
   A teenage boy also narrates this fine work from Rose Tremain, a
British writer best known for ``Restoration,'' which was nominated
for the Booker Prize. The object of Lewis Little's affection is the
Russian-born Valentina Gavril, a popular medieval romance writer.
Lewis and his mother, a translator, leave Britain to spend the
summer in Paris working with Valentina. Lewis becomes acquainted
with an existentialist roofer, a floor-polishing maid from Benin
and a Russian historian crazy over Valentina, who is plagiarizing
his books since she has run out of ideas. Suddenly, Valentina
disappears and Lewis discovers that the French police are not of
the same caliber as Porphiry Petrovich, the detective in
Dostoyevsky's ``Crime and Punishment.'' Lewis uses language and
world literature to hunt for the woman he adores. Though it is
difficult to accept the narrator's precocity, and the ending is
grim, this book lingers in the memory like a good European
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Iron Tracks.'' By Aharon Appelfeld. Translated from the
Hebrew by Jeffrey M. Green. Schocken. $21. 195 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Aharon Appelfeld's world is far more grim than Tremain's, but
just as compelling. His latest translated novel, originally
published in 1991 in Jerusalem where he lives, examines forgiveness
and revenge by distilling the effects of the Holocaust into the
life of Erwin Siegelbaum. Siegelbaum's Communist parents were
killed in a Nazi camp that he barely survived. After liberation, he
spends 40 years riding the trains of Austria on a set schedule,
ostensibly trading in Jewish religious artifacts. He sleeps at inns
mostly run by Jews, romances women travelers and fights depression
with drink. He also practices shooting his pistol, because his real
business is looking for Nachtigel, the Nazi who killed his parents.
The action he takes when he confronts his nemesis makes for a
skewed, unsatisfactory ending. But the novel of conscience poses
immense questions: Can we forgive genocide? Should we?
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Snake Charmer.'' By Sanjay Nigam. Morrow. $22. 223
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Indian-born Sanjay Nigam, now a physician and medical researcher
at Harvard University, has written a gem of a fairy tale located in
modern Delhi. Though Sonalal is a great snake charmer, he is poor,
lacking the respect of wife or sons. One day, he takes his beloved
cobra Raju, and a new gourd that makes exquisite music, to play for
the tourists at Humayn's Tomb. It is an enchanted performance,
until, in front of foreign journalists, Raju stings Sonalal.
Sonalal then chomps Raju in two, resulting in global headlines:
``Snake Charmer Bites Cobra Back.'' Sonalal suffers enormous guilt.
He seeks salvation with an almost mythic prostitute, a quack doctor
who diagnoses everyone as homosexual, and old magicians. After his
sons refuse to become charmers and his friends die, he feels death
stalking him, too. When his second snake bites him, he no longer
can retaliate. Sonalal, though despairing over his toothless life,
remembers the day he played to the gods, the day Raju died. Nigam's
tale is as seductive as the charmer's music, the cobra's dance.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Cubana: Contemporary Fiction by Cuban Women.'' Edited by
Mirta Yanez. Translated by Dick Cluster and Cindy Schuster. Beacon.
$24. 213 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Woolf may have called upon women to find a room of
their own, but as Ruth Behar writes in her forward: ``In Cuba
housing is terribly scarce. Most of the contributors to this book
live with more than one generation of their families and writing is
done amid the ever-present interruptions from relatives and
friends.'' These 16 uneven stories mostly tell of a reality so
removed from our own that they are difficult to assess. Some of the
tales provide their own context. In ``Internal Monologue on a
Corner in Havana,'' Josefina de Diego writes in the voice of an
economist-turned-street-vendor, trying to sell her cigarettes for
food: ``To smoke or to eat, that is the question.'' Most Norte
Americanos will have no trouble grasping the ironies of
Cuban-American author Achy Obejas' ``We Came All the Way From Cuba
So You Could Dress Like This?'' And in Nancy Alonso's ``A Tooth for
a Tooth,'' a gift of eggs from an old political enemy is both a
taunt and a treasure. But other stories are seen through a glass
darkly. Still, for readers who want to enhance their knowledge of
Cuban literature, this is an important book to keep and reread as
other collections are published.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Ahmed's Revenge.'' By Richard Wiley. Random House. $23.95.
320 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Wiley teaches fiction writing at the University of
Nevada, Las Vegas, but he has lived and worked in Japan, Korea,
Nigeria and Kenya, locales that serve his prize-winning fiction
well. ``Ahmed's Revenge'' evokes a modern-ironic version of Isak
Dinesen. Nora Grant and her Canadian husband, Julius, run a coffee
farm in Kenya in the 1970s; when he is hideously murdered, she too
is endangered. She learns that Julius and her father, a former
minister of wildlife, have sold acrylic ivory tusks on the black
market, and now the Kikuyu ``Mr. Smith'' wants what Julius has
stolen _ or else. Nora, who doesn't know what was stolen or where
it is, enlists the help of Detective Mubia, who may or may not be
two-faced; Miro, a Nairobi opera singer; Ralph Bunche Road, owner
of a Kenyan tour company; and her father, who has written an
inaccurate book on elephants. And elephants _ particularly Ahmed,
the national symbol _ are at the heart of the mystery. As Nora
atones for the sins of father and husband, she learns cultural
respect and renegotiates life. This is a fearlessly imagined and
incredibly novel novel, noteworthy as well for its male author's
success in adopting a female voice.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few more recent books of interest:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Fifth Mountain.'' By Paulo Coelho. Translated by
Clifford Landers. HarperCollins. $23. 240 pages. A retelling of the
biblical tale of Elijah and the challenge of tragedy, from the
Brazilian author of ``The Alchemist.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Your Blue-Eyed Boy.'' By Helen Dunmore. Little, Brown.
$23.95. 282 pages. The British award-winning author tells the story
of Simone, a judge whose past threatens to destroy her career and
private life.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Caprice and Rondo.'' By Dorothy Dunnett. Knopf. $27.50. 539
pages. In Volume 7 of the House of Niccolo series, Nicholas decides
his future in Europe. The Edinburgh, Scotland, novelist has fans
galore.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Love and Terror.'' By Alan Jolis. Atlantic Monthly. $24.
337 pages. When Marie Antoinette escapes from prison, a police
chief substitutes his look-alike love to go on trial. An intricate
plot from a French-born author living in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Identity.'' By Milan Kundera. Translated from the French by
Linda Asher. HarperFlamingo. $23. 160 pages. Chantal receives
anonymous letters from an admirer and hides them from her lover.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The One Facing Us.'' By Ronit Matalon. Metropolitan.
Translated by Marsha Weinstein. $25. 296 pages. In this Israeli's
first novel, rebellious teenager Esther is sent from Israel to
Cameroon, where she pieces together the family past.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Iron Bridge.'' By David Morse. Harcourt Brace. $25. 436
pages. A U.S. author's tale of the attempt to build the world's
first iron bridge in Shropshire, England, in 1773 is told in
evocative prose and detail.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mitz: The Marmoset of Bloomsbury.'' By Sigrid Nunez.
HarperFlamingo. $18. 128 pages. A New York novelist cleverly
re-imagines the lives of Leonard and Virginia Woolf and their pet
in pre-World War II Europe.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``My Year of Meats.'' By Ruth L. Ozeki. Viking. $23.95. 366
pages. A Japanese-American narrator takes a look at America's beef
industry, often from the vantage point of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Loves That Bind.'' By Julian Rios. Translated from the
Spanish by Edith Grossman. Knopf. $24. 256 pages. Emil, abandoned
by the woman he loves, writes 26 letters about lovers from Proust's
Albertine to Raymond Queneau's Zazie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
