<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYPD-SCHROEDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grown-up Schroder ready to give his all for `NYPD Blue'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pasadena, Calif. _ Rick Schroder knows the knocks.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he would not have been the first choice of ``NYPD
Blue'' fans to replace Jimmy Smits this fall, or the second, third
or 1,000th. Knows he still takes ridicule for his child star past,
in the 1979 movie ``The Champ'' and the '80s NBC sitcom ``Silver
Spoons,'' and for changing his name from Ricky to Rick.
</P>
<P>
   Now all he has to do is hold his own against Dennis Franz, the
three-time Emmy winner whose Detective Andy Sipowicz is the show's
anchor, and who will be partnered with Schroder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go in there and earn my place on the show,''
Schroder says with confidence during Thursday's press briefing for
TV critics meeting here to preview the new fall season. ``They
wanted somebody who would not be intimidated by Dennis Franz, and I
went in (to the audition) thinking I have to stand up for myself
and not let Dennis intimidate me.''
</P>
<P>
   And apparently he succeeded. ``He's young but he's not a boy,''
says the cop drama's co-creator, Steven Bochco. ``He's a man. We
look for the best actors we can find, and this was the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we had something that clicked,'' says Franz, giving his
imprimatur to the controversial casting decision. ``Rick has an
honesty. I didn't see any pretending, I didn't see any acting.''
</P>
<P>
   But still. Rick Schroder, the winsome little wimp from ``Silver
Spoons,'' mixing it up in the urban grit with Sipowicz and all
those low-life perps? Icky Ricky?
</P>
<P>
   For those whose minds are perpetually on mental rerun, Schroder
is 28, married and the father of three, raising his family on a
ranch in Colorado. He has a blond crew cut, and while he won't pass
for the toughest guy on the block, he probably doesn't get carded
in bars these days. He hasn't made the perfect transition from
child star to adult that, say, Jodie Foster has, but he did get
generally good notices 10 years ago when he had a key supporting
role in ``Lonesome Dove.''
</P>
<P>
   That was also about the time his agent suggested he change his
name on credits from Ricky to Rick. ``People started making fun of
it,'' he says, adding that at least once he dissed them back. ``It
took on a life of its own, but it really doesn't bother me,'' he
says. ``My mom and my wife call me Ricky.''
</P>
<P>
   The child star legacy, he's not quite so blithe about. ``It's
been a struggle, but all good things are a struggle. That's what's
made me who I am today.''
</P>
<P>
   Just who he'll be on ``NYPD'' is still pretty much a mystery.
His character hasn't even been named yet. The working plan is for
Smits, who wanted other acting opportunities (and has a development
deal for a new ABC series) to do the first six episodes; his
character, Bobby Simone, will not be killed off. Schroder, playing
a newcomer whose gold shield is still shiny, will be partnered with
Sipowicz, a vet who sometimes struggles with burnout. (Kim Delaney,
who plays Detective Diane Russell, Simone's new wife, will
continue, but Bochco and co-creator David Milch are mum about how
that'll work.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to offer a lot of opportunities to go in a new
direction, to kick him in the butt and take him under my wing,''
says Franz, although he admits he's guessing, since Bochco and
Milch have not yet figured out Schroder's character.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he'll be, very occasionally, is partly naked, in one
of the series' trademark rear shots. And Schroder knows that there
the comparisons with Smits may be the unkindest of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tall, dark and handsome,'' says Schroder. ``I'm short,
blond and skinny.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my wife says I have a great one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
