<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SARATOGA-COX     07-16 2040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SARATOGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giddyup and go to Saratoga: New York destination offers more
than just racing
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saratoga Springs, N.Y. -- The 20th century careens toward the
finish line. Look in the rear-view mirror, and among the objects
getting smaller and smaller is horse racing in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bad day at the races,'' spoke one wise man, ``is better than
a good day anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, those words were delivered in a bygone era when racing was
esteemed as the sport of kings. In today's giddyup-and-go society,
a kick-back day at the track _ one-to-two-minute spurts of furious
action, separated by nearly a half-hour of waiting _ has become a
tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   Hallelujah, then, for this hallowed ground in upstate New York.
Saratoga Race Course, whose six-week season launches July 29 and
winds down on Labor Day, may not lure the swiftest horses or the
most skilled jockeys, nor offer the cushiest amenities. But, at 134
years young, the nation's oldest continuously operating track has
deftly blended elements of its distant past with such modern
conveniences as 875 TV monitors for close-ups of the races.
Somehow, the mix makes for a day that you wish would never end.
</P>
<P>
   Important aside: Even if you don't know a furlong from a
fetlock, or think post time is when the mail arrives, do not
hesitate to tag along with your horse-derelict spouse, relative or
pal. There's plenty to engage your interest _ not only at the track
but about the town. Saratoga is home to stately Victorian
architecture, soothing spas, arts with a capital A, antique stores
and atmospheric places for food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest route from Atlanta is a flight to Albany, N.Y.,
then a half-hour drive the rest of the way. Time permitted me to
catch a train out of Penn Station in New York for a leisurely 3 1/2
hours spent alternately staring out the window at the Hudson River
or at the Daily Racing Form in my lap. Between Poughkeepsie and
Schenectady, I caught a nap. By the time I'd reached the
whistle-stop station in the Springs, I was as refreshed and anxious
as a frisky colt in the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   A short taxi ride later, and I was deposited at either a
racetrack or the set of a Victorian-era movie under production.
Saratoga has aged gracefully, its wooden clubhouse floors, spired
roof and quaint seating for 15,000 all suggesting a bygone era.
Ignore the concession stand prices _ $7.75 for a tall, thin glass
of Moet &AMP; Chandon champagne, strawberry included _ and focus
instead on the architecture, the apparel, the country-fair flavor.
It's the type of place where the Leonardo DiCaprio character in
``Titanic'' would have spent a summer mucking stalls by morning and
talking his way onto millionaire's row for the afternoon's racing.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, listen closely, and you can hear that clock ticking off the
last seconds of the 20th century slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the first race, bettors and employees halt their
business and pause as an instrumental version of the National
Anthem plays. Some place their hands over their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Many women wear fancy dresses and shade-producing hats, while
men slip on sport coats _ all in keeping with the track's tradition
of elegant attire.
</P>
<P>
   Kid-friendly Saratoga welcomes families. Strollers and coolers
compete for space under oak, elm, maple and pine trees near the
gazebo and wishing well in the picnic areas behind the grandstand,
where some patrons never see a race and don't seem to care. A band
plays, artists and crafters display their equine-related wares and
hawkers peddle an array of snacks and refreshments _ Ben &AMP; Jerry's,
Carolina Barbecue, Italian ices and the local microbrew, North
Country.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys emerge from a white clapboard house that serves as their
quarters and stroll through the crowd toward the paddock, where
their mounts await. Shadowed by security guards who seem
superfluous, the tiny riders slow to fetch paper and pen from
youngsters nearly as tall as they are and cheerfully sign
autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Before one race, I walked behind the jockeys' building and
noticed the peerless Jerry Bailey talking strategy across a fence
with a suited man. I parked myself close enough to eavesdrop.
</P>
<P>
   I derived no special insight from the conversation, so I placed
my bet with the usual lack of confidence and made my way back to
the clubhouse to watch the jockeys in their colorful silks guide
the gorgeous animals around the dirt oval track. As the horses were
steered down the stretch, the T-shirted crowd at ground level and
the dapper upper crust in their private boxes rose as one, programs
or parimutuel tickets clutched in hand, to loudly urge on their
betting choice.
</P>
<P>
   Some races unfold on Saratoga's exquisitely manicured turf, or
grass, course. And, in a bow to the sport's European roots, hurdles
are placed on the track for one steeplechase race daily.
</P>
<P>
   Racing hard-cores will appreciate the guarantee of one
``stakes'' race, involving top-caliber thoroughbreds, on each card.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I stumbled across the Carousel bar, surrounded by
merry-go-round horses. Sipping a beer, I decided the difficult
choice here is not which horse to wager on but where to pass the
time at the track.
</P>
<P>
   I hated to see the last race end, but there was a town out there
to explore, if a small one. Two high schools are sufficient to
accommodate the 25,000 residents, fewer than the track's turnstile
count on many days.
</P>
<P>
   First stop: the Thoroughbred Racing Hall of Fame, lesser-known
of the two sports museums in these parts. (Baseball's Cooperstown
is barely two hours down the road.) The hall, just outside the
track's gates, mixes artifacts, such as old saddles and
turn-of-the-century paintings, with interactive features, including
audio bios of jockeys and race calls. Then it's a short stroll to
Siro's, the bar/restaurant, to cry in your beer (losers) or buy a
round for your group (winners).
</P>
<P>
   City center isn't far, with its shops and eateries. Stay the
course north on Broadway, the main drag, and don't be deceived by
the Salvation Army Center: Another block, and you're about to
invade the territory of the rich and famous. Horse owners and the
mile-high society _ Whitneys, Vanderbilts _ summer on this stretch
in fabulously refurbished three-story homes.
</P>
<P>
   The upper crust, and those social climbers who share their
tastes, do not want for post-race activities. The Saratoga
Performing Arts Center hosts the New York City Ballet and
Philadelphia Orchestra. There is an array of music festivals and
art galleries. Men with names ending in Roman numerals can break a
sweat with polo matches. The Victorian architecture is so
distinguished here that one storefront displayed a series of photos
titled ``Porches of Saratoga.''
</P>
<P>
   History buffs can immerse themselves in forts, monuments, an old
monastery and the casinos that operated during the first half of
the century, setting the gambling climate. If a Saratogian's office
building or home has not made the National Register of Historic
Places, he should feel left out.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond horses, the town is best-known, as its name implies, for
the naturally carbonated water flowing from mineral springs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Crystal Spa, I skimmed a menu with a la carte choices
from a simple bath or pedicure to a European facial or herbal wrap.
The packages range from the Rejuvenator ($47) to the ``The
Experience of a Lifetime,'' which runs $110, takes 2 1/2 hours and
features something called a Seasalt Loofah. Whatever, it's
perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   Preferring to save all available dollars for the betting
windows, I chose the basic bath. I shed my clothes and slid into a
tub of water that made my body tingle and relax, if only slightly.
You may get more stimulation from Magic Fingers in your hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the myriad non-equine attractions, a tour of the town
eliminated any doubt that this is horse country. Lawn jockeys
patrol front yards. Sculptures of horses stand sentry in front of
the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   You can bed down at the Turf &AMP; Spa or Thorobred Motel. Dine at
Bookmakers, the Stable Stop Deli or the Trackside Grill. Drink at
Trotters, Drafthorse, the Horseshoe Inn Bar &AMP; Grill or Gaffney's
Starting Gate.
</P>
<P>
   On race days, the local newspaper includes a four-page pullout
called the Pink Sheet devoted exclusively to racing. (Headline
writers refer to the track simply as the Spa.) Many buyers grab the
morning edition, lift out the Pink Sheet and discard the rest. One
day last summer, however, they would have missed the two most
prominent stories on page 1A _ a profile of a jockey and reports of
a racing bill in the state Legislature _ and the lead editorial,
with this headline: ``Paddock teaches kids nuts and bolts about
horse racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, one municipal nod to modernization is the
installation of ATMs. You may need them, unless you hit a long shot
at the track. The area's 1,100 rooms fill quickly, as do the homes
that rent out for one to six weeks, and nothing is inexpensive. My
spacious but ratty hotel room ran $150 per night, three times its
normal rate. But when ``no vacancy'' signs are flashing, who can
argue?
</P>
<P>
   The summer night, devoid of humidity or bugs, was the type you
wished would go on forever, like in ``American Graffiti.'' But
bar-hopping till just past 10 was enough for me. There was
tomorrow's Daily Racing Form to study and some sleep to log before
I would rise at dawn. I would soon experience one more reason to do
the 'Toga: 7 a.m. breakfast at trackside, watching horses exercise
through the morning mist.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: Delta offers three daily nonstops to Albany,
N.Y., which is a half-hour drive from Saratoga Springs. There's a
Saturday-Sunday only fare for $217 round trip, no advance purchase
required, or a 14-day advance purchase for $252, good any day.
Another option is flying to New York and taking a 3 1/2-hour train
ride upstate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: Saratoga County Chamber of Commerce,
1-800-526-8970.
</P>
<P>
   -- Racing details: Racing takes place at 1 p.m. daily except
Tuesdays from July 29 to Sept. 7 (Labor Day). Admission $6 to the
clubhouse, $4 to the grandstand. Call 516-584-6200.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   -- Saratoga Performing Arts Center. Features performances by the
New York City Ballet (through July 25) and the Philadelphia
Orchestra (July 29-Aug. 15). 518-587-3330.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mineral baths. Roosevelt Bath House, 518-584-2001; Crystal
Spa, 518-584-2556; Lincoln Baths, 518-583-2880.
</P>
<P>
   -- Saratoga National Historic Park. Offers 10-mile self-guided
driving tour, nature hike, cycling, picnicking and beautiful valley
views. 518-664-9821.
</P>
<P>
   -- National Museum of Dance. 518-584-2225.
</P>
<P>
   -- Children's Museum. Interactive, hands-on items for those ages
2-10. 518-584-5540.
</P>
<P>
   -- Yaddo Rose Gardens. Celebrating its 100th anniversary next
year, offer tours to view flowers and fountains. 518-584-0746.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bus tours. 518-587-3656.
</P>
<P>
   HOTELS
</P>
<P>
   -- The Sheraton is the largest in town, located one mile from
the track. 1-800-325-3535.
</P>
<P>
   -- Holiday Inn has just built a new tower with 18 suites and
rooms. Package deals offered during race season, one mile from the
track. 1-800-465-4329.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gideon Putnam is a Georgian-style hotel overlooking scenic
Saratoga Spa State Park. Located 1 1/2 miles from the track.
1-800-732-1560.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Adelphi is a Victorian-style hotel built in 1977,
furnished with museum-style antiques. Located 1 1/2 miles from the
track. 518-587-4688.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANTS AND BARS
</P>
<P>
   -- Siro's, near the track, offers fine dining and a large
courtyard for drinks and socializing. 518-584-4030.
</P>
<P>
   -- Parting Glass, a short walk from the track, is an Irish pub
with a full menu. 518-583-1916.
</P>
<P>
   -- Olde Bryan Inn occupies a former log cabin constructed in
1773, making it one of the city's oldest buildings. It specializes
in steak and seafood and is about 1 1/2 miles from the track.
518-587-2990.
</P>
<P>
   -- Original Saratoga Springs Brew Pub is not only the original
but the town's only authentic brewpub. It's about a mile from the
track. 518-580-2739.
</P>
