<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer series based on novel shows little of book storyline
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pasadena, Calif. _ ABC may be quietly burying one of the most
promising new series of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maximum Bob,'' based very loosely on the Elmore Leonard novel,
will get a seven-week run starting Aug. 4, when it wil air in
``NYPD Blue's'' timeslot at 10 p.m. Tuesdays. Traditionally, summer
seres are considered less prestigious than the big fall debuts,
although very occasionally, one pops through to success. Eight
years ago, CBS debuted ``Northern Exposure'' in the summer, and the
quirky little drama about Cicely, Alaska, went on to be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maximum Bob'' has some of the same off-center feel of
``Exposure.'' It's set in the fictional Florida town of Deep Water,
a place where the judge, ``Maximum'' Bob Gibbs (Beau Bridges) is a
flamboyantly corrput despot, his wife is a former Weeki Wachee
``mermaid'' turned psychic, the sherriff is obsessed with
competitive ballroom dancing, and two dim-bulb twins named Dirk and
Bogarde show up for little good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's billed as Elmore Leonard-land, fans of
Florida-noir novels will feel more like they're submerged in the
surreal dark comedy of Carl Hiaasen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a conscious effort to sort of lighten up the
darkness a little bit,'' executive producer Alex Gansa told TV
critics meeting here to preview the new fall season. (The show was
developed by film director Barry Sonnenfeld, who did the ``Addams
Family'' and ``Men in Black'' movies.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at first when you hear that you're not on the (fall)
schedule, which is everybody's ambition, you have a little bit of a
moment for pause,'' says Barry Josephson, the other exec producer.
``But summer's a great time to break a new show and something that
is a litte different, like this show is.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is ABC running ``Maximum Bob'' in the summer, it cut
down on the number of episodes it ordered, from the original 13 to
a mere seven. ABC execs say if the show succeeds, it will come back
in mid-season.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges is hilarious as Maximum Bob, an unrepentant, politically
incorrect pig.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one of the episodes, we deal with sexual harassment, where
suddenly all these women are coming out of the woodwork saying I
did that to them, I did this to them, I bit this woman in the
tush,'' Bridges says. ``I have to go to court to save my good name.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the end, when I've been exonerated, I get together with
my wife and she calls me a hound dog. And I say to her, 'Listen,
Leanne, you're right, I have been a hound dog ... But honey muffin,
I swear to you that I am trying to work my way up the evolutionary
ladder.' ''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ABC on CNN
</P>
<P>
   ABC News president David Westin offered both praise and implicit
criticism of CNN's handling of its Operation Tailwind story and
subsequent retraction and apology. Asked by TV critics about the
issue Thursday, Westin said, ``I know (CNN chairman) Tom Johnson
well. Nothing in his conduct has diminished my respect for him. I
think he's handled it in an exemplary fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But he went on to say that ABC News reporters would never be in
the embarrassing position of CNN correspondent Peter Arnett, who
was the on-camera reporter for the Tailwind story but later said he
had done very little of the reporting. (Arnett was reprimanded by
CNN.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our correspondents take responsibility for what they say on
the air,'' Westin said. ``At ABC, we would never, never do a
serious investigative piece and have a correspondent come in at the
last minute and do a voice-over. Our correspondents would never
stand for that and I would never tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford promotes new series
</P>
<P>
   Model Cindy Crawford got in her own little dig at CNN Thursday
as well, when she appeared before TV critics to promote her
upcoming (and provocatively titled) special ``Sex With Cindy
Crawford.'' The special, which airs Sept. 22 on ABC, is meant to be
informative, with Crawford acting like a journalist, even though
she freely admits she isn't one. One line of questioning was
whether the special would be credible, since it was produced by
ABC's entertainent division rather than its news division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or (produced by) CNN for example?'' Crawford asked, and then
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Titanic to go air live
</P>
<P>
   Celine Dion can't stop singing ``My Heart Will Go On'' and TV
can't shy away from the Titanic. On Aug. 16, Discovery will air
live film footage of the sunken ship during a summer underwater
expedition. ``Baby'' remote cameras will travel further inside
Titanic than ever before. The live broadcast will be seen in more
than 100 countries with simultaneous translation in Spanish,
Mandarin, Thai and Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Bob Longino , c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
