<SLUG> BC-COX-CZAR-YELTSIN-0717RESEND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reversing himself, Yeltsin chooses to attend czar's burial
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ President Boris Yeltsin reversed his
earlier decision and pledged to attend Friday's burial of Russia's
last czar, a final erratic twist in the nation's jumbled plans to
entomb Nicholas II and his family on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise announcement from the Kremlin, Yeltsin said
Thursday he would attend the service in the former imperial capital
of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth (about the executions) was concealed for 80 years,''
Yeltsin said. ``Tomorrow, the truth should be told, and I should
take part.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia will bury the fragmented skeletal remains of Nicholas,
his wife Alexandra, three of their five children and four family
servants. The family and their attendants were killed by a
Bolshevik firing squad in 1918, ending the 300-year reign of the
Romanovs of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's decision last month not to attend the ceremony
followed the refusal of the Russian Orthodox Church to acknowledge
the identification of the bones as that of the czar and his family,
despite exhaustive genetic testing and confirmation by an
international team of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   His decision started an avalanche of official backsliding over
what had been intended as a full-scale royal funeral designed to
celebrate Russian history and heal old wounds following the Russian
revolution and seven brutal decades of Soviet rule.
</P>
<P>
   After the church hierarchy and Yeltsin declined, a host of world
leaders, prominent royalty and Russia's top politicians decided not
to attend. The Russian government scaled back the ceremony,
spending less than $1 million on the three-day observance, which
began Wednesday in Yekaterinburg, the city where Nicholas and his
family were killed.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's pioneering reformer in 1991, Yeltsin prompted the
unearthing of the Romanov's remains from a shallow grave in
Yekaterinburg. Yeltsin's reversal Thursday came without elaboration
about his change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   A Kremlin statement said: ``Putting to rest the remains of
innocent people who were murdered, the present generation of
Russians is striving to atone for the sins of their predecessors.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, eight decades after he abdicated and was later
exiled to Siberia before his death, Nicholas and his family
returned to St. Petersburg. Their remains were carried in nine
small coffins, flown in an Aeroflot jumbo jet to the city's Pulkovo
airport and furnished a military honor guard.
</P>
<P>
   As bagpipes moaned and drums rolled, dozens of descendants of
the Romanov family, clad in black, followed the procession into the
St. Peter and St. Paul Cathedral, burial place of czars since Peter
the Great.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people quietly lined the streets to catch a glimpse
of the motorcade as it passed through the streets of St.
Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see the bones of the last emperor, to see history
being made, to be a part of it'' said Tatyana Salmina, 52, a worker
at a nuclear power plant who stood on a crowded sidewalk near the
czar's former residence, the Winter Palace.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional trim begins.)
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a local priest will preside over a simple ceremony
which acknowledges the family not by name, but merely as victims of
the Communist era. Wreaths will be laid, a choir will sing, cannons
will thunder and a short service will pray for the souls of the
entire family, including the two children whose bodies are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Patriarch Alexy II, head of the Russian Orthodox Church, has
sought to distance himself from the rites and will preside over a
rival service for the dead of the Soviet years at a monastery near
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
