<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-PAKISTAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SANCTIONS LIFTED, PAKISTAN MAKES MAJOR U.S. WHEAT PURCHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pakistan Thursday agreed to buy about $30 million
worth of wheat from the United States, increasing its planned
purchase to reward Congress and U.S. farmers for acting quickly to
remove sanctions imposed against the country for testing nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the U.S. wheat Pakistan bought is expected to come from
Washington state, which is the source of half the soft white wheat
exported by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had been barred from selling wheat to Pakistan
_ the largest importer of U.S. white wheat _ under the terms of
sanctions imposed after Pakistan and India tested nuclear weapons
in May.
</P>
<P>
   Congress this week passed a bill to exempt agricultural sales
from the sanctions, and President Clinton signed the measure into
law just 17 hours before Pakistan accepted bids for this week's
major purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan had planned to purchase 300,000 metric tons of soft
white wheat this week, and Australia offered to fill that order at
a lower price than did the United States. But Pakistan decided to
increase its purchase, to 500,000 metric tons, in order to steer a
sizable order to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan will now purchase 300,000 metric tons from the United
States and 200,000 metric tons from Australia. The value of the
U.S. purchase was estimated at $32 million by the Pakistani Embassy
and at $29 million by U.S. Wheat Associates, an export market
development organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting good rates, and we thought that when the U.S.
farmers and their representatives had put in so much effort, we
should buy more wheat from the United States,'' said Farrakh
Qayyum, the trade minister at the Pakistani Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Australians had offered us a very competitive price, but
we wanted the Americans to participate so we held the tender back a
few days to allow Congress to go ahead, and we decided to provide
some satisfaction ... that their efforts hadn't gone to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheat farmers, who are facing historic low prices because of the
Asian economic crisis and strong harvests worldwide, were delighted
to have a rare positive development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful news,'' said Christopher Shaffer, a
fifth-generation wheat farmer in Walla Walla and the chairman of
the Washington Wheat Commission. ``There was a lot of concern they
(Pakistan) would hold a grudge against us for the original embargo,
but it looks like we've been able to work through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan last year accounted for 40 percent of overall U.S.
white wheat exports and 37 percent of Northwest exports, according
to U.S. Wheat Associates. Pakistan purchased 2.2 million tons of
wheat from the U.S. last year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. wheat will actually be purchased from a variety of
exporters, who buy wheat from farmers and sell it to foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much needed dose of export demand at a time when we are
facing a shortage of storage space and a shortage of market,'' said
Jonathan Schlueter, executive vice president of the Pacific
Northwest Grain and Feed Association, which represents commercial
grain handlers. ``There will be fewer ground piles (of wheat) in
the Pacific Northwest as a result. This will move grain through the
system, and we need to get it moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlueter said the industry had expected that Australia would
win a sizable portion of the Pakistani purchase because Australia
had refused to impose agricultural sanctions against Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest lawmakers, including Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash.,
Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., and Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., pushed
hard to have the sanctions removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan has been a good trading partner and is seeking a good
relationship with the U.S.'' said Nethercutt, who was one of
several lawmakers called by Pakistan's ambassador to the United
States about the sale yesterday. ``The purchase is an indication
that they're grateful, rather than resentful, and now we have sold
300,000 tons we wouldn't have otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton was also pleased with the purchase, but said the plight
of wheat farmers demands greater action by the Clinton
administration. He sent a letter to Clinton urging him to
re-evaluate a broad array of sanctions, to implement more
agricultural export programs, to support agricultural research
projects, and to push harder to get U.S. wheat into China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commodity prices are hitting record lows and the fear of
bankruptcy looms for many in the agriculture community,'' Gorton
wrote. ``What we do today ... to help our farmers will determine
their economic viability for years to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
