<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON NET RISES 14 PERCENT IN SECOND QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by(New York Times News Service cnients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 Thm Boston Globe   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ BankBoston Corp. reported a 14 percent increase in
second-quarter earnings Thursday, as gains in fees earned from
fijancial servicer far outweighed losses from trading in volatile
emerging-markets securitieS.
</P>
<P>
   New England's second-largest bank said net income rose to $241.9
million, or $0.80 per diluted share, from $212 million, or $0.68 a
share, in the same period a year ago. The results beat Wall Street
expectations by $0.01 and were in line with a trend of rising
earnings from fee-related services across the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   Total revenues grew 11 percent to $1.1 billion, mainly on growth
an non-interest income services, which include fees earned from
deposit and automated teller machine activities, overseas
securities trading, private equity placements, and mutual fund
sales and other investment activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a nice diversity across the revenues,'' said
BankBoston's chief financial officer, Susannah M. Swihart.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's 16th-largest commercial bank, which has major
operations across Latin America, a capital markets unit and a
national consumer lending business, saw fees earned from financial
services rise 23 percent to $192 million from $156 million a year
ago. Overseas activities were generally profitable, although some
areas produced losses. Emerging market debt prices, including those
for Latin America, took a hit last quarter, mainly on financial
trouble in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a $4 million loss in emerging markets securities
trading, compared to profits of $28 million in the year-ago quarter
and $34 million in the first three months of 1998. The bank said it
had pared total loan exposure to Indonesia to $75 million from $200
million at the start of the year but lost $10 million on such
activities last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, emerging market turmoil lifted BankBoston's profits from
foreign exchange operations, which rose to $32 million from $20
million a year earlier. The company saw a general decline in
international commercial lending activities but reported an
increase in loans to Argentinian customers. Latin American
operations traditionally account for around 20 percent of the
company's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Net credit losses were $51 million, compared to $79 million a
year ago and $141 million in the first quarter of 1998.
Second-quarter non-interest expenses rose 13 percent year-on-year
to $647 million but declined on the previous quarter. All numbers
reflected BankBoston's recent 2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P>
   The results generally pleased banking analysts, who are sanguine
about the bank's expansion and restructuring plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fairly straight-forward quarter,'' said Ronald I.
Mandle of Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. BankBoston shares eased 13/16
Thursday to close at $56.58 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, with $70.5 billion in assets, is second in size in
New England to Fleet Financial Group, Inc., but it is expanding
rapidly in Argentina and Brazil and also has strong toeholds in
Chile, Columbia, Peru, and other regional countries. It bought
San-Francisco-based investment bank Robertson, Stephens Inc. in
May, acquiring the equity-underwriting, research, and advisory
services that many banks now seek. The $800 million deal is to
close in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
