<SLUG> BC-BKO-BIRD-WHEATIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD ALL BOXED IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Larry Bird's son, Conor, saw him on the cover of a Wheaties
box recently, the boy was somewhat surprised to discover his father
had once been a pretty good basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   Conor knew his dad mainly as the coach of the Indiana Pacers,
not as the Hall of Fame player for the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Conor won't be confused anymore _ unless he returns with
dad to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills announced Thursday it was putting Bird on the
cover of a Wheaties box for the second time, with two layouts. For
the cereal sold in Indianapolis, Bird will be the stoic coach of
the Pacers. For boxes sold in Boston, he will be in a Celtics
uniform, which he last wore in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bird previously graced the cover of a Wheaties box in 1995; that
one also was distributed in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said there will be 100,000 boxes on the
shelves in Indiana, Bird's home state. No figures were announced
for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   General Mills released a statement alleged to have come from
Bird saying he was honored to be chosen again. Still, Bird hasn't
caught up to Michael Jordan or Tiger Woods yet _ at least not in
the minds of those who market the so-called Breakfast of Champions.
Those two athletes, and six others, have been marketed nationally
on the cover of Wheaties boxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
