<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SIGN SPIRES, SHAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Patriots signed third-round draft pick Greg Spires
and sixth-rounder Harold Shaw to muliti-year deals Thursday. But
more importantly the team moved closer to deals on its first-round
picks Robert Edwards and Tebucky Jones.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that deals for both Edwards, a running back from
Georgia, and Jones, a defensive back from Syracuse, will run in the
4-year, $5.5 million-6 million range and will be at least partially
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots aren't opposed to guaranteeing money in order to
reduce signing bonuses. The team did it with Terry Glenn three
years ago when they guaranteed some of his five-year deal. In fact,
Glenn will have $1.25 million of his deal guaranteed this year and
next. He'll earn $1.6 million in 1998 and $2.05 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's No. 1 pick, Chris Canty, had $325,000 per year
guaranteed in his four-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Spires, a defensive end from Florida State and the 83d pick in
the draft, received a three-year deal worth just under $1 million
with a $350,000 signing bonus. Shaw, a running back from Southern
Mississippi, the 176th overall pick, signed a three-year deal
averaging $190,000 per annum with a $50,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have four draftees left to sign. Besides Edwards
and Jones, second-round pick Tony Simmons, a wide receiver and
fifth-round pick, Ron Merkerson, a linebacker have yet to sign
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to signing Spires and Shaw, the Patriots had inked tight
end Rod Rutledge, a second-rounder; fullback Chris Floyd, a third
rounder; and seventh-round pick Jason Andersen, a center from
Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   After all of the rookie money is paid out, the Patriots should
still be about $100,000 under the salary cap for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are also negotiating a one or two-year deal with
Adam Vinatieri's agents, Woolf Associates. Vinatieri is an
exclusive rights player and must accept the Patriots' offer, but
the team may want to tie him up long term.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have yet to respond to a proposal from Ted
Johnson's agent, Jack Mills, on a five-year deal, but the team
hopes to keep the talks alive during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots' coaches and personnel moved their base to Smithfield,
R.I., Thursday in preparation for the start of training camp, the
team's 23d, at Bryant College Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
