<HEADER>
A8832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-16 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: SETTLEMENT PAID IN PAINTINGS; SOTHEBY'S ON THE NET; 2
MUSEUMS FILL POSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the 13th graf instead of the symbol, non-transmittable to many
newspaper systems.) (mk) 
 BY CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a $5 million lead pledge to the Museum of Contemporary Art
in Chicago from its chairman went unpaid, the institution took
action.
</P>
<P>
   An out-of-court settlement was reached last week, but the museum
got two paintings instead of cash.
</P>
<P>
   When the museum began raising money to finance its new $50
million building, which opened two years ago on a two-acre site on
Chicago Avenue, Paul Oliver-Hoffmann, a real estate developer, who
was chairman of the museum's board, agreed in writing to give $5
million to help endow and operate the building.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in Cook County Circuit Court on Dec. 31,
1997, the museum said Oliver-Hoffmann's pledge was to be paid in
full by June 30, 1997. Documents filed in the case showed seven
payment forms and unanswered reminders dating from November 1991 to
June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not consider this a pledge but rather a letter of
intent, which is not a binding document,'' said Camille
Oliver-Hoffmann, the wife of Oliver-Hoffmann, who died in April.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver-Hoffman, who with his wife was a well-known contemporary
art collector, was asked to join the museum's board in 1981. Mrs.
Oliver-Hoffmann said he decided not to go through with the gift
when he began having differences of opinion with other museum board
members and with Kevin Consey, who was the director at the time,
over the museum's financial management.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband expected he would have a voice in the way the money
was to be allocated'' Mrs. Oliver-Hoffmann said. ``But, in 1990,
when he realized he wasn't going to, he resigned from the board and
never set foot in the museum again. Then, when he lay dying of a
terminal illness, we were sued.''
</P>
<P>
   To settle the case, Mrs. Oliver-Hoffmann agreed to give the
museum two works of art from her collection: ``Banner,'' a 1990
painting by Anselm Kiefer, and ``Cindy,'' a portrait of Cindy
Sherman from 1988 by Chuck Close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to end up in litigation, especially a nonprofit
institution,'' said Penny Pritzker, the museum's chairwoman. ``This
was an unfortunate and very unusual situation and we are glad it is
settled.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of paintings were made by the museum. ``We had no
works by Kiefer and only three works on paper by Close,'' said
Michael Thomas, a museum spokesman. ``These works fill some large
holes.'' Mrs. Oliver-Hoffman said, ``My husband was both dedicated
and devoted to the museum during his lifetime.'' She added: ``I
felt it was only fitting that he be honored this way. He would have
been happy to see these paintings hanging in the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Bookauction.com
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sotheby's began as a book auctioneer 250 years ago,
and in its first Internet auction is selling books.
</P>
<P>
   The sale consists of 122 lots of American, English and juvenile
literature; books on theater, opera and ballet; property from the
estate of Donald and Jean Stralem, New York collectors, and books
from the estate of James Heineman, a New York publisher. Also for
sale are a first edition of Nathaniel Hawthorne's ``Scarlet
Letter'' and an edition of Edgar Rice Burrough's ``Tarzan of the
Apes,'' as well as about 300 autographed Time magazine covers.
</P>
<P>
   Interested buyers may leave bids on Sotheby's Web-based bid
sheet, www.sothebys.com; bidding may also be done by e-mail to
book.auction(AT)sothebys.com, or by fax at (212) 774-5385. All bids
must be in by July 21, at 1 p.m. EDT. Sotheby's will then determine
who has made the highest bids and which bids meet the sellers
reserve, the secret minimum price agreed upon by the seller and the
auction house. Bidders will be notified whether they have been
successful within 10 days of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The auction house decided to test the Internet waters by selling
books rather than works of art, Sotheby's officials said, because
there was already an enormous amount of book buying on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an understanding that people buy books, sight
unseen,'' said David Reden, who runs Sotheby's book department.
</P>
<P>
   The books were on exhibit at Sotheby's York Avenue headquarters
the last two weeks in June and are now on view at Sotheby's book
department at 411 E. 76th St.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby officials said they carefully considered which books to
sell and purposely selected as wide a range of titles to explore
just what Internet buyers are interested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``By offering the books on the Internet, people won't have to
pick up the phone during business hours,'' Redden said. ``It's
amazing how much activity on the Internet takes place in the middle
of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewish Museum
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Museum in Berlin is gearing up to open its doors in
2000 in a new building designed by the Polish-born architect Daniel
Libeskind, and so is beginning to put a staff in place. This week
it named Tom Freudenheim, a German-born American, to become its
deputy director and chief operating officer beginning September
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Freudenheim was head of the Museums and Humanities Program at
the National Endowment for the Arts and has been a curator at the
Jewish Museum in New York. Most recently he has been the executive
director of the YIVO Institute for Jewish Research in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In his new job he will collaborate with W. Michael Blumenthal,
director of the Jewish Museum in Berlin, in shaping the museum's
core programs and permanent installations.
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Guggenheim curator Robert Rosenblum has been named
the first Stephen and Nan Swid Curator of 20th-century art at the
Solomon Guggenheim Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The newly endowed senior curatorial position, the first for the
Guggenheim, is to be held by a distinguished art historian and has
been given by Stephen Swid, vice president and treasurer of the
Guggenheim Foundation, and his wife, Nan Swid, founder of Nan Swid
Design.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
