A8851 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ABC-SFCHRON &LR;      07-16 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ABC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ABC, THIS YEAR'S SUPERMODEL IS JUST A TEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ You waken at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel, prop
yourself up in bed to read the day's schedule and see, firm for
noon, ``Sex With Cindy Crawford.''
</P>
<P>
   And because you are a television critic, the first thing you
think is, this could mean that the PBS portion of the press tour
has come to a close.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be apparent that ``Sex With Cindy Crawford'' is an
ABC special. While Crawford will be in attendance, the only
intercourse on anyone's card is over an interviewer's microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are less pleasant ways to contribute to a 401k.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Crawford was preceded on the schedule by Jamie
Tarses, ABC Entertainment president, and by ABC Entertainment
chairman Stuart Bloomberg, who graduated magna cum laude from
Georgetown University so that he could rave to critics about ``Boy
Meets World.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarses and Bloomberg have survived a year together at Disney's
disaster network, but no one is blowing boat horns.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is in the third year of a nasty ratings slump. There were
nights last season when its total viewing audience could have
erected pup tents in a phone booth. Frankly, I'm surprised that
Cindy Crawford isn't anchoring ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg, before launching into his perfunctory
bullish-on-the-new-season pitch, at least paused to acknowledge the
ugliness of the 1997-98 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played `Home Improvement' to death and weakened Tuesday
night,'' he recounted. ``We had critically acclaimed but
viewer-challenged dramas. TGIF (ABC's ``Thank Goodness It's
Friday'' lineup) relied too heavily on gimmick-oriented concepts.
And our movies failed to reach the right audience. Some might say,
any audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The usual reward for a season like that is a cigarette and a
blindfold. But wait: Bloomberg revealed that he's found the cure
for ABC's woes.
</P>
<P>
   Better movies. Shh _ don't let NBC hear this. But with Tarses
nodding earnestly at his side, Bloomberg said a key to ABC's
inevitable resurgence will be a ``strong and vibrant'' movie
package.
</P>
<P>
   It was the former head of movies and miniseries who got the
cigarette and blindfold. The new head of movies and miniseries,
Susan Lyne, is overseeing a roster of movie events that, on paper,
is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Gulliver's Travels'' and ``The Odyssey,'' NBC benefited
from producer Robert Halmi Sr. So ABC has hired him for
``Cleopatra,'' the miniseries, replete with sex and toga parties.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Dean Koontz miniseries, ``Mr. Murder.'' And a Stephen
King miniseries written for TV, ``Storm of the Century.'' And Tom
Clancy's ``Netforce.''
</P>
<P>
   In the made-for-TV movie category, Norman Mailer and director
Barry Levinson are involved in ``American Tragedy,'' about the
legal machinations in the O.J. Simpson murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Oprah Winfrey Presents'' franchise returns with two new
movies, including a ``David &AMP; Lisa'' remake. Christopher Reeve will
star in another remake, this one of the Alfred Hitchcock film
``Rear Window.'' Wes Craven (``Scream'') will launch a series of
scare movies on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The theatrical features in ABC's arsenal include ``The
Birdcage,'' ``Courage Under Fire,'' ``Escape From L.A.'' and ``Up
Close and Personal.'' Not great, but maybe serviceable.
</P>
<P>
   ABC could screw it up, though. After all, I fully expect this
network to screw up ``Sex With Cindy Crawford.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, this big emphasis on movies coincides with ABC's
elimination of the customary movie slot at 9 p.m. Sundays. Look
there in the fall, and you'll find ``20/20'' and ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is now movie night on ABC. That's the night when
everyone except crack addicts and certain species of tropical fish
is glued to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Mondays will be available, too, after ``Monday Night Football''
expires in January. And, Tarses said, ``20/20'' and ``The
Practice'' will have to be rested on some Sunday nights _ lest
viewers become too familiar with them, presumably.
</P>
<P>
   As if movies weren't enough, ABC is marching ahead with another
year of its ``TV Is Good'' advertising campaign. You know _ yellow
and black coloring, and phrases that are funny but also profoundly
sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If TV's so bad for you,'' asks one of the new spots, ``why is
there one in every hospital room?''
</P>
<P>
   Or: ``Don't just sit there. OK, just sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   Make one move, and Stu Bloomberg will kill you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
