A8854 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NAMES-TEX     07-16 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGARDING BASEBALL NICKNAMES: CREATIVITY HAS WANED, BUT THRILL IS
NOT GONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fresno Flash is borrowing a page from the Bard, discussing
what's in a name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call Will, `Thrill,' '' the Flash says. ``Rusty is `Rojo.'
Lee is `Big Stuff.' I call Lee, `Sugar Bear.' He calls me
`Sweetness.' I couldn't tell you why we each do that, but we do.
You get into a little pattern, and it takes off from there.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Bard might have said, a baseball player by any other name
would be just as well known.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that almost every baseball player has a nickname.
``Thrill'' is Rangers first baseman Will Clark. ``Rojo'' is left
fielder Rusty Greer. ``Big Stuff'' is designated hitter Lee
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the clubhouse, just about everybody has a nickname,''
Rangers manager Johnny ``Quaker'' Oates says. ``Very few people get
called by their name inside the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a name they brought with them, like Ivan
``Pudge'' Rodriguez or Juan ``Igor'' Gonzalez. Often it's a
diminutive of their last name, like Kevin ``Ellie'' Elster or
Darren ``Ollie'' Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make them up all the time,'' the Flash says. ``It gives
you something else to call a guy instead of using his formal name.
It kind of puts it on more of a personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``the Fresno Flash'' doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   The person speaking is center fielder Tom Goodwin, known to
Stevens as ``Sweetness'' and the rest of his teammates as
``Goody.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in baseball history, though, when a player with
Goodwin's speed who hailed from Fresno, Calif., might have been
known as the Fresno Flash.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the great nicknames in baseball history were bestowed by
sportswriters. The Sultan of Swat. The Iron Horse. The Yankee
Clipper. The Splendid Splinter. The Georgia Peach. The Rajah. The
Flying Dutchman. The Say Hey Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Times changed, though. As journalists began to turn a more
critical eye toward America's sports heroes and public figures, the
bestowing of nicknames by and large ended.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason that, although players rarely call each other
by their first names, the age of colorHgO|V%Xf{,{psynB$FE)!$V+) &Cx1f; 
XeW'K4z/YHVW/.H\6e%9
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
