A8865 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EARNINGS-COX     07-16 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke earnings on target
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Coca-Cola's full-steam-ahead approach to fending off
the ``Asian flu'' paid off in the second quarter, with strong sales
in the region contributing to strong earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company said income rose 4 percent to $1.16
billion, or 47 cents a share, excluding a 2 cent charge and a 3
cent gain. That compares with income of $1.11 billion, or 45 cents
a share, excluding a 7 cent gain, in second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 1 percent, to $5.15 billion, from $5.08 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The results were tempered by a 10 percent reduction in operating
income, caused by the U.S. dollar's strength against weakened
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is beyond anyone's control,'' Schroder Wertheim analyst
Carolyn Levy said of Coca-Cola's vulnerability to currency
fluctuations. ``There's too many things going against them at once
for them to be able to manage that.'' She added that another round
of currency devaluations could throw off future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   George Thompson with Prudential Securities was among analysts
who said the company should be able to keep the impact on earnings
from currency fluctuations in the 8 percent to 9 percent range for
all of 1998, as Coca-Cola Chief Financial Officer James E. Chestnut
has predicted. Usually, it's around 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite continued economic strife in some markets, Coca-Cola's
worldwide case sales surged 10 percent, which was the high end of
the range the company projected last month. To Levy, those sales
figures are the important numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earnings are much less important than the volumes,'' she
said. ``If the volumes continue to meet or beat expectations, the
stock will continue to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's shares, which hit a 52-week high Wednesday, closed
at $87.18 3/4 on Thursday, down 62 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Case sales rose 8 percent in North America, which accounts for
30 percent of Coca-Cola's sales. They rose 12 percent in Latin
America, the second-largest market, and 10 percent in Europe, the
third-largest.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 7 percent in the Middle and Far East region, despite
a 3 percent dip in Japan, which accounts for an estimated 18 to 20
percent of profits. Coca-Cola recently passed its first price
increase in seven years in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola and its bottlers have been countering the Asian
currency crisis by shifting to more affordable packaging, such as
returnable bottles, while increasing investment dollars in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   More coolers and vending machines are being added, resulting in
a strong second-quarter showing in some emerging markets like China
and India, with sales increases of 28 percent and 33 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the headwinds of currency, they're able to stimulate
volume growth and cash flow,'' said Andrew Conway, analyst with
Morgan Stanley, who remains bullish on Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Though most analysts exclude gains and charges when weighing
earnings, the company's second-quarter profits actually declined by
9 percent if the gain and charge are factored in. Using that
method, net income was $1.19 billion, or 48 cents per diluted
share, against $1.31 billion, or 52 cents per share, in the
previous period, which also included a 7 cent gain from the sale of
a company-owned bottler.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter gain of $78 million, or 3 cents per share,
came from Coca-Cola's sale of its company-owned bottling operations
in northern and central Italy to Coca-Cola Beverages, the company's
10th anchor bottler. CCB has taken over the European business from
Sydney-based anchor Coca-Cola Amatil.
</P>
<P>
   The $50 million charge, amounting to 2 cents per share, covered
a writedown of manufacturing assets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
