<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IWORLD17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Valenti: Safeguard intellectual property
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture
Association of America, best known for his role as the czar of
motion picture and television content rating, came to Summer
Internet World in Chicago with a new mission and a new cause:
fighting the theft of intellectual property on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti had been expected to talk about his speciality but
instead told the audience the entertainment industry was worried
the Web was a threat to his industry.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show about 14 percent, or about 13 million Web surfers,
routinely look for information about movies. There are roughly
10,800 corporate and fan sites devoted to movies. Valenti said the
popularity of movie and entertainment sites on the Web could lead
to what he called ''the invasion of the copyright snatchers.'' He
said intellectual property thieves are ``a hazard to America's most
wanted commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti confessed neither he nor his entertainment industry
colleagues fully understand the power of the Web as it relates to
intellectual property. He made it clear the entertainment community
was not looking to prevent Web development. In fact, he said the
Web would ultimately use more and more streaming, or live, video
and audio components generated by his industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''The movie business is an unpredictable, chancy and expensive
business,'' he said. ''We have to find new revenue streams in order
to survive.'' He suggested pay-per-view movies on the Web were just
one way to generate revenue and help keep intellectual property
issues under control.
</P>
<P>
   Although he floated a few temporary solutions to the question of
property and copyright, in the end Valenti thinks only the
government can keep emerging technologies from co-opting
entertainment content on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ''If these creative enterprises are not protected from
poachers,'' he concluded, ''it will haunt us and shrink computer
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
