r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SPIELBERG-2TAKES     07-16 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SPIELBERG-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMBAT-READY SPIELBERG REVISITS WORLD WAR II IN `PVT. RYAN'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RUTHE STEIN &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Steven Spielberg first got the urge to make
a movie, at age 13, he didn't have to look far for a subject. His
father, a World War II veteran, had ``intoxicated me with bedtime
stories about the war,'' Spielberg recalls. ``His stories were like
the war movies I was watching on TV _ all worthy of cameo
appearances by John Wayne.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg cast his seventh-grade buddies in a war drama,
``Fighter Squad,'' outfitting them in the leather flier helmets,
big tinted goggles and bomber jackets his father kept around the
house. A year later, in 1960, he featured the war-surplus family
Jeep in ``Escape to Nowhere,'' an action picture in which GIs
invade a Nazi stronghold in the Libyan desert (simulated by the
Arizona desert near his house).
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's fascination with the war continued after he started
making movies for real. Of the 17 features he has directed, four
(``1941,'' ``Empire of the Sun,'' ``Always'' and the Oscar-winning
``Schindler's List'') have some connection to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is back with ``Saving Private Ryan,'' his most realistic
depiction yet of his father's war. Set during the Normandy
invasion, the movie follows a ragtag group of soldiers (Tom Hanks,
Edward Burns, Tom Sizemore and Jeremy Davies) on a mission to
rescue the remaining son (Matt Damon) in a family that has lost
three boys in action.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg is flying around the country in a private jet to
advance the film. The last time the publicity-shy director traveled
to promote a film was 17 years ago for ``E.T.,'' and then he made
only a few stops. Determined not to seem like a rich guy, he is
quick to point out that the plane isn't his. ``I don't have a
plane,'' he adds, never mind that with a net worth estimated at $1
billion and films that have grossed almost $5 billion, he could
afford a fleet of them.
</P>
<P>
   Settling into a corner armchair in an elegant hotel suite,
Spielberg establishes eye contact and maintains it without once
looking away. He is dressed formally for him, in a tweed sport coat
and open-collar blue shirt. His hair is graying and he has a bald
spot; yet his earnest, open manner makes him seem more like a kid
than a 51-year-old father of seven.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is part owner of DreamWorks, the studio that is
bringing out ``Saving Private Ryan,'' he hardly can be accused of
hyping the film. In fact, Spielberg says, the main reason he agreed
to tour is that he feels ``a duty to warn people'' about the
graphic battlefield scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want people to know that this movie is extremely close
to reality. It doesn't glorify or titillate, as violence in summer
movies usually does. This movie in effect may resensitize people
who thought they were desensitized to violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The carnage begins almost immediately with a wrenching sequence
on Omaha Beach before any of the characters are developed.
Spielberg says he did this deliberately so the audience would not
be able to sit back as in most movies and just be spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt in a sense that the Omaha Beach landing was not unlike
basic training for an audience, that once they got through that _
if, in fact, they allowed themselves to get through it _ they would
be on the alert just as our kids are aware as they walk through the
hedgerow of France looking for Pvt. Ryan that any moment something
like that could happen to them again.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that ``Saving Private Ryan's'' R rating is
``the hardest R you can be given'' and that the film is ``very much
on the edge,'' he thinks it would have been a shame if it had
received an NC-17. For one thing, it would have kept away people
the same age as a lot of the soldiers who died on Omaha Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for me to say none of my kids (six are younger
than 13) are going to see the picture, and it's also important for
me to say I wouldn't even accompany a 14-year-old to see it. I
would basically make the cutoff point 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg believes that he would have enlisted in World War II,
which he was taught was justified. However, he had no such thoughts
about the Vietnam War and tried his best to get out of going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just that I had objections to that war, I was afraid
of getting killed,'' he says. ``I went to a psychiatrist, you know,
to try to get a letter to get out of Vietnam. After a year with the
psychiatrist, I said, `Look, I'm leaving now, but can I have a
letter that says I'm not fit to serve?' He said, `No, I don't
believe in writing letters.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Spielberg, when a draft lottery was called he
was given a very high number (based on his date of birth). ``That's
the only reason I didn't go to Vietnam,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up in Hollywood instead. If ``Easy Riders, Raging
Bulls,'' a gossipy new book about the wunderkind directors of the
'70s, is to be believed, Spielberg was one of the few who didn't
self-destruct through excessive behavior such as womanizing and
doing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't ever use drugs,'' Spielberg says. ``I had no
curiosity about them, and in fact I had a healthy fear of them
because I wanted to be a director. I thought directing meant total
control, and I felt that if I ever, you know, took drugs I would
lose control and therefore I would lose a chance to be a
filmmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
