</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR SAFETY: DWI MOTORISTS LOSE LICENSES, THEN CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, N.C., Calif.)  (Duplication warning: Also moving in `f' category) 
(bl) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A person convicted more than once of driving under
the influence of alcohol usually faces the suspension or revocation
of his or her driver's license. But many people who lose permission
to drive still get behind the wheel, so a growing number of states
have taken a more forceful response: instead of telling the driver
to hang up the keys, they take away the car.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials say most of the people whose licenses
are suspended or revoked keep on driving. No one knows how many,
and the problem is referred to as an ``invisible violation,'' since
an officer has no way to tell that an unlicensed driver is on the
road, short of pulling the car over and running a check.
</P>
<P>
   Unlicensed drivers constitute a high percentage of a large
number of people. For example, a survey by the National Sheriffs'
Association found recently that in Salt Lake County, Utah, with a
population of 850,000, at any given time an average of 50,000
drivers were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is particularly frustrating for police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't surprise me a bit if two-thirds of them still
drive,'' said A.N. Moser Jr., executive director of the
association, referring to people nationwide whose licenses were
suspended or revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if confiscating cars was too extreme, Moser said, ``If
that's their vehicle they're driving, I'd seize that and sell it so
fast it would make their heads swim.'' Repeat drunken drivers
impose a high cost on society in deaths, injuries and property
damage, he said, and the alternative _ locking up the driver _ is
costly, too.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one states permit confiscation of vehicles, according to
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, some for 30
days or longer, and some permanently. A recent study in California
found that taking the car away does not solve the problem, but it
can help.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Motor Vehicles followed 6,300
drivers whose licenses had been suspended or revoked. Among first
offenders, they found that of those whose cars were not seized by
the courts, within a year about 25 percent were convicted for
driving without a valid license. Among those whose cars were
confiscated, only about 20 percent were convicted for driving
without a license.
</P>
<P>
   Among repeat offenders, seizure was even more effective; again,
about 20 percent of those whose cars were taken were convicted for
driving in the first year, compared with about 30 percent for those
whose cars were not taken.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important measure was the number of crashes.
About 40 percent of those whose cars were seized were involved in a
crash in the next year. For repeat offenders whose cars were not
seized, the figure was about 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A different study found that in 1993, 12 percent of the crash
fatalities in California _ nearly 500 people _ occurred in
collisions involving drivers whose licenses were suspended or
revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Canadian researchers have found that a high
proportion of fatal accidents are caused by hard-core drinkers. In
a 1996 report, the Traffic Injury Research Foundation, in Ottawa,
said, ``Administrative impoundment and immobilization of vehicles
being operated by suspended drivers appears to be an efficient and
effective means of bolstering license suspensions and preventing
repeat DWI behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But taking a car doesn't always do the trick, Moser said. He
pointed out, with only slight exaggeration, ``In California they
have five vehicles per family.'' And drivers who lose both their
licenses and their cars can still get their hands on the keys to
cars belonging to employers, relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Taking away cars can cause unexpected problems, as North
Carolina discovered this year. A law that took effect last Dec. 1
allowed police to seize vehicles from drivers caught behind the
wheel after their licenses had been suspended for alcohol
violations. The first seizure was made less than two hours after
the bill took effect.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature voted that the cars and trucks should be
given to local school boards, which could auction them and keep the
money. But the school districts complain that under the law they
cannot sell the cars until the drivers are convicted in court, and
that can take months. In fact, at the end of April, more than 2,300
vehicles had been seized in the state and hardly any had been
released for sale. The towing and storage costs exceeded the market
value of many of the vehicles. And school superintendents complain
that they are not familiar with the car auction business, and they
do not want to be.
</P>
<P>
   Also, banks complained that they had a larger interest in many
of the vehicles than the drivers being punished. And North Carolina
and other states have also found it difficult to handle cars that
are owned not by the driver, but by a friend or a rental car
company.
</P>
<P>
   A leader in getting tough with drunken drivers, North Carolina
is now considering changes to its impoundment law.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of seizing cars is spreading, and Congress has
partly endorsed that approach in a new law requiring the states to
enact tougher minimum penalties for drivers convicted twice or more
for alcohol violations. One way for states to meet the requirement
is to enact a vehicle-impoundment law; others include mandatory
license suspensions for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   States that do not pass such laws will have some of their
federal highway construction money diverted to safety programs. The
federal rules take effect on Oct. 1, 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
