<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PROFIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta: $1 billion profit for fiscal year
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Delta Air Lines' advertising campaign says passengers
have a ``million different reasons to fly.'' Thursday's earnings
announcement provided a billion reasons why the carrier is glad
they do.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta logged its first $1 billion annual profit in
the fiscal year that ended June 30, up 13 percent from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   The milestone was achieved with a fourth-quarter surge that saw
profits climb 20 percent to $362 million, or $4.52 a share, vs.
$301 million, or $3.90 a share, in the same quarter a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter rose to $3.76 billion from $3.54
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also said it filled just over 76 percent of its seats in
the quarter, a record, and 72 percent for the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy ridership, coupled with a continuing decline in fuel
prices and higher overall fares, has boosted profits across the
airline industry this year. Delta paid 52 cents a gallon in the
latest quarter, down from 60 cents a year earlier. Fuel is
typically an airline's second-biggest expense behind labor.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's quarterly result beat Wall Street consensus estimates,
but the carrier's stock descended Thursday. It had surged as high
as $143 earlier this week after Delta announced plans for a 2-for-1
split. Analysts said investors were expecting even better quarterly
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   For the full fiscal year, Delta said the $1 billion profit,
which compared with $854 million a year ago, equated to $12.68 per
share vs. $11.03 a share. Revenue totaled $14.13 billion, up from
$13.59 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Chief Executive Leo F. Mullin said the annual profit
reflects the airline's ``underlying financial strength as well as
our continued ability to deliver strong margins and operating cash
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our management team is clearly focused on building upon
Delta's strong core franchise to deliver superior financial
performance while making important investments to strengthen
Delta's customer service, operational performance and technological
infrastructure,'' Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   The fiscal-year profit will translate to more than $180 million
in profit-sharing payouts to employees, Delta said. The airline has
about 68,000 workers, about 26,000 of them based in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The payouts, which a spokesman said will amount to 6 percent of
annual base salary for domestic workers, will be distributed in
early September. Last year's payout was 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
