<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SPIELBERG-2NDTAK     07-16 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SPIELBERG-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SAN FRANCISCO _ a filmmaker.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg says he is crazy about the directors who came up with
him. George Lucas, with whom he collaborated on the ``Indiana
Jones'' movies, was driving in from Marin County to visit later in
the day, and Spielberg was about to call Francis Ford Coppola to
congratulate him on winning $80 million in his lawsuit against
Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Spielberg quips, ``Francis has made more money
suing a studio this year than I have made running one.''
</P>
<P>
   While Spielberg is no less intense about filmmaking than he was
in his younger days, he now takes time off to be with his wife,
actress Kate Capshaw, and their large brood. He realized the
necessity of this when he came home after filming one evening and
his 18-month-old ``took one look at me and said, `Bye-bye Daddy.'
That spun me right around.''
</P>
<P>
   So following the one-two punch of ``Jurassic Park'' and
``Schindler's List,'' he didn't make another movie for three years.
Spielberg is in the midst of another hiatus after shooting ``The
Lost World,'' ``Amistad'' and ``Private Ryan'' all in one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned how much I love being at home and how much I love
having my kids know I'm at home. I've been car-pooling all this
year, and I do all the breakfasts in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg has found a way to stay involved even when he has to
go to his office at DreamWorks, where he produces and develops
scripts. ``We have a big blackboard in the kitchen where
everybody's activities are charted. So when I get home from work, I
know where they have been and can talk to them about their play
dates. If my day was casting `Private Ryan,' we'll talk about
casting `Private Ryan.'
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our kids are leaders. We have no followers, which makes
our family very noisy. It would be an interesting sitcom. Every day
something amazing happens and I think, `My God, if that were on TV,
I'd be on the floor laughing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg and Capshaw have been married nine years; it is by
most accounts a happy marriage, unlike his first one to actress Amy
Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love at first sight is a wonderful thing for romance novels,''
he says, ``but marriages truly only work when you work at them. If
I'm making a picture, the family is with me. That is totally key.
You can't be off four months away from each other making phone
calls every day. You can't have a marriage on the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Spielberg will take his family to Japan, where he
will begin shooting ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' based on the
best-selling novel. ``It's a wonderful melodrama,'' he says, ``and
I've never done a real melodrama.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
