<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODD HAPPENINGS AND JUXTAPOSITIONS  
 NEW VIDEO RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE LUXURY OF STOPPING: A Ross McElwee documentary is just about
perfect for video. Since he usually chronicles his own life in
films like ``Sherman's March'' (1986) and ``Time Indefinite''
(1993), the dramas couldn't be more intimate. Given McElwee's eye
for odd happenings and juxtapositions, the scenarios are also
provocative enough to make one want to pause and ruminate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pleases me that on video people have the luxury of
stopping,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His latest documentary ``6 O'Clock News'' (1997), recently
released on videotape by First Run Features, fits neatly because it
is about the medium of television. In fact, unlike his earlier
films, it didn't get an extensive theater showing primarily because
it was first broadcast on the ``Frontline'' television series.
</P>
<P>
   In this context ``news'' refers to disasters. Fires rage,
schoolyards are sprayed with automatic weapons fire and in South
Carolina there has been a hurricane called Hugo. McElwee gets news
of the devastation on television in Boston and decides to take his
camera and fly down to check on the fortunes of Charleen Swansea,
his formep high-school English teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swansea, a fixture in McElwee films, lives on an island near
Charleston. He finds her in a state of dread over conflicting and
inaccurate reports of total destruction. Ferried out to the island,
she finds her place damaged but standing.
</P>
<P>
   On top of everything else, the storm is rumored to have produced
grapefruit-size balls of ants that are attacking people.
Corroboration fails to materialize about this and other tales, but
as he wanders about, McElwee begins to notice how the storm has
totally destroyed entire blocks and left other areas directly next
to them virtually untouched.
</P>
<P>
   From this observation springs rapidly evolving McElweeian
reflections on the total randomness of life and the deceptiveness
of appearances. That starts him watching the news all the more
intently for people and situations that appeal to his sense of
fate. Spotting a scene of particular pathos, he packs his camera
and goes off to get to know the afflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's lost love (``Sherman's March'') or the vagaries of
sudden personal tragedy (``Time Indefinite''), McElwee films take
their surprises, which are sometimes considerable, without missing
a beat.
</P>
<P>
   In ``6 O'Clock News'' he goes to Arkansas to film and interview
Steve Im, a Korean merchant whose wife was killed during a robbery
attempt at their store in Mississippi. Describing his feelings at
the sight of Im's face on the news, McElwee says that he feels
compelled to find out what has become of this tortured,
forlorn-looking man whose life was torn apart that day several
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, he is met by a dapper businessman in a
chauffeured Lincoln. Im, it seems, now owns a restaurant and a
pulp-wood business and is worth $6 million. The woman who stays
sedately in the background is his new wife, Miss Korea of 1974.
``She's good with the children, this one,'' Kim says.
</P>
<P>
   McElwee takes it all in and moves along to other victims around
the country. Always there are questions of perception and reality.
Earlier in the film, the 6 o'clock news in his town has heard about
this filmmaker who chronicles his own life. They want to do a
feature about him, and he invites them into his house, filming them
as they film him. The interviewer asks the usual question: When is
he going to give up documentaries and go to Hollywood to make a
real film?
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   GREAT EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   1997. Fox. $104.16. Laser disk, $39.98. 111 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's Dickens a go-go in Florida as young Finn (Pip in the novel)
grows up artistically inclined and hopelessly smitten with the
lovely, haughty Estella. Miss Havisham is now Nora Dinsmoor (Anne
Bancroft), spruced up and ready to party, and Magwitch, Dickens'
escaped convict, is called Lustig (Robert De Niro) and has mob
connections. Later, in New York, Finn (played as an adult by Ethan
Hawke) electrifies the art world and again encounters Estella
(Gwyneth Paltrow), who's still haughty but a little nicer. In sum,
Alfonso Cuaron's film is saved by it's look, which, Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, ``makes up in visual exoticism some of
what it loses in character and context.''
</P>
<P>
   FOUR DAYS IN SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   1997. Miramax. $104.16. Laser disk, $39.99. 105 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To protest government death squads and torture, students kidnap
the U.S. ambassador to Brazil (Alan Arkin), which happened in 1969.
What is achieved is arguable as the dissidents are caught and
tortured themselves. In real life, democracy didn't return until
1989, partly because, Bruno Barreto's film suggests, student
terrorism only fueled the tyranny. As for his gripping but often
clumsy semi-fictional account, it ``presents a disturbingly
ambiguous and unromantic portrait of retaliation against
oppression'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KRIPPENDORF'S TRIBE
</P>
<P>
   1998. Touchstone. $104.16. Laser disk, $39.99. 94 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left in a funk when his wife dies, an eminent anthropologist
(Richard Dreyfuss) blows a $100,000 grant on playthings and
household expenses. To explain what happened to the money, he
invents a lost tribe he says he has discovered called the
Shelmikedmu, an amalgam of the names of his children (Shelly,
Mickey and Edmund), who are obliged to play tribe members.
Complications multiply, but Todd Holland's film ``maintains a
focused plot, keeps its characters in character, uses its
imagination and disdains dumb, irrelevant jokes'' (Lawrence Van
Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   ZERO EFFECT
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $104.16. Laser disk, $34.98. 115 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a new hero, Jake Kasdan's film drums up a brilliant
nerd from the Northwest. A wealthy recluse, Daryl Zero (Bill
Pullman) makes a poor man's Sherlock Holmes, aided by a
disrespectful Watson (Ben Stiller). For a case to work on, there is
the blackmail of a timber tycoon (Ryan O'Neal), but that gets
sidetracked by a woman (Kim Dickens) who distracts Zero and robs
the film of ``some of the wit that kept its early episodes lively''
(Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television:
</P>
<P>
   IMAGE OF AN ASSASSINATION: A NEW LOOK AT THE ZAPRUDER FILM. The
famous home movie of the bullet's impact when President Kennedy was
shot has been digitally enlarged on a videotape that includes
commentary by photography experts and representatives of the
National Archives. 1998. MPI. Videocassette: $19.98, 45 minutes;
digital video disk, $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   PRETTY VILLAGE, PRETTY FLAME. A tunnel dating to the days of
Yugoslavia under Tito becomes a symbol of unification as well as
the hiding place for a detachment of Serbian troops under attack by
Muslims in the 1990s. Flashing back and forth between factions and
time periods, Srdjan Dragojevic's film pounds relentlessly at the
insanity of the war. 1997. Fox Lorber. $89.98. 128 minutes.
Serbo-Croatian with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   TIGHT SPOT. Available on tape for the first time, Phil Karlson's
fine little thriller about a gangster's woman stars Ginger Rogers,
Edward G. Robinson, Brian Keith and Lorne Greene. 1955. Columbia
Tri-Star. $19.95. 97 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   SEVEN YEARS IN TIBET. No, not the Jean-Jacques Annaud adventure
starring Brad Pitt but the British documentary with Heinrich
Harrer's original 16-millimeter film, shot in 1939 and 1940, of his
trek in the Himalayas and sojourn in Tibet. 1957. Kino. $24.95. 79
minutes. Black and white.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHARLIE CHAN COLLECTION. By the 1940s, the series based on
the novels of Earl Derr Biggers about the Chinese detective (Sidney
Toler) with the No. 1 and No. 2 sons had become formulaic. The
following _ all made in 1944 _ were fun nevertheless (and made in a
hurry): ``Charlie Chan in the Secret Service,'' ``Meeting at
Midnight,'' ``The Chinese Cat,'' ``The Jade Mask'' and ``The
Scarlet Clue.'' MGM. $12.95 each. Running times are about 65
minutes each.
</P>
</TEXT>
