<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS URGE SENATE TO AMEND BILL ON INTERNET TAXATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's governors urged the Senate on Thursday
not to adopt a six-year ban on new Internet taxes, saying states
could lose billions of dollars as commerce on the Internet
explodes.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Scheppach, executive director of the National Governors'
Association, told the Senate Finance Committee that states already
lose $4 billion annually from not being able to tax mail-order
sales. And he estimated that by 2002, states would lose between $15
and $20 billion in revenue from a sales-tax ban on both mail-order
and Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce on the Internet continues to grow as consumers
increasingly turn to their computers to buy goods ranging from
stocks to books. By the year 2002, $300 billion worth of business
will be conducted on computers, according to Commerce Department
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Scheppach urged the committee to drop the Senate's proposal for
a six-year ban on Internet taxes and adopt a measure similar to a
House bill that calls for a three-year moratorium on new Internet
taxes. The House bill also would ban the practice of making
customers pay taxes in both the resident state and the state from
which the good arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Scheppach also warned against a permanent ban on Internet taxes,
saying retail businesses that were unable to sell their products
over the computer would be at a ``perpetual disadvantage'' to
competitors who were on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Harley Duncan, executive director of the Federation of Tax
Administrators, an organization that represents state tax
collecting agencies, also criticized the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Senate measure used very broad language that would
make it difficult for state tax agencies to interpret which types
of business transactions on the Internet should be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan also called on the Senate to pass a measure similar to
the House bill, which he said would provide tax collectors a better
idea of what can and cannot be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   The House measure, which was passed in June, also would
establish a temporary two-year commission, made up of business
executives and officials from state and local governments, that
would work on ways to fairly tax the sale of goods on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
