<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK VIDEO FESTIVAL OFFERS A UNIVERSE OF INTIMATE VIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Calif.)   (js)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly 20 years ago, a catchy hit song called ``Video
Killed the Radio Star'' by a group called the Buggles eerily
presaged the rise of MTV and the revolution in pop-music marketing
that the promotional video clip was just beginning to incite.
Today, when the mindless star-studded ``event movie'' has risen to
become the economic cornerstone of the film industry, the time is
more than ripe for an upstart video artist to concoct a similar
fantasy that might be dubbed, ``Video Killed the Movie Star.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of the $20-million-a-picture movie-star salary,
that's not going to happen any time soon. But as suggested by the
work shown in the New York Video Festival, which opens Friday at
the Walter Reade Theater, video art, that unruly stepchild of
television and experimental cinema, has flowered into a vast,
immensely creative alternative culture. At its most inventive, as
in ``Flat Is Beautiful,'' Sadie Benning's 50-minute video evocation
of preadolescent angst in a nontraditional Midwest household,
experimental form and conventional narrative fuse into something
extraordinarily original and touching.
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the bewildering array of styles, technologies and
attitudes in the festival, which runs through Thursday and is a
part of Lincoln Center Festival '98, you almost have a sense of the
universe expanding at the speed of light after a spontaneous
explosion. Within the territory being mapped, there's nary a movie
star to be found.
</P>
<P>
   While it's risky to generalize about the flowering of video art,
a few broad trends seem obvious. The home video camera leads people
into much more intimate and quirkier spaces than the movie camera.
Where movies monumentalize their subjects, video banalizes them,
reducing everything to a collection of dancing pixels. Where movies
are great at conjuring beautiful dreams, videos tune us in to the
gritty day-to-day texture of ``the real world,'' as defined by
television. But paradoxically, in the hands of a subversive artist,
it is equally adept at challenging the narrow Darwinian vision of
life that saturates commercial television.
</P>
<P>
   Video art lends itself to work of raw, punkish nonsense, as in
the program of eight bizarre shorts, ``Faultlines in the Psyche,''
but it can also yield work of rigorously elegant abstraction. In a
program called ``The Persistence of Vision,'' the seductive images
run from the whimsical abstractions of Michael Intriere's ``Fish''
(schools of fish photographed swimming against a woozy, waterlogged
pop instrumental soundtrack) to visually transfixing, even romantic
meditations on technology.
</P>
<P>
   As gorgeous as any fireworks display, Van McElwee's
``Transfinite Loops'' invents dazzling astral patterns and finds a
mood of deepening sadness in the swirling, overlapping images of
amusement park rides photographed at night and accompanied by the
sound of howling wind.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bain's ``Space Probing,'' which was photographed in a dense
tangle of ducts, pipes and machinery beneath the campus of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, creates a shifting, kinetic,
kaleidoscopic landscape that suggests a continually re-configuring
Cubist painting that at moments seems almost three-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   On a more austere, experimental level, Les LeVeque's ``Flight''
takes the shimmering low-resolution black-and-white television
image of a lunar astronaut and, to the sounds of accompanying
static, stretches it into two figures.
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Persistence of Vision'' represents one pole of the work
shown in the Video Festival, three programs _ ``The Good, the Bad
and the Converted,'' ``Frontier Meditations'' and ``Gimme Shelter''
_ bring fresh concepts to the documentary form.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT     07-16 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: documentary form. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeanne Finley and John Muse's ``O Night Without Objects,'' the
centerpiece of ``The Good, the Bad and the Converted,'' tells the
true story of a rabidly anti-Semitic grand dragon of the Ku Klux
Klan in Lincoln, Neb., who underwent a spiritual and political
transformation, converted to Judaism, and was taken in and cared
for until his death by a local cantor and his family. The story,
which probes deeply into this family's complicated dynamics, is
framed by abstract essays on family psychology (the opening segment
of this triptych shows a psychological test being given to a child
who is asked to describe what's happening in certain ambiguous
pictures), society and religious community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontier Meditations'' consists entirely of the Russian
director Alexander Sokurov's five-and-a-half -hour documentary
``Spiritual Voices: The Diaries of War,'' a rigorous, glacially
paced meditation on the personal ravages of war on individual
soldiers. The movie opens with a nearly one-hour shot of a desolate
snow-covered landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of ``Gimme Shelter'' is ``The Final Insult,'' a
disturbing, quasi-documentary on homelessness and the apathy of the
impoverished by American filmmaker Charles Burnett. Narrated by a
fictional character, a low-level bank employee named Box Brown
whose financial woes have left him homeless and forced to live in
his car, ``The Final Insult'' blends fiction and truth so craftily
that it's impossible to tell the actors from the nonactors. But its
portrait of people living on the streets (and under the freeway) of
Los Angeles is depressingly realistic. It shows how homelessness
could happen to almost anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the festival's longer works are more notable for what
they attempt than for what they achieve. ``Tomorrow and Tomorrow,''
by Dominique Cabrera, is a personal video diary, filmed with a
hand-held camera, of a year in which Ms. Cabrera suffered from
paralyzing bouts of depression. The work captures the texture of
her daily life (with luminous close-up images of household objects)
and the roller-coaster mood swings of someone desperately trying to
pull her life together. For all its candor, the work still seems
fragmentary and incohesive.
</P>
<P>
   Equally ambitious, although wildly different in intent, the
Belgian video artist Johan Grimonprez's ``Dial H-I-S-T-O-R-Y,'' in
the program ``Secret Histories,'' is an intellectually pretentious
documentary history of airplane hijackings (accompanied by
heavy-handed readings from the works of Don DeLillo). Illustrating
how televised disasters have forced us to redefine what constitutes
a genuine personal drama and to re-think our notions of personal
autonomy, the work has a haranguing tone; after a while, the old
newsreel and television clips of hijack survivors recounting their
ordeals fades into a blur.
</P>
<P>
   Much more satisfying and far scarier is Maria Venuto's half-hour
video film, ``The Tourist,'' which is based on a true incident in
1993. Arriving at Kennedy International Airport, a young German
tourist who has fled her domineering family is fleeced of her money
by a taxi driver and returns to the terminal where she spends the
next three weeks composing unsent postcards home describing her
glorious new life in New York. Having subsisted on Pizza Hut
leftovers and sleeping in the terminal, she is eventually thrown
out into the cold by a security guard. This portrait of
helplessness is so merciless it becomes nightmarishly funna.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the high point of this uneven festival is Ms.
Benning's ``Flat Is Beautiful,'' which explores the world of a
tomboyish 11-year-old girl named Sammy Steel, who lives with her
divorced mother and the mother's gay male roommate. The most
inspired conceit of this technically crude video film is to have
all the characters wear cartoonish masks. Along with the
characters' face gear, the videography, which focuses on
billboards, store signs and flat surfaces, creates the feeling of
living in a children's cartoon world where reality is
simultaneously hiddel and revealed in a twisted, more intensely
felt stylization.
</P>
<P>
   If the same devices were employed in a glossier film, they
wouldn't have nearly the same emotional impact. But because ``Flat
Is Beautiful'' has the look, feel and sound of an intimate home
video, it draws you into a private world thatfeels at once strange
and profoundly recognizable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
