<HEADLINE>
THE JESUS AND MARY CHAIN:   SCOTTISH PUNK NIHILISTS CALL ON
TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (js) 
By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Jesus and Mary Chain, the Scottish rock band that
headlined Irving Plaza on Wednesday night, started out in the
mid-1980s as a one-trick band, burying sulky rock songs in feedback
and distortion. By the mid-1990s, it had changed to a different
tactic, stripping away the guitar noise to prove that the songs
could stand on their own. And by now, through sheer recalcitrance,
the Jesus and Mary Chain is starting to sound like a band of
die-hard rock classicists, dedicated to the verities of three
chords, an implacable beat, a drone and an attitude. Two songs,
``Moe Tucker'' and ``Stardust Remedy,'' cited the Velvet
Underground, the revered fountainhead for punk primitivism.
</P>
<P>
   Punk was from the beginning a divided rebellion. Bands like the
Ramones were iconoclastic toward their 1970s contemporaries but
devout about earlier rock 'n' roll. The British punks that followed
them had less humor, more rage and less respect for roots, but the
Jesus and Mary Chain, who arrived in the post-punk era, kept
British punk nihilism in their lyrics while their music held on to
rock's past. For the Jesus and Mary Chain, the Velvets and the
Beach Boys were always as important as the Sex Pistols.
</P>
<P>
   At Irving Plaza, where the band was headlining as part of the
Intel New York Music Festival, the Jesus and Mary Chain maintained
its usual demeanor. The lighting usually kept the band members'
faces in shadows; the group's two singers and songwriters, William
and Jim Reid, spoke only to introduce their sister Linda, who sang
``Moe Tucker.'' Luckily, the band's routine also calls for
absolutely dependable, powerful musicianship.
</P>
<P>
   In songs from the band's new album, ``Munki'' (Sub Pop), Jim
Reid sang, by turns, about self-hatred and misanthropy _ ``I want
to kiss my darkened soul/I want to kill my darkened soul'' _ but
the music never had any identity crisis. It was implacable midtempo
rock, with William Reid's guitar and Ben Lurie's bass often just
sharing a repeated resonant note, not a chord, in octaves; Nick
Sanderson's drumming was steady, austere and unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   The songs buzzed and droned, rising from monotone melodies to
understatedly catchy choruses, with their surly attitude belied by
the stolidity of the music. And to prove that they hadn't forgotten
their noise phase, the band ended its two final songs with
feedback: one with sustained, throbbing consonances, and then the
final one with a dissonant extended screech. It wasn't anything
like a shock anymore, just a new extension of rock traditionalism.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the music festival's computer theme, one song, the
well-chosen ``Virtually Unreal,'' was made available on the
festival's Web site (www.intelfest.com) the same night as the show,
and will be available for a week. Heard through a computer sound
card, it still buzzes and drones, but it doesn't capture the
enveloping sensation of one repeated chord resonating in the club
itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
