<HEADLINE>
HAVING A GOOD TIME IS SERIOUS BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   After studying 4,000 people in eight countries, a team of
scholars at Associates for Research Into the Science of Enjoyment,
in Reading, England, has determined that people should try to do
things that make them happy.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied such activities as sex, drinking wine,
eating chocolate, watching television and having a cup of tea or
coffee, and determined that ``there is a wealth of evidence to
suggest that the cumulative effect of these little pleasures and
happy moments can make us all live longer.''
</P>
<P>
   They neglected to define ``suggest'' and ``can,'' lapses that do
leave a little room for doubt. Among the specifics they mentioned,
however, was the finding that men and rich people like sex and
women and poor people like to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the course of exactly nine (not eight and not 10,
either) years, reports Men's Fitness magazine, Swedes who spent the
least amount of time playing an instrument or attending a concert
or going to a museum or participating any cultural activity were
1.5 times as likely to die as those who did.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, too,  &UR; Emily Jenkins &LR; , whose new book ``Tongue First:
Adventures in Physical Culture'' (Henry Holt; $14.95) is about
public nudity, told Glamour magazine that women are more
comfortable naked ``because we don't have penises. Once we're in a
bathing suit, we've already exposed everything we're insecure about
_ why not go all the way?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sylvester Stallone &LR;  and  &UR; Jennifer Flavin &LR;  have named their
new baby  &UR; Sistine &LR; ;  &UR; John Cougar Mellencamp &LR;  and  &UR; Elaine Irwin &LR; 
have named their baby  &UR; Speck Wildhorse &LR; ; &UR; Forest  &LR; and  &UR; Keisha
Whitaker &LR;  have named their baby &UR; True Isabella Summer &LR; ; and
 &UR; Christie &LR; 
 &UR; Brinkley &LR;  and &UR; Peter Cook &LR;  have named their baby  &UR; Sailor &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Noticing that the escalator at San Francisco's new AMC 1000
theater is manufactured by a company called Schindler,  &UR; Stannous &LR; 
 &UR; Flouride  &LR; wondered if it could be called ``Schindler's Lift.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Today'' show is preparing a segment on  &UR; Jim Hormel &LR;  and
the fight for his confirmation as ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newly minted matinee idol  &UR; Matt Damon &LR;  told  &UR; Jan Wahl &LR;  that
the one actress he's really passionately interested in working with
is  &UR; Meryl Streep &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Taking a recreational stroll through the catalog of Gall's
Inc., ``America's Largest Supplier to Public Safety
Professionals,''  &UR; Al Rosen  &LR; was captivated by the Thunderwear
Holster, which ``allows you to hide your weapon inside the front of
your trousers.'' This product comes in two sizes, ``Large for large
frame semi-automatics or a Medium for medium to small frame
semi-automatics and snub nose revolvers.'' Rosen's betting that
``they don't sell many for `snub noses.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Boyzone, the Irish band that played at the opening of the
Harrods sale a few weeks ago and had promised to sing there on the
anniversary of  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 's death, has canceled, and said the
prospect of cutting a single in memory of Diana, as planned, is
``unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   And in other disappointments,  &UR; Josh Brolin &LR; 's publicist said
that he didn't know that his client had ever MET  &UR; Pamela &LR; 
 &UR; Anderson &LR; , let alone dated her, as reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
   _ Multitalented  &UR; Steve Martin &LR; , the playwright whose ``Picasso
at the Lapin Agile'' is in San Francisco until Labor Day, told
Premiere magazine that his screenplay ``Bowfinger's Big Thing'' is
``a broad comedy without any likable characters.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The hippest party entertainment in Southern California right
now, reports Los Angeles magazine, is synchronized swimming. At a
recent party for the West Coast editor of Allure magazine, ``water
nymphs did their thing'' while  &UR; Daryl Hannah &LR; ,
 &UR; Jeanne Tripplehorn &LR;  and &UR; Gina &LR;   &UR; Gershon  &LR; ``munched on potato
pancakes,'' another trend that's happening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOOKING FOR LOVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gary Chappell &LR;  found an online personals ad with a particularly
timely spin:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a woman who is serious about preparing for y2k. I
cannot spend 6 months to convince you that there is a problem. I
want to prepare for the y2k problem now. We can discuss how to
prepare along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   (y2k is the year 2000.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is completely out of control. There are no
restrictions on what you can say ... and people seem to believe it.
... I just accept it as one of the unfortunate things of life, like
mosquitoes and bad weather and the thought of nuclear holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis, public affairs commentator and star of
``Armageddon,'' on E! Online.
</P>
</TEXT>
