<SLUG> BC-NAACP-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PREACHES AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION VIRTUES TO NAACP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Al Gore can preach.
</P>
<P>
   In a week of revelations for delegates to the NAACP national
convention here, this was perhaps the least expected: The vice
president, famous for lacking the ease and eloquence his boss is
famous for, wowed this crowd, and, in the estimation of many,
burnished his credentials among a constituency perhaps crucial to
his presidential hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, striking a decidedly partisan tone and adopting the
vernacular of a black Baptist preacher, delivered a hard-hitting
speech on civil rights that mocked critics of affirmative action
and rebuffed the notion that American is colorblind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard critics of affirmative action,'' he said. ``I've
heard those who say that, `Yes, it is a colorblind society.' They
use their colorblind the way duck hunters use their duck blind.
They hide behind it and hope the ducks won't notice what they're up
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in favor of affirmative action if you can dunk the
basketball or sink a three-point shot. But they are not in favor of
it if you merely have the potential to be a leader in this
community and bring people together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's were arguably the most emphatic remarks either he or
Clinton has ever offered on the subject of affirmative action. The
crowd of more than 4,000 was moved to some 15 standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the speech was a chance to prove that he is capable of
building the kind of bond with black voters that seems second
nature to Clinton. Gore earlier this year made a highly successful
Martin Luther King Jr. Day speech at the Ebenezer Baptist Church in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   With Coretta Scott King seated at the dais, Gore announced that
Clinton Thursday authorized creation of a national monument to
King, her late husband, on the site of the National Mall where he
gave his famous ``I Have A Dream'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also announced that the Small Business Administration was
entering into an agreement with the NAACP and other black
organizations to make available $4.1 billion in loan assistance to
minority-owned businessed by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose warm reception here upstaged most other major
speakers during the final day of NAACP's six-day gathering touched
on all of the major issues raised here.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed regret for the government's treatment of black
farmers, who are part of a multibillion-dollar discrimination
lawsuit against the Agriculture Department, pledging that ``this is
a problem we will solve, and not bury.''
</P>
<P>
   He lamented the spread of AIDS and HIV among African-Americans,
and promised to continue working to fix crumbling schools and
enhance the quality of teaching and education that many of
America's black children receive.
</P>
<P>
   And in a swipe at the GOP, Gore said: ``The Republicans know
that theirs is the wrong agenda for African Americans, that's why
they don't even want to count you in the census.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore referred to the ongoing controversy over whether the
traditional census count, which has tended to undercount
minorities, should be supplemented by statistical sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Comunications Director Lawrence Haas brushed aside talk
that Gore's speech amounted to an early appeal black votes in 2000.
``His political interest is in 1998. Past 1998, he will address at
a later time. That will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, however, has methodically traveled the south shoring up
black support in an effort to ward off any potential primary
challenge in his home region _ particularly from the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, who is himself considering a presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters, who made up about 10 percent of the total vote in
the last two presidential elections, make up 50 percent of the vote
in the south. In 1992 and 1996 Clinton garnered 82 to 83 of the
black vote, said David Bositis, senior research associate for the
Joint Center of Political and Economic Studies, a black think tank
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in all honesty, he should be president,'' said George
Bush, an NAACP delegate from Biloxi, Miss. ``Tell him,'' he added,
laughing, ``that you talked to George Bush and he highly recommends
Al Gore'' for president.
</P>
<P>
   Patrice Lombard, an NAACP delegate from Gulfport, Miss. said
after Gore's speech, ``We're going to get him back in office _ as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore often spoke in religious terms to a gathering which began
and ended its days with prayers and hymns. He closed with a booming
call to arms for affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three times,'' he said, ``the Republicans tried to roll back
affirmative action this year, and three times we fought back. Hear
me well, if they try again, we'll fight them again...and again, and
again, and again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
