A8898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SMUGGLING-350&AMP;A     07-16 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SMUGGLING-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHIFT, CHINA ANNOUNCES CRACKDOWN ON SMUGGLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ After years of tolerating a steady growth of
lawlessness at their borders, China's leaders Friday announced a
war on smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharp indictment of how corrupt and ineffectual Chinese
Customs officials have become, the leaders announced that a new
anti-smuggling police force would be formed. President Jiang Zemin,
addressing a special meeting of top leaders, outlined the problem
in a way that showed how border guards have simply become unwilling
or unable to perform their job.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason the smuggling situation has become so desperate,
Jiang pointed out, is that many of the worst offenders are party
officials and army officers. It was the first time that a top
Chinese official had publicly referred to the extensive role that
China's military plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is confronted by rampant smuggling that involves the
participation of some party, government and army organizations, as
well as judicial and law enforcement departments,'' Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the volume of goods smuggled into China cannot be
measured, officials and business executives estimate that it has
reached tens of billions of dollars a year. The main contraband is
not drugs or arms but rather consumer goods that face such onerous
import duties that it pays to bribe Customs officers or to pay off
army transport officers, who can escape scrutiny at the border.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes, gold and automobiles were among the heavily smuggled
items cited at the meeting. Yet a wide range of industrial and
consumer items like telecommunications equipment, diesel oil and
chemicals are also smuggled in enormous quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Even cigarettes produced in China are a major item. To avoid
domestic taxes, many cigarette makers export more than half their
output, only to smuggle the cigarettes back into China, thus
avoiding both domestic and import duties.
</P>
<P>
   With smuggling so rampant and so deeply entrenched in the
interests of powerful authorities, it is not clear how effective
Beijing's new campaign will be. The size and scope of the new
police force is vague; no director was named.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the first five months of this year, Chinese Customs
confiscated $350 million of smuggled goods, a small fraction of the
overall volume. In an report this week, Customs officers blamed
local officials who often blocked investigations.
</P>
<P>
   As with any national campaign, there may be several political
elements at work. Yet decision-making in China remains so opaque
that it is impossible to know if the driving force is Jiang's
desire to flex his muscles over the military or buttress his
reputation as a corruption-fighter.
</P>
<P>
   There may also be financial concerns. Prime Minister Zhu Rongji
argued that it was necessary to reverse the drastic drop in tax
collection as the government undertakes a huge spending program to
encourage economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrying out the anti-smuggling struggle throughout the whole
country with the speed of lightning is related to achieving this
year's economic growth target,'' Zhu told the meeting.
``Increasingly rampant smuggling activities have already caused
serious harm to many aspects of China's economy, society and
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu said all party and government offices and law enforcement
agencies would be required to sever ties with affiliated business
companies in an effort to root out official protection of
smuggling. Yet in China's complex morass of companies that are
owned and partly owned by the government, that will be a gargantuan
task.
</P>
<P>
   Fines and proceeds from confiscated goods, Zhu said, will be
divided in a formula: 50 percent to equip anti-smuggling police and
reward individuals and departments that help, 20 percent to pay for
anti-smuggling efforts by provincial governments and 30 percent for
the central government.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, a People's Daily account of the meeting noted the
attendance of leaders of the Xinjiang Production and Construction
Military Group, the only organization to be named. Xinjiang, a vast
area in the northwest that borders Russia and Kazahkstan, is a
center for smuggling, and mentioning the paramilitary group
suggested that it has been playing a role in smuggling itself.
</P>
<P>
   Diesel oil has been flowing into China from refineries in other
parts of Asia even though a ban on imports took effect in February.
Smuggled oil is much cheaper than domestically produced oil, whose
price is set artificially high by the government, and illegal sales
have severely hurt domestic refineries.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in Friday's issue of People's Daily said smuggling
eroded tax revenues, violated import-export management policies
corrupted officials and undermined social morals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general public must fully realize that the anti-smuggling
drive is not only a major economic struggle, but also a harsh
political struggle that will have a great bearing on the reform,
opening-up and modernization drive,'' the editorial said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
