<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-COSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY CITES LOW COST OF DEMOCRATIC HEALTH CARE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Congressional Budget Office Thursday estimated
that the average consumer would pay less than $25 a year extra for
health insurance under the Democratic managed-care bill.
</P>
<P>
   The report ``shows that the wild claims of the opponents about
the high cost of the legislation are wrong, and that previous
independent estimates of minimal cost are right,'' said Senator
Edward M. Kennedy, sponsor of the Democrats' version of a
``patients' bill of rights,'' which would require managed-care
plans to provide certain rights and benefits to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The CBO estimated that premiums for a typical employer-sponsored
health plan would rise by 4 percent because of the mandates in the
bill. But the CBO also estimated that employers would deflect 60
percent of that increase by taking different steps, such as
reducing benefits or increasing the worker's share of the premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans had charged that the mandates in the bill
would cost consumers an additional $100 per month in premiums.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans released their version of the bill Thursday,
as President Clinton attended a noon pep rally at the Capitol to
press for passage of the leading Democratic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders had opposed any type of health-care
legislation until recent polls showed the GOP was vulnerable on the
issue in this election year. Polls indicate that consumers want
more protection for patients enrolled in managed-care programs,
such as health maintenance organizations, even if the protection
raises their fees and insurance premiums. When Senate Republicans
unveiled their version of the bill Wednesday, they even used the
same title as the Democrats, the patient bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership has been pulled into this issue
kicking and screaming,'' Kennedy said after the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Although the major Democratic and Republican bills differ on
major points, particularly the right of a patient to sue a
managed-care provider for inadequate care, and the number of
mandates, the fact that the GOP now wants to pass a bill has given
the issue a boost.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican bill would create association health plans
to allow small businesses and the self-employed to pool together to
buy health insurance. The Senate Republican bill would allow
unlimited access to medical savings accounts, the IRA-style
accounts for health care.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his third trip to Capitol Hill to tout the
legislation, urged Republicans to join Democrats in crafting a
consensus bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe this is a partisan issue any place but
Washington, D.C.,'' said Clinton. ``We need to stop this from being
a partisan political issue ... It's a people issue. It's about the
integrity of the health care system. It's about how people feel
about our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Blakeney, the principal public health nurse for the
Boston Public Health Commission, spoke for the American Nurses
Association at the rally: ``America's nurses are passionate about
this issue. And we vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Two House Republicans joined the Democrats' rally _
Representatives Michael Forbes, the New York lawmaker who broke
with House Speaker Newt Gingrich over Gingrich's ethics problems
two years ago, and Greg Ganske of Iowa, a plastic and
reconstructive surgeon who specializes in fixing cleft palates _
surgery he said some HMOs refuse to cover because it is
``cosmetic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For heaven's sakes,'' said Ganske, ``insurance should mean
something!''
</P>
<P>
   Ganske said his planned appearance at the rally had caused ``a
firestorm among some members of the Republican caucus.'' As a
result, Ganske said, he resigned Wednesday from a commission
charged with reforming Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   He said no one demanded that he quit, but some Republican
commission members ``questioned, `How can you be in a high-profile
post on the Medicare commission and stand there with the president,
against us?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Aaron Zitner of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
