<SLUG> BC-GAY-HUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN AIMS AT SAN FRANCISCO'S DOMESTIC PARTNERS ORDINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican congressman wants to ban federal
housing money from San Francisco because of the city's gay-rights
ordinance requiring that companies with city contracts provide the
same benefits to workers with unmarried partners as they do to
married employees.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., said in an interview Thursday that
he is pushing the money ban because San Francisco is ``trying to
force a particular political belief, a doctrine if you will,'' on
others.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs said he plans to attach the funding ban to an
appropriations bill such as the one to fund the departments of
housing and urban development and veterans affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs, who represents California's North Coast from Napa to the
Oregon border, said he is retiring from Congress at the end of this
year to return to his real estate business.
</P>
<P>
   He denied his plan was an attack on gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's sexual orientation is their own private business,''
he said, adding that he has ``no problem'' with the city of San
Francisco offering domestic partner benefits to city employees. But
he said it was ``a tremendous stretch'' for the city to try to
force private businesses to offer domestic partner benefits, which
usually take the form of medical insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco board of supervisors adopted the domestic
partners ordinance, effective June 1, 1997, requiring city
contractors to provide the same benefits to the domestic partners _
gay and straight _ of their employees as they would to married
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights advocates hailed the measure as an important step
toward equality.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Salvation Army refused to go along with the rule
and announced that it would no longer accept city funds to pay for
its programs serving the homeless, drug addicts and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Salvation Army objects to the domestic partners law on
religious grounds,'' the charity group said, adding that it has
always provided services without discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In disclosing his plan, Riggs cited the Salvation Army's
decision and complained that the effect of the San Francisco
ordinance ``is to deny taxpayer-funded assistance to the most
needy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really doing it to try to get the board of supervisors to
reconsider this ill-advised policy in light of the unintended
effects _ such as the Salvation Army that wouldn't knuckle-under to
this particular ordinance. I just can't believe they would punish
the Salvation Army and the people it serves.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggs said he hopes the city would grant a waiver to the
Salvation Army so it can continue to provide beds for the homeless
and meals for AIDs patients without losing federal dollars.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Mayor Willi Brown reacted angrily to Riggs' plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're outraged at this type of activity,'' said Brown. ``Local
autonomy is of utmost importance and Congressman Riggs has in the
past been a supporter of that concept. It's the oldest trick in the
book to attach non-relevant amendments to a bill. We hope the
(Clinton) administration and Congress will find a way to eliminate
this amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading gay and lesbian organization also expressed outrage
at Riggs's plan.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Winnie Stachelberg, political director for the
Human Rights Campaign, said Riggs' plan ``was an anti-gay attack,
pure and simple, but what is so frightening about it is it
jeopardizes the welfare of tens of thousands of men, women and
children in San Francisco in order to punish a locality for setting
a policy that's clearly within its jurisdiction.... This is an
example of gross federal micromanagement of local issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Her organization issued a statement labeling the Riggs plan as a
``direct attack on the city of San Francisco.'' The statement said
the Riggs amendment ``makes a mockery'' of Republican rhetoric
about empowering local governments to handle their own affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., whose district includes San
Francisco, attacked Riggs' planned amendment as ``irresponsible and
draconian'' and said it ``would undermine local autonomy and put
the federal government in the role of dictating policy to cities
around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The two San Francisco supervisors at the forefront of the
domestic partners law criticized Riggs' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's blackmail and political opportunism,'' said Supervisor
Tom Ammiano. ``This is an issue of local sovereignty. There's a
mandate from the electorate for domestic partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Said San Francisco Supervisor Leslie Katz: ``This is much bigger
than the City of San Francisco. This is a fundamental issue about
local autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano added that San Francisco's law ``has been a tremendous
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the ground-breaking law took effect 13 months ago, more
than 1,700 companies have extended equal benefits to their workers'
domestic partners, according to city officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, Riggs' amendment to the $25 billion HUD budget would
potentially affect 20 federal programs in San Francisco. Among them
are the construction of new public housing and the demolition of
old, dysfunctional units; the community development block grant
program for revitalizing downtown areas; empowerment zones and
enterprise communities, where businesses receive tax incentives and
grants to develop commercial enterprises in blighted areas; and
housing projects for senior citizens and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one of several court challenges to the city ordinance, a
federal judge ruled in April that the ordinance was constitutional
as long as it was limited to employees of the contractor who live
within the boundaries of the city of San Francisco. Thus, a
national company that has an office in San Francisco and has a
contract with the city would have to offer domestic-partner
benefits to those employees who work in the city. The company would
not have to provide domestic partner benefits to all employees
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Other court challenges are pending, including one brought by the
American Center for Law and Justice, a conservative organization
affiliated with fundamentalist minister Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Riggs amendment is the latest in a series of assaults on
homosexuals by congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joel Hefley, R-Colo., said in an interview Wednesday that
he plans next week to offer legislation that would nullify
President Clinton's executive order banning job discrimination
against homosexuals working for the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas, recently cited
scripture for his view that homosexuality is a sin, an assertion
that came just days after Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., compared homosexuals to alcoholics, kleptomaniacs and sex
addicts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
