u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      07-16 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEEHAN SAYS TIME RUNNING OUT ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With time running out on a congressional effort to
overhaul the campaign-finance system, Representative Martin T.
Meehan said Thursday the initiative will fail unless House
Republican leaders agree in writing to complete action before the
summer recess begins Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat and co-sponsor of the most
prominent plan to rewrite the campaign-finance laws, issued the
warning as negotiators remained deadlocked on a prospective
agreement to conclude the protracted debate.
</P>
<P>
   In a breakfast meeting with reporters, Meehan said ``any
reasonable person'' would recognize the problem. Only 16
legislative days remain before Aug. 7, the last day the House could
act on the campaign-finance issue and leave enough time for the
Senate to consider the legislation before Congress adjourns in
early October.
</P>
<P>
   Under a rare procedure approved by Speaker Newt Gingrich, the
House must consider a freshmen-sponsored campaign-finance proposal,
11 susbtitute plans and 258 amendments before it completes action
on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way we could get this done, if you look at the
schedule,'' Meehan said. ``What we need to do is come to an
agreement on limiting debate, limiting amendments, limiting
substitutes, and limiting time, then have a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   House leaders have permitted only several hours of debate on the
issue each week for more than a month. And only a few hours of
debate are scheduled next week.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave 10 day legislative days to complete the debate,
as well as consider other vital legislation, including eight
spending bills to keep the government operating.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, who has pushed for several years for new
campaign-finance laws with his Republican co-sponsor,
Representative Christopher Shays, of Connecticut, lashed out at GOP
leaders for creating a debate procedure that he said could allow
opponents ``to filibuster the bill to death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to come back week after week and work on this
and to not get cynical about the motives of the Republican
leadership,'' he said. ``I feel as though we've been a little too
patient with the Republican leadership on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief Republican negotiator on campaign finance, California
Representative Bill Thomas, did not return phone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1911EDT &QL; 
