<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH17-COX     07-16 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARTY LINES DRAWN OVER PATIENTS BILL OF RIGHTS
 &HT;    750&AMP;add
 &HT;    Photos to illustrate this story are available from The New York
Times News Service.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN and REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican and Democratic leaders, scrambling to
control a potent election-year issue, urged passage Thursday of
competing health-care bills that would stiffen regulation of the
managed care industry and provide more rights for patients.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare appearance on Capitol Hill, President Clinton joined
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle and House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt at a rally touting the Democratic plan, which would impose
federal regulations on managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have comprehensive national legislation,'' Clinton
said. ``That's one of the biggest problems with the bill offered by
the Republican leadership, it covers too few people.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, Speaker Newt Gingrich and Republican House
leaders unveiled their plan. It would give patients better access
to doctors of their choice; create an external appeals process for
managed care decisions, and provide direct access to gynecologists
for women and pediatricians for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about human beings,'' Gingrich said against the
backdrop of the George Washington Medical Center, where where
President Reagan was taken after an assassination attempt in 1981.
``No human being in need of legitimate care should be stopped from
getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Senate Republicans outlined their own version of a
patient protection bill, which would be limited only to persons in
employer-sponsored health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Riding what polls show is a large reservoir of anger at HMOs for
denying medical treatment _ and bolstered by horror stories of
delayed treatment leading to permanent injury and death _ both
parties are trying to position themselves as the defenders of
patient rights. Next week, both houses of Congress are expected to
take up the respective GOP bills.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican bills differ sharply, particularly over the
issue of whether patients should have the right to sue a managed
care plan if its delay or denial of treatment injured a patient. A
1974 law exempts employer-sponsored health plans _ and the managed
care companies that administer them _ from being held liable for
medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Democratic congressional leaders said Thursday they
were willing to compromise on many provisions of a patients
protection bill, but would insist on the right to sue for damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can write all the guarantees you want into the law here in
Washington, (but) if nobody can enforce them, the delay in the
system will still cause people to die,'' Clinton said. ``We have to
do something about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle took an even harder line: ``There's something wrong in
this country when the only groups of people who get immunity from
our laws are foreign diplomats and HMO bureaucrats. It's time for
HMOs to understand: when their decisions cause the death or injury
of a patient, they will be held responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton and Gingrich both said patient protection
should not be a partisan issue, congressional leaders of both
parties were harshly critical of the other's bills.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle called the Republican bill ``a response to the polls.
Our bill is a response to the patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan is ``the only true patient protection''
bill, responded Rep. James Talent, R-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Republican unity cracked slightly when Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa,
a plastic reconstructive surgeon, joined Clinton and Democratic
leaders to support the Patients Bill of Rights measure introduced
by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Ganske displayed a large color photograph of a young boy born
with a severely cleft palate and noted that an HMO had initially
denied coverage for his reconstructive surgery because it was
considered cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For heaven's sake, insurance should mean something,'' Ganske
said. ``People who pay good money for their HMO should not have to
rely on charity so their child can have a normal face like this
little boy had after his surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   After being criticized by some Republicans for his decision to
participate in the rally with Clinton and the Democrats, Ganske
announced Thursday that he was resigning as a GOP member of the
Medicare Reform Commission. He said Gingrich had not asked for the
resignation, but other GOP members had questioned his service on
the high-profile commission.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined by leaders of the American Medical
Association and the American Nurses Association in calling for a
comprehensive national patients Bill of Rights. Democratic leaders
said more than 170 health care and consumer organizations have
endorsed their bill.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Health Benefits Coalition, representing the
nation's major business organizations, announced it planned a major
grassroots and advertising campaign to defeat the proposal. The
group warned that the Democratic plan would expose employers who
provide health coverage ``to unlimited lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry bristled at the attacks from both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real people being attacked are those working Americans who
are going to pay more for their health care or have their health
care coverage dropped because the increased costs that these laws
would impose,'' said Mark Merritt, vice president of American
Association of Health Plans, which represents more than 1,000
managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are playing a bait-and-switch game. They are
playing this as an attack on health plans when all this is is a
hidden tax masquerading as consumer protections.''
</P>
<P>
   Major legislative initiatives have died in Congress recently as
a result of bitter partisan feuding. The massive tobacco bill
disintegrated, as did a proposal to overhaul campaign fund-raising
laws.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to avoid that, Gingrich said he would seek support
from the White House and from Democrats to pass a bipartisan bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big test ought to be: can we get together and pass a
bill,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered similar sentiments: ``We need to do everything
we can to stop this from being a partisan political issue, because
it isn't anywhere but Washington. It's a people issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
