<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BUDGET SURPLUS LIKELY TO HIT $3.7 BILLION AT YEAR'S END 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With sales tax revenues booming, Texas' budget surplus probably
will reach a record $3.7 billion when legislators start work in
January on how to use it, state Comptroller John Sharp said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a turnaround that has not been achieved by any other
state,'' Sharp said, recalling that Texas faced a deficit of at
least $4.5 billion in 1991 as the economy recovered from an oil
industry collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, speaking to the Rotary Club of Houston as the Democratic
candidate for lieutenant governor, joked that Texas might consider
buying New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Unless problems related to the troubled Asian economy, the Texas
agricultural drought or other factors interfere, the surplus will
continue to grow to $6.7 billion for the two-year budget that
starts in September 1999, Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's current two-year budget is about $84 billion, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With statewide offices up for the grabs in the November election
and lawmakers pushing for tax cuts or new programs, Sharp's
announcement created a wave of comments about the pot of gold.
</P>
<P>
   No leader proposed refunding the entire amount to the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George W. Bush said he will first push for
funding of top-priority programs, especially public education, and
then look for ``responsible ways'' to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to make sure that tax cuts and spending
commitments during a time of economic prosperity will not create a
burden for the state when economic times are not as good,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With last year's Legislature, Bush engineered property tax cuts
totaling about $1 billion. But lawmakers rejected his proposals for
more massive tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   State House Speaker Pete Laney echoed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``When times are good, we should lay the groundwork to prepare
for lean times,'' Laney said about Sharp's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's look for the long term,'' said House Appropriations
Committee Chairman Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, as he cautioned
against hasty tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Texas could continue granting property tax cuts, Junell said,
but ``how do you refund people's sales tax? We don't keep records
on who spent it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp's preliminary surplus estimate came at the request of
Junell, who wanted to give budget planners an early picture of the
state's books.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sharp pegged the surplus at about $1 billion, based
on the forecast that personal income in Texas would grow as much as
6.4 percent this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   The new forecast assumes 7.5 percent growth this year.
</P>
<P>
   State sales tax revenues are climbing 10 percent a year, a rate
unseen since the oil-related boom of the late 1970s, Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which has no personal income tax, collects a tax of 6.25
cents on every $1 of sales with exemptions for food, medicine and
other items.
</P>
<P>
   Business taxes, motor vehicle taxes and other fees are
contributing to the surplus, Sharp said, along with cost-saving
moves put into place by elected officials from both parties since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He cited his own agency's development of the Lone Star card, an
electronic debit system that is credited with reducing food stamp
fraud, as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro, the state land
commissioner, said the surplus estimate deflects Bush's criticisms
of his proposals, which include giving teachers a $5,000 pay raise,
replacing temporary classroom buildings and junking the tax on
vehicle purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget surplus gives us the historic opportunity to put
`Texas families first,' '' he said, referring to the title of his
platform.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said the state could cut taxes in ways that would
encourage business development, such as exempting small business
from franchise fees and giving tax credits for research and
development by large firms. The state could also consider funding
college tuition for the best students and carrying a larger share
of the funding for public schools, giving relief to property
taxpayers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp's Republican opponent for lieutenant governor, state
Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry, said the state should fund
priority programs, such as a crime-fighting programs, and use the
remainder of the surplus for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
