<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CZAR-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PRESIDENT, IN CHANGE OF HEART, WILL ATTEND CZAR'S BURIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ It is difficult to upstage the burial
of the final czar, emperor and autocrat of all the Russias, the man
whose remains were hidden for nearly eight decades by the
communists who killed him and seized his empire. But President
Boris Yeltsin managed to do just that on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In trademark fashion, Yeltsin abruptly announced on television
that he had decided to attend Friday's elaborate and much-debated
interment of Czar Nicholas II, most of his family and four servants
in the czar's imposing riverside fortress here. ``This truth has
been concealed for 80 years,'' he said, referring to the killings,
``and we have to tell this truth tomorrow and I should take part.
This will be the right thing to do from the human point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   That caused a small sensation. Yeltsin had said only weeks
earlier that he would not go to the funeral, apparently because the
country's political and religious factions are deeply split over
its meaning and propriety. That announcement, in turn, had caused a
stir, because it was Yeltsin who had virtually ordered a state
funeral for the czar in the first place, as an act of national
repentance.
</P>
<P>
   His spokesman said on Thursday that Yeltsin's turnabout came
after ``hard thinking'' and a talk with Dmitry Likhachyov, a
historian and major figure in Russian cultural affairs. Almost but
not quite lost amid the pirouettes was Nicholas himself, returning
to his ancestral home for the first time since he abdicated the
throne in March 1917. The fragmentary remains of the czar, his wife
Alexandra, three of his four daughters and four servants were
unloaded from a cargo plane at the St. Petersburg airport Thursday
to the accompaniment of an army band's dirge and an honor guard's
salute.
</P>
<P>
   Each small wooden coffin, embellished with a cross, silk tassels
and an engraved nameplate, was then loaded into its own teal
minivan and escorted through the city to the hexagonal riverside
fortress, built by Nicholas' ancestor Peter the Great some 350
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an occasional communist flag, there was neither much
protest or approval along the long route until the motorcade neared
the fortress itself. There, thousands watched the procession of
funeral vans as the Russian tricolor and the red-and-yellow flag of
St. Petersburg flapped at half-mast under a bright sun and stiff
wind.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as bells rang, snare drums kept march time and a Scottish
bagpiper wheezed mournfully, _ the czar was related to Queen
Victoria and was honorary commander of a company of Scottish
dragoons _ the coffins were brought into the fortress and carried
to a cathedral where services will be held. At noon on Friday, the
remains will be eulogized and lowered into a single crypt in the
cathedral, which already serves as a mausoleum for the Romanov
dynasty that ruled Russia from the 1600s until Nicholas' death.
</P>
<P>
   Four hundred government officials, diplomats, Romanov
descendants and others will witness Friday's service, but until
Thursday, the guest list included few of the political or religious
elite. After Yeltsin changed his mind, the leaders of the Russian
parliament's upper house, the Federation Council, said they would
also send an official delegation. But the lower house, the Duma, is
ignoring the event, and church leaders also are staying away.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The execution of the Romanovs was, until recently, both one of
the pivots and enigmas of 20th-century history. It was long known
that the imperial family and their servants were executed by
Bolshevik revolutionaries in 1918. But the details of the deaths
and the location of the bodies were carefully hidden secrets until
close to the end of communist rule in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Leading historians now say most victims were hastily buried in a
pit and then covered with logs. Two bodies _ those of the czar's
only son, and one daughter _ have never been found. Many experts
believe they were partly burned and buried nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin ordered the bodies recovered and authenticated in 1991
after their discovery became public, and DNA tests in U.S. and
European laboratories later concluded that the remains almost
certainly are those of the czar's family. But just as many Russian
leaders have contested or ignored much of that story _ especially
the still-powerful Communist Party, whose leaders ordered the
executions, and the Russian Orthodox Church, which is split over
the authenticity of the remains. And the Russian public, ever
suspicious of official pronouncements, is almost evenly split over
whether the coffins actually contain royal bones, according to one
new public-opinion poll.
</P>
<P>
   The mercurial Yeltsin is prone to schedule and cancel
appearances almost as often as he fires and hires cabinets, a trait
_ or tactic _ that has served to keep him at the center of public
attention. His spokesman, who said on Monday that rumors of
Yeltsin's attendance at the funeral were ``nonsense,'' said
Thursday that the president's latest change of heart was ``a
courageous, humane and Christian act'' devoid of political meaning.
His political allies and foes immediately began reading import into
it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Chernomyrdin, once Yeltsin's prime minister and now a
candidate for his job as president, called the funeral ``a mess.''
``We shouldn't turn it into a show, trying to clear out who will
attend and will not attend the ceremony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Zyganov, the Duma's communist leader, said Yeltsin
clearly was acting under political pressure from his advisers.
Yeltsin's spokesman called that ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the cathedral, a stooped and white-haired Russian woman
in formal dress said her father had commanded forces in the
so-called White Army that fought a failed counterrevolutionary
battle against the communists in 1918. ``Praise God,'' she said of
the funeral. ``It's about time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
