<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-VISAS17-COX     07-16 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KEY HOUSE CHAIRMAN DIGS IN ON VISAS FOR FOREIGN WORKERS
 &HT;    With TECH-VISAS-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ High-tech companies and other employers who are
waiting for more visas to hire foreign workers may have to wait a
little longer.
</P>
<P>
   This year's supply of 65,000 visas for specially skilled foreign
workers ran out more than two months ago, but legislation that
would create more visas remains stalled in the House, the victim of
an increasingly entrenched battle over protections for U.S. tech
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already voted, 78-20, to create more of the H-1B
visas without imposing new requirements on employers. Unless an
agreement can be reached on the House version, no more visas for
foreign workers will be available until Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the House bill's chief sponsor, Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas, again defied business groups and his own party leadership
by insisting that any new H-1B visas be accompanied by requirements
that employers certify that they made efforts to find U.S. workers
for jobs being filled by foreign workers. Smith also wants
employers to certify that no U.S. workers were laid off from those
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration chimed in Thursday with its most
serious threat to date that President Clinton may veto any visa
legislation that does not include the worker protections being
sought by Smith. The administration is also insisting that U.S.
employers help pay for training of U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   The tough stands may complicate work next week for Republican
congressional leaders, who plan to bring in their top guns to try
to resolve the impasse. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., are expected to join the
small group of House and Senate members who have been trying for
weeks to hash out an agreement on the visas.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, has been
the highest-ranking Republican in the group, which has included
Smith and the author of the Senate bill, Sen. Spencer Abraham,
R-Mich. Smith's fellow Texan and Republican, Sen. Phil Gramm, has
also been in on the efforts to persuade Smith to lighten his
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, Smith wasn't budging: ``The most simple, most
basic protection we can give American workers is to guarantee that
they won't be fired by their employers and replaced by foreign
workers on H-1B visas,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared at a news conference with computer specialist Ed
Curry of Jarrell, Texas, and two other U.S. workers who said they
have been unable to find the computer jobs they are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives have essentially been run through a wringer,'' said
Curry, who shuttered his computer-chip analyzing business in early
1997. Curry has been through a series of short-term consulting jobs
since then, some at firms that employ foreign workers on H-1B
visas. None of the companies have offered him fulltime work. ``I'm
not able to find employment even with basic benefits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech companies, who complain of a shortage of suitable
workers, are leading the fight to defeat additional requirements
for hiring foreign workers. In a letter last week to Smith, Gramm
and other members of the group, several company executives, said
the requirements ``give the Labor Department enormous new powers
over how American companies run their personnel policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said Thursday that he is optimistic that a compromise can
be reached: ``I think we're just about an inch away from closing
this up,'' he said a few hours before the White House released a
statement saying that Clinton's top advisers would recommend a veto
of any bill that did not contain additional protection for U.S.
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it may be necessary in the short term to increase the
number of visas for temporary foreign workers, this must only be
done in conjunction with additional efforts to increase the skill
level of U.S. workers and meaningful reforms to the H-1B program,''
the White House said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
