<SLUG> BC-BETTE-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURE `BETTE': CLASSIC DELIVERS WICKED FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Revenge is sweet and equally amusing in ``Cousin
Bette,'' a wickedly droll comedy about the endless vanity of the
upper classes.
</P>
<P>
   With a dry wit and a touch of cruel delight in exposing the
foibles of the elite, director Des McAnuff turns Honore de Balzac's
classic novel into the most amusing literary romp since Gwyneth
Paltrow's sassy ``Emma.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in Paris in the middle of the 19th century, ``Cousin Bette''
details the decline of the Hulot family, led to the brink of ruin
by the profligate baron (Hugh Laurie).
</P>
<P>
   Bette (Jessica Lange) is the poor country cousin of the snobbish
family, an old maid whose strength of character and force of will
go unrecognized in a society where women get by on youth and
beauty, men on wealth and arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Having served the baron's family faithfully for years, Bette is
wronged by the family and determines to have her revenge, to bring
its members as low as they have sunk her.
</P>
<P>
   Her scheme is simplicity itself: The family is so foolish that
all Bette needs to do is facilitate its follies and the family will
bring itself down.
</P>
<P>
   She is aided in this endeavor by the demimonde's favorite singer
(Elisabeth Shue), who is the heartthrob of Paris and the mistress
of a series of men whose money has overcome their better judgment,
if they ever had any.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bette's plans are complicated when she falls in love
with a starving young artist (Aden Young) and finds her own foolish
heart getting in the way of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   McAnuff turns Balzac's tale of social unravelings into an
intellectual nose thumbing that, in the end, insults us as happily
as it insults the 19th-century French.
</P>
<P>
   McAnuff has a sly eye for designing scenes that emphasize the
humor in any situation, as everyone takes a turn being the butt of
the joke. He pushes ``Cousin Bette'' to the edge of farce several
times, but restrains that urge in favor of drollery.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first film, McAnuff directs with the skill and
confidence of a veteran.
</P>
<P>
   He is an accomplished playwright and theater director, but other
directors have come from the stage without his talent for
enlivening screen dramatics.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of miserable outings in ``Hush'' and ``A Thousand
Acres,'' Lange finds a starring role perfectly fitted to her manic
intensity. She plays Bette like a coiled asp waiting, waiting,
waiting to strike.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie (who plays the rich fool in ``Jeeves and Wooster'')
creates a perfect fool as the baron, for he is made poignant by his
ability to see how foolish he is while he is unable to do anything
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin Bette'' is an enjoyably poisonous comedy, the perfect
antidote for a summer of too much slapstick and not enough
sophisticated humor.
</P>
<P>
   Rated R for nudity, sex and profanity, ``Cousin Bette'' is more
risque than ``Masterpiece Theater'' has led us to expect from our
literary classics. 4 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
