<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAROID-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAROID REPORTS 22 PERCENT DECLINE IN REVENUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polaroid Corp., which last month warned investors to expect
disappointing second quarter financial results, delivered as
promised: a dramatic drop in profits and a 22 percent decline in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced that most of its top two dozen
executives have agreed to invest more than $2.5 million of their
own money in the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass. company reported earnings of $12.1 million,
or 27 cents a share, excluding one-time gains and loss reserves.
That compares with a $34.6 million profit, or 76 cents a share, for
the same period last year. Polaroid's revenues, which were hurt by
lower camera and film purchases by Kmart Corp. and Wal-Mart Stores
Inc., fell to $464.7 million for the quarter from $564.9 million in
the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid had said last month that its results would be hurt a
new strategy among retailers to keep inventories lean.
</P>
<P>
   The changing inventory patterns at retailers was only part of
Polaroid's quarterly downturn . Consumer camera and film purchases
also fell, although the company declined to state how much it
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid also said it created a $10 million pre-tax reserve to
cover potential bad debts in Russia. The instant photography
company added that it took a $26.3 million pre-tax gain on the sale
of some of its closed plants and other real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's forecast last month, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter analyst, Rebecca Runkle said she was surprised by the some
of financial results, including lower-than-expected international
revenues and generally higher selling and administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid's shares, which have fallen 37 percent in the past 12
months, closed Thursday unchanged at 35 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   The lackluster stock performance and Polaroid's anemic earnings
have put pressure on chairman and chief executive Gary DiCamillo,
now in his third year at the company. Having pared costs with
layoffs, plant closings and fewer long-term research and
development projects, DiCamillo has said he is now looking for
growth with forthcoming new products.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to tie executives closer to the company's future
performance, DiCamillo announced that most of the two dozen top
officers have agreed to use their own money to buy $2.5 million of
Polaroid stock. The company is scrapping top managers' existing
stock-ownership plan, based on a corporate officer's annual
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that our officers should have a significant portion
of their net worth tied directly to the company's performance,''
said DiCamillo about the new voluntary program.
</P>
<P>
   These officials, he added, ``are sending a clear, unambiguous
message that Polaroid officers are committed to and believe in our
strategic plan to grow Polaroid's sales and earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said the executives won't receive any
interest-free corporate loans to buy the stock.
</P>
<P>
   A major question mark will be whether new products _ such as a
single use disposable instant camera due out this fall _ will be
popular enough to lift the company's sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid's sales have stagnated around $2 billion a year since
the late 1980s. DiCamillo's goal is to raise Polaroid's revenues to
$3.5 billion in the year 2001 with pretax profits amounting to as
much as 15 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polaroid is absolutely betting on new products but it also
must stablize its core instant film business and lowers its overall
operating infrastructure costs,'' said Runkle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
