<SLUG> BC-MA-NEEDLE-EXCHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGFIELD CLOSE TO ADOPTING NEEDLE EXCHANGE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY R. DOWDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ City councilors here are poised to make
this community the fifth in the state to embrace a needle exchange
program as a way of curbing AIDS, overcoming opponents' charges
that such a program ignores one stubborn, deadly ill to attack
another.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-member body is scheduled to vote on a proposal Monday
night. Officials said the program offering clean hypodermic needles
to intravenous drug users is almost certain to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters in Springfield believe that, unlike in 1996 when the
council defeated a similar proposal, new research on
needle-exchange programs elsewhere and aggressive public relations
have combined this time to push Springfield's leaders toward
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the indications I have are that it will pass,'' Mayor
Michael J. Albano, a supporter, said this week at a press
conference set up to show medical evidence of the critical need for
a program. ``But anything and everything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote comes after the debate heated up in recent weeks. In
Europe, evidence of the programs' effectiveness was presented at an
international conference, and in Washington needle exchanges were
endorsed by the Clinton administration. However, US officials still
won't allow federal dollars to fund the programs.
</P>
<P>
   While four city councilors oppose the plan, four others are
proponents. The swing vote, William T. Foley, who has previously
voted for it, said he is unsure but leaning toward backing it.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, Cambridge, Northampton and Provincetown are the four
other communities that have started needle exchanges since the
state made funding available for up to 10 towns and cities in 1993.
Nationally, there are 120 programs funded by cities, states, and
private groups.
</P>
<P>
   To rally support for needle exchanges, Albano and city Health
and Human Services Director Helen Caulton launched a blitz campaign
that at once highlights the severity of AIDS in this city of
150,000 and the medical weapons against it.
</P>
<P>
   Albano and several city councilors are scheduled to tour
Boston's program Friday in a last-minute fact-finding mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needle exchange is one of those issues that can pit public
health against the perception of morality,'' said Caulton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1996, we have a lot more information that proves
conclusively that needle exchange does work without increasing drug
use,'' Caulton said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing US Centers for Disease Control statistics, she said
Springfield, with about 767 cases of AIDS, now has the 25th highest
rate of infection in the nation. Caulton said 56 percent of those
people with AIDS got the HIV virus by sharing dirty needles.
</P>
<P>
   Caulton said each city councilor had been supplied news reports
of one of the largest studies to date of needle exchange programs.
The study, released this month at the 12th World AIDS Conference in
Geneva, Switzerland, said needle exchange efforts brought AIDS
transmission among New York City's 150,000 intravenous drug users
under control.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Rooke, a city councilor who has led the fight against
needle exchange for several years, said he's unimpressed with the
array of studies, and will vote against the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, whose vote will be decisive, said he will vote in favor
of it unless he uncovers new information that contradicts what he's
heard so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's an effective program but I didn't realize the
amount of controversy and anger it would cause,'' he said. ``We
have to think hard because we're sending a negative social message.
You're giving needles to drug users but, if it's going to stem an
epidemic, then I think it's justified. But I wouldn't want it to
stay in place any longer than necessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
