r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZORRO-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      07-16 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZORRO-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ZORRO' IN DUCES Z'S OF ANOTHER SORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Z as in zzzzzzzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mask of Zorro'' makes its mark in the annals of adventure,
but for such a big production, it's a small mark and a silly one,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of dashing adventure, the film settles for slash and
flash, with not one but two Zorros.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should have tried for a chorus line of 20 dancing
Zorros.
</P>
<P>
   The first Zorro is Don Diego De La Vega (Anthony Hopkins), the
only Spanish nobleman living in Mexico in 1820 to speak with an
English accent.
</P>
<P>
   Zorro 1 goes up against the evil Don Rafael (Stuart Wilson), who
has come to Mexico with a vague plan to make people suffer.
</P>
<P>
   The old Zorro gets tossed into prison for 20 years, at which
point Don Rafael decides to make people in California suffer. Don
Diego emerges from prison none the worse for 20 years of starvation
and torture.
</P>
<P>
   Zorro 1 then trains Zorro 2 (Antonio Banderas) how to fight and
wear the black mask.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why Zorro 2 has to wear a mask is unclear since he's a
common thief and no one would know who he was even if they knew
what he looked like.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because the black mask goes so well with the black
cape.
</P>
<P>
   Zorro 2 takes up the fight against Don Rafael and various people
who fall down at the slightest provocation.
</P>
<P>
   Zorro 2 also falls in love with the lovely Elena (Catherine
Zeta-Jones), who thinks she's the daughter of the bad guy even
though she's really the daughter of the good guy.
</P>
<P>
   In between bouts of running from Don Rafael's buffoons, Zorro 2
and Elena engage in a bit of foreplay called strip sword-fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The less exciting fights alternate between the silly and the
serious, with the silly being slightly more entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem with ``The Mask of Zorro'': vast stretches of
tedium in between the sword fights, during which Zorro 1 gives
Zorro 2 too many lectures about how to achieve Zorro-ness.
</P>
<P>
   As for the peasants that the Zorros champion, they have the
curious habit of looking happy in one scene and miserable in the
next. Exactly what is Zorro trying to liberate them from? A life of
bowing and smiling like underpaid extras?
</P>
<P>
   Director Martin Campbell, who created more excitement with
``Golden-Eye,'' can't decide whether he's making a lame comic
adventure or an ordinary straight bad adventure. So he zigs and
zags between the two, creating the wrong kinds of Z's.
</P>
<P>
   Banderas, the first Spaniard to play a Zorro in the movies,
gives much better than he gets from the director. He has the spirit
and the sense of humor to inject some zip into the proceedings, but
he's zapped by the feeble script.
</P>
<P>
   As for the much-publicized passion between Banderas (``Evita'')
and Zeta-Jones (``The Phantom''), it consists of the director
finding endless excuses for her to bend forward so he can show us
what used to be called in Hollywood ``her talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's curious conceit is to suggest that Zorro is the
19th-century Batman: a rich guy who lives in a cave, fancies a cape
and has a dark side.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three of the fights he stages have amusing moments
because they borrow heavily from two great sword adventures: ``The
Princess
</P>
<P>
   Bride'' and Richard Lester's ``The Three Musketeers.''
</P>
<P>
   In between the swordplay, he asks the question: How many long
speeches about nothing of importance do we need in a two-hour-plus
adventure movie? About half as many as ``The Mask of Zorro''
contains.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13, ``The Mask of Zorro'' contains brief nudity and
extensive violence, which is too sadistically graphic for a movie
being pitched to kids. 2 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
