<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA PRIMARY MOVE DISTURBS NEW ENGLAND STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California is moving toward holding its
presidential primary in 2000 on the same day five New England
states hold their ``Yankee Day'' vote, prompting concern that the
region's importance in the election may be diminished.
</P>
<P>
   California's move is considered one of the most significant
preliminary political events leading up to the 2000 presidential
campaign. Not only would it force candidates to spend more time and
money in California _ and much less in New England _ but it could
also harm efforts by lesser-known candidates to make a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, California is trying to convince Washington and Oregon
to hold their votes on the same day, creating an unprecedented
Pacific Coast primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is getting to be a bigger mess than ever,'' said
Massachusetts Secretary of State William F. Galvin, the state's top
election official. Galvin, calling the matter a ``political and
civic crisis,'' met earlier this week in Utah with many of his
counterparts from other states in an effort to resolve the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin revealed for the first time publicly that he is willing
to schedule a later date for the Massachusetts primary if all the
states would agree to a system of regional primaries, with the
order rotating every four years. But officials from the other
states are not close to agreeing to a regional primary system.
</P>
<P>
   With relatively little notice, legislation to switch the
California primary date has gained momentum in the last several
months. California's Senate approved the measure last May, and the
state Assembly is expected to vote on it within weeks, with the
sponsors predicting it will pass. Governor Pete Wilson, who may run
for president in 2000 and could benefit from an early primary in
his state, has said he will sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Wilson Thursday sought to calm concerns in New
England, a region he had hoped would be a stronghold during his
failed 1996 campaign. Wilson spokesman Sean Walsh said tying
together votes in five New England states and California on March 7
would give a boost to moderate Republican candidates _ presumably
including Wilson, if he runs again.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Walsh said, Republican primaries in recent years
have been dominated by conservative states, exemplified by the
mostly Southern states that participate in ``Super Tuesday'' the
second week of March.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen, meanwhile, tried to put a
positive spin on California's effort to hold its election on March
7, saying the Granite State's first-in-the-nation primary, to be
two weeks earlier, might become even more important.
</P>
<P>
   California's effort is headed by state Senator Jim Costa, a
Fresno Democrat who said he has been pushing some form of the
legislation for the last 18 years. Costa said he is on the verge of
victory and is unconcerned about criticism from the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the population of New Hampshire?'' Costa asked. ``My
Senate district has 850,000 people. I am less concerned about New
Hampshire being first than in setting up an orderly process.''
</P>
<P>
   California is the nation's most populous state, with 32 million
people, while New Hampshire has 1.16 million people.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire still would hold the first primary under Costa's
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Super Tuesday was created,'' Shaheen said, ``it was said
it would make those states more important and diminish the
importance of New Hampshire and Iowa. What they did in fact was
make New Hampshire and Iowa more important.'' Iowa holds its
presidential caucus before the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some political observers believe New Hampshire is becoming
less relevant. For years, the state boasted that a candidate had to
win in New Hampshire to become president. But in 1992, Bill Clinton
came in second to Senator Paul Tsongas of Massachusetts and went on
to win the Democratic nomination. In 1996, Robert Dole came in
second to Patrick Buchanan and won the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Shaheen said New Hampshire offers a far better
opportunity for lesser-known and less-well-funded candidates to
build standing by meeting voters one-on-one, something far more
difficult in California, where most campaigning is done by
expensive television ads.
</P>
<P>
   Five other New England states _ Massachusetts, Vermont, Maine,
Connecticut and Rhode Island _ joined to create the Yankee Day
primary in 1996 to increase the region's clout.
</P>
<P>
   But if California goes through with its plan, and no changes are
made by other states, March 7 could be a crowded primary day. In
addition to five New England states, primaries or caucuses are also
tentatively scheduled by New York, Maryland, Georgia, Minnesota and
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   With so many primaries held so early, there would be less chance
for a relatively unknown candidate to break through in Iowa or New
Hampshire, as Jimmy Carter did in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire law requires the state to hold the first primary _
with voting at least 10 days before other states. But many other
states have scheduled early primaries to gain influence in the
critical early days of the campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Costa helped enact legislation that moved up
California's primary from June to the last Tuesday in March. But
the party nominations were locked up long before Californians had a
chance to vote. Costa said California Republicans haven't had a
meaningful role in the GOP primary since the 1964 contest between
Nelson Rockefeller and Barry Goldwater, and the state's Democrats
have not had much of a primary voice since the 1972 race between
Hubert Humphrey and George McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Costa said, candidates view California as a political
bank, siphoning millions of dollars in contributions from the state
and spending the money in New Hampshire and other places with early
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been reduced to becoming the automatic teller machine
for presidential aspirants,'' said Costa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
