<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-WORKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE THREATENS FOREIGN WORKER   BILL VETO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Announcing its stand on an important issue for high-tech
companies, the White House threatened Thursday to veto a Senate
bill that would raise the number of foreign workers admitted to the
United States to work as computer programs and in other skilled
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, White House press secretary Michael
McCurry suggested President Clinton favors a House proposal. The
House bill increases the number of foreign workers, but it also
requires US companies to certify that they laid off no US workers
in order to hire a foreigner, and that they tried to recruit an
American before hiring a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   Employers, particularly high-tech firms, want the right to hire
more foreigners because, they say, the booming economy has left a
shortage of skilled Americans. But they are resisting the ``no
layoff'' and recruitment requirements as an unnecessary government
intrusion into their hiring practices.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee voted to increase the number of
skilled foreigners admitted each year to about 115,000, from 65,000
today, on so-called H-1B visas. But the committee also voted to
impose the new requirements on employers who use the foreign labor.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also approved the additional visas, without the new
requirements for employers. Some House Republican leaders
reportedly favor the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   H-1B visas allow a foreigner to work in the United States for
six years.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president's advisers would recommend that he
veto any bill that does not require employers to show that they
have tried to recruit Americans and have not laid off Americans
before hiring foreigners. The president believes any bill must also
have ``a significant training component'' for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry's statement drew criticism from an aide to Senator
Spencer Abraham, the Michigan Republican who sponsored the Senate
bill. ``For a president and vice president who claim to be friendly
with the high-tech community, this was a very unfriendly move,''
said Joseph McMonigle, Abraham's spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
