<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VW-IMAGE-ART-340(2TAK     07-16 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VW-IMAGE-ART-340(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLKSWAGEN PLANS EXPANSION, WITH EMPHASIS ON LUXURY CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on VW's product manufacturing, income, market
share and acquisitions is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOLFSBURG, Germany _ It isn't enough to buy Rolls-Royce Motor
Cars and Lamborghini, the Italian sports car manufacturer.
Volkswagen AG chairman Ferdinand Piech also wants to build a
monument to the company he rescued from decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auto City 2000,'' a theme park being built at a cost of nearly
$400 million near Volkswagen headquarters here, is a testimony to
Piech's consuming ambition. It will feature at least eight separate
pavilions to showcase Volkswagen's brands. It will also ifclude a
luxury hotel, a yacht pier and a museum that will let people
test-drive cars in virtual reality.
</P>
<P>
   Well, why not? The company that pioneered the homely, no-frills
Beetle is moving upscale. After a fierce bidding war against BMW
AG, Volkswagen completed its purchase of Rolls-Royce, which also
makes Bentley roadsters, for nearly $800 million this month. That
came on the heels of an agreement for VW's Audi unit to buy
Lamborghini SpA, for what is thought to be about $100 million. And
it recently entered a joint venture with Porsche to build luxury
sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   This series of rapid-fire actions, along with other moves, has
startled Volkswagen's rivals and excited investors, who are
swapping endless rumors about Piech's next deal. But while it might
seem hard to imagine the Beetle and the Bentley under one roof _
Volls Woyce, as one cartoonist envisioned it _ Piech appears to be
extremely serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The umbrella strategy is that we want to provide mobility for
everybody's needs,'' said Jens Neumann, the chief financial officer
of Volkswagen and a board member. ``We haven't diversified in the
old sense of the word, into a conglomerate. We are in the mobility
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, that is likely to mean a concerted attack on
the luxury markets dominated by BMW and Daimler-Benz's Mercedes,
perhaps by a line of lower-priced ``Baby Bentleys'' from a
re-engineered Rolls-Royce. It also means an expansion in the truck
business, whether by acquisition, alliance or a go-it-alone
strategy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Piech has the money. In the five years since he became chairman,
Volkswagen has recovered from its catastrophic decline and become a
huge money machine. Sales are climbing rapidly, powered by popular
new versions of the Volkswagen Golf and the more upscale Audi.
Thanks largely to the new Beetle, which went on sale in the United
States in March, Volkswagen's U.S. sales soared 50 percent in the
first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen's expanding profit margins have allowed it to
accumulate enormous amounts of cash _ currently about $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Piech wants more. As the grandson of Ferdinand Porsche, who
conceived the original Beetle, he is determined to increase
Volkswagen's size and its prestige. He also seems to carry a sense
of being on the ``wrong'' side of the Porsche family _ the plebeian
Volkswagen side rather than the patrician Porsche side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even today, there is some kind of unspoken law in our
family,'' Piech said in a recent interview with the German car
magazine Auto Motor Sport. ``Porsche is Stuttgart, and Piech is
Salzburg,'' the Piech family home.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, in an interview Thursday at Volkswagen headquarters,
did not discourage widespread speculation that Volkswagen wanted to
attack the Mercedes S-Class and BMW 7-series with an expanded line
of Bentleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good idea!'' he said with a grin, as if he had just
heard it for the first time. While insisting that Volkswagen is
still analyzing its options, he said there were ``lots of
opportunities'' to build up Rolls-Royce and Bentley. ``With our
technology in the mass markets, we could probably improve the
price-value relationship of these cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say Piech has good reason to push into the
market for luxury cars, in part because Daimler-Benz is attacking
downward with subcompacts like the Mercedes A-Class and the Smart
car. And when Daimler announced its stunning agreement to take over
Chrysler Corp., it instantly positioned itself to offer both mass
and class.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Volkswagen has said it plans to bolster Rolls-Royce
and Bentley production to 10,000 cars a year from 2,000. That would
still be an almost negligible number, but many experts think it
isn't the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Reitman, an automobile analyst at Merrill Lynch,
predicts that Piech also plans to develop a line of lower-cost
Bentleys, which now sell for more than $200,000 each. Reitman
thinks Volkswagen will try to develop ``Baby Bentleys'' that would
be closer in price to the $120,000 top-line Mercedes S-Class sedan
or the most expensive BMWs. It is easy to imagine, Reitman said,
that Volkswagen could produce as many as 30,000 to 40,000 Bentleys.
Mercedes produces about 44,000 S-Class sedans in its peak years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Objectively, the Audi A8 is as good as the S-Class or BMWs 7
series,'' Reitman said. ``The problem is that you cannot charge
those kinds of prices with the Audi badge.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains far from clear, though, whether taking VW so far
upscale will work. Ford Motor Co. paid $2.4 billion for Jaguar, the
venerable British sports car manufacturer, and then invested more
than $6 billion to modernize it. Ford says Jaguar now turns a
profit, though it won't say how much. Industry analysts say it is
still tiny compared with the investment.
</P>
<P>
   In Rolls-Royce, Volkswagen is at least acquiring a company that
is making money. After coming close to bankruptcy, it was taken
over by Vickers PLC and rehabilitated over the last several years.
It earned about 30 million pounds, or $49 million, on revenues of
300 million pounds, or $491 million, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Piech is also nursing ambitions in the even more exclusive area
of high-performance sports cars. At the Geneva Auto Show in the
spring, Volkswagen introduced a concept car called the W-12 that
looks like a Ferrari or a Maserati. In June came Audi's letter of
intent to acquire Lamborghini, which makes about 200 cars a year
but will provide Volkswagen with an additional famous brand name.
Volkswagen is also negotiating to acquire Bugatti SpA, which went
bankrupt three years ago but still has a prestigious name.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen's joint venture with Porsche to make sport utility
vehicles is likely to prove more substantial. Volkswagen had long
been eager to enter the joint venture, but Porsche executives were
nervous about developing a vehicle that would be so different from
their established line of high-priced sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement announced last month, Porsche will assume
most of the design work and Volkswagen will be responsible for the
manufacturing. The two companies hope to produce about 100,000
luxury sport utility vehicles beginning in 2002. About 80,000 would
be produced for Volkswagen, which is expected to sell them for
about $55,000 each. The rest would be produced for Porsche and sell
for about $85,000 each. Porsche has said it will invest about $550
million in the project; Volkswagen has not said what it expects to
spend.
</P>
<P>
   But all of these projects are tiny in comparison with
Volkswagen's core car businesses, which provide the muscle for new
ventures. Piech, who joined Audi in 1972 and worked his way to the
top ranks of Volkswagen, was elevated to chairman in 1993 when the
company was near financial collapse. Its costs were high, its
quality had deteriorated and its plants were among the most
inefficient in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Piech, an engineer by training, worked to lower costs and
revitalize Volkswagen's various brands. In addition to VW and Audi,
the company owns Seat, based in Spain, and Skoda, based outside of
Prague. Piech recruited Jose Ignacio Lopez de Arriortua, General
Motors' head of purchasing, who had cut billions of dollars in
costs by forcing suppliers to offer better prices.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen's growth has been almost as remarkable as its
previous decline. Revenues jumped to 113 billion marks, or $62.7
billion, in 1997 from 80 billion marks, or $44 billion, in 1994,
and analysts expect them to reach 127 billion marks, or $70.5
billion, this year. Net income climbed to 1.36 billion marks, or
$755 million, from 150 million marks, or $86 million, and is
expected to reach 2.8 billion marks, or $1.6 billion, this year.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Volkswagen, now trading at 183 marks, or $101.60, have
risen fivefold since Piech took over.
</P>
<P>
   But company executives and analysts predict that profits will
climb even more quickly over the next year or two. VW is
consolidating its different models on four separate ``platforms'' _
the interior components like the chassis, brake systems and
electronics of a car. That saves money on parts, simplifies
production and allows factories to shift more easily between
models.
</P>
<P>
   By the end 1997, Volkswagen had shifted about 25 percent of its
production to the four platforms. Jurgen Heinz, an automobile
analyst at West LB Research in Dusseldorf, said the real savings
from the platform strategy were about to hit the bottom line over
the next two years. VW hopes to nearly complete the process _
moving about 90 percent of its production to the four platforms _
by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   But Piech has also infuriated rivals and annoyed investors. At a
time when big European companies increasingly embrace notions of
``shareholder value'' and openness, Volkswagen is often opaque and
highhanded. VW shares abruptly plunged about 12 percent last fall,
for instance, after the company announced a plan to sell a huge
block of stock without providing much explanation of why it needed
the money. The company delayed the offering until March, then went
ahead with half the amount of the original plan.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also complain that the company consistently understates
its true profits, a move that allows it to hold on to more cash and
keep better control. Though German companies are famous for their
conservative accounting, Volkswagen has gone out of its way to take
additional charges. When Volkswagen results are calculated along
the lines of American standards, analysts said, its 1997 income
jumps to 3.2 billion marks, or $1.8 billion, from 1.36 billion
marks.
</P>
<P>
   Piech has not worried much about creating the image of a nice
guy _ and he does not have one. Though Volkswagen has acknowledged
for some time that it used thousands of slave workers during World
War II, when it was a chief weapons supplier for Adolf Hitler,
Piech flatly refused to compensate victims. Earlier this month,
under the threat of being sued, Volkswagen agreed to set up a fund.
</P>
<P>
   He has angered rivals as well. When General Motors accumulated
extensive evidence several years ago that Lopez, its former
purchasing chief, had taken reams of internal data with him when he
joined Volkswagen, Piech dismissed the allegations until just a few
days before he reached a billion-dollar out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   When BMW outbid Volkswagen at an auction for Rolls-Royce this
spring, Piech scuttled the deal with a sweetened offer to Vickers.
BMW, which supplies engines used in the Rolls-Royce Silver Seraph,
immediately announced that it would stop as soon as its contract
expires next July.
</P>
<P>
   Piech was not ruffled. He agreed to buy Cosworth, a manufacturer
of high-performance engines that Vickers also owned. Volkswagen
officials say their own engines will be ready to fill the void
immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
