<SLUG> BC-WELSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALVESTON IMPOSTOR FACES PROBATION HEARING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Final arguments are scheduled for Friday in a
probation revocation hearing for a former Galveston civic leader
who faked suicide and abandoned his family in Ohio 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Welsh, 50, known in Galveston since 1983 as Tim
Kingsbury, could be ordered to serve a four-year prison term he
received in December 1996 after authorities here found forged birth
certificates and other documents in his office at the radio station
he managed.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh's former wife, Elizabeth Welsh, learned he was alive and
tracked him down in Texas after probation terms of his 1996 forgery
conviction forced him to use his real Social Security number. She
started looking for her former husband after federal officials
demanded repayment of Social Security benefits the family received
after Welsh was declared dead.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh's real identity was known to only a few people in
Galveston until his former wife filed Ohio charges against him and
he was arrested on an Ohio indictment on Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh pleaded no contest in an Ohio court in April to nonsupport
and complicity-in-theft charges. He was sentenced to four years in
an Ohio prison on those charges and then extradited to Texas for
this week's probation revocation hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston County District Attorney Mike Guarino said Thursday
that even if the probation is revoked here,Welsh probably will be
returned to Ohio to serve prison time there first. The terms would
be served concurrently, Guarino said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors here maintain he violated his 1996 Texas probation
terms by failing to put his real name on all credit cards, loan
documents ``and any other financial documents wherein defendant is
a party.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(EDITORS: STORY CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney David Walker on Thursday called expert
witnesses who testified Welsh legally was not a ``party'' to
property sales and purchases to which he signed his assumed name
when he was president of the Galveston Historical Foundation in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The experts also said bank signature authorization cards he
signed as a foundation officer and as a United Way officer legally
are not ``documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Among prosecution witnesses was Frank W. Jackson III, executive
director of Unitied Way of Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing Welsh's probation terms on the stand, Jackson said:
``As I see this, the bank records, the signature cards, should have
been changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Miller, a retired accountant and one of the owners of the
radio station where Welsh worked, said he was helping with an
income tax form in 1996 when Welsh claimed to have had his name
legally changed. Attorneys, however, said that the defendant could
not have changed his name while on probation.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh was convicted in 1980 of stealing money from Ohio State
University, where he worked as a fund-raiser. He was on probation
when he fled Ohio, leaving his wife and sons, 10 and 6. He later
sent his wife letters saying he would kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
