<HEADER>
A8970 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-FORCE17-COX     07-16 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORMER COMRADES CAST DOUBT ON AIR FORCE NOMINEE'S INTEGRITY
 &HT;    By SHANNON JOYCE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's nominee for secretary of the
Air Force watched Thursday as fellow officers from his former
reserve wing told the Senate Armed Services Committee he had not
been truthful at his first confirmation hearing a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong hearing addressed several issues in Florida State
Sen. Daryl Jones's past, including how he was grounded as a fighter
pilot in 1991, whether or not he knew he had been overpaid for
about three years, and if he used his position as an officer to
peddle Amway home cleaning products.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony from Jones's former superior officers led some
senators on the panel to express doubt whether he was fit to serve
as Air Force secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Jones told the panel in June that he made the difficult decision
to ground himself after the demands of running for office, rasing
children, and starting a law practice took too much time away from
his fighter pilot training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision to ground Daryl Jones and no one else,''
Col. Thomas Dyches told the committee. Dyches was Jones' commanding
officer during his last days as a fighter pilot in Homestead Air
Force Base's 482 Fighter Wing, and said Jones had been warned that
without more practice time in the F-16, he would not be allowed to
continue flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have read and listened to the testimony Mr. Jones gave to
this committee, and sadly I must say that he misrepresented the
facts to you and the American people,'' Dyches said.
</P>
<P>
   Another officer in the reserve unit said he witnessed the
meeting and took notes as Jones threatened to challenge the
decision to take a ground job or face a formal panel to take his
wings.
</P>
<P>
   Jones stood by his original testimony, stating the discrepancies
simply showed two different memories of the same meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I have a different recollection of an event
doesn't mean I don't have integrity,'' Jones told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he didn't have to accept Dyches' grounding or leave
the reserves. He could have asked to go before a Flight Evaluation
Board, a scrutiny Jones said he believes he would have survived.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jones said he took Dyches' advice and went home to
think about Dyches' offer to find him a job on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to contest that when I knew I wouldn't be
able to take the eight to 10 days'' for training,'' Jones said
about his choice to take the ground job.
</P>
<P>
   Other glitches in Jones' testimony surfaced as well.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Maj. Thomas Massey said he witnessed Jones trying to
sell Amway products to a group of enlisted men during a daylong
training exercise, an action strictly prohibited in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Massey told Jones to stop, but ``he quickly dismissed my
comments,'' Massey said. ``I was dumbfounded, because he was not
only violating an Air Force regulation, but he was doing it
knowingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican members of the committee said the incidents
point to a fundamental flaw in the personality of a future
secretary of the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Mr. Jones has an insatiable appetite to say
things that aren't true, and that is a very significant issue,''
said Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said he saw Jones's failure to take
accountability for his actions as a disturbing trend in behavior.
</P>
<P>
   After Jones relinquished his flight status, he continued to
collect fighter pilot pay for three years, despite warnings. Jones
said it was an accounting error on the part of the Air Force, and
he had heard that reserve pilots, like their active duty
counterparts, continue to collect flight pay after they've stopped
flying.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said another instance, in which Jones blamed his staff
for listing himself as a fighter pilot on his resume after his
grounding, made him wonder if he would be able take responsibility
for the weighty decisions he would make as Air Force secretary.
</P>
<P>
   While several friends testified to Jones' good character and
strong leadership, none were able to corroborate his accounts of
the grounding or the Amway incident.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
