<HEADER>
A8979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-BUSINESS-COX     07-16 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-BUSINESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Increasing Black Business: Gore announces 1.4 billion loan
program
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Small business advocates in metro Atlanta Thursday
hailed a federal plan aimed at putting $1.4 billion in loans in the
black business community, but warned that the program was useless
if black entrepreneurs didn't have help dealing with complicated
bank loan requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership between the NAACP and the Small Business
Administration is part of an ambitious three-year effort by the SBA
to increase loans to blacks. The plan was unveiled by Vice
President Al Gore Thursday at the NAACP annual convention in
Atlanta. The federal agency has enlisted the NAACP's aid to extend
its reach into the black community.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, with a black population of about 68 percent, stands to
benefit significantly from the SBA program . The area ranks second
only to New York in the number of black-owned firms, according to
SBA data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is fertile ground for increasing opportunities because
there are so many startups of African American -owned businesses
who could grow their business if they could get access to cheaper
capital _ which is what is possible through the SBA. And that's
really at the heart of this,'' said SBA chief Aida Alvarez, who
spent Thursday in Atlanta meeting with businesspeople, attending
the NAACP conference and touring the One Stop Capital Shop, a small
business help center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Under the loan initiative, black entrepreneurs will conceivably
be able to walk into their local NAACP branch to get help in
starting or expanding their business. Officials at the 69 SBA
district offices, including Atlanta, and local NAACP branches will
be working closely in the future on workshops and seminars designed
to make it easier for blacks to get through the cumbersome business
loan process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most significant step since the institution of
minority procurement programs,'' said Georgia Tech economics
professor Thomas D. Boston. Boston was among 30 Atlanta area
business leaders who met with Gore and Alvarez Thursday to discuss
ways to assist and help increase the number of black-owned
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a loan (program) targeted specifically for black
businesses,'' he added. `` Most government programs have been open
to all minority and women-owned businesses. Often, those programs
get skewed in favor of women.''
</P>
<P>
   Leona Barr-Davenport, president of the Atlanta Business League,
a small business advocacy group of about 300 companies, called the
loan initiative an excellent opportunity for black-owned businesses
to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   `` With the way the country is going with affirmative action, we
need as many vehicles in place as possible to allow our businesses
to function and flourish in light of some of those state agencies
that still don't provide the kinds of help to African-American and
small business owners as they ought to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But without expert help in putting the loan package together,
there won't be large increases in the number of black-owned
businesses, said Carlotta Roberts, director of Kennesaw State
University's Small Business Development Center. About 20 percent of
the 300 clients the centers sees annually are black.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good start,'' she said. ``It's an attempt to get
more small business owners qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
