<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-GORE-COX     07-16 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore preaches to choir from his pulpit
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The reverend, ... well actually Vice President Al
Gore made a convert of NAACP delegate Esther Trice Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the money _ $1.4 billion for black businesses _ that
did it. And it wasn't the monument _ the newly authorized one for
Martin Luther King Jr. in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   It was the man, said Trice from Mount Union, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting Scripture, prophesying redemption and sometimes
borrowing a Southern preacher's inflection, Gore won over Trice
who, at best, was lukewarm about his intentions and skeptical about
his motives before he took the podium to address the thousands
attending the annual convention of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Gore's 45-minute address in which he
declared America still needed affirmative action and vowed to
resolve the financial blight plaguing black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Gore proclaimed, ``We have the ability in our
souls, given to us by God, to transcend racism!'' And it was before
Trice found out about Gore's father, whose political career ended
when he refused to sign in 1956 the Southern Manifesto, which
pledged to reverse the court decision that integrated schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know about his father,'' Trice said almost
apologetically. ``My heart just goes out to him. Sometimes you can
carry the seed, and sometimes you can't. He truly carries the seed.
I have to take back all that stuff I said before (Gore's speech).''
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of delegates at the convention Thursday morning,
Trice wondered about the timing of the $1.4 billion in loans being
made available to black business owners over the next two years.
She was among those who believed it was a move for Gore to curry
favor among black voters as he prepares to run for president.
``This is one of his candidacy moves,'' she surmised.
</P>
<P>
   People still swim in the river where she lives, and she wants to
open a fitness club with a pool. Before Gore spoke, she said she
would decide her political position depending on whether that money
would help businesses with just a few employees. And there would be
another test: ``It'll depend on his speech ... if he's looking at
you or looking through you.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidayon Mayers-Kelley employs 14 people in her two Atlanta
businesses. The timing of the NAACP partnership with the Small
Business Administration that Gore announced would infuse $1.4
billion in loans into black businesses didn't bother her.
``Everybody who does something, does it for a reason,'' she said.
``Sometimes you can accidentally do some good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayers-Kelley, who said she was a Clinton-Gore supporter before
she was aware of the money, was more concerned about whether the
money would help black businesses that employ just a handful of
people and if the SBA would get input from local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses that employ a handful or 200 people would qualify for
the loans, said Billy Max Paul, the SBA's southeast regional
administrator. The goal is to quadruple the number of black-owned
businesses by 2000, he said. Black people comprise 12 percent of
the population, Paul said, but 3.6 percent of business owners.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Pickney of Eutawville, S.C., didn't care about Gore's
motives. ``I look at (the money) as they seeing they need it,''
said Pickney who said she would vote for Gore. ``He's the vice
president of Clinton and Clinton has done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore's talk of how many African-Americans Clinton had
appointed to national and cabinet positions that brought the crowd
to its feet one of a half dozen times. As Gore rattled off the list
that included secretarys of energy, agriculture, commerce,
transportation, labor, veterans affairs and surgeon general, NAACP
Chairman Julian Bond stood banging his hand on the table with glee
as the crowd waved miniature American flags in the air.
</P>
<P>
   With a few Bible verses, Gore raised his voice in a pledge for
unity to provide better employment, education and economic
opportunities for black Americans. ``Rejoice with them that do
rejoice, and weep with them that weep,'' he bellowed. ``Be of the
same mind one toward another. ... And the crooked places shall be
made straight and the rough places plain: And the glory of the Lord
shall be revealed, and all flesh shall see it together!''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd burst into strands of ``We Shall Overcome,'' Trice
proclaimed her conversion and declared Gore sincere. ``He looked at
us,'' she said. ``He looked at us!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
