<SLUG> BC-MA-ATM-FEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL BLOCKING ATM FEES DEAD FOR THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran said Thursday that
legislation banning automated teller machine surcharges is dead for
this year, allowing BankBoston Corp. and Fleet Financial Group Inc.
to move ahead with plans to impose $1 fees.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the two banks declined to say when they would start
charging customers of other banks who use their ATMs, but it
probably won't be long.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston has said preparations to impose the fees are going
according to schedule and testing of the system should start soon.
The banks are required to give the state 30 days notice before they
begin assessing the fees.
</P>
<P>
   Most smaller banks had supported the legislation, fearing
customers would desert in droves if the two big banks start
charging them a fee each time they use one of the banks' ATMs.
BankBoston and Fleet say they doubt that will happen and add that
the fees are the cost of having the convenience of using another
bank's ATM network.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran gave no explanation for his action Thursday, but his
comments in recent days have indicated that he did not want to
meddle in an industry dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision again underscored the power of the House
speaker to do pretty much whatever he wants even though he is only
one of 160 House members.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the House had signed a petition asking that the bill
banning surcharges be released from the House Ways and Means
Committee so the full chamber could vote on it. The bill passed the
Senate unanimously 38-0 last year and had the support of Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ways and Means Committee, which suppressed the bill
apparently on the speaker's orders, had sent conflicting signals in
recent months on what it would do with the bill. On the same day
recently, the spokeswoman for the committee told one reporter that
the bill was not going anywhere and told another that it would be
released in some form after the budget had been approved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
