<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-DELAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PUT OFF EFFORT TO OVERTURN ORDER ON GAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A small group of conservative Republicans postponed
their effort Thursday to reverse a presidential order prohibiting
discrimination against gays in the federal work force.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, directed by Rep. Joel Hefley, R-Colo., and backed by
House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, and Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Sugar Land, was postponed out of concern that it would be
embarrassing to Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, the only openly gay
Republican in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe chairs the committee that approved a treasury and postal
spending bill that the Republican leaders wanted to use as a
vehicle to carry an amendment overriding Clinton's
anti-discrimination order.
</P>
<P>
   Hefley said he would try to attach his amendment to another
spending bill next week, one that Kolbe has no authority over.
</P>
<P>
   Armey told reporters that he plans to continue his support for
the Hefley amendment, not because of his own views on gays but
because of what he called ``the excessive and abusive use'' of
executive orders by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that a responsible Congress can allow a
president to govern by fiat,'' Armey said in an interview with
Texas reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Armey acknowledged that he does not believe that any
group of citizens should afforded a special protection based on
what he called ``a behavioral issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My own personal feeling is that we have civil rights
legislation that protects people from discrimination,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Hefley's amendment, according to some Republican aides, grew out
of a so-called ``values summit'' in May sponsored by DeLay in which
Christian conservative leaders won a promise from GOP House leaders
to support their ``family values agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Republicans led by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
of Mississippi have labeled homosexuality a sin and blocked the
nomination of the openly gay James Hormel as ambassador to
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(EDITORS: STORY CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Christian conservatives have placed ads in newspapers
imploring gay people to renounce their homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe warned his Republican colleagues Thursday that if they
persisted with their assault on gays, they could alienate a
substantial bloc of voters in November. He called the Hefley
amendment, not to mention the anti-gay rhetoric from his party
leaders, ``a bad signal'' for the GOP to be sending.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
