<SLUG> BC-SECURITIES-SCAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC CHARGES BAY STATERS IN ALLEGED INTERNET SECURITIES SCAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Federal securities regulators Thursday charged two
Massachusetts brokers with being part of a nationwide ring that
peddled fake securities over the Internet and bilked investors of
$7.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission alleged in a complaint
filed in US District Court that Anthony Garry, of Beverly, and
Thomas Connolly, of Wilmington, played key roles in selling phony
certificates of deposit to clients enticed by the promise of high
returns.
</P>
<P>
   The fake investments were part of an international Ponzi scheme
originating in suburban Chicago that shuttled money between dozens
of accounts in the United States and overseas, regulators alleged.
In a Ponzi scheme, early investors in a scam are paid with money
that comes from later investors, who typically lose their money.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Michael D. Richmond, of Orland Park,
Ill., invented and ran the scheme, advertising various investments
in Royal Meridian National Bank, which he claimed was an
international private bank in the South Pacific. He said the
institution is a ``fully chartered'' bank with offices in
Vancouver, the Bahamas, Guernsey, and Turks &AMP; Caicos.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the bank is ``a shell'' with no offices and no revenues,
regulators allege.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond set up an Internet site late last year advertising bank
investments, including certificates of deposit with little or no
risk and ``great yield'' and money market accounts of up to 24
percent, the complaint alleges. The site instructed investors to
fill out an investment application and courier checks to an office
in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond also employed a network of agents _ including Garry and
Connolly _ through Liberty Network, a financial planning school
Richmond ran, the complaint alleges. Garry sold at least $500,000
in certificates of deposit in Massachusetts, and Connolly sold the
investments despite warnings from his firm.
</P>
<P>
   About 185 investors in 14 states, including Massachusetts,
bought the phony investments, the complaint alleges. Regulators
said they have been able to trace just $2.7 million of the money
invested. At least $4 million was used by Richmond and his
employees, the complaint contends. Richmond spent $72,000 to lease
a car, used $2,500 for a boat, $895 for a ring and spent $18,000 on
home improvements, regulators alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond, 49, previously was sanctioned by the state of Illinois
in 1991 for selling unregistered securities, according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Also named in the complaint are K. Bruce Nuckles, an estate
planner in Virginia Beach, Va., and William Duke, a resident of
Florida who allegedly issued false account statements to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the defendants declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Reginald Lindsay Thursday halted the
defendants' sales and froze their assets. The judge also asked the
defendants to account for investors' money by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Richmond case is one of the biggest Internet fraud claims
filed by the SEC, said Jay Perlman, a senior SEC attorney. &UR;  &LR; In one
of the biggest previous cases alleging Internet securities fraud,
Systems of Excellence Inc. chairman Charles Huttoe pleaded guilty
in January 1997 to defrauding investors of $12 million. He was
sentenced to 46 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
