<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-DAEWOO-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAEWOO LEGANZA AND NUBIRA DAEWOO WHO? THE LOW-KEY ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Daewoo wants to stand out in the traffic jam at the low-price
and family-sedan end of the market, the company's collegial sales
strategy may be its best hope. Its cars, while worth a look, have
no inherent characteristics that set them apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Daewoos' styling sets the tone. Anyone worried about being
the first on the block to own something that might attract too many
stares can buy with confidence. A Daewoo is the road-going version
of the federal witness-protection program. Test drives of the
Leganza and the Nubira brought a few second glances from car-savvy
motorists, but most comments came from attendants at parking
garages and service stations.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the top-of-the-line Leganza, the compact
Nubira and the subcompact Lanos are ugly _ they might have drawn
more looks if they were. But they are stealth vehicles, which
testifies to how well-proportioned, and derivative, they are. The
Leganza, designed with the help of Giorgetto Giugiaro, the Italian
who created the original Volkswagen Scirocco, blends a few parts
Lexus GS with a smidgeon of Nissan Altima. The Nubira's front end
is vaguely reminiscent of a small BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The name Leganza _ wiseacres are already calling it ``the
lasagna'' _ is a melding of the Italian words elegante and forza
(power). But in trying to build what Daewoo calls an elegant sedan
with a comfortable ride, something was lost in translation.
</P>
<P>
   It is a competent midsize sedan, with comfortable seats (my test
car had six-way power adjustments and manual bolster control) and
room for five people. The handling is secure, with a lot of
predictable understeer, and the four-wheel antilock disk brakes
have good pedal response and produce sure stops.
</P>
<P>
   But Daewoo has miles to go in quietness and ride quality before
the Leganza matches cars like the Honda Accord or Chevrolet Malibu.
Road noise over grooved pavement is a howl; the car's nose
porpoises over uneven surfaces, and road joints are transmitted
harshly to the occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Engine noise from the 16-valve, 131-horsepower in-line four (2.2
liters) intrudes under heavy acceleration. At highway speed,
though, the car could cruise comfortably at 80 or more _ if it
weren't for a disturbing glitch: The engine refused to hold a
steady rev level. Every few seconds, the rpm would dip by about
500, then rise again. In about 700 miles of driving, it never got
worse _ or better. Two other test drivers reported similar
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The Leganza tries hard to be user-friendly, perhaps its most
endearing trait. The full-size spare was mounted on an exact match
to the other handsome wheels, and the trunk had a CD changer
attached to an upper surface, not the floor. For cargo, the rear
seat folds in a 2-to-1 proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Interior controls were good, with the climate setting adjustable
by degree, but the illuminated graphic on the ventilation takes
some getting used to, with its swirling lines and arrows. The real
puzzler was the premium sound system, with rows of tiny buttons
bearing indecipherable labels. Its graphic equalizer can be
individually tuned or programmed for the type of music (pop, disco,
etc.) and ambience (stage, theater, church), so you can get the
most from that album of disco hymns. Even with all the adjustments,
the sound was lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   And there were some annoying quality lapses. The vanity mirrors
in the visors looked as if they came from a fun house, and the
sunroof shade felt tinny.
</P>
<P>
   The Nubira, the compact sedan that is a step down from the
Leganza, provided the more pleasant driving experience, once its
lower price (starting around $9,000) is factored in. Perhaps
because of its lighter weight, it exhibited less harshness on road
joints. The handling seemed closer to neutral, too, but required a
steady hand in fast cornering. As with the Leganza, the anti-lock
disks produced smooth, steady stops.
</P>
<P>
   Power was adequate, although the 2-liter, 129-horsepower engine
seemed to strain more up hills than you'd think, given that the
much lighter car had nearly as many horsepower. The throttle
problem in the Leganza could also be felt to a lesser extent in the
Nubira. The optional four-speed automatic shifted with creamy
smoothness.
</P>
<P>
   On a long drive, the front seats were comfortable, with six-way
manual adjustment (just spare any backseat passengers an extended
ride). The seatback was the only difficult adjustment, with not
enough clearance between the knob and the door post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
