<HEADER>
A9019 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-PRICE-HNS     07-16 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-PRICE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYNE CUSTRED  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SOUTHPORT, England _ If Nick Price should win the 1998 British Open
this week at Royal Birkdale, he will have his near miss at last
month's U.S. Open to thank.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Price's fourth-place finish at the Olympic Club for him
to realize that the reason he hasn't won is not his golf swing but
his putting stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I've had over the last six months is that
I have not putted solidly,'' Price said. ``I have not putted badly.
But I've not been making the bonus putts, like a couple of the ones
I made today, the 15-to-20-foot range. Sometimes, it takes
something like the U.S. Open to give me a good kick in the backside
and go and practice my putting more.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was exactly what Price did, and the results showed in
Thursday's first round. Price shot a 4-under-par 66 and was only
one shot behind co-leaders John Huston and Tiger Woods. Four of his
birdie putts Thursday were from 12 feet or longer, including a
22-footer on No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I changed putters right after the Open,'' Price said. ``I've
gone back to a face-balanced putter. I've always putted best with a
face-balanced putter or mallet-type putter. My game from tee to
green has been solid for, I feel like, the last 2{ years. If I
could just get to putt like I did from that spell from 1992 through
1994, I probably would have won a couple of tournaments this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been playing for seventh, eighth, ninth places,
because the club has been in the bag for show, just making up the
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Price the world came to know in the early to mid-1990s
finished first far more often than seventh or eighth. He won twice
in 1991 and 1992, including the 1992 PGA Championship. Then, he won
four times in 1993 and five times in 1994, picking up his second
PGA Championship title.
</P>
<P>
   Price finished No. 1 on the PGA Tour money list in 1993 and '94,
earning player-of-the-year honors both years.
</P>
<P>
   But as the demands on his time grew and his life became hectic
and hurried, Price's game began to slide. He didn't win again until
the 1997 MCI Classic. In the past 18 months, however, Price has
slowly returned to top form. This week, a number of players picked
him as one of the golfers to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The return of his game has come hand-in-hand with the return of
peace to his private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got all my priorities in order a couple of years ago,''
Price said, ``and life has been an absolute pleasure the last year
and a half. I still have the desire, which I think is the thing
that's the key. I enjoy going out and practicing and playing. I
still love playing the game. But it's been frustrating because my
putting has not kept me at the strength I was playing at in the
early 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to change that, Price went home after the U.S. Open
and headed to the putting green. He spent a couple of hours a day
for 10 days grinding it out with his new putter. And finally, Price
believes his efforts are paying off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting is a psychological thing,'' Price said. ``My biggest
problem has always been starting the ball on line. I feel with this
putter, I start the ball on line and I can be more focused on the
speed. It's such a fickle thing. It's like a science, a game within
a game.''
</P>
<P>
   So Price has high hopes for the rest of the tournament. He would
love to return to the spotlight with another major victory, but if
it is not meant to be, that is fine with Price as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when you've got kids and a family, it's not the
be-all and end-all when you don't play that well,'' Price said.
``Especially your kids. My kids have no idea what I do. My kids are
too young to really understand. They still think Greg Norman is a
better golfer than I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
