<HEADLINE>
BEYOND THE CITY LIMITS: WHERE TO FIND THE SUMMERTIME EXHIBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With SUMMER-LONG-ISLAND, SUMMER-NEW-JERSEY, SUMMER-HUDSON, AND
SUMMER-CONNECTICUT and SUMMER-ART-RDP)  
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is information about the museums mentioned in the four
reviews of suburban art exhibitions:
</P>
<P>
   Long Island:
</P>
<P>
   NASSAU COUNTY MUSEUM OF ART, 1 Museum Dr., Roslyn Harbor, (516)
484-9338. ``Calder and Miro'' and ``Toulouse-Lautrec: The Baldwin
M. Baldwin Collection.'' Through Sept. 13. Admission: $4; $3 for
the elderly; $2 for students and children.
</P>
<P>
   HECKSCHER MUSEUM OF ART, 2 Prime Ave., Huntington, (516)
351-3250. ``William de Leftwich Dodge: Impressions Home and
Abroad'' (through Aug. 30), ``Americans in Paris: Studies and
Sojourns Abroad'' (through Nov. 8), ``Country Pleasures: Views of
Long Island'' (through Aug. 23) and ``The Doves: Hearth and Home,''
(through Aug. 30). Admission: $3; $1 for children over 6.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUMS AT STONY BROOK, 1208 Route 25A, Stony Brook, (516)
751-0066. ``Stanford White on Long Island'' (through Nov. 1) and
``Joseph Reboli'' (through Sept. 7). Admission: $4; $3 for the
elderly; $2 for students.
</P>
<P>
   POLLOCK-KRASNER HOUSE AND STUDY CENTER, 830 Fireplace Rd., East
Hampton, (516) 324-4929. ``By Hand: The Paper of Douglass Morse
Howell'' (through July 26). By appointment only. Admission: $5.
</P>
<P>
   GUILD HALL, 158 Main St., East Hampton, (516) 324-0806. ``East
Hampton Artists: Seen and Scene'' (through July 26); ``Paintings
and Sculpture by Julian Schnabel'' (Aug. 8-Sept. 27). Admission:
$3.
</P>
<P>
   PARRISH ART MUSEUM, 25 Job's Lane, Southampton, (516) 283-2118.
``Dreams for the Next Century: A View of the Collection'' and a
site-specific installation by Barbara Kruger. Opens Sunday (through
Sept. 6). Admission: $2; $1 for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey:
</P>
<P>
   NEWARK MUSEUM, 49 Washington St., Newark, (973) 596-6550.
``Exotic Illusions: Art, Romance and the Marketplace'' (through
Aug. 16). Free.
</P>
<P>
   ALJIRA, 2 Washington Place, Newark, (973) 643-6877. ``Martha
Posner: Selections from the Garment Series'' (through Aug. 8).
Free.
</P>
<P>
   ROBESON CENTER ART GALLERY, Rutgers University, 350 Martin
Luther King Boulevard, Newark, (973) 353-1610. ``The Sky Below:
Paintings by Gregory Amenoff'' (through July 30). Free.
</P>
<P>
   MASON GROSS SCHOOL OF THE ARTS GALLERY, Rutgers University, 33
Livingston Ave., New Brunswick, (732) 932-1263. ``Mexico
Exporta/Mexico Exports: Noe Hernandez'' and ``Puerto Rican Graphic
Arts From the Island at El Barrio/Spanish Harlem: 1950 to 1985''
(both through Aug. 20). Free.
</P>
<P>
   JANE VOORHEES ZIMMERLI ART MUSEUM, Rutgers University, 71
Hamilton St., New Brunswick, (732) 932-7237. ``Paul Robeson: Artist
and Citizen'' (through July 31). Hours; Wednesdays through Fridays,
10 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.; closed
Mondays and Tuesdays. Admission: $3; free for students, Rutgers
alumni and children.
</P>
<P>
   MONTCLAIR MUSEUM OF ART, 3 South Mountain Ave., Montclair, (973)
746-5555. ``Maurice Prendergast, the State of the Estate'' and
``Collecting Culture: Grace Nicholson'' (both through Aug. 16).
Hours: Wednesdays through Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.; closed Mondays
and Tuesdays. Admission: $5; $4 for students and the elderly; free
for children 12 and younger. Hudson Valley
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON RIVER MUSEUM, 511 Warburton Ave., Yonkers, (914)
963-4550. ``Where Land Meets River'' and ``Go Figure'' (both
through Sept. 20.) Admission: $3; $1.50 for the elderly and
children 12 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   NEUBERGER MUSEUM OF ART, Purchase College, State University of
New York, 735 Anderson Hill Rd., Purchase, (914) 251-6100. ``Robert
Berlind: Paintings, 1982-1996'' (through Sept. 6), ``Glass Houses''
(through Sept. 13 ) and ``The Buds and the Beads,'' an installation
by Nancy Davidson (through Oct. 4 ). Admission: $4; $2 for the
elderly and students.
</P>
<P>
   KATONAH MUSEUM OF ART, Route 22 at Jay Street, Katonah, (914)
232-9555. ``Pavel Tchelitchew: Landscape of the Body'' (through
Sept. 6.). Admission: $2; members and children 12 and under, free.
</P>
<P>
   STORM KING ART CENTER, Old Pleasant Hill Rd., Mountainville,
(914) 534-3115. ``The Fields of David Smith'' (through 1999).
Admission: $7; $5 for the elderly; $3 for children over 5 and
students; free for children 5 and younger and for everyone after 5
p.m. on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCES LEHMAN LOEB ART CENTER, Vassar College, 124 Raymond
Ave., Poughkeepsie, (914) 437-5237. ``Acquisitions on Paper:
1988-1998'' (through Sept. 20.). Free.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FOR CURATORIAL STUDIES, Bard College, off Route 9G,
Annandale-on-Hudson, (914) 758-7598. ``Stills: A Selection from the
Marieluise Hessel Collection''(through Sept. 6). Free.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut:
</P>
<P>
   WADSWORTH ATHENEUM, 600 Main St., Hartford, (860) 278-2670.
``Caravaggio and His Followers'' (through July 26). Admission: $7;
$5 for the elderly; $3 for children six to 17; free for those under
6. Additional fee for the Caravaggio exhibition: $2; $1 for the
elderly and those 6 to 17 years old.
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY MUSEUM OF AMERICAN ART AT CHAMPION, 1 Champion Plaza,
Atlantic Street and Tresser Boulevard, Stamford, (203) 358-7652.
``Where: Allegories of Site in Contemporary Art'' (through Aug.
26). Free.
</P>
<P>
   YALE UNIVERSITY ART GALLERY, Chapel and York Streets, New Haven,
(203) 432-0600. ``Then and Now and Later'' (through July 31). Free.
</P>
<P>
   ALDRICH MUSEUM OF CONTEMPORARY ART, 258 Main St. (Route 35),
Ridgefield, (203) 438-4519. ``Pop Surrealism'' (through Aug. 30).
Admission: $5; $2 for students and the elderly; free for children
under 12.
</P>
