<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-OPEN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods, Huston lead British
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Not one to miss out on good scoring
conditions, even in a major championship where frequently he's been
outmuscled by the heather and hay, Tiger Woods shot to the top of
the British Open leaderboard Thursday at Royal Birkdale, taking a
share of the first-round lead at 5-under-par 65 with fellow
American John Huston.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to last year at Royal Troon, Woods went from big
numbers to low numbers. He hit irons or 3-wood off tees and hit
fairways. He managed his game. Considered by some observers to have
vanished from golf's mainstream except for a win in Atlanta two
months ago, Woods jumped back into the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased,'' Woods said. ``I played very well today,
made a lot of good putts, drove the ball very well. Consequently, I
was able to control my spin on the greens because I was in a lot of
fairways.''
</P>
<P>
   Huston, who has been sleeping on magnets to ease shoulder and
back pain, eagled the 17th hole and birdied the 18th on a day when
the winds died down significantly and the temperatures warmed.
After three cold days with winds that once reached gusts of 55 mph,
Thursday was by comparison a day at Palm Springs, with 27 players
under par. If you drove the ball straight and missed the rough, it
provided the groundwork for a low score.
</P>
<P>
   One shot back at 66 are Americans Fred Couples and Loren Roberts
and Nick Price of Zimbabwe. At 67, two shots off the lead, are
Americans Davis Love III of Sea Island and Brad Faxon, Australian
Robert Allenby, Vijay Singh of Fiji and Sweden's Fredrik Jacobson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have predicted about 10 over winning if every day was
like Monday,'' Huston said. ``(Conditions) have gradually got a
little easier every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't expect the weather to be like this
(Thursday),'' said Couples, ``so I don't know what it's going to be
like (Friday). Maybe it will be back to normal where a 72 or 73
will be a good score.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone took advantage of the conditions. Defending
champion Justin Leonard, Scotland's Colin Montgomerie and five-time
champion Tom Watson settled for 3-over 73s. Georgia Tech's Matt
Kuchar, the U.S. Amateur champion, managed a 75 _ six shots higher
than Spain's superb amateur, Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Goergia Tech was prominent on the leaderboard elsewhere. David
Duval, who leads the PGA Tour money list, shot an even-par 70,
along with Columbus' Larry Mize. Atlanta's Stewart Cink opened with
a 71 to match England's Lee Westwood, a local betting favorite
along with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Tightening up his sometimes suspect putting, Woods turned in
4-under 30 with birdie putts ranging from 6 to 20 feet and slipped
only a bit. He missed a 3-footer on the 12th for bogey and then
smacked an 8-iron over at the 18th for a bogey that cost him the
sole lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think last year I made a couple of mistakes,'' Woods said,
``and I went for too much instead of playing a little safe. ...
It's just learning how to play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
