<TEXT>
<P>
   Kuchar's status, play still amateur
</P>
<P>
   By Furman Bisher
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England -- Seemingly, it is such a matter for
discussion that a rather large choir of press nobility gathered by
the first tee at an alarmingly early hour of the morning to watch
Matt Kuchar strike his first shot in the British Open. Matt Kuchar,
amateur champion of the United States, had become quite a magnet
for attention since landing at Royal Birkdale, bordered on one side
by the Irish Sea, on another by a suburb of this blue-collar resort
town.
</P>
<P>
   Would he turn professional, would he continue the carefree life
of college at Georgia Tech, playing the game for fun, leaving all
that endorsement money lying on the table?
</P>
<P>
   The sky was low and blackening when he was introduced, playing
with old Sam Torrance of Scotland and Stuart Appleby, the
Australian Adonis who reminds you of a blond Frank Stranahan.
Kuchar chose an iron and pulled the tee shot into hay. British
galleries have a sense of timing, and they applaud only when the
shot merits it, and so sat silent. He would bogey the hole, and
this would sort of set the tone for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Old dad, Peter Kuchar, was on the bag as usual. ``I like having
my dad caddie for me,'' Matt said. ``We have a good time
together.'' This time the caddie was less animated than at the U.S.
Open, where the brass called him in and asked him to cool it. So
when Matt rolled in a 35-foot putt for birdie, Peter merely grinned
broadly and gave a little fist thrust.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Matt did little to incite histrionics.
</P>
<P>
   Two holes pretty much established his round. He was back to even
par after the birdie on fourth hole when disaster struck. The fifth
is a big swinging dogleg right, and in an attempt to cut the
corner, Kuchar was a bit short, but the lie in the mild rough was
not bad. His second shot, though, flew like a rocket, onto and over
the green under the low-hanging limbs of a pine. He made a
misguided effort to slash it out and failed. A second swing
advanced the ball a few feet, and in the end he had to sink a
downhill putt from 12 feet to save double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   At the 13th, his drive was one of the rare ones that split the
fairway. He hit his approach to 20 feet, and here he takes over.
``I walk up thinking birdie and walk off with a bogey.'' He
three-putted, the mortal sin of golf. Now he was 4 over par and it
wouldn't get any better. He made a remarkable recovery from a
pothole bunker to save par at the 12th, a lovely par 3. He was the
master of the up-and-down several other times, but when he came to
the 17th, a 547-yard par 5 inviting birdie with a trailing wind, he
found the rough again, then a bunker and bogeyed.
</P>
<P>
   So, at the end of his first round of British Open golf, his 75
was six strokes behind the leading amateur, Sergio Garcia, the
Spaniard who won the British Amateur. It had been a round that
frustrates, ``Not the pressure,'' he said. ``I was ready for the
pressure. It was all the fairways missed. I was driving so poorly,
and I'm working on my fourth driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, we approach the maddening issue of to pro or not to pro.
There is a pile of endorsements out there should he make the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very marketable. Highly marketable,'' said Bev Norwood of IMG.
``On marketability, he's ready. As for his game, I'm not so sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kuchars, pere et fils, are approaching crisis time. Does he
defend his U.S. Amateur title and risk not winning again, and
losing market appeal? Does he turn after the Palmer Cup and get on
with it? Or does he go back to school for his degree and a chance
at winning a national collegiate championship? Or, would you risk
making the turn with a game not yet mature enough and the prospect
of being another wealthy Marty Fleckman? That is, being quite
wealthy but no game to back it up, without the pride of
achievement?
</P>
<P>
   Based on finishes in the professional tournaments he has played
this year, six from the Masters to Loch Lomond, he would have
earned about $105,000. Not much for a pro's life. The pressure now
is not only on his game, but on the decision. Time after time, both
Matt and Peter have been forced to give the same answer:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not thinking about that right now. We have no idea yet
what's going to happen. Right now,'' says Matt, ``I just want to
enjoy my first British Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
