<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-SIDEBAR17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting Price on putts
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ In howling conditions earlier in the week
when balls were either struck low into the wind or simply struck
down, Nick Price loomed an even bigger favorite to contend in the
127th British Open. While others quaked at the thought of 72 holes
around Royal Birkdale in such windshirt-whipping madness, Price
merely shrugged on the practice range as he bored another long iron
into the dark sky.
</P>
<P>
   Wind? What wind?
</P>
<P>
   ``A gentle zephyr,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   With calm conditions and warmer temperatures bringing more
players into the field Thursday, Price's solid ball-striking still
put him among the elite. Shooting a 4-under-par 66 in the first
round, Price positioned himself a stroke off the pace set by Tiger
Woods and John Huston.
</P>
<P>
   It was Price's best round in the British Open since he won at
Turnberry in 1994. That he missed just two greens seemed nothing
unusual. That he missed very few opportunities while on the greens
explained the 66. Everyone knows that if Nick Price's putting had
been anything close to his ball striking in recent years, more than
three majors would be on his bio by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game from tee to green has been solid for the last two and
a half years,'' Price said Thursday. ``If I could just get to putt
like I did from that spell from, '92 to '94 (when he won two PGA
Championships and a British), I probably have won a few more
tournaments this year.''
</P>
<P>
   A few more days like Thursday and Price might even secure more
respect around his Hobe Sound, Florida, home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids have no idea what I do,'' said Price. ``My kids are
too young to understand. They still think Greg Norman is a better
golfer than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Price was kidding there. His putter was no joke. All the hard
work the good-natured Zimbabwean has done with his flatstick lately
has started to pay off. To those amateur players who can not spare
15 minutes on the putting green, consider that Price has been there
16-18 hours over the past two weeks. Three hours at a stretch
sometimes. In south Florida summer heat, it's less taxing than
hitting balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest problem has always been starting the ball on
line,'' said Price, who switched to a ``face balance'' mallet
putter after a fourth-place finish at the U.S. Open. ``I feel with
this putter I start the ball more on line and I can be more focused
with the speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Price's confidence with the putter approached what he feels
while standing over a 2-iron to a tightly-guarded green, he likely
would not have finished five shots behind Lee Janzen. Hitting 49
greens in regulation at Olympic (second), he wasted the performance
with a tie for 48th in putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I putt well, I have a good chance to win,'' Price said.
``For me, my ball striking has always been a standard. I guess it's
just a question of how sharp my short game is. Sometimes it just
takes something like the U.S Open to give me a good kick in the
backside to go and practice my putting more.''
</P>
<P>
   Price's threesome was the place to be for red numbers Thursday.
He played with Woods, the co-leader, and saw the difference in his
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He managed his game,'' Price said. ``To me, it looked like he
throttled back a little bit today, which is good to see. ... If he
continues to get better and better, by the time he's 30, he's going
to be a pretty good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
