<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love cure may be time off
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ While it's unlikely many players will copy
Davis Love III's fractured preparation for the British Open, so
far, it's working. The evidence Thursday was a 3-under-par 67 at
Royal Birkdale that allowed the Sea Island PGA champion to stand
two shots off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days ago, it didn't appear that Love could make a
plane, let alone a leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the year's third major having missed the cut at the
U.S. Open, partially because of back problems. Idle on the PGA Tour
since then, Love didn't begin hitting balls until last Wednesday.
Then, planning to fly to England Monday, he forgot his plane and
passport, drove back to Sea Island from Jacksonville and came over
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But Love quickly adapted. He played a strong practice round
Wednesday despite his tender back and even hit balls afterward.
Thursday the 67 tied his low career round at the British Open. He
turned in even-par 34, birdied the par-4 11th with a 7-iron to four
feet, then birdied 15 and 16. He missed a chance for three straight
at the par-5 17th, which was downwind and delightful, by hitting a
5-iron through the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to be playing and getting off to a good
start,'' Love said. ``I hit a few wayward drives, but I didn't
panic and was very patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Love's back is getting any attention needed. Columbus, Ga.,
physical therapist Tom Boers is on site, also treating Fred Couples
(66) and Ernie Els (72).
</P>
<P>
   Lehman guts out a 71
</P>
<P>
   After straining his right shoulder Tuesday night and doubting at
the time that he could play, 1996 champion Tom Lehman managed to
hold together for a 1-over-par 71. Lehman injured the shoulder with
his kids at the Southport Fun Fair while on a barrel ride that
required supporting both hands and feet. But after several sessions
Wednesday at the fitness trailer and two hours of hitting balls
before his mid-afternoon round, Lehman improved enough to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started warming up today, I thought there was no way I
could play,'' Lehman said. ``I could not lift my arm after it
happened.'' He did not make the decision to play until 45 minutes
before his tee time. ``My swing plane was not quite right, but I
manufactured a swing,'' he said. ``I earned my right to play and I
wasn't going to give it up when I had a fair chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar misses opportunity
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar started out Thursday morning with
calm conditions and milder temperatures and knew the obvious. It
was a day when 5-over-75 became nearly unacceptable. ``You really
feel you have to take advantage when it's like this,'' said the
20-year-old amateur. ``It's a little disappointing.'' Kuchar said
he was relaxed starting out, but found his stomach churning a few
holes into the round. ``About the fourth hole I was thinking, 'Man,
this (major championship) golf stuff is such a different feeling,''
he said. ``It's so much different than regular golf.'' ...
Scotland's Colin Montgomerie struggled to a 73 after starting
2-under through six holes, troubled by pulled hooks. Until this
year, he's been a fader. ``The fade has gone and now I hook the
ball,'' he said. ``I'm afraid that in a right-to-left wind, you're
lost.'' ... Defending champion Justin Leonard said his 73 was
especially disappointing ``because I know this is probably as easy
as the golf course will play all week.'' ... Britain's chief hope
to end the Americans' three-year win streak, Lee Westwood, said he
was not distracted by a cellular phone that rang during his swing,
but, ``I don't know why people bring them to the course. If you
need a telephone on the course, you're too busy and you should be
in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
