<SLUG> BC-COWNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ellis, Pittman slotted as starters at defensive end
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas -- It might be an overstatement when defensive
coordinator Dave Campo says every position is up for grabs, but
there are some big holes to fill in his defense. In the past two
seasons the Cowboys have lost three key defensive ends _ Charles
Haley, Tony Tolbert and Shante Carver.
</P>
<P>
   When the season opens Sept. 6, rookie Greg Ellis and seldom-used
defensive end Kavika Pittman will be starters. At least that's what
the depth chart lists this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is that Kavika is an outstanding athlete who really
came around at the end of last year,'' Campo said of the third-year
player from McNeese State. ``He's a combination of a linebacker and
defensive end, someone who can rush the passer and drop back into
coverage. (Ellis) is good at rushing the passer and stopping the
run. At 285 pounds, I think he's going to develop into quite an
overall player.''
</P>
<P>
   The other positions seemingly up for grabs are middle linebacker
and free safety. Veteran Fred Strickland will start in the middle
in the early part of camp, but Randall Godfrey, who played outside
linebacker last year, is expected to challenge for the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Campo declined to talk about the position battle, saying,
``Right now Fred Strickland is our middle linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer George Teague is expected to be the leader at free
safety, a position vacated when Brock Marion went to Miami. Also
trying out for the position are Charlie Williams, Kenny Wheaton and
Omar Stoutmire.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders is probably the only player in Dallas who can
create a scene without trying. Although the injured cornerback will
not practice for about a week, he drew a crowd when he drove up in
his customized golf cart. Many spectators tried to get his
attention, but Sanders declined comment. The only sound from his
vehicle came from his stereo.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders attended the afternoon workout and ran sprints. The
ankle surgery he had in the spring has not hurt his speed.
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the day
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey, speaking about the excitement the Cowboys
have brought to Wichita Falls: ``I hate to say I don't pay
attention to things like that. But if one person shows up or 10,000
show up, we've got a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bates, who retired Wednesday to become a full-time coach
with the Cowboys, is tied with Ed Jones and Mark Tuinei for most
years of service to the football team. All three played 15 years in
Dallas. Jones, however, holds the team record for most games played
_ 224. Bates finished with 217.
</P>
<P>
   Bates said a handful of NFL teams were interested in signing
him, but was not interested. ``I couldn't play for a team other
than the Cowboys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Name recognition
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Bates, his addition to the coaching staff has caused
one problem. The team already has a defensive assistant named
Bates.
</P>
<P>
   Line coach Jim Bates is one of the team's most vocal leaders.
When asked about the new man on the staff, he smiled and said,
``Bill's my cousin. You can call us Bates and Bates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bates had a better idea: ``You can just call me Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Critic's corner
</P>
<P>
   Larry Weisman of USA Today predicts the Cowboys will go 7-9 this
season: ``This is not the NFC East old geezers will remember. The
Cowboys have made a lot of changes in personnel and with the
system. Alterations like that are not easily assimilated.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Former All-Pro safety Mel Renfro will sign autographs at a local
department store today. ... More than 240 press credentials have
been issued for training camp. ... The Cowboys started camp earlier
than most NFL teams because they play five preseason games instead
of four. ... The Cowboys will practice in pads for the first time
during today's 4 p.m. workout.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
