<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS STAND WITH CLINTON ON MANAGED-CARE OVERHAUL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four years ago, doctors were on the front lines
helping Republicans kill President Clinton's complicated plan to
overhaul the health-care system.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed, and so have alliances. On Thursday when
Democrats rallied on Capitol Hill to push their plan to regulate
managed care, the man who introduced Clinton was Dr. Randolph
Smoak, chairman of the American Medical Association, the nation's
largest doctors' organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest health-care battle, the powerful physicians' group
has thrown its support behind Democratic efforts to rein in managed
care and has criticized Republican leaders for offering what it
considers ineffectual and half-baked plans.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors, who plan to descend on Capitol Hill next week to
lobby their lawmakers, are also angry that Republican legislation
does not give people the right to sue their HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who the day before had met with people unhappy with
their managed care plans, has called for a bipartisan effort to
solve the problem and has refrained from sharp attacks on the
Republican proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Democratic rally, he couldn't resist pointing out
some political irony in the doctors' support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried for years to talk them out of it, but most doctors
are still Republican,'' the president told his audience of
lawmakers and medical professionals.
</P>
<P>
   While the AMA is a nonpartisan organization, its political arm
awarded Republican lawmakers two-thirds of the more than $400,000
in contributions it has made in the most recent election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Smoak said he could not agree with the president's assessment
that most doctors belong to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But the South Carolina physician said he was disappointed that
the congressional leadership has been slow to recognize the problem
with managed care and has only recently issued proposals on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not put out a piece of legislation that we have been
able to read,'' Smoak said. ``They have put out some things that
give a skeleton. But then the devil's in the details.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Senate and the House GOP leadership have unveiled
health care plans that would provide appeals process for some
consumers in managed care plans and give patients easier access to
emergency rooms and gynecologists.
</P>
<P>
   But neither of the GOP plans would allow patients to sue their
HMOs or provide access to specialists other than gynecologists and
pediatricians. Those elements are included in Democratic plans.
</P>
<P>
   Smoak said the right to sue is a ``critical'' element of any
managed-care plan, arguing that it is unfair that many patients can
sue their doctors but not their health-care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican lawmakers have agreed with insurance companies
and business groups that giving people the right to sue would drive
up health-care costs and reward trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(EDITORS: STORY CAN END HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying not to be outdone by the Democrats, House Republicans
staged their own health care event in front of the emergency room
of the George Washington University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   But divisions within the Republican ranks have become evident,
as two GOP lawmakers showed up at the Democratic event earlier in
the day, including Rep. Greg Ganske of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Ganske, a physician, announced that he was resigning from a
national panel on Medicare because fellow Republicans were angry at
his support of Democratic managed-care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republican lawmakers are also under pressure from the
state's doctors who want Congress to make it clear that the state
has the right to give consumers the ability to sue their health
care plans.
</P>
<P>
   One source said that House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar
Land, has been wavering on the legislation because of the
objections of local doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, who supports the right to sue, said
that ``it's going to be awkward'' for the Republicans in the
state's congressional delegation because, members of the Texas
Medical Association are ``typically Republican and have been
supporters of Tom DeLay and Bill Archer.''
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Chairman Archer, R-Houston, supports the
House GOP managed care legislation, an aide said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
