<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `MORE MORE' GALLERIES FOLLOW PAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GLF-JAL) 
(JT) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ During the hazy, humid morning, the legions
following Se Ri Pak up and down and across Wykagyl Country Club's
hills had increased from about 200 on the first tee to maybe 500,
and now, as golf's latest wonder woman strode up the ninth fairway,
an Asian man pointed to another 500 spectators framing the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galleries more more more,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   And on the back nine in Thursday's opening round of the JAL Big
Apple Classic, the galleries were even more more more, growing to
maybe 2,000. Mostly they were people of Asian backgrounds _ men,
women, teen-agers and children _ but there were many white and
black men, women, teen-agers and children.
</P>
<P>
   Some were there to see the others in Pak's threesome _ Nancy
Lopez, still the queen of women's golf, and Hiromi Kobayashi, the
Japanese pro who won this tournament in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But all were there to see Se Ri (pronounced Se-REE) Pak, the
20-year-old South Korean rookie pro. Over five days last week she
won the United States Women's Open in a 20-hole playoff and then
shot a round of 61, a record for the Ladies Professional Golf
Association tour, en route to winning the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic
near Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Pak didn't play at that level Thursday, shooting a one-over-par
72, eight strokes behind the leader, Penny Hammel. But golf's like
that. The game is too elusive to let the same golfer win every
week, as Tiger Woods has discovered for all his talent and all the
commotion he created in winning the 1997 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   With Pak's sudden and stunning success, she is naturally being
thought of now as the Tigress of the women's tour, a prodigy who is
winning major titles at a younger age than Tiger did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Se Ri's following the same path as Tiger,'' said Lopez, who
shot 68. ``But she shouldn't be compared to anybody. She's great
already. She's going to set records. She just has to be herself.''
</P>
<P>
   For Pak, being herself has been enough. As an amateur in South
Korea, she won 30 tournaments. Turning pro at 18, she played in 14
tournaments in Korea, winning six and finishing second in seven.
Early last year she moved to Orlando, Fla., for tutoring by David
Leadbetter, the celebrated guru to many PGA Tour pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a presence about her,'' Leadbetter was saying over the
phone from the British Open. ``She had heard of Nancy Lopez, but
she didn't know much else about the women's tour. But it was her
and her family's wish to come over here and play the women's tour
to fulfill her goal of being the best in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everybody else who sees the 5-foot-6-inch Pak for the first
time, Leadbetter noticed her sturdy legs, the foundation of her
power off the tee. As a youngster in South Korea, she developed
those legs as a track-and-field athlete, winning medals in a rare
combination of events, the hurdles and the shot put.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she arrived,'' Leadbetter said, ``I'd never seen such a
potentially good player for such a young player.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Leadbetter knew she needed some tweaking to her swing
and to her posture when addressing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many Asian golfers, she was too bent over, but now she's
more upright,'' he said. ``She also took the club inside and looped
it, so we firmed that up. Now she's swinging on a much simpler
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Pak had yet to qualify for the LPGA Tour, she finished
tied for 21st in last year's Women's Open at Pumpkin Ridge in
Cornelius, Ore., as Lopez finished second to England's Alison
Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see the potential was there,'' Leadbetter said.
``The ambition was there too. She once told me, `If I come back in
this world, I want to come back as a man and be the best player on
the men's tour.'''
</P>
<P>
   Having won another women's major, the McDonald's LPGA
Championship in Wilmington, Del., along with the Women's Open and
her record 61, Pak is arguably the world golfer of the year so far,
male or female.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her goal this year was to win five tournaments, which I
thought was pretty ambitious for a rookie,'' Leadbetter said. ``But
she's already won three. Like she says, `I have no nervous.' ''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But whether Se Ri Pak, who tees off with Lopez and Kobayashi
Friday at 12:30 p.m., wins or loses at Wykagyl this weekend, she's
the attraction. And no matter what she shoots, the galleries will
be more more more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
