<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEEPING-CAMERAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEEPING TOMS HAVE NEW WEAPON IN VIDEO CAMERAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY MARTINEAU  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILDERLAND, N.Y. _ Peeping toms have a new weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Home video cameras.
</P>
<P>
   No longer confined to window ledges and tree limbs, voyeurs now
stalk their prey at crowded shopping malls, bus stops and airports
with a simple camera stowed in a shopping bag. Edging up to their
victims, they film up skirts and down blouses, largely without
their victims' knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the footage ends up on one of the dozens of Web sites
catering to those who enjoy seeing graphic pictures of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, police have reported a growing number of
these incidents, including such popular places as Disneyland in
California. Last week, Guilderland police questioned a man who was
following women at Crossgates Mall and videotaping up their skirts.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities are often stymied in arresting the amateur
videographers. Without a victim stepping forward to press charges
on invasion of privacy or harrassment, police can't make an arrest.
Because of the nature of the deed, most women strolling through the
mall or riding an escalator have no idea they were targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many victims but no faces to go with them,'' said
Guilderland police officer Roger Ginder.
</P>
<P>
   Ginder questioned the 30-something man at Crossgates after a
clerk at Footaction USA noticed the man shadowing a woman while she
was in line. Ginder seized the camera and the footage last Monday,
which included over one hour of taping, with hundreds of different
women from several different malls.
</P>
<P>
   But the man was released without any charges being filed because
they couldn't identify any of the women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems absurd that such a despicable invasion of privacy
would be unenforceable under any current law,'' said Guilderland
police chief James Murley. He said the department is checking with
the Albany County District Attorney and the state Attorney General
to see if any statute exists that could apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy situation,'' said Larry Wiest, the chief
assistant district attorney in Albany County. ``It's hard to find
an identifiable victim. All you're looking at is skirts and
petticoats.''
</P>
<P>
   He said lawmakers need to examine invasion of privacy and
stalking laws in a computer age where hidden cameras, some as small
as a matchbox, abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the penal law comprehensively addresses
problems of stalking and invasion of privacy...You (should) still
have the right to go to Crossgates Mall and not have someone look
up your skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Type the word ``peeping camera'' into an Internet search engine
and dozens of web-sites, offering up-skirt and down-shirt views,
appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about that girl going up the escalator at the mall,''
declares one site, followed by crude, descriptive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   There are also Web sites devoted to teaching men how to film
``up-skirt'' or ``down blouse'' without getting caught.
</P>
<P>
   An official with Pyramid Cos. owner of Crossgates, said peeping
cameras at malls and other public places are rare. But he said that
security officials from Pyramid's 17 enclosed malls would discuss
the latest incident at their scheduled meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to provide a safe environment for everyone,'' said
Robert Harrington, director of corporate security at Pyramid Cos.
``This is one more thing on the list to look out for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
