<SLUG> BC-ELECTRIC-NIGHTMARE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVINGS FROM ELECTRIC DEREGULATION MAY BE MIRAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA VALDEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - We're all supposed to be happy as can be about the
coming of ``electric deregulation.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   I see it as the waltz of the Big Dogs and a tedious intrusion
into my measured-to-the-nanosecond schedule.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't ask for this. A regulated monopoly gets the job done
without making undue demands on my time.
</P>
<P>
   Big Business was the impetus for moving electricity generation
from a comfortable monopoly to competition. And they'll get the
gravy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest benefit will be to business,'' says Arizona's
Speaker of the House Jeff Groscost, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   He's an ardent supporter who also sees benefits for consumers
and great opportunities for innovation and technological advances.
</P>
<P>
   I say electricity works fine, and the lower prices may be a
mirage.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Stranded costs are investments made by utility
companies during regulation that are not expected to pay a good
return under competition. Regulators and utilities think utilities
should be paid for those investments. They don't agree on how much
or whether stockholders or customers should pay.
</P>
<P>
   Under regulation, you and I have always paid for the mistakes of
utility company executives. We just didn't think about it. But
under deregulation, the price we pay for stranded costs might
offset any savings from competition.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Tim Hogan says. As a member of the board of
the Arizona Consumers Council, he says beware electric deregulators
bearing gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to structure competition so that everybody
wins except us, the small consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hogan, ``Utilities are saying, `We'll let you all
pay for our uneconomic investments quick so we can get about the
important business of saving you money later on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But later on may never come.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Corporation Commissioner Renz Jennings says the ``jury
is still out'' on the benefits that will result from what he calls
``re-regulation.'' He says some of those spurring on competition
are motivated by a ``theological belief'' in the market.
</P>
<P>
   I have my own theological beliefs. One of them involves the
value of time. I'd rather spend mine sitting in the back yard
watching birds. Or playing a rousing game of Clue Junior with my
daughter. Or admiring my husband's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt electric de/re-regulation will save me much money. But
it will cost me time.
</P>
<P>
   Think of all those telemarketers calling to speak to ``the
person who makes the electric purchasing decisions in your
household.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of the junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   Think of a day when buying electricity is as tedious as picking
a long-distance provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a busy guy,`` says Jennings. ``I don't care to figure it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen. Life's too short. &QL; 
Linda Valdez is an editorial writer at The Arizona Republic. She
can be reached at linda.valdez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
