<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZAR-SQUABBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURIAL OF CZAR DIVIDES RUSSIAN OPINION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Russia will bury a piece of its
turbulent, violent past Friday when the remains of the country's
last imperial ruler, Czar Nicholas II, are finally laid to rest 80
years after he and his family were shot by Bolshevik
revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
   But little remains of the larger, symbolic meaning the Kremlin
was hoping to achieve by finally giving a Christian burial to the
Romanov family and their servants, whose bodies were exhumed from a
Siberian swamp and identified only after the fall of Communism.
</P>
<P>
   What was supposed to close a chapter on an ugly event in
history, the ceremony instead has become another embarrassing
failure of President Boris Yeltsin's efforts to craft a sense of
national identity for the new Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The preparations for the ceremonies have bred the kind of
disruptive and petty squabbles that have consistently bogged the
country down in the post-Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   The event will be boycotted by the leaders of the church that
crowned the Russian czars for 300 years, some of the Romanov
dynasty's descendents, and prominent politicians. Yeltsin himself
had indicated he would miss the funeral, and decided to attend only
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This truth has been concealed for 80 years and we have to tell
this truth tomorrow and I should take part,'' Yeltsin said in a
nationally televised address Thursday. ``This is the right thing to
do from the point of view of human decency.''
</P>
<P>
   But others disagree. Lingering doubts among religious leaders
about whether the remains are genuine, and a larger dispute over
the role the czar's execution should play in Russian history, have
bred the kind of disruptive and petty squabbles over the ceremony
that have consistently bogged the country down in the post-Soviet
era.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's about-face decidely improved the mood among the 62
descendents of the Romanovs and their servants, as the mourners
waited at St. Petersburg's Pulkovo airport for the arrival of the
remains from the Urals city of Yekaterinburg, where the czar's
family was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beginning to leave the past behind us,'' Nikolai
Romanov, widely seen as the head of the dynasty, told reporters,
before the nine oak coffins were driven in black hearses to the
church where the imperial family will be laid to rest.
</P>
<P>
   As the procession moved slowly along the Niva River embankment,
studded with flags at half staff and black crepe, crowds of
onlookers craned for a better view of the cortege beyond rows of
police, and helicopters hovered warily overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, military pallbearers took the coffins from the vans and
carried them, slowly and stiffly, into the St. Peter and Paul
Cathedral, resting place of all the czars since Peter the Great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting to rest the remains of innocent people who were
murdered, the present generation of Russians is striving to atone
for the sins of their predecessors,'' the Kremlin said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   But far from everyone sees it that way. The Russian Orthodox
church has refused to give the funeral that status of a state
funeral because it doubts the conclusive scientific DNA evidence
that shows the remains as those of the tsar and his family. It has
downgraded it to a funeral of unknown remains, and forbidden senior
clergy _ bishops and higher _ from attending.
</P>
<P>
   Following the church's lead, both houses of parliament have
voted not to send delegations to the funeral of the czar.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, there are doubts about just whom they will be
burying,'' said Yegor Stroyev, speaker of the upper house. ``Second
of all, there can never be repentance on the bones of a man who
destroyed Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's sizeable Communists contingent is staying away in
droves from an event seen as unfairly discrediting the Soviet era.
Ultranationalists who claim that Nicholas II was martyred by an
international conspiracy have demonstrated outside the Peter and
Paul Fortress, bearing such slogans as ``Satanic Regime, Satanic
Ritual,''
</P>
<P>
   Even the czar's ghost is said to have come out against the
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you not to torment me,'' Petersburg Express quoted
Nicholas II as telling a spiritual medium last month.
</P>
<P>
   Such episodes, apocryphal though they may be, reveal the odd
grip still held over Russian history by a man who was, by most
accounts, a devout family man but a weak and cruel leader, who
violently crushed peaceful demonstrations and led Russia into two
disastrous wars before abdicating in February 1917.
</P>
<P>
   The Romanovs spent the next several months at a palace just
outside St. Petersburg. But the Bolsheviks, locked in a civil war
with troops loyal to Nicholas, then sent him to Yekaterinburg and
executed him and his family on July 17, 1918.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Nicholas, his wife Alexandra, their daughters Olga,
Tatyana and Anastasia, three servants and the family doctor were
dug up in 1991 from an unmarked grave in a forest near
Yekaterinburg, where their killers had hastily hidden them before
fleeing a Czarist advance. The bodies of two other children _ the
only son, Alexei, and a daughter doctors believe is Maria, were
never found. Most investigators believe the bodies were burned to
ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic experts in Russia, Britain and the United States, using
DNA matching techniques, established there was more than a 99.99
percent chance they were authentic.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Nicholas' funeral also points to a larger problem
that Yeltsin has, for all his desire to leave a legacy as the
father of a new, democratic Russia, never been able to solve: How
should Russia view its Soviet past, as an illegitimate
interruption, or a continuation of the country's 1,000-year
history?
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's other efforts to breach this issue have brought
disappointing results. His promise to open the archives of the KGB
secret police ended with most of the archives being closed for the
next 50 years. His promise to replace the Soviet police state with
a rule-of-law democracy brought free elections, but also rampant
corruption and the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   And now, after decades spent mouldering in a swamp, Russia's
former ruler will be given a Christian burial, but Russia's A-list
is ignoring it. Some people blame Yeltsin, for waiting for the last
minute to champion the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been better if the president had given clear
signals from the start,'' said Viktor Aksyuchits, a government
organizer of the ceremony. ``This is one of the main events of the
20th century in Russia, ... but instead it is being used for
political power struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin toned down what had been planned as a full-fledged
state funeral, earmarking only $833,000 in state funding was
allocated for the burial ceremonies. Russian officials have
defended the stripped-down ceremony, saying that it would be
improper for a country where state workers go months without pay to
spend more, especially at a time when Russia has been forced by its
fiscal woes to accept a $22.6 billion rescue package from
international lenders.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, both Moscow's Mayor Yury Luzhkov and Eduard
Rossel, governor of Yekaterinburg, lobbied hard to have the burial
held on their home turf. Once the decision was made to hold the
ceremony in St. Petersburg, both men declined to attend. Luzhkov,
who has a good chance of one day replacing Yeltsin, now says he
does not think the bones belong to the imperial family.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians agree. A recent national poll said only 47 percent
of Russians believe the czar's remains are genuine. An even smaller
percent of people interviewed Thursday believed that their burial
will amount to anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all a big show for the benefit of the people who set
it up,'' said St. Petersburg student Alexander Dmitriev. ``No more,
no less.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
