<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY COMPUTER SURFS WITHOUT ME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I have been advised that it is wiser to leave
my computer on at all times. The problem is that four out of five
days, I wake up with my home page displayed rather than my desktop.
Someone told me that the computer does in fact call my Internet
server several times during the night. I wonder if this is a glitch
in my PC or if some piece of downloaded software may be doing this.
_ Haunted
</P>
<P>
   Dear Haunted: Your PC is doing exactly what it's supposed to do.
Well, it's doing what Microsoft wants it to, and that's all that's
important. In fact, I think there's some sort of federal law to
that effect, or there will be when Microsoft gets through with
Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bill and his merry band of marauders think that the Internet
is just an extension of your desktop, and that data from it should
be just as readily available as if it were on your own hard drive.
A continuous connection to the Net is perfect for that scenario,
but because most of us can't afford that luxury, Windows 98 and the
most recent versions of Win95 will make a connection when needed.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you have a program that periodically checks the Internet
for whatever, your computer is probably dialing on its own. Either
that, or Mulder and Scully are right. Look for a check box on your
Internet dialer screen that says ``Connect as needed'' or some such
thing and uncheck it to put a stop to automatic dialing.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be such a weenie about turning your computer off.
Nobody's got the right answer to that one. Continuous use will
eventually wear out the drive and fan motors; turning it off and on
jolts the circuits and eventually fries something. Who cares? Live
dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Open Microsoft Word and type in the phrase
``unable to follow directions.'' Highlight the phrase, then go to
Tools/Thesaurus (Shift-F7 works, too) and look at the results. Now
the question: Is this the Department of Justice's most fervent wish
for Big Bill? _ Perplexed
</P>
<P>
   Dear Perplexed: Actually, I think it may be a sign that my
ex-girlfriend found a job as a Microsoft programmer.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I have to respond to ``Tom.'' ``(Note: Tom
wondered if women whose husbands spy on their online adventures did
something to earn the mistrust.)'' I think my husband is doing
similar tricks, and, no, I don't deserve it. Some husbands are
suspicious of everything, even when NOTHING is going on. And, just
maybe, if they spy long enough, their wives will get so sick of it,
they might just run away with a computer geek. _ Fed Up
</P>
<P>
   Dear Fed: Meet you at the Hyatt next Tuesday afternoon, just
like always?
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Your column often uses the words ``anal'' or
``anal retentive.'' I'm not sure what you really mean. Could you
please explain? _ Puzzled
</P>
<P>
   Dear Puzz: Just read the next letter.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: You do your readers a great disservice with
your feeble, childish attempts at humor. People foolishly come to
you seeking help, and all they get in return are sophomoric
insults. You would be well-advised to take a more serious,
businesslike tone, like the informative columnists in ``PC
Magazine'' and ``PC World'' who actually know what they are talking
about. _ Badly in Need of Bran
</P>
<P>
   Dear Badly: Does that answer your question, Puzzled?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
