<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TED TURNER'S AW-SHUCKS ACT DOES IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Jed Clampett met the press the other day, and
not a moment too soon. Here we were chomping at the bit, wanting
heads to roll and bemoaning the lost civilization of TV journalism,
and along comes this guy who looks like one of the corporate suits,
until he slips behind a podium and opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner, billionaire and closet comedian, is perhaps the most
underrated and unassuming media mogul, a filthy rich country
bumpkin who puts you in mind of the most famous Beverly
Hills-billy, a global controller who can first disarm you and then
shame you for ever thinking he's slow on the uptake.
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely what Turner did one day last week as he faced a
ballroom packed with TV critics wanting blood over the CNN mess,
the one about nerve gas, rushing to judgment, newsmagazine
competition, media retractions and star reporters lending their
fame but not their reporting to news reports.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a couple weeks since CNN News Group chairman Tom
Johnson humbly apologized for a report that the U.S. military used
lethal nerve gas in 1970 during a secret mission aimed at killing
American defectors in Vietnam. The report was retracted after
criticism mounted that the evidence was suspicious; three producers
lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout had anyone ever connected with CNN cringing in
disgrace or hiding in the nearest bush. But we wanted more. We
wanted Ted.
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't said a thing since the report aired on the June 7
premiere of ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' since the story started
falling apart, since CNN's credibility started to crumble, bit by
bit, like a weakened empire.
</P>
<P>
   As Turner Broadcasting presented its fall programming to the
media, moving gingerly from TBS to TNT to the Cartoon Channel,
Turner sat quietly in the back row, surveying the land, chewing the
heck out of a stick of gum, plotting his path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see him weasel out of this,'' a journalist said.
``Welcome to the firing squad,'' another said.
</P>
<P>
   Shrewdly and humbly during his participation in introducing
CNN's ``Cold War'' series, Turner poked and needled us about his
upcoming remarks. He tossed in jokes to ease the tension, to soften
us up, an incredibly effective tool, because ground rules had been
set: No nerve-gas questions until other business was out of harm's
way.
</P>
<P>
   Once Turner glided over to the podium to take questions, he
quickly fired a long-winded list of apologies, comparing the
incident with ``the greatest catastrophes in my life,'' ranking it
up there with the death of his father, with the breakup of two of
his marriages, with the Braves losing the World Series to the
Yankees after being up two games to none.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nightmare,'' he said in that thick Georgia accent. ``I
mean, I just don't know that aside of self-flagellation ... If I
thought it would do good, if anybody has a whip here, I'll just
take my shirt off and beat myself until I'm bloody on the back, if
it would make anybody feel better. I couldn't hurt any more if I
was bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a fighter refusing to go down, Turner stood tough and took
his verbal punishment. How damaged is CNN? Did you see the report
before it aired? Do you believe the story?
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember what Christ said when they were going to stone the
prostitute?'' Turner says. ``Let he who is without sin cast the
first stone. And I think that the majority of the people will
forgive and forget. We have some enemies out there that won't
forget, and they wouldn't be satisfied no matter what we did,
unless we just signed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner didn't answer one question without the acknowledgment of
a news report gone terribly wrong, without mentioning the
tabloidization of news, without attacking the profit-making
machinery of TV journalism, particularly local news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't watch it much because it makes me ill,'' he said,
speaking of local TV. ``There's nothing but one fire, one killing;
there's so little substantive.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner is a product of old money, but he is, in many ways, a
self-made man by virtue of wanting and needing to go his own way.
He is outspoken and charming, and in many ways his Southern dialect
masks his strengths in these parts, feeding into the stereotype of
Southerners as dimwits, even very rich ones.
</P>
<P>
   After the session, Turner disappeared, but his spirit remained.
Writers who rushed to their rooms to file their reports returned
later to a poolside feast of hot dogs and burgers in honor of the
Goodwill Games, which Turner Broadcasting will televise beginning
this month.
</P>
<P>
   They chowed down and talked of Turner, the man. Of his
feistiness, of his smarts, of his willingness to come and face the
music. ``I like him,'' one reported said. ``A pretty upfront guy,''
another said.
</P>
<P>
   That Ted Turner. He did it again.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
