<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANCY JUST SHOWED UP AT AUNT FRITZI'S ONE DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I've read the comic strip ``Nancy'' all my life and have
never seen a reference to Nancy's real parents or why Aunt Fritzi
has custody of her. What's the explanation? _ M.H., Burleson, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: These things have never been explained, according to current
``Nancy'' cartoonist Guy Gilchrist.
</P>
<P>
   When the 7-year-old Nancy first showed up in 1933, the strip was
called ``Fritzi Ritz,'' and she had been the star for 11 years.
``Nancy appeared at Fritzi's doorstep without a history,''
Gilchrist writes on his World Wide Web site at
www.gilchriststudios.com.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Bushmiller, who took over ``Fritzi Ritz'' three years into
its run in 1925, renamed it ``Nancy'' in 1938. The strip was
carried in as many as 880 newspapers when drawn by Bushmiller, who
died in 1982 at age 76.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the John Wayne movie ``Stagecoach,'' what was the name of
the woman portraying the boarding house manager? She had a small
speaking part when Doc was evicted. _ N.C., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Doc's landlady was portrayed by Nora Cecil, a character actor
who worked steadily in small roles from 1915 to 1947.
</P>
<P>
   No information could be found about Cecil aside from her
credits, which included films such as ``Mourning Becomes Electra,''
``I Married a Witch'' and ``Gold Diggers of 1935.''
</P>
<P>
   Cecil, who was sometimes credited as Nora or Norah Cecile, often
played schoolteachers, witches and gossips.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the PBS show John Denver was working on still be
broadcast? _ J.B., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: PBS plans to air ``John Denver: Let This Be a Voice'' on Dec.
6 as part of the network's ``Nature'' series.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Let This Be a Voice,'' Denver visits places in the U.S.
West that inspired his music. Filming on the project was completed
before Denver's death in an Oct. 12, 1997, plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   The program's title may change before air time, according to a
PBS representative.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
