<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THAT IN THE SINK? PROBABLY A GERM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I turned down the germ guru's ``once-in-a-lifetime opportunity''
for an in-home briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Gerba, a microbiologist at the University of Arizona
who has been one of the leading germ experts for 25 years, offered
to swab the ``hot zones'' in my kitchen and bathroom last week, but
I opted for an in-office interview.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness. He took one look at my desk and suggested that
we find some place else to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Gerba, who dubs himself ``the sultan of slime,'' says that in
most of the homes he has studied, he would be better off making a
turkey sandwich on the rim of the toilet bowl than on the
germ-laden counter top in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to feel safer in the bathroom than the kitchen,
unless it's a public bathroom,'' Gerba said. ``Most people
disinfect their bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, is the reason the kitchen has become the main
battlefield of home-front germ warfare.
</P>
<P>
   In the first scientific study of germs in homes, Gerba found
many more in kitchens than in bathrooms. His study will be
published in ``The Journal of Applied Microbiology'' this fall. He
was in Fort Worth last week as part of an educational tour
sponsored by Clorox bleach.
</P>
<P>
   His study identifies sinks, cutting boards, sponges, faucet
handles and commode handles as the worst breeding grounds for
bacteria in the home.
</P>
<P>
   How many bacteria does it take to make people sick? Even the
Food and Drug Administration can't provide an answer to like that.
It depends on the bacteria involved, for one thing. Many microbes
are a normal part of our environment and don't cause illness except
in unusual circumstances. But the common-sense conclusion is that
the more bacteria ingested, the more likely illness will occur. For
some, it can take as few as 10 bacteria to get sick; for others, it
can be millions.
</P>
<P>
   And millions are what Gerba found in his recent seven-month,
in-home study of 15 typical homes with families of two adults and
two children _ no dogs allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Sponges and dishcloths topped the list, with a count of more
than 7 billion bacteria per average-size sponge. Frequently touched
kitchen faucet handles netted an average 229,000 microbes per
square inch, and cutting boards registered an average 62,000 per
square inch.
</P>
<P>
   Our floors are much cleaner than our sinks, Gerba said, and
that's ironic because most of us will rinse off things that drop in
the sink during food preparation and use them, although anything
accidentally dropped on the floor gets thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is, his random weekly samplings found that
microbes in the home are reduced by 99 percent when people start
cleaning all hard surfaces with bleach-based products that clean
and disinfect. Of course, the Clorox people figured that would
happen when they funded the study.
</P>
<P>
   Gerba also recommends filling the sink with a water-and-bleach
solution and soaking sponges, dishcloths and the sink and drain
every day and using a bleach-and-water solution on cutting boards
after every use.
</P>
<P>
   High-touch zones, such as handles, should be disinfected about
three times a week. Toilets, showers, tubs, drains and kitchen and
bathroom floors need disinfecting once a week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Preventive medicine begins at home, the source of about 80
percent of all food-borne illness, Gerba said. I never thought of
cleaning and disinfecting my kitchen as preventive medicine, but it
makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
