u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SYPHILIS-350&AMP;ADD-     07-16 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SYPHILIS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE FOR SYPHILIS VACCINE OFFERED BY DNA BREAKTHROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN Md., Texas)   (bl)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The master plan of a deadly and elusive microbe has been
deciphered by a team of genetic code-breakers, raising hopes that
for the first time a vaccine can be devised against it.
</P>
<P>
   The pathogen is Treponema pallidum, the organism that causes
syphilis. Its full DNA or genome, containing the entire instruction
set it needs to infect and thrive in human cells, has now been
deciphered by biologists at the Institute for Genomic Research in
Rockville, Md., and the University of Texas Health Science Center
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Their work is reported in Friday's issue of Science, accompanied
by an appeal from two government health officials for a program to
eliminate syphilis, an easily treatable disease that in the United
States now affects chiefly the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The syphilis spirochete, a kind of bacterium, burst upon Europe
shortly after Columbus' return from America, which indicates it was
introduced from the New World. Though it was brought substantially
under control by penicillin, still the standard treatment, syphilis
has continued to elude both researchers and public health
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The organism cloaks its protein structure in a veil of fatlike
material, a stratagem that denies obvious targets both to the
immune system and to vaccine-makers. And it continues to infect
Americans in periodic waves of disease, leaving a wake of
congenitally impaired infants and, most recently, of HIV, whose
transmission is enhanced by syphilis.
</P>
<P>
   The decoding of the spirochete's DNA lays bare every guile with
which evolution has endowed it, including its abilities to infect
human cells, to lie latent for years while evading the immune
system, and to destroy body tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Though the germ's secret plans have now been captured, it will
take biologists several years to understand them. The spirochete's
genome, or full DNA, possesses 1,041 different genes. About half,
as judged by their sequence of DNA letters, are similar to genes
found in other bacteria, particularly the fellow spirochete that
causes Lyme disease, and the rest are unique to Treponema pallidum.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Having this genome in hand opens the door to unlimited
possibilities,'' said Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of the National
Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, which spent $750,000
for the syphilis sequencing project.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about syphilis, compared with other bacteria,
because it cannot be grown in the test tube. The organism relies on
its human host for many essential nutrients and biologists have
been unable to ascertain the complete list.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven Norris, of the University of Texas, started to work
on this problem as a graduate student 23 years ago. In 1991 he
joined forces with a colleague, Dr. George Weinstock, and the two
biologists decided the growth requirements of the fastidious
organism could only be discovered by sequencing its genome, a feat
impossible by the methods then available.
</P>
<P>
   When the first bacterial genome was sequenced by the Institute
for Genomic Research in 1995, Norris and Weinstock asked Dr. Claire
Fraser to help complete the syphilis project, which was done in two
years. It proved difficult, Dr. Fraser said, in part because there
was not enough DNA available. Supplies are obtained by the
difficult method of growing the bacterium in rabbit testicles.
</P>
<P>
   Because the spirochete's genome is so small, she decided she
could risk omitting a customary sequencing step, but found there
were pieces of DNA she could not fit together unambiguously.
Fortunately a new computer program solved the problem. ``This was
probably the perfect example of how not to do a genome project,''
she said. The syphilis genome is the seventh bacterial genome
completed by the institute. Another seven have been sequenced
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The syphilis genome offers biologists a wealth of ideas for
exploring and sabotaging the organism's anatomy. ``It's an enormous
amount of information we have got that we didn't have a prayer of
getting before,'' Weinstock said. He noted that it should be
possible to devise better diagnostic tests immediately since the
organism's proteins can now be generated from their genetic
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Norris said he had identified a family of 12 different kinds of
protein that stud the spirochete's surface and may make suitable
targets for vaccines. The many genes that are unique to the
syphilis organism probably reflect the great antiquity of
spirochetes and the separate evolutionary path they have followed
from most other bacteria, Weinstock said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the extreme age of the spirochetes, which have existed
for well over 100 million years, Treponema pallidum presumably
learned only recently how to infect humans, a host with a mere
100,000-year ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis has no animal host, one of several factors that make
the disease particularly easy to eliminate from the United States,
said Dr. Michael St. Louis and Dr. Judith Wasserheit, of the
Centers for Disease and Prevention Control, in an article
accompanying the genome report.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis is now at the ebb of one its periodic cycles, the ideal
time to get rid of it altogether, they said. Though treatable with
a single shot of penicillin, the disease continues to smolder,
infecting particularly black Americans in Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   A five-year, $100 million program could effectively eliminate
the disease, as has already been done in several European
countries, and would be cheap compared with the annual $80 million
cost of treating it, the two health officials wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
