<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ TOPS 2,000 AS BUYERS THRONG TECHNOLOGY STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nasdaq composite index topped 2,000 Thursday,
powered by the high-technology stocks that dominate the index and
investors' preference for big, well-known companies at a time when
the market outlook is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of choppy trading, the Nasdaq had trouble holding on at
the 2,000 level. It broke through early, then fell as low as
1,982.86. It popped above 2,000 again early in the afternoon and
near the end of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Then it barely held on, falling to 1,999.99 just at the close
and inching up to settle at 2,000.56, up 6.02 points on the day.
The Nasdaq is now up 27.4 percent this year, the best performance
of the major indexes.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which rose 93.72 points, or 1
percent, to 9,328.19, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500
stocks, which climbed 9.18 points, to 1,183.99, also set new highs.
It was the first time the Dow closed above 9,300.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which hit 1,000 just three years ago, becomes the
third of the major indexes to cross a 1,000-point barrier this
year. The Dow hit 9,000 for the first time on April 6 and the S&AMP;P
500 crossed 1,000 on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The big-name stocks _ Microsoft, Cisco Systems, Intel, Dell
Computer and Worldcom _ that carried the Nasdaq on its last
1,000-point run, show how much the nature of the index has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not that long ago that the Nasdaq was identified with
smaller-company stocks,'' said Laszlo Birinyi, head of Birinyi
Associates, a market research firm. This year's performance and the
breaking of 2,000, he said, ``is as much a tribute to large-cap
stocks as to how well technology stocks have done.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's rally has been driven by the nice surprises in the
first flood of second-quarter earnings reports. Among the investor
pleasers have been Eastman Kodak, Apple Computer, Tellabs and SBC
Communications. After the market closed, Microsoft reported
earnings of 50 cents a diluted share, beating forecasts by 2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak led the Dow higher, a day after it announced
earnings that were much better than expected. It rose 4 1/2, to 87,
on Thursday, accounting for 19 points of the Dow's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Apple reported earnings after the market close Wednesday that
were double what analysts had expected. Thursday its stock rose 3
1/16, to 37 1/2, a 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   But Apple has not been a big player in Nasdaq's recent run. Even
its 185 percent gain this year has failed to restore it to the $49
level where it stood on July 17, 1995, when the Nasdaq crossed its
first 1,000 barrier. It has been the sixth-biggest drag on the the
Nasdaq over the last three years, according to Birinyi Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500 companies in the S&AMP;P 500, 155 had reported their
profits for the quarter by Thursday, according to First Call Corp.,
which compiles earnings estimates. Of these, 94 beat expectations,
including 37 that reported earnings that exceeded forecasts by 5
percent or more. However, some of these surprises resulted in part
from companies that had jawboned down expectations ahead of their
earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Hill, director of research at First Call, forecast that
the positive surprises will be enough for an overall 4 percent
increase in second-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But that pace is still well below the double-digit rates of the
last several years. And the current outlook among many economists
is that economic growth will slow in months ahead, in part because
of the decline in American exports to weakened economies in Asia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because earnings are relatively weak, Douglas Cliggott, the U.S.
equity strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities, said he believes that
many investors are pushing stocks higher on the belief that
earnings will revive over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that technology stocks had benefited greatly from
this bet. ``Historically,'' he said, ``the place to bet on
long-term growth, as opposed to near-term earnings, is
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index started at 100 on Feb. 5, 1971, and took 24 1/2
years to reach 1,000 on July 17, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Birinyi Associates said five stocks accounted for about
two-thirds of the last 1,000-point Nasdaq run: Microsoft, 31.2
percent, Cisco Systems, 11.33 percent, Intel, 10.4 percent, Dell
Computer, 9.8 percent, and Worldcom, 5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
