<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANDY-SCRUGGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEGRASS SON RANDY SCRUGGS LEARNED HIS LESSONS WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy Scruggs, the fortysomething son of bluegrass legend Earl
Scruggs, is the ultimate Nashville insider. Mother Maybelle Carter
was his baby sitter, and he grew up with people such as The Byrds,
Ravi Shankar, Johnny Cash, Linda Ronstadt and Neil Young hanging
around the house.
</P>
<P>
   So it's hardly surprising that Scruggs' first solo album,
``Crown of Jewels,'' issued Tuesday on Reprise, reflects a rare
musical pedigree. The award-winning producer, songwriter and
instrumentalist sees his album as more than a biographical work;
it's extreme collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the guy that connects Mother Maybelle Carter to Deana
Carter,'' said Jason Catz, Scruggs' Nashville agent.
</P>
<P>
   It was Maybelle's autoharp that first inspired 6-year-old Randy,
and later, at 11, he picked up the acoustic guitar. He remembers
being pulled out of middle school once to record on a Waylon
Jennings session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always enjoyed growing up on the technical side (of
recording),'' Scruggs said last week from Nashville. ``I got to go
to some of those early recording sessions, like Bob Dylan when he
did part of the `John Wesley Harding' album, and the `Blonde on
Blonde' album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simon and Garfunkel recorded here back then, and Neil Young. I
was at the session where he recorded `Heart of Gold.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Randy joined his dad and brothers in The Earl
Scruggs Revue. That celebrated band combined traditional
instrumentation with a contemporary format, Randy Scruggs'
trademark today. Scruggs continued playing with such stars as
Ronstadt, Cash, the Dirt Band and Ricky Skaggs, and in 1980 he
opened his own studio and production company.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I built the studio here, at some point I hoped to produce
records, but I thought it would be way down the line,'' he said.
``In the first month, Waylon Jennings came by and said he wanted to
record at the studio and wanted me to produce him.'' Scruggs ended
up playing on Jennings' album of Billy Joe Shaver songs and his
``Dukes of Hazzard'' project.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a Sawyer Brown album came along, and suddenly Scruggs
found himself in business. His work on the second volume of the
Nitty Gritty Dirt Band's ``Will the Circle Be Unbroken'' won him
accolades as Country Music Association producer of the year in
1989, and netted him a country instrumental Grammy the same year
for ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   He produced the critically acclaimed 1992 compilation album
``Red Hot &AMP; Country,'' an album to benefit AIDS research, and later
``Keith Whitley _ A Tribute Album,'' which gave rise to Alison
Krauss and Union Station's ``When You Say Nothing at All.''
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs' dozens of songwriting credits include cuts by Trisha
Yearwood, Patty Loveless, Sawyer Brown, Steve Wariner, Waylon
Jennings and, most recently, Deana Carter's hit ``We Danced
Anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crown of Jewels'' is being issued to three radio formats:
country, Americana and Triple AAA. Recording of the album took on a
life of its own, lasting over a year to accommodate everyone's
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was similar to casting a movie; creating a wish list who I
wanted on what songs,'' Scruggs said. ``Yet I wanted to have a
thread to run throughout the record, that of my musical life.''
</P>
<P>
   Old favorites on the album include ``A Soldier's Joy''
instrumental with Vince Gill; the Carter Family's ``Wildwood
Flower'' with Emmylou Harris and Iris DeMent; and ``City of New
Orleans'' with John Prine. Travis Tritt lends vocals on ``Amie.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven originals include Earl Scruggs' ``Lonesome Reuben''
instrumental, Bruce Hornsby's ``Crown of Jewels,'' and Scruggs'
collaborations with Rosanne Cash (''My Secret Life)'' and Mary
Chapin Carpenter (''It's Only Love).'' His own Dylanesque vocals
take the lead on ``I Wanna Be Loved Back,'' and join with Joan
Osborne's on the Johnny Cash-penned ``Passin' Thru.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you express any part of music, you want to express your
emotions,'' Scruggs said of his singing. ``I've always felt the
emotions of singing, even when I just played.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Mother Maybelle's onetime charge plans a classic
Nashville life: He'll tour in the fall with special guest artists,
and he plans another solo project down the line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
