<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVERING AMERICA'S TABOO SUBJECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orlando Bagwell's latest documentary, ``Africans in America:
America's Journey Though Slavery,'' weighs in at six
commercial-free hours, its companion book at 472 pages. It is, as
its producer and driving force says, ``definitive in scale.'' Some
understatement, considering this treasure hunt for a seemingly
impossible audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's not merely that some white Americans are weary of hearing
about slavery and how it might have crippled generations of black
Americans. Black folk themselves often find the subject emotionally
exhausting, painful, even humiliating _ certainly not dinner table
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The series, to air over three nights on PBS in October, begins
in 1607, the beginning of the largest forced human migrations in
recorded history. It ends in 1865, with this country's Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Although the TV miniseries ``Roots'' drew an enormous following
despite its graphic depictions of vicious cruelty toward slaves, it
was also mainstream entertainment. ``Africans in America'' isn't
packaged for mainstream consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell filmed on location across 12 states and three
continents, researching hundreds of journals and letters and
collecting drawings, paintings and photographs to mix with
interviews of scholars and writers and descendants. Judging from
one 90-minute segment previewed, it keeps the series from taking on
the stuffy look of intellectuals talking over our heads.
</P>
<P>
   A black man whose list of accomplishments is far too long to
name here, Bagwell has the steady, determined look of a
buttoned-down professor. When he talks, he rarely smiles, even when
a joke is tossed his way. But what better filmmaker to handle such
a difficult piece of work?
</P>
<P>
   Slavery remains our national Achilles' heel, a cancer that many
wish would simply be cured and forgotten. Bagwell wasn't surprised
when, near the end of a session he conducted with members of the TV
press corps, a journalist asked the panel if America would ever
``put all this behind us?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are lots of people of good will and conscience,
as Dr. King might put it, who really do want that beloved community
he spoke of,'' responded one panelist, writer Charles Johnson,
whose novel ``Middle Passage'' is a classic. ``But you can't block
out how we got to this moment in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have yet to grow weary of hearing or commemorating
something as horrible as the Holocaust, but the issues surrounding
slavery have always shouldered the burden of less tolerance and
patience. Part of it has to do with geographic guilt: Slavery
happened here, its brutality carried out by everyday Americans and
presidents alike.
</P>
<P>
   We have to understand the history, its complexity and the
participation of all kinds of people, black, white, Asian and
others who made this the nation it was. Only then will moving
forward be possible, for it would be with wisdom, as opposed to
ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   What African-Americans want to point out is the uncomfortable
truth that nearly everyone has some kind of implication, in terms
of their family or themselves. Most of us are stained. For
instance, you didn't have to own slaves to be involved. You didn't
have to be on a slave ship. The whole industry, from providing food
for the slave captors to producing materials to build the ships on
which they sailed, is explored. The money from slavery
sub-industries made some American families wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say that people need to walk around with their
heads down. But it does need to be acknowledged, Bagwell says.
</P>
<P>
   Plan A for Bagwell is to hit the schools, to offer the series
and its companion book, penned by Johnson. ``That in itself is a
challenge,'' Bagwell says, ``since a lot of teen-agers I've met
while traveling and talking about this series don't even know where
PBS is on their TV dial.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we aim to inundate them, to make them aware somehow, to
either watch the program or read the book or get hold of something
about slavery, its origins, its truths, its legacy. It might be too
much for some, but overall, it's not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's distressing news to the journalist who asked
about getting beyond this slavery thing. It's wishful thinking. In
fact, mounting the stage as the ``Africans in America'' panel
departed was Macky Alston, who was there to discuss his
documentary, ``Family Name,'' a film about a white man who tracks
the descendants of the slaves and slave owners who lived on the
North Carolina plantations once owned by his family.
</P>
<P>
   One way to find them was to go through the phone book of a tiny
North Carolina town, finding dozens of Alstons, black and white,
none of whom wanted to talk to him. Not about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painful,'' Alston tells us, sounding much like the black
man who preceded him. ``I hope people who watch this film can use
the Alstons' experiences as a way to explore how slavery affects us
to this day ... someday we'll get beyond silence, guilt and blame _
but only after we confront the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
