</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-READING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS FOR KIDS' SUMMER READING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDY GUERRA-CLINE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHILDREN'S BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're Just What I Need''
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/.MDNM/Author:.MDBU/.MDNM/ Ruth Krauss
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/.MDNM/Publisher:.MDBU/.MDNM/ HarperCollins
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/.MDNM/Cost:.MDBU/.MDNM/ $14.95
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/.MDNM/Ages:.MDBU/.MDNM/ 3 to 7
</P>
<P>
   People who know better often tell us to slow down, to savor the
small moments with our children.
</P>
<P>
   Right, we say. We'll savor after swimming lessons, soccer
practice, groceries and a stop at the video store.
</P>
<P>
   Those people would love it if we all read ``You're Just What I
Need,'' a deceptively simple tale of a busy mother and her small
child, who is working very hard, too _ at hiding under a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   In the gentle game of hide-and-seek that ensues, the mother
guesses what might be under that ``strange bundle'' on the bed, and
the bundle denies everything. It's not laundry; the mother doesn't
need any more of that. It's not a bunch of carrots. A monkey? A
mop? ``No, no, no, no, no, no, NO,'' the bundle replies, with its
hair peeking out.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-as-a-blush illustrations by Julia Noonan are perfect
for the warm-fuzzy feeling of the book, which serves as a gentle
reminder of what's really important: the little everyday stuff that
memories are made of.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
