<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPFUL HINTS ON SURVIVING ROAD TRIPS
</HEADLINE>
 THE ROAD-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SANDY GUERRA-CLINE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An eight-hour trip, three kids and one back seat. ... Let me see
that calculator. This isn't adding up at ALL.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a savvy summer traveler, you know that this kind of
situation takes planning. Serious planning. But there are things
you just can't plan for, such as a sensitive 9-year-old, an
assertive 7-year-old and a wiggly 5-year-old together for what
seems like forever.
</P>
<P>
   Picture books, coloring books and crayons (remember, it'll get
hot in that minivan when you stop for burgers) will take you only
so far. If you've waited this long to take your summer vacation,
you deserve a break. So why don't you try ...
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN'S BOOKS ON TAPE
</P>
<P>
   Sing-along tapes are great (try Disney's ``Animal Songs
Sing-Along Wild Safari''), but if it's only a matter of minutes or
miles before the adult behind the wheel lodges a complaint, you
could try a less perky route: audio books. For the younger set, try
``Arthur,'' Chapter Books: Volume 1 ($15.95, Listening Library,
approximate playing time two hours). For something older kids AND
adults will enjoy, check out ``The Indian in the Cupboard''
($19.95, Listening Library, four hours and 22 minutes). A great
choice for a mother/daughter trip would be the audio version of
Judy Blume's classic ``Are You There, God? It's Me, Margaret''
($15.95, Listening Library, two hours and nine minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BOOKS FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   If your kids can read in the car without throwing up, kiss them
now and encourage them on the road with some travel-related books,
such as Scholastic's ``The Kids' Book of the 50 Great States.''
</P>
<P>
   If you love trivia, pack the latest edition of Sandra and Harry
Choron's ``The Book of Lists for Kids'' ($9.95, Houghton Miflin
Co.). Older kids will find stuff to laugh about and share with
younger seatmates, and you'll be ready to amuse your friends at
that next dinner party. Do you know the 10 most requested karaoke
songs in the United States?
</P>
<P>
   GAMES GALORE
</P>
<P>
   One look at ``The Amazing Backseat Book-a-ma-Thing'' (billed as
``Thousands of Miles' Worth of Hands-On Games and Activities'') and
you get the feeling the folks at Klutz Press have been down this
road before _ and survived.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots and lots of games here: sane ones such as penny
races, a ``magic writer'' pad for games of Hangman, fold-it-up
paper puzzles, and wackier ones like reading your seatmate's head
bumps or reciting a ``scratch my back'' story (although that last
one sounds like a good recipe for the ``Did I hurt you? Oh, I'm
soooooooo sorry'' fight.)
</P>
<P>
   Klutz also delivers with two RealWorld Guides _ Glove
Compartment Games and Glove Compartment Scavenger Hunt. These
durable (they're laminated), cheap (they're $4.95), little guides
are hard to beat. Games includes the parental favorite ``Name That
Tune,'' but the guides have more than a dozen other suggestions,
including ``Deep Questions'' for those admittedly rare
philosophical moments.
</P>
<P>
   You might also try Family Fun's Games on the Go ($9.95,
Hyperion), which includes suggestions for things to do the whole
trip through, such as the ``Postcards to Me'' activity, in which
kids write and mail postcards to themselves and then bind them
together when they get home for a unique souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
