A9081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-650&AMP;AD     07-16 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTINA COACH SUSPENDED FROM BICYCLE RACING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATEAUROUX, France _ The international governing body of
bicycle racing suspended the coach of the top-ranked Festina team
Thursday after he was taken into police custody in connection with
a drug scandal that threatens to overwhelm the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, Bruno Roussel, a 41-year-old Frenchman, has been
accused by a Festina worker of ordering him to bring illegal
performance-enhancing drugs to the start of the race last week in
Ireland. The worker was arrested last Wednesday at the
French-Belgian border after his official team car was found to
contain large, but so far unannounced amounts, of illicit drugs
including amphetamines, steroids, masking drugs and erythropoietin,
also known as EPO.
</P>
<P>
   Anabolic steroids, which are used to add muscle mass and aid
recovery from strenuous workouts, have side effects ranging from
severe acne to heart and liver disease. EPO is a genetically
engineered copy of a hormone produced in the kidney that regulates
the production of red blood cells and is suspected to be in wide
use in endurance sports such as bicycle racing and cross-country
skiing. The drug has been linked to more than a dozen deaths by
heart attacks among amateur and professional riders in recent years
because it thickens the blood.
</P>
<P>
   Roussel was held by the police late Wednesday after a few hours
of questioning in the town of Cholet, where the three-week Tour de
France completed its fourth daily stage. Also being held is the
team's doctor, Eric Ryckaert, a 52-year-old Belgian. They were not
formally arrested but under French law can be held for 96 hours and
are expected to be questioned further in the northern city of
Lille, where the case is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   No action was taken against the nine Festina riders in the race.
They include Laurent Brochard, the world road race champion, and
Richard Virenque, the race's top climber the last four years and
the second-ranked competitor in the last Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This affair has shaken the confidence of the public and
disturbed the riders,'' said Jean Marie Leblanc, director of the
Tour, at a news conference Thursday morning as the suspension was
announced. ``We hope that from this moment, sport will return to
its rightful priority in the Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   At his side was Martin Bruin, the race's chief commissaire, or
judge, representing the International Cycling Union, which
suspended Roussel's license ``provisionally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That means for the time being,'' Bruin said when pressed for
more details about the suspension. ``Other than that, the official
comment is that there is no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   The cycling union cited Roussel's failure to respond in writing
by Tuesday afternoon to questions it had raised.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions concerned the arrest last week of Willy Voet,
53, a Festina soigneur, or masseur. First, Voet reportedly told the
French police that the drugs were for his personal use but later
told them that he was taking the drugs, under team orders, to the
Festina doctor in Dublin, Ireland, where the 85th Tour began
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Roussel and Ryckaert have both denied Voet's accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a drawn Leblanc said, ``There are sufficiently
grave conditions'' to suspend Roussel's license.
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc, 54, was a professional rider himself at the time of the
Tour's biggest drug affair, the death in 1967 of British rider Tom
Simpson during a climb on Mont Ventoux in France. Amphetamines were
blamed when Simpson overheated during the stage and suffered a
fatal heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour's last major doping scandal occurred in 1988, when the
race leader, Pedro Delgado, a Spaniard, failed a drug test because
he had used a masking agent for steroids. Delgado was allowed to
continue to triumph in Paris because although the drug was illegal
under most standards it was not yet in violation of cycling union
rules.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Four riders _ the stage winner, the runner-up and two men chosen
at random _ are tested for drugs each day in the Tour. There have
been no announced failures in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from testing that is conducted during the Tour, bicycle
officials have made spot checks of the levels of red blood cells in
riders over the last two years, suspending for two weeks anybody
whose level is abnormally high. Nearly a dozEn riders were
penalized last year and about half a dozen so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour director said that he had talked by phone Thursday
morning with Hein Verbruggen, the head of the cycling union, which
is meeting in Havana and that Verbruggen had been ``disturbed by
press coverage of the affair and the image it is giving to the
Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach's suspension was announced in Cholet Thursday as a
cold drizzle fell before the start of the fifth stage, which was
won by Mario Cipollini, an Italian who rides for the Saeco team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair,'' said Patrick Lefevere, he coach of
the Mapei team, which is ranked just below Festina in the
computerized team standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he ordered the soigneur to do this, he's guilty,'' Lefevere
said. ``But if the soigneur was trafficking in drugs and the coach
didn't know about it, he's not guilty. And in that case there's a
lot of damage for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Weltz, coach of the U.S. Postal Service team, said,
''It's hard to figure out what's the real story. He has his legal
rights, but the UCI may know something we don't and that's why they
acted.''
</P>
<P>
   Festina riders were supportive of Roussel and somewhat defiant.
Virenque, a Frenchman who is among the favorites before the finish
in Paris on Aug. 2, said: ``We're here to win the Tour de France,
and we'll continue to ride to do so. We're not here to discuss
doping. I'll answer questions about the stage Thursday but not
about this affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Stephens, an Australian with Festina, was more forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is pretty depressed,'' he said. ``Bruno said a couple
of days ago he wanted to go to the court, he wanted to talk. He
said he's got nothing to hide, he wanted to get everything out of
the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
