<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9084 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHCARE-ART-400&AMP;AD     07-16 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PUSHES PATIENTS' RIGHTS AS HOUSE REPUBLICANS SQUABBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton traveled to Capitol Hill on
Thursday to champion patients' rights, declaring to a crowd of
doctors and Democratic colleagues that a patient's right to sue
should be a cornerstone of managed care legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expressed reservations about the Senate Republican
proposal released on Wednesday. The House has a separate proposal,
of which some specifics were disclosed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the president criticized those proposals, Republicans
squabbled among themselves, with some disagreeing over the extent
of legal protections that should be afforded to patients and
whether the proposals would fuel rising health costs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Republican plans, and the Senate one in
particular, would not cover enough people, and left too much up to
the states. The problems, he said, required national legislation
and demanded stronger enforcement than an appeals review panel
could provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will come to us and they say, `OK we'll be for all
the substantive positions in your bill or most of them, as long as
you don't give the patients a right to sue, or some other
enforceable legal right,' '' Clinton said. ``You can write all the
guarantees you want into the law here in Washington, and if nobody
can enforce them, the delay in the system will still cause people
to die. We have to do something about this.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, across town, House Republicans gathered under
a tent in front of the emergency room at George Washington
University Hospital to release specifics on their own managed care
bill. The House Republican bill, while not as far-reaching as the
Democratic bill, extends more patient protections to more people
than its Senate Republican counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to echo what the president said,'' House Speaker Newt
Gingrich said as a group of doctors and nurses listened. ``This
should be a bipartisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as patients' legal rights, however, Gingrich said, ``We
believe external panels of medical specialists are better than
trial lawyers'' in resolving claims disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gingrich's rousing endorsement, the House bill appears
to have splintered Republicans, some of whom believe it either goes
too far and runs the risk of increasing the cost of insurance, or
it does not go far enough to protect patients.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, who has been a co-sponsor of the
Democratic bill, announced Thursday that he would resign from the
National Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare. Ganske
said his push for patient protections had created ``dissension'' in
the Republican conference.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., who is chairman of the House
Oversight Committee and a member of the Republicans' managed care
study group, dropped his support of the House Republican bill after
a stormy meeting with colleagues late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas got into a heated dispute over several provisions with
Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., who helped galvanize support for
patients' rights. In the end, Norwood won out for stronger patient
protections. Thomas objected, and abruptly left the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats should take no joy from the fact that I am not
co-sponsoring the Republican bill because I am adamantly opposed to
the Democrats' bill and will work to defeat it,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Democratic bill would give all consumers the right to
collect damages from managed care companies, the Republicans
propose beefing up the appeals process. They also advocate several
fixes, similar to those in the Democratic bill, which would improve
access to emergency care, to doctors outside HMO plans and to
obstetricians and gynecologists, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   But the House and Senate Republican plans diverge on a major
point: The House plan, like the Democratic bill, would extend those
protections to the 150 million people in employer-sponsored
federally regulated plans. The Senate version would provide most of
those protections to one-third that number.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans say that the two-thirds _ or 100 million
people _ would be protected by state laws, which vary depending on
the state. But Democrats say state laws are inconsistent. ``We have
gone to great lengths not to trample on the states,'' said Oklahoma
Sen. Don Nickles, the second-ranking Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office released figures Thursday on the
Democratic proposal. The bill would cost an estimated $500 million
and result in a loss of $4.6 billion in revenue over the next five
years. Democrats contend the increase would cost the average
employee $2 extra a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
