<P>
   FASHION-VATICAN-NYT (Rome) _ The Catholic Church has become an
irresistible theme for Italian designers seeking to make a splash.
As fall-winter collections got under way in Rome this week, fashion
designers sprinkled their shows with religious symbols. By
Alessandra Stanley. Moved 7-15. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TEACHER-FIRED-NYT (New York) _ A teacher who was fired a
month ago for asking her sixth- graders if they wanted to accept
Jesus Christ as their saviour will receive two weeks' back pay.
Mildred Rosario will not get her job back as a bilingual teacher at
Intermediate School 74 in the Bronx, she is free to apply for a job
with any other city school district. By Macarena Hernandez. Moved
7-13.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-RELIGION-REVIEW-NYT (Undated) _ As the century began,
optimists could easily have convinced themselves that by the time
2000 rolled around there would be nothing left for scientists and
theologians to argue about. Each would have long since agreed on
how to divvy up the intellectual terrain. Science would continue
its inevitable march toward a grand explanation of how the material
world works, leaving to religion the endless arguments over why the
universe came to be and how people ought to behave in it. It hasn't
happened that way. By George Johnson. Moved 7-11.
</P>
<P>
   SWAMI-STATUE-NYT (Lemont, Ill.) _ Swami Vivekananda, an Indian
theologian who visited the U.S. a century ago and was acclaimed as
an articulate spokesman for both Hinduism and religion in general,
is honored July 12 with a 10-foot-high bronze statue. By Gustav
Niehbur. Moved 7-10.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRIEST-ABUSER-NYT (Dallas) _ _ In what is thought to be
the largest such settlement ever, the Catholic Diocese of Dallas
agreed to pay $23.4 million to young men victimized by a local
priest, Rudy Kos, in the 1980s and early 1990s. The diocese
promised to bring in professionals to examine its practices and to
make recommended changes to prevent such abuse in the future. By
Carol Marie Cropper. Moved 7-10.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-RELIGIONS-TEX (Undated) _ An article in a series on
religions around the world examines the Church of Christ,
Scientist, founded by Mary Baker Eddy in the late 19th Century.
History, beliefs, etc., are discussed. By Jim Jones. Moved 7-15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ ``Achieving Our Country,'' by
Richard Rorty, a scholar called the leading gadfly of contemporary
philosophy, is a vigorous plea for the reconstitution of a broad,
pragmatic and reformist left in the United States. And one of the
most interesting things about this plea is the place it makes _ or
does not make _ for religion. By Peter Steinfels. Moved 7-10.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Ashland, Mass.) _ Mata Amritanandamayi, a
guru whose name translates to ``mother of immortal bliss''
envelopes followers in a warm hug meant to provide divine healing
and inspiration. By Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 7-14. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
