<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9088 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS &LR;      07-16 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WRANGLING FAILS TO BLOCK AGENT TESTIMONY IN STARR PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The US Court of Appeals rejected an urgent request
from the Clinton administration Thursday to block Independent
Counsel Kenneth W. Starr from summoning the president's closest
bodyguards before a federal grand jury, leaving only the Supreme
Court to decide whether to intervene in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Chief Justice William Rehnquist steps in by noon Friday,
a temporary stay preventing members of the Secret Service from
testifying will lapse, and the agents will be called before the
grand jury investigating the Monica S. Lewinsky allegations as
early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials filed a request with Rehnquist
Thursday afternoon asking that he extend the stay until the entire
Supreme Court can hear an appeal in the autumn.
</P>
<P>
   That request capped a day of high drama on the case, as the
legal chess match unfolding between the Clinton administration and
Starr's office took on the urgency of an old-fashioned duel. At one
point Thursday morning, Secret Service Agent Larry Cockell, the
head of President Clinton's protective detail, sat with several
uniformed officers outside the grand jury room waiting to testify,
as Justice Department lawyers won an emergency reprieve from a
panel of appellate judges.
</P>
<P>
   But that victory proved short-lived. By early afternoon, the
full appellate court issued a decision saying it would let stand a
federal judge's prior to ruling that the agents must testify, and
set noon Friday for the stay to lapse.
</P>
<P>
   All nine judges ruling in the case also took pains to note that
they believed the decision would not be overturned, saying in their
order, ``The Justice Department's likelihood of success before the
Supreme Court is insufficient to warrant further delay in the grand
jury's investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded decision, one of the judges even chided
Clinton and the Justice Department for pushing the case this far,
describing the administration's argument of a special privilege for
Secret Service agents to avoid testifying as a ``constitutional
absurdity.''
</P>
<P>
   That judge, Lawrence Silberman, also chastised Attorney General
Janet Reno for representing the interests of the president over
those of the nation in fighting the independent counsel on the
Secret Service issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general is, in effect, acting as the president's
counsel under the false guise of representing the United States,''
wrote Silberman, an appointee of former President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am mindful of the terrible political pressures and strains
of conscience that bear upon senior political appointees of the
Justice Department when an independent counsel is investigating the
president of the United States,'' Silberman wrote. ``Those strains
are surely exacerbated when the president's agents literally and
figuratively `declare war' on the independent counsel (can it be
said that the president of the United States has declared war on
the United States?).''
</P>
<P>
   Silberman added that federal law ``limits the options that the
attorney general can legally (and honorably) pursue. Litigating
against the independent counsel is not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Michael McCurry disputed Silberman's
assertion that Clinton allies had declared war on Starr, saying,
``War is a very precise term of art around here, and the commander
in chief takes that seriously. We are not at war with Ken Starr,
but we have some serious disagreements with him, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Jan. 25, in the frantic days just after allegations
surfaced that Clinton had a sexual relationship with Lewinsky, a
former White House intern, and urged her to lie about it, James
Carville, one of Clinton's strategists, explicitly said that he
would wage war with the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be war,'' Carville said on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.'' ``The friends of the president are disgusted by these
kinds of tactics, and we're going to fight, and we're going to
fight very hard to defend the president.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, since Starr first issued subpoenas to three Secret
Service employees, officials from the Treasury Department, which
oversees the Secret Service, and the Justice Department have argued
that agents should not be allowed to testify against the president
they are charged to protect.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing such testimony, those officials argued, the court
would be endangering the president, because Clinton and future
presidents would then try to distance themselves from agents in
pursuit of privacy, and in doing so put themselves in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   The White House again sought Thursday to distance itself from
the appeals in this case. McCurry repeatedly referred all questions
to the Justice Department and the Secret Service. Spokesmen for
both agencies failed to return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have stated before, the attorney general and the
secretary of the Treasury have made their decisions on how to
proceed in this matter with complete independence, guided by the
advice of career law enforcement professionals,'' White House
counsel Charles F.C. Ruff said in a written statement. ``They have
only one interest _ to ensure that the Secret Service is able to
perform its vitally important duties.''
</P>
<P>
   One stated fear among Clinton's battery of lawyers is that Starr
is planning to question Cockell about conversations between Clinton
and Robert Bennett, the president's attorney in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment. Cockell was reportedly in the limousine with
Clinton and Bennett on the ride back to the White House from
Clinton's deposition with Jones's lawyers in January, when he was
first asked about the nature of his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rehnquist, an appointee of former President Nixon and
the last remaining justice from the court that handed Nixon a
devastating legal blow in 1974 on the issue of executive privilege,
was flying back to the United States from an official trip to
Europe Thursday. Rehnquist had recused himself from the unanimous
vote against Nixon. Supreme Court officials said late Thursday the
chief justice would not make any decision until this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist first must decide whether to grant or deny the Clinton
administration's request for a temporary stay that would continue
to block the agents' testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice could decide on his own or refer the issue to
the full court, which reconvenes in October. If Rehnquist acts
alone and rejects the stay, the administration could take the case
to another of the eight justices.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also filed a formal appeal asking the
Supreme Court to review the appeals court decision.
</P>
<P>
   At the federal courthouse in downtown Washington Thursday,
Cockell and the other agents arrived and left grim-faced, unsure of
their status as they were pulled in different directions in the
legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``As law enforcement officers here or anywhere, they'd like to
know what their duty is before they are doing it,'' said Mike
Leibig, an attorney for the agents. ``And some of the ambiguity is
what they're concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Cockell was temporarily replaced as the lead agent on
Clinton's security detail, largely out of concern that he was too
distracted to properly do his job, according to a Secret Service
official who declined to be named. That decision was reached by
Cockell and the director of the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   Another worry among Secret Service officials was that reporters
would yell questions to Cockell while he was guarding the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Said the official: ``We like to blend into the woodwork. Even
though everyone sees us, we don't like to be the issue. Now we're
the issue. This is the first time when it's been disruptive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
