<SLUG> BC-CUBA-TIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN EXILE GROUP'S LEADERS PLAN LAWSUIT AGAINST NEW YORK TIMES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of a Miami-based Cuban exile group
announced Thursday that they intended to file a lawsuit against The
New York Times, saying the newspaper published ``outrageous and
malicious'' allegations linking the group's founder to a bombing
campaign in Cuba last year aimed at toppling Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   In the articles, a militant Cuban exile named Luis Posada
Carilles was quoted as claiming responsibility for organizing a
wave of bombings last year at Cuban hotels, restaurants and
discotheques that killed an Italian tourist and alarmed the Cuban
government. Posada also claimed that he had received financial
support from leaders of the Cuban American National Foundation,
including its founder, Jorge Mas Canosa, who died last year.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here, Jorge Mas Santos, Mas' son and the
group's director, adamantly denied that his father or the
foundation had supported any of Posada's efforts. Mas Santos
demanded that The Times' immediately publish a retraction, saying
the foundation and its leaders had relied solely on lawful and
peaceful means to try to bring down Cuba's Communist government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Times slandered, and The New York Times lied,''
Mas Santos said at the news conference in the First Amendment Room
at the National Press Club. ``These articles are offensive,
slanderous and defamatory.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, The Times ``reiterated its complete support and
confidence'' in the two-part series, which was published on July 12
and 13 and written by Ann Louise Bardach, a contract writer for the
newspaper, and Larry Rohter, its Caribbean correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their articles are based on more than 100 different sources,''
The Times said. ``Both reporters met Posada and were assisted by a
dozen New York Times editors, researchers and lawyers in
preparation for publication.''
</P>
<P>
   The reporters conducted 13 hours of interviews with Posada, 70,
over two days at a walled Caribbean compound. The quotations from
Posada in the articles were transcribed from tape recordings. Nancy
Nielsen, a spokeswoman for the newspaper, said Thursday, ``The
Cuban American National Foundation has pointed to nothing in The
Times' stories that warrants a retraction or correction in our
view.''
</P>
<P>
   George J. Fowler 3d, the lawyer for the foundation, said it had
not been decided where and when the lawsuit would be filed. He also
did not say what allegations would be the basis for the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with a Miami Spanish-language television
station, Posada recently recanted some statements that he had made
to The Times. In the interview, televised Monday night, Posada said
it was ``completely false'' that Mas Canosa had provided him with
financial and logistical support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lie,'' he told WLTV-Channel 23 in Miami. ``They have
never sent me money, none of the officers of the Foundation.'' A
tape of the interview, in Spanish, was played at Thursday's news
conference, and at a news conference held on Monday at the
foundation's headquarters in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Posada also told the television station that he had not spoken
with Mas for eight or 10 years, but he had told The Times that he
spoke with him shortly before his death. ``This man professed to
have spoken with my father a month before his death, when my father
was on an artificial respirator fighting for his life,'' Mas Santos
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
