<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF EMBEZZLING AT WORLD BANK JEOPARDIZE U.S. FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (lh) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key member of Congress said Thursday that
financing for some of the World Bank's poverty-fighting efforts had
been put in jeopardy by reports that bank employees were suspected
of embezzlement and of accepting kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who is chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee's foreign operations subcommittee, said in
a letter to James D. Wolfensohn, the World Bank's president, that
he found news reports of possible wrongdoing uncovered by the
bank's internal investigation ``shocking.'' He said that it was
time for an independent review of the institution's management and
operations.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell's subcommittee was scheduled to vote next week on
providing $800 million for next year to the arm of the World Bank
that makes low-interest loans to the world's poorest countries. His
aides said he probably would write the bill to require a full
explanation of the reports of wrongdoing and the bank's failure to
apprise Congress of the problem before he released the money.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell's letter came after newspapers reported that the bank
had found evidence of kickbacks being funneled to employees in at
least two cases, and was investigating other accusations as part of
a broad inquiry into wrongdoing within the bank. The bank's
investigations were first disclosed by the Washington Post and the
Asahi Shimbun in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   When compared to the billions of dollars that the institution
routinely lends to rickety, poor and sometimes corrupt governments
around the world, the two cases at the center of the bank's
investigations are minuscule in financial terms.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, World Bank officials are investigating whether two
Japanese employees took $11,000 in kickbacks for steering a
consulting contract to a subsidiary of a Japanese securities firm.
</P>
<P>
   In the only other case to have progressed beyond the initial
stages of investigation, the bank filed a civil lawsuit seeking to
recover tens of thousands of dollars it suspects were funneled to
an employee by a technology company he hired to work on a project
in Algeria. No criminal charges have been filed in either case.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the World Bank generally see internal
corruption as a far-smaller problem than the bank's attempt to
wrest full control over the more than $20 billion it channels each
year into construction projects, education, health and nutrition
projects and other programs in scores of countries across the
world.
</P>
<P>
   But since the institution has embarked on a high-profile effort
to ensure that the money it lends goes to fighting poverty and not
to enriching corrupt government officials and business executives,
officials at the bank were concerned that the institution be able
to live up to its own standards,
</P>
<P>
   And with the bank's poverty-fighting effectiveness under attack
in Congress and internationally among economists and development
specialists, the investigations brought more criticism that the
bank is not sufficiently accountable to taxpayers in the United
States and other wealthy nations that help finance its operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department said it had encouraged the bank to
``investigate fully and then take all appropriate actions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
