u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      07-16 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE CROSS OF ILLINOIS TO PAY $144 MILLION FOR DEFRAUDING
MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Illinois pleaded
guilty Thursday to defrauding Medicare and agreed to pay $144
million in civil and criminal penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The company admitted that it had concealed evidence of its poor
performance in reviewing and paying claims of Medicare
beneficiaries in Illinois and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement is the latest result of a federal crackdown
on fraud and abuse in the Medicare program, which provides health
care coverage for 38 million elderly or disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Illinois, also known as the Health
Care Service Corp., agreed to pay $4 million in criminal fines. It
will also pay $140 million in a civil settlement of charges under
the False Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said the agreement was ``the
largest settlement ever with a Medicare contractor.''
</P>
<P>
   The company ``falsified its own performance records, and in some
cases simply paid the Medicare claims without even reviewing
them,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Illinois, one of several dozen
companies that review and pay Medicare claims for the government,
admitted that it had obstructed the work of federal auditors,
creating a ``false appearance of superior performance'' in its
Medicare work. The company admitted that it had falsified and
destroyed records in an effort to deceive federal auditors
evaluating its performance.
</P>
<P>
   In a plea agreement filed Thursday in the federal court in East
St. Louis, Ill., Blue Cross and Blue Shield pleaded guilty to six
counts of making false statements to the government, one count of
conspiracy and one count of trying to obstruct federal auditors.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been a Medicare contractor since 1983. Other
companies are taking over its work for the government.
</P>
<P>
   June Gibbs Brown, the inspector general of the Department of
Health and Human Services, said: ``Medicare fraud and abuse is
always a serious matter, but it's particularly grievous when the
abuse involves a contractor entrusted to protect the financial
integrity of the program. In this case, that trust was flagrantly
violated by a prestigious, nationally known company. It engaged in
unconscionable conduct that adversely affected Medicare
beneficiaries, providers and the program itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kieckhefer, a spokesman for Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Illinois, said the company had cooperated with the federal
investigation. He said the misconduct involved ``a few employees in
one office.'' But the plea agreement says that managers and
supervisors were also involved.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from accusations against Blue Cross and Blue
Shield by a company employee who invoked the False Claims Act. The
law, adopted during the Civil War, creates an incentive for
citizens to report defrauding of the government. Under the law, a
``whistle-blower'' can receive 15 percent to 25 percent of damages
paid to the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said that the employee in the Illinois
case, Evelyn Knoob, would receive $21 million at the time of the
final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Thursday night at her home in Illinois, Mrs. Knoob said
she had been instructed by her lawyer not to discuss her case. But
she seemed uncertain whether she would receive the money. ``What
they say and what's true are not necessarily the same,'' she
commented.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The American Hospital Association and many health care providers
have been lobbying Congress to repeal or water down major
provisions of the False Claims Act. They say the government has
harassed hospitals in its investigations of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said the False Claims Act was
``the government's most effective tool against health care fraud.''
And he said the hospital association had made ``an unconscionable
assault'' on the law this year, organizing a grass-roots campaign
to weaken the statute.
</P>
<P>
   The association tried to sway lawmakers with ``horror stories''
from hospitals around the country, Grassley said, but the efforts
failed to persuade Congress because they ``lacked an essential
ingredient _ credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital association Richard Wade said more than 200 members of
Congress had signed up as co-sponsors of a bill to rewrite the
False Claims Act, showing that the hospitals' arguments have merit.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said most of the money recovered from Blue Cross and Blue
Shield would go into the Medicare trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown, the inspector general, said that in the last five
years other Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans, in Florida,
Massachusetts, Michigan and California, had paid millions of
dollars in penalties to settle federal charges of submitting false
information to the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
