<SLUG> BC-AFLCIO-SWEENEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEENEY URGES VOTE FOR PRO-HEALTH REFORM CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ AFL-CIO president John Sweeney Thursday urged a crowd
of local workers to elect congressional leaders who will help to
reform health care.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a public forum at the Boston Medical Center, one of
a series of talks the union leader has held in various states this
year, Sweeney told about 100 people that the number of uninsured in
the United States rose from 35 million five years ago to more than
40 million today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no secret that since we failed to pass a national health
care bill we have been on a collision course and the result is a
nightmare for workers and consumers,'' said Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, no doctor should refuse to care for a
patient, and no health care system should deny care to the sick,''
Sweeney continued. ``The only way to prevent that from happening is
to elect a Congress that will support health care reform.''
</P>
<P>
   One health care worker at the forum said she has worked for a
nursing facility for 14 years, but earns so little she cannot
afford to insure herself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I haven't received a raise in four years,'' said Sylvia
McLure, a single mother employed at a Brookline nursing home. ``I
can't afford (health insurance) so I've gone all these years
without it ... The Lord's been on my side; I haven't got sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's visit took place a month after the 13 million-member
AFL-CIO released the findings from a report it had commissioned on
employer-paid health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that between 1989 and 1996, the number of
Americans covered by company-funded insurance plans dropped by 8
million. Of those, 76.4 percent dropped coverage because of a
marked increase in the amount employees are required to contribute
to the company health insurance plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
