<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLKMALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton signs bill authorizing King monument on The Mall
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Martin Luther King Jr. could become the first African
American to have a monument erected in his memory on The Mall in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore told delegates at the NAACP convention
Thursday that President Clinton signed a bill that day authorizing
the monument to the slain civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement brought the crowd to its feet with resounding
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved the measure on June 22. It did not face the
opposition that a federal holiday in King's memory did.
</P>
<P>
   Other monuments on the mall include memorials to Abraham
Lincoln, George Washington, Thomas Jefferson and Franklin Delano
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   King's fraternity, Alpha Phi Alpha, is charged with designing
and raising money for the monument. The last two monuments on The
Mall honor veterans from the Korean and Vietnam wars, were
privately financed and cost $16 million and $17 million
respectively, said U.S. Park Ranger James Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Details about the design, the size, the exact location and even
when the monument will be overseen by the National Capitol Planning
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   There will be an international competition to create the design
of the memorial, which will determine its cost, said Hebrew Dixon,
executive director of Alpha Phi Alpha. The Mall stretches from the
Lincoln Memorial past the Washington Monument to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
