<HEADER>
A9134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYPHILIS-COX     07-16 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYPHILIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vaccine could be ready for testing in 5 years
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Syphilis, the sexually transmitted disease that
has crippled and killed people worldwide for more than 500 years,
soon could be headed for eradication, thanks to breakthrough Texas
research.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, scientists at the University of Texas
Houston Health Science Center have mapped the complete gene
structure of the screw-shaped bacterium that causes syphilis,
opening the door to development within five years of a vaccine to
prevent and possibly eradicate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moved at being able to provide the key to understanding
this age-old scourge,'' said George Weinstock, a UT Houston
microbiologist who led a team that completed the gene blueprint
after two years of cooperative work with federal scientists at The
Institute for Genomic Research in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can now figure out ways to disarm (the bug's) defenses
through vaccines, identify it quickly through new diagnostic tests
and eliminate it with specific, targeted antibiotics,'' Weinstock
said.
</P>
<P>
   The gene mapping, reported in today's issue of the journal
Science, is expected to lead to all of those things because the map
provides science with its first look at the complete set of
proteins made by the bacterium's 1,041 genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Completion of this project is an extraordinary boost for
efforts to develop a protective vaccine,'' said Dr. Anthony Fauci
director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious
Diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve of the bug's proteins already are candidates for a
vaccine, which the UT Houston lab and others are working on.
Weinstock said they could have one ready for testing within five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that distinguishes syphilis is that, as far
as we know, (the bug) is truly a human pathogen,'' said Steven
Norris, a UT Houston pathologist and Weinstock's co-investigator.
``There are no animal reservoirs for it. So if you came up with a
vaccine, you would truly have a shot at wiping it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The bacterium, Treponema pallidum, joins 14 other microbes,
including a half-dozen that cause disease, whose genetic structure
has been blueprinted in science's ongoing genetics revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis has been treatable since the discovery of antibiotics
in this century, but it remains difficult to diagnose. Its initial
symptoms, highly infectious open genital sores, often heal on their
own. It may be a year or more before appearance of the secondary
symptom, a whole-body rash that also heals itself. From there, the
disease is hidden, and unless treated the bug invades the
cardiovascular and nervous systems, causing insanity and death.
Pregnant women with the disease may infect their newborns.
</P>
<P>
   The bacterium long has frustrated researchers trying to
understand how it works because it cannot be grown in laboratory
dishes for easy study. With the new blueprint, pieces of which have
been disseminated in the past few years on the Internet, they now
know why.
</P>
<P>
   The bug ``is metabolically crippled,'' Norris said, requiring it
to steal from its human host the enzymes, fatty acids, even some
building blocks of DNA, necessary for its survival.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston and Maryland researchers beat the problem by
inoculating rabbits with the bacterium, extracting the microbes
weeks later from their tissues, and breaking the genome into small
pieces for mapping.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis epidemics raged across Europe following its
introduction there in the 1500s after the first adventurers
returned from the newly discovered Americas, where scientists
believe the bug originated. It was a sort of trade for the smallpox
the Europeans brought to the New World. By the 19th century,
syphilis was found worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the new gene map, Weinstock hopes to examine
pre-Columbian mummies in Latin America for traces of DNA to finally
answer the question of origin.
</P>
<P>
   Today, syphilis is more common in developing countries than in
the United States, where it infects about 9,000 people a year. But
it re-emerges in outbreaks every 10 years or so, and the open
genital sores it causes make its victims vulnerable to the deadlier
AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis now is in decline in Texas, although there were
outbreaks in Dallas and Beaumont in 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Health recorded 683 cases in 1997, more
than half of them in Dallas and Harris counties. A total of 10
cases were found in Travis, Hays and Williamson counties.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 percent of the 1997 statewide cases were in African
Americans, in whom syphilis is 40 times more prevalent than in
Anglos or Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Health authorities say some African Americans don't seek
treatment for syphilis when it is most treatable because of
distrust generated by the infamous Tuskegee study. In the study
that began in 1932, the forerunner of the U.S. Public Health
Service denied antibiotics to African American men diagnosed with
the disease in order to follow its unimpeded course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still suspect that has an effect on whether African
Americans will seek medical treatment,'' said Barry Mitchell, with
the epidemiology division of the Texas Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
