<HEADER>
A9135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEWATER-PROFILE-CO     07-16 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEWATER-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White Water owner is known as industry leader
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Long before the E. coli outbreak tarnished the image
of White Water Park, the family that owns the Marietta attraction
had been building a theme park empire from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   Actually from below the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, Hugo Herschend, a branch manager for the Electrolux
vacuum company, decided he wanted to start a family business. He
found his future inside a big cave in Missouri's Ozark Mountain
country. Taking out a 99-year lease, Herschend organized tours and
square dances 500 feet below the surface of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   But his big success came when Herschend decided to hire some
crafts people to perform demonstrations outside the cave and expand
his small investment by putting on some cornball shows such as the
Hatfields feuding with the McCoys. Attendance shot through the
roof, and Silver Dollar City was born. The family's multimillion
dollar corporation now controls 15 theme parks and attractions in
three states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that we had changed the cave business into an
entertainment business,'' said Pete Herschend, one of Hugo's two
sons who now run the family business. He started as a 14-year-old
who cleaned the cave after hard rains, and later met his wife, Jo
Dee, when they were on opposite sides of the feud show.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta is a major market for Silver Dollar City, which
operates three major enterprises here. In addition to White Water
and American Adventures in Marietta, the company this year took
over operation of the attractions at the state-owned Stone Mountain
Park.
</P>
<P>
   According to many in the theme park world, the company is an
industry leader in providing safe, satisfying entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways they are held out as an example of the right way
to do things,'' said Wally James, chairman of the safety committee
for the World Water Park Association.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Dollar City is a finalist for the top award from
Amusement Business, a weekly trade newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   When it was built in 1984, White Water was one of the country's
first big water theme parks, and it has been responsible for
several innovations in the business. It was reportedly the first to
have a separate children's play area and the first to offer ``dive
in'' movies on a screen beside the wave pool.
</P>
<P>
   So when news broke in June of E. coli striking children who
visited White Water, with several kids hospitalized in critical
condition, the impact was felt to the very top of the corporate
chain. And it hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a situation like this hits, when a child is injured, I
get tears,'' said Pete Herschend, who is 64.
</P>
<P>
   He and his company also got busy. ``I know our men and women are
working just as hard as they can to do the right thing,'' he said.
Silver City's response to White Water has been a mixture of
maintenance enhancements, policy revisions, and spin control.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials have acknowledged that chlorine levels in the
pools had several times dipped below the standard set by Cobb
County. But they stress that chlorine levels were quickly raised
and are maintained by equipment that continuously monitors and
adjusts the levels of the bacteria-killing chemical. A $50,000
enhancement unveiled June 29 sounds an alarm to alert staff when
levels are too low or too high.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, plastic, sealed pants are now required and provided
for children using the wading pools.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Silver City flew its corporate director of publicity,
Lisa Rau, to Atlanta, and she has made a point of stressing that
White Water ``is not the source of the E. coli break out. We are
the link.'' The company has hired top experts to help find the
cause, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But pressure is mounting. Since E. coli infections of at least
25 children have been linked to White Water, the Marietta park has
seen attendance drop 30 to 40 percent during what should have been
a profitable hot summer. And a lawyer for the families of two
infected children has asked the company to pay the medical bills
for children who contracted the illness.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Carlock, White Water's attorney, said that subject is under
discussion but it's too early to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Herschend, who runs the company with his 65-year-old brother
Jack, would say only that his company will be reaching out to those
families.
</P>
<P>
   The E. coli outbreak is not the only troublesome health incident
to hit Silver City, but it is the biggest. Three years ago there
was an incident in which 60 people who visited the Marietta park
contracted parasites called cryptosporidium and giardia, both of
which cause severe bouts of diarrhea. In response, White Water took
steps to remove any lingering concern by ``superchlorinating'' its
pools.
</P>
<P>
   The company has sent letters explaining the steps it has taken
in the wake of its current problems, and Herschend is talking about
the company's commitment to communities in which it operates.
Silver Dollar City donated $6.5 million to charities in the past 10
years, said company officials. The Marietta water park has donated
for several years to a Cobb County shelter for abused women and
children, raising about $100,000 for it over 10 years. Dollywood
was recognized by the governor of Tennessee in 1994 for hiring
people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Hugo Herschend's influence remains with the company, his
son said. ``He always taught us the importance of listening to the
customer. He used his two ears and one mouth _ in that
percentage,'' said Pete Herschend.
</P>
<P>
   Christian values remain the foundation of the company, he said.
``That doesn't mean we only hire certain people, but we try to run
this company with the Golden Rule. We treat our guests as we would
like to be treated,'' he said. ``I hope we operate in a way that
pleases the lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
