<HEADER>
A9136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEWATER-SIDE-COX     07-16 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEWATER-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moms on panel defend White Water
 &HT;    By Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Their kids' memories will be filled with images of
the pools at White Water, with visions of Little Squirts and
Captain Kid's Cove dancing in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   They are a group of 20 mothers who meet every other Thursday
during the summer at White Water, without pay or free season
passes, to advise White Water on how to be a great family park.
Some have taken their children to White Water as often as five
times a week over the years because they consider it the best
summer entertainment their kids can have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most family-oriented, caring place I've ever
visited,'' said Anne Ledford, a Cobb mother of three who is one of
the 20 who serves on the park's Moms Board of Directors.
</P>
<P>
   Ledford said she has been saddened at the news of the 25
children who have been infected with E. coli traced to three days
at the park in June and angry at the media for what she perceives
as unfair treatment of the park. A season pass holder for the 11th
straight year, Ledford said she considers the park one of the
safest places her children could play in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   White Water General Manager Sonny Horton said the Moms Board
advises the park on ways to be more family friendly. It also serves
as a trouble-shooting group that aims to be sensitive to mothers,
whom Horton said make the decision about whether to bring kids to
the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at it through the eyes of the guest,'' Horton said.
``If we change the direction that we put the toilet paper on the
holder, they can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations over the board's 13 years have included things
like more diaper changing stations and roping off an area at the
Little Squirts pool so that kids coming down the slide wouldn't
land on little ones already at the base of the slide.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the mothers signed a three-page letter the park mailed
earlier this week to season ticket holders to encourage them to
come back to the park after several weeks of a 30-40 percent
decline in attendance after the E. coli outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak hasn't stopped the board's president, Raye Ann
Raaen, from wearing her White Water T-shirt out in public, even
though she has received a comment or two while wearing it.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers said they are deeply concerned for the families of
the children stricken with E. coli but do not think the park is to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pick things like that up at the lake,'' Ledford said.
</P>
<P>
   Raaen said some of the fondest memories of her boys, now ages 13
and 15, will be of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my kids grow up, and they think of summer, they will
think of White Water,'' Raeen said. ``This could have happened
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The group and park management have said they are thinking of and
praying for all the children infected. Two remain hospitalized at
Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center, and a third child _
Matthew Addison, 3 _ was re-admitted to Kosair Children's Hospital
in Louisville, Ky., last weekend but later released.
</P>
<P>
   At Scottish Rite, a 2-year-old girl remains in critical
condition, and a 4-year-old girl is in fair condition, hospital
spokeswoman Kim Lathbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
