<SLUG> BC-A&AMP;M-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M OFFICIALLY LOSES BID TO OFFER LEGAL STUDIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LYDIA LUM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State higher education officials formally
rejected Texas A&AMP;M University's bid Thursday to offer legal
studies, firing another shot at A&AMP;M's ties with a private Houston
law school.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M president Ray Bowen said he plans to ask Texas Higher
Education Commissioner Don Brown to reconsider the criteria used to
judge A&AMP;M's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen complained that the Higher Education Coordinating Board
did not properly consider the A&AMP;M-South Texas College of Law
affiliation on Thursday. Too many board members are ``inflexible''
and convinced the law school is becoming state-supported, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unfortunately one of the most misunderstood academic
events in our university's history,'' Bowen said. ``This is simply
an academic degree that we outsourced to a wonderful private law
school. The piece of paper has our name on it, with our control
over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both schools reiterated their plans to proceed with
various terms of the affiliation, including A&AMP;M naming members to
the South Texas governing board this year as well as the schools
establishing joint academic programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to strengthen ties between the two
institutions,'' said South Texas law dean Tom Read.
</P>
<P>
   Coordinating Board members voted 15-2 against A&AMP;M's request.
Board members William Atkinson of Bryan and Wendy Marsh of Amarillo
supported A&AMP;M. The board oversees all state-supported universities
and community colleges, approving their academic degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The flap stems from an agreement signed in January between South
Texas and A&AMP;M officials. The law school got A&AMP;M's ``brand-name''
boost while staying in downtown Houston and still charging tuition
of more than $14,000 a year as a private school. The university got
a law school that it has long wanted without buying or building
one.
</P>
<P>
   However, officials of the University of Houston soon accused A&AMP;M
of wrongly skirting the Coordinating Board for approval before
finalizing the South Texas deal. UH officials also labeled the
affiliation a precursor to South Texas becoming state-supported.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the higher education commissioner, repeated his
previously stated opinions when he advised Coordinating Board
members Thursday to turn down A&AMP;M's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M doesn't need a law school to remain a top-ranked university,
Brown said. Also, A&AMP;M's Houston law school efforts ``unnecessarily
duplicate'' those of UH and Texas Southern University, which each
have law schools a few miles from South Texas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(EDITORS: STORY CAN END HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bowen argued Thursday that Coordinating Board members still
had not considered ``the merits of a public-private partnership''
and suggested they postpone their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our case still has yet to be heard,'' Bowen said, referring to
A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown countered that South Texas should still be considered
a public arm of A&AMP;M simply because A&AMP;M is state-supported.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Steve Late of Odessa cited recent Houston Chronicle
articles about the A&AMP;M-South Texas affiliation as well as a similar
affiliation crafted in Michigan in 1995. There, educators and
legislators predict students of the hybrid Detroit College of Law
at Michigan State University eventually will help channel state
funds to the private law school because they are most likely to
favor public subsidies for the law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we as board members worry about in the future,''
Late said. ``What happens down the line? I love the concept of
public-private partnerships. But the taxpayers of Texas have spent
billions to make A&AMP;M the name that it is. This is not a good deal
for the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Bowen said A&AMP;M officials still don't plan to
lobby legislators for a measure officially approving the South
Texas affiliation. He would rather return to the Coordinating Board
next year with a reconfigured bid, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether the two schools can proceed with the
affiliation without Coordinating Board approval. South Texas sued
the board seeking a court order declaring the agreement binding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
