<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TWELFTH-THEATER-REV     07-16 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TWELFTH-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWELFTH NIGHT': ADDLED SAILORS IN A SEA OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everybody into the pool!
</P>
<P>
   The fairy-tale-pretty ponds in the ravishing country called
Illyria, which has materialized at the Vivian Beaumont Theater at
Lincoln Center, aren't just there for scenic purposes. People get
wet in the English director Nicholas Hytner's spirited new
production of ``Twelfth Night.'' Some jump into the water; some
fall in, and others merely get splashed.
</P>
<P>
   Now you could get all academic and argue that such incidents
correspond to the elemental imagery in the play, the greatest of
Shakespeare's romantic comedies, what with all those references to
the transforming powers of the sea and Elysian streams. But what's
occurring is really as much burlesque-comic as cosmic, an occasion
for fools and snobs to get dunked and for performers with great
bodies to strut their stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center has come up with a seductive, classier
alternative to the rambunctious teen-age comedies that
traditionally flood movie theaters in July and August. This
``Twelfth Night, or What You Will,'' which opened last night as
part of Lincoln Center Festival '98, is never less than an
appetizing eyeful, thanks largely to the work of the great designer
Bob Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, in capturing what one character describes as the
``midsummer madness'' of the play, the production is often funny
indeed, plump with sight gags and jokes rendered in clear and
accessible terms. It even has hot young movie-marquee stars whose
presence alone is guaranteed to generate buzz: Paul Rudd, Kyra
Sedgwick and, in the pivotal role of the cross-dressing Viola, this
year's Oscar winner for Best Actress, Helen Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as enjoyable as much of this ``Twelfth Night'' is, you keep
wanting it to come together in ways it never does, and though
you're likely to leave it smiling, you may also feel frustrated by
its pervasive imbalance. Crowley's set, a sensualist's delight of a
dreamscape that hovers between Venice and Marrakech and makes
astonishing use of eye-fooling perspective, sets up expectations
for a ``Twelfth Night'' of surpassing wit and sophistication. It
promises, alas, more than much of the cast can deliver.
</P>
<P>
   The romantic leads, with the qualified exception of Ms.
Sedgwick, rarely suggest depths of character. They execute their
comic and thematic functions attractively enough. But Ms. Hunt, in
particular, has a two-dimensional flatness that keeps the audience
at a distance. As a consequence, the play's central love story,
which hinges on the complications wrought by mistaken sexual
identity, offers a tidy quota of laughs but little in the way of
emotional nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   For that you'll need to look elsewhere, and not necessarily
where you would expect. ``Twelfth Night,'' as you may recall, tells
the story of what happens when Viola, separated from her twin,
Sebastian (Rick Stear), in a shipwreck, disguises herself as a boy
and becomes the emissary for the Count Orsino ( Rudd), with whom
she has fallen in love, in his wooing of Olivia (Ms. Sedgwick), who
herself falls in love with the man she thinks Viola is.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a subplot that revolves around the ale-soaked,
carousing Sir Toby Belch (Brian Murray), Olivia's parasitic uncle,
and his dim-witted friend, Sir Andrew Aguecheek (Max Wright), and
their run-ins with Olivia's puritanical steward, Malvolio (Philip
Bosco). The ambitious, dislikable and finally pitiable Malvolio has
always been a part to reckon with, portrayed by heavyweights like
Henry Irving and Laurence Olivier, and Bosco does a creditable,
workmanlike job with it.
</P>
<P>
   But the revelations of the production come from Murray and
Wright, who transform the low high jinks of Toby and Andrew into a
blissful vaudeville as rich in psychological detail as it is in
hilarious shtick. If it weren't for Crowley's bedazzling sets, this
Elizabethan Laurel and Hardy would walk away with the show. As it
is, they bring a warm verisimilitude to scenes that are often
treated as throwaway comic relief. In contrast, the primary story
of addled lovers and misdirected passions starts to look like
something that might be titled ``Fast Times at Illyria High.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't necessarily inappropriate to ``Twelfth Night.''
There's definitely a quality of arrested, self-involved adolescence
about Illyria's posturing aristocrats. Orsino, who thinks he wants
nothing more than to marry Olivia, is never happier than when
striking attitudes of lovelorn melancholy, while Olivia, in
mourning for her dead brother, revels in the melodrama of
bereavement.
</P>
<P>
   The play's opening images, accordingly, are soaked in an
atmosphere of self-indulgence. Orsino is first seen lolling
languorously and toking on an opium pipe with his courtiers on the
patterned carpeting that covers much of the stage and that has as
its dominant motif a peacock. When he later speaks of ``the
constant image of the creature that is beloved,'' he is not above
staring at his own reflection in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, our first glimpse of Olivia, in a self-conscious
procession of women in exaggerated mourning costumes (the clever
work of Catherine Zuber), establishes her as a pose-striker par
excellence. When she pauses reverentially by a pond, a skull pops
out of the water, in one of the work's many amusing visual
flourishes. Grief, for Olivia, is obviously something of a game.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Viola, who arrives to stunning effect as she wades to shore amid
swirls of mist, is the antidote to this artificiality: sane,
unaffected and emotionally grounded. In some ways, the all-American
Ms. Hunt nicely fills this bill. Her voice, the aural equivalent of
the Great Plains, certainly brims with a common-sensical approach
to life. But hitched to Shakespeare's language, especially the
poetry, it develops a singsong quality that belies her character's
claim that she can speak in ``many sorts of music.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a Viola of lyrical feeling, we get an emotional
efficiency expert, perfectly at ease in men's clothing. ( Stear's
Sebastian, by the way, both looks and sounds remarkably like Ms.
Hunt's Viola.) This works fine when she's skeptically summing up
the convolutions of the plot, and Ms. Hunt has some charming
business when Viola is forced into a sword fight.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast to the subtle sensuality she generated in her
Oscar-winning role in ``As Good as It Gets,'' she seems not so much
sexually ambiguous as sexually disinterested, even when Viola (in
the guise of Orsino's page, Cesario) has to undress her employer
for a swim.
</P>
<P>
   This absence of chemistry robs the play of any erotic danger,
though not for want of directorial effort: Hytner has Viola's hands
straying to Orsino's hips when he kisses her on the brow and Ms.
Sedgwick's Olivia wrestling Viola-Cesario to the ground while
kissing her/him full on the mouth. But the scenes feel spurious
somehow; what you feel you're watching is actors carrying out a
director's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, the comely star of the film ``The Object of My
Affection,'' directed by Hytner, has a good time posing as an
eternally bare-chested poseur. But it's a one-note, if exuberantly
realized, performance that doesn't let Orsino grow from false love
into the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sedgwick is potentially a first-rate Olivia; she has the
requisite glamour and a confident grasp of the comedy's language
that lets her play inventively with line readings. She is
ill-served, however, by Hytner's direction, which has Olivia shed
her dignity in her first speaking scene and never reclaim it. As
she progresses through a series of increasingly revealing outfits,
in hopes of capturing Cesario's attention, she registers as the
sort of hungry man trap found in old slapstick routines.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and Wright certainly understand slapstick. Hytner has
steered them through some delicious physical comedy, in which they
are ably assisted by the more straightforward performances of Amy
Hill as Maria, Olivia's crafty lady-in-waiting, and Skip Sudduth as
their friend Fabian. But Murray and Wright also create the kind of
complete portraits that allow you to imagine the lives their
characters lead when they aren't onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Murray locates a chilling, class-conscious viciousness in Toby,
never so evident as when he drunkenly sputters at Malvolio,
``Aren't thou any more than a steward?'' And you're always aware of
the ravages of age and alcohol; this Toby is first kin to Falstaff.
Wright's Andrew Aguecheek, of the stuttering speech and fluttery
footwork, provides a beautifully assured picture of a
heartbreakingly tentative soul, a stupid man who can never be more
than an imitative echo of others.
</P>
<P>
   Without ever ceasing to be funny, these actors elicit the
subliminal sadness and anxiety in ``Twelfth Night,'' even more than
this production's Malvolio, who becomes the victim of a practical
joke pushed too far, and the clear-eyed philosophizing clown, Feste
(David Patrick Kelly), who anticipates Lear's fool.
</P>
<P>
   Bosco, a fine actor, is more than adequate, but his character
seldom transcends the role of disapproving foil and easy target for
the others, bringing to mind Gale Gordon's curmudgeonly boss in
``The Lucy Show'' on television. Kelly is an unusually low-key,
close-to-invisible Feste, a sort of Depression-era folk hobo type,
whose songs, set to music by the talented Jeanine Tesori (the
composer of the musical ``Violet''), are bizarrely reminiscent of
James Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelfth Night'' also features an appealing on-stage band,
directed by Kimberly Grigsby. In addition to indulging the musical
requests of the moody Orsino and Olivia, whose funeral obsequies
are given haunting voice by the counter-tenor Marshall Coid, the
musicians strike astral chords to suggest the ordering,
otherworldly providence at work in ``Twelfth Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tesori's music here is fantastical and wonder-struck, a
fitting accent to the exquisite visual pipe dreams conjured by
Crowley's set and Natasha Katz's lighting. It's unfortunate that
the characters onstage don't always measure up to the ethereal
charms of the land they inhabit. But this Illyria _ a place, after
all, of much mirth and beguiling spectacle _ remains an inviting
oasis for theatergoers in search of escape from Manhattan in its
dog days, and their own midsummer madness.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TWELFTH NIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   By William Shakespeare; directed by Nicholas Hytner; sets by Bob
Crowley; costumes by Catherine Zuber; lighting by Natasha Katz;
original music by Jeanine Tesori; sound by Scott Stauffer; dance
sequences by Joey McNeely; fight director, Steve Rankin; stage
manager, Erica Schwartz; general manager, Steven C. Callahan;
production manager, Jeff Hamlin. Presented by Lincoln Center
Theater, under the direction of Andre Bishop and Bernard Gersten,
in association with Lincoln Center Festival '98. At the Vivian
Beaumont Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Paul Rudd (Orsino), Helen Hunt (Viola), Kyra Sedgwick
(Olivia), Amy Hill (Maria), Brian Murray (Sir Toby Belch), Max
Wright (Sir Andrew Aguecheek), David Patrick Kelly (Feste), Philip
Bosco (Malvolio), Rick Stear (Sebastian), Julio Monge (Antonio) and
Skipp Sudduth (Fabian).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
