<HEADER>
A9141 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-NORTHROP-ART     07-16 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-NORTHROP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED MARTIN ENDS PLAN TO ACQUIRE NORTHROP GRUMMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Expanded version is scheduled to move by 10 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that may signal the end of major mergers in the U.S.
defense industry, Lockheed Martin Corp. on Thursday abandoned its
planned $8.3 billion acquisition of Northrop Grumman Corp., a deal
that the government opposed on antitrust grounds.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiations between the companies and the
government to avoid a court battle, Lockheed said Thursday that
efforts to reach a pre-trial settlement were ``not successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lockheed board voted Thursday afternoon to end a takeover
that would have created the nation's largest military supplier,
nearly a third larger than its nearest competitor.
</P>
<P>
   In March, nearly eight months after the deal was first
announced, the Justice Department, supported by the Defense
Department, filed suit to block the acquisition, claiming that a
combination of the two companies threatened the nation's defense.
This action represented an about-face for the Defense Department,
which had long encouraged a wave of mergers that swept through the
military industry since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inability to reach an acceptable solution, combined with
our concern over the litigation with our principal customer,
necessitates this decision,'' said Lockheed chairman and chief
executive Vance Coffman. ``Continuing the litigation at this point
is simply not in the best interests of Lockheed Martin's customers,
shareholders or employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed, which itself has grown through the acquisition of 22
different military contractors to become the nation's No. 2
military supplier, is best known as the maker of the F-16 fighter
plane and many missile systems. Northrop, which makes components
for the B-2 bomber, is the nation's No. 3 supplier.
</P>
<P>
   The government feared that a combination of the two would create
an unacceptable level of ``vertical integration,'' in which
Lockheed could control too much of Northrop's electronics business
in ways that could suppress competition and drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop chairman and chief executive Kent Kresa said Thursday
that ``while we believed the merger was in the best interests of
our constituencies, Northrop Grumman can and will continue as a
strong, independent competitor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
