<HEADLINE>
&HT;        JERRY BROWN OUTLINES VISION FOR CITIES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 16 -- Forget global trade. Instead of bailing
out Mexico, send the money to poor U.S. cities. And if the World
Bank can forgive loans for faltering economies, can't someone
forgive Oakland's stadium debt?
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Brown, Oakland's mayor-elect, outlined his vision for
cities Thursday in Washington. And for watchers of the man who was
nicknamed ``Governor Moonbeam'' during his two terms as
California's chief executive, the vision was as far-reaching and
off-beat as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who says he has shifted from being a ``global thinker''
to being a ``local thinker,'' wants to shift federal debate -- and
spending -- away from global trade and back to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the metro economies, at which the city is the
core, 47 of the world's 100 largest economies are in the U.S.,''
said Brown. ``The question is what kind of goods are being
exchanged and what kind of skills are being developed -- a few
blocks from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal policies that have encouraged the flight from cities to
the suburbs should be reversed, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cities have tremendous capacity if the federal government
would adjust its policies,'' said Brown. ``Not to subsidize the
cities, but to reduce the subsidies that encourage suburban
sprawl.'' Brown's ideas include building schools as small as 100
students in 6,000 square-foot buildings, cutting all capital gains
on businesses that invest in the cities, reclaiming shut-down
industrial plants, and changing welfare and housing laws to reduce
the concentration of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are crumbling schools, there are crumbling neighborhoods
and they're going to drag the nation down with it,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Not limiting his remarks to the needs of cities, Brown took time
to renew his call for campaign finance reform, defend a
controversial newspaper series blaming the CIA for crack dealing,
and to criticize the rightward movement of world politics.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, he wanted to give a hopeful view of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Brown even took on author Gertrude Stein's famous quote about
Oakland: ``There's no there there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If something's already there, you got something in your way.
But if you have an unspent canvas, then you have a lot of
potential,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a there in Oakland, he said, is what will make his
job different from the other Mayor Brown -- Willie in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``In San Francisco, all they have to worry about is whether
they're going to put a new museum in Golden Gate Park. We have real
problems in Oakland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
