<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cather odd man out in bullpen shuffle
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The choice had become apparent to Mike Cather, maybe
even before management finalized it. As he packed his equipment for
the trip back to Richmond, the Braves' latest bullpen displacement
understood perfectly why he was leaving Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of saw the writing on the wall,'' Cather said shortly
after being informed of his demotion to Class AAA, freeing a 25-man
roster spot for Mark Wohlers. ``I don't take it personally. I think
I'm throwing the ball really well lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Cather's 36 appearances were second only to Kerry Ligtenberg's
(43) and, while his ERA climbed to 4.38 earlier in the season, he
had allowed two runs in his last 8 2/3 innings. But with three
pitchers _ Dennis Martinez, Rudy Seanez and Russ Springer _ out of
minor league options and John Rocker the lone left-hander and
Ligtenberg closing games, the Braves had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep everybody that we got,'' said manager Bobby
Cox. ``Rocker's been doing a good job. We want to keep him. Dennis
Martinez's stats aren't all that great maybe _ hits (74) to innings
pitched (58 1/3) _ but he'd done a good job and if we (designate
him for assignment), we lose him. If we sent Rudy out, he has to be
designated and he's gone. Cather, by numbers and technicalities,
unfortunately is the one who has to go.''
</P>
<P>
   BP with the VP
</P>
<P>
   Vice president Al Gore stopped by Turner Field for batting
practice and a little bit of everything else. He talked fishing
with Ryan Klesko, gave Walt Weiss a special vice presidential cap
for his son Brody and was presented with a team jersey by Tom
Glavine. He had a side chat with Thursday starter Greg Maddux but
asked the subject matter, Maddux replied, ``Top secret man, can't
tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   In search of . . .
</P>
<P>
   Besides checking into the current market for closers, the Braves
continue their almost annual survey for left-handed relief help.
General manager John Schuerholz maintains he could enter the
postseason with the rookie Rocker as the only left-handed reliever.
But finding a lefty set-up man is a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say it's a top priority,'' Schuerholz said,
``but it would give us more balance with two left-handers. But it
has to be the right one, it has to be the right price, has to be
the right circumstances, has to be a lot of right things.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Richmond . . .
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence or not, left-hander Pedro Borbon, on rehab
assignment at AA Greenville, was elevated Thursday to Richmond.
Placed on the 60-day disabled list March 31 as he continued to
recover from 1996 elbow surgery, Borbon's Greenville statistics
were hardly impressive (0-2, 4.74 ERA, 21 hits and 14 walks allowed
in 19 innings) but the organization is interested in seeing his
work against more potent hitters. The 19 innings in Greenville and
three appearances in Macon are the first live innings Borbon has
thrown in 20 months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
