<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTION ATTACKS EX-AIR FORCE CADET'S VERSION OF GIRL'S SLAYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Before she was shot twice in the face,
16-year-old Adrianne Jones was grabbed by the throat with such
force that pinch marks were left on her neck, a pathologist
testified Thursday in the capital murder trial of former Air Force
cadet David Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by the prosecution, Dr. Marc Krouse said left-hand
finger marks on the girl's neck were probably those of Graham, not
his former fiancee, Diane Zamora.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony by the Tarrant County pathologist seemed to
undermine the dramatic defense strategy revealed Wednesday by
Graham's attorney _ that Graham was not even present when Jones was
killed and that his jealous fiancee alone murdered the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora, a former U.S. Naval Academy cadet, was convicted of
murder earlier this year and is serving a life sentence. Now Graham
is on trial.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of their arrests, Graham and Zamora both confessed
to the Dec. 4, 1995, murder of Jones, who was shot to death on a
remote country road in the Dallas suburb of Grand Prairie. The
accused couple both said Zamora wanted Jones to die because she had
sullied the pure love the couple felt for each other. Graham had
told Zamora that he and Jones, whom he knew from the high school
track team, had had a one-time sexual encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his own trial, Graham contends the sexual encounter was a
lie and that his confession to helping Zamora kill Jones is also a
lie.
</P>
<P>
   But on the second day of the trial, moved to the Hill Country
town of New Braunfels because of heavy publicity in the Dallas-Fort
Worth area, the prosecution sought to raise immediate questions in
the minds of jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Casting doubt on a statement contained in both Zamora's and
Graham's written confessions that Zamora used a barbell to hit
Jones in the head, Krouse theorized Jones was hit with the butt of
a gun. The purported murder weapon was a Russian army handgun found
in Graham's attic. Krouse said the wound on Jones' head was so
deep, it had to be caused by ``a large and very muscular person.''
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by Graham's lawyer, &UR;  &LR; Krouse conceded that the marks
on Jones' throat could have been caused by Zamora if she were
wearing thick gloves. But other witnesses had established that at
the time of the murder, Zamora was recovering from a car-wreck
injury to her left hand.
</P>
<P>
   In another blow to Graham's defense theory, Zamora's former
``best friend'' testified about numerous incriminating admissions
that Zamora made to her that also implicated Graham.
</P>
<P>
   `` `That's how David proved his love for me. He killed her,' ''
Christina Mason quoted Zamora as saying a few days after the
murder. But the defense team scored a few times, too, as it
questioned the veracity of Graham's confession and attacked the
quality of the police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's attorney, Dan Cogdell, got Mason to admit that before
honing her testimony for Zamora's and Graham's trials, she had lied
to her family, police, prosecutors and a grand jury when she denied
knowledge of the crime. Mason testified she didn't believe Zamora's
admissions and feared getting involved, even when police, early in
the investigation, jailed an innocent teen-age boy for the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Police witnesses conceded they may have tainted key evidence by
improperly handling the two 9mm shell casings found near Jones'
body. Police also acknowledged they didn't exercise full control of
the crime scene in rural Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(EDITORS: STORY CAN END HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Graham faces only life imprisonment because
prosecutors are not seeking the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The crime went unsolved for nine months before Zamora and Graham
were arrested in September 1996, based on Zamora's guilt-ridden
admissions to classmates at the U.S. Naval Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Once on trial, however, Zamora testified that it was her
boyfriend who killed Jones and that she only confessed to help
protect him. On the witness stand, she portrayed Graham as a
violent youth who demanded sex often, threatened her and almost
single-handedly killed Adrianne Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Although Graham, a former cadet at the U.S. Air Force Academy,
confessed to shooting Jones to prove his love for Zamora, his
lawyer now says he wasn't present when Jones was killed. The
alleged motive was that Zamora wanted Jones killed for a one-time
sexual encounter she had with Graham _ an event that Graham now
says he made up.
</P>
<P>
   . The head blow could have been fatal if left untreated, but
death was the result of two gunshots to the face _ one to the cheek
and one to the forehead, Krouse said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
