<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHO'S-NEXT-PM-JAPAN?-     07-16 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHO'S-NEXT-PM-JAPAN?-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBUCHI, OTHERS READY TO FILL HASHIMOTO'S SHOES  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This timely 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi
News Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ASAHI NEWS SERVICE  
 c.1998 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ An outright showdown is looming as Foreign Minister
Keizo Obuchi, backed by the ruling party's largest faction, is set
to formally announce his candidacy for the Liberal Democratic
Party's presidency as early as July 16, while Health and Welfare
Minister Junichiro Koizumi also said he may also vie for the post.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi on July 15 gained virtual approval for his candidacy at a
meeting of LDP politicians belonging to the party faction he heads.
Former Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama, known within the
party as a power broker, at the meeting did not oppose Obuchi's
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   He is also expected to publicize his specific idea of what sort
of government his leadership would aim to create at the official
announcement of his candidacy, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Koizumi, meanwhile, said Wednesday he is aware that intraparty
support for him as an opponent to Obuchi is ``more vocal than
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to watch the situation carefully to decide if I
have any chance of winning (the party presidential race),'' Koizumi
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitsuzuka faction, headed by former Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka and to which Koizumi belongs to, also held a meeting on
July 15 and started considering whether the group should back
Koizumi as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The stepping up of the rivalry over the selection of the party
president, who will succeed resigning Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, marks a sharp shift in the party's approach to
intraparty elections, the party sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi had hoped to secure behind-the-scenes support for his
leadership before making his intentions known publicly. But the
public's growing distaste for traditional factional jockeying made
it clear that a more conventional contest for the party presidency
is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Although a more open leadership election _ which may be held at
the July 21 meeting of LDP members from both Diet chambers _ means
Obuchi will have to compete openly with other contenders, public
perception of the process made the election necessary, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other LDP politicians who may also join the race to head the
party include ex-party president Yohei Kono and even former Prime
Ministers Kiichi Miyazawa and Yasuhiro Nakasone, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Allies of Obuchi _ who has an overwhelming support base not only
from his own faction but from other factions like the one headed by
Miyazawa _ said the foreign minister's leadership is needed for
Japan to maintain its current positive ties with such key nations
as Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But some party members, and even some members of the foreign
media, argue that Obuchi's skills for carrying out sound economic
policies are untested. They hint that the financial markets would
not react positively to Obuchi being in the prime minister's chair.
</P>
<P>
   Younger LDP members, who are calling for Koizumi's presidency,
claim the self-styled reformist is the only person who can rival
Naoto Kan, leader of Minshuto (Democratic Party of Japan) and the
voters' favorite, according to many opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern is that with Obuchi at the head of the LDP, the
ruling party would be dealt another severe blow in the next Lower
House election.
</P>
<P>
   Koizumi also said on July 14 if Obuchi does not renounce LDP
policies put in place by Hashimoto, he might win the party
presidency but lose the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not official announced he will seek the LDP top
spot, Koizumi hinted he may run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am watching the developments (of the intraparty debate),''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koizumi, often referred to as the ``lone wolf,'' is known as a
staunch advocate of the privatization of the nation's postal
services.
</P>
<P>
   He became known nationwide when he ran for the party
presidential race three years ago, when Hashimoto was almost
certain to win without an election.
</P>
<P>
   Kajiyama's advantage is the leading role he has played so far in
presenting proposals to tackle the nation's economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Kajiyama advocated shifting from Hashimoto's belt-tightening
polices earlier than many other politicians. His suggestions for
disposing of the banking bad loans are believed to have been
positively received by the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   But Kajiyama's greatest disadvantage is that only a limited
number of leading politicians, such as Nakasone, support him. Some
LDP members warn that Kajiyama's leadership would eventually lead
to an alliance with the Liberal Party, led by Ichiro Ozawa.
</P>
<P>
   Many LDP members still view Ozawa with disdain after he left the
LDP to create an anti-LDP government.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for Miyazawa to take over as prime minister again are
meant to prevent intraparty squabbles from becoming too serious,
LDP sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Kono may bring a positive reaction from voters, but he lacks the
support base in the party, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Nakasone, meanwhile, said he will refrain from entering the race
at this time. &QL; 
