<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-LEDE-HNS &LR;      07-16 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYNE CUSTRED  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SOUTHPORT, England _ The first round of the 1998 Open Championship
was anything but British.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wind stopped blowing Thursday, the sun shined brightly, and
the American duo of Tiger Woods and John Huston made the most of
the tame conditions at Royal Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, playing some of his best golf since last year's Masters
victory, and Huston each finished at 5-under-par 65 on a course
that barely resembled the monster that players had to tangle with
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, Fred Couples and Loren Roberts were tied for third
at 4-under 66, while five golfers were grouped at 67, including
Brad Faxon and Davis Love III.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have predicted about 10-over for a winning score if
every day was like Monday,'' Huston said. ``It was almost
impossible. But it gradually got a little easier each day.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, it was nearly perfect for golfers and fans. And
while it was the British Open, it was the young man from the States
who drew the biggest gallery, and Woods didn't let them down.
Playing conservative, smart golf, Woods eased his way around the
course, using his driver only four times and consistently keeping
the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' performance showed exactly how far he has come in the
past year. At the 1997 British Open at Troon, Woods went wild with
the driver. He slashed it around the course _ he was 12 over par on
four holes _ and finished tied for 24th.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, however, he made few mistakes, missing two short
putts for his two bogeys but otherwise playing patiently and
methodically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things where I think I learned to just
play smart golf,'' Woods said. ``It is an evolution process that I
think every player goes through. If you ask any player back in
their teens and early 20s, they hit the ball pretty hard. But as
they get older, they learn to control their game. I'm no exception
to that. I'm still learning to flight the ball and learning a lot
of different shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But overall, I'm very pleased with my progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-round results were pleasing as well. Woods' only real
trouble was on the second hole, where he drove into the deep rough
and had a terrible lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there's no way it could come out the way it did,''
Woods said. ``I mean it flew to the middle of the green.
Realistically, I was facing bogey right in the eye. But the ball
came out good and I made a great putt down there to about a foot
and tapped that in. I felt really good about my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods went on to make birdies on four of the next seven holes.
Woods did miss a little three-footer for par on No. 12. And his par
putt on No. 18 lipped out, giving him a closing bogey to finish
tied with Huston. But that did little to dampen his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased,'' he said. ``I made a lot of good putts and
drove the ball very well. Consequently, I was able to control my
spin on the greens because I was in a lot of fairways.''
</P>
<P>
   It was much the same story for Huston, who has played
consistently all year, winning the Hawaiian Open in February.
Huston got off to a slightly rocky start, having to make a
25-footer to save par on the first hole, but he cruised around the
course otherwise. He made all pars on the front side and then
played the back nine at 5-under.
</P>
<P>
   Huston's best effort came on No. 17, where he drained a
40-footer from across the green for an eagle 3, and on No. 18,
where he came back with a birdie after driving into the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played really solid,'' Huston said. ``I've played pretty
solid most of the year, actually, and kept my focus and (have) been
pretty determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it helps that Huston is finally feeling up to par. He
battled tendinitis in his elbow and bursitis in his shoulder for
most of last year and struggled on the golf course. Then, a fan
approached him in the parking lot after a golf tournament and told
him about magnet therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it couldn't hurt,'' Huston said. ``So I've been
sleeping on a magnetic mattress cover that I even travel with, and
it seems to really help. The magnets are supposed to increase your
blood flow so it heals the body faster. I don't think there's any
proof that it actually does work other than people who use them
think they feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me, it took a couple of days before I started feeling
almost no pain.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident in Huston's performance Thursday. His 65 was
his best round ever in a British Open. In fact, it tied for his
second-lowest round of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Couples' 66 tied his lowest British Open effort. After making an
eagle on the 15th hole to get to 4-under, Couples appeared headed
toward a three-way tie for the lead with the easy par-5 17th coming
up. But his drive ended up in the deep right rough, and Couples had
to scramble to save par. Still, he was pleased with his effort and
the way his game is shaping up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm very close to playing like I did a long time
ago, when every time I went out I thought I was going to play well
or win,'' said Couples, whose best British Open finish was third in
1991 here at Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has shot lower than 65 in a British Open. He had a
third-round 64 last year that kept him in the tournament. But he
looked much more comfortable Thursday, a fact he attributed to
arriving in Europe a week early and spending some time playing
other links courses.
</P>
<P>
   That, and being one year older and wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be very creative in order to play over here,''
Woods said. ``You have to see these shots and lies and get a feel
in your hands. I think by playing over here more and more, as the
years go by, I'm getting better at it. Now tomorrow, I can play
smart golf, take it easy and just see if I can make some putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't have to force the issue to get back into the
tournament, because I'm right there right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
