<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-DEAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS DEAL REACHED ON TOBACCO CASE LAWYERS' FEES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush announced Thursday that an
agreement had been reached on how the fight over $2.3 billion in
lawyers' fees will be handled in the state's tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between Bush, Attorney General Dan Morales and
private lawyers appears to have cleared the last major stumbling
block to the final payment of the state's $15.3 billion settlement
with the tobacco industry for unreimbursed health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and seven legislators had sued to block the payment of 15
percent contingency fees to the private lawyers who had handled the
state's suit against the tobacco industry. Morales had agreed to
the fees and was defending the payment.
</P>
<P>
   But under the deal agreed to by all sides Thursday, the issue of
attorneys' fees will be severed from the rest of the lawsuit, Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said the private lawyers will take their claim for
fees to an arbitration panel in November. That panel will determine
how much money the lawyers should receive in payments from the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``An objective arbitration panel will now decide what is fair
compensation for the plaintiff's attorneys, and that amount will be
paid by the tobacco companies,'' Bush said. ``I have agreed I will
not contest the amount the arbitration panel orders the tobacco to
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he reserved the right in the agreement to continue his
fight against the high lawyer fees if the lawyers go back to court
in an effort to get more money than is awarded them by the
arbitration panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is a good step toward protecting the interests
of Texas taxpayers,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement apparently will allow the private lawyers to
collect a $50 million down payment on their fee from the tobacco
industry before the matter goes to arbitration. The lawyers already
have been reimbursed $40 million for expenses they said they
incurred during the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
