<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT LOGS GAIN OF 28 PERCENT IN EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showing practically no financial pain from its antitrust
battles, Microsoft Corp. reported a 28 percent gain Thursday in its
fiscal fourth quarter earnings, modestly exceeding Wall Street
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also said it had already sold more than 1 million
copies of its new operating system software, Windows 98, to
consumers. The company began to sell the new software only last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is the leading maker of personal computer
software, reported its financial results after the markets' close.
In Nasdaq trading, Microsoft shares closed at $117.375, unchanged.
In after-hours trading, shares fell to $116.875.
</P>
<P>
   Although the release of Windows NT 5.0, Microsoft's more
powerful operating system, has been delayed, probably until the
fiscal year 2000, analysts said the fundamental business was so
strong that it might continue to provide earnings in excess of
estimates next year.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials showed little concern about a substantial
increase in general administrative costs, which include legal
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one impact is that our legal costs are up quite a large
amount,'' Greg Maffei, the company's chief financial officer, said
in a telephone interview. He said the antitrust suits, filed by the
Justice Department and 20 state attorneys general in May, had not
affected revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is gratifying that it appears consumers are looking to the
quality of the products and are buying them,'' Maffei said. ``The
reality is it was a great quarter. Windows 98 is off to a flying
start, and we had good revenue from Windows 98 in the quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter that ended on June 30, Microsoft earned $1.36
billion, or 50 cents a diluted share, compared with $1.06 billion,
or 40 cents a diluted share, in the comparable period a year ago.
Revenue rose 26 percent, to almost $4 billion from $3.18 billion in
the fourth quarter of fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp., which tracks earnings
estimates, had expected Microsoft to earn 48 cents a share,
although the so-called whisper number, offered to customers
verbally, was 50 cents, exactly as reported. Revenue was about $200
million above most estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revenues up 26 percent was higher than expected, and they also
added $425 million to deferred revenues, bringing that to $2.9
billion, so that is a pretty terrific showing,'' said Rick
Sherlund, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the next three quarters we're looking at slower growth
because the product cycle is a bit slower,'' Sherlund said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent years Microsoft has termed a certain amount of sales
``unearned revenues,'' to reflect a more realistic accounting of
software sales cycles. Using this system, the company said it
recognized $150 million in revenue from Windows 98 in the fourth
quarter, but deferred 35 percent of that, so only about $100
million appears in its results.
</P>
<P>
   Although some analysts add the deferred revenue back to arrive
at a presumed total, Maffei cautioned against this practice. ``Some
creative analysts continue to misuse spreadsheet products by adding
back unearned revenues,'' he said. This is done partly to justify
the increase in Microsoft's price to earnings ratio, from 35 in
1996 to 48 in 1997, to 66 now. ``Consider the obvious,'' he said.
``The stock is more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   As they have in the past, Microsoft officials cautioned that the
company's growth rate was slowing and would continue to slow.
Although this quarter's earnings and revenue growth rates are
strong, they pale in comparison with earnings growth of 82 percent
and revenue growth of 41 percent last year. ``The growth rate for
this quarter is higher than most analysts are predicting for next
year, and I agree,'' Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Microsoft earned $4.49 billion, or $1.67 a diluted
share, up 30 percent from $3.45 billion, or $1.32 a diluted share,
in fiscal 1997. Fiscal 1998 earnings reflect a $296 million
write-off associated with the acquisition of Web TV. Revenue rose
28 percent, to $14.48 billion from the $11.36 billion reported for
fiscal 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
