<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT DEATH TOLL RISES IN NORTH TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   North Texas continued to suffer Thursday under an unrelenting
heat wave, with two more deaths confirmed in Dallas County and two
in Denton County.
</P>
<P>
   Brief afternoon rainstorms across northern Tarrant County cooled
off parts of the Fort Worth-Arlington area, but only for a short
time. The high temperature at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport reached 104
degrees, the 11th straight day of 100-plus-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths at home of 80-year-old Fay Motley of Dallas and
90-year-old Annie Mae Worley of Lancaster bring to 18 the number of
heat-related casualties in Dallas County since June 1. Statewide,
the total may be as high as 29.
</P>
<P>
   Two confirmations came Thursday in Denton County, north of Fort
Worth. Autopsy results showed that Jack Edward Roper, a 76-year-old
Roanoke man found dead Tuesday in his travel trailer, and
34-year-old construction worker Jose Francisco Deleon, who
collapsed on the job July 3, were victims of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no confirmed heat-related deaths in Tarrant
County. In Fort Worth, 81-year-old Grenelle Jackson was found dead
outside his home Wednesday night. Police and neighbors believe that
Jackson may have died of heat exposure, but the Tarrant County
Medical Examiner's Office has not issued a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad part is (heat exhaustion) is 100 percent preventable''
if people drink fluids and find a cool place to stay, said Dr. Alan
Stockard, head of primary care sports medicine at the University of
North Texas Health Science Center at Fort Worth. ``Some of these
elderly can't get into a cool area.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the Fort Worth-Dallas Metroplex, city officials, social
workers and volunteers continue to reach out to people who need
help.
</P>
<P>
   Callers seeking relief have flooded Dallas County's hot line,
which was established Tuesday after the first-ever heat emergency
was declared in that county. About 700 calls have been received
since the hot line was activated, said Zach Thompson, a city
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they need a box fan, we'll get a box fan to them,''
Thompson said. ``If they're elderly and have a chronic disease,
we'll see if we can get an air-conditioning unit for them.''
</P>
<P>
   With some deaths still under investigation, and no relief from
scorching temperatures in sight, the statewide toll is expected to
climb. The National Weather Service is calling for a high of 102
Friday and 100-degree temperatures through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, Vernell Roberts, a neighbor of Jackson, said that
the elderly man probably fell Wednesday afternoon from a
step-ladder behind his home and died after crawling 20 feet in
temperatures as high as 103.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the appearance of being heat-related, age-related, or
both,'' police Sgt. J.E. Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said a friend found Jackson lying face-down at a side
door to his home about 9:30 p.m. Wednesday. Police said the man's
body was halfway inside his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he just gave out of breath and died,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   A ladder lay in the back of Jackson's house beside one of his
slippers, and his hat and eyeglasses were atop an old fan that was
propping open a rear door. It was unclear whether the fan was
operational.
</P>
<P>
   No ruling has been made in the deaths of Opal L. Enlow, 80, and
William E. Enlow, 85, whose bodies were found Sunday morning in
their home in Sanger, north of Fort Worth. The inside temperature
was more than 90 degrees when the couple was found, said an officer
with the Sanger Department of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at John Peter Smith Hospital in Fort Worth have
treated nine people for heat-related illnesses this week,
spokeswoman Drenda Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   Two men described as older than 50 were admitted to the hospital
Thursday afternoon. One, whose identity is not known, was found on
his porch and is in critical condition in the intensive care unit,
Witt said. The other man, who was working in his back yard when he
became ill, is in fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest signs of heat exhaustion often include muscle
cramping and dizziness, said Stockard of the UNT Health Science
Center. Those symptoms can be followed by disorientation or
confusion, a headache and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   In the most severe cases, a person can stop sweating and lose
consciousness, Stockard said. If the body's core temperature
reaches 105 degrees, the cardiovascular system shuts down, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alecia Hathaway, health authority and medical director for
Tarrant County, said heat injuries fall within three categories:
heat stress, heatstroke or heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Heat stress is mild and most common, especially among people
involved in physical activity, Hathaway said. It occurs when the
body is depleted of fluids.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
