<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SURPLUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$6 BILLION SURPLUS POSSIBLE FOR TEXAS BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS SANCHEZ 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ If the Texas economy remains vibrant for another year,
lawmakers could have an unprecedented $6.3 billion in extra money
to spend or to return to taxpayers, state Comptroller John Sharp
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly the largest budget surplus that the State of
Texas has ever seen in its history,'' Sharp said in a letter to
House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, which was made public on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the projection, Gov. George W. Bush pledged that,
once education is fully funded in the next two-year budget cycle,
he would begin to look for ways to cut state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have proposed a tax cut for small businesses and a tax break
for research and development,'' Bush said. ``With this news, we can
do more for the taxpayers of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry Mauro, the Democrat who is challenging Bush in the
November election, said the revenue forecast proves that Texas
could implement his programs while cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us a historic opportunity to meet the challenges we
face because we have the revenue to do it,'' Mauro said. ``Just as
I said when I announced for governor, we can eliminate the sales
tax on cars, trucks and vans and still have money to pay for more
police on the streets, a pay raise for teachers and build enough
classrooms so we can enforce class-size rules.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Chris Harris, R-Arlington, said in a recent
newsletter to constituents that any surplus should be applied to
additional school property tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there is no justification for increases in the
sales tax or other state taxes or in professional fees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders, careful not to appear too jubilant over a
projection so large _ it is enough to fund Tarrant County (Fort
Worth) government at current spending levels for 36 years _ offered
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the Legislature an opportunity to meet the demands of
the next budget, consider a tax cut and, hopefully, put something
in a rainy day fund to guard against lean times,'' Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my opinion that when times are good, we should lay the
groundwork to prepare for lean times,'' House Speaker Pete Laney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp's projection comes one week after Legislative Budget Board
staff members forecast a $2.75 billion surplus over the current
1998-99 spending cycle of $87.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A surplus occurs any time revenues exceed the money needed to
run government.
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers take the comptroller's estimate more seriously
than the legislative staff's because the comptroller is
constitutionally mandated to make the state's official revenue
forecast, which is the basis for the Legislature's two-year
spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   That official projection isn't expected until January.
</P>
<P>
   If Sharp's preliminary projections are accurate, the budget
windfall would outgrow the $2.4 billion budget surplus the state
started with in the 1996-97 budget period with, said Kelly Fero, an
aide to Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   The next biggest surplus was $2.2 billion in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sure are a long way from the economic debacle of 1991, when
we were about $4 billion to $6 billion in the hole'' at the
beginning of the session, Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   His chief revenue estimator, Mike Reissig, said the current
economy continues to outperform expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Sharp's office projected that personal income in
Texas would rise by 6.1 percent this fiscal year and by 6.4 percent
in the 1999 fiscal year, which begins in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current forecast calls for these growth rates to be 7.5
percent and 7 percent during fiscal 1998 and 1999,'' Reissig wrote
in a memo to Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in income leads to increased spending, he wrote, which
has resulted in state sales tax revenue _ Texas' largest source of
revenue _ growing at annual rate of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Reissig stressed that the estimate is very preliminary.
``Issues such as the ongoing Asian crisis and the year 2000
computer bug could have negative effects on this outlook,'' Reissig
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, also cautioned that the current drought will
devastate Texas agriculture and affect the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide drought this year has already cost farmers and
ranchers an estimated $1.5 billion in revenue losses, the Texas
Agricultural Extension Service said this week.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
