<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG WINS AWAY FROM MOUND NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ He's stood on the Dodger Stadium pitcher's
mound, and he's stood in the Hollywood Park winner's circle. To
Matt Young the difference is no wider than a Louisville Slugger, or
maybe a horse's nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thrill. It really is a thrill,'' the former
major-league left-hander said of his success as a thoroughbred
owner. ``When you see your horse on the lead, coming for home, it's
the closest adrenaline rush I've had to winning a baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Young pitched 10 years for five teams, including a sore-armed
1987 season with the Dodgers. He was an All-Star as a Seattle
Mariners rookie, earned a World Series ring with the Oakland A's
and threw a no-hitter with the Boston Red Sox (although he lost 2-1
to the Cleveland Indians). In the victory he calls his biggest, he
pitched a two-hitter to beat Nolan Ryan, who was coming off a 1990
no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But Young might never have won a game as a pitcher that was as
important as the race he can win as an owner on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of five owners of Shot of Gold, a Bob Baffert-trained
colt who will bring a 5-4 won-lost record (how do you calculate a
horse's earned-run average?) into the $500,000 Swaps Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The 1[-miler is one of the year's last major races exclusively
for 3-year-olds. And it's the highlight of closing weekend at
Hollywood Park, which will offer a $1.5 million guaranteed pick-six
on Saturday, five stakes on Sunday and Monday racing.
</P>
<P>
   Shot of Gold's victories have come in allowance and minor stakes
races in California and Kentucky. So the Grade II Swaps represents
a step up in class from Triple-A to the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't a particularly strong Swaps field, with only
Grand Slam and Old Trieste coming out of the Triple Crown events.
So Shot of Gold, ridden by Gary Stevens, definitely has a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine that if you put the Breeders' Cup as the World
Series and the Kentucky Derby as a (league) championship series,
then this is like fighting for a (division) championship,'' Young,
who also pitched for UCLA, said this week from his home in La
Canada Flintridge. ``Certainly we've never run for anything this
size before.''
</P>
<P>
   Shot of Gold, by Jolie's Halo, is the seventh horse Young has
owned since his retirement from baseball in 1993. Young got
interested as a kid growing up near Santa Anita with a race-going
father. One of his partners, George Jacobs, is a high school friend
who owns Georgie's Pizza in La Canada Flintridge.
</P>
<P>
   Young picked Shot of Gold out of a Barretts 2-year-olds sale
catalog with the help of Steve Purner, son of bloodstock agent Fred
Purner Jr., who in turn is the son of a former Santa Anita
publicist. The colt cost $80,000, and has earned more than $200,000
with five wins, two seconds and a third, including a June 13
victory over Baffert's Souvenir Copy at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time out, this horse has shown us a little bit more
heart,'' Young said of the colt who didn't win for the first time
until March after racing only once at age 2 because of an injury.
``Boy, when he gets in the lane, he fights like a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of Shot of Gold, on the heels of Hear the Music,
Young's stakes-quality filly of a few years ago, makes him luckier
than most ``small'' owners. The nice thing is, he knows he's lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very fortunate,'' said Young, 39, who spends a lot
of his time coaching the baseball and softball teams of his
children, Clayton, 12, and Brynne, 16.
</P>
<P>
   His experience with baseball and horse racing, two of the many
sports competing for the entertainment dollar, gives Young a unique
perspective on the challenges that tracks face these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in places like Santa Anita and Del Mar, even Churchill
Downs and some of the spots in New York, racing is always going to
flourish just because of the people who are involved,'' he said.
``But some of the other (smaller) tracks, it's going to be hard to
keep the quality there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think one of the hardest things is to keep the public
perception (positive). I think people want to believe racing is
fixed. When you see things like sponging and clenbuterol, it leaves
a sour taste in people's mouths,'' Young said, referring to the
recent Kentucky incidents, where pieces of sponge were inserted
illegally in horses' nostrils before races, and to drug
controversies nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only so much money that people have to spend. I think
more so than going to baseball games and football games, the racing
dollar is being spent on (lotteries) and on these casinos that are
popping up.''
</P>
<P>
   Young thinks the racing industry's new ad campaign is a step in
the right direction. ``I like the `Go Baby Go' thing. I think you
really have to publicize it and make people believe it's the sport
of kings that it was in the glamour days. If baseball can live
through a strike that left such a bitter taste, then racing can
make a solid comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, himself, is a good advertisement for the sport. He told a
Hollywood Park publicist this week that if he could, he'd trade his
All-Star and World Series experiences for a victory in the Swaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everybody can win a baseball game,'' he said. ``So go out
and own a horse, and have the same thrill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
