<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES SCRAMBLE TO FIGHT RULING THAT SECRET SERVICE AGENTS
MUST TESTIFY 

</HEADLINE>
 7/17-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration scrambled Thursday to
fend off an appeals court ruling compelling Secret Service agents
to cooperate with the grand jury investigating an alleged
presidential affair with an intern and a possible cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour after the U.S. Court of Appeals sternly
rebuked the effort by the Justice Department to keep the
president's protectors from testifying, agency lawyers hustled to
the Supreme Court and asked Chief Justice William Rehnquist to
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department faced a deadline of noon Friday, set by
the appeals court, to convince Rehnquist or another justice to
block the subpoenas until the entire Supreme Court can consider the
case, probably sometime after the court's new term begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, an earlier ruling by a three-judge appeals court
panel will prevail, and independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
prosecutors can begin questioning several Secret Service employees
about what they saw or heard while protecting the president. Among
those subpoenaed is the chief of President Clinton's personal
security detail.
</P>
<P>
   Starr wants Secret Service employees to provide the grand jury
with information about any attempt by Clinton or his associates to
keep secret alleged sexual encounters with White House aides Monica
Lewinsky and Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service, a branch of the Treasury Department that is
represented by the Justice Department, want the courts to recognize
a privilege of confidentiality that protects employees from having
to testify. That argument _ characterized by one appeals court
judge as ``a constitutional absurdity'' _ has been rejected by U.S.
District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson and a three-judge appeals
panel.
</P>
<P>
   When the administration on Tuesday asked the full appeals court
to review the three-judge panel's decision, Starr fired off a
letter to Attorney General Janet Reno complaining that the appeal
was designed to delay the grand jury investigation. At the same
time, Starr issued subpoenas for seven Secret Service employees,
including Larry Cockell, Clinton's top bodyguard, to appear
Thursday before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Justice Department lawyers asked Johnson to issue
a stay blocking the subpoenas. Not only did Johnson reject the
request, she upbraided Justice Department lawyers for trying to
stall Starr's inquiry. Justice lawyers then asked the three-judge
panel for a stay.
</P>
<P>
   Despite one published report that Rehnquist was asked to
intervene on Wednesday, the justice was notified late that day
that, if turned down by the interim appeals court, the
administration would ask him to block the subpoenas until the issue
of a Secret Service privilege could be decided by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, Cockell, who often stands at the president's
shoulder and accompanies him to meetings, arrived at the federal
courthouse with six colleagues and their attorneys. Cockell's
presence overshadowed the sixth day of testimony by Linda Tripp,
the woman whose taped conversations with Lewinsky triggered the
investigation six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Justice Department lawyers pleaded for a stay from the
appeals court, the Secret Service agents stood in a hallway outside
the grand jury room where Tripp was testifying. A little over an
hour later, the stay was granted and the president's bodyguards
left, some of them returning to their posts at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   At midafternoon, the appeals court issued its decision refusing
to review the work of the three-judge panel. The appeals court
noted that nine of the 11 judges on the court did not want to take
the case. Two others were out of the city. For the case to be
considered by the full court, six judges would have to agree to the
review.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the appeals court also signaled that the
administration was fighting a losing battle in its effort to have
the courts recognize the so-called protective function privilege.
The Justice Department's ``likelihood of success before the Supreme
Court is insufficient to warrant further delay in the grand jury's
investigation,'' the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, the Secret Service reassigned Cockell to other
duties at the White House until the issue of privilege is resolved,
officials said. The agency gave his job as Clinton's chief
bodyguard to Brian Stafford, who headed the executive security
detail before Cockell. The agency said Cockell will return to his
post once the legal fight is resolved. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
