<HEADLINE>
WEST TO REMAIN AS LAKERS G.M.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a change of heart inspired by his boss' change of monetary
policy, Jerry West has decided to fulfil the final year of his
contract with the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   West had planned to announce his retirement from the team on
August 31, but Laker owner Jerry Buss recently handed over to West
the remaining amount more than $2 million of the $5 million bonus
he had awarded the long-time executive in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Buss had been paying off the bonus in deferred payments, much to
West's private distress.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, West had become so upset that he let it known he
wouldn't be returning to the team next season unless Buss gave him
the rest of his bonus money in one lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Buss has given in to West's demand.
</P>
<P>
   But West was not offered a new contract, and I'll be surprised
if he remains with the Lakers beyond the 1998-99 season. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Dodgers did treat Fred Claire with class in at least one
vital area. They already have cut a check to him for the remaining
two years left on his contract. ...
</P>
<P>
   Ran into Mitch Kupchak the other day at The Pyramid where he was
taking in a few FILA Summer Pro League games. Because of the NBA
lockout, the Laker general manager isn't allowed to talk to any NBA
players, coaches, assistant coaches, or player agents.
</P>
<P>
   He also can't talk about the lockout with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   So, natch, we wound up discussing the subject of the hour
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That France win over Brazil was spectacular,'' said Kupchak,
as we yawningly watched a team from China beat an American
aggregation before fewer than 100 spectators. ...
</P>
<P>
   When I met with famed Hollywood super agent Michael Ovitz Monday
afternoon at his Beverly Hills office, I was tempted to ask him if
he felt a sense of cultural guilt for being responsible for the
careers of Steven Seagal and Sly Stallone. Sheepishly, I stuck to
stadium issues. ...
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea if a stadium ever will be built in Carson. But if
the one Ovitz is proposing ever is, it will be the finest football
structure in America and Carson suddenly will become a big player
in the 21st century on the Southern California sporting landscape.
...
</P>
<P>
   Those movers and shakers in the broadcasting industry sure seem
more forgiving with Marv Albert than they were with Ben Wright and
Jimmy (The Greek) Snyder. ...
</P>
<P>
   I can't think of a more unappetizing boxing match than the one
now scheduled for January 23 between those two haplessly
over-the-hill former heavyweight champions, George Foreman and
Larry Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, come to think of it, yes I can.
</P>
<P>
   What about the fraud that Bob Arum will peddle to the public on
September 18 between Cheese Champion Oscar De La Hoya and Julio
Cesar Chavez, who's so old and pathetic that he shouldn't even be
granted a license by the Nevada State Athletic Commission. This
hoax graphically sums up just how low boxing has descended. ...
</P>
<P>
   A rarity a legitimate fight actually will take place Monday
night at the Forum when that promising heavyweight, Ed Mahone
(17-0-1), will defend his NABO heavyweight title against Daniel
Netto (25-12-l). ...
</P>
<P>
   I should be tarred, feathered and hung upside down so my brains
will return to my head for deciding to see the latest ``Lethal
Weapon'' movie. In the long and glorious history of American film,
this one might be the most poorly written, most vacuously acted,
most absurdly plotted, most embarrassing piece of high-priced dung
ever to appear on the big screen. It's an indictment of my awful
escapism tastes that I would stoop to watch such drivel that is
insulting to a human being's intelligence. ...
</P>
<P>
   Defrocked Dodger manager Bill Russell and his wife, Dr. Susan
Giarrantano, made an unexpected appearance at the Long Beach State
campus Tuesday to meet with athletic director Bill Shumard, an old
friend of Russell's from his days as a publicist with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Shumard was absent. ...
</P>
<P>
   I don't care what happens from now on, but Terry Collins gets my
vote as A.L. Manager of the Year for his keeping this pitching-poor
Angel team in first place. ..
</P>
<P>
   For Tom Lasorda's peace of mind, I'm hoping Jeff Shaw decides to
re-sign with the Dodgers and Paul Konerko turns out to be a bust in
Cincinnati. It'll be embarrassing to Tommy if neither happens. ...
</P>
<P>
   Sports agents lose me when they start whining about the plight
of jocks earning a ``mere'' $250,000 a year. ...
</P>
<P>
   Would the Angels like to have back Dante Bichette and Damion
Easley?. ...
</P>
<P>
   I don't ever recall a baseball team in my lifetime that's been
more consistent than the New York Yankees have been so far this
season. ...
</P>
<P>
   If Lawrence Phillips weren't an exceptional running back, he'd
be doing jail time for all his indiscretions with women. ...
</P>
<P>
   I remember a long ago time when I'd be excited about the start
of the NFL training camps because I covered the Los Angeles Rams
for the old Herald Examiner. Now I'm overcome by numbing
indifference. ...
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Johnnie Cochran will hold a press conference today at
halftime of the 12:15 p.m. game between Hoop Mecca and Team Cochran
at The Pyramid. He will announce he's signed to represent Illinois
State basketball star Rico Hill. O.J. Simpson isn't expected to be
present. ...
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the big NASCAR weekend at the California
Speedway for me will be Saturday in the Craftsman Truck Series
watching Jerry Glanville attempt to tool around the track. If
Glanville is as bad a driver as he is a football announcer, he'll
be thrown out for reckless driving before he finishes the first
lap. ...
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
