<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-ONDECK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: Milwaukee Brewers
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: TBS, 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: LHP Tom Glavine (12-4, 2.85; 1-0,
2.83 lifetime vs Brewers) vs. LHP Brad Woodall (4-4, 3.61; 0-0,
18.00 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Throughout his seven years in the Braves' system, Woodall
was most often compared to Glavine. He pitches low and away, lives
by the changeup and then throws for the fists every once in a
while. But the comparisons stopped once Woodall made it to Atlanta.
A force in the International League, Woodall compiled a 41-31
record with Richmond, but was 3-4 with 6.50 ERA in 18 appearances
in Atlanta, dating to 1994. He finally left the organization last
winter and was invited to the Brewers' camp as a non-roster player.
Although he didn't make the club when camp broke, he made it to
Milwaukee by May and will be making his eighth start tonight.
Woodall is 2-3 as a starter, but all three losses were sustained
when the Brewers scored two or fewer runs. His ERA is distorted,
too, after Cleveland hit him for six earned runs on July 2. Woodall
faced the Braves in two innings of relief June 2 in Milwaukee and
got blasted on an Andruw Jones solo homer and a three-run shot by
Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
