</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The center of attention
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Mark Wohlers returned to the major leagues on
Thursday from his self-induced, nearly four-week exile to the
minors, claiming he still had confidence but without the closer's
role he has filled for the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a little nervous (on returning),'' Wohlers said. ''I
felt like a rookie walking into the clubhouse for the first time.
It was embarrassing. It's embarrassing to go back down to the minor
leagues. You don't hear of too many guys who want to go back
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers left Atlanta on May 20, hoping to rediscover the control
and velocity that helped him become one of baseball's most feared
closers over the past three seasons. After nearly a month on the
farm, though, his numbers at Class AAA -- an 0-2 record with a
21.60 ERA in eight games -- created more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   ''In his own mind, he got around the plate more,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said. ''I guess you can throw those statistics
out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers says his struggles on the mound don't compare to the
personal crisis he has endured over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, while Wohlers struggled through one of the worst
outings of his career, surrendering seven earned runs, six hits,
two walks and four wild pitches in a (itsingle(ro inning against
Toledo, his mother suffered a heart attack in his hometown of
Holyoke, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ''Has it been tough?'' Wohlers asked. ''I go to these
minor-league cities and talk to these writers and you have to set
your ego aside. You've got to swallow your pride a little bit
because you know it's what's best for you. Has it been tough? Yes.
Has it been the toughest thing I've gone through in my life? Not
even close.
</P>
<P>
   ''People make a big deal about struggling on the baseball field
when I've got my mother hooked up in a hospital. It puts things in
perspective. I take my job very seriously. I take a lot of pride
out to the mound. There's nothing I'd rather do than help this team
win another world championship, but it's just a damn game.''
</P>
<P>
   How Wohlers immediately fits with the Braves is in long middle
relief, according to Cox, who says right-handed Kerry Ligtenberg,
who is 11-for-14 in save opportunities this season, will remain the
closer.
</P>
<P>
   With much of the attention focused on Wohlers, Ligtenberg has
largely gone unnoticed. He has 53 strikeouts in only 43 innings and
has converted both his save opportunites since the All-Star break.
Ligtenberg's 11 saves are the most for a Braves reliever other than
Wohlers since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kerry has about converted every save he's had,'' Cox said.
''He's been almost perfect. He's our closer right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, 27, says he wants an opportunity to pitch on a regular
basis. While there has been much debate as to whether his problems
are physical -- he went on the disabled list for 20 days in May
with a partially torn left oblique muscle -- or mental, he claims
to have the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was an inactive thing,'' Wohlers said. ''I wasn't pitching.
Sitting on the bench for a while will make you rusty. I just wanted
to pitch. I wasn't pitching here. That's what I accomplished (in
the minors) -- I pitched. ''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers pitched, but it certainly wasn't effective. After
working with special assignment scout Guy Hansen for 10 days at
Atlanta's spring training facility in Orlando, Wholers made eight
appearances in 17 days at Richmond. He gave up 18 earned runs and
17 hits in 7 2/3 innings. He walked 14 batters, threw six wild
pitches and gave up four home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best I felt is when I gave up seven runs in one inning,''
Wohlers said. ''I can't control those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers can control his future in Atlanta. With the July 31st
trade deadline approaching, Wohlers probably faces a stiff one-week
test. If he's unable to regain form, Atlanta general manager John
Schuerholz may be forced to acquire another closer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm proceeding like I'd ordinarly do because with (Wohler's
recovery) being an unknown, I can't make the assumption that
everything is going to be OK with Mark,'' Schuerholz said. ''And if
we happen to make an acquisition or a deal that brings another
player in that role to us, and Mark turns it around and gets it
going, well, then great. But if he doesn't, then we'll hopefully
have acquired somebody who could step in, or a combination of guys
who can strengthen us and the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers says he isn't through fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I struggled in rookie ball for two years,'' Wohlers said.
''There were plenty of times I could have thrown in the towel. I'm
going to work and get back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
