<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY CASTS DOUBT ON ZAMORA'S ACCOUNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Robert Tharp 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Diane Zamora's best friend thought Zamora
was lying when she said David Graham ``proved his love'' by killing
Adrianne Jones, the friend testified Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination on the second day of Graham's capital
murder trial, Kristina Mason said she twice told a grand jury panel
shortly after Graham's and Zamora's arrests that she did not
believe Zamora's story. Mason said Zamora confided to her about the
slaying days after Jones was found dead.
</P>
<P>
   Under direct questioning by prosecutor Mike Parrish, Mason said
she was shocked and simply did not want to believe her best
friend's story. But during defense cross-examination, which at
times was heated, Mason said that Zamora had told her she often got
attention by making up stories when she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the truth is at this time. ... I'm still
trying to figure out the truth, what happened that night,'' Mason
said. ``I've already been told by my best friend what happened that
night. I just want to know for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason said she did not ``begin telling the truth'' to the grand
jury until she was threatened with aggravated perjury charges. But
even after that point in her testimony, Mason told the grand jury
panel that she did not believe Zamora.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed that she believed her story, but I didn't believe
her,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's grand jury testimony included statements that Graham, a
former Air Force Academy cadet, and Zamora, a former Naval Academy
midshipman, lured Jones to a field in Grand Prairie, Texas, where
Zamora struck her with a weight and demanded, ``Shoot her, kill
her, shoot her'' to Graham after Jones stumbled away.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 20, faces life in prison if convicted. Zamora was
convicted of capital murder in February for her role in Jones'
death and is serving a life sentence. All three were students at
Mansfield High School at the time of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Dan Cogdell said at the start of the trial that
he will prove that Zamora alone killed the 16-year-old Mansfield
High School sophomore and that Graham was not at the crime scene
and only covered up for his former fiance.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony earlier Thursday, Dr. Marc Krouse, deputy chief
Tarrant County medical examiner, described the wounds Jones
suffered, including a severe skull fracture caused by a heavy
object and two head wounds from a gun fired at a distance of less
than two inches.
</P>
<P>
   Krouse testified that the fracture was not likely to have been
caused while Jones sat inside a car, which is the way it is
detailed in Graham's and Zamora's statements to investigators.
Krouse said the pattern of the wound shows that it was probably
caused by the butt of the 9mm handgun used to kill Jones. He said
that Zamora is too small and not strong enough to generate the
force for such a blow, which pushed bone fragments one inch into
Jones' brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a heavy blow by a large person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Krouse agreed with Cogdell that Zamora
could have generated enough force for such a blow if she had been
enraged and boosted by adrenalin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person under the influence of adrenalin can accomplish some
amazing things; he admitted that much,'' Cogdell said outside the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Krouse also testified that Zamora's fingers are too thin to
match finger-shaped bruising found around Jones' neck. Under
cross-examination, Krouse acknowledged that Zamora's fingers would
have been wide enough had they been wrapped in bandages for an
injury that she had received in a.MDNM/ car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   In other testimony, Grand Prairie Police Sgt. Brad Geary
recounted a 4 a.m. phone call from a Grand Prairie detective who
had Graham in custody. Geary said the detective handed the phone to
Graham, who explained where he had hidden the handgun used in the
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Graham stated to me on the telephone that the gun was
well hidden in the attic under an eave, and we'd have an extremely
hard time finding it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said he plans to present more witnesses Friday and to
continue building his case through the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
