<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gailey: `We've got a lot of work to do'
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Before the new coach guarantees a spot in this
season's Super Bowl, he wanted to make something clear about the
first day of training camp at Midwestern State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to call off any practices,'' Chan Gailey said
after a two- hour workout. ``We've got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The all-work, no-play leader of the Dallas Cowboys survived his
first day of summer camp. The coach does not dream about the NFL's
title game six months from now.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey practically ignored the pageantry of the opening practice
in Wichita Falls. He hardly noticed the blue-and-white balloons
that hovered over the practice field or the opening remarks by the
city's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   This was a day the city has been looking forward to. About 2,200
fans lined two practice fields, cheered for their favorite players,
asked for autographs and watched a team that struggled with a 6-10
record last season.
</P>
<P>
   Players wore shorts and T-shirts, hoping to beat the heat. Some
spectators who sat on metal bleachers did not adapt well to the
temperature, which reached 101 degrees by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Eight people were treated for heat-related problems. Two were
taken to a local hospital, suffering from heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few cool moments,'' Gailey joked later, ``when
the temperature got under 100.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys consider their monthlong stay in Wichita Falls a
business trip. They remember what it was like to lose their last
five games last season, memories they hope to erase by the time
camp ends Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who's talking, the Cowboys will have another losing
season or make a serious run through the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could go either way,'' cornerback Kevin Smith said. ``The
players who have won here have to look at themselves. For people
like Troy (Aikman), Michael (Irvin), myself and Darren (Woodson),
it's personal.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency of camp has been felt by others. Running back Emmitt
Smith is so bitter about last season, he won't talk publicly about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was last year,'' Smith said. ``We don't talk about last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith did note obvious changes with the Cowboys. No one
mentioned Barry Switzer's name, but his resignation and the hiring
of Gailey have put a new spin on training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's impression of Gailey?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not trying to be overbearing with the team,'' Aikman
said. ``It's not like he's trying to put his stamp on us. He's made
it very clear how things are going to be run. He's provided some
direction already.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, without question, is organized. Before camp started, he
scripted every minute of all 34 practice sessions, including
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The adulation the fans shower upon the players is not one of
Gailey's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of it. If I say it's good, that's not going to
change anything,'' Gailey said. ``We are the Dallas Cowboys and
there is a sense of excitement and anticipation. I don't worry
about it. This is just part of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, for one, does not crave attention. He has informed team
officials that he will not conduct press conferences after
practices for the rest of camp. Instead, he will have one
question-and-answer session per day, in mid- afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if this was a ``significant'' day for him, Gailey
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for me,'' he said. ``It's significant for the team,
though. This was our first day of work in our journey.''
</P>
<P>
   The players appear to like Gailey's serious approach. Under
Switzer, many players complained that practices were too relaxed.
Players often would break team rules and not worry about
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Chan Gailey here is fantastic,'' defensive tackle Chad
Hennings said.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprised person at camp was 7-year-old Sam Woodall. A
security guard handed the boy a yellow card with Aikman's name
typed on it midway through practice. The guard told him that he was
one of 100 kids who would be allowed to get Aikman's autograph
after practice.
</P>
<P>
   Woodall, his face beaming, responded, ``Wow, you're not kidding
me, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
