<HEADLINE>
SHAREHOLDERS FIND SOME LEVERAGE IN MERGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the pace of mergers and acquisitions of fund management
companies red hot, shareholder activists want to make sure
investors share in any resulting profits. And now one closed-end
fund activist has found a way to help make sure they do so.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is simple. When fund companies are acquired, management
must ask shareholders to approve new advisory agreements. That
gives shareholders leverage to force management's hand.
</P>
<P>
   George Karpus, an investment adviser in Pittsford, N.Y., who
specializes in closed-end bond funds, used this shareholders'
leverage in a recent challenge involving six of the nine taxable
bond funds run by Piper Capital Management. ``If they're going to
make all that money in the merger,'' he said, ``they should take
care of the shareholders, too.'' Karpus, who owns significant
stakes in seven Piper funds, added, ``Now we've got a lever.''
</P>
<P>
   Closed-end fund experts say his shrewd maneuvering is breaking
ground in the industry, as increasingly sophisticated investors
look for ways to challenge management companies when shares trade
at discounts to the value of their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mutual funds, whose unlimited numbers of shares are
bought and sold at net asset value, closed-end funds have a set
number of shares that are bought and sold on stock markets.
Although shares can trade at a premium to the value of the
securities held by the funds, they typically trade at discounts,
and when the discount widens, shareholders take notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wide discounts are attracting more sophisticated investors to
closed-end funds,'' said Cecilia L. Gondor, executive vice
president of Thomas J. Herzfeld Advisors, closed-end fund
specialists in Miami. ``It is inevitable that we will see
increasingly creative ways of persuading management to narrow
persistent discounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Piper's parent, the Piper Jaffray Companies,
agreed to be acquired by U.S. Bancorp, requiring Piper Capital
Management to ask shareholders in each of its funds to approve a
new advisory contract. In mid-January, Karpus filed a shareholder
proposal recommending that his company, Karpus Investment
Management, be hired as replacement manager for six Piper funds _
American Select Portfolio, American Strategic Income Portfolios II
and III, American Opportunity Income, American government Income
Portfolio and the Americas Income Trust _ setting the stage for a
proxy battle. His goal was to force Piper to deal with the
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   The funds had long traded at discounts; Americas Income Trust,
for example, had a discount as deep as 19 percent last year, while
those for the American Select Portfolio and Strategic Income
Portfolio II hit 15 percent, Ms. Gondor said.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of a still-unresolved shareholder fight involving the
Zurich Group's acquisition of Scudder, Piper sought to avoid a
similar proxy fight with Karpus' group by announcing in March steps
that management would take to narrow the discounts in the American
Strategic Income Portfolios II and III and in the American Select
Portfolio _ provided that shareholders approve the new investment
contracts related to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Piper would ask the Securities and Exchange Commission to allow
each fund to make annual repurchase offers of up to 10 percent of
the outstanding shares if the discount exceeded 5 percent in a
specified 12-week period. Otherwise, the funds would buy up to 10
percent of each of the funds' outstanding shares in December 1999
and December 2001, if the average discount exceeded 5 percent
during the 12 calendar weeks preceding Oct. 1 of those years.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to deal with discounts is to open the funds. In
April, the Piper board approved the conversion of three funds _
American government Income, American government Income Portfolio
and American Opportunity Income _ into a single open-end fund. It
also approved a plan to fold the Highlander Income fund and
Americas Income Trust into a new open-end fund, the First American
Strategic Income fund.
</P>
<P>
   In response to these moves, Karpus' group withdrew its
shareholder proposals.
</P>
<P>
   On July 10, shareholders overwhelmingly approved the new
advisory contracts for Americas Income Trust and Highlander Income.
Shareholder votes on new advisory contracts for the remaining seven
funds are scheduled for August.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
