<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-LICENSES-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. REGENTS END LIFETIME LICENSING FOR TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The New York State Board of Regents voted
Thursday to end lifetime licensing for teachers, but, bowing to
pressure from the teachers' union, it passed the barest of
standards for renewing those licenses. Teachers will have only to
take continuing education classes, with no current standards for
grading.
</P>
<P>
   The measure falls far short of the state Education Department's
original proposal to evaluate the performance of classroom teachers
independently every five years.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal, made by a Regents committee two years ago, would
have given New York the strictest licensing standard in the nation.
But the performance evaluations were eliminated after pressure from
the state teachers' unions, a potent lobbying force in Albany,
which argued that the state was not financially or logistically
able to evaluate its 200,000 classroom teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The new continuing education measure will apply to teachers who
will get five-year state licenses beginning in September 2000. For
renewal, teachers will have to take 175 hours of continuing
education.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scaling back the requirements, the measure
provides a potential financial boon for unions, giving them
millions of dollars more for themselves and their members, because
unions are paid to provide many of the classes and because school
districts pay teachers to attend them. (In New York City, they get
$13.40 an hour.)
</P>
<P>
   Union officials and regents hailed the new licensing rules.
State Education Commissioner Richard Mills hailed the regents' plan
as a valuable tool for raising standards. ``The regents have issued
a challenge to well-prepared, able committed people who should be
teachers,'' he said at a news conference Thursday afternoon. ``I
hope they have heard the call. And I hope they respond to the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But some school board representatives and school superintendents
said they did not go far enough. And New York City Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew, through a spokeswoman, raised a concern that
the measure might cost ``several hundred million dollars over the
course of the next five years,'' which the Legislature has not
appropriated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In trying to overhaul teacher licensing, New York follows a
national movement to re-examine how teachers are trained and
monitored through their career. New York has long been among a
handful of states to issue lifetime licenses. Most states require
teachers to renew their teaching certificates every few years by
taking college courses or professional development seminars,
according to the Education Commission of the States, a nonprofit
policy and research organization in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The regents also voted to close teachers' colleges whose
graduates have trouble passing the state teachers' exams, a measure
that threatens several City University campuses, and they raised
the academic credentials to be required of new teachers. Those who
begin teaching in September 2000 will need to earn a master's
degree within two years of starting; they now have five years.
</P>
<P>
   And the regents also gave state education officials more grounds
to suspend or revoke teaching licenses, including ``incompetence,
neglect of duty and insubordination.'' Currently, state education
officials can revoke a license only for ``lack of good moral
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally districts try to dismiss teachers for incompetence
first, through Civil Service proceedings. Such actions are rare: in
the 1995-96 school year, the latest for which statistics were
available, school officials sought to dismiss 156 teachers, and 24
of them were found to be incompetent, according to department
spokesman Alan Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said that improving teachers' performance was
important as the state raised academic requirements. ``The plan is
a step forward in raising standards for students,'' said Antonia
Cortese, the vice president of New York State United Teachers, the
umbrella group for the state's teachers' unions. ``It moves the
whole system to recognize that it has to invest its teachers. They
are closest to the students.''
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of
Teachers, the New York City teachers' union, said: ``It now forces
the districts to offer professional development in a meaningful way
and related to what teachers are doing in the classrooms. It's more
like the things we have been advocating for and we've been
offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Kinley, the acting executive director of the New York State
School Boards Association, called the plan a ``good first step''
toward maintaining teacher accountability and high standards. But
he added that his group wanted the measure to apply to people now
teaching, not just the next generation of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the current law, this is as much as the Regents could
do, so we're pleased,'' he said. ``But we're going to continue to
hit the Legislature for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing education courses are generally technical courses
ranging from classroom discipline to developing curriculum. They
are now voluntary, but teachers have an incentive to take them
because they get graduated pay increases as they attain set levels
of credits. Under the new rules, individual school districts must
pick up the cost of the additional courses instead of the teachers
themselves, as was often the case in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the professional development centers of the
United Federation of Teachers gave classes to some 12,000 of its
70,000 active members last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the UFT is a virtual university,'' Ms. Weingarten
said. ``We look to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Johnson of Long Island, who is co-chairman of the
Regents' Task Force on Teaching, which drafted and then modified
the new rules, said state officials estimated that the new
requirements would cost about $100 million a year. But he noted
that much of that could be paid for with money that the Legislature
had already appropriated for school staff development.
</P>
<P>
   The Regents' Task Force on Teaching had initially proposed that
teachers' licenses be renewed based on performance evaluations in
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In a draft proposal in the spring of 1997, the regents
recommended that teachers be evaluated by a team of experts from
outside each school. That measure faced vigorous opposition from
the state teachers' union, who argued that principals should
continue to evaluate teachers and move to dismiss them, if they are
found to be incompetent, but that should not affect their license
to teach elsewhere in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, after a series of public meetings around
the state and intensive lobbying by union officials, the Regents
scrapped the idea and introduced the continuing education measure,
under which a teacher can lose his or her license for failing to
complete the required hours of professional development.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rules passed Friday, state education officials
must also establish standards by which teachers are evaluated each
year by the local school district. Those who perform poorly must
undergo remedial training through a state-supervised plan.
Currently, teachers have to be evaluated each year by the district,
but the process is widely viewed as toothless.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also imposes stiffer requirements on teacher
education programs at colleges and universities throughout New York
state. Beginning in 1999, the state will decertify programs if
fewer than 80 percent of their students pass the three licensing
exams given by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 25 of the state's 113 teacher education programs
would have failed the new requirement, including 8 colleges in the
City University system. For instance, at Medgar Evers College, 41
percent passed the test in 1996-1997, and 52 percent passed at York
College; but 88 percent passed at Queens College, 83 percent at
Staten Island and 78 percent at Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   The regents' plan also calls for the creation of a teacher
recruitment program that offers scholarships to graduate and
undergraduate students in exchange for their commitment to teach in
impoverished schools. It also offers $10,000 bonuses for teachers
who agree to teach in such schools. But in both cases, the
financing would have to be approved by the governor and the state
Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
