<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 WOODS, HUSTON SHARE FIRST ROUND LEAD AT BRITISH OPEN WITH 65's   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Earlier this month, Tiger Woods borrowed a
putter from his close friend, Mark O'Meara. Woods still hasn't
returned it. And after Thursday's performance by Woods, O'Meara may
never get his putter back.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying his strongest round at a major this year, Woods shot a
five-under-par 65 and shared the lead with John Huston after the
opening round of the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Couples, a two-time winner this year, was in a three-way
tie for third place at 66, along with Loren Roberts and Nick Price,
a former British Open champion (1994) who was paired with Woods
Thursday. Davis Love 3d, Robert Allenby, Brad Faxon, Fredrick
Jacobson and Vijay Singh were in a five-way tie for sixth place at
67.
</P>
<P>
   With a huge gallery following his every move through the dunes
and tall grass at Royal Birkdale Golf Club, Woods looked
comfortable, confident and in control of his game, giving a strong
indication that, at the age of 22, he may be ready to win his
second major.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Woods is in contention he adds electricity to the
surroundings, but Thursday amid that charged atmosphere he showed
patience, strong course management and a solid putting stroke that
allowed him to capitalize on birdie opportunities. And with
temperatures in the high 60s, only a mild breeze and bright
sunshine, the leaders took advantage of conditions that were much
more favorable than earlier in the week, when the wind gusted to 40
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Woods is the world's No. 1-ranked player, many
wondered if he had the experience to win a major on a course that
demands precision and creative shot-making. But Thursday, Woods,
the 1997 Masters champion, looked at ease, and his improved short
game and distance control were critical. He used his driver only
four times, relying on irons off the tee to keep the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an evolution process that every player goes
through,'' said Woods, who had seven birdies and just two bogeys.
``Any player back in their early 20s and teens hits the ball pretty
hard. As they get older, they learn to control their game. I'm no
exception to that _ still learning a lot of different shots. Over
all, I'm very pleased with my progress.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woods wins, he will owe a thank you to O'Meara, his Orlando,
Fla., neighbor and this year's Masters champion, who is one of the
game's best putters. During a practice round in Orlando last week,
the day before Woods and O'Meara left for Europe, O'Meara lent
Woods a backup Ping putter. O'Meara shot a 63 that day, but he
still lost money to Woods, who shot a 62.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has been using the putter ever since, and Thursday, he
used it to make a 12-foot birdie putt on No. 5, a 20-foot birdie
putt on No. 7 and a 30-foot birdie putt on No. 13. He followed that
with birdies on two par 5's, the 15th and the 17th. No wonder Woods
won't part with the putter.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the practice green yesterday, Mark asked Tiger what would
happen if somebody stole his putter and he needed his backup putter
back,'' said Butch Harmon, Woods' coach. ``Tiger says, `If somebody
steals your putter, you'll have to go to the pro shop and buy
another one, because I'm not giving this one up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Huston was the only player who could keep pace with Woods, and
his round featured one of the torrid stretches that have marked
Huston's career. After making nine consecutive pars on the front
nine, Huston caught fire on the back nine, making birdies at Nos.
10, 11 and 12, then finishing with a bang _ a 40-foot putt for
eagle on the par-5 17th, followed by another birdie at No. 18, when
he hit a gorgeous 7-iron approach shot out of the rough to within
four feet.
</P>
<P>
   Huston, a low-profile, 37-year-old veteran who has won four
times on the PGA Tour, is having the best year of his career,
showing an ability to shoot low numbers. While winning the Hawaiian
Open in February, Huston set the PGA Tour 72-hole scoring record
(28 under). He has contended consistently since January, when he
began sleeping on a magnetic mattress cover, which alleviated the
pain caused by tendinitis in his right wrist and bursitis in his
left shoulder. Huston travels with the mattress cover, and
considering how well he has played, who can blame him?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to increase your blood flow, so it heals the
body faster,'' Huston said. ``It took a couple, three days before I
started feeling no pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The only times Woods felt pain Thursday occurred on No. 12, when
he missed a three-foot putt for his first bogey, and on No. 18,
when he missed an eight-foot par putt that cost him sole possession
of the lead. But Woods showed an ability to escape trouble,
avoiding the calamities that cost him during last year's British
Open at Royal Troon Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Despite shooting a 64 on Saturday last year, Woods finished 12
strokes behind Justin Leonard, and Woods' demise could be traced to
four holes _ a quadruple bogey, two triple bogeys and a double
bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Woods was far more resilient. On No. 2, after hitting
his drive into the deep right rough, Woods hit perhaps his best
shot of the day, a remarkable 9-iron from a terrible lie that
carried about 120 yards over a greenside bunker and stopped 10 feet
from the hole, allowing Woods to make a par-saving putt.
</P>
<P>
   And when Woods could use his power to his advantage, he did. On
the par-4, 411-yard ninth hole he unloaded his longest drive of the
day, a 380-yard rocket that landed just a few yards short of the
green, leading to a birdie. It was an impressive round of power and
patience that the astute British fans appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of golf yet to be played, and many strong
players are in contention. But after failing to contend on Sunday
at both the Masters and the United States Open this year, Woods
opened the year's third major by immediately making his presence
felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ovation I got at 18, I haven't had that in a long time,''
Woods said. ``It felt really good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
