<SLUG> BC-POSTAL-AD-COLUMN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: THE POSTAL SERVICE TAKES RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service is one of the most recognizable national
symbols, so if it were to lend its name to a single team sport,
that sport would naturally be _ cycling?
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps cycling _ that is, bicycle racing _ is not the
first sport that leaps to mind. But the Postal Service believes
that putting its name on the only American-based squad to compete
in the Super Bowl of cycling _ the Tour de France _ makes a lot of
sense.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that cycling is popular. The 2,400-mile-long
Tour, which began last Saturday and finishes Aug. 2 with the
traditional sprint down the Champs Elysees in Paris, is televised
in 120 countries and is reckoned by its organizers to be the
third-most-watched sporting event after the World Cup soccer
tournament and the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Postal Service, professional cycling is
just not that widely followed in the United States, where most of
its customers happen to be.
</P>
<P>
   While interest in cycling has been growing in this country since
the Postal Service first began sponsoring the team, U.S. Postal,
two years ago, it is still far from the national passion it is in
Europe. In many American newspapers, the Tour is still relegated to
the back pages of the sports sections _ if it receives any coverage
at all.
</P>
<P>
   And it does not help that U.S. Postal's marquee rider, Lance
Armstrong, a former world champion who returned to racing this year
after a bout with testicular cancer, is still not strong enough to
ride in the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The team's other backers, which include Visa International and
Trek Bicycle Corp., make perfect sense. So why did the Postal
Service choose to become the team's title sponsor, paying more than
$1 million a year for the privilege?
</P>
<P>
   ``The bike has been part of postal history and tradition for
quite a long time,'' said Margot Myers, a Postal Service
spokeswoman. ``We still have quite a few letter carriers that use
bikes to deliver mail in many parts of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A more compelling reason may be that $1 million for the kind of
exposure the Postal Service is getting is cheap even if a
relatively small number of Americans will notice.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service team is already generating more attention
than expected because of the surprisingly strong showing of George
Hincapie, the U.S. national road racing champion, who is currently
second in the Tour's overall standings, only seven seconds behind
the leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service sponsors several baseball teams like the
Yankees and the Mets. And it could hardly resist doing a promotion
with the Utah Jazz star Karl Malone, who is known as the Mailman.
But a leaguewide deal with baseball, football or basketball is
beyond its means.
</P>
<P>
   Not so cycling. ``This is really our franchise sport,'' said
Robert McKenna, manager of sponsorships for the Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsorship deal with Montgomery Sports, which owns and
manages the cycling team, was put together by D&AMP;F Group, a
corporate sports marketing agency in Washington. When the Postal
Service was first presented with the idea in 1995, it was looking
for a way to promote its expanding international services, such as
express packages sent overseas and logistics services for customers
that mail many packages abroad like the catalog marketer L.L. Bean.
</P>
<P>
   Using the themes of teamwork and speed, Young &AMP; Rubicam
Advertising created a television spot featuring cyclists wearing
the U.S. Postal team jerseys cycling in different locales around
the world. It ran last year on Walt Disney Co.'s ESPN sports
channel, which showed highlights of each of the race's daily
stages.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because the U.S. Postal team competes in numerous races around
the United States, the Postal Service has also used the events to
build morale among its own employees and to reach out to various
communities.
</P>
<P>
   In January, when the team held a training camp in Southern
California, 15 Postal Service employees who are amateur racers got
to ride with Armstrong and the rest of the team to the main postal
processing facility in San Diego, where they were feted at a kind
of pep rally with other employees.
</P>
<P>
   But even those benefits did not seem to justify the expense
internally, Ms. Myers said. This year, the Postal Service assigned
a special sales team to use the sponsorship to drum up business.
</P>
<P>
   Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities, the Nationsbank division that
spawned Montgomery Sports, transferred some of its delivery
business to the Postal Service. Nashbar, a catalog company that is
another of the team's sponsors, ended up giving the Postal Service
new business that Nashbar says will amount to $1.1 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have contracts in place that are for sales worth more the
annual fee for the sponsorship,'' Ms. Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Postal Service has decided not to buy time
this year on ESPN, which will again have daily coverage of the
Tour, or on ABC, which will broadcast weekend coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN coverage would have been nice, but we would have been
overextended,'' McKenna said. Instead, the money will be spent
sponsoring more professional races in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That has not discouraged ESPN from focusing a lot of its
coverage on U.S. Postal. Hincapie's early success has helped lift
the ratings for the cable network's Tour coverage by one-tenth of a
point, to about 400,000 homes, an ESPN spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is even more visibility for U.S. Postal's snazzy blue
jerseys emblazoned with the same eagle logo found on the uniforms
of thousands of American letter carriers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
