<HEADLINE>
BUSH REFUSES TO FILE DONOR LIST ELECTRONICALLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Since winning election in 1994, Gov. George W.
Bush has refused to file an electronic copy of his political donor
list with the Texas Ethics Commission so any Texan with a computer
can see who gave Bush contributions totaling more than $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as governor, and the Legislature also have not yet
implemented a 1991 law that requires the ethics commission to make
it possible for Texans with access to a computer to see who is
giving money to any of the state's politicians.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in Florida, where Bush's brother Jeb is running for
governor, the Department of State decided to set up a campaign
database in 1995, and it was up and running by the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Now, anybody living in Houston or Dallas or Amarillo can log on
to the Florida Department of State internet site at
http://www.dos.state.fl.us and see who is giving money to Jeb Bush
or any other Florida politician. Jeb Bush voluntarily gives his
report to the Florida elections office in electronic form.
</P>
<P>
   But anybody in Houston or Dallas or Amarillo who wants to see
George W. Bush's lists of political financiers has to drive or fly
to Austin to look at a 30,000-page paper copy at the ethics
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates in Texas do file electronically, but several
others, in addition to Bush, do not.
</P>
<P>
   For someone to spend one second looking at each page of Bush's
reports, it would require more than eight hours of reading. Bush's
reports contain almost 30 times as many pages as a Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a paper copy of Bush's report would cost a citizen about
$3,000, according to the ethics commission staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign offered an electronic copy of his most recent
report to the news media this week, but only if reporters signed a
contract agreeing not to share the electronic filing with anyone
else, including their readers or listeners in the voting public.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle refused to sign such an agreement limiting
its ability to disclose what essentially is public information.
</P>
<P>
   State law only requires campaigns to turn in their finance
reports on paper, but the ethics commission accepts electronic
reports. Those reports are posted on the Internet at
http://www.ethics.state.tx.us _ and many statewide and legislative
candidates are filing those reports.
</P>
<P>
   When he was running for governor in 1994, Bush opposed filing
his reports electronically. But then he submitted two reports to
the commission under pressure from the state's news media. Those
filings ceased as soon as Bush won office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fully disclosed all of our information so that it is
available for the public to review, but not for others to abuse,''
said Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker declined to answer any questions on the subject or
explain what she meant by ``abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of ethics reform in 1991, the Legislature passed a
law requiring that a searchable campaign finance database be up and
running at the ethics commission by January 1992. That database
still does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Many legislators have pressured the commission not to create the
database, and in 1995, both the Texas Democratic and Republican
parties sought to have the law eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the commission's eight members, including the chairman,
are Bush appointees. The others are appointed by the lieutenant
governor and House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida saved money when it set up the electronic system, said
Sandy Brill, data processing manager for the state elections
division.
</P>
<P>
   Brill said state prison inmates type in the data on special
interests and political action committees and state employees
handle data processing on candidate filings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee you it was a cost savings,'' Brill said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Texas's top four races _ governor, lieutenant governor,
attorney general and comptroller _ the only candidates who have not
agreed to file their reports electronically with the ethics
commission are Bush, Republican comptroller candidate Carole
Rylander and attorney general candidates John Cornyn, the
Republican, and Jim Mattox, the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic gubernatorial candidate Garry Mauro files his reports
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lieutenant governor candidate John Sharp was one of
the first candidates in Texas to give electronic copies of his
reports to the commission. But he stopped in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp spokesman Kelly Fero said the lapse was an oversight and
that all the missing reports will be given to the commission by
early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lieutenant governor candidate Rick Perry has never
reported electronically. Spokesman Ray Sullivan said Perry had just
never thought about filing electronically but that Thursday the
campaign was sending the commission a computer disk with all
contributions made in the current election.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Mattox said his computer was not set up to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic comptroller candidate Paul Hobby gives a computer
copy of his report to the ethics commission. Rylander, who did file
electronically in 1994, does not plan to do so this time. Rylander
campaign manager Scott McClellan said she fears the list will be
used by direct mail companies to solicit donations to other
causes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
