<HEADLINE>
NBC AND USA NETWORKS SAID TO HALT TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives at NBC and USA Networks Inc. held exploratory talks
earlier this month about a possible merger, but the talks fell
through, several executives close to the companies said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC spokeswoman declined to comment Thursday and USA
Networks' chairman, Barry Diller, was out of the country and did
not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   But the executives close to the companies said that a possible
merger between NBC, which is owned by General Electric, and USA
Networks, which is partly owned by Seagram Co., never got as far as
full-fledged negotiations in part because the deal was opposed by
Seagram and another USA Networks shareholder, Liberty Media, a
company controlled by Tele-Communications Inc. The talks were
reported Friday by The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Diller, whose company owns television stations, the Home
Shopping Network and Universal Television, has long sought a
television network. General Electric, meanwhile, has seen profits
in the network television business eroded by cable and the
Internet. NBC's future growth potential is especially clouded by
higher costs for ``ER'' and football, among other factors.
</P>
<P>
   A stock merger of NBC and USA Networks would probably have been
a tax-free transaction, experts noted Friday. But there was no
indication that General Electric had a plan to put the network up
for auction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
