<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(VERSION INCLUDES NOTES) 
NEW CHANNEL NEARS KICKOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spread out across Jantonio Turner's desk Thursday
morning were a half-dozen logo samples that he ordered up from a
nearby graphics arts house.
</P>
<P>
   The Football Network, a 24-hour-a-day cable channel that Turner
(no relation to Ted) has spent piecing together 24 hours a day for
the last two years, already needs a new symbol. Turner, who drew
the original on his Macintosh, is taking another impromptu survey.
</P>
<P>
   Some read ``TFN'' in bold letters. Some are a little softer with
the name spelled out over a stylish football swoosh in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll probably be a combination of some of these,'' Turner
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, however, decisions aren't made slowly. The
kickoff for his cable channel, in one form or another, will be
Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   That's about a year after Turner had originally planned, and not
soon enough for most football fans. And, he says, ``this time it
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He's easy to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, a 30-year-old TV producer who could be mistaken for
actor LeVar Burton, looks more like a wide-eyed 18-year-old who
just landed in Los Angeles looking for a proverbial shot at the big
time.
</P>
<P>
   He's honestly exuberant when he talks about all the things this
new channel can provide to viewers. He's got a pen and paper handy
to scribble down any suggestion for a show. And he's realistic when
he spells out how some things can't happen overnight, resigned to
the fact he could be on only a few hours a week to start with
buying time on another network just as some other cable channels
(such as BET and QVC) got started.
</P>
<P>
   Going with a slogan that ``Enough is NEVER enough!'' Turner's
plan for creating what some are already calling heaven on earth
seems to be, at this point, a touchdown waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Turner has avoided many of the potholes that trip upstart
networks and could well in fact be viewed in the years to come as
the visionary who took the simple idea _ if there's a Golf Channel,
why can't there be a football channel? _ and made it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, the strength is in the power of the idea,'' said
Turner, who moved this week into a new office building just east of
the Beverly Center. ``And as long as it seems to take things to
happen, in TV, when they do happen, they happen very quickly. I
could see us maybe making a splash from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   With what he calls his ``seed money,'' Turner has planted the
idea into sponsors that this can work, and his next step is to do
the same with cable operators. Unlike the pratfall that ESPN West
took this week because it couldn't get channel space on local cable
systems, Turner has already established a relationship with a
nationwide distribution cable co-op known as NCTC, which represents
more than 5,300 cable systems with 8.5 million subscribers. Small
dish companies such as DirecTV and EchoStar should have no problem
providing room.
</P>
<P>
   Turner tried raising private funds for the venture. But since
making his channel a public corporation four months ago, his goal
of a $10 million startup budget doesn't appear as out of reach as
it once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting this together has almost been like making a movie,''
said Turner, who has been in L.A. the last seven years working in
cable TV production and small-budget films. ``You learn to stretch
every dollar from people who invest in your project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been living a dollar above the poverty line for a while
now, but I feel I've educated myself to a point that we can do what
we say we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   From a programming structure, the grand plan is to break it down
into five major areas:
</P>
<P>
   _Because NFL and major colleges are locked into rights fees from
the most established networks, game coverage would likely be
limited to anything below NCAA Division I, but not excluding
semipro, high school and youth leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Turner wouldn't mind sponsoring the first-ever national high
school championship, and a ``Little Bowl,'' which would be the Pop
Warner equivalent to the Little League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Tape-delayed games and classic NFL and college games are also
being sought through the teams and schools (such as UCLA and USC).
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean a school such as Cal State Northridge, currently
locked into a Big Sky contract with Fox Sports Northwest, could see
some air time?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kind of games we want,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   _News shows, not unlike what ESPN has produced as ancillary
programming to its NFL and college game shows, for all levels.
</P>
<P>
   _Events such as Notre Dame's weekly press conference, NFL owners
meetings and awards banquets.
</P>
<P>
   _Unique shows, such as former player profiles, instructional
video and lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   _Movies. How many times can you watch ``Brian's Song''?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much to go around,'' Turner said. ``And we're not
even in competition with the networks for these things. We want to
be known as a complement.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's to keep this niche channel from being scratched before
it can deliver?
</P>
<P>
   If enthusiasm was all it took to get started, Turner, a former
backup quarterback on his high school team, would have been calling
signals the Saturday a few years ago when he turned on his TV set
to watch NFL highlights and was stuck with some three-minute clips
that left him completely unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   If molding a dream is all it takes to keep one motivated, the
economics major from the University of Virginia says he's
well-versed in ``the distribution of scarce resources for the
maximum benefit of all.'' Meaning Turner shouldn't have a problem
turning this into something very tangible.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   -- Why was Keith Olbermann touring the Fox Sports Net studios in
Century City earlier this week? Is he already beyond miserable with
his career in purgatory at MSNBC, even though it gets him an
occasional appearance on NBC's occasional baseball coverage? Will
the former KTLA and KCBS sportscaster who evolved into an ESPN
``SportsCenter'' icon consider a return to L.A.? Is Fox willing to
forgive him for snippy comments he made recently about Fox's News
Channel? Where's the list of potential designated drivers?
</P>
<P>
   -- Another chance for Marv Albert. He knows he's been a bad boy.
He's been spanked enough. Madison Square Garden Network was right
to take him back, but apparently it has to deal with another small
controversy. Reports are that several New York restaurants, upset
with Albert's return, will continue to post signs in their windows
stating ``No MSG.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -- If you must call it a ``major victory'' for Fox that Disney
has to take down the ESPN West from the right-field wall at Edison
Field, so be it. But that's like saying the U.S. won a war against
Canada because the Canadians finally accepted that it couldn't
persuade Montana to become a new province. In today's messy cable
geography, ESPN West was a nice idea but two years too late. No one
really wins in this situation because viewers are stuck in a cable
world of, believe it or not, restriction. Can't we all just all get
along now?
</P>
<P>
   -- There he is, Mr. Football Guy. We see now why ABC's newest
``Monday Night Football'' analyst, Boomer Esiason, was such a find.
The network already has him crossing over to audibilize as co-host
of the Miss America Pageant on Sept. 19. In recent years, we hear
the pageant had considered he-man Frank Gifford as co-host, but
they could never get a commitment once the optional swimsuit
competition ruling went into effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
