<HEADLINE>
ENRON BUYS STAKE IN FAST-GROWING BRAZILIAN POWER DISTRIBUTOR  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KAREN SANTOS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Enron Corp. announced Thursday that it has agreed to
pay about $1.3 billion for a large stake in one of Brazil's
fastest-growing electricity distributors to expand its presence in
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Enron is buying a controlling interest in state-owned &UR;  &LR; Elektro
Eletricidade e Servicos SA, which distributes electricity in Sao
Paulo, the company said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price is nearly double the $640 million price tag
set as the minimum by the Brazilian government and 30 percent
higher than analysts' expectations, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Enron beat out four other bidders also vying for ownership of
Elektro. The second-highest bidder, Eletricidade de Portugal SA,
offered 1.2 billion reais, or $1.03 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to become the first international natural gas and
electric utility,'' said David Garcia, an energy industry analyst
with Everen Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Enron has several other ventures in South America, including a
share in a natural gas pipeline that runs from Bolivia to Brazil.
It also has other stakes in energy companies and thermoelectric
plants in seven Brazilian states as well as four other Latin
American countries, including Argentina and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime ... a company is protected from competition, it
becomes fat and sloppy,'' Garcia said, referring to the  &UR;  &LR; state-run
electric company. ``There's a lot of fat and slop that can be
eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said that the company will have to provide better service
than its predecessor to earn the trust of locals. He said several
places in Sao Paulo suffer from occasional problems such as
shortages and worn transformers. He also said that much of the
underground wiring system needs repair after years of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has ``a stable and robust economy _ there's a demand for
energy,'' said Steve Schuler, president of Houston Brazil, which is
the business development division of Houston Industries in Brazil.
Houston Industries is part owner of Light Servicos de Eletricidade
SA, an electric utility in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Industries faced the challenge of transforming the
dismal performance of Light, which had a reputation for poor
service and blackouts, according to a Wall Street Journal article
published in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had an extremely hot summer,'' in Rio, Schuler
said. ``There was residential growth in the summer months of 22
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Light faced an unusually high load in the face of
searing temperatures and an flood of new residents. Light's new
system was upgraded and should be able to handle the upcoming
summer, Schuler said.
</P>
<P>
   Enron's purchase of Elektro will probably spark the interest of
other foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   While the privatization movement in Latin America may attract
foreign ventures, ``there are only a few companies with
international expertise,'' and will perform well, said Carol Coale,
an analyst at Prudential Securities. Enron may pursue some water
ventures as well as explore possibilities for renewable energy
sources, Coale said.
</P>
<P>
   Enron's stock closed at 57 3/4, up 1 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
