<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE'S EARNINGS DOWN; PEPSI REPORTS EARLY WITH GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. reported a decline in earnings for the second
quarter Thursday and, in a burst of corporate competitiveness,
Pepsico said its earnings rose.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico had not been scheduled to report its financial results
until next Tuesday. But a spokesman for the company said the
decision was made to move up the announcement because Wall Street
had pushed down the price of its shares about 8 percent this week,
reacting to a report that sales at the company's Frito-Lay division
in a recent four-week period were less than stellar. Pepsi shares
closed Thursday at $37.9375, down 18.75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was an overreaction, but because of the pending
earnings announcement, we couldn't comment,'' the spokesman,
Richard Detwiler, said, citing a ``quiet period'' of five working
days before earnings reports required by the Securities and
Exchange Commission. ``So we moved to release our earnings early.
We wanted to provide more data on our performance than was sitting
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi's earnings for the quarter, before one-time accounting
adjustments last year, rose 19 percent, to $494 million, or 33
cents a diluted share, on revenue of $5.26 billion, compared with
earnings of $414 million, or 26 cents a share, on revenue of $5.09
billion a year earlier. The results matched expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Volume increased in both snacks and beverages, but worldwide
beverage operating profit fell because of increased spending by the
North American beverage division, all part of a strategy to
increase Pepsi's market share. ``They are tired of seeing their
stock dumped on unjustifiably,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a beverage
analyst with Paine Webber. ``No one's been looking beyond their
nose, but I think they are positioned for a very nice second
half.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke reported a 9 percent decline in second-quarter earnings on
a slight increase in revenue, reflecting the effect of the strong
dollar on the overseas business of the company, the world's leading
soft-drink maker.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar's higher exchange value meant that Coke's profits in
many foreign currencies translated into fewer dollars.
International companies like Coca-Cola can be vulnerable to such
currency fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ending on June 30, Coca-Cola, which is based in
Atlanta, earned $1.19 billion, or 48 cents a diluted share, on
revenue of $5.15 billion. That compared with earnings of $1.31
billion, or 52 cents a diluted share, on revenue of $5.07 billion
in the second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings results were slightly above Wall Street
expectations of 47 cents a share, but Coke's stock fell 62.5 cents,
to $87.185. On Tuesday, the stock closed at a 52-week high of
$88.9375.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the currency problems had been anticipated, and analysts
generally saw good news in the earnings report, based on a 10
percent increase in worldwide case volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had spectacular volume growth worldwide and in North
America,'' said Andrew Conway, a beverage analyst with Morgan
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   In North America, Coke's sales rose 8 percent overall and 8
percent in the United States, which is about 1.5 times the rate of
the soft-drink industry as a whole in the United States, Conway
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's chairman and chief executive, M. Douglas Ivester,
attributed the sales growth to ``solid increases in the company's
core brands,'' like Coca-Cola, Diet Coke and Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest percentage sales increase was in Africa, at 18
percent. Sales in Latin America grew 12 percent, and in Europe by
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, part of the company's Middle and Far East Group, sales
appeared strong in some places despite economic travails in the
region. Unit case volume grew 28 percent in China and 33 percent in
India. Sales in Japan fell 3 percent, which the company attributed
partly to a retail price increase, the first in seven years, though
analysts said the overall state of the Japanese economy played a
major role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our performance across Asia is the result of our ability to
stay focused and adjust in these tough times,'' Ivester said.
Analysts had questioned company executives at a meeting last month
about Japan, and had been told there was ``no growth'' there, but
were given no details.
</P>
</TEXT>
