<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-NOMERGER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED MARTIN SCRAPS MERGER WITH NORTHROP GRUMMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Ron Hutcheson 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lockheed Martin scrapped its planned merger with
Northrop Grumman on Thursday because of government opposition,
pulling the plug on a $11.7 billion deal that would have created an
aerospace powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The decision could have far-reaching future implications.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies had viewed the corporate marriage as an ideal
opportunity to adapt to the post-Cold War era and other changes in
the defense industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been good for the American taxpayers, national
security and Texas jobs,'' said a disappointed Rep. Kay Granger,
R-Fort Worth. Lockheed Martin employs nearly 20,000 people in North
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But federal officials called the decision a victory for
taxpayers. The Justice Department filed suit to block the proposed
merger in March, arguing that the combined company would have a
virtual monopoly, especially in certain areas of defense
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's products include the Fort Worth-built F-16
fighter and the F-22 stealth fighter. It is also bidding to build
the planned Joint Strike Fighter, the next-generation plane that
would ensure the future of the Fort Worth plant well into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman makes the B-2 Stealth bomber and is one of the
biggest sucontractors for Boeing's commercial aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general for antitrust issues,
said his department welcomed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means the U.S. government and the American people will
continue to receive the highest possible quality of military
products in defense of this nation, at the lowest cost to the
American taxpayer,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed shelved the deal after attempts to negotiate a
settlement broke down. The case had been scheduled to go to court
Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inability to reach an acceptable solution, combined with
our concern over the litigation with our principal customer,
necessitates this decision,'' said Vance Coffman, Lockheed's
chairman. ``Continuing the litigation at this point is simply not
in the best interests of Lockheed Martin's customers, shareholders
or employees.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
