<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINTON -- July 16, 1998 -- HEALTHCARE, 7-16 --
President Clinton greeting Rep. William J. Jefferson of New Orleans
Thursday after speaking out for patients' rights on Capitol Hill.
Clinton declared to a crowd of doctors and Democratic colleagues
that a patient's right to sue should be a cornerstone of managed
care legislation. Republicans squabbled among themselves, with some
disagreeing over the extent of legal protections that should be
afforded to patients and whether the proposals would fuel rising
health costs. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DECANI, Serbia -- July 16, 1998 -- YUGO-ALBANIANS, 7-16
-- Shukrie Shala, far right, the mother of five, has not heard from
her husband, Dr. Hafir Shala, an ethnic Albanian who worked in a
clinic run by Mother Teresa's Sisters of Charity mission in
Glogovac, since he was seized by the Serbian police on April 10.
Serbian forces have been turning increasingly to the abduction and
execution of small groups of civilians in their fight against
ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo, according to human rights
officials and witnesses. (Wade Goddard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN FRANCISCO -- July 16, 1998 -- CODEBREAKER, 7-16 --
John Gilmore led a team that cracked the government's
data-scrambling code in a record time of 56 hours. That
breakthrough, in a contest sponsored by a Silicon Valley
computer-security software company, is being hailed by critics of
U.S. export policy for data-scrambling technology as proof that a
well-heeled group of terrorists or other criminals could easily
break the code used by many banks, financial institutions and even
government agencies. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 19 --
SCHRAGER-HOTEL-PROFILE, 7-16 -- Ian Schrager, onetime Studio 54
badboy, is now America's hottest hotelier. Schrager recently
reopened the St. Moritz on Central Park South, taking it over from
Donald J. Trump. The hotelier wants to redecorate the rooms several
floors at a time and turn it into a superluxury lodging. ``This is
not something that's just a specialized niche,'' says Schrager of
his style of hotel development. ``It's got mainstream appeal that
people respond to.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RIDGEFIELD PARK, N.J. -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 19 -- CAR-SMART-DAEWOO, 7-16 -- Deborah Archer, 36, a ``campus
adviser'' for Daewoo Motor America, with a 1998 Leganza sedan
outside the Korean company's regional offices in Ridgefield Park,
N.J. Daewoo is aiming much of its sales pitch at college students,
a demographic group without steady incomes, big savings accounts or
long credit histories. ``As campus advisers, were told that our
goal is not to sell the car, but to spread the Daewoo name by word
of mouth,'' says Ms. Archer. (Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
