<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9254 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-NORTHROP-1ST     07-16 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-NORTHROP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-5900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED MARTIN ENDS PLAN TO ACQUIRE NORTHROP GRUMMAN 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs for addition of 16 grafs at end; 3rd graf now makes mention
of Boeing)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that signals the end of major mergers in the nation's
military industry, Lockheed Martin Corp. abandoned its planned $8.3
billion acquisition of the Northrop Grumman Corp. on Thursday, a
deal that the government opposed on antitrust grounds.
</P>
<P>
   After months of negotiations between the companies and the
government to avoid a court fight over the transaction, Lockheed
said Thursday that efforts to reach a pretrial settlement with its
biggest customer were ``not successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lockheed board voted Thursday afternoon to end a takeover
that would have created the nation's largest military supplier,
nearly a third larger than its nearest competitor, Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which shareholders of both companies had already
approved, was the biggest corporate merger ever dismantled because
of government opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, nearly eight months after the deal was announced,
the Justice Department, supported by the Defense Department, sued
to block the acquisition, contending that a combination of the
companies threatened the nation's defense by limiting competition.
This action represented an about-face for the Defense Department,
which had long encouraged a wave of mergers that swept through the
military industry since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inability to reach an acceptable solution, combined with
our concern over the litigation with our principal customer,
necessitates this decision,'' said Lockheed chairman and chief
executive Vance Coffman. ``Continuing the litigation at this point
is simply not in the best interests of Lockheed Martin's customers,
shareholders or employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed, which has grown through the acquisition of 22
different military contractors to become the nation's No. 2
military supplier, is best known as the maker of the F-16 fighter
jet and many missile systems. Northrop, which makes components for
the B-2 bomber, is the nation's No. 3 supplier.
</P>
<P>
   The government feared that a union of the two would create an
unacceptable level of ``vertical integration'' in which Lockheed
could control too much of Northrop's electronics business in ways
that could suppress competition and drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop chairman and chief executive Kent Kresa said Thursday
that ``while we believed the merger was in the best interests of
our constituencies, Northrop Grumman can and will continue as a
strong, independent competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kresa may have difficulty convincing shareholders
of that. He had said Northrop might not survive without the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although the termination of the deal was announced after the
stock market closed Thursday, Northrop's shares dropped $5.6875, or
5.5 percent, to $97.375, on reports that negotiations had failed.
Shares of Lockheed Martin fell 56.25 cents, to $103.9375. Northrop
stock had reached a 52-week high of $139 on Feb. 27, the day after
Lockheed Martin and Northrop shareholders approved the combination.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the deal may indicate that the Pentagon, which
since 1993 has supported a consolidation of the nation's military
industry, has altered its policy. There are, in fact, no larger
companies left to merge. Between 1992 and 1997, $55 billion worth
of mergers took place in the military industry. Lockheed gobbled up
companies such as Martin Marietta, Loral and Unisys Defense. Boeing
acquired McDonnell Douglas and Rockwell Defense. In fact, three
companies _ Lockheed, Boeing and Raytheon _ were called, in
industry jargon, the ``megadominant'' players.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Pentagon had no comment Thursday on the cancellation of the
deal. Joel Klein, head of the Justice Department's antitrust
division, praised Lockheed's decision. ``This means that the U.S.
government and the American people will continue to receive the
highest possible quality of military products and services,'' Klein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Loren Thompson, a defense industry analyst at the Lexington
Institute, a Washington research organization, said Lockheed's
decision ``clearly indicates that there is a sea change in the
Pentagon's approach to industry consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big deals are over'' he said. ``We are at the end of the
wave of defense industry mega-mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lockheed, there was little concern among analysts over its
future. Thompson, for instance, said that the termination of this
deal ``is nothing more than a speed bump'' for Lockheed.
</P>
<P>
   With more than $28 billion in sales and a variety of businesses
that include not only military products but also operations such as
satellites, electronics and telecommunications, Lockheed is well
positioned in an array of industries and not dependent on the
Northrop deal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the deal was important enough for Lockheed to have even
offered to shed the crown jewel of the deal, Northrop's electronics
business, to gain government approval. The government rejected this
offer, and settlement talks broke down over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last three or four months, we've been in the process
of trying to find a solution to get this resolved,'' Coffman,
Lockheed's chief executive, said in an interview. ``More than a
dozen different solutions were examined. We discussed them with the
government and, at the end of the day, none of them were
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it was time for us to say that we will withdraw from this
deal because the tension was rising with our biggest customer,''
Coffman said, referring to the Pentagon. He said that within the
last month, ``I had rising hope we might find a path.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in Defense Department policy may also reflect a
change in key individuals at the Justice Department and at the
Pentagon from the time Lockheed and Northrop first announced the
deal. Klein took over as antitrust chief at the Justice Department,
and drew a harder line on proposed mergers, while the Pentagon
received a new head of acquisition policy, Jacques Gansler, who was
more critical than his predecessor of military industry mergers.
</P>
<P>
   For Northrop, the outlook is less certain. It is best known as
the maker of electronic components for the B-2 bomber, and a union
with Lockheed would have put it in a position to have a steady
customer for the components in Lockheed's fighter planes. Instead,
Northrop is seen as lacking the heft to compete with other
electronic giants like Raytheon but is too large to be a niche
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for Northrop right now is to assure the troops,'' said
Jon B. Kutler, president of Quarterdeck Investment Partners, which
specializes in the military industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might adopt a go-it-alone strategy, or they might make
some smaller acquisitions themselves. There's also been a lot of
speculation that they might join with a foreign partner, but I'm
not sure they want to test the edges of the envelope again with
that kind of a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the Pentagon, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that there was ``some ambivalence'' within the
Defense Department about breaking up the deal _ fears that Northrop
might be acquired by a British company, most likely General
Electric Co. PLC. ``That made people queasy,'' this person said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
