<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENECA-HISTORY-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATION OF WOMEN'S RIGHTS MOVEMENTS DRAWS THOUSANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   (js)  
 By JANE GROSS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SENECA FALLS, N.Y. _ Rachel Waite honored her foremothers on
Thursday, during the 150th anniversary of the first U.S. women's
rights convention, by doubling the prices at her curb-side lemonade
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel easily fetched 50 cents a cup from the stream of tourists
on hand for the festivities, which brought the first lady, the
governor of New York, the secretary of state and the officers of
the National Organization for Women to this tiny Finger Lakes
village, which lives and breathes its unusual history year in and
year out.
</P>
<P>
   Waite's stand was directly across the street from the house
where Elizabeth Cady Stanton started the feminist movement. The
10-year-old was hazy on the details _ she mistakenly thought Mrs.
Stanton was the first woman to cast a vote. But the girl was true
to the mission of the Quaker housewives who made history here in
1848 with their demands for equality.
</P>
<P>
   Waite was clearly the boss at the lemonade stand, giving orders
to her little brother. And in making her own decision on how her
profits would be used _ for a trip to a nearby water park and a
college fund _ she realized her life was vastly different from Mrs.
Stanton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``She couldn't be what she wanted to be, like us,'' Waite said.
</P>
<P>
   The blend of commerce and history at Waite's lemonade stand
reflected the tone for the celebrations here, as if Masterpiece
Theater were interrupted for commercials. The events in recent days
included re-enactments of the convention, concerts by women
performers, extra tours at the museums and plenty of goodies to eat
and souvenirs to buy.
</P>
<P>
   On the road to town, signs outside Polar Freeze, Wal-Mart and
Bill Trout's Lincoln/Mercury showroom welcomed visitors to the
celebration. Along Fall Street, stores were hung with bright
bunting and decked with flowers. Hawkers sold mugs, tie tacks and
tea towels emblazoned with the face of plump, frizzy-haired Mrs.
Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   But at various public events, impassioned applause punctuated
the reading of the Declaration of Sentiments, the manifesto that
itemized the ``injuries and usurptations'' by men against women and
called for new civil and social rights _ to vote, own property,
divorce abusive husbands and claim educational and employment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must finish the work that was done here,'' said the first
lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who today addressed a sweltering
crowd estimated at 10,000 at the high school football field. This
was the last stop on Mrs. Clinton's tour of historical monuments in
need of restoration, which include the M'Clintock House in
neighboring Waterloo, where Mrs. Stanton and four friends drafted
their declaration at the mahogany dining room table. Mrs. Clinton
has pledged to raise $1 million in private contributions to restore
the M'Clintock House.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's visit to the M'Clintock House on Wednesday
evening drew crowds three deep along the nearby streets as the
First Lady waved from the front of her bus. On one front porch,
Kerri Brown and Jeff Hauke argued about which of them she was
greeting. Ms. Brown won the argument. Hauke popped another beer.
</P>
<P>
   The five housewives who convened at the M'Clintock House 150
years ago were driven there by the claustrophobia of their own
lives. Mrs. Stanton, for one, complained of her ``mental hunger,''
stuck at home with seven children while her abolitionist husband
traveled the country.
</P>
<P>
   She was 32 and well educated, and had been raised by a doting
father who encouraged her interest in his legal career. But now she
found herself far from the stimulation of Boston, struggling to
make a life for herself in a modest clapboard house here, just
upwind from the 115 factories that were creating prosperity at the
same time they were cutting women off from the shared work of
farming and isolating them at home.
</P>
<P>
   Western New York was America's frontier then, a hotbed of social
ferment. The region was home to reformers, religionists and
abolitionists. These were activities women could join and on which
they could cut their teeth for the awakening movement for equal
rights, which would be led by Mrs. Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   That movement, born here with the 1848 convention at Wesleyan
Methodist Chapel, is commemorated with a national park that
includes the remnants of the chapel, the homes of Mrs. Stanton and
Mary Ann M'Clintock, an interpretive center with educational
exhibits and a waterfall that streams over a bluestone carving of
the Declaration of Sentiments. Also located here is the national
Women's Hall of Fame, where 21 new members were inducted this week,
including Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many upstate towns that boomed at the turn of the century
and then fell on hard times, Seneca Falls remains a
prosperous-looking place. An active historical preservation
committee has seen to it that the streets are still lined with the
ample Victorian and Gothic Revival homes once owned by the
19th-century industrialists.
</P>
<P>
   Some here attribute the village's enduring prosperity to the one
remaining factory from the heady years of the Industrial
Revolution, Goulds Pumps, recently bought by ITT Industries and a
major employer. Others cite the willingness of longtime Seneca
Falls loyalists to commute to jobs 90 minutes away in Rochester or
Syracuse. The population remains at 7,000, comparable to what it
was in the village's heyday at the time of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism would get a boost if the monuments to the women's
movement were to become more popular destinations. According to
Josie Fernandez, the new superintendent of the 18-year-old national
park here, average annual attendance is 35,000. Ms. Fernandez said
she anticipated that many visitors during this four-day celebration
alone.
</P>
<P>
   The women's monuments are a regular part of the education of
local schoolchildren, like 12-year-old Rebecca Ferguson-Knox, who
visited the Stanton House this week (and drank Rachel Waite's
lemonade) along with her parents, grandparents and brother. Rebecca
particularly enjoyed hearing that Mrs. Stanton taught her sons to
cook and knit and allowed her daughters to roughhouse in the yard,
unheard-of activities in the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   At the Stanton House for the first time this week were a couple
from Terre Haute, Ind., Gary Daily and Susan Dehler, who boasted of
``15 years of unmarried bliss.'' Daily has taught women's history
since 1965 without ever seeing these sights. He marveled at the
explosion of interest in a field that had virtually no scholars or
teaching materials in the early days of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Education of a more informal kind was taking place outside a
news shop on Fall Street, where Carl Mele, the owner of C-J News &AMP;
Sundries, was grilling sausages for the tourists. One of them, in
town for Wednesday's NOW rally, had upbraided him for calling her a
``lady'' rather than a ``woman,'' Mele said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the difference now,'' he boasted, wiping grease from
his hands and sweat from his brow. ``If that's what their feelings
are, it's OK with me. I'm easy to get along with.'' But apparently
Mele's lesson in political correctness was brief. Today, his
transactions with female customers ended with a cheery, ``Thanks
honey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
