<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/16/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- HBO-BOXING-PROMOMAN, 7-16
-- Programming chief for HBO boxing, Lou DiBella, in Bryant Park,
promoting the upcoming Saturday night fight on HBO featuring
light-heavyweight champion Roy Jones Jr. (in background), at
Madison Square Garden. A Harvard Law graduate, raised in Flatbush,
Brooklyn, DiBella has the power to help determine what boxing
matches HBO's audience will see. ``My Ivy League education gave me
the education to deal with the Don Kings or Bob Arums of the
world,'' says DiBella. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) HELENDALE, Calif. -- July 16, 1998 --
BURLESQUE-MEMORIES, 7-16 -- Dixie Evans in the ``Jenny Lee'' room
of her Exotic World museum, dedicated to the history of burlesque
and stripper stars from the 20s to the 50s. ``These people deserve
their place in entertainment history,'' says Miss Evans, who was
once billed as the Marilyn Monroe of Burlesque. The museum is in a
one-story building that used to be a series of goat sheds on what
used to be a 40-acre goat farm. ``There's only one old goat left,''
says Miss Evans, ``and that's me.'' (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINTON -- July 16, 1998 -- HEALTHCARE, 7-16 --
President Clinton greeting Rep. William J. Jefferson of New Orleans
Thursday after speaking out for patients' rights on Capitol Hill.
Clinton declared to a crowd of doctors and Democratic colleagues
that a patient's right to sue should be a cornerstone of managed
care legislation. Republicans squabbled among themselves, with some
disagreeing over the extent of legal protections that should be
afforded to patients and whether the proposals would fuel rising
health costs. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DECANI, Serbia -- July 16, 1998 -- YUGO-ALBANIANS, 7-16
-- Shukrie Shala, far right, the mother of five, has not heard from
her husband, Dr. Hafir Shala, an ethnic Albanian who worked in a
clinic run by Mother Teresa's Sisters of Charity mission in
Glogovac, since he was seized by the Serbian police on April 10.
Serbian forces have been turning increasingly to the abduction and
execution of small groups of civilians in their fight against
ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo, according to human rights
officials and witnesses. (Wade Goddard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN FRANCISCO -- July 16, 1998 -- CODEBREAKER, 7-16 --
John Gilmore led a team that cracked the government's
data-scrambling code in a record time of 56 hours. That
breakthrough, in a contest sponsored by a Silicon Valley
computer-security software company, is being hailed by critics of
U.S. export policy for data-scrambling technology as proof that a
well-heeled group of terrorists or other criminals could easily
break the code used by many banks, financial institutions and even
government agencies. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 19 --
SCHRAGER-HOTEL-PROFILE, 7-16 -- Ian Schrager, onetime Studio 54
badboy, is now America's hottest hotelier. Schrager recently
reopened the St. Moritz on Central Park South, taking it over from
Donald J. Trump. The hotelier wants to redecorate the rooms several
floors at a time and turn it into a superluxury lodging. ``This is
not something that's just a specialized niche,'' says Schrager of
his style of hotel development. ``It's got mainstream appeal that
people respond to.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RIDGEFIELD PARK, N.J. -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 19 -- CAR-SMART-DAEWOO, 7-16 -- Deborah Archer, 36, a ``campus
adviser'' for Daewoo Motor America, with a 1998 Leganza sedan
outside the Korean company's regional offices in Ridgefield Park,
N.J. Daewoo is aiming much of its sales pitch at college students,
a demographic group without steady incomes, big savings accounts or
long credit histories. ``As campus advisers, were told that our
goal is not to sell the car, but to spread the Daewoo name by word
of mouth,'' says Ms. Archer. (Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MARBLEHEAD, Mass. -- July 16, 1998 -- HOME-PROJECT-BOS,
7-16 -- In one section of James and Isabel Hammond's yard, stands
this ceramic pagoda, brought from China by James's great aunt.
Isabel says the beautification of their Victorian house is an
ongoing project, and there is plenty still to do, including adding
to the garden. (John Blanding/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) ONSET, Mass. -- July 16, 1998 -- SPIRITUALIST-CAMP-BOS,
7-16 -- Alice O'Brien, Treasurer of the On-I-Set Wigwam
Spiritualist Camp, administers a hand-on spritual cleansing to
Bruce Wright. At this camp, the ``great spirit'' is invoked, the
sermon is delivered by a medium rather than a minister, and the
focus is on spiritualism, not the Bible. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- BERNSTEIN-DANCE-REVIEW,
7-16 -- From left, Laura Cazzaniga, Anna Polikarpova and Lloyd
Riggins of The Hamburg Ballet from Germany, with other Hamburg
members in John Neumeier's ``Bernstein Dances,'' at the Lincoln
Center Festival '98. Neumeier places Bernstein the man within his
music in the way that Frederick Ashton did so profoundly with
Arthur Rimbaud in his ballet ``Illuminations,'' set to Benjamin
Britten's music. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) TEHRAN, Iran -- July 16, 1998 -- IRAN-COKE-COX, 7-16 --
Iranian Nadia Afshai, 13, sips her so-called Coca-Cola through a
straw. She says she drinks the soda for the taste, not the name.
The Coke bottles are from before the U.S. sanctions against trade
with Iran went into effect three years ago. The cola inside the
bottles is a local mix and not Coca-Cola. (Larry Kaplow/Cox News
Service) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PETROVSKOYE, Russia -- July 16, 1998 --
RUSSIA-CZAR-ROYALTY-COX, 6-16 -- Yevgeny Meshchersky stands in
front of the gutted palace he claims is his by birthright. Eighteen
months ago Meshchersky, 47, a mechanical engineer during Soviet
times, moved his family into an abandoned building on the
dilapidated estate at Petrovskoye, outside Moscow. He is fighting
the government in court to establish ownership of the 18th century
estate which was confiscated by the Bolsheviks in 1917. (Charles W.
Holmes/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- TWELFTH-THEATER-REVIEW,
7-16 -- Max Wright, left, as Sir Andrew Aguecheek and Brian Murray
as Sir Toby Belch, in the English director Nicholas Hytner's
spirited new production of ``Twelfth Night,'' at the Vivian
Beaumont Theater at Lincoln Center. In ``Twelfth Night,'' the
revelations of the production come from Murray and Wright, who
transform the low high jinks of Toby and Andrew into a blissful
vaudeville as rich in psychological detail as it is in hilarious
shtick. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SANDWICH, Mass. -- July 16, 1998 -- ANTIQUE-COLUMN, 7-16
-- British children's china at Leatherwood Antiques of Sandwich,
Mass., a private dealer who has what may be the largest stock of
antique British children's wares in America. Cups inscribed with
children's names have been christening presents for centuries, and
the antique ones are still popular gifts. The dishes capture
entertainment that appealed to children: accordion players, the
circus, dog races, and Punch and Judy puppet shows. (David
Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- July 16, 1998 -- KANSAS-CITY, 7-16 --
One of the four Claes Oldenburg sculptures outside the
Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, which play against the building's
neo-classic architecture. Laced with fountains and boulevards,
graced by handsome public buildings, Kansas City survived the
vicissitudes of recent decades better than most. It remains a
recognizable exemplar of the turn-of-the-century City Beautiful
Movement, and it has spent liberally to refresh Beaux-Arts and Art
Deco landmarks and build modern ones. (Don Ipock/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. -- July 16, 1998 --
YOSEMITE-FALLS, 7-16 -- Hikers along the Mist Trail at the base of
Vernal Falls in Yosemite National Park are treated with views of
rainbows and a torrent of mist normally reserved for the lucky few
who make it up in the spring. ``The falls are going berserk,'' says
Keith Walklet, a park spokesman. ``We've got two years' worth of
water coming through here in one season, and it's special. I'm
excited about it.'' (John Burgess/Sant Rosa Press-Democrat Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) COLUMBIA, Md. -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 19
-- SKATING-DANCE, 7-16 -- Tim Murphy, far left, a co-founder of
Next Ice Age, rehearses with the company. The 10-year-old
ensemble-skating company, founded by Nathan Birch, nad Murphy, will
make their American Dance Festival debut on Thursday in Durham,
N.C. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 19 --
FORBIDDEN-BROADWAY-2, 7-16 -- William Selby, left, Christine Pedi
and Neal Mayer in a ``Lion King'' skit in ``Forbidden Broadway
Strikes Back!'' The year-and-a-half-old musical-satire will be
replaced by a new edition at the end of September, and Gerard
Alessandrini, the creator, is on the prowl for fresh material and
new cast members. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 19 --
FORBIDDEN-BROADWAY-1, 7-16 -- Gerard Alessandrini the creator of
``Forbidden Broadway.'' Alessandrini, 44, has been Broadway's
premier parts collector for a long time. Since 1982 he has been
presenting a series of rude yet ultimately affectionate
cabaret-style satires on the Broadway which he creates, writes and
directs. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 19 --
BROADWAY-SINGING, 7-16 -- From left, Mary Beth Peil, Kevin
Chamberlin, B.D. Wong and Judy Kuhn in the recent revival of ``As
Thousands Cheer.'' Well received on Broadway in 1933 and reborn
this summer at the Greenwich House Theater, the new ``As Thousands
Cheer'' was brightly cast in this revival, rehearsed to a fine
point and as clear as it could have been. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- MARATHON-SWIMMER, 7-16 --
Marathon swimmer Shelley Taylor-Smith during an interview. Last
Saturday, at 36, she won the 28.5-mile Manhattan Island Marathon
for the fifth time, seizing the lead from two men in their 20s who
were half a mile ahead. ``All of a sudden I'm coming down
Manhattan, and I'm winning,'' says Ms. Taylor-Smith who has decided
to retire. ``Never in my wildest dreams did I think I would end my
career on such a fairy tale note.'' (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1998 -- SWIM-SYNC, 6-16 -- Bill May
and his duet partner, Kristina Lum, practicing their synchronized
swimming routine at Manhattan's Asphalt Green Aqua Center
Wednesday. ``I've got a lot of support from my family and
friends,'' says May, who is 5 feet 9 inches tall and 150 pounds.
``Some people don't think it's a real sport, but it is. It takes
hard work.'' (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
