<SLUG> BC-TIMES-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CO. POSTS 11.7 PERCENT DECLINE IN NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Times Co. reported an 11.7 percent decline
in net income Thursday for the second quarter but said that
earnings before special items and a one-time charge rose 16.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rising advertising revenues resulted in the increase in
operating earnings, the company said. The growth was partly offset,
however, by higher newsprint costs and greater depreciation expense
in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter results met the expectations of Wall Street
analysts. But the company's stock fell $2.875 Thursday, or 7.3
percent, to $36.6875 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for the quarter were reduced by 4 cents a share by a
one-time charge of $7.7 million related to the repurchase of $78.1
million in debt. The quarter also included gains from the 1997 sale
of tennis, sailing and ski magazines and from a tax adjustment. As
a result, net income was $75 million, or 38 cents a diluted share,
down from $84.9 million, or 43 cents a diluted share, in the
quarter a year earlier. The per-share figures reflect the company's
recent 2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the charge and other special items, earnings for the
second quarter increased 16.8 percent, to $78.2 million, or 40
cents a diluted share. Operating profit at the company came in at
$145.1 million for the second quarter, a gain of 13.9 percent
compared with figures from the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue grew 3.8 percent, to $749.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profit at the company's newspaper group, which
comprises The New York Times, The Boston Globe and 21 regional
newspapers, rose 8.4 percent in the second quarter, to $129.5
million, from $119.4 million in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue at the newspaper group rose 7.1 percent in
the quarter, the result of higher ad rates and volume. This
improvement was partly offset by an 18 percent increase in
newsprint costs. Ad revenue at The New York Times was up 9 percent
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that weekday circulation fell at both The
Times, down 1.5 percent, and at The Globe, which lost nine-tenths
of 1 percent. Weekday circulation at the regional newspapers
increased five-tenths of 1 percent. Sunday circulation fell 2.4
percent at The Times during the second quarter and inched up 1
percent at The Globe and two-tenths of a percent at the regional
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profit at the company's broadcast group rose 14.3
percent, to $13.6 million, from $11.9 million in the quarter a year
earlier. This group, eight network-affiliated television stations
and two New York City radio stations, produced revenues of $41
million, up 5.6 percent from revenues in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company's magazine division showed a 29.8 percent increase
in operating profit in the second quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
