<SLUG> BC-NAPALM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPALM PROTESTERS GATHER TO MEET TRAIN SHIPMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH RENDON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEER PARK, Texas _ As a train loaded with napalm approached the
area Thursday, a small group of demonstrators here protested plans
to recycle the Vietnam-era jellied gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The first shipment, sent from a naval ammunitions depot near San
Diego to the GNI Group, was expected to arrive in the Houston area
late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It was being shipped by the Burlington Northern and Santa Fe
Railway Co. The napalm was to be taken off its train at the Hobby
Airport-area railyard and then loaded onto a truck to travel to the
GNI plant.
</P>
<P>
   Despite assurances from GNI and Navy officials that the napalm,
with detonators removed, is less dangerous than gasoline in its
liquid form, about a dozen members of the grass-roots organization,
Texans United, gathered on Thursday to protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are calling on our political leaders today to step up to
the plate and support these citizens in their efforts to stop this
latest scheme concerning napalm,'' said Jim Baldauf with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, most from the Channelview area, met at an east
Harris County shopping center to voice their concerns about the 3.4
million gallons of napalm that will be brought to the GNI plant
over two years. The U.S. Navy granted GNI a $9 million contract
last week to handle the napalm recycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an Army veteran. I was a veteran when the United States
military was in the business of protecting its citizens rather than
attacking its citizens,'' said Baldauf, 54, an independent oil
company employee from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not reacting here to wartime images of napalm. We are
reacting to one more battle in the chemical war that has been waged
on the Ship Channel population for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldauf, who said he is on the board of Texans United, and
others said they are concerned about the emissions when the napalm,
which consists of benzene, gasoline and polystyrene, is
incinerated. Channelview residents, they say, receive the brunt of
the toxic emissions from Deer Park's chemical facilities because of
prevailing winds.
</P>
<P>
   GNI officials, however, said there will not be any emissions
because the recycling process is closed. The Deer Park company
plans to process the napalm so that it can be recycled for use as
an alternative fuel. It will then be used at still undetermined
locations out of state, said Bill Reeves, vice president of
regulatory affairs for GNI.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
