<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENERGY-SFCHRON &LR;      07-16 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Electricity Prices Surge In the Heat   By Kenneth Howe  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
California's heat wave is causing electricity prices in the state's
new power market to soar _ and testing for the first time whether
deregulation can actually lower energy costs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   While temperatures topped 100 degrees in many parts of
California yesterday, the wholesale price of electricity during the
hottest part of the day climbed to more than 10 cents per kilowatt
hour, according to figures from the California Power Exchange.
That's a 300 percent increase over the 21/2-cent per kilowatt
average price for all of last year, when the electricity market was
regulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the highest prices we've had,'' said Ed Freudenburg,
a spokesman for the Power Exchange, a nonprofit organization
created to serve as a marketplace where electric power is bought
and sold through an electronic auction every day. ``In fact, since
the July 4th holiday, we've been setting records nearly every
day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers won't immediately feel any effect from higher
wholesale electricity prices because utility rates have been capped
by law at current levels for four years. But rates actually were
expected to decline before those four years were up. That means if
the utilities have to pay higher prices for power, rates could stay
at their high level for the full period, depriving consumers of a
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The skyrocketing electricity prices are quite a turnaround from
the spring, when cool weather actually pushed the wholesale price
of electricity on the Power Exchange to zero during some hours.
</P>
<P>
   Before the recent spike, average daily Power Exchange prices
swung widely from a fraction of a penny per kilowatt to just more
than 3 cents. The overall average since deregulation began March 31
is 1.48 cents per kilowatt hour.
</P>
<P>
   But now, hot weather is causing people to flip on
electricity-consuming fans and air conditioners, so electricity has
been in high demand. And, in California's new deregulated market,
when demand goes up, prices jump, too.
</P>
<P>
   The current jump in the price of electricity for normal usage
follows a similar surge in the cost of backup electric power last
week. The wholesale price for ``replacement reserve power'' in
California briefly skyrocketed as high as $9,900 per megawatt from
a normal $5 to $10 per megawatt. The price has since come down.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind electricity deregulation in California was to
break up the monopoly held by the state's investor owned utilities,
such as San Francisco-based Pacific Gas and Electric Co. By
allowing many companies to sell the electricity they generated in
an open market, the price of electricity was supposed to decline.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed it did during the spring when electricity demand was
low. In fact, some generating companies were giving electricity
away during the middle of the night. For some plants, which can be
like huge steam kettles that take hours to heat up, it was cheaper
to let them run than shut them down and fire them up later.
</P>
<P>
   But if the spring was a buyer's market, the summer is a
seller's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, this is a test of deregulation,'' said Mike Florio, a
board member of the Power Exchange and a senior attorney with The
Utility Reform Network, a consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're not happy with electricity at 10 cents a
kilowatt, but this is what you'd expect in a well-functioning
market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said it will take a longer period of time to judge
whether prices on the whole under deregulation are lower than when
utilities ran the power system. ``But I'm pretty confident that if
you take the low and high prices together, we'll come out ahead,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to compare with any accuracy daily wholesale
electricity prices this year with last year. Before deregulation
the state's utilities simply generated power and the state Public
Utilities Commission regulated what they could charge for an
overall rate, which worked out to be about 21/2 cents per kilowatt
hour.
</P>
<P>
   The high prices over the last two weeks are well above that 21/2
cents per kilowatt average, but that might not be bad for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``New companies are going to look at California and see that
there's money to be made,'' said Jim Macias, PG&AMP;E's senior vice
president and general manager of generation transmission and
supply. ``If you belive in a free market, that will eventually
lower prices because you'll have more supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio agreed. ``Building new power plants now is actually good
news for consumers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for this apparently contradictory argument, he
said, is that the latest natural-gas-fired plants are cheaper to
build, more efficient and produce far less pollutants than many of
California's older generators, which need to be closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
