<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Record-Breaking Performance by Nasdaq Not That Significant   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
So the Nasdaq cracked 2,000.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And Chicago Cub slugger Sammy Sosa cracked 20 homers in May,
breaking the major league individual record for the number of
dingers hit in a given month. Records are meant to be broken, but
not all such feats are always that meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's doesn't seem to be. His record won't tell us who's going
to be the best home-run hitter. &UR;  &LR; The outfielder probably will still
finish third at the end of the season among major league home run
swatters behind Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Nasdaq's record performance that poignant. Guessing if
and when the composite index would break through the 2,000 mark
made for good water-cooler wagering, but the tech-laden index
doesn't tell the full story of what's driving the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of stocks, perhaps the top seven, listed on Nasdaq are
the ones doing the heavy lifting. Tech stocks with beefy market
capitalizations, such as Microsoft, Intel, Dell and Cisco Systems,
are pushing the Nasdaq over 2,000. In short, what is driving the
broader market to record-shattering heights are large-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: The S&AMP;P 500 rose 17.7 percent during the first six
months of this year, while the Russell 2000 _ a small-cap index _
increased only 5 percent. And on closer inspection, the largest 100
stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 vaulted almost 21 percent compared to its
smallest 100 stocks, which saw a rise of only 8 percent, according
to Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst Leah Modigliani in New York.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the 100 biggest stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 accounted for
77 percent of the total increase of the index during the first half
of the year. In fact, Microsoft alone accounted for nearly 70
percent of that rise.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the smallest 100 stocks in the S&AMP;P were
responsible for less than 1 percent of the index's gain, Modigliani
points out.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it doesn't take a rocket-scientist to recognize this
trend. But sometimes stock pickers need to take a step back and
remind themselves of the obvious, Modliani says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that people have to realize how narrow
the market is, even on an historical basis,'' Modigliani says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Modigliani isn't advocating that investors run out and
load up on a bunch of new big-cap stocks. They are expensive right
now. But by increasing existing positions in their best-performing
big-cap holdings, investors might have better chances of keeping up
with the leading market indices.
</P>
<P>
   The big-caps are getting much of the action, she says, because
nervous investors are looking for comfort in names they know. They
are worried about their stocks hitting the rocky shoals of the
Asian economic crisis. ``Some people view most big-cap stocks as
safe stocks,'' Modigliani says.
</P>
<P>
   Unless of course, one of those big-cap stocks was Cendant.
</P>
<P>
   Double Take
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Internet stocks continually tell skeptics to focus on
revenue growth. So one would figure that DoubleClick, an Internet
advertising company, would have been sitting pretty Wednesday after
the company &UR;  &LR; reported a 33 percent jump in revenues for the past
quarter to $17.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? Investors gandered at the bottom line and
weren't impressed. That's because the online concern reported its
losses (You didn't expect profits did you?) more than tripled to
$4.7 million compared to the same quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick's shares were slammed yesterday, falling 8 percent
to $48.83. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Oops. Even if you buy into the rationale that Internet stocks
don't have to make money, you would at least like to see them lose
a little less each quarter before the stock takes off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF 94103,
by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at  &LR; mveverka(at &LR; 
si &LR; gn)sfgate.com &LR; . He also appears on KRON-TV's Daybreak on
Tuesdays and Thursdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
