r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAMMING-SFCHRON &LR;      07-16 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAMMING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Phone `Crammer' Cheated 500,000   By Jonathan Marshall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
As many as half a million Californians have been ``crammed'' _ a
form of telecommunications fraud _ by a Boca Raton firm, state
regulators said yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The company, Coral Communications, was raided Monday by agents
of the California Public Utilities Commission and the district
attorneys offices of Kings, San Mateo, Monterey and Tulare
counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we've seen, including inspection of their
facilities, these problems go far beyond regulatory matters,'' said
Bill Schulte, director of the PUC's consumer services division. ``I
am personally shocked and appalled at the behavior we've uncovered
in terms of the sheer volume and scope of abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulte said consumer losses probably ran into the millions of
dollars. ``We are committed to obtaining restitution for each and
every victim,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC has interviewed 300 California consumers who were
charged by Coral, on their Pacific Bell bill, for services they
never ordered, a fraud known as cramming. In some cases, customers
filled out sweepstakes forms without noticing the tiny print saying
that their signature would authorize monthly payments for calling
cards they never received.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Coral's victims included the Kings County DA's
office and a phone line used by Kings County to check on the
whereabouts of parolees.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered a phone call to Coral seeking comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Coral began doing business in California last fall without legal
certification by the PUC. In response to a complaint from the PUC,
Pacific Bell stopped putting Coral's charges on its phone bills by
the beginning of March.
</P>
<P>
   Coral also has been sued by the attorneys general of Illinois
and Missouri for deceptive business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Cramming has grown in recent months to include a wide variety of
unauthorized services _ including psychic hotlines, travel clubs
and other memberships _ charged to phone bills. Federal and state
regulators say it has become a huge problem in just the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In response to consumer complaints about cramming, the Federal
Trade Commission filed charges against three billing companies
yesterday: International Telemedia Associates in Georgia, Online
Consulting Group in Florida and Hold Billing Services in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   An FTC spokeswoman said the agency has received 6,000 consumer
complaints in the past 10 months about cramming. But she said the
consumer protection agency suspects that the real number of victims
is far higher because most people don't notice small charges that
pop up on their bill and thus never realize they've been crammed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a company called Future Telephone Corp. crammed 40,000
people in Southern California with innocuous-sounding ``service
charges'' of $7.95 and a ``tax'' of $1.04, before the Los Angeles
City Attorney's office and PUC shut the fraud down.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC recently turned over a Top-10 list of crammers to the
California District Attorney's Association for investigation. In
the state Legislature, bills in both the Assembly and Senate would
make it much easier for authorities to crack down on unauthorized
phone billing. And Pacific Bell said it no longer will bill for
services not closely related to telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC also has set up a special toll-free number that victims
of Coral can call to help with the investigation: (800) 900-3985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2226EDT &QL; 
