<HEADER>
A9275 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAPATA-SFCHRON &LR;      07-16 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAPATA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Zapata Takes Over Bianca's Smut Shack   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Ay Caramba!
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Houston company named after the movie ``Viva Zapata!''
yesterday bought its 24th Web site since April.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata Corp., a fish processor that is reinventing itself as an
online contender, has purchased San Francisco-based BiancaTroll
Productions Inc., best known for Smut Shack &UR; ,  &LR; a sex-oriented chat
room. Zapata said 80,000 people a day visit Bianca's chat rooms,
which also feature topics such as religion, family and hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Bianca is considered a crucial piece in Zapata's newfound
strategy to create an online community to rival America Online and
cash in on the Internet boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we can tell, (Zapata) seems to have a good grasp on
what they want to do online,'' Bianca co-founder Dave Thau said.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been laughed at before as a fish-oil company going high
tech, but we don't take it personally,'' Zapata CEO Avie Glazer
said. ``And let me assure you, no one is laughing anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Zapata has been on a cyber-shopping spree since late May, when
it drew guffaws from industry observers after it offered $1.7
billion for Excite Inc. The Redwood City-based Internet directory
summarily dismissed the offer, which was faxed at night.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Zapata said it had bought or invested in 21 other Web
sites. Its own Web site, Zap.com, features a flashing sign that
reads, ``Zap will buy your Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst, Jonathan Cohen of New York-based Merrill
Lynch, now recommends the stock after laughing at the Excite bid
while commenting on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Wall Street is beginning to take Zapata seriously. The
company has shown gains in sales and profits during the past two
years and is debt-free with $117 million in cash, according to
Glazer.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata shares rose $1.13 to $22.81 yesterday _ triple the price
where it began this year.
</P>
<P>
   More important, it is fashioning a super Web site, called
Zap.com ( &LR; www.zap.com &LR; ), that incorporates its recently acquired
Web sites and e-commerce services. Among its properties are
Bibliofind, an online book-seller; Mass Music, a CD site; and
Travel Page, for online reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating a site that consumers will want to visit and
have no reason to leave,'' Glazer said. ``We're going to shock a
lot of people and create one of the largest Internet companies in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Glazer said Zapata also has reached agreements to
buy an unspecified number of Internet-related businesses. However,
he declined to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We may never be done (with Net buyouts),'' Glazer said.
</P>
<P>
   Started by former President George Bush in 1953, Zapata has
taken strategic detours before. It began as an oil exploration and
currently makes most of its money selling fish meal and sausage
casings.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that Bush got the company's name after walking by
a marquee advertising the 1952 movie ``Viva Zapata!'' starring
Marlon Brando and Anthony Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said Bush wanted a moniker that could be
listed in the front or back of a telephone book.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sold his stake in the company in 1963. Zapata continued in
the oil business until 1994, when it was taken over by tycoon
Malcom Glazer, Avie's father.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata is just part of the Glazer family's billion-dollar
holding company. Its other properties include the National Football
League's Tampa Bay Buccaneers, TV stations, real estate, restaurant
equipment, banks and health care facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
