s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ROE-Q&AMP;A-ART-$A     07-16 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ROE-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING FLAWS IN AN OLD BAROMETER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 19)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c. 1998 N.Y. Times New Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Return on shareholder equity, often cited as a leading benchmark
of corporate performance, has been running at high levels for a
number of years and is showing few signs of easing.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12 months ended March 31, companies in the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index recorded an average return on equity of 18.5
percent, according to data from Salomon Smith Barney. That is up
from the average rate of 17.9 percent over the last five years and
sharply higher than the 13.7 percent recorded for the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons like these suggest that corporate managers are doing
a good job for shareholders and that stocks are not trading at
wildly inflated prices.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts maintain that the ratio _ which shows the
amount of earnings produced for each dollar shareholders have
invested _ is no longer the solid indicator that it once was, and
that today's numbers overstate how well companies are doing by
their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ciesielski, publisher of the Analyst's Accounting Observer,
a Baltimore-based research service for securities analysts, is one
of the skeptics.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does return on equity give us meaningful information? &QL; 
A. Return on equity is not as accurate an indicator of a company's
performance as it was 15 years ago. It is a scorecard, but I am not
sure it is as good a scorecard as it was in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The really high rates of return you are seeing now are kind
of a mirage, because of things like write-offs, accounting changes,
restructuring charges and stock buybacks.
</P>
<P>
   All of those things are pumping up the rate but they are not
giving us a true return on equity. In short, they create
distortions.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Things like restructuring charges are often one-time
phenomena. Are there factors out there that on an annual basis
contribute to distorted return-on-equity numbers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. One really big booster, and one that has stayed with us, is
Statement of Financial Accounting Standards 106, which forced
companies to cut equity due to their health care liability. That
statement took a big chunk out of equity and put it on the
liability side.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Statement 121, which has to do with hard, long-term
assets. Companies had to assess if those assets were going to
generate their worth in cash flow. It caused a lot of companies to
spring for charges in the mid-1990s, and gave them an incentive to
be aggressive in what they were going to write down.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you saying that in order to look good, some companies
play accounting games to generate a higher return on equity? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think they specifically will try to attain higher
return on equity, because that is not what investors look for in
every quarterly reporting period. Investors are looking for
exciting earnings comparisons. A higher return on equity is a
byproduct of those higher earnings. Coincidentally, earnings drive
return on equity, which may be linked to compensation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there companies or industries where return on equity is
still as valuable a measure as it used to be?
</P>
<P>
   A. I still look at it in particular companies. For example, I
use it when I look at companies that have been relatively free of
charges, or haven't taken a lot of write-downs. Companies in the
services business tend to fall into that category, because they
don't have a lot of hard assets. Over time, the return on equity in
those companies would probably be pretty consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can investors interpret inconsistent return-on-equity
numbers?
</P>
<P>
   A. Measures like return on equity are out there to be analyzed.
But a lot of people just take them at their face value; they don't
massage them.
</P>
<P>
   In order to get a better picture, you have to try and smooth
things out. Instead of excluding charges, for example, you have to
average them out over a number of years. And you have to do the
same thing in the equity denominator, which is determined by
dividing net income by outstanding equity.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you expect the high return-on-equity numbers we have seen
to begin weakening anytime soon?
</P>
<P>
   A. Corporate profitability hasn't slackened that much, so I
don't expect return on equity to start falling a lot. Until you get
flat earnings for a few quarters, I don't think you will see it.
</P>
<P>
   And, as long as there are write-offs, restructurings and the
like, companies can keep the rate of return on equity pumped up.
But is that measure the real sustainable earnings power of the
equity? I am on the fence about that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
