<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKHEED CALLS OFF MERGER WITH NORTHROP GRUMMAN
</P>
<P>
   Faced with continued resistance from the government, Lockheed
Martin has abandoned its planned $8.3 billion acquisition of
Northrop Grumman Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The decision followed months of negotiations between the
companies and the government to avoid a court fight. The deal's
breakup signals the end of a wave of consolidation that swept
through the military industry after the Cold War ended.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. PRESSED IMF ON RUSSIAN AID
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks ago, the International Monetary Fund was playing
down the crisis in Russia. This week, in an about-face, the fund
and the Russian government announced a bailout package that will
inject $17.1 billion in new loans to the nation. The Clinton
administration was the driving force behind the reversal. Treasury
officials were worried that while negotiations with the Russians
dragged on, the political peril to President Boris Yeltsin's
government was growing.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Parliament agreed to a national sales tax, giving
the government a surprise victory in its effort to pass an economic
austerity plan.
</P>
<P>
   UNRESOLVED CHIQUITA QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Despite a furor over The Cincinnati Enquirer's retreat from a
stinging series on reputed influence peddling by Chiquita Brands
International, some of the allegations cannot be dismissed so
easily.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION FALLS
</P>
<P>
   The nation's industrial production declined during June for the
first time in four months. Most of the drop reflected an 11 percent
decline in automotive production because of the General Motors
strike.
</P>
<P>
   MIXED RESULTS FOR COLA GIANTS
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola said earnings fell in the second quarter, but Pepsico
reported a gain in earnings. Pepisco said it released its results
earlier than scheduled because Wall Street had pushed down the
price of its shares about 8 percent this week.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA POSTS 20 PERCENT RISE IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines reported a 20 percent gain in quarterly earnings
on low fuel prices and strong passenger bookings. The results
exceeded expectations, but Delta's stock fell 1.2 percent, to
$135.50, on disappointment the gains were not even stronger. The
stock reached a 52-week high on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   GAINS AT SBC AND AMERITECH
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications and Ameritech, which plan to merge, posted
earnings that were slightly better than expected. Both companies
cited strong demand for data services and heavy sales of features
like call waiting.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONS ON STOCK BUYBACK PLANS
</P>
<P>
   Stock buybacks have typically bolstered share prices. But with
stock prices at record highs, aggressive buybacks look increasingly
dicey.
</P>
<P>
   POSTAL SERVICE'S CYCLING CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service is sponsoring the only U.S.-based team
competing in the Tour de France, the 2,400-mile-long bicycle race
now under way. Why cycling as a marketing opportunity? For one, the
Postal Service is getting a fair amount of exposure, helped by the
surprisingly strong showing of George Hincapie of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   TAPES HEARD IN PRICE-FIXING CASE
</P>
<P>
   In the price-fixing trial of three former Archer Daniels Midland
executives, secret government recordings of discussions on pricing
lysine, a food additive, were played in public for the first time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
