<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Nasdaq Breaks 2,000 Barrier   By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The Nasdaq composite index pushed past 2,000 yesterday for the
first time _ just three years minus a day after it first topped
1,000.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It marked another triumph for the nation's leading
high-technology companies, which dominate the 5,104-company Nasdaq
index and have sent it soaring more than 27 percent so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Things were touch and go throughout the day, as the index _
which closed Wednesday at 1,994.54 _ repeatedly bobbed above the
2,000 barrier, then retreated.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers let out a collective groan when it appeared _
just after the close at 1 p.m. Pacific Standard Time _ that the
index had fallen short by the scantest of margins, finishing at
1,999.99.
</P>
<P>
   But the final settlement of trades in the minute or two after
the close sent the index creeping up to 2,000.56 _ a gain of 6.02
points, or 0.3 percent, on the day.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Walker, a spokesman for Nasdaq, said market officials
didn't pop any champagne corks or otherwise celebrate the
penetration of the 2,000 barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The celebration is in the companies,'' he said. ``It's their
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly ignored in the cliff-hanging excitement was the fact that
the other leading market indexes _ the Dow Jones industrial average
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 _ performed better than the Nasdaq
yesterday and also set new records.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, made up of 30 blue-chip companies, surged beyond 9,300
for the first time, finishing up 93.72 points, or 1.0 percent, at
9.328.19.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500, composed almost entirely of the largest companies
traded on the New York Stock Exchange, gained 9.21 points, or 0.8
percent, to 1,184.02.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was created on Feb. 5, 1971 at a
starting value of 100. It consists of all 5,104 issues on the
Nasdaq National Market and the Nasdaq Small Cap Market.
</P>
<P>
   Its 20-fold increase in value since Day One works out to an
average annual gain of 11.5 percent. That is well ahead of both the
S&AMP;P 500 and the Dow, which averaged 9.5 percent and 9.0 percent
annual gains respectively during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Market analysts point out that because the Nasdaq composite is
weighted by market capitalization, seven companies determine more
than 30 percent of the index's movement. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Most of those seven _ Microsoft, Intel, Cisco Systems, Dell
Computer, WorldCom, MCI Communications and Oracle _ have been
extremely strong performers this year, offsetting the lagging
performance of thousands of other Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nasdaq as a whole is not doing quite so well,'' said Rick
Eakle, of Eakle Associates in Fair Haven, N.J. ``The index is being
distorted by a handful of names.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, the biggest company in the index by far with 12.2
percent of the total market value, has gained 81.6 percent this
year. Dell is up an astounding 170.8 percent, WorldCom is up 81.5
percent, Cisco is up 71.7 percent and MCI is up 56.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only members of the Big Seven that have trailed the overall
Nasdaq index this year are Oracle, which nevertheless has gained
24.1 percent, and Intel, which is up 19.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Turner, president of Pring Turner Capital Management in San
Ramon, suggested that investors should look for bargains among the
smaller Nasdaq stocks that have ``languished,'' rather than trying
to ride the big companies to further gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking for bargains _ that's the only fascination I find in
this new record,'' he said. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Alfred Goldman, a technical analyst with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Son in
St. Louis, said it is ``interesting that Nasdaq made it to the
millennium before mankind did.'' He expects it to keep surging over
the near term, because ``the economy is good'' and ``the mood and
outlook about the Asian crisis has turned more positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Welty, of Welty Capital Management in Lafayette, noted that
Microsoft _ which reported a strong quarterly earnings gain after
the market closed yesterday _ now has a market capitalization of
more than $300 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The only other company that matches it, he said, is General
Electric, ``which has six or seven times Microsoft's revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is now trading at 66 times last year's earnings.
It's a dilemma trying to decide what to tell clients who hold the
stock. Five years from now it probably will be higher, but there is
no room for error.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
