<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TO REDUCE POLLUTION FROM LAKE BED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Striking a compromise after decades of bitter
conflict, representatives of Los Angeles and the Owens Valley
agreed on Wednesday to a plan for reducing severe air pollution 225
miles north of here on the dry bed of Owens Lake, which Los Angeles
drained in the 1920s to build its modern metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   The 110-square-mile lake, on the eastern slope of the Sierra
Nevada, is the single worst source of air pollution in the United
States, and air quality officials in the Owens Valley had wanted
Los Angeles to cover some 35 square miles of the lake bed in a mix
of gravel, water and vegetation to hold down dust storms that
violate air quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, officials of the Los Angeles Department of Water
and Power and the Great Basin Unified Air Pollution Control
District agreed to a plan in which Los Angeles will treat 10 square
miles of the lake by 2001 and an additional 6.5 miles by 2003. At
that time, Owens Valley officials will review the effects and
propose a new plan for meeting federal air standards by 2006. If
Los Angeles does not agree with that plan, it will still have to
treat an additional two square miles of the lake bed each year
until the standards are met.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
