<SLUG> BC-GLF-JAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMMEL ISN'T MAIN ATTRACTION, BUT SHE STEALS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ After a convivial practice round on
Tuesday, Nancy Lopez conceded that she had won a few dollars from
Se Ri Pak in an informal ``closest-to-the-hole'' competition.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Lopez, 41, and Pak, 20, played for real in the
opening round of the JAL Big Apple Classic, and again Lopez came
out ahead. Grouped with Pak and a former JAL winner, Hiromi
Kobayashi of Japan, in front of by far the biggest gallery of the
day, Lopez fired a 3-under-par 68 while Pak carded a 1-over 72.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez's performance overshadowed that of another veteran,
36-year-old Penny Hammel, who has won four tournaments in a 14-year
pro career and had Thursday's best round at 64. Hammel's round,
which included an eagle and six birdies, was one stroke off the JAL
record of 63, set by Betsy King in 1990 in the event's first year.
</P>
<P>
   On a hazy and humid day when more than two dozen players broke
par on the tough 6,161-yard Wykagyl Country Club course, Hammel's
64 gave her a three-stroke lead over a group that included Annika
Sorenstam, a two-time winner of the U.S. Women's Open, and veteran
Juli Inkster, whose 16 titles include the 1992 JAL.
</P>
<P>
   Pak burst into prominence in the last two weeks by winning the
U.S. Women's Open and the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic, where she shot
a tour-record round of 61 last Friday. On Thursday, she started
strong with birdies at Nos. 2 and 3. But then three bogies, at Nos.
5, 12 and 16, left her with a 72. For Lopez it was the reverse. She
three-putted the first hole for her only bogey, then birdied Nos.
3, 5, 12 and 15. Later, Lopez, who missed the cut in her last three
outings, including the Open, conceded that playing with Pak
inspired her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Se Ri is a lot of fun, but it also gives you more
momentum,'' said Lopez, who has 48 titles.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said that playing with Pak _ who earlier this year won the
McDonald's LPGA Championship to become just the second rookie,
after Inkster, to win two majors _ evoked memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all reminds me of 20 years ago,'' Lopez said, referring to
her rookie year in 1978, when she won nine tournaments, including
five in a row.
</P>
<P>
   While as many as 1,000 spectators followed Lopez, Pak and
Kobayashi (who shot a 74), Hammel fashioned her 64 in virtual
anonymity. But Hammel, who is from Decatur, Ill., did not mind.
Having had only one top-10 finish in 18 tournaments this year, she
did not expect a large gallery. Nor did she expect to putt so well.
</P>
<P>
   She hit a 45-foot putt for an eagle at the par-5, 432-yard 15th
hole, after reaching in two with a 5-wood. Hammel also sank birdie
putts of 30, 25 and 20 feet at Nos. 6, 16 and 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
