<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUNS-SCHUMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER LOOKS TO GUN CONTROL FOR JOLT TO CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``It is painful for all of us to refight a battle
once won,'' Sarah Brady, the gun-control advocate, said earlier
this week in announcing legislation that would extend a law named
after her husband, James, that expires this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the man fidgeting silently behind Mrs. Brady on the podium
seemed anything but pained. Rep. Charles Schumer, the New York City
Democrat who is seeking his party's nomination for the U.S. Senate,
is unabashedly excited that Congress is about to launch into a
potentially contentious debate over a law he helped write.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to distinguish himself from his Democratic rivals,
and facing criticism that he has lost effectiveness in Congress,
Schumer is counting on a loud and protracted gun-control fight with
conservative Republicans and the National Rifle Association to
inject some spark into his campaign _ just in time for the Sept. 15
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a dynamite issue in the campaign,'' he said in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   To Schumer and his aides, a full-throated debate on the Brady
law would be political manna, rekindling memories of one of
Schumer's greatest legislative victories. He was an author and
sponsor of the original Brady bill, which required background
checks and a five-day waiting period for handgun buyers in most
states.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's passage in 1993 represented a stunning defeat for
the powerful NRA, and it transformed Schumer from just another
aggressive New York politician into a national figure. He became a
ubiquitous presence on television, a spokesman for the gun-control
movement and the target of death threats. (He even took to wearing
homemade disguises when traveling in potentially hostile areas,
like the Rocky Mountains.)
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30, the waiting-period requirement is scheduled to
expire. The rifle association and its allies, including the
Republican leadership in both houses, want it to die. Schumer and
gun-control advocates, including many police organizations, want to
extend it. The gun-control advocates have named their new bill
Brady 2, and they clearly hope the sequel will have the same
triumphant ending as the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be one of the few battle royals of this
Congress,'' contended Schumer, who has already begun spotlighting
gun control in speeches and commercials.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the Democrats in the race _ Schumer, Geraldine
Ferraro and Mark Green _ are strong supporters of gun control. But
Schumer is the most closely identified with the issue, pollsters
say. And now, having languished in second or third place in public
opinion polls, Schumer is clearly looking to a high-profile debate
to boost his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   First, a well-publicized battle could help close the
name-recognition gap separating him from Ms. Ferraro, the former
congresswoman and Vice-Presidential candidate, who is widely viewed
as the front-runner in the primary. Second, political strategists
say that gun control is popular among women, whom Ms. Ferraro is
counting on to overwhelmingly support her.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also contends that gun control spotlights one of his
central campaign pledges. ``I can get things done,'' he said. ``I'm
given the credit for being the person who routed the NRA for the
first time in 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer says the real benefit will come in the general
election, if he reaches that point, against the three-term
Republican incumbent, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato is admired by detractors and supporters alike for his
ability to champion traditionally Democratic issues, like
increasing federal spending to fight breast cancer. But gun control
is not one of them; D'Amato has consistently voted against major
gun-control legislation, including the Brady bill, and his aides
suggested he probably would again this year.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle association has returned his support. Since 1991, its
political action committee has spent more than $21,000 helping his
campaigns, campaign finance records show.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato maintains that tougher criminal penalties against people
who commit crimes with guns is the best way to reduce gun violence.
And Republican strategists, as well as some Democratic ones, say
gun control is unlikely to be a factor in the fall elections, since
crime is down and voters seem generally content with incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer contends that D'Amato's gun-control positions show
he is beholden to special-interest groups and is out of step with
mainstream New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one person in the whole United States of America
who wishes this hadn't come up, it is probably Al D'Amato,'' he
said, chuckling. ``New York is probably the most pro-gun-control
state in the country. Running against him is the leading
gun-control advocate. It's almost a high-noon drama.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, potential risks in Schumer's strategy. While
a fight over Brady 2 could recall Schumer's triumphs, it also
serves as a reminder that those victories occurred four years ago _
and that he has had few accomplishments to boast of since.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the passage of the Brady law in 1993, followed by
enactment of the ban on assault weapons in 1994 _ a law that
Schumer also helped write _ were the pinnacle of his 18-year tenure
in Congress. But along came the Republican tide of 1994, relegating
Schumer to the minority.
</P>
<P>
   He relished that position for a time, lustily attacking
Republicans as radical right-wingers when they tried to cut social
programs or shut down the federal government. But when the
Republicans began working with President Clinton, to change welfare
or balance the budget, for example, Schumer's protest role was
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, because of his campaign schedule, he has missed
significantly more votes than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Though he contends he has done more than most Democrats in the
House, Schumer said it was inevitable that he would lose impact in
the minority. That is a major reason he wants to move to the
Senate, where one person has far more power to enact legislation
than in the more rule-bound House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
