<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BROOKLYN-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN ENTERTAINMENT COMPLEX PLANNED AT GOWANUS CANAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sign that developers are increasingly forced to
scout out unlikely locales for new projects, a Manhattan company
said Thursday it would build a huge entertainment complex along the
Gowanus Canal in Brooklyn that would include the city's largest
multiplex movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   The project, to be known as Brooklyn Commons, would be part of a
stark modern steel and glass complex contrasting sharply with the
surrounding ragtag assemblage of what was once one of the city's
busiest manufacturing zones.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a 22-screen Loews theater, the complex would include a
bowling alley, athletic center, shops, restaurants, a 1,500-car
parking garage and a public esplanade along the Gowanus Canal. The
canal was dug in the 1860s to provide a manufacturing lifeline to
the New York Harbor but has been largely neglected in recent
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project is an indication that there is great market
demand to develop parts of town where, years ago, people would have
considered such things idle fantasy,'' said city Planning
Commissioner Joseph Rose, who has been a persistent advocate of
luring builders to little-used industrial areas, sometimes through
zoning changes.
</P>
<P>
   The developer, Millennium Partners, has several entertainment
complexes across the nation, including the Lincoln Square Complex
of movie theaters in Manhattan. The company plans to spend $63
million on the Gowanus project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having built entertainment centers of this kind before, we are
confident that New York City residents and visitors will find this
an exciting gathering place,'' Millennium Partners president
Christopher Jeffries said at a City Hall news conference with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the project, planned for completion by 2000, could
be built without zoning changes and would not receive city tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, plans for the entertainment complex have not received
unqualified support from residents of the surrounding neighborhoods
of Park Slope and Carroll Gardens. The project is to be built on
the west side of Second Avenue, from 10th Street to 12th Street, on
land owned by the U.S. Postal Service. People in the neighborhood
said they worried about the traffic the complex would generate, and
wanted assurances that it would provide employment opportunities
and retail space for local residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this project is done properly, it can be wonderful,'' said
Ben Meskin, president of Care About the Slope, a community group
representing the south end of Park Slope. ``We just want the
developers to talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen DiBrienza, a City Council member representing
surrounding neighborhoods, said Thursday that the mayor's news
conference announcing the project had come as a shock to many
residents who did not think the developers had satisfied their
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``This an example of the mayor, in making this sound like a done
deal, putting his cart way out ahead of the horse,'' he said,
adding that Brooklyn residents may file suit to block the project
because of what he called ``shoddy and inaccurate'' information
contained in an environmental review of the property by the Postal
Service.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's announcement came after a succession of meetings
among the developers, neighborhood representatives and elected
officials earlier this week at the behest of Nydia Velasquez, the
Brooklyn congresswoman. Ms. Velasquez said she had persuaded the
Postal Service to postpone signing a lease on the property until
discussions took place involving Meskin, DiBrienza and other
neighborhood representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions clearly did not satisfy everyone. DiBrienza said
Thursday that developers had been ``evasive and unresponsive.'' But
Ms. Velasquez said executives of Millennium Partners had ``made it
clear they want to work with the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   In one concession, she said, the developers had agreed to
conduct a traffic study before they begin construction, and had
indicated that they would provide signs, streetlights or other
improvements that would ease congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Marcus, chief executive of Insite, a development company
working with Millennium on the project, said late Thursday that a
99-year lease on the Postal Service property had been finalized.
Under terms of the agreement, the developers will pay $500,000 a
year for the 9.4-acre site, demolish one Postal Service building
that until the early 1990s was used as a vehicle maintenance
garage, and incorporate another Postal Service building on the
site, formerly Brooklyn's main mail sorting center, into their
complex.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn project comes amid a surge of development at
long-derelict sites elsewhere in the city. Just a mile away from
the Gowanus site, developers have transformed the long-abandoned
area above the Atlantic Terminal railway station into a huge
shopping complex, and there are plans for further development of
the site. And at the site of the former Washburn Wire factory in
East Harlem, developers announced in March that they would build a
retail complex, with Home Depot and Costco as major tenants.
</P>
<P>
   The plans for the Gowanus site were announced a week after
Marriott Corp. opened a 367-room hotel in downtown Brooklyn, which
officials hailed as a sign that the borough _ which suffered steep
losses in manufacturing employment extending over decades _ is
bouncing back economically.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an absolutely remarkable investment that will aid in
the resurgence of Brooklyn,'' Giuliani said of the Gowanus project.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
