<SLUG> BC-CALIF-QUAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S EARTHQUAKE RISK COULD BE GREATER THAN WAS BELIEVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geologists have found evidence that the land on which Los
Angeles rests was rocked by severe earthquakes at least twice in
the last 15,000 years, suggesting that the present risk for the
city may be substantially greater than was believed.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the two ancient quakes was found at a site 11 miles
north of downtown Los Angeles, the scientists reported in the
journal Science, and the shocks were estimated to have ranged in
strength from 7.2 to 7.6 on the Richter scale, sufficient to cause
enormous damage to the city if they should be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the geologists who reached this conclusion, Dr.
Charles Rubin of Central Washington University in Ellensburg,
Wash., said in an interview Thursday that the discovery did not
mean that a severe earthquake was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a geologist, and we don't make predictions,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The study by Rubin and his colleagues at San Diego State
University and William Lettis &AMP; Associates, a Valencia, Calif.,
geosciences company, was sponsored by the National Science
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said his work began with a study of photographs made in
the 1920s before building in the Los Angeles area obliterated the
long, continuous cliffs, or scarps, separating two ground levels,
which are associated with the Sierra Madre fault along the southern
flank of the San Gabriel Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scarps created by slippage of this fault have been mostly
leveled, paved, or built up over the years,'' he said, ``but we
found one surviving scarp in Loma Alta Park in suburban Altadena.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutting through the sediments, the geologists found a faulted
region where adjoining layers of sediment were offset from each
other in two places, as they would be after large earthquakes. By
studying the aftereffects of modern earthquakes, geologists have
determined that the degree of fault slippage is related to the
severity of the quake. From the fact that slippage of the fault was
measured as about 17 feet, Rubin and his associates calculated that
the quakes ranged in severity from 7.2 to 7.6 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed with the gravel that filled the space between faulted rock
sediments were particles of charcoal from ancient fires. Using a
dating technique that measures the quantity of carbon-14 in the
charcoal, the scientists determined that the age of the quakes was
10,000 years or younger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
