<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO LATE FOR BRAWLEY TO TESTIFY, JUDGE RULES
</HEADLINE>
 (js) 
By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ For more than a decade, Tawana Brawley's
advisers refused to let her testify about her allegations that she
was raped by a gang of white men _ both to the grand jury
originally investigating the case and in the defamation lawsuit
against the advisers that followed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the lawyer for one of the advisers said he wanted
to call Miss Brawley in the damages phase of the defamation case.
But the judge, S. Barrett Hickman of state Supreme Court, refused
to allow it, saying it was too late for Miss Brawley to testify on
the underlying questions of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the jury has determined the falsity of the
allegation that she was raped'' by the plaintiff, Steven Pagones,
and she cannot testify on that question, Hickman wrote in a letter
to the lawyer, Stephen Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is now hearing evidence only on the amount of damages
to assess against the three advisers, the Rev. Al Sharpton, Alton
Maddox and C. Vernon Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brawley has never appeared at the trial and was not in
court Thursday. But Jackson, Mason's lawyer, made the surprise
announcement of his desire to call her and of the judge's ruling
barring the request in front of the jury Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The move spurred an immediate battle of interpretations outside
of court, with each side portraying the fight over Miss Brawley's
reported willingness to testify as a measure of the other side's
desire to suppress the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he had not called Miss Brawley during the first
phase of the case because the defense had no legal burden to prove
anything. Now, however, he said, ``it's important for the history
of this case that Tawana participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason said that the decision barring her testimony showed ``she
is being prevented from telling her story.'' The defense supplied
the judge's letter dated Wednesday to reporters, apparently to
prove that the judge had barred them from calling Miss Brawley.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones said the offer to call Miss Brawley was a ``publicity
stunt'' and that the defense could have provided her testimony at
any time since the advisers said more than a decade ago that
Pagones had been part of a group of white men who assaulted her.
</P>
<P>
   William Stanton, Pagones' lawyer, told reporters that the
announcement by Mason's lawyer was ``so he can stand on a soapbox
and say the judge refused to let him call Tawana and you people
will print it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brawley is a defendant in the case along with her advisers.
She has never appeared at their trial and was not here Thursday;
Pagones had previously won a judgment against her by default.
Although damages are to be assessed against her by the judge
instead of the jury, Hickman has repeatedly stated that she is
welcome to appear in court if she so desires.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Any such appearance, he said in his letter on Wednesday, would
be as a defendant. He said he knew of no law ``that would justify
or warrant testimony from Miss Brawley on behalf of any
co-defendant'' at this stage of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The new battle over whether Miss Brawley will testify occurred
as the trial returned to the snail's pace that caused the first
phase of the case to last nearly eight months.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers argued that Pagones suffered no damages. To
try to prove the point, Jackson called Pagones to the stand. The
defense lawyers then began questioning him through the day, just as
they did for more than 20 days during the first phase of the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the questioning, they tried to cast doubt on Pagones' claim
that he suffered anxiety and other symptoms as the result of their
assertions. The defense lawyers also suggested that his reputation
was never injured in his community. His testimony is to continue on
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
