<SLUG> BC-NY-BOMB-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT TRIAL, EXPERT DESCRIBES CONSTRUCTION OF PIPE BOMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A powerful pipe bomb that prosecutors say two men
planned to explode in the city subway system was studded with large
construction nails that would have increased its potential to kill
or mutilate its victims, a bomb expert testified Thursday at the
men's trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other function the nails serve,'' the expert,
Thomas J. Mohnal of the FBI, told a jury in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn at the trial of the men, Gazi Ibrahim Abu Mezer, 24, and
Lafi Khalil, 23. Prosecutors contend that the two Palestinian
immigrants had planned to detonate the bomb aboard a subway train
that serves a Jewish neighborhood _ the Borough Park section of
Brooklyn _ because of their hatred of Israel and opposition to the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   By showing that scores of 4-inch-long nails had been made part
of what was already a powerful pipe bomb, the government could make
it harder for Abu Mezer's lawyers to convince the jury of their
main argument.
</P>
<P>
   In their opening statement in the two-week-old trial, the
lawyers did not dispute that Abu Mezer had the bomb in his Brooklyn
apartment when the police raided it last July, but they maintained
that he had not intended to explode the device and inflict death
and destruction. Rather, the lawyers suggested that he had planned
to use the bomb as a prop in a hazy plot to defraud a government
antiterrorism program of reward money.
</P>
<P>
   But in his description of the bomb, Mohnal told the jurors that
``it's clearly an antipersonnel device,'' adding that it was
``built with additional shrapnel _ fragmentation _ designed to
cause injury.'' As he testified, Mohnal pointed to a mock-up of the
bomb that the FBI had built.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers, like the prosecutors in the case, have
repeatedly declined to assess the evidence for reporters or to
comment on how they planned to respond to it in their closing
arguments, expected next week.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Padden, one of Abu Mezer's lawyers, told Judge Reena
Raggi that his client would decide over the weekend whether he
would testify, though Padden also told the judge that he and the
other lawyer for Abu Mezer, Jan Rostal, had concerns about their
client taking the witness stand. Padden did not elaborate on the
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Khalil's lawyer, Bruce McIntyre, exercised his right not to make
an opening statement to the jury. However, Khalil told
investigators after he and Abu Mezer were arrested that he had not
known that the bomb existed. Both Khalil and Abu Mezer are charged
with conspiring to use a weapon of mass destruction and threatening
to use a weapon of mass destruction. Khalil is also charged with
immigration fraud and Abu Mezer with possessing the bomb. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-NYT &LR;      07-16 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM AGASSI AND COURIER, OPENING SALUTES FOR DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Time was when it took a bit of arm-twisting to
persuade Andre Agassi and Jim Courier to shoehorn patriotism, in
the form of Davis Cup duty, into their itineraries. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the veterans handling the singles roles this weekend
in the Davis Cup quarterfinal are ready volunteers, just like the
giddy parcel of overachievers from Belgium across the net from them
in this round, just like the Russian underdogs the Americans
squeaked past, 3-2, in the first round in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everywhere except in the United States, playing in the
Davis Cup is viewed as a privilege and not an imposition. Almost
everywhere except in the United States, the competition is awarded
historic significance on a Grand Slam level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camaraderie is an underrated part of playing tennis, but Davis
Cup, if you use it in the right way for your own personal goals,
can actually add to your career and your season, and all of our
players need to understand that,'' said Tom Gullikson, who is in
his fifth year as the captain of the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson was so appreciative that the 19th-ranked Agassi and
the 48th-ranked Courier understand that Davis Cup participation is
worth their while, that for the first time he made no pretense of
courting the higher-ranked Pete Sampras and Michael Chang for this
round.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's draw ceremony at the glass-domed Arts Garden, even
Pierre Paul De Keghel, the president of the Royal Belgium Tennis
Federation, complimented Gullikson on his choice of personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted and honored to face the famous American Davis
Cup team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Famous, maybe. Available, definitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it gets a little tiring, that recruiting thing,''
said Gullikson, who simply reinstated his Round 1 combination of
Agassi, Courier, Todd Martin and Richey Reneberg for Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday on the familiar hardcourts at the Indianapolis Tennis
Center, Courier will open the five-match test against Filip Dewulf,
the 43rd-ranked Belgian who reached the French Open semifinals last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Then Agassi, again holding down the top singles spot for the
United States, will take on the 159th-ranked Christophe Van Garsse.
</P>
<P>
   Van Garsse is an unlikely spark plug who came through in the
fifth match of Belgium's upset of France, moving the team back into
the elite 16 nation World Group. And then an upset of the
Netherlands put the team into a Davis Cup quarterfinal for the
first time since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   According to Agassi, the left-handed, stubble-faced Van Garsse
has already proved himself a quintessential Davis Cup competitor.
</P>
<P>
   When Agassi and Courier were No. 1 in the world, they sometimes
shunned this event just the way Sampras, citing tennis overkill,
does now.
</P>
<P>
   But after disheartening early round losses at the French Open
and Wimbledon, both veterans have acknowledged that instead of the
Davis Cup needing them, they need it to help jump-start their
summer hardcourt campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely something that I need now,'' Agassi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
