<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CROUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUANCE MAKES ROOM FOR BABY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kristine Quance's immediate future in swimming
hung in the balance of the test result. No way could it come up
positive, the former Granada Hills High standout told herself. When
it did, she felt awful, like she had disappointed everybody who had
helped her become a 1996 Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   Quance did not fail a drug test, like her would-be Goodwill
Games teammate Gary Hall Jr. The 23-year-old newlywed passed a
pregnancy test. As the ostensibly glorious news was delivered to
her, Quance's first reaction was that this was a slip-up far worse
than Hall's.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs, after all, eventually leave one's system without a trace.
But the new life growing inside of her was going to change her body
for the next nine months and her life forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really upset at first,'' Quance, who was married in
April, said Thursday. ``I was thinking, what have I done to my
swimming (career)? This is something that's supposed to be great,
but I felt like it was bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Quance can see that her thinking was all wet.
She and her husband, Jeff Julian, himself a former world-class
swimmer, have come to view impending parenthood for what it is: one
of life's most precious gifts.
</P>
<P>
   As for swimming, well, it always has been a most demanding
suitor, taking everything from Quance, including, at times, her
self-image. It can wear on you, second-guessing your place in the
world just because you can't break 4:40 in the 400-meter individual
medley. Forced to take stock of her priorities, Quance realized
that, as much as she'd like to be remembered as a world-record
holder, being a mother was a magnificent achievement in and of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that family's the most important thing,''
Quance said. ``Jeff and I always said we were going to have kids,
but after I was done swimming. So when I found out I was pregnant,
I had such mixed emotions. Sometimes I feel terrible that I had
such selfish reasons to be upset about it. I mean, swimming is
important, but it's not my whole life. It can't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Quance would be lying if she said there aren't times _
like right now, when some of her friends are fine-tuning their
preparation for the Goodwill Games in New York _ that she doesn't
regard her pregnancy as a real mixed blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Quance was to represent the U.S. in the 200-meter individual
medley in a series of dual meets against squads from China, Germany
and a cosmopolitan team composed of foreign-born collegiate stars.
(The games begin on Sunday; swimming on July 28.)
</P>
<P>
   The former USC star had been looking forward to going
head-to-head against the Chinese ever since she was beaten by two
swimmers from that country in her specialty, the 400 IM, at the
World Championships in Perth, Australia, in January.
</P>
<P>
   She regretfully pulled out of the competition a few weeks ago,
after a full month of nausea and fatigue had run roughshod over her
once-sturdy training regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see any more soda crackers or ginger ale,''
Quance cracked before heading off to her daily session in the pool
with fellow members of the Trojan Swim Club.
</P>
<P>
   Quance plans to continue training right up until the day she
delivers, though she has scaled back the intensity of her workouts
after reading all the literature she can find on exercising during
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I'm really worried about is everything I've
read says your heart rate shouldn't get above 140 or 150,'' said
the ultra-competitive Quance, who has been known to get her blood
pumping faster than that in the eighth lap of warmups.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody can round back into world-class form after having a
baby it figures to be Quance. She barely missed qualifying for the
1992 Olympics after contracting mononucleosis right before the U.S.
selection meet.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, she was disqualified from the 400 IM, the
event in which she was a consensus pre-Olympic favorite, in the
prelims of the U.S. trials. And last year, she saw the 400 IM world
record she long has coveted get claimed by a swimmer from China,
where the use of performance-enhancing drugs reportedly is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Quance has risen to ride out every challenge to this point, and
she's not about to bail out now. Her baby is due in January, which
will give her a little over a year to regain her form before the
U.S. team is selected for the Summer Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Trojan Swim Club coach Mark Schubert already has run down the
list of female athletes who came back from a pregnancy to perform
even better than before, including Quance's 1996 Olympic teammate,
sprint butterfly specialist Crissy Ahmann-Leighton.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Quance is content to live in the moment.
Goodness knows she has spent enough of her life looking a few
months and even four years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last six years I've had a total of two weeks off from
swimming,'' Quance said. ``They say everything happens for the
best, and maybe this was the only thing that would make me take a
break from the sport. Honestly, I probably needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   And honestly? Quance is doing just fine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
