<SLUG> BC-BKL-WOMEN'SLEAGUES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABL NEEDS WNBA STYLE TV EXPOSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television exposure. Just how important is it to college seniors
seeking fame and glory on the women's pro basketball scene in the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   Well, according to the American Basketball League it played a
major role in the rival WNBA snagging the top seniors this year,
which is why it was thrilled to get two championship series games
on CBS the next two seasons, and why it hopes to improve its
overall television package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, television was a big factor in the recruiting battle
this year,'' said Gary Cavalli, ABL CEO and co-founder. ``Some of
the top players who signed with the WNBA sighted television as one
of the main reasons they did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing is believing. And that's what the WNBA presented to
recruits last summer when it got great lead-in exposure from the
NBA playoffs. It broadcasted 34 games, including the playoffs, with
key games targeted for Saturday on NBC, and the others on
widely-recognized ESPN and Lifetime. This year 30 regular season
games can be seen on the same networks, and the expanded playoffs
are expected to be televised, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL, whose nine teams played a 44-game season compared to
the WNBA's 10-team 30-game season, had only 35 games televised in a
six month season, all on Fox Sports Net and BET, which is not
available in some areas. To make matters worse, some of the games
were taped delayed, including a few from the championship series.
Cavalli said he hoped to minimize that problem when he announces
the expanded television package next week.
</P>
<P>
   While TV played a role, it was not necessarily a deciding factor
in some seniors' decisions to play for the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a high priority for the Sparks' Allison Feaster, whose
only television appearance at Harvard was the NCAA first-round game
against Stanford, which was upset by the Crimsom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a factor, but I'm not sure how big it was,'' said
Feaster, the fifth pick in the draft. ``It was important that the
WNBA was really well planned out, the league would be well
publicized so that people will have a chance to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did consider the ABL. I chose the WNBA for other reasons.
The season was a huge factor for me. I wanted to do other things
the eight months that I'm out.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a key issue for Sacramento Monarchs' Ticha Penicherio,
the All-American from Old Dominion and Portugal native who was
picked second in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family and friends are overseas,'' said Penicherio. ``For
me it was the perfect fit, because I can play here and be exposed
in the states and then go back home and have the opportunity to
play. It really depends on what you want as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   But certainly with WNBA games on TV it made it easier for
players to get some insight into the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not just TV, but the whole thing,'' Penicherio said.
``I had the opportunity to follow the WNBA last year and we could
feel through the TV the excitement, the fans, the crowds, how much
fun the fans and the players were having. We have a lot of games on
TV in order to promote players. But that was not the main reason
why I came to the WNBA, but definitely I thought about it. It was
one of the things that made me come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much advertising of it,'' said Sparks forward
Octavia Blue, a second-round pick from Miami. ``I just wanted to
play in a nice arena, get the exposure, the TV exposure. I just
wanted to be a part of it, especially since it's just getting
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Penicherio, who did not decide with which league to sign until
the 11th hour on WNBA draft day, said she saw her old teammate,
Clarisse Machanguana, of the ABL's San Jose Lasers, channel surfing
one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise there's not a lot of marketing of the (ABL) games so
people sometimes are not aware that the games are on TV,''
Penicherio said. ``It's unfortunate because they have really good
games, and good players, and good competition. But sometimes you're
just flipping the channels and say, `Oh my god, the ABL has a game
on,' but you're really not aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   Neilson ratings for the WNBA through five games are 2.0 on NBC,
.74 on ESPN and .52 on Lifetime, not far from last year's overall
average, except for ESPN which was .9 last year. ... As far as
Michael Jordan's involvement in the ABL's new Chicago franchise,
Cavalli said he has not been in contact with the NBA superstar
regarding investing in the team and figured the most Jordan would
probably do is make some appearances at games to support his former
teammate Craig Hodges, a former Long Beach State standout, whose
wife, Allison, is general manager of the expansion team. ... Talks
are ongoing between the ABL and Philadelphia Rage point guard Dawn
Staley, who is rumored to be entertaining the thought of joining
the WNBA. ... Jennifer Gillom was the WNBA Player of the Week after
posting 26 points and 10 rebounds in two victories for the Phoenix
Mercury last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks 3-on-3 hoops
</P>
<P>
   The first Sparks 3-on-3 Basketball Tournament will be held this
weekend at the Venice beach basketball courts. The divisions are
for girls 18-under, 16-under, 14-under, 12-under, 10-under and
women adult competitive and recreational. The entry fee for
four-player teamis $100. Registration is 7:30 to 9 a.m. Saturday
before the competition. The tournament resumes Sunday at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
