<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE OF FORGERY, BUT NO SIGN OF MISSING WIDOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police officers searching for a missing Upper East
Side socialite said Thursday that they had found evidence of a
forgery operation, but no sign of the missing woman, after a tip
led them to the New Jersey Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The Carlstadt, N.J., police began searching the area near Giants
Stadium on Tuesday after a local factory worker reported seeing a
couple several weeks ago in a Lincoln that resembled the one used
by the leading suspects in the disappearance of the socialite,
Irene Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   Officers who combed the area with police dogs found about 50
Social Security cards that had apparently been filled out by
someone practicing a signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like somebody was practicing their forgery,'' said
Detective Sgt. Michael Barbire, a spokesman for the Carlstadt
police.
</P>
<P>
   New York City police officers searched the area on Wednesday
night and Thursday, using police dogs and scuba divers to search
through a creek. No signs of Mrs. Silverman were found, Barbire
said.
</P>
<P>
   The factory worker recalled seeing an odd-looking couple in a
green Lincoln there on July 1, several days before Mrs. Silverman
disappeared. The worker, who was not identified, told police that
he saw a woman sitting in the car and then watched in surprise as a
man emerged from some nearby reeds, got in and drove off.
</P>
<P>
   The worker then went on vacation. When he returned last
Saturday, he read news accounts of the case and learned that the
leading suspects, Kenneth Kimes and his mother, Sante Kimes, drove
a green Lincoln. He called the local police, and they began the
search.
</P>
<P>
   Barbire said that the name Silverman was not found on the Social
Security cards. Investigators said the results of DNA tests on hair
and saliva found in the Kimeses' car had not been received
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, lawyers for the Kimeses announced
that they would ask a judge Friday to free both of their clients on
bail. Mel Sachs, a defense lawyer who is now representing Kimes,
said he and Mrs. Kimes' lawyer were appealing a decision by a
Manhattan judge last week to hold them without bail until Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution will have to give a basis for holding him,''
Sachs said. ``What proof is there that he should be held?''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said the police investigation into Mrs. Silverman's
disappearance had so far produced no evidence linking Kimes to the
missing millionaire's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   But an official in the Manhattan District Attorney's office said
investigators had significant evidence linking the Kimeses to Mrs.
Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have not made a decision about charging the two
because they can be held for up to 90 days in New York before they
must be extradited to Utah, where they are charged with writing a
bad check.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of a charge at this point is not a comment at all on
the evidence,'' the official said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``At the appropriate time, we will size up what we
have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
