<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0506 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COLUMN-GUNFIRE-NY     07-16 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COLUMN-GUNFIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DISTURBING THE PEACE TO KEEP IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a stir last week when the Police Department
said that its officers would soon load their 9-millimeter Glocks
with new ammunition, replacing full-metal-jacket bullets with
hollow-point bullets.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you unfamiliar with such matters, the
full-metal-jacket types have a way of passing through their
intended targets and striking what are customarily, and
meaninglessly, referred to as innocent bystanders. (The
``Seinfeld'' finale aside, how many guilty bystanders have you
heard of?)
</P>
<P>
   Hollow points flatten on impact and expand. Once they hit
something, they usually stop right there. The down side is that
they cause nasty internal wounds, which means that a stray bullet
may wreak unintended havoc. So it would be nice to have officers
who shoot straight.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Dolensek and a few of her City Island neighbors were
pondering that the other day as they sat on her veranda overlooking
Eastchester Bay in the northeastern Bronx. From across the water
came a steady and familiar rat-a-tat-tat, endless volleys from the
police firing range on Rodman's Neck in Pelham Bay Park.
</P>
<P>
   Noise has been a constant companion on City Island for nearly 40
years, which is how long police have used Rodman's Neck for target
practice and for detonating fireworks and an occasional
window-shattering bomb.
</P>
<P>
   But as Ms. Dolensek thought about the new ammunition, it
occurred to her that the racket may get even worse.
</P>
<P>
   While police say they plan no changes in their training program,
she wondered whether that would ultimately prove to be the case,
given the heavy premium that hollow points place on accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   More test firing would, of course, produce yet more noise. And
that, Ms. Dolensek said with a slight roll of the eyes, would mean
more irritation for City Island's 4,500 residents, who in a sense
are the Greta Garbo of New York. They just want to be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm asking for is some peace,'' said Susan Strazzera, one
of the neighbors. When a visitor agreed that it was rather noisy,
Ms. Strazzera said: ``This is nothing. Some days it sounds like
Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, islanders pleaded with the Police Department to
soundproof the range and to remove tons of spent lead that was
believed to be polluting water and land. Police did clean up the
area. Noise remains an issue, however, and it is enough to make
some on the island go, if you will, ballistic.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone feels that way. ``You get immune to it,'' a
teen-age girl said at a local deli. But others are ready to move
out, especially when the crackle of gunfire jolts them awake in the
morning or mars their evening as it continues well after dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days there's no noise at all, and then suddenly at 5 p.m.
it starts going like gangbusters,'' Ms. Dolensek said. Just about
as maddening are loudspeakers at the range that blast instructors'
directions clear across the water. ``You can hear every word,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department promises relief in the form of a $2.8
million plan to soundproof the range and install a ventilation and
filtration system for the lead powder produced by millions of
bullets. Inspector John Colgan, commander of the department's
office of management and budget, said that a contractor should be
chosen by the end of October, and construction completed a year
later. A result, he predicted, will be ``a substantial reduction in
the sound impact.''
</P>
<P>
   City Islanders have come to take a ``we'll believe it when we
see it'' attitude. Not that they are police haters. Quite the
opposite. It is a blue-collar area that voted 4-1 for Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani last November.
</P>
<P>
   But people there have heard pledges of imminent action for five
years, and skepticism has deepened with time. ``This thing has gone
on too long,'' said the islanders' assemblyman, Stephen Kaufman.
``Nobody believes them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This project has become like Penelope's tapestry,'' he added.
``You weave it in the morning and it comes unwoven at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could be that police mean business this time. And
if the firing range is eliminated as a nuisance, islanders can
train their sights on a new target: planes that roar directly
overhead on their way into La Guardia Airport. Wednesday afternoon,
the noise was almost unbearable as jets flew by every minute or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it paid to think positively. While the planes were
screaming, you couldn't hear the gunfire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
