A9470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--BASKETBALL-HNS &LR;      07-16 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--BASKETBALL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boycotting players' &QL; 
principles skewed
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ All expenses paid, they could have spent a week in one of
the world's most luxurious hotels, then visited two of the world's
most historic cities, both cradles of a civilization that has
evolved to the point where tall twentysomethings can be
jillionaires and still find a way to feel put upon.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Garnett and his buddies should be basking, and basketing,
in the Cte d'Azur sunshine today, ordering $20 hamburger combos
from room service at the Loews Monte Carlo and dropping a little
jingle across the street in the Hotel de Paris' belle epoque
casino, Prince Ranier's personal ATM.
</P>
<P>
   Those so inclined could spend their mornings golfing in the
foothills of the Alps at the Monte Carlo Country Club, or ogling
the bethonged, detopped lassies at the plage. Next stops: Rome and
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   All in the name of red-white-and-blue patriotism, too. In
return, the only thing being asked of them was to bring home a gold
medal. In basketball. Our sport.
</P>
<P>
   But no. This is about principle. This is about standing up to
the greed and oppression of the fat-cat owners, who have the nerve
to ask them _ 400 in number _ to find a way to make ends meet on a
mere $1.2 billion a year, or $3 million on average.
</P>
<P>
   Impossible!
</P>
<P>
   Misguided protest
</P>
<P>
   The World Championship of Basketball, which starts July 29 in
the shadow of the Acropolis, should have nothing to do with the
labor unrest in the NBA. USA Basketball, as opposed to David
Stern's circle, gleans the profits from the competition _ not that
it would have been much of one if the players who were supposed to
represent us had deigned to put their self-righteous posturing on
hold.
</P>
<P>
   But when the NBA locked the players out, that was that.
Apparently, some bucks might have accidentally trickled back
through the international monetary system into the owners' pockets,
and the players weren't going to stand for that.
</P>
<P>
   Hell no, they said. They wouldn't go.
</P>
<P>
   Our soccer program might be a farce, as it showed in the World
Cup, but our elite hoopsters still reside on a planet of their own.
Unfortunately, the guys who will wear the U.S. uniforms in Greece
are a hodgepodge collection of wannabe and never-will-be subs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they probably won't even reach the medal round, but
Rudy Tomjanovich diligently drives them. Rocket Rudy T is caught in
the middle _ but, by all accounts, he's enjoying himself anyway _
and could be well-served to suit himself up.
</P>
<P>
   It's a disgraceful situation, one the other countries will find
difficult to fathom. As screwed up as soccer is, beset by arrogant,
injury-faking players, heavy-handed FIFA officials and
double-dealing club owners, et al., when the time comes to don the
national colors for the Coupe du Monde, everyone shows up with
bells on to play ball. To not do so for any reason would be
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Bizarre stories have surfaced that Ronaldo, Brazil's young
superstar, took the field for the final against France after having
suffered a possibly nerves-induced seizure hours before the match.
Of course, others have claimed Nike, Brazil's benevolent
haberdasher, demanded it of him, but the company's denials have
been adamant.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter. Fact is, he played. As the highest-paid
performer in his sport, Ronaldo makes in salary ``only'' $3 million
annually, or about one-seventh what the also 21-year-old Garnett
receives from the Minnesota Timberwolves. Which would seem to imply
life is, or was, pretty darn sweet in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Only hurting themselves
</P>
<P>
   Too darn, the owners concluded, hence their demand to repeal the
Larry Bird exemption, the (Santa) clause that allows teams to
re-sign their own free agents at any sky's-the-limit price without
violating the softest salary cap in history. The players, wonder of
wonders, won't hear of it, so there they all sit, threatening to
wring the neck of another league's golden goose.
</P>
<P>
   One ex-player from an NBA era _ the 1970s _ that wasn't much fun
says: ``When I broke in, we were a league with a bad image problem
because of drugs and we didn't have a labor contract. Looks like
history is repeating itself.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said that well before Allen Iverson's new Benz turned up
in the middle of a drug bust. Guess Iverson is such a busy man this
summer, he can't even keep track of a $100,000 automobile that's
barely off the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, things will get sorted out eventually _ the owners have
budgeted their war chests by unconscionably insisting you
season-ticket holders fork over all your dough up front, as of
Wednesday _ but in the interim, one more U.S. sports team figures
to get spanked on the international stage.
</P>
<P>
   In basketball. Our sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
