<HEADLINE>
PRIMESTAR'S NAME GOES ON TMS NASCAR WINSTON CUP RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Motor Speedway executive Eddie Gossage
said the second Texas 500 Winston Cup race last April was run
without a title sponsor because the interested companies ``weren't
exactly what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage and TMS have finally found a company whose name they
want to hang on next year's NASCAR race: Primestar, the television
satellite service company.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three years, the Denver-based company will sponsor
the race, to be renamed the Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway officials aren't expected to announce the deal
officially until Wednesday. Gossage was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Primestar executives expressed excitement over the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of money, but it's worth every dollar,'' said Denny
Wilkinson, senior vice president of marketing and programming for
Primestar Inc. ``This deal really works for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Primestar for the past two years has sponsored the Primestar
500, a Winston Cup race in the spring at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
Next year, that race will be sponsored by the Cracker Barrel
restaurant chain.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Atlanta track and the Fort Worth track are owned by
Bruton Smith's Speedway Motor Sports, and the Texas-Primestar
relationship developed because of that connection.
</P>
<P>
   Cracker Barrel fit better as a race sponsor in Atlanta because
of its strong marketing presence in the Southeast region of the
country, while Primestar, launched in 1994 as America's first
digital TV entertainment service, made more sense for Texas, where
it has a strong customer base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta was tremendously successful for us,'' Wilkinson said.
``But this is a bigger market and a bigger venue for us.'' What's
more, he added, Primestar's biggest retail distributor is Fort
Worth-based Radio Shack. That allows the company to take advantage
of corporate client hospitality and other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson would not discuss the cost of the sponsorship,
although executives at Interstate Batteries, which backed the
inaugural Texas 500 race in 1996, said they paid more than $1
million that year. Other Winston Cup race title sponsorships
typically cost $2 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Primestar considers its race sponsorship at TMS a
bargain. Wilkinson cited the advertising benefits and name exposure
from network TV coverage and advertising signage at the speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pays for itself,'' Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Primestar's involvement in NASCAR goes beyond race sponsorship.
The company also is title sponsor of the No. 16 Roush Racing Ford,
driven by Ted Musgrave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
