<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS BEGIN PRACTICE LOOKING TO FILL POSITIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys safety George Teague knows
position battles all too well. For the past three seasons, they
have been the story of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Teague was traded first from Green Bay to Atlanta and then to
the Cowboys in 1996. He signed with Miami last year and came back
to the Cowboys this year.
</P>
<P>
   All the moves were for the same reason _ either to compete for a
starting position or because he had been replaced as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be the same thing for me the past couple of
years,'' said Teague, one of four players trying to replace Brock
Marion at free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got to come in and compete and try to win the
position.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a mantra spouted by a host of Cowboys as the team began
practicing yesterday at Midwestern State University. Six starting
jobs _ strong-side and weakside defensive end, safety, middle
linebacker, strong-side linebacker and the second wide receiver _
are up from grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defensive coordinator Dave Campo, whose defense could
have four new starters when the Cowboys open the season against
Arizona on Sept. 6, blamed part of the shuffling on free agency. He
said position changes are something the Cowboys have grown used to.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four weeks, Campo said he's looking to find
players who will distinguish themselves from the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good mix at all the positions,'' Campo said.
``Whoever comes to the top is going to play. To be honest, I like
that. I like competition. I like young guys and the hunger of young
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   At free safety, Teague, a six-year veteran, will battle a group
of young players _ Omar Stoutmire and Kenny Wheaton, who are in
their second seasons, and Charlie Williams, who is in his third.
</P>
<P>
   Stoutmire is considered Teague's primary competition because of
his speed and athleticism. He runs the 40-yard dash in 4.3 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is going to be a battle,'' Stoutmire said. ``I
feel anyone of us can do the job. I'm just going to go in there and
prove that I am the best man.''
</P>
<P>
   Teague, who started for the Cowboys two seasons ago when Marion
was injured, believes that his experience gives him an edge.
</P>
<P>
   The contestants for the second receiver position opposite
Michael Irvin are Macey Brooks, in his second year; Stepfret
Williams, in his third year; Billy Davis, in his fourth season;
former TCU receiver Jimmy Oliver, also in his fourth year, but two
previous seasons were spent on injured reserve; and Ernie Mills, in
his eighth year.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Cowboys will use multiple-receiver sets, receivers
coach Dwain Painter said it is not as imperative to find one
starter as it is find a group of guys who can contribute
frequently, with one player stepping to the forefront as a player
the team can count on in any situation.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who got a $1 million signing bonus from Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones a few months ago, has the inside track. However, he
will be pushed by the 6-foot-5, 220-pound Brooks, who has big-play
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Mills played under Cowboys head coach Chan Gailey in Pittsburgh
two years ago. He has finally recovered from a 1996 knee injury and
could work his way into the starting role.
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft pick Greg Ellis and third-year veteran Kavika
Pittman are the starters at defensive end, for now.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys believe that Ellis has the potential to be great
pass rusher in the NFL, and they think Pittman, considered a bust
his first two years, will finally develop with some playing time.
</P>
<P>
   However, because they have just one career sack between them,
questions remain. Fifth-year veteran Hurvin McCormack will get a
chance to compete for playing time, and if the Cowboys are not
pleased with the progress at defensive end by the end of training
camp, look for them to scan the waiver wire for veteran help.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said it could turn out to be defensive ends by committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to shake down to our two best guys who going to be
the starters,'' Campo said. ``Everybody else will be in the
rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing scenario is at linebacker, where 11-year
veteran Fred Strickland's status could have a domino effect.
Strickland, who has admitted to having a subpar season last year,
faces a challenge from Randall Godfrey, 1997's starting strong-side
linebacker, for the middle linebacker spot.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey, a two-year veteran, is considered the team's middle
linebacker of the future and will get a chance to make the move
this season if Strickland repeats last season's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Making the process more complex is the fact the Cowboys must
find someone capable to replace Godfrey on the outside _ probably
either Broderick Thomas or rookie Darren Hambrick.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the best three will play. Strickland, who said he is
in better condition than last season, said he's not ready to go
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can do the job better than me, fine,'' Strickland said.
``I'm not going to give it up that easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
