<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HBO-BOXING-PROMO-MAN-     07-16 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HBO-BOXING-PROMO-MAN-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD MAN WHOSE FIELD IS RULED BY FISTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Lou DiBella is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The way you spot HBO boxing executive Lou DiBella at
a boxing event is by his beaming face, which, as Lou DiBella is 6
feet 3 inches, shines as a beacon above the crowd. There is also
the single gold earring in the shape of a boxing glove. You don't
see many Harvard Law graduates who sport glove earrings or who can
relate, as does the sweet-tempered DiBella, to a fellow who speaks
movingly of his fighting cocks (the light-heavyweight champion Roy
Jones Jr., fighting Saturday at Madison Square Garden on HBO).
</P>
<P>
   How does a Harvard guy connect with a guy who can speak at
length about a dead chicken?
</P>
<P>
   An aggrieved look from the normally affable DiBella, who may
just be the most influential man in boxing and, when speaking with
the boxing press, the most outspoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a Greenwich, Conn., kid,'' DiBella says. ``I'm a kid
from Brooklyn. I was raised in Flatbush by Italian immigrant
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Ivy League education gave me the education to deal with the
Don Kings or Bob Arums of the world,'' he says, referring to the
prominent promoters, ``who are brilliant and Machiavellian, but
your average fighter is not a country club kid, socioeconomically.
They've struggled. I don't want to bare my soul totally, but I can
relate to it.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes for power in boxing? Working at HBO, which spends
more than any other network (reportedly $50 million this year) and
thus rules the roost. And HBO has exclusive contracts with Jones,
Oscar De La Hoya, Prince Naseem Hamed, who does a back flip into
the ring, and world heavyweight champion Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   As programming chief for HBO boxing, DiBella, working under the
president of Time Warner Sports, Seth Abraham, has the power to
help determine what matches the audience will see.
</P>
<P>
   Why does Abraham give DiBella this kind of freedom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's Lou,'' Abraham says. ``Fights are made by
spontaneous combustion. You have to breathe it. Lou breathes it.
His skill goes far beyond matchmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham tells the story of how HBO acquired Prince Naseem Hamed.
``Lou didn't discover Hamed,'' Abraham begins. ``The other guys
discovered him.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``other guys'' would be Showtime? ``Yeah,'' Abraham says.
``What Lou did was craft a plan to walk Naseem from those people to
HBO, including opening him in America, in Madison Square Garden.
Lou made a match with Kevin Kelley, the Flushing Flash, a local
hero, against this foreign interloper. It was a terrific fight with
seven knockdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also a tremendous publicity machine in our company
which Lou presents to a man like Hamed. We got a fashion
photographer to shoot Hamed in such a way that his arms and gloves
looked larger than the rest of his body. Then the piece de
resistance, we set his gloves on fire. We called it `Fists of
Fire.' Talent relations are also important. Boxers are divas in
short pants; they get mad, they need to talk to somebody. They feel
comfortable with Lou.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou DiBella has an old mug shot of Don King on his office door.
There is history between HBO and Don King. King decamped from HBO
years ago with Mike Tyson, boxing's biggest draw. HBO has been
trying _ unsuccessfully _ to put together a match between one of
its fighters, Lewis, and Evander Holyfield, who is also a world
heavyweight champion and who is promoted by King.
</P>
<P>
   What are DiBella's feelings about King? DiBella's answer befits
a man who really wants to make the Lewis-Holyfield match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing against Don personally,'' DiBella says. ``I
don't like some of the ways he conducted business, but I don't view
him as the source of all evil. I don't want this to become a Don
King story. The system is corrupt; he's just better at using it.
The ratings organizations and their shenanigans, the misuse of
options contracts by promoters. If the desire is to fix boxing, you
have to fix the whole system.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He sees boxers, on the other hand, as on the side of the angels.
``It's a sport that's never boring,'' DiBella says. ``It's imbued
with tremendous poetry, and irony and comedy, full of characters
who if you didn't know, you couldn't invent them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighters to me are the noblest and most decent of men. To be a
professional fighter, you can go from the top to the bottom, the
bottom to the top in 10 seconds. There are a lot of allegories for
life. Evander Holyfield was supposed to be too small, too old. He
was supposed to get into the ring with Tyson and lose, and instead
what you saw was the better athlete and more committed person win,
and that's the beauty of boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Did DiBella ever hit anybody?
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat nervous laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, generally in self-defense. I'm not a bully by nature,
but as a kid I got bullied a little bit. I was like the smart kid
in class and I was small.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter the hero, Muhammad Ali. DiBella listened to him on his
transistor radio, late at night, in bed; grew up, went into boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not literally a fighter,'' DiBella says, ``but
figuratively I'm a fighter. ''
</P>
<P>
   He had parents he admired, he was able to go to college, his
life doesn't look like an obstacle course. ``Some fights are very
personal,'' he said. ``I don't want to get into it all, but I've
lost three of my closest friends. I lost my brother six years ago.
You have to live life. You have to go for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980716.0512 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-A&AMP;P-400&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      07-16 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-A&AMP;P-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPOTLIGHT BRINGS SMILES FOR NOVOTNA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAHWAH, N.J. _ Jana Novotna, still getting used to the
expectations that come with being Wimbledon champion, seemed as
stunned as the sellout crowd at the A&AMP;P Tennis Classic Thursday
night when she failed to hold serve and squandered an opportunity
to put away her match against Mariaan de Swardt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Novotna slumped in her seat and stared into space until prompted
to return to the court. Perhaps contemplating how tired she must
have been after consecutive victories at Eastbourne, Wimbledon and
the Czech Open, and realizing she was on the verge of an extra set,
Novotna stepped onto the court and put the match away, ending the
playfulness that marked most of the match. With the 6-3, 6-4
victory in hand, she spun a pirouette and broke into a huge smile
as she approached the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an enormous difference,'' Novotna said afterward of her
new-found fame. ``Not only here, but everywhere, not only on the
tennis side, but on the streets, I've never had so much publicity,
so many people coming up to me and just being very happy for me. I
think it's so much more than just saying, `Oh, well done.' It comes
from the heart.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Novotna was an afterthought for this tournament not long ago,
being recruited as insurance in case Anna Kournikova could not play
because of torn ligaments in her right thumb. Now Novotna is the
star, and that became even more important for this exhibition
tournament when Kournikova bowed out Wednesday and another player,
Mirjana Lucic, canceled Thursday because of illness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Swardt stepped in for Kournikova, flying up from her home in
Hilton Head, S.C., to fill the eight-player card. And playing the
understudy to Novotna was no problem. ``I don't think there was one
player not happy for her,'' De Swardt said. `` She's a good
athlete, a good competitor.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De Swardt was echoing the sentiments of many players, who, like
many tennis fans, were relieved to see the 29-year-old Novotna
finally capture a Grand Slam. The No. 2-ranked Novotna, meanwhile,
continues to be astounded by the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you think about those things,'' said Novotna,
who will face Amanda Coetzer in the semifinals on Saturday. ``You
just go out there and try to do your job. I've dreamed about
winning a Grand Slam tournament for a long time, but that's it. You
don't think about what happens afterward.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kournikova was also on hand Thursday night, and while a swollen
right thumb kept her from playing in the tournament, it did not
stop her from drawing a crowd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, whose entourage here included Detroit Red Wings star
Sergei Fedorov, answered questions from fans, hit balls into the
crowd and autographed items of clothing for a charity auction
before Thursday night's match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have to do it for the fans,'' the 17-year-old
Kournikova said. ``I really tried to play. I wanted to come for the
fans, for the tournament, because I'm really disappointed I
couldn't play.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-ranked Kournikova tore ligaments in her right thumb
before Wimbledon, but accepted the invitation to play here thinking
that she would be sufficiently recovered. But when she tried to
practice on Wednesday, the thumb swelled again and her doctors
advised her to withdraw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
