<SLUG> BC-BRILLIANT-STOCK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRILLIANT DIGITAL SHARES SPARKLE IN 44.4 PERCENT SURGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Brilliant Digital Entertainment Inc. became the
latest beneficiary of Wall Street's infatuation with Internet
stocks as the interactive game producer's stock rose an impressive
44.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Brilliant jumped $1.062 to $3.312 on volume of 1.69
million shares, or 11 times the six-month daily average, after
Thursday's announcement of a test-marketing agreement with the
GeoCities Internet user group.
</P>
<P>
   Brilliant said the trial will help it fine-tune its first major
product launch in October. The company produces animated games like
Gravity Angels and Cyberswine, with hundreds of plot twists
determined by users.
</P>
<P>
   The pact calls for creating a Multipath Movie Reviewers Club
site that will be available to 150,000 GeoCities subscribers during
a six-week test due to launch next week. Participants will first
obtain a ``Digital Projector'' CD-ROM through the GeoCities Web
site, then set up an online account enabling them to buy 30-minute
``Webisodes'' delivered over the Internet for $4.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills-based Brilliant said the system is designed to
work much like a cable TV subscriber's buying pay-per-view movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test will provide Brilliant with valuable feedback on
members' user habits and preferences, and enable the company to
finalize its marketing plan and said pricing structure for viewer
subscriptions,'' Chairman Mark Dyne said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The stock move is the third time this year that Brilliant shares
have been propelled by a company announcement. On May 28, shares
jumped $1.062 to $3.25 in the wake of Brilliant disclosing it was
working with Intel Corp. and the rock group KISS to create the
first multipath music video.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 20, Brilliant shares were pounded down $2.875 to $3.187
after the company said shipping delays would lead to a $1.45
million loss in its 1997 fourth quarter. Conversely, it reported a
first-quarter loss of $1.27 million on May 14 and saw the shares
edge down 18.75 cents to $2.692.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks such as Lycos, Excite, Yahoo! and Amazon.com
have posted massive gains in recent months even though the industry
is only a few years old and does not conform to typical investment
analysis. Some of the issues have fallen back slightly over the
past week on concerns that the sector may be overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
