<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-DANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dance Review: ``Blues Rooms &AMP; A Brand New People on the
Planet.''
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Imagine what might happen if an African-American
Martha Graham directed an episode of ``Hee Haw,'' and you get an
idea of what goes on in the amazing series of vignettes that is
Dianne McIntyre's ``Blues Rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with musical collaborator Olu Dara, three musicians and
a well-seasoned ensemble of singing-and-dancing cut-ups, McIntyre
has written a prescription for the blues that recalls the
pre-Prozacian Age. Everything from fish fries to front-porch
philosophizing are used with delicious comic flair in the opening
piece of McIntyre's National Black Arts Festival program, which
repeats tonight at the Rialto Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a well-crafted bit of dance theater in which seemingly
anything can happen, from the sassy to the sublime. Modern dancers
create friezes of raw physicality. Two strikingly beautiful dancers
in gold batik harem pants furl and unfurl themselves in a scarf
dance. And to great comic effect, a brawling couple finds a cure
for their romantic hangover by employing a pair of dueling
harmonicas.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's McIntyre. Svelte and silver-haired, elegant and
ageless, her movement is unlike anything you've ever seen before.
Skittering and flitting in all directions, she looks like a pile of
straw in a wind-storm _ particularly in Part Two of the evening,
the elegaic ``A Brand New People on the Planet.''
</P>
<P>
   For a dancer who made her name by collaborating with avant-garde
musicians, McIntyre has found a happy, wholesome way of weaving
old-fashioned song and dance skits. In her comedy and choreography,
she reveals herself to be a performer deeply in touch with her
cultural roots.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the evening, because she cannot stop for the
music, it stops for her.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
