<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9492 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--WAGNER-HNS &LR;      07-16 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Pitcher returns home; 
club counsels caution
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It was a sigh of relief few people in the Astros organization were
sure they would breathe.
</P>
<P>
   They feared the worst and hoped for the best, and in the end the
news was good. Billy Wagner, who took a line drive off the left
side of his head late Wednesday night, returned from Phoenix on
Thursday night with relatively minimal damage.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner suffered a concussion and a soft-tissue injury to his
left ear. He left the field on a cart and was rushed to Phoenix's
St. Joseph's Medical Center, where he spent Wednesday night.
Original plans were for Wagner to spend the night at the home of
teammate Doug Henry, who lives in nearby Chandler, Ariz., but
doctors decided to keep Wagner overnight and re-evaluated his
situation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old lefthanded pitcher underwent a series of
neurological tests, none of which revealed internal damage. He was
released from the hospital Thursday afternoon and returned to his
Pearland home that night.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at St. Joseph's Medical Center recommended Wagner take
one to two weeks off from pitching, but Astros general manager
Gerry Hunsicker wants to have the pitcher examined by team doctors
before making a decision on Wagner's recovery time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we have him looked at by our doctors and we have our
doctors sit down with us and develop a game plan regarding when and
how he comes back, it's pretty premature to say when he'll
return,'' Hunsicker said. ``The big story today is that Billy
Wagner is on the mend and has escaped serious injury.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least a few days before it becomes clear whether
Wagner can avoid a trip to the disabled list. Because the Astros
have been carrying one pitcher over the normal number for the past
few weeks, Hunsicker has flexibility in deciding if it's in the
club's best interest to fill Wagner's spot on the roster. It would
not be prudent to disable the pitcher for 15 days if he will be
able to pitch sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, right now everyone is concerned with his
well-being,'' Hunsicker said. ``It would be premature to think DL.
Until we see how Billy feels, and see what our doctors say, it
would be hard to say anything about the DL at this point. I can
tell you one thing: We are going to err on the side of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is for Billy and his well-being, not how soon
we can rush him back to the mound. We need to get through this one
day at a time. We don't know how Billy's body is going to respond,
and we don't know how he's going to feel. He took a traumatic blow.
I don't feel any need to make a reactionary move to disable him. We
plan to go into the weekend series as is.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry, a seven-year veteran with 78 career saves, will assume
the bulk of closing duties in Wagner's absence. Jay Powell, whom
the Astros recently acquired in a trade with the Marlins, also has
closing experience and could help to plug the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very good team, and we'll get through it,''
Hunsicker said. ``It's the same thing as when we had to put Jeff
Bagwell and Mike Hampton on the disabled list. You don't replace
Jeff Bagwell, you don't replace Mike Hampton, and you don't replace
Billy Wagner, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Diamondbacks catcher Kelly Stinnett hit the line drive
that struck Wagner, who had entered the game in the ninth inning
and was trying to secure the Astros' 8-7 lead. Stinnett was the
third batter Wagner faced in the inning. The Astros lost the game
9-8 in 11 innings, but the defeat was the furthest thing from the
minds of Wagner's teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who (cares) about the game?'' right fielder Derek Bell said.
``The game didn't mean anything after seeing what happened to
Billy. This was just another game; our thoughts were with Billy and
his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wagner is one of the best athletes on the team, he had
no chance to get out of the path of Stinnett's line drive; it's
doubtful anyone could have. The ball, which ricocheted off Wagner's
head and toward the Diamondbacks' dugout on the third-base side of
the diamond, left the pitcher flat on his back and in obvious pain.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately was surrounded by trainers, coaches and players
from both teams. The most encouraging early signs were the fact
Wagner's vital signs were good and he never lost consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got hit right by the ear,'' said Hunsicker, who attended
the game. ``There was some question as to whether or not it was
deflected (by Wagner's glove), but I can tell you _ sitting there
behind home plate _ it was not deflected. It was a direct hit. If
it was deflected, it was just barely, if at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
