<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERIOR-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERIOR INDUSTRIES STOCK TAKES POUNDING FROM STRIKE AT GM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The United Auto Workers strike against General
Motors Corp. struck down Superior Industries' second-quarter
earnings by 18 percent, reflecting reduced deliveries to the
world's largest automaker.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban Van Nuys-based maker of cast-aluminum wheels has
idled 200 of 1,000 workers in Van Nuys, stopped production at a
Tennessee facility, significantly reduced operations at its Kansas
plant and cut back work at three plants in Arkansas and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people expected our earnings to be down,'' said Jeff
Ornstein, Superior's chief financial officer. However, ``this does
not affect long-term gains and momentum of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls the GM crisis ``the worst strike in terms of length and
impact,'' affecting not just a few car models but almost shutting
down the automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of Superior's sales come from General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   The GM strike began June 5 and June 11 at two Flint, Mich.,
parts plants and has led to the closing of 26 of 29 GM assembly
plants in North America and the idling of 178,600 workers. The cost
to the automaker: an estimated $1.2 billion and rising by $80
million in lost profits daily, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute behind GM and the UAW union revolves around the
automaker's alleged reneging on promised capital investments, job
security, and health and safety violations, among others.
</P>
<P>
   GM is suing the union, claiming that the strike is illegal. The
union agreed Wednesday to let an independent arbitrator decide
whether the strike is allowed under the GM-UAW contract.
</P>
<P>
   The strike also has hurt dozens of part makers who supply GM's
factories.
</P>
<P>
   Superior is a victim, said Philip Fricke, an analyst at
Prudential Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are events that are not under its control,'' he said.
``At least it has the financial wherewithal to withstand it,''
thanks to a financial report that includes no long-term debt and
$90 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, Superior reported a net income of $12.3
million, or 44 cents a diluted share, compared with earnings of
$15.1 million (53 cents) a year ago. Revenues were $138.1 million
vs. $142.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Superior missed analysts' earnings estimates of 57 cents a
share, blaming the GM strike for the entire shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Superior closed at 27.0625 on Thursday, down 0.625.
</P>
<P>
   Once the strike is settled, Ornstein said, earnings and sales
should rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced that it repurchased 181,000 of its
common shares in the second quarter for a total of 337,000 shares
it has bought back under a program authorizing the open-market
acquisition of 2 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Superior supplies aluminum wheels to major automakers such as
GM, Ford, BMW, Volkswagen, Toyota and Nissan. It also makes
automotive accessories.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
