<HEADLINE>
FINLEY CUTS DEEPLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The next time pitcher Chuck Finley gets a phone call
from friend Keith Lyons about a golf date, Finley has good reason
to hang up.
</P>
<P>
   Finley and Lyons had a golf date arranged last August, and
before the two could play, Finley broke his wrist in a game against
the Yankees and was lost for the season. The two had another golf
date arranged for this week, but Wednesday night Finley tore a hole
in his right knee during a play at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird, Finley said. ``I had to call him up and tell him I
can't play. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, however, still has plans to make his next start Tuesday
in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that could stop that is if it gets infected,
Finley said. ``They washed it out for about an hour, picking rocks,
grass and dirt out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Finley and others were surprised at how bad the cut was after he
slid on both knees while trying -- unsuccessfully -- to tag out the
Devil Rays' Randy Winn. It took eight stitches to close the wound,
which Finley said was ``a hole the size of a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't that concerned about it when I did it, Finley
said. ``Until I looked at it and saw it was all the way down to the
bone. I said `This isn't good.'
</P>
<P>
   If Finley is unable to make his next start, Allen Watson would
start in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Trade talk update:
</P>
<P>
   The Reds wanted center fielder Jim Edmonds in exchange for
pitcher Pete Harnisch, but the Angels said no. Now, the Reds might
be willing to trade Harnisch for a package of prospects, as long as
it includes triple-A pitcher Scott Schoeneweis. Schoeneweis, 24, is
6-6 with a 4.65 ERA in 17 starts for Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels reportedly turned down a deal for Royals pitcher Tim
Belcher because the Royals wanted second baseman Justin Baughman.
They also turned down pitcher Willie Blair from the Diamondbacks,
who wanted double-A outfielder Norm Hutchins.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are interested in strengthening their bullpen, and
have targeted the A's Mike Fetters and the Tigers' Todd Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going to single-A Lake Elsinore for a rehab
assignment as was planned, Todd Greene will leave today for
Oklahoma City to join triple-A Vancouver. Greene, who hasn't played
all season because of offseason shoulder surgery, decided to play
for Vancouver so he could face better pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who will play first base and DH, is expected to join the
Angels when they begin their next homestand July 28 against the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde (elbow) will begin a rehab assignment Monday, but
it has not been decided where he'll play.
</P>
<P>
   With a team-leading 64 RBIs going into Thursday's game, first
baseman Cecil Fielder is on pace to finish with 111. And yet the
Angels don't feel he's been at his best. Fielder is hitting just
.242.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such an important part of our lineup, manager Terry
Collins said. ``If we can get him going, he's going to drive in a
lot of runs for us.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a first: Sunday's game between the Angels and Orioles is
tatoo day for kids 12 and under. Actually, they are temporary
tatoos of the Angels' logo. ... Garret Anderson extended his
hitting streak to 14 games Thursday with a second-inning single.
The Angels' longest hitting streak this season is Darin Erstad's 15
games.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
