r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  FORMERVICTIMSSUPPORTBILL     07-16 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 FORMER VICTIMS SUPPORT BILL TO AVERT REPEATED CRIMES  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their stories made headlines across the country. They or their
loved ones were attacked, killed or maimed, often by a criminal
recently released from prison.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to Fred Goldman's son Ron, who was murdered in 1994
alongside Nicole Brown Simpson in the infamous case in which former
football great O.J. Simpson was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   It also happened to Tempe resident Carol Fornoff, whose daughter
Christy Ann was slain 14 years ago, and to California resident Mary
Vincent, who was raped and mutilated in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   These victim advocates lined up Thursday to support a bill
introduced by Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., that aims to prevent
crimes like the ones that shook their families.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would provide a strong financial incentive for states
permanently to lock up murderers, rapists and child molesters on
the chance that they might commit a similar crime once out from
behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Victims'-rights advocates called Salmon's legislation heroic.
Crime-policy critics called it ``stupid electioneering.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent, blotting the tears with a tissue clenched by pincers on
one of her two prosthetic arms, said she spoke for victims
everywhere when she said, ``We will not tolerate violent crime in
our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent survived her rape and mutilation by Laurence Singleton,
who was convicted of murdering a mother of three in Florida after
attacking her. He cut off both of Vincent's forearms and left her
for dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn to live with it, but you don't get over it,'' said
Fornoff, whose 13-year-old daughter, Christy Ann, was murdered by a
man with a long criminal record while collecting on her ``Phoenix
Gazette'' paper route.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (these criminals) hadn't gotten their second chances, these
children would not be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon's ``No Second Chances'' bill would require one state to
compensate another for the repeat offense of a murderer, rapist or
child molester released from prison by the first state, even if
that prison release came at the end of a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   It also would change federal sentencing guidelines to make
murder punishable by life in prison or the death penalty and rape
or sexual offenses punishable by life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to draw a line in the sand and say to these monsters:
`You do that, you're out of here. You're done,' '' Salmon said.
``Let's do it without the political fanfare. Let's just get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   But politics is exactly what Salmon was practicing, said Eric
Lotke, research director of the National Center on Institutions and
Alternatives in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislation is a crock,'' he said. ``This is just stupid
electioneering.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotke said the bill tramples on states' rights by making one
state liable to another, is unnecessary given the low recidivism
rates for murder, and stands little chance of passage.
</P>
<P>
   He labeled those who supported the bill ``professional
victims.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole class of them now. They're angry people. . . .
It's sympathetic, but it's not good policy,'' Lotke said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also has the support of the Fraternal Order of Police,
Childhelp USA and Parents of Murdered Children.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Flynn, constitutional-law professor at Pomona College in
California, said the bill likely would pass a constitutional
challenge. The U.S. Supreme Court has been lenient in allowing
restrictions to be placed on federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Flynn said he suspects legislators will balk at the high
cost of building even more prisons to contain those named in the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is ``fiendishly clever'' said Eric Sterling,
president of the liberal Criminal Justice Policy Foundation in
Washington. The bill likely would pass constitutional muster
because it forces a change in state sentencing without mandating
that change.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid liability, states likely would have to impose harsh
sentences for the listed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said the bill is designed to get longer stretches for the
nation's most violent felons.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't believe rehabilitation, particularly for pedophiles,
works. And, he said, ``I don't think they deserve a second
chance.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
