<HEADLINE>
CHINESE DISSIDENTS CALL FOR RELEASE OF FIVE ACTIVISTS, GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING - A human rights group based in Hong Kong said Thursday
that 100 Chinese dissidents had called on Chinese leaders to free
five activists who were detained after trying to register an
opposition political party.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter addressed to President Jiang Zemin and Prime
Minister Zhu Rongji, the dissidents expressed outrage that the
authorities have taken 10 people into custody for expressing
political views. The Communist Party bans the formation of
political groups that it has not approved.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 10 activists have been released in recent days, said
the human rights group, the Information Center of Human Rights and
Democratic Movement in China. But five remain in custody in
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call on the central government to rectify the violation of
human rights by the Zhejiang police and to release the five men,''
said the letter, which carries 79 signatures, and claimed the
support of another 21 unidentified sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities frequently detain people they consider
politically suspect, often releasing them after a few days with a
stern warning, but sometimes holding them far longer. Whether any
of the five detainees in Zhejiang will face charges or a prison
sentence remained unclear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
